Fire continued to burn inside the Achille Lauro early Thursday , a day after the flames forced the nearly 1,000 people aboard take to lifeboats and abandon the cruise ship off Somalia .
Two people were reported dead and one missing in the flight from the Achille Lauro , which gained notoriety in 1985 when Palestinian terrorists hijacked and killed a wheelchair-bound American passenger .
Overflights by U.S. Navy helicopters at dawn Thursday found the ship listing but in no danger of sinking some 25 kilometers -LRB- 15 miles -RRB- offshore in the Indian Ocean , said Cmdr. T. McCreary , spokesman US Naval Forces Central Command in the Gulf .
After fighting the blaze , the last 60 crewmembers abandoned the badly listing vessel Wednesday and boarded merchant ships helping in the rescue .
The 23,478-ton vessel was 210 kilometers -LRB- 130 miles -RRB- south of the Horn of Africa when the crewmembers left .
`` I just passed the Achille Lauro overhead and she is fully engulfed , almost now in flames .
Flames have progressed far forward in the ship , '' said U.S. Navy pilot Lt. Paul Frost , who flew over the site Wednesday afternoon .
Eight people were injured in the fire .
The ship 's owner , Genoa-based Starlauro , said the blaze apparently broke out in the passenger area , but the cause was unknown .
Capt. Ferdinando Lolli , a port official in Rome , said the ship was carrying 581 passengers and 404 crew .
Most of the crew was Italian , and the passengers mainly South African , German , Dutch and British .
Late Wednesday evening , Italian Coast Guard officials reported that one person from the Achille Lauro was still unaccounted for .
The two reported dead were identified by Italian news agencies as a Briton and a German .
The Panamanian oil ship Hawaiian King was one of the first ships to arrive at the scene and took on about 800 people , said a coast guard official in Rome , Adm. Eugenio Sicurezza .
The Liberian-registered Bar Du , and a Greek ship , the Treasure Island , also were picking up passengers .
Two U.S. warships , the USS Gettysburg and USS Halyburton , reached the scene overnight and dispatched helicopters to ferry water , food and medical supplies to the survivors , said McCreary .
The commerical and Navy ships will divide up the passengers Thursday and send them on , mostly to Mombasa , Kenya , and Djibouti , McCreary said .
Others reportedly will be taken to the Seychelles .
All three destinations are about 1,930 kilometers -LRB- 1,200 miles -RRB- away from the Achille Lauro .
The Achille Lauro left Genoa on Nov. 19 , stopped in Israel , and its next port of call was to be Durban , South Africa , on Friday , said Carla Gotta , a spokeswoman for the cruise ship 's owner .
The terrorists who hijacked the Achille Lauro in 1985 shot American Leon Klinghoffer and pushed him in his wheelchair off the ship .
The hijackers escaped the vessel and boarded a jet , but U.S. fighter planes forced it to land in Italy and the hijackers were captured .
The Achille Lauro resumed service as a cruise ship shortly after the hijacking .
Klinghoffer 's convicted killer is serving a 30-year term in an Italian prison .
Two other men are serving lesser terms and a fourth person , 17 at the time of the hijacking and tried as a juvenile , was paroled in 1991 .
George Bennett , spokesman for the U.N. operation in Somalia , said the Achille Lauro 's position was close to the small Somali fishing village of Eil , about 25 kilometers -LRB- 15 miles -RRB- off the coast .
Launched in 1946 in the Netherlands , the Achille Lauro was acquired 20 years later by the Neapolitan shipping dynasty .
Its sides painted a royal blue , the Achille Lauro first transported Italian immigrant workers to and from Australia .
In 1970 it was outfitted for pleasure cruises .
But it has had its share of problems : The liner rammed a fishing boat in 1971 off Italy , killing a Neapolitan fisherman .
On Dec. 2 , 1981 , fire broke out aboard ship off the Canary Islands .
Panicked passengers jumped into the sea , and two of them drowned .
Prime Minister Jean Chretien has started a week-long trip to Europe as concerns about 55 Canadian peacekeepers detained in Bosnia threaten to overshadow his remarks today to the French Senate .
Chretien is only the second leader to be invited to speak to the French Senate .
The first was German Chancellor Helmut Kohl last year .
While in Paris , Chretien will also attend a world summit on AIDS .
In his remarks to the Senate , the prime minister plans to stress trade and commercial links with France while playing down concerns about Canadian unity , federal officials said .
But these comments may take a back seat to worries about Canadian troops who continue to be held by Serbian forces and wider concerns about the future of United Nations ' peacekeeping efforts in the former Yugoslavia .
The prime minister arrived in Paris late Wednesday as a rift between the United States and other allies seemed to deepen over what role United Nations ' forces should play in the war-torn eastern European country .
`` The Americans want to control everything and fight down to the last Canadian and Frenchmen , '' Chretien said in an interview published Wednesday in the French daily Le Monde .
Congressional leaders from the United States , which has committed no ground troops in the former Yugoslavia , said this week that UN peacekeeping efforts there are a failure .
Chretien said again that the U.S. is in no position to criticize UN efforts .
But the prime minister also suggested in the interview that it 's time to reconsider the role of peacekeepers in Bosnia .
`` The peacekeepers in Bosnia have become a sort of armed Red Cross in a badly defined role .
To be in Bosnia is difficult for us .
It 's a European problem and we are North Americans , '' he told Le Monde .
A senior Canadian official in Paris , speaking on condition of anonymity , also said the prime minister would not turn down the opportunity to intervene personally if that would help win the release of Canadian soldiers .
The Bosnian situation is evolving hour by hour and will top the agenda in meetings in France with President Francois Mitterrand and Prime Minister Edouard Balladur , the Canadian official said .
Canada has about 2,000 peacekeepers in the former Yugoslavia , the third largest force from UN countries .
In Bosnia , Canada has about 800 troops , Britain 3,517 and France 4,354 .
Bosnia is also expected to top the agenda when Chretien travels Sunday to Budapest for the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe .
On another matter , the federal official said Chretien will answer questions about Canadian unity if they 're raised by French officials but wo n't broach the subject himself .
In his interview with Le Monde , the prime minister repeated that Ottawa has no intention of trying to defuse separatist sentiments in Quebec with federal spending .
`` I will not buy Quebecers ' votes .
I have too much respect for them .
Quebecers are not for sale , they are rational , they will consider coldly their main interests and those of their children . ''
Malaysian tin closed at dlrs 15.27 per kilo Thursday , up 20 cents .
A year that began with bitter disappointment is ending in superb fashion for Todd Eldredge of the United States and Surya Bonaly of France .
Both skaters are on hot streaks early in this figure skating season .
They won the International Pro-Am Challenge on Wednesday , giving Bonaly her fourth successive win and Eldredge his second and third straight strong showing .
Viktor Petrenko , the 1992 Olympic champion , was first in the free skate , worth two-thirds the total score .
But the Ukrainian was fifth entering the program and could move up only to third .
Eldredge won the technical routine on Tuesday and , skating to music from the film `` Gettysburg , '' was tied for second behind Petrenko in the free skate , giving him the title .
He also won Skate America last month , but this field was stronger , including defending Olympic champion Alexei Urmanov of Russia , who tied Eldredge on Wednesday night and was second overall .
`` I had a very good short program and then I put a decent long program out there , '' Eldredge said .
`` I think everybody had a bobble here and there .
`` With the past two Olympic champions , that makes it a tough field . ''
Eldredge , 23 , won the 1990 and '91 U.S. titles , then sustained a back injury that disrupted his career .
He was a stunning fourth at the nationals in January , failing to make the Olympic and world team .
Bonaly , who struggled at the Olympics , then claimed home-ice judging cost her the world championship , won the free skate with all seven judges , passing Olga Markova of Russia for the title .
Bonaly previously won the Goodwill Games , Skate America and Trophy of France this season .
The streak comes after she entered the Lillehammer Olympics as one of the favorites and finished a weak fourth , then was second at the worlds , held in Japan , to Yuka Sato .
Bonaly , 20 , is trying to think only happy thoughts these days .
It seems to be working for the four-time European champ who has been criticized for her lack of artistry .
`` I wish and hope I am going to be accepted , '' she said .
`` It 's a long time I have been working on it .
I hope one day they will realize I did my job well and did my work .
I ca n't say it was 100 percent excellent today , but I did my job . ''
Before a crowd of 6,414 , Bonaly delivered a solid performance .
She hit six triple jumps but did little in between , with virtually no footwork and little imagination to her program .
`` It was OK .
It can be better , '' she said .
`` I was a little tired .
I will be in better shape for the next competition . ''
Bonaly is the top-ranked woman in the world .
Most of the better female skaters turned pro and China 's Lu Chen rarely has skated since winning a bronze medal at the Olympics .
Michelle Kwan , the top-rated American amateur skater , was second in the free skate and finished third overall .
Kwan now will take time off from competition after finishing behind Bonaly in all four events this season .
The other disciplines went to Russian couples , with Americans challenging the world champions in pairs .
Evgenia Shishkova and Vadim Naumov barely edged U.S. champions Jenni Meno and Todd Sand in pairs .
Both couples performed superbly , as did third-place finishers Kyoko Ina and Jason Dungjen , also of the United States .
All three pairs received at least one first-place vote .
Anjelika Krylova and Oleg Ovsiannikov , in their first international appearance , were sensational in winning the ice dance with a flamenco presentation that earned first place from all of the judges .
The mother of a British backpacker found murdered told a court Thursday that her daughter was `` bright and bubbly '' when they spoke on the phone days before she disappeared from a Sydney hostel .
Jacqueline and Ian Clarke , parents of Caroline Clarke , also identified a hairbrush police found in raids on the homes of suspect Ivan Milat and two of his brothers as identical to one their daughter had when she left their house in Northumberland .
Clarke also said a sleeping bag recovered during the raids was similar to one he remembered his daughter having .
Caroline Clarke and her traveling companion Joanne Walters were last seen April 19 , 1992 .
Mrs. Clarke told Campbelltown Local Court she had spoken to her daughter by telephone a week to 10 days before Easter 1992 .
`` She was quite bright and bubbly ... she sounded happy and everything seemed fine , '' said Mrs. Clarke , who has traveled from Britain to give evidence .
English stockbroker Stephen Wright also testified Thursday that a tent seized in the raids was the same one he gave Clarke when he , Clarke and Walters traveled together in Tasmania in 1992 .
Wright said he recognized the tent by the address labels he used to make repairs after it was damaged by a knife he used while picking grapes .
Wright also identified a sleeping bag as one he saw Walters buy during their trip to Tasmania .
The tent and the sleeping bag were allegedly found in the home of Richard Milat on the day police arrested Ivan Milat , 49 .
Milat was charged in May with the murders of Melbourne couple James Gibson and Deborah Everist , both 19 ; German backpackers Simone Schmidl , 21 , Gabor Neugebauer , 21 , and Anja Habschied , 20 ; and Britons Clarke , 21 , and Walters , 22 .
Milat has denied the charges .
If convicted , he could be sentened to life in prison .
Survivors of the U.S. atomic bombing of Japan and anti-nuclear bomb activists said Thursday they are angry about a U.S. Postal Service plan to issue a stamp commemorating the attack .
`` This is outrageous , '' said Sunao Tsuboi , acting director of the 30,000-member Hiroshima Prefectural Confederation of A-bomb Survivors Organizations .
`` It makes our blood boil with anger , '' he told the Associated Press .
Tsuboi was commenting on the stamp 's caption : `` Atomic bombs hasten war 's end , August 1945 . ''
Many critics of the bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki on Aug. 6 and 9 that year say there were more humane ways to make Japan surrender , ending World War II .
The stamp design , a composite of mushroom clouds created by the wartime bombings and nuclear tests after the war , is scheduled to be released next year around the 50th anniversary of the Allied victory of World War II .
About 140,000 of Hiroshima 's 340,000 residents died within five months after the Aug. 6 raid , while the attack on Nagasaki killed another 70,000 of that city 's 270,000 .
Japan surrendered on Aug. 15 , 1945 .
Tsuboi said his organization will consult with other anti-nuclear groups in Hiroshima and Nagasaki on what action to take against the stamp .
`` The use of weapons of mass destruction like those dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki should never be legitimated under any circumstances , '' said Kazuya Yasuda , a top official of the Japan Council Against Atomic and Hydrogen Bombs , a private group campaigning to abolish nuclear arms worldwide .
Local officials in both cities also expressed displeasure with the stamp .
In October , Takashi Hiraoka , the mayor of Hiroshima sent a letter , to Vice President Al Gore contending that a U.S. Senate resolution seeking changes to a war exhibit in Washington next year was tantamount to condoning the 1945 atomic bombing of his city .
The exhibit , which will feature the first public display of the Enola Gay , the plane that dropped the bomb on Hiroshima , is planned for May 1995 at Washington 's Smithsonian Institution .
The Smithsonian agreed to revise the script earlier this year after veterans groups said it was too sympathetic to wartime Japan .
They also said it was unjustly critical of the use of a device that may have saved thousands of lives by making a bloody invasion of the Japanese home islands unnecessary and hastening the end the war .
Chinese import and export of high-technology products reached a record level in 1993 at dlrs 20.59 billion , up 40 percent from 1992 , according to figures released Thursday .
The statistics were the first ever China has released on its high-tech trade volume , said the Economic Information Daily .
The State Science and Technology Commission released the statistics in the official Chinese-language paper .
Computers , telecommunications equipment and similar products accounted for 10.5 percent of the country 's entire 1993 commodity trade volume of dlrs 195.7 billion , it said .
High-tech imports were up to dlrs 15.91 billion in 1993 , and exports rose to dlrs 4.68 billion , leaving a trade deficit of dlrs 11.23 billion , the newspaper said .
Exports of high-tech products increased by dlrs 680 million , or 17 percent , in 1993 , while imports jumped by dlrs 5.2 billion , or 48.5 percent , during the same year , the newspaper said .
The 1993 deficit widened from dlrs 10.71 billion a year earlier and was a big factor in China 's overall commodity trade deficit of dlrs 12.19 billion in 1993 , it said .
Computers and telecommunications equipment accounted for nearly 54 percent of all Chinese-made high-tech exports during the past year , the report said .
Lester Ellis of Australia will face a new opponent in Filipino Al Coquilla when he fights for the vacant International Boxing Organization junior-welterweight title in Kalgoorlie on Saturday night .
Coquilla replaces his compatriot Noel Toledo , who originally was earmarked to fight Ellis for the lightly-regarded IBO title .
Ellis , 29 , is the former IBF junior-lightweight and WBF welterweight champion .
He has a 37-6 professional record .
Promoter Bill Hartmann said Coquilla claims a record of 30-5-2 .
After months of hot debate , Beijing has passed a law meant to discourage raising dogs .
Under the new law , dog owners must pay a 5,000-yuan -LRB- dlrs 600 -RRB- dog registration fee -- or 3,000 yuan -LRB- dlrs 360 -RRB- if the dog is registered within three months of when the law goes into effect on May 1 .
Annual renewal fees will be 2,000 yuan -LRB- dlrs 240 -RRB- .
That compares with the average annual income of about 6,000 to 9,000 yuan -LRB- about dlrs 725 to 1,100 -RRB- of Beijing workers .
The new law , passed on Wednesday , allows only one dog per family and bans `` large and fierce dogs , '' the Beijing Daily reported Thursday in its top front-page story .
It did not say what breeds would be banned .
News reports said small dogs will only be allowed outdoors between 8 p.m. and 7 a.m. , and bigger ones can never go out at all .
Every dog will be banned from public areas .
Beijing newspapers and radio phone-in shows have carried both sides of a debate on whether and how to restrict dogs in the city and its suburbs .
The proposed law put the registration fee at 6,000 yuan -LRB- dlrs 700 -RRB- , and many people complained it was too high .
The Beijing area has about 190,000 dogs , compared with 20,000 in 1986 , the Xinhua News Agency said .
It was not immediately clear how the city would enforce the new law .
Xinhua quoted Zhang Liangji of the Public Security Bureau as saying 52,000 residents were bitten by dogs last year , and 89 people died of rabies from 1988 to 1993 .
Dog-owning was considered decadent in China before the current economic reforms took hold over the past decade .
Xinhua noted on Wednesday that China has 120 million dogs who eat 15 billion kilograms -LRB- 33 billion pounds -RRB- of grain , enough to feed 40 million people .
China 's foreign exchange reserves increased 106 percent in the first 10 months of the year , reaching dlrs 43.7 billion , the China Daily reported Thursday .
The foreign debt , meanwhile , is expected to top dlrs 100 billion by the end of the year , said Guan Tao of the State Administration of Foreign Exchange Control .
China 's foreign debt surpassed dlrs 90 billion at the end of August , compared with dlrs 83.6 billion dlrs at the end of last year , the China Daily said .
Lin Zeti , deputy director of the administration , said the growing reserves show that China 's foreign exchange system reform has been working well , the report said .
With the country 's market economy taking shape , China will maintain a good balance of payments for the next few years , Lin said .
Guan attributed the fast growth of the foreign exchange reserves to the new foreign exchange system under which all institutions in China are required to sell their foreign exchange to banks .
Burgeoning exports , stimulated by the deprecation of the yuan at the start of this year , also brought more foreign exchange into the country , the report added .
In addition , foreign direct investment in the first nine months of this year has reached dlrs 22.7 billion , up 49 percent from the same period a year earlier , Guan said .
Parliament has enacted more power and independence to the Election Commission , but the effort to guarantee fair voting failed to satisfy the opposition or to end Bangladesh 's nine-month political crisis .
The law , passed unanimously late Wednesday , provides for voter identity cards and gives the Election Commission authority to punish officials involved in malpractice .
It empowers the commission to stop voting at any polling station if it suspects `` coercion , intimidation and pressure . ''
The legislation was rejected by the opposition , which has boycotted Parliament since March 2 , accusing Prime Minister Khaleda Zia 's government of election fraud , corruption and mismanagement .
Law Minister Mirza Golam Hafiz , concluding a brief debate on the bill , said `` it will help ensure free , fair and impartial voting , check false voting , and effectively protect the rights of the voters . ''
But opposition spokesman Mohammad Nasim said the bill `` is nowhere close to our demand for free and fair polls under an interim government . ''
The opposition wants the government to step down three months before elections , yielding to a neutral caretaker government that would supervise voting .
Mrs. Zia rejects the demand as `` unjustified and unconstitutional , '' but has offered to bring opposition members into a pre-election Cabinet .
The next election is scheduled for 1996 .
After an international mediation effort failed last month to break the deadlock , opposition leader Sheikh Hasina called for an accelerated campaign of national strikes and demonstrations .
On Tuesday , a strike backed by a rail and road blockade choked off routine business in the capital .
Hasina has called for a 48-hour general strike next week .
Businessmen have complained that the prolonged deadlock is hurting exports , discouraging foreign investment and diverting the government 's attention from its program of deregulating the economy .
The U.S. dollar closed at 99.01 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market Thursday , up 0.03 yen from Wednesday 's close .
Secretary of State Warren Christopher is telling the NATO allies the Clinton administration has swung to their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the war in Bosnia .
It is the first time in the post-World War II history of the alliance that the Europeans led by France prevailed over the United States in formulating a major policy .
It is a difficult assignment for Christopher , putting him in the awkward position of shifting gears even while denying U.S. policy on the war has changed or that there is a trans-Atlantic rift .
National Security Adviser Anthony Lake , in a speech Wednesday at Princeton University , acknowledged it is a path `` rife with frustrations and setbacks . ''
Nonetheless , he said , `` it 's the best , the steadiest course .
... Both sides face the same choice : They can perpetuate a bloody military stalemate or they can stop the senseless killing and come to terms . ''
By chance , it is the U.S. turn to preside over a meeting today of the North Atlantic Council , NATO 's policy-making arm .
This puts Christopher under an even brighter spotlight , and he was responding both with a brief speech opening the session and a detailed one outlining the revised U.S. approach to the Bosnian war .
It is centered on a call for an international peace conference that would give the Bosnian Serbs an opportunity to demand changes in the peace plan they have rejected repeatedly .
They already have strong intimations of support from the Clinton administration in pressing for cross-border political ties to the Serb-dominated government in Belgrade -- a big step toward their goal of a Greater Serbia .
And even the peace plan map the Bosnian Serbs rejected is open to negotiations , Clinton administration officials promised in this week of candid admissions by Defense Secretary William Perry and other senior U.S. officials that the Bosnian Serbs can not be stopped in their territorial conquests by military force .
The European allies , particularly France and Britain , have taken this position throughout the 31-month war .
They managed to limit NATO air strikes despite U.N. assurances that Bihac , the mostly Muslim town on the verge of falling to the Serbs , was a `` safe area '' from which heavy weapons were to be excluded .
They also hemmed in the 23,000 peacekeepers in Bosnia .
Lake , in his speech at Princeton , stressed that NATO had chosen not to intervene directly in Bosnia and had given the lead to the United Nations .
`` Right or wrong , that decision has consequences with which we must continue to struggle , '' he said .
Before leaving Washington , Christopher grumbled to reporters about NATO 's refusal to engage in a sustained bombardment of Serb positions in the northwestern region of the bloodied country .
But having threatened the Serbs in the past with NATO might , he abandoned the threat when asked what `` sticks '' the United States was using to persuade the Serbs to relinquish their grip on Bihac .
If they kept fighting , Christopher said , they risked Serbia closing its border and a tightening of sanctions -- measures that are far less threatening than attacks by NATO warplanes .
Serbia has been the principal arms supplier to Serbs in Bosnia .
And while Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic has promised to cut them off , a senior U.S. official said there was considerable `` leakage '' and arms were getting through .
Seeking to limit the damage to the alliance , which successfully stood up to the Soviet Union but has caved on Bosnia , Christopher said he wanted to stress that `` the crisis in Bosnia is about Bosnia and the former Yugoslavia ; it 's not about NATO and its future . ''
But NATO 's impotence has raised questions about NATO 's future .
Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas suggested after meeting in Brussels with alliance officials that the alliance may have become irrelevant .
`` There 's been no pressure on the Serbs and until there 's some leverage , it 's going to be very difficult to stop the fighting and reach some kind of settlement , '' Dole said .
The 76-year-old schoolteacher carries her anger and disenchantment in her waistcoat pocket , in a little blue booklet and a shiny plastic card tucked among its well-worn pages .
Fan Ximei received the booklet in 1958 , when she joined Taiwan 's ruling Nationalist Party , firmly believing in its doctrine of reunifying Taiwan with the Chinese motherland .
She got the plastic card from the New Party , to which she deserted 13 months ago , feeling that the Nationalists had betrayed her most cherished beliefs .
The New Party split from the Nationalists last year to uphold the doctrine of reunification .
On Saturday it faces its first major test in local elections that present the Nationalists with their sternest political challenge since they fled to Taiwan from Communist China in 1949 .
The polls for governor and mayors of Taiwan 's two largest cities are part of a shift toward democracy initiated by the Nationalists in 1987 .
Never before have Taiwanese elected their governor , and mayors have n't been elected in Taipei since 1967 and in Kaohsiung since 1979 .
The feverish campaigning testifies to the enthusiasm with which Taiwanese have grasped democracy .
Taipei 's streets are awash with banners .
Callers wanting to discuss election issues besiege radio phone-in shows .
Campaigners roam the streets banging cymbals and drums , and gesturing `` V '' for victory to passersby .
At election rallies , ordinary Taiwanese practically line up to discuss election issues with foreign reporters -- a far cry from the pre-1987 years of martial law , when Taiwanese were afraid to discuss politics even among themselves .
The New Party , which claims 50,000 members , is the smallest of Taiwan 's three major parties and is not considered a frontrunner in Saturday 's polls .
But it could still play a crucial role by splitting the Nationalist vote .
That could open the door for a force people like Fan do n't want in power -- the Democratic Progressive Party , which wants to dump the constitutional tie with China and make Taiwan independent .
In Taipei , where its supporters are concentrated , the New Party 's Jaw Shau-kong could draw enough votes from Nationalist incumbent Huang Ta-chou and hand a historic victory to the DPP 's Chen Shui-bian .
But despite that scenario , people like Fan say they can no longer support the Nationalists with a clear conscience .
`` We are disgusted with everything Lee has done , '' said Fan , fixing her listener with jet-black eyes .
`` We are the only real Nationalists . ''
She was referring to Lee Teng-hui , who took power in 1988 as the island 's first Taiwanese-born president and is credited with steering Taiwan peacefully from virtual dictatorship to democracy .
But for New Party supporters , Lee has betrayed Nationalist principles , particularly the dream of reunification .
They fear that despite his denials , the secretly wants an independent Taiwan .
Others said they were sickened by the allegations of Nationalist corruption and vote-buying .
Some also blamed both the Nationalists and the DPP for the excesses that have accompanied democracy , such as campaign violence .
`` Taiwanese democracy has developed too fast , '' said Lo Feng-hsiang , a medicine importer who was among several thousand New Party supporters at a rally in central Taipei Tuesday night .
`` We need some peace . ''
Many of those at the rally were worried about whether the Nationalists are veering toward declaring Taiwan 's independence -- a move Beijing says would provoke war .
`` I love the Nationalist Party , but it ignores our wishes , '' said a man who gave his surname as Huang .
He was switching his support to the New Party after 50 years as a Nationalist , he said , adding : `` We ca n't run away from reunification with the mainland . ''
Dino Radja scored 26 points and the Boston Celtics survived a late 3-point barrage by Detroit as they got above .500 for the first time this season with a 118-115 win Wednesday night .
The Pistons made five 3-pointers in 1:07 to close a 110-100 deficit to 116-115 with six seconds remaining .
Dominique Wilkins then made two free throws for Boston with five seconds to go .
The Celtics , who never trailed , got a season-high 21 points from Rick Fox , 18 while Radja had 12 rebounds .
The Pistons were paced by Terry Mills with a season-high 37 points .
