Botswana and South Korea pledged closer economic and political ties Thursday at a summit meeting in Seoul .
Botswana President Ketumile Masire said he hoped his visit would help form greater economic cooperation , the presidential office said .
South Korea 's Kim Young-sam welcomed Masire , and explained Seoul 's continuing efforts to bring rival North Korea 's nuclear program under international guidelines .
The Communist North is suspected of making nuclear weapons .
Masire , who arrived Wednesday for a three-day visit , is to meet heads of leading conglomerates .
He is the first president to visit since the two countries established diplomatic ties in 1968 .
A Japanese bank is in court seeking a foreclosure notice on the owners of the Koolau Golf Course .
The Longterm Credit Bank of Japan says Minami Corp. owes it more than $ 30 million , and has been in default of its loan for over two years .
The bank wants to foreclose on the golf course in hopes of forcing the company to sell the course , a bank attorney said .
There are no plans to close the golf course .
HONOLULU -LRB- AP -RRB- -- A group of Hawaii businessmen are planning to open the first Subway sandwich store in the former Soviet Union .
A Subway store is set to open in the Russian city of St. Petersburg on Dec. 7 , according to John Finney , who heads the local business group that owns exclusive rights to Subway franchises in Russia and the Baltic .
If the store is successful , as many as 25 to 30 more could be opened in St. Petersburg and as many as 200 in Russia by 2005 , Finney said .
Finney and his Nevada-based East West Invest Limited Partnership have been working for three years to open a store in Russia .
`` This thing has been unbelievably expensive and frustrating , '' Finney said Wednesday .
`` We have no clue as to how we 're going to do it . ''
A threat by Bosnian Serbs to shell a Canadian peacekeeping camp near Sarajevo did not materialize Wednesday , but Canadians kept a wary eye on Serb army movements .
The Serbs threatened Monday to shell the camp in Visoko within 48 hours .
By dusk Wednesday , when no attack came , a cautious sense of relief spread through camp .
Troops had been on high alert , filling sandbags , posting more lookouts and wearing flak jackets .
`` It 's still seen as a possibility but getting more remote by the day , '' said Capt. Tom Newton , a camp spokesman .
`` There 's little reported activity in the camp area . ''
On Sunday , a Serb rocket attack caused minor damage to a building .
`` People are uncomfortable with the whole idea of shelling , obviously , but they get used to the idea and get on with their job , '' said Newton , 30 , a native of Victoria .
Canadians monitor Serb army movements by several means , including radio reports from 55 Canadians detained for more than a week by Serbs at various locations near Visoko .
Meanwhile , Prime Minister Jean Chretien expressed frustration in an interview with Paris daily Le Monde , saying : `` The peacekeepers in Bosnia have become a sort of armed Red Cross , in a badly defined role .
`` To be in Bosnia is difficult for us .
It 's a European problem , and we are North Americans .
The Americans want to control everything and fight down to the last Canadian and Frenchman . ''
In Ottawa , Defense Minister David Collenette said it 's `` a shame and a disgrace '' that Canada is not in the five-country Contact Group trying to negotiate peace in the former Yugoslavia .
He suggested Chretien will raise the matter in Budapest this weekend at the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe .
Canada has one of the biggest UN contingents in the region -- 800 troops in Bosnia and 1,200 in Croatia -- while Contact Group members Germany and the United States have none there .
Things went badly Wednesday for UN Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali , who went to Sarajevo to work for a ceasefire and try to persuade Serbs to stop detaining more than 400 UN troops as insurance against NATO air strikes .
Serb leaders refused to meet him and he was jeered by Sarajevo residents while visiting the Muslim-led Bosnian government .
An orange alert at the Canadian camp at Visoko was being observed Wednesday and was to stay during the night , requiring personnel to wear flak jackets outside and cancel non-essential trips outside camp .
The camp went to the highest level -- red -- Monday night , forcing personnel to sleep in bunkers and sea containers in two camp buildings .
About 400 Canadians stay in the camp at night .
Since Monday , 100 non-essential personnel have slept in nearby Kiseljak , returning to the camp during the day .
Maj. Dean Milner , senior officer among Canadian detainees , makes daily contact with his soldiers and Serb commanders , said camp spokesman Newton .
`` Everything has been pretty cordial so far and they 've been treated fairly , '' he said .
`` Everybody in camp just wants to give a call home and let everybody know they 're OK . ''
After nearly half a century , South Korea on Thursday regained peacetime control over its armed forces from the United States .
The turnover was part of an effort to lower the profile of the U.S. military and push South Korea toward self-reliance in defending itself .
`` I am here to express my happiness that we have earned back the right to control our own forces today , '' Gen. Lee Yang-ho , chairman of the joint chiefs of staff , said at an elaborate ceremony marking the change .
Dozens of honor guards , some dressed in black and white traditional Korean costumes and others in brightly colored red and blue uniforms with gold braid , saluted Lee as a brass band played .
Earlier Thursday , Lee received the `` baton of command '' from President Kim Young-sam , the head of the armed forces , at the presidential palace .
Shortly after the beginning of the Korean War in 1950 , South Korea turned over the command of its military to U.N. forces , headed by the United States .
Thursday 's transfer also has symbolic significance in South Korea 's continuing standoff against North Korea .
The Communist North considers the South a `` puppet regime '' controlled by the United States , and has pointed to Seoul 's lack of command over its own armed forces as evidence .
The North has repeatedly used the argument to snub the South and refuse talks on improving relations .
The two Koreas never signed a peace treaty after their three-year war , and still have nearly 2 million troops along their border .
Thursday 's ceremony followed Wednesday 's signing of a note of exchange to complete the transfer .
Under the agreement , the U.S. side reassumes command in times of crisis or war , and still controls certain functions even in peacetime , such as the early-warning system and joint military exercises .
Some 35,000 U.S. troops are stationed in South Korea .
About 1 million American soldiers fought in the Korean War .
