Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao 's personal popularity and the strength of his Congress Party was being tested in an election Thursday in his home state .
Voting for state legislatures in two south Indian states was seen as an important bellwether for Congress , which already has suffered setbacks in the north and must retain its support in the south .
A loss in his own state of Andhra Pradesh could unleash rivalries in the governing party that Rao suppressed with difficulty last year .
Results will be announced Dec. 9 for elections in Andhra Pradesh , Karnataka and two other states that voted last month .
The voting is staggered to allow police forces to move from one to another to protect polling stations .
The Andhra Pradesh campaign was marred by violence from left-wing militants , the Peoples War Group , that claims to fight for peasants ' rights .
Land mines set by the militants killed at least 29 people in the last week .
The Congress campaign in Andhra Pradesh was thrown into disarray by the promise of an aging film star-turned-politician , N.T. Rama Rao , to sell rice to the poor at two rupees per kilogram -LRB- three cents per pound -RRB- -- six times less than the market rate .
Pursuing free market reforms , Rao could offer no subsidies to match his opponent 's challenge .
Rama Rao , 72 , who built a popular image by playing Hindu deities in classic films in the local Telugu language , campaigned with the help of his young crowd-pulling wife , whom he married last year .
The prime minister put his own prestige at stake by campaigning hard in his state , but his party 's prospects were hurt by infighting among the local politicians .
Unfazed by the prospect of a complete withdrawal of all U.N. peacekeepers , Bosnia 's rebel Serbs refused even to meet with the U.N. chief to discuss a nationwide cease-fire .
U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali said it may be time to send U.N. troops home after his six-hour mission to Sarajevo on Wednesday failed to move the two sides toward peace .
The threat reflects a growing frustration as the Serbs continue their assaults and the Muslim-led government refuses new concessions .
U.N. peacekeepers are being held hostage and the West is divided about how to respond .
Boutros-Ghali said Wednesday he will not recommend a pullout `` for the time being . ''
But he said `` it will become impossible '' to sustain support for the peacekeepers in the Security Council unless the Serbs and the government agree to talk peace and cooperate with the United Nations .
In New York , French U.N. Ambassador Jean-Bernard Merimee said `` there is no question '' of a withdrawal now , `` but if the situation continues to deteriorate , it will be more difficult to keep the troops there . ''
A withdrawal by peacekeepers would likely lead to more fighting and could be dangerous for the departing troops , as both Bosnian Serbs and government forces rush U.N. camps to seize equipment before it can be destroyed .
It also would cause widespread hardship , Boutros-Ghali said , because the United Nations feeds an estimated 3 million people across the former Yugoslavia .
Most are in Bosnia .
More than 200,000 people are dead or missing in the 2 -LCB- - year conflict launched by Serbs after Bosnia 's Muslim-Croat majority voted to declare independence from Serb-led Yugoslavia .
Tens of thousands more have been forced to flee their homes .
Serbs have rejected a peace plan that would reduce their war-won land holdings to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
On Wednesday , Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic told Boutros-Ghali that his government would negotiate only if Serbs accept the peace plan .
He said they have proposed a three-month cease-fire , but the Serbs want something more permanent .
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic refused even to meet Boutros-Ghali .
The Bosnian Serbs would n't mind seeing the United Nations leave Bosnia , believing it would allow them to force the government to settle on Serb terms .
Boutros-Ghali 's visit followed admissions from top U.S. and NATO officials that they ca n't force a solution to the conflict without a huge ground force no one is willing to provide .
The impact of airstrikes is questionable .
NATO struck three times last week on Serb positions near the U.N.-designated `` safe area '' of Bihac in northwest Bosnia .
The action only prompted the Serbs to take more than 400 U.N. soldiers hostage as insurance against more bombing .
NATO members provide two-thirds of the peacekeepers .
Forty-five Britons were released Wednesday , but some Canadian , French , Russian and Ukrainian peacekeepers have been held now for a week .
More than 100 Dutch troops have been hostage since Saturday .
U.N. sources , who spoke on condition of anonymity , reported `` intense bombardment '' around Bihac on Wednesday .
Some 70,000 mostly Muslim civilians are trapped in the government-held town , which is supposed to be under U.N. protection .
Four Indian Tamils have been jailed for traveling on fake Bangladesh passports , police said Thursday .
Their interrogation so far has not established any links with the Tamil movement for a separate homeland in Sri Lanka , a top police official said on condition of anonymity .
Police arrested them on Nov. 18 at Dhaka International airport when they arrived from Singapore .
The Tamils , in their thirties , claimed to have bought the passports for dlrs 700 each in Singapore and faked the names of Bangladesh citizens after they lost their Indian passports , police said .
