The Duchess of York stayed too long at the ball and decided to sleep in , arriving late Thursday in Melbourne and disappointing health professionals who had gathered to meet her .
The Duchess is on a three-day visit to Australia as worldwide patron of the Motor Neurone Disease Association -LRB- MNDA -RRB- .
MNDA is a fatal nerve disease .
She arrived for her brief visit two hours late because she was tired after her schedule in Sydney on Wednesday , which included a ball Wednesday night , organizers said .
Her late arrival forced the cancellation of a meeting with 40 health professionals representing the Victorian MNDA .
`` The Duchess was very tired after her activities in Sydney because there was a ball there last night , so I think that she decided to delay her trip out of Sydney so she could have a little longer rest , '' event coordinator Maxine Miller said .
`` We are very disappointed because we 've got nearly 300 people here who are very excited about her visit , '' she said ,
The Duchess -- Sarah Ferguson before her marriage to Britain 's Prince Andrew -- made a presentation to the MNDA at a function Thursday afternoon and met sufferers of the disease .
The Duchess said it was important to remember that sufferers , although physically affected , were not mentally disabled .
She recalled the death of a close friend from the disease nine years ago , saying they had continued to write a book together right up to his death .
