Australian rice is best suited for making Japan 's sweet-flavored bean paste , a private food research institute said Thursday .
The Central Miso Research Institute said bean paste made of Australian rice placed first among 26 entries in the sweet-flavored category in the institute 's annual miso contest last month .
Miso , or bean paste , is made by mixing steamed soybeans or rice with salt and a fermenting agent .
Miso , together with soy sauce , is the basic flavoring of Japanese cuisine .
`` We hope this result of the contest is n't misunderstood to question the quality of Australian rice , '' said Mitsuyuki Mori , a director of the Tokyo-based institute for 1,700 miso manufacturers across the country .
`` We came to know last year that Australian rice is as good as Japanese rice in cooking , '' Mori said .
`` Also , only good rice can make good miso . ''
Last fall , Japan suffered its worst rice harvest since World War II and the government allowed imports of foreign-grown rice for the first time in many decades to make up a shortage of more than 2 million tons .
For their dinner tables , however , most Japanese tried to obtain domestic rather than foreign rice .
In the sweet-flavored category , Japanese rice placed second and third and Thai rice fourth , followed by Chinese rice , Mori said .
Makers normally use rice for sweet miso and soybeans for salty miso .
Under a furious lobbying barrage from the Clinton administration and corporate executives , the U.S. Senate seemed headed toward approving a new world trade agreement in a vote Thursday .
Senior administration officials were guarding their vote counts , but Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen declared `` momentum is swinging our way '' and a smiling U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor assured reporters , `` We 're in very good shape . ''
Senate approval was the last legislative hurdle .
The House of Representatives endorsed the accord , negotiated under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade , by a 288-146 vote Tuesday .
Thirty-three countries already have ratified the 124-nation accord and , according to Bentsen , the others will act before Jan. 1 if the United States backs it .
For that to happen , 60 of the 100 senators must vote to override a parliamentary objection lodged by Sen. Robert Byrd .
According to an Associated Press survey , GATT proponents appeared to have achieved that number , when counting those who were leaning in favor but not firmly committed .
President Clinton hoped to widen the still-thin victory margin at a breakfast meeting Thursday with 20 lawmakers , including a late and crucial supporter , Senate Republican leader Bob Dole .
Opponents ' only hope was to muster 41 votes in favor of the procedural hurdle imposed by Byrd , who charges the accord will increase the U.S. deficit .
Under Senate rules , the legislation approving GATT must offset all of the projected dlrs 43 billion in lost tariff revenues over the first decade of the accord .
To make up for the lost tariffs , the administration is cutting farm subsidies and raising revenue with a number of measures , including changing the minimum rate on savings bonds and auctioning licenses for a new generation of wireless broadcast services .
But Byrd said the bill falls dlrs 14.5 billion short and some senators said they would not vote to bust the U.S. budget .
The administration counters that the tariff cuts , averaging 38 percent globally , will so stimulate economic growth that federal revenues will rise , not fall .
The AP head count had 60 senators for or leaning toward waiving budget rules , 26 against or leaning against and 14 undeclared .
Byrd and others also complain that a new Geneva-based World Trade Organization , created to referee trade disputes , will inevitably infringe on U.S. sovereignty .
But Dole , who had voiced the same concern , secured a promise from the administration to create an independent panel to review WTO decisions .
If U.S. interests were being harmed , the panel could recommend that Congress withdraw from the organization .
The administration is predicting 500,000 new American jobs as a result of increased U.S. export sales under GATT .
In addition to bringing foreign tariffs closer to U.S. levels , it reduces barriers to trade in agricultural goods and services and protects U.S. intellectual property , such as computer programs , from being pirated .
South Korea sold a record amount of products overseas in November but still ran a trade deficit of dlrs 292 million for the month , the Trade , Industry , and Energy Ministry said Thursday .
The November deficit , after a dlrs 88 million surplus in November last year , resulted from a continuing surge of capital goods imports , the ministry said in its monthly report .
Exports of dlrs 9.29 billion broke the previous monthly record of dlrs 8.89 billion , set in October .
Sales of semiconductors , petrochemical products , ships and automobiles pushed exports up by 26.4 percent from November last year , the ministry said .
But imports rose 32.0 percent from a year earlier to dlrs 9.58 billion , with capital goods purchases shooting up because of active corporate investment , the report added .
November 's trade brought the cumulative deficit for the year 's first 11 months to dlrs 6.30 billion , up from a deficit of dlrs 2.21 billion in January-November last year .
Champion Yasuei Yakushiji meets interim champion Joichiro Tatsuyoshi next week in Japan 's richest boxing match -- a World Boxing Council bantamweight unification title bout .
The two Japanese fighters each are to receive dlrs 1.7 million for the 12-round fight Sunday at Nagoya Municipal Gymnasium in central Japan .
