Fire continued to burn inside the Achille Lauro Thursday , a day after the flames forced the nearly 1,000 people aboard take to lifeboats and abandon the cruise ship off Somalia .
Two people were reported dead and one missing in the flight from the Achille Lauro , which gained notoriety in 1985 when Palestinian terrorists hijacked and killed a wheelchair-bound American passenger .
U.S. Navy personnel and commercial ship captains taking part in the rescue said the Achille Lauro was listing but in no danger of sinking Thursday morning .
`` She is presently listing at about 20 degrees .
There 's a tremendous amount of smoke and steam still coming from over three quarters of the length of the vessel , '' John Briand , captain of the oil tanker Lima , told the BBC .
The fire started Wednesday , apparently in the passenger area , but the cause was not known , said the ship 's owner , Starlauro of Genoa , Italy .
Eight people were injured in the fire .
About 60 crewmembers fought the fire before abandoning the 23,478-ton ship 210 kilometers -LRB- 130 miles -RRB- south of the Horn of Africa .
An official with the U.N. mission in Somalia put the ship 's position at about 25 kilometers -LRB- 15 miles -RRB- off the small Somali fishing village of Eil .
Capt. Ferdinando Lolli , a port official in Rome , said the ship was carrying 581 passengers and 404 crew .
Most of the crew was Italian , and the passengers mainly South African , German , Dutch and British .
Late Wednesday evening , Italian Coast Guard officials reported that one person from the Achille Lauro was still unaccounted for .
Italian news agencies identified the dead as a Briton and a German .
The Panamanian oil ship Hawaiian King was one of the first ships to arrive at the scene and took on about 800 people , said a coast guard official in Rome , Adm. Eugenio Sicurezza .
Many had to spend the night on the Hawaiian King 's deck , Briand said , and other ships sent over food , blankets and toiletries .
Two U.S. warships , the USS Gettysburg and USS Halyburton , arrived overnight and dispatched helicopters to ferry water , food and medical supplies to the survivors , said Cmdr. T. McCreary , spokesman for the U.S. Naval Forces Central Command in the Gulf .
`` Quite a few people were injured in the transfer -- there 's a few broken bones and some pretty tortured souls , '' Briand said , adding that many of the rescued passengers were elderly .
The commerical and Navy ships will divide up the passengers Thursday and send them on , mostly to Mombasa , Kenya , and Djibouti , McCreary said .
Others reportedly will be taken to the Seychelles .
Briand said the transfer was expected to take most of the day .
His ship was taking on the Achille Lauro 's 50 Honduran crewmembers .
The Achille Lauro left Genoa on Nov. 19 , stopped in Israel , and its next port of call was to be Durban , South Africa , on Friday , said Carla Gotta , a spokeswoman for the cruise ship 's owner .
The terrorists who hijacked the Achille Lauro in 1985 shot American Leon Klinghoffer and pushed him in his wheelchair off the ship .
The hijackers escaped the vessel and boarded a jet , but U.S. fighter planes forced it to land in Italy and the hijackers were captured .
Launched in 1946 in the Netherlands , the Achille Lauro was acquired 20 years later by the Neapolitan shipping dynasty .
It first transported Italian immigrant workers to and from Australia and was outfitted for pleasure cruises in 1970 .
The liner rammed a fishing boat in 1971 off Italy , killing a Neapolitan fisherman .
And on Dec. 2 , 1981 , fire broke out aboard ship off the Canary Islands .
Panicked passengers jumped into the sea , and two of them drowned .
In 10 years , a trip to a music store may involve sticking a card filled with computer memory chips into a vending machine , and downloading the latest hits into it , Japan 's NEC Corp. says .
NEC announced Thursday that it has developed a Walkman-like pocket stereo that uses such memory cards instead of tapes to store music .
The interchangeable cards are the size of fat credit cards , and contain rows of tiny computer memory chips .
Each card can currently hold up to 24 minutes of high-quality music , the company says .
But NEC says it will wait to commercialize the product .
The reason : the `` flash '' memory chips used in the cards are still so expensive that 24 minutes ' worth , or 32 megabytes , currently costs about dlrs 2,000 .
Prices of the chips are expected to drop , however , and NEC predicts that 90 minutes of capacity will be priced at about dlrs 100 in the year 2000 .
The rest of the player will cost only about dlrs 50 to make , and the circuitry eventually could be incorporated into the memory card itself , resulting in a card-size player , NEC spokesman Mark Pearce said .
Since the music is stored digitally in memory chips , the players are lighter than conventional cassettes and do n't have any moving parts to wear out or skip .
And unlike tapes , the chips allow instant random access to different music tracks .
The cards also could be used to store other kinds of information , including text , still pictures and moving images .
NEC is considering a version that could also function as a debit card , with each music purchase subtracted automatically from the total credit on the card , Pearce said .
The player , which NEC calls Silicon Audio , uses a compression method called MPEG to reduce the size of the music data , which otherwise would require eight times as much memory .
NEC is Japan 's largest semiconductor maker .
It announced earlier this week that it will invest 100 billion yen -LRB- dlrs 1.01 billion -RRB- over the next three years to build the world 's first line for making 256-megabit dynamic random-access memory chips .
Those would hold 16 times as much information as the largest chips now on the market , which are 16 megabit .
The new line will also be used to make high-capacity flash memories , the type used by the music player , NEC said .
Unlike DRAMs , flash memories maintain their data even after the power is turned off .
Two Christian zealots were sent to jail Thursday for killing a woman after a ceremony to exorcise demons they claimed were possessing her .
The accused told police that Joan Leonora Vollmer spoke in voices other than her own , that she had enormous strength and that her face sometimes took on the appearance of a dog or a pig .
Under sentences handed down in County Court , Leanne Merlyn Reichenbach , 32 , will serve four months in prison and David Andrew Klingner , 30 , will serve three months for the 1993 manslaughter of Mrs. Vollmer .
Two other defendants , Vollmer 's 56-year-old widower , Ralph Vollmer , and Matthew Paul Nuske , 22 , received suspended sentences of 12 and three months , respectively .
Mrs. Vollmer , 49 , died of a heart attack on Jan. 30 , 1993 , at her farm in Antwerp , near Horsham , after a weeklong attempt to rid her of demons , according to court testimony .
Her husband , Reichenbach , Klingner and Nuske held her on a chair for four hours in 102-degree Fahrenheit -LRB- 40-degree Celsius -RRB- heat .
They prayed over her , slapped her , forced her mouth open and massaged her neck and stomach .
Prosecutors said the stroking of her neck , on the carotid artery , triggered the fatal heart attack .
`` Unrestrained religious enthusiasm can well be , as we have found out here , a crime under our law and people should be made to know that it is , '' Judge Graeme Crossley told the defendants .
