Assault charges against five Aborigines charged with beating a teen-ager and a woman as tribal law punishment should be dropped , the Aboriginal Legal Service said Thursday .
Five Aborigines from the desert Jigalong community were charged with assault over punishment they inflicted last week on a 14-year-old girl and a 25-year-old woman .
Rob Riley , the service 's chief executive officer , said the five acted under the authority of community elders and should not have been charged under European law .
The beatings were linked to the death of an elderly community member after he was hit by a truck .
The two women were present when the accident occurred .
Under Aboriginal law , if someone dies of an unnatural cause , another person is generally held responsible for the death and punished accordingly .
Both females were severely beaten with crowbars , the girl was speared through the leg and hand and the woman had her arm broken .
A hospital staff member who treated the 14-year-old reported the attack to police .
Riley said the two women faced further punishment as a result of the charges being filed .
The police officer who pressed charges , however , disputed Riley 's account .
Det. Phillip Farris said community elders assisted police in laying the charges because the five acted without authority and did not properly inflict the punishment .
A mob of about 20 people attacked the girls at the man 's funeral and seven other people were speared during the attack , Farris said .
Riley said it was unfair for Australians of European descent to enforce white law on the entire population .
He noted white Australians were inconsistent in accepting some parts of Aboriginal culture , such as arts , while rejecting others .
