Fighting in the Bihac area of northwestern Bosnia could do more than cause a U.N. withdrawal from Bosnia .
It could draw Croatia back into war .
And that new fighting between Croatia and its rebel Serbs could mushroom into a much broader conflict .
Croatia is chafing that rebel Serbs still control over one-third of its territory , almost three years after a cease-fire ended six months of war between the two sides .
It holds out the option of taking the territory back by force .
Thousands of peacekeepers monitor an uneasy truce in Croatia .
Bosnia 's Bihac region , surrounded by Bosnian and Croatian Serbs , is the softest spot of Croatia 's vulnerable underbelly .
Serb-held territory that borders the Bihac area is less than 15 miles from Zagreb , the Croatian capital .
If Serbs control the area around Bihac , they will be able to cooperate more easily across the border , making it more difficult for Croatia to regain Serb-held territories .
Negotiations between the Serbs and Croats have been stalled , although the Serbs ' self-styled government late Wednesday recommended that a Serb assembly today accept an economic agreement .
If accepted , it would be the first accord between the foes since they agreed on a formal cease-fire March 29 , and could help to reduce tensions .
Croatian officials say they were ready to intervene in Bihac when rebel Serbs from Croatia crossed the border to fight Bosnia 's Muslim-led army .
But the Croat intervention was put off after NATO gave assurances it would prevent the fall of Bihac , said prominent hardliner Vladimir Seks , who is deputy speaker of parliament .
Three NATO airstrikes did nothing to stop the Serbs there , however , and now the United Nations is threatening to pull its peacekeepers out all together .
The Croatian parliament is working on a resolution that is expected to endorse intervention , but any decision would have to be made by President Franjo Tudjman .
Officials say the fighting in Bihac proves that Croats must look out for their own security .
`` If the Croatian army intervenes , it will not be to save Bihac , '' said Fran Visnar , a military analyst in Zagreb , `` but to use the opportunity to regain some of its territories . ''
However , if the Croatian government got involved , the Croatian Serbs would almost certainly get help from the Bosnian Serbs .
And it would be difficult for Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic to stay out of the conflict , despite his recent efforts to distance himself from his Bosnian Serb bretheren .
The United Nations has slapped sanctions against Serbia for whipping up nationalist Serb sentiment that ignited wars in Croatia and Bosnia .
The Bihac fighting could also threaten Bosnia 's Croat-Muslim federation .
A U.S.-brokered agreement , signed last March with great fanfare , ended a year of fierce fighting between Muslims and Croats in central Bosnia .
Some Croats now say there appears to be little point to the federation .
Unions on Thursday called off a general strike after the government agreed during all night talks to scale down cuts in Italy 's generous pension system .
Premier Silvio Berlusconi 's spokesman Jas Gawronski said the government and union leaders reached an accord on pension reforms , which are part of the 1995 deficit-fighting budget now being debated in the Senate .
The strike , scheduled for Friday , would have been the second general strike in six weeks .
`` We are talking about a very satisfactory agreement that concludes a complex dispute , '' Giancarlo Fontanelli leader of the UIL union told ANSA .
Union officials sat down with the premier and cabinet minsters early Thursday morning and worked through the night to arrive at the settlement .
Making good on a promise to upgrade relations with Taiwan , the United States is sending Transportation Secretary Federico Pena here Sunday to attend an economic conference .
Pena is only the second U.S. Cabinet member to visit the island since 1979 , when Washington switched diplomatic recognition from Taiwan to the rival Communist government in Beijing .
Carla Hills , the then U.S. trade representative , came in 1992 when Washington lifted a ban on Cabinet member visits in a battle with European and Asian countries for contracts in a massive plan to improve Taiwan 's infrastructure .
Welcoming the announcement of Pena 's visit , Foreign Ministry spokesman Rock Leng said Thursday it was `` a step to enhance understanding and pave the way for the development of better relations . ''
In September , the United States announced a modest relaxation of restrictions on Cabinet-level contact between the two governments .
The change came in recognition of Taiwan 's economic might , which has made it the United States ' fifth largest trading partner , and of its rapidly developing democracy and improved human rights record .
Pena 's visit was seen likely to provoke protests from China , which regards Taiwan as a renegade province and has sought to keep it in diplomatic isolation .
Taiwan is the seat of the Nationalist government that fled the Chinese mainland in 1949 after losing a civil war to the Communists .
Two weeks ago , at a meeting in Jakarta , Chinese President Jiang Zemin warned President Clinton that any wavering on Taiwan would be `` an insult to the Chinese people . ''
Pena , heading a six-member delegation , will attend a U.S.-Taiwan economic meeting during his three-day visit , officials said .
The annual conference is the same one that Hills attended in 1992 .
The officials declined to comment on newspaper reports that he will call on President Lee Teng-hui .
Hills met Lee when she was here .
Former U.S. President George Bush will address the opening session of the three-day economic meeting on Monday , officials said .
China urged Britain Thursday to find ways to meet a U.N. deadline to settle the problem of Vietnamese boat people in Hong Kong by the end of next year .
Foreign Ministry spokesman Chen Jian said the United Nations decided in 1989 that Vietnamese boat people in Hong Kong should not be settled in the British colony and that the problem should be resolved by the end of 1995 , two years before Hong Kong reverts to Chinese rule .
However , Hong Kong 's colonial government has said recently that it can not repatriate the 24,000 Vietnamese still in refugee camps in the territory by the deadline .
Chen said , `` The British Hong Kong government has the responsibilty to settle this issue by the end of 1995 instead of leaving the burden to the future Hong Kong special administrative region '' under Chinese rule .
`` We will seek ways to urge the British side to settle this issue no later than the end of 1995 , '' he added .
Asked what China would do if Vietnamese refugees remained in Hong Kong in 1997 , Chen said the deadline must be adhered to `` since it 's a decision of the United Nations , and China and Britain are both members .
Both countries are committed to this program of action . ''
In response to Hong Kong 's assertion that some of the refugees are ethnic Vietnamese from China , Chen said the Beijing governmment was willing to take back those `` few people '' who are identified as Chinese citizens and who are willing to return to China .
Thailand has freed an Australian and a New Zealander serving long sentences for heroin possession after the king granted them pardons , embassy officials said Thursday .
King Bhumibol Adulyadej pardoned Harry Yau , 45 , of Sydney , Australia , and Alan Robert King , 40 , of Dunedin , New Zealand , last week .
No reasons were given for the pardons , granted before his Dec. 5 birthday .
Yau , who was arrested in 1986 , had been serving a life sentence commuted to 20 years , said an Australian Embassy spokesman who declined to be named .
Yau already has returned to Australia .
The spokesman said 21 other Australians are serving sentences in Thailand , most of them on drug charges .
King , who was arrested in 1984 , was serving a life sentence commuted to 50 years .
Three other New Zealanders remain in Thai prisons .
King is to return home in the coming days , said an official at the New Zealand Embassy , who also requested anonymity .
