Police Minister Moshe Shahal recommended Thursday that Israel bar entrance to Palestinians living in the West Bank and Gaza until their self-rule government proved capable of preventing attacks on Israelis .
Shahal spoke to Israel radio a day after a Palestinian axed a 19-year-old woman soldier to death and two days after Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin said he wanted to begin separating Palestinians and Israelis .
Talk of dismantling small , isolated settlements was also growing this week , as Islamic militants opposed to the Israel-PLO peace talks escalate attacks on Israelis .
Thirty-two Israelis have been killed since Oct. 1 .
`` There is no alternative other than to demand separation , '' Shahal said .
`` Separation means that we do not have to open the territory out of economic and employment concerns until the Palestinians prove that they can prevent attacks . ''
Tens of thousands of Palestinians work in Israel and lose their only means of livelihood when barred from jobs by closures imposed following attacks on Israelis .
The latest closure , which is gradually being lifted , sealed off the West Bank and Gaza following the Oct. 19 bombing of a Tel Aviv bus that left 22 civilians dead .
But despite the strict restrictions on West Bank and Gaza residents entering Israel , Wednesday 's Palestinian assailant managed to sneak through army roadblocks into the northern Israeli town of Afula .
`` We must reach a formula of separation , the ability to close off the hundreds of entrances that exist today , '' Shahal said .
Shahal added that he was suggesting a permanent separation as part of the second stage of the autonomy accord with the Palestinians .
Negotiations over the next stage of the agreement , that includes elections of a Palestinian governing council , are to resume next week in Cairo , Egypt .
The Cabinet is expected to discuss the upcoming talks during its weekly meeting Sunday , Shahal added .
Asian basketball players who are short in height but not on talent want an international league of their own .
The Malaysian Basketball Association suggested Thursday that the game be split up into different height divisions as boxing is divided into weight divisions .
Association president Loke Yuen Yow said Asians were tired of losing to taller Americans and Europeans .
Under a proposal submitted to the German-based International Basketball Federation and the Asian Basketball Confederation , shorter teams from around the world would compete against each other .
`` To narrow the gap , there is a need for a change in line with weightlifting and boxing , which have different -LRB- weight -RRB- categories , '' Loke said .
Loke suggested a second division of basketball be created for players under 6 feet , 3 inches -LRB- 190 centimeters -RRB- .
Vietnam 's Foreign Ministry gave credence Thursday to unofficial reports that the Association of Southeast Asian Nations has already voted to admit Vietnam as its seventh member .
Vietnam has long sought membership in anticipation of trade and investment benefits from closer ties to the more developed ASEAN economies .
A Foreign Ministry spokesman , Ngo Van Hoa , told a news conference that ASEAN Secretary-General Ajit Singh announced the decision in a recent interview with a Malaysian newspaper , the Star .
Asked if Vietnam had received any direct notification of the decision from ASEAN , Hoa only smiled and said , `` I am asking you to read between the lines . ''
But he indicated that Vietnam regards the decision as official and final .
Again quoting the Star , he said ASEAN officials made the decision at a meeting in Brunei Nov. 3-5 , with the actual admission to come next July when ASEAN foreign ministers hold their regular meeting .
Vietnam hopes for economic benefits from membership , but its admission also would dramatize the extent to which former Cold War divisions have melted away in the region .
ASEAN was formed in 1967 at the height of the Cold War as a buffer against the spread of communism in Asia , represented by Vietnam and China .
It has become influential and active only in recent years since shifting its focus more heavily to economic cooperation .
The current members are Brunei , Indonesia , Malaysia , the Philippines , Singapore and Thailand .
The Orlando Magic are looking every bit like the U.S. National Basketball Association title contenders they were projected to be at the start of the season .
A 114-107 victory over the Sacramento Kings gave Orlando its eighth consecutive win , a record for the fifth-year franchise , and the best record in the league at 10-2 .
`` How you start is important , but how you finish means more , '' Magic coach Brian Hill said .
`` It may be imperative that we got out to this type of start . ''
The Magic have been winning with balanced scoring , and Wednesday night 's victory was no different .
Shaquille O'Neal led the way with 41 points , while Anfernee Hardaway added 23 and Nick Anderson 22 .
