In China 's only World AIDS Day activity not organized by the government , about a dozen activists took to Beijing streets Thursday to distribute pamphlets about AIDS prevention .
The leafleting was sponsored by the AIDS Action Project , a group with no government ties and no money , said one member , who asked that his name not be used .
The group wants to encourage gay and bisexual men to serve as peer educators , he said .
It called for volunteers late Wednesday on a radio program .
It 's rare for a group not sanctioned by the government to be allowed to organize high-profile public activities such as passing out leaflets .
The government 's apparent tolerance for the volunteers Thursday was in line with recent calls for more efforts to teach people how to avoid the spread of AIDS .
The leaflet the volunteers distributed on Wangfujing Street , one of the city 's main shopping areas , and in other parts of the city gave basic information about AIDS .
It also said drug abusers and prostitutes , who are at high risk for the disease , `` have rights as human beings that should be respected . ''
Prostitution and drugs have become growing problems in China since economic reforms and opening to the outside world began in the late 1970s .
Until recently , Chinese officials characterized AIDS as a disease that strikes only foreigners or fringe groups such as drug users .
The director of a government-sponsored AIDS hotline was accused of empathizing with homosexuals and prostitutes and fired last year .
Homosexuality is not accepted in China , and is technically illegal .
This fall , an official report noted an alarming lack of knowledge about AIDS and called for strengthening anti-AIDS programs .
AIDS is spread through sexual contact , contaminated needles shared by drug users , and infected blood or blood products and from pregnant women to their offspring .
Government statistics show 1,453 people have tested positive for HIV , the virus that causes AIDS , since 1985 in China , the China Daily reported Thursday .
But AIDS activists said the number would be higher if the government used statistical methods to estimate the incidence of the virus , rather than simply counting the number of known cases .
The China Daily said experts at an international AIDS symposium this week in Beijing concluded that AIDS could spread rapidly in China in the next decade if preventive measures are not taken immediately .
They also called for government funding for laboratories for blood testing and mass publicity campaigns to explain the testing 's importance .
China 's blood supply now is checked for HIV only in Beijing , Shanghai , Canton and Yunnan province , the official newspaper said .
Yunnan is on the border with Burma , a major source of heroin .
Nearly 200 blood donors nationwide have been carriers of the virus , the official Xinhua News Agency reported Thursday .
Officially sanctioned World AIDS Day events in Beijing included educational activities at hospitals and a television special .
On Wednesday , about 200 people attended the opening of a play titled `` Things Related to AIDS . ''
Another show was planned Thursday .
A law strengthening Bangladesh 's electoral watchdog agency has failed to satisfy the opposition , whose campaign against the government has produced a nine-month political stalemate .
The law , passed by Parliament late Wednesday , provides for voter identity cards and gives the Election Commission authority to punish officials involved in malpractice .
It also empowers the commission to stop voting at any polling station if it suspects `` coercion , intimidation and pressure . ''
The legislation was rejected by the opposition , which has boycotted Parliament since March 2 , accusing Prime Minister Khaleda Zia 's government of election fraud , corruption and mismanagement .
Opposition spokesman Mohammad Nasim said the bill `` is nowhere close to our demand for free and fair polls under an interim government . ''
The opposition wants the government to step down three months before elections , yielding to a neutral caretaker government that would supervise voting .
Mrs. Zia rejects the demand as `` unjustified and unconstitutional '' and has offered to bring opposition members into a pre-election Cabinet .
The next election is scheduled for 1996 .
After international mediation failed last month to break the deadlock , opposition leader Sheikh Hasina called for an accelerated campaign of national strikes and demonstrations .
On Tuesday , a strike backed by a rail and road blockade choked off routine business in the capital .
Hasina has called for a 48-hour general strike next week .
Businessmen have complained that the prolonged dispute is hurting exports , discouraging foreign investment and diverting the government 's attention from its program to deregulate the economy .
Ernesto Zedillo becomes president Thursday , promising profound political and legal reforms to match the market-opening that resulted in a free trade agreement with the United States and Canada .
The 42-year-old U.S.-trained economist caps an unlikely journey when he assumes the red , green and white presidential sash to start a six-year term as leader of this country of 90 million .
The former Mexicali shoeshine boy achieved a Yale University doctorate in economics .
Bypassed once for his party 's presidential nomination , he was thrust into the campaign by the March assassination of Luis Donaldo Colosio , first choice of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party , or PRI .
He won the presidency Aug. 21 in the most credible elections ever held in Mexico .
U.S. Vice President Al Gore and President Fidel Castro are among 63 foreign dignitaries attending the inauguration .
Zedillo has pledged to use the near-absolute powers of Mexico 's presidency to weaken his own office .
He says he will give greater independence to the congress , the courts and local governments as well as the PRI itself .
He says he will end the practice of having the president hand-pick all top PRI candidates .
Zedillo , former budget and planning minister under President Carlos Salinas de Gortari , is sure to continue his predecessor 's free-market economic policies -- a commitment underlined by the Cabinet choices announced Wednesday .
Leading negotiators of the North American Free Trade Agreement were named heads of treasury , trade and foreign policy .
Seven other free-market economists also were named to the 25-person cabinet .
Zedillo also made a political opening by naming an opposition party member to the Cabinet for the first time .
Antonio Lozano , a conservative , will be attorney general -- a crucial post since Zedillo has made fighting government corruption a major part of his campaign .
The Cabinet includes three women -- the most ever appointed at the outset of a Mexican administration .
They are Norma Samaniego as controller ; Silvia Hernandez for tourism ; and biologist Julia Carabias for fisheries .
On Tuesday , Zedillo reached out to the left as well , meeting with leaders of the Democratic Revolution Party and promising reforms to help make Mexico more democratic .
Salinas never met publicly with leaders of that main leftist opposition during his administration .
The party apparently responded by pulling some 4,000 protesters out of the capital 's main plaza Wednesday , indicating an effort to avoid the confrontations that marred Salinas ' inauguration in 1988 .
The demonstrators were protesting alleged vote fraud in recent state elections .
A protest was planned Thursday by leftist supporters of the Zapatista National Liberation Army rebels of southern Mexico .
That rebellion , stalled since January by a cease-fire , is one of the toughest problems facing the new president .
President Boris Yeltsin ordered the government to sell off shares of Russia 's largest state television and radio company , with 51 percent of the stock remaining in state hands .
Ostankino , once called commonwealth television , is broadcast throughout the former Soviet Union .
Its Moscow broadcasting tower was the scene of the worst fighting during the political uprising in October 1993 .
Yeltsin 's decree Wednesday said the new venture , called Russian Public Television , would inherit Ostankino 's nationwide Channel One and would pay for the broadcast time on unchanged terms .
Ostankino chief Alexander Yakovlev , who was the architect of `` glasnost '' under former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev , told the ITAR-Tass news agency that the sale would help make Russia 's television independent .
Yeltsin 's opponents have complained that state television favors the government and offers biased coverage of political events -- charges that Russian broadcast executives deny .
Twelve major companies and organizations will buy the 49 percent of Ostankino 's stock , including ITAR-Tass , Menatep , Stolichny and Inkombank commercial banks , Aeroflot International Airlines and the Avtovaz car manufacturer .
NATO foreign ministers met Thursday to begin laying the groundwork for the entry of former Warsaw Pact foes as new members in the coming years .
But their two-day meeting was likely to be overshadowed by the crisis in Bosnia that has put extraordinary strains on the relationship between the United States and its European allies .
During the talks , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher was expected to tell the allies the Clinton administration has swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
It marks the first time in the post-World War II history of the alliance that the Europeans , led by France , prevailed over Washington in formulating a major policy .
The foreign ministers , though , are anxious their talks not be entirely hijacked by the Bosnian crisis .
They intend to order a study that would set out the terms and conditions for the acceptance of East European countries as new members .
`` The main issue will be the enlargement -LRB- of NATO -RRB- ... I do n't think there will be a huge discussion of Bosnia , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd as he entered the headquarters of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
Laos has agreed for the first time to let former North Vietnamese soldiers into that country to help locate possible burial sites of missing American servicemen , U.S. officials said Thursday .
Laos ' agreement marks a breakthrough in efforts with Vietnam and the United States to resolve the fates of some of the 505 Americans listed as missing in that country .
`` This is something the United States has wanted to do for a long time , getting Vietnamese witnesses into Laos , '' said Navy Lt. Cmdr. Thomas Adams , who works at the Hawaii headquarters of the unit responsible for MIA investigations .
Four Vietnamese , who claim to have witnessed the burials of several Americans inside Laos during the war in Indochina , will join in searches for their remains later this month and in January , said James Wold , U.S. deputy assistant secretary of defense for POW-MIA affairs .
Wold led an American delegation that met with Laotian and Vietnamese officials about cases that require the help of both Asian countries .
`` The progress was good , '' Wold said after the four-hour meeting ended Thursday in Hanoi .
`` We achieved most of our objectives . ''
He said the three sides agreed on a mechanism for additional visits by Vietnamese witnesses in other investigations .
Representatives of the three countries last met in November 1993 to discuss joint MIA investigations .
President Clinton has said Vietnam must show more cooperation in such efforts with neighboring Laos before the United States will establish full diplomatic relations with Hanoi .
Wold said Laotian and Vietnamese officials both expressed a willingness to help , but he spoke with particular praise about Vietnam 's efforts .
`` I would characterize their cooperation in working jointly with the U.S. and Laos as excellent , '' Wold said .
U.S. officials have said Laos generally has lagged behind Vietnam in helping to settle cases of the 2,214 Americans unaccounted for from the war .
Communist Vietnamese troops occupied large sections of Laos during the conflict .
Investigators plan to take one Vietnamese witness later this month to help look for evidence of 11 Americans missing at Phou Pha Thi mountain in northern Houaphan province , said Air Force Maj. Roger Overturf , public affairs officer for the MIA investigation task force .
Communist troops overran a secret U.S. aircraft navigation base there in 1968 .
Another three Vietnamese veterans will travel to central Savannakhat province in January for the search for clues to eight airmen shot down while flying in an AC-47 aircraft in 1966 , Overturf said .
Winning Laotian cooperation for the Vietnamese to visit the sites has been `` a tough nut to crack , '' Adams said .
Laos insisted on interviewing the witnesses first to gauge their credibility before letting them inside Laotian territory , Adams said .
Of the remaining U.S. servicemen still unaccounted for from the war , the Pentagon lists 1,624 in Vietnam , 505 in Laos and eight in China .
Most are known to be dead , U.S. officials say .
The Export-Import Bank of Japan is planning to extend 26 million dollars in a loan for a Japanese-Dutch joint venture for battery production in Poland , bank officials said Thursday .
The governmental bank and the joint venture company are expected to sign an agreement on the loan while President Lech Walesa is on a three-day visit to Japan beginning Tuesday .
Since Paris Club donor countries agreed to reduce Poland 's debts at its session in April 1991 , Japan has not provided public loans to the East European nation .
However , the loan is exceptional because it will help fund a private firm 's project , the officials said .
Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. , Matsushita Battery Industrial Co. and N.V. Philips Gloeilampenfabrieken of the Netherlands set up the joint venture , called Philips Matsushita Poland S.A.
It is capitalized at 9.5 million dollars .
The firm will produce manganate batteries starting next September , with annual output expected to reach 600 million units in fiscal 1999 .
Factory construction is now underway .
The loan will be used to finance the building of production facilities and establishment of a sales network , bank officials said .
Red Army Faction terrorist Irmgard Moeller leaves prison .
Irmgard Moeller , the Red Army Faction terrorist who blew up three American soldiers with a car bomb 22 years ago , walked out of prison Thursday after being freed early from her life sentence .
Wearing jeans , a leather jacket and red sweater , Moeller smiled , waved and gathered up bouquets as supporters `` international solidarity . ''
About 150 supporters with red flags , champagne bottles and Christmas gifts waited outside the blue steel prison gates , chanting revolutionary slogans and singing 1960s anti-Vietnam War songs .
Demands for Moeller 's freedom have been a feature of leftist demonstrations for years .
The U.S. State Department and relatives of the victims objected to her release .
Moeller , 47 , the longest serving female prisoner in Germany , was freed because of her poor health , although she has shown no remorse and refused to cooperate with psychiatric evaluations to determine whether she is still dangerous .
A court in the state of Schleswig-Holstein , where the prison is located , determined that she is not likely to commit another violent crime , and placed her on probation for five years .
Moeller 's release could lead to freedom for the seven other Red Army Faction terrorists still imprisoned in Germany .
After its last actions -- assassinating a German official in 1991 and blowing up a new prison in 1993 -- the Red Army Faction issued statements saying it was ending its 20-year campaign of attacks on what it called `` imperialist '' targets .
Moeller was convicted of driving one of two explosives-laden cars that blew up in a parking lot at U.S. Army Headquarters in Heidelberg on May 24 , 1972 .
Capt. Clyde R. Bonner and two enlisted men , Charles L. Peck and Ronald A. Woodward , were killed .
In a statement after the bombing , the leftist Red Army Faction called the attack a protest against `` genocide '' in Vietnam .
Moeller was arrested six weeks after the attack and sentenced to life in prison plus 15 years .
She lived through 12 hunger strikes and survived the night of Oct. 18 , 1977 , when three other imprisoned Red Army Faction leaders were found dead in their cells in what authorities said were suicides .
Moeller was found with four stabs in her chest , but survived .
Politicians , theologians , authors and her prison warden campaigned for Moeller 's release on humanitarian grounds , although she apparently has not given up her political views .
The news magazine Der Spiegel reported recently that Moeller still believes `` the armed struggle was legitimate . ''
In a 1992 interview with the magazine , she was asked if she felt sympathy for the victims of Red Army Faction violence .
`` I ca n't deal with this so personally and individually , '' she replied .
A striking black-haired woman when she went to jail at the age of 25 , Moeller 's lined face and graying hair now reflect her long life behind bars .
She is also said to be in deteriorating health , suffering from skin , eye and other ailments .
State prosecutors did not challenge the decision ordering her release .
But the U.S. State Department said on Nov. 1 , before the court 's decision , that the U.S. government opposes freeing terrorists who show no remorse for politically motivated attacks .
U.S. Air Force Sgt. Charles Bonner , the 29-year-old son of victim Clyde Bonner , contacted German officials to protest against the decision .
`` I was only 7 when my father was killed .
Our housing was just across from that parking lot .
That 's something I 'll never forget .
I think releasing her is ridiculous , '' he said in a telephone conversation last week .
A daughter of strict Roman Catholic parents from Munich , Moeller became involved in the leftist student movement of the 1960s , got to know the founders of the Red Army Faction , Andreas Baader and Ulrike Meinhof , and went underground in 1971 .
Moeller could throw some light on the deaths of Baader , Jan-Carl Raspe and Gudrun Ensslin , who died in October 1977 in the top-security Stuttgart Stammheim prison .
German authorities and foreign experts ruled the deaths suicides , but Moeller , who survived , has always maintained they were state-ordered murders .
Early in her imprisonment , Moeller was held in isolation and harsh conditions in Stammheim , with no human contact apart from her guards and wardens .
In 1980 , she was moved to the relative comfort of the Luebeck prison .
There , she and two other convicted terrorists shared a special unit that includes a kitchen , a bathroom , a television room and a library .
The government will appeal a court ruling that could deprive Hong Kong anti-corruption officials of one of their most powerful weapons .
The Legal Department announced its decision Thursday , the day after a District Court invalidated a law whereby public servants can be prosecuted for failing to explain a standard of living above their salary .
Judge Gerard Muttrie said the law violates Hong Kong 's Bill of Rights because it requires the defendant to explain his income , thus reversing the principle of innocence until guilt is proved .
The law is part of the Prevention of Bribery Ordinance , a tough legislative package enacted in 1971 to curb the corruption then rampant in Hong Kong .
The case before Muttrie , involving a senior estate surveyor , was the first based on the earnings clause since the enactment of the 1991 Bill of Rights , which affirms a person 's innocence until proved guilty .
The Independent Commission Against Corruption , Hong Kong 's powerful anti-graft agency , says 51 people were prosecuted under the clause before 1991 , and 32 were convicted .
ICAC official Jim Buckle was quoted by the South China Morning Post as saying Muttrie 's ruling was `` quite a blow . ''
`` The legislation is designed to catch people where you ca n't prove receiving individual bribes , '' he was quoted as saying .
`` People do n't normally come in and complain that they have been given bribes . ''
