Nervous civilians fled the Chechen capital for the countryside Thursday in fear of an attack by Russian troops trying to unseat the president of the breakaway southern republic .
A trickle of cars , packed tightly with family and a few belongings , left the city , along with a few trucks piled high with furniture and rugs .
Central Grozny was virtually empty following another nerve-jangling night of intermittent small arms fire from jumpy fighters around the city .
A single military jet roared over Grozny as a Russian ultimatum expired .
Russian President Boris Yeltsin ordered warring Chechens to lay down their arms and release all prisoners by Thursday morning or face Russian military intervention .
The ultimatum has been met with defiance by Chechens .
In Freedom Square outside the presidential building , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches while a tank maneuvered into position .
Chechen elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots , danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
The conflict in the Caucasus Mountains region of southern Russia has escalated in the past week after months of skirmishes .
Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , a former Soviet air force general who was elected in 1991 and declared Chechnya 's independence , accuses Moscow of leading and arming his opponents in a civil war .
Moscow , which openly supports the opposition politically , denies offering any military assistance .
After Dudayev 's forces captured Russian fighters in fierce fighting Saturday , Moscow officials said mercenaries were fighting on both sides .
In Moscow , Yeltsin spokesman Vyacheslev Kostikov indicated that Moscow was already moving to resolve the Chechen conflict .
`` A series of measures designed to improve resolutely the situation in the Chechen republic and restore the constitutionao order , law and protection of human rights has begun to be implemented , '' he said .
`` All necessary measures are being taken to save the Russian soldiers , '' he said , referring to those captured on Saturday .
Russian media reported that several transport planes have brought weapons and troops to the border of Chechnya .
Most of the civilians fleeing Grozny went only a few kilometers -LRB- miles -RRB- to stay with relatives in the countryside , in hopes that any battle for Grozny will be short and decisive .
`` Already , the majority of people have left the city , '' said 43-year-old Lyuba Ishkirchira , a Russian woman married to an ethnic Bashkir .
`` I have no relatives to go to , and my father and mother are ill here -- I can not leave them . ''
A hairdresser with blond hair falling below her headscarf , Lyuba recently sent a telegram to her daughter urging her not to return to Grozny .
`` If the Russians come and fight , it will be bad for us -- we 'll be taken hostage -LRB- by Chechens -RRB- , '' she said , referring to a centuries-old custom in the Caucasus in times of war .
Grozny 's central bazaar , which once thronged with thousands of people , was nearly empty on Thursday .
A few old women trudged through the mud and wet leaves in search of bread .
Although the Chechens are fighting among themselves , many agreed that they have one thing in common : Distrust of Russia .
`` I do n't like the opposition or Dudayev , but I 'll fight the Russians , '' said one restaurant owner who refused to give his name .
Wrapped in an old leather coat and a thick , gray scarf , a 60-year-old Chechen woman walking among the bazaar 's empty stalls said Russia would have a tough time trying to overrun Chechnya .
`` Whoever fights the Muslims never wins , '' Tamara Ofsayeva said .
The decision to authorize the study will mark a cautious move forward in drawing former adversaries in Eastern Europe .
Poland , Hungary and others have appealed for membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
`` Today , we take an important step in the process that will lead to NATO expansion , '' Christopher told the opening session of the ministers ' meeting .
The study -- dubbed an `` owner 's manual '' for NATO membership -- will take a year to complete .
It will not name candidates for membership , nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
Instead , it will focus on such questions as : What effect will newcomers have on NATO 's common military command structure ?
How much will enlargement cost NATO ?
Do NATO troops need to be based in the new member states ?
The study will also make clear to prospective applicants what membership would cost them in money and materiel .
To counter Russian worries about an eastward expansion of NATO , the allies intend later Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Russia and agree to hold regular talks with Moscow on security matters .
Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao 's popularity and the strength of his Congress Party was being tested in elections today in southern India , including his home state .
The voting for two state legislatures was seen as an important bellwether for the party , which already has suffered setbacks in the north and must retain its support in the south .
A loss in his own state of Andhra Pradesh could unleash rivalries in the governing party that Rao suppressed with difficulty last year .
Results will be announced Dec. 9 for the elections in Andhra Pradesh and Karnataka , as well as two other states that voted last month .
The voting is staggered to allow police to redeploy to protect polling stations .
The Andhra Pradesh campaign was marred by violence from left-wing militants , who claim to fight for peasants ' rights .
Land mines set by the militants killed at least 29 people in the past week .
The Congress campaign in Andhra Pradesh was thrown into disarray by the promise of a film star-turned-politician , N.T. Rama Rao , to sell rice to the poor at three cents a pound -- a sixth of the market rate .
Pursuing free market reforms , Rao could offer no similar subsidies .
Rama Rao , 72 , who played Hindu deities in classic films , campaigned with the help of his young crowd-pulling wife , whom he married last year .
The prime minister put his own prestige at stake by campaigning hard in his state , but his party 's prospects were hurt by infighting among the local politicians .
Morale is still high in the England cricket camp despite a 184-run defeat against Australia in the first Test in Brisbane , England captain Mike Atherton said Thursday .
Atherton said he believed the Test had shown England can counter the wizardry of leg-spinner Shane Warne .
Warne took a career best 8-71 in the second innings Tuesday to give him match figures of 11-110 as he spun Australia to victory .
But Atherton said the efforts of Graeme Hick and Graham Thorpe on the fourth day of the Test had shown Warne could be countered .
`` Hick and Thorpe were both able to score runs and they spent time at the crease , '' he said .
`` The spirit is not too bad .
The players are disappointed , naturally , at the Test defeat , but we have to get on with it and look forward to a new day tomorrow . ''
The tourists will play the traditional match against a Sir Donald Bradman XI in Bowral , southwest of Sydney , on Friday .
The Bradman side will be captained by former Australian skipper Allan Border and will feature young players who learned the game in the country areas of Australia .
