A bid to salvage the near-bankrupt airline Iberia appeared doomed Thursday after overnight talks between management and pilots ended in total disagreement over pay cuts .
Management and representatives of the carrier 's two main unions had reached a tentative agreement Tuesday on a viability plan that entailed a wage freeze , salary cuts averaging 8.5 percent and a reduction of some 3,500 jobs through early retirements and pay-offs .
Acceptance by the pilots would have paved the way for the plan to be implemented .
The plan was considered crucial if the European Commission is to consider allowing the Spanish government to grant Iberia a 130 billion peseta -LRB- dlrs 1 billion -RRB- capital injection .
Iberia chairman said the state-owned company would hold meetings with other unions Thursday to evaluate the situation in view of the pilots ' rejection .
It was not immediately clear whether the lack of an across-the-board agreement meant a much more drastic plan touted last week by Iberia -- involving 5,200 job cuts and the sale of company assets -- might be implemented .
That proposal triggered an one-day wildcat strike that paralyzed Spain 's airports and affected more than 100,000 travelers here and abroad .
Negotiations with the pilots reached a dead end as Iberia demanded a salary reduction of 15 percent based on 1992 earnings .
The pilots insisted that an existing wage agreement through 1995 must be implemented before the 15 percent salary cut could be enforced .
`` The company has presented a generic plan that does not guarantee the future of Iberia and only concentrates on disproportionate salary cuts , '' said Armando Guajardo of the pilots ' union SEPLA .
`` Management has let the situation rot to such an extent so that it could enforce such a plan worked out in advance , '' he said .
SEPLA said the company needed a complete overhaul and not just a reduction in salaries and staff .
He said SEPLA had sent a letter to Iberia warning of drastic action by the pilots if the current wage agreement was broken .
Pilots represent some 5 percent of the 24,000-strong staff .
Salas has warned that the company would be technically bankrupt by March 1995 .
Iberia has posted losses since 1990 .
It ended last year 67 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 530 million -RRB- in the red while losses for this year are expected to top 40 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 300 million -RRB- .
Unions are to decide Thursday if a strike called several weeks ago for Friday still holds .
The company has said it would continue to operate all its flights on that day .
Despite attempts to keep the focus on new members , the Bosnian crisis will no doubt occupy a large amount of the ministers ' time .
At a breakfast with Hurd , Christopher reviewed the warning U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali delivered Wednesday that unless warring Serbs and Muslims cooperate with the U.N. mission the peacekeepers might be withdrawn .
Christopher and Hurd said they may go to Belgrade , the Yugoslav capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
`` We will redouble our efforts to find a diplomatic solution , '' Christopher said .
The latest American approach centers on a call for an international peace conference that would let Bosnian Serbs seek changes in the peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
That plan would require them to cut their holdings in Bosnia from 70 percent to 49 percent .
The Clinton administration , officials say , is also leaning toward approval of political ties between Serbs in Bosnia and Serbia proper -- a big step toward a Greater Serbia .
On Friday , Christopher will meet with here his counterparts from France , Germany , Britain and Russia to discuss new plans to revive their moribund peace plan for Bosnia .
If nothing else , the new American stance is bound to heal a nasty rift within NATO over the alliance 's mission in the Bosnian war .
In his opening statement , Christopher sought to underscore the importance of NATO to the United States .
`` This alliance will continue to be the anchor of American engagement in Europe , the linchpin of transatlantic security , '' he said .
He also assured the 15 foreign ministers that the Clinton administration was committed to keep 100,000 American troops in Europe `` as part of our continuing engagement . ''
France and Britain have been criticized in the U.S. Congress for refusing to let the United Nations use the Western military alliance 's air power to the full .
In turn , Congress has forced the Clinton administration to seek a lifting of the arms embargo against Bosnia 's Muslim-led government , something the European NATO allies oppose for fear it would escalate the fighting .
The transatlantic rift came to a head with the de-facto loss of the Muslim enclave of Bihac as a U.N. `` safe area . ''
Seeking to mend fences , Christopher told the allies :
`` Let me stress one important fact : The crisis in Bosnia is about Bosnia and the former Yugoslavia .
It does not diminish NATO 's enduring importance . ''
Share prices in Hong Kong closed lower Thursday for the second straight day in light trading .
The Hang Seng Index , the market 's key indicator of blue chips , fell 35.46 points , or 0.4 percent , closing at 8,430.80 .
On Wednesday , the index had plunged 192 points .
Turnover amounted to 3.027 billion Hong Kong dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 388 million -RRB- , down from Wednesday 's 3.915 billion Hong Kong dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 502 million -RRB- .
Brokers said trading was generally directionless , with many investors staying on the sidelines because of worries that the U.S. Federal Reserve would raise interest rates again soon .
Among losers , Cheung Kong fell 40 Hong Kong cents to 31.80 , Swire Pacific `` A '' fell 25 cents to 51.25 , Sun Hung Kai Properties fell 20 cents to 49.50 , and Hutchison Whampoa fell 10 cents to 30.70 .
Going against the trend was Hang Seng Bank , which rose 50 cents to 58.25 .
Remaining unchanged was HSBC Holdings at 85.50 .
Mark Calcavecchia got a putting lesson from fellow American Brad Faxon Thursday and then shot a 4-under-par 68 for a one-stroke lead after the first round of the Greg Norman Holden Classic golf tournament .
Faxon offered to help after seeing Calcavecchia struggle on the greens during last week 's Australian Open and in practice around the 6,993-yard -LRB- 6,395-meter -RRB- , par-72 Royal Melbourne course .
The result was a flawless round for Calcavecchia that contained four birdies .
`` I regard Brad as one of the top five putters in the world , '' Calcavecchia said .
`` He told me I needed to lighten up a little bit .
He said I looked like I was trying to figure out so hard what was going on .
`` He said my speed was all wrong .
` Just stand up there and hit it , ' he said .
And for the most part it worked today . ''
Calcavecchia is one shot ahead of three Australians -- Paul Moloney , American-based Steve Rintoul and Japan-based Peter McWhinney .
Greg Norman , who complains that his many business activities are affecting his golf , was well in contention to win the tournament that bears his name .
His first-round 71 put him a group with Faxon , Australian Open champion Robert Allenby and former U.S. PGA champion Wayne Grady .
The tournament continues through Sunday and offers a first prize of dlrs 115,000 .
