A German diplomat 's report in advance of Thursday 's NATO ministerial meeting in Brussels accused the United States of sowing mistrust over Bosnia and the eastward expansion of the alliance .
NATO Ambassador Hermann von Richthofen filed the cable to the German Foreign Ministry on Nov. 22 , according to the Suddeutsche Zeitung , which published excerpts and provided a copy to The Associated Press on Thursday .
At the time it was written , U.S. policymakers were urging more forceful attacks against Bosnian Serbs and lifting the arms embargo against the Muslim-led government .
There were reports , denied by U.S. officials , of secret military assistance to the Muslims .
The U.S. moves caused especially deep mistrust in France , which is not part of NATO 's military structure but had been drawing closer to the alliance , the cable said .
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher was expected to tell the allies in Brussels that the Clinton administration had swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , was the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
While the conflicts described in the classified document come as no surprise , the cable offered an unusually detailed view into NATO in the midst of a severe crisis .
Richthofen accused the United States of acting behind the backs of its allies and of lacking a clear strategy in its push to expand NATO membership eastwards at a time when NATO states are at odds on priorities .
Greece and Italy favor expanding NATO in the south , to include Romania , Bulgaria and possibly Malta , the paper says , while the northern alliance members think the top priorities are Poland , Hungary , and the Czech republic .
The U.S.-designed Partnership for Peace for eastern Europe and the former Soviet republics has n't convinced many of the states it 's aimed at , `` thereby discrediting a piece of Alliance policy , '' the cable says .
`` Yet the U.S. administration is moving quickly to expand NATO without consultations on the ... consequences for the alliance , '' it said .
The Republican victory in U.S. Congressional elections raised the threat of a U.S. policy even more alienating to Russia , it said .
