Defenders and attacking Serbs traded heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire around embattled Bihac on Thursday in the wake of a failed peace mission by U.N. chief Boutros Boutros-Ghali , the United Nations said .
The Bosnian army commander pledged that despite heavy losses in the northwest corner of Bosnia , Bihac would not fall into Serb hands and the Muslim-led army would win the war .
Comments by Gen. Rasim Delic to the Sarajevo daily Oslobodjenje underscored the government 's unwillingness to compromise further to reach a cease-fire and a comprehensive peace .
Intransigence by both sides led Boutros-Ghali to suggest for the first time Wednesday that the U.N. peacekeeping mission might have to end .
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic told Boutros-Ghali that his government would negotiate only after Serbs accepted a peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
He reiterated his government 's offer of a three-month cease-fire .
Serbs want something more permanent .
Bosnian Serbs snubbed Boutros-Ghali altogether .
Their leader , Radovan Karadzic , refused to come to the Sarajevo airport to meet him , and Boutros-Ghali rejected entering Serb-held territory for the meeting .
Maj. Herve Gourmelon , a U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , said heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire broke out around Bihac late Wednesday and in the predawn hours Thursday .
That was after it was clear the Boutros-Ghali mission was a failure .
Some shelling also was reported .
There was no immediate information on any changes in the frontlines .
Sketchy information indicates that they have been stable in recent days , with Serbs holding 30-40 percent of the U.N.-declared `` safe area '' consisting of Bihac town and its environs .
Bosnian Serbs have been joined in the fighting by Serbs from neighboring Croatia and renegade Muslims under warlord Fikret Abdic .
In the newspaper interview , Delic said government forces still could win .
`` Bihac will not fall , '' he said .
The Bosnian army is much stronger and better-organized than the rag-tag group that formed at the beginning of the war with rebel Serbs in 1992 .
`` That does not mean we will not lose some battles , '' Delic said .
`` But we definitely will win the war . ''
But with the threat of Western military force against them discredited , the Serbs appeared to be in no mood to compromise .
NATO ministers meeting in Brussels on Thursday were to hear a proposal from U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher for a new international conference on former Yugoslavia at which the Serbs could make demands for new peace proposals .
Already , senior Western officials are proposing that the Bosnian Serbs be allowed links to Serb-led Yugoslavia , which they long have desired .
That would be a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal , a Greater Serbia .
Bosnian Serbs have rejected a peace plan that would reduce their holdings in Bosnia to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
The Bosnian Serbs would n't mind seeing the United Nations leave Bosnia , believing it would allow them to force the government to settle on Serb terms .
A withdrawal would likely lead to a bloodier conflict and could draw peacekeepers into battle as both sides rushe to seize U.N. equipment .
Widespread hardship probably would result .
Boutros-Ghali stressed that the United Nation feeds an estimated 3 million people across the former Yugoslavia .
Most are in Bosnia .
More than 200,000 are dead or missing in the 31-month conflict launched by Serbs who rebelled against a Muslim-Croat vote to declare independence from Serb-led Yugoslavia .
A German diplomat 's report in advance of Thursday 's NATO ministerial meeting in Brussels accused the United States of sowing mistrust over Bosnia and the eastward expansion of the alliance .
NATO Ambassador Hermann von Richthofen filed the cable to the German Foreign Ministry on Nov. 22 , according to the Suddeutsche Zeitung , which published excerpts and provided a copy to The Associated Press on Thursday .
At the time it was written , U.S. policymakers were urging more forceful attacks against Bosnian Serbs and lifting the arms embargo against the Muslim-led government .
There were reports , denied by U.S. officials , of secret military assistance to the Muslims .
The U.S. moves caused especially deep mistrust in France , which is not part of NATO 's military structure but had been drawing closer to the alliance , the cable said .
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher was expected to tell the allies in Brussels that the Clinton administration had swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , was the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
While the conflicts described in the classified document come as no surprise , the cable offered an unusually detailed view into NATO in the midst of a severe crisis .
Richthofen accused the United States of acting behind the backs of its allies and of lacking a clear strategy in its push to expand NATO membership eastwards at a time when NATO states are at odds on priorities .
Greece and Italy favor expanding NATO in the south , to include Romania , Bulgaria and possibly Malta , the paper says , while the northern alliance members think the top priorities are Poland , Hungary , and the Czech republic .
The U.S.-designed Partnership for Peace for eastern Europe and the former Soviet republics has n't convinced many of the states it 's aimed at , `` thereby discrediting a piece of Alliance policy , '' the cable says .
`` Yet the U.S. administration is moving quickly to expand NATO without consultations on the ... consequences for the alliance , '' it said .
The Republican victory in U.S. Congressional elections raised the threat of a U.S. policy even more alienating to Russia , it said .
`` The alliance is divided and in crisis , '' the cable concludes , because in the post-Cold War era , it can only hold together with a clear sense of mission and strategy -- which it lacks .
Secretary of State Warren Christopher is telling the NATO allies the Clinton administration has swung to their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the war in Bosnia .
It is the first time in the post-World War II history of the alliance that the Europeans led by France prevailed over the United States in formulating a major policy .
It is a difficult assignment for Christopher , putting him in the awkward position of shifting gears even while denying U.S. policy on the war has changed or that there is a trans-Atlantic rift .
Trying to patch over the embarrassing dispute , Christopher pronounced the alliance strong and he charted a plan for growth through absorption of East European countries .
A ceremony was scheduled to establish links to Russia , for decades the direct target of NATO 's massive military preparedness program .
He told the allies in a speech that `` the tragedy of the war and bloodshed in Bosnia does not diminish our responsibility to build a comprehensive European security architecture . ''
`` America 's interests in Europe have not changed , '' he said .
`` Neither have the basic principles guiding our engagement . ''
And at the top of the list , Christopher said today , was that `` the United States has enduring political , military , economic and cultural links to europe that must and will be preserved . ''
Earlier , at breakfast with Douglas Hurd , the British foreign secretary , Christopher reviewed the warning U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali delivered Wednesday that unless warring Serbs and Muslims cooperate with the U.N. mission the peacekeepers might be withdrawn .
Christopher and Hurd said they may go to Belgrade , the Yugoslav capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
`` We will redouble our efforts to find a diplomatic solution , '' Christopher said .
However , his aides spread the word a trip by Christopher to Belgrade was unlikely .
Asked if the troops would be withdrawn , Hurd replied grimly : `` We certainly hope not . ''
National Security Adviser Anthony Lake , in a speech Wednesday at Princeton University , acknowledged it is a path `` rife with frustrations and setbacks . ''
Nonetheless , he said , `` it 's the best , the steadiest course .
... Both sides face the same choice : They can perpetuate a bloody military stalemate or they can stop the senseless killing and come to terms . ''
By chance , it is the U.S. turn to preside over a meeting today of the North Atlantic Council , NATO 's policy-making arm .
This puts Christopher under an even brighter spotlight , and he was responding both with a brief speech opening the session and a detailed one outlining U.S. plans for NATO 's expansion .
On Friday , Christopher intends to lay out the U.S. approach to the Bosnian war in a meeting with Hurd and Foreign Ministers Alain Juppe of France , Andrei V. Kozyrev of Russia and Klaus Kinkel of Germany .
It is centered on a call for an international peace conference that would give the Bosnian Serbs an opportunity to demand changes in the peace plan they have rejected repeatedly .
They already have strong intimations of support from the Clinton administration in pressing for cross-border political ties to the Serb-dominated government in Belgrade -- a big step toward their goal of a Greater Serbia .
And even the peace plan map the Bosnian Serbs rejected is open to negotiations , Clinton administration officials promised in this week of candid admissions by Defense Secretary William Perry and other senior U.S. officials that the Bosnian Serbs can not be stopped in their territorial conquests by military force .
`` This alliance will continue to be the anchor of American engagement in Europe , the linchpin of trans-Atlantic security , '' Christopher said in a brief statement opening the North Atlantic Council session .
He also assured the 15 foreign ministers that the Clinton administration was committed to keep 100,000 American troops in Europe `` as part of our continuing engagement . ''
The European allies , particularly France and Britain , have taken this position throughout the 31-month war .
They managed to limit NATO air strikes despite U.N. assurances that Bihac , the mostly Muslim town on the verge of falling to the Serbs , was a `` safe area '' from which heavy weapons were to be excluded .
They also hemmed in the 23,000 peacekeepers in Bosnia .
Lake , in his speech at Princeton , stressed that NATO had chosen not to intervene directly in Bosnia and had given the lead to the United Nations .
`` Right or wrong , that decision has consequences with which we must continue to struggle , '' he said .
Before leaving Washington , Christopher grumbled to reporters about NATO 's refusal to engage in a sustained bombardment of Serb positions in the northwestern region of the bloodied country .
But having threatened the Serbs in the past with NATO might , he abandoned the threat when asked what `` sticks '' the United States was using to persuade the Serbs to relinquish their grip on Bihac .
If they kept fighting , Christopher said , they risked Serbia closing its border and a tightening of sanctions -- measures that are far less threatening than attacks by NATO warplanes .
Serbia has been the principal arms supplier to Serbs in Bosnia .
And while Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic has promised to cut them off , a senior U.S. official said there was considerable `` leakage '' and arms were getting through .
Seeking to limit the damage to the alliance , which successfully stood up to the Soviet Union but has caved on Bosnia , Christopher said he wanted to stress that `` the crisis in Bosnia is about Bosnia and the former Yugoslavia ; it 's not about NATO and its future . ''
But NATO 's impotence has raised questions about NATO 's future .
Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas suggested after meeting in Brussels with alliance officials that the alliance may have become irrelevant .
`` There 's been no pressure on the Serbs and until there 's some leverage , it 's going to be very difficult to stop the fighting and reach some kind of settlement , '' Dole said .
Challenging the influential Republican , Hurd said Dole `` does not understand the consequences '' for Sarajevo , the Bosnian capital , for Muslim enclaves and for the people of the country if U.N. peacekeepers were withdrawn .
`` NATO is a collective security organization and that is to say it is the organization which keeps us safe in our beds at night , '' Hurd said .
Bitter Russians lashed out at the U.S. Embassy on Thursday after being surprised by what one called `` the latest insult '' to Russians trying to visit the United States : a new dlrs 20 visa application fee .
`` I wonder why we 're trying so hard to go to this ` wonderful ' country , America , when its embassy has so little respect for us , '' said Sergei Tumbasov , a construction engineer hoping to go to Virginia on business .
The U.S. Embassy announced Wednesday several changes to its much-criticized visa application process , including the new fee , which was payable in rubles and went into effect Thursday .
Human rights activists and Russian officials have criticized consular officials in recent months for rudeness and for humiliating visa applicants .
Tumbasov said no one had told him of the fee until he arrived at the embassy Thursday morning , not even the consular officer he had spoken to the day before .
The new non-refundable application fee is especially painful for the more than 100 applicants who are rejected for visas by the Moscow embassy daily .
`` This unexpected fee is the final insult in an absolutely absurd process , '' said Marina Orlova , an eye doctor from the prestigious Fyodorov Clinic , who was turned away Thursday for not sufficiently proving her intent to return to Russia .
`` Who do they think we are ?
We 're doctors , professionals . ''
If Orlova returns to the embassy with further documentation to support her application , she must pay an additional dlrs 20 , according to the new regulations .
This fee does not include the cost of the visa itself , which runs an additional dlrs 20 for a single-entry visa , or dlrs 120 for a multi-entry visa .
`` The system is made for the mafia .
No one else can afford it , '' Orlova added loudly , prompting a guard to ask her to leave the crowded sidewalk in front of the embassy .
An average of 550 people apply for U.S. visas at this embassy daily , and about 133,000 people have applied in the past year , according to embassy figures .
But the overwhelmed consular office can not hold all the applicants , forcing them to wait for hours outside , even in the city 's bitter December weather .
Vladimir Gulagin , a technical consultant planning a business trip to New York , brushed the falling snow off a medium-sized suitcase full of documents Thursday .
Gulagin was refused a visa on Tuesday and was told to return with further documentation .
He was not told , however , about the new fee .
`` It 's a good thing I had borrowed money from my wife this morning , '' Gulagin said .
`` I spent most of my paycheck yesterday , getting all these documents copied . ''
After announcing the new fee , U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering on Wednesday outlined a number of steps designed to ease the visa process , including an `` express lane '' and easier processing for business visa applications .
Vasily Ignatkin , head of the visa department at the Diplomatic Corps Administration Bureau , said the changes in the process were welcome , but that it would be `` some time before any serious improvements are evident . ''
Those in line outside the embassy were even more skeptical .
`` It 's all talk , '' Tumbasov said .
`` They 're trying to comfort us -LRB- with the other changes -RRB- while they ask us for more money . ''
