Taiwan 's first homemade patrol boat became operational Thursday to help defend the island 's coastal waters .
The 500-ton vessel will be equipped with a locally developed Hsiung-feng I anti-ship missile system and 40mm artillery , the navy said .
`` The boat is very swift and has powerful ammunition .
The navy 's defense capability can be significantly boosted if we can have more of the boats in the future , '' navy chief Ku Chung-lien said at the commissioning ceremony in Kaohsiung , southern Taiwan .
The `` Chinchiang '' was privately manufactured by the Lien Ho Shipbuilding Co. and the United Ship Design and Development Center .
The navy declined to say how many it will buy .
It was priced at 490 million Taiwan dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 18.15 million -RRB- and construction began in August last year , said Lien Ho 's vice manager , Tai Fu-pin .
The navy said the boat also will be used to crack down on smuggling activities and protect Taiwanese fishing boats .
Taiwan wants to buy advanced weapons abroad and develop military technology at home to meet threats from China , which regards the island as a breakaway province and has not renounced the use of force to recover it .
Taiwan is the seat of the Nationalist government which fled China 's mainland in 1949 after losing a civil war to the Communists .
A 44-year-man convicted of stabbing three women to death in 1977 was hanged Thursday , news reports said .
It was the first execution reported in one year in Japan .
The mass-circulation newspaper Yomiuri Shimbun and Kyodo News Service reported that Yukio Ajima was hanged at the Tokyo Detention House , nine years after the Supreme Court rejected his final appeal .
Executions in Japan , all by hanging , are carried out in secret and authorities give no information afterward to media , relatives or the public , although there has been recent discussion of announcing executions .
Relatives and lawyers now confirm executions by checking whether the condemned person 's name has been crossed off registration lists at government offices .
The execution came five days after the Prime Minister 's Office announced the results of its first survey in five years on the death penalty .
It showed 73.8 percent of those responding favored retaining the death penalty , the highest percentage since such surveys began in 1956 .
The office said 13.6 percent favored abolition , the lowest figure in 38 years .
Senior Justice Ministry officials suggested that public opinion may have been influenced by recent increases in violent crime in Japan , generally considered a safe country .
In the survey , the office questioned 3,000 adults at random throughout the country in early September .
In the last survey , in 1989 , 67 percent favored the death penalty and 16 percent opposed it .
Before Thursday , the last reported executions were four on Nov. 26 , 1993 .
Before that , three on March 26 , 1993 , were the first reported in three years .
Executions require an order from the justice minister , and some holders of the office have declined .
Before Thursday 's reported hanging , 59 convicts had been awaiting execution , according to Amnesty International Japan .
