NATO foreign ministers met Thursday to begin laying the groundwork for the entry of former Warsaw Pact foes as new members in the coming years .
But their two-day meeting was likely to be overshadowed by the crisis in Bosnia that has put extraordinary strains on the relationship between the United States and its European allies .
During the talks , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher was expected to tell the allies the Clinton administration has swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
It marks a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the European allies , led by Britain and France .
The change in U.S. policy will help heal an unprecedented rift within the alliance over Bosnia .
Seeking to mend fences , Christopher told the allies :
`` Let me stress one important fact : The crisis in Bosnia is about Bosnia and the former Yugoslavia .
It does not diminish NATO 's enduring importance . ''
NATO 's new Secretary General Willy Claes appealed for unity .
`` We are now being put to -LRB- the -RRB- test , and I have every confidence that our solidarity will see us through now has it has in even darker circumstances . ''
The foreign ministers are anxious their talks not be entirely hijacked by the Bosnian crisis .
They intend to order a study that would set out the terms and conditions for the acceptance of East European countries as new members .
`` We have a moral duty not to squander this historic opportunity to anchor the new democracies of central and eastern Europe permanently in the West , '' Claes told the meeting 's opening ceremony .
The decision to authorize the study will mark a cautious move forward in drawing former adversaries in Eastern Europe .
Poland , Hungary and others have appealed for membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
`` Today , we take an important step in the process that will lead to NATO expansion , '' Christopher said .
The study -- dubbed an `` owner 's manual '' for NATO membership -- will take a year to complete .
It will not name candidates for membership , nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
Instead , it will focus on such questions as : What effect will newcomers have on NATO 's common military command structure ?
How much will enlargement cost NATO ?
Do NATO troops need to be based in the new member states ?
The study will also make clear to prospective applicants what membership would cost them in money and materiel .
To counter Russian worries about an eastward expansion of NATO , the allies intend later Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Russia and agree to hold regular talks with Moscow on security matters .
