Bosnian Serbs snubbed Boutros-Ghali altogether .
Their leader , Radovan Karadzic , refused to come to the Sarajevo airport to meet him , and Boutros-Ghali rejected entering Serb-held territory for the meeting .
Maj. Herve Gourmelon , a U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , said heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire broke out around Bihac late Wednesday and into Thursday , after it was clear that Boutros-Ghali 's mission had failed .
Some shelling was also reported .
There was no information on any changes in the frontlines , which have been stable in the past few days .
Sketchy reports indicate the Serbs hold 30 to 40 percent of the U.N.-declared `` safe area '' consisting of Bihac town and its environs .
Bosnian Serbs have been joined in the offensive by Serbs from neighboring Croatia and renegade Muslims under warlord Fikret Abdic .
In the newspaper interview , Delic said government forces still could win .
The Bosnian army is much stronger and better-organized than the rag-tag group formed at the beginning of the war with rebel Serbs in 1992 .
`` That does not mean we will not lose some battles , '' Delic said .
`` But we definitely will win the war . ''
With members of NATO and the United Nations unwilling to use vigorous military force , the Serbs appeared to be in no mood to compromise .
NATO ministers meeting in Brussels on Thursday were to hear a proposal from U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher for a new international conference on the former Yugoslavia at which the Serbs could make demands for new peace proposals .
Already , senior Western officials are proposing that the Bosnian Serbs be allowed links to Serb-led Yugoslavia .
Serb nationalists have in part waged war to create a Greater Serbia .
The Bosnian Serbs would n't mind seeing the United Nations leave Bosnia , believing it would allow them to force the government to settle on Serb terms .
A withdrawal would likely lead to a bloodier conflict and could draw peacekeepers into battle as both sides rush to seize U.N. equipment .
Widespread hardship probably would result .
Boutros-Ghali stressed that the United Nations feeds an estimated 3 million people across the former Yugoslavia .
Most are in Bosnia .
More than 200,000 are dead or missing in the 31-month conflict launched by Serbs who rebelled against a Muslim-Croat vote to declare independence from Serb-led Yugoslavia .
Irmgard Moeller , the Red Army Faction terrorist who blew up three American soldiers with a car bomb 22 years ago , walked out of prison Thursday after being freed early from her life sentence .
Wearing jeans , a leather jacket and red sweater , Moeller smiled , waved and gathered up bouquets from fans , who were singing 1960s anti-Vietnam War songs and chanting revolutionary slogans outside the blue steel prison gates .
`` It still feels unreal , '' she said , her words nearly drowned out by the chanting crowd of 200 , who carried red flags , champagne bottles and Christmas presents .
Moeller , 47 , appealed for freedom for other `` political prisoners '' and thanked her supporters and friends for helping her cope through 22 years in prison .
Then she was driven away in her lawyer 's car , while a loudspeaker mounted on a truck played `` Internationale , '' the revolutionary socialist hymn .
Moeller was convicted of driving one of two explosives-laden cars that blew up in a parking lot at U.S. Army Headquarters in Heidelberg on May 24 , 1972 .
Capt. Clyde R. Bonner and two enlisted men , Charles L. Peck and Ronald A. Woodward , were killed .
The U.S. State Department and relatives of the victims objected to her release .
Moeller , the longest serving female prisoner in Germany , was freed because of her poor health , although she has shown no remorse and refused to cooperate with psychiatric evaluations to determine whether she is still dangerous .
A court in the state of Schleswig-Holstein , where the prison is located , determined that she is not likely to commit another violent crime , and placed her on probation for five years .
Moeller 's release could lead to freedom for the seven other Red Army Faction terrorists still imprisoned in Germany .
After its last actions -- assassinating a German official in 1991 and blowing up a new prison in 1993 -- the Red Army Faction said it was ending its 20-year campaign of attacks on what it called `` imperialist '' targets .
The Red Army Faction faction had issued a statement after the 1972 Heidelberg bombing , calling it a protest against `` genocide '' in Vietnam .
Moeller was arrested six weeks after the attack and sentenced to life in prison plus 15 years .
She lived through 12 hunger strikes and survived the night of Oct. 18 , 1977 , when three other imprisoned Red Army Faction leaders were found dead in their cells in what authorities said were suicides .
Moeller was found with four stabs in her chest , but survived .
Politicians , theologians , authors and her prison warden campaigned for Moeller 's release on humanitarian grounds .
In a 1992 interview with the magazine Der Spiegel , Moeller was asked if she felt sympathy for the victims of Red Army Faction violence .
`` I ca n't deal with this so personally and individually , '' she replied .
A striking black-haired woman when she went to jail at the age of 25 , Moeller 's lined face and graying hair now reflect her long life behind bars .
She is also said to be in deteriorating health , suffering from skin , eye and other ailments .
State prosecutors did not challenge the decision ordering her release .
But the U.S. State Department said on Nov. 1 , before the court 's decision , that the U.S. government opposes freeing terrorists who show no remorse for politically motivated attacks .
U.S. Air Force Sgt. Charles Bonner , the 29-year-old son of victim Clyde Bonner , contacted German officials to protest against the decision .
`` I was only 7 when my father was killed .
Our housing was just across from that parking lot .
That 's something I 'll never forget .
I think releasing her is ridiculous , '' he said in a telephone conversation last week .
A daughter of strict Roman Catholic parents from Munich , Moeller became involved in the leftist student movement of the 1960s , got to know the founders of the Red Army Faction , Andreas Baader and Ulrike Meinhof , and went underground in 1971 .
Moeller could throw some light on the deaths of Baader , Jan-Carl Raspe and Gudrun Ensslin , who died in October 1977 in the top-security Stuttgart Stammheim prison .
German authorities and foreign experts ruled the deaths suicides , but Moeller , who survived , has always maintained they were state-ordered murders .
Early in her imprisonment , Moeller was held in isolation and harsh conditions in Stammheim , with no human contact apart from her guards and wardens .
In 1980 , she was moved to the relative comfort of the Luebeck prison .
There , she and two other convicted terrorists shared a special unit that includes a kitchen , a bathroom , a television room and a library .
A contempt of court case against an American scholar and a Paris-based newspaper was postponed Thursday for five weeks , the state television reported .
The case involves an article by Christopher Lingle published in the International Herald Tribune on Oct. 7 in which he criticized unnamed Asian governments and their court systems .
In its suit on Nov. 11 , the government charged Lingle , who used to teach at the National University of Singapore ; the International Herald Tribune -LRB- Singapore -RRB- Private Ltd. ; the Tribune 's regional editor , Michael Richardson , an Australian based in Singapore ; and the Tribune 's publisher , Richard McClean .
The case was scheduled to be held Friday in the High Court but was postponed to Jan. 9 to accommodate the Tribune , whose lawyer requested more time to prepare the case , the television reported .
K. Shanmugam , the Tribune lawyer , was not immediately available for comment .
The case reflects the friction between the Singapore government and the foreign press .
The government controls the local media by issuing licenses to operate .
In the past , the government has temporarily restricted the circulation of the newspaper Asian Wall Street Journal and the magazines Time , Asiaweek and the Far Eastern Economic Review for articles it considered offensive or defamatory .
The International Herald Tribune , published jointly by the New York Times and the Washington Post , was threatened earlier this year with a defamation suit over an article that alleged nepotism in Singapore .
The newspaper apologized but the two sides have not reached a settlement yet .
In the latest contempt case , the government has also named Singapore Press Holdings Ltd. , a local company that prints the Tribune 's Singapore edition .
Contempt of court is punishable by a fine or imprisonment or both , but the law leaves the amount or term to the judge 's discretion .
Lingle is not expected to appear for the court deliberations .
He returned to his home in Atlanta , Ga. , on Oct. 21 , fearing arrest after police started an investigation against him .
He also resigned his year-old job teaching European economics at the university here .
The Achille Lauro smoldered on a placid sea Thursday , a day after a raging fire forced the nearly 1,000 people aboard to take to lifeboats and abandon the cruise ship off Somalia .
Two people were reported dead from the Italian liner , which gained notoriety in 1985 when Palestinian terrorists hijacked and killed a wheelchair-bound American passenger .
At mid morning on Thursday , the empty , scarred vessel was still afloat , listing badly to port .
White steam and and gray smoke poured from its port side and smaller streams came drifting out of the lower starboard deck .
Though her name was still visible on the stern , the cruise ship 's blue and white paint was scorched and mottled , the white stars on her two smokestacks blackened by heat and soot .
Although crippled , the Achille Lauro appeared in no danger of sinking quickly .
`` She is presently listing at about 20 degrees .
There 's a tremendous amount of smoke and steam still coming from over three quarters of the length of the vessel , '' John Briand , captain of the oil tanker Lima , told the BBC .
The fire started Wednesday , apparently in the passenger area , but the cause was not known , said the ship 's owner , Starlauro of Genoa , Italy .
Eight people were injured in the fire .
About 60 crewmembers fought the fire before abandoning the 23,478-ton ship 210 kilometers -LRB- 130 miles -RRB- south of the Horn of Africa .
The pilot of a plane carrying an Associated Press reporter and cameramen put the ship 's position at 160 miles east of the small Somali fishing village of Eil .
Capt. Ferdinando Lolli , a port official in Rome , said the ship was carrying 581 passengers and 404 crew .
Most of the crew was Italian , and the passengers mainly South African , German , Dutch and British .
Late Wednesday evening , Italian Coast Guard officials reported that everyone on the Achille Lauro was accounted for .
Italian news agencies identified the dead as a Briton and a German .
The Panamanian oil ship Hawaiian King was one of the first ships to arrive at the scene and took on about 800 people , said a coast guard official in Rome , Adm. Eugenio Sicurezza .
Many had to spend the night on the Hawaiian King 's deck , Briand said , and other ships sent over food , blankets and toiletries .
Two U.S. warships , the USS Gettysburg and USS Halyburton , arrived overnight and dispatched helicopters to ferry water , food and medical supplies to the survivors , said Cmdr. T. McCreary , spokesman for the U.S. Naval Forces Central Command in the Gulf .
`` Quite a few people were injured in the transfer -- there 's a few broken bones and some pretty tortured souls , '' Briand said , adding that many of the rescued passengers were elderly .
The commerical and Navy ships will divide up the passengers Thursday and send them on , mostly to Mombasa , Kenya , and Djibouti , McCreary said .
Others reportedly will be taken to the Seychelles .
Briand said the transfer was expected to take most of the day .
His ship was taking on the Achille Lauro 's 50 Honduran crewmembers .
The Achille Lauro left Genoa on Nov. 19 , stopped in Israel , and its next port of call was to be Durban , South Africa , on Friday , said Carla Gotta , a spokeswoman for the cruise ship 's owner .
The terrorists who hijacked the Achille Lauro in 1985 shot American Leon Klinghoffer and pushed him in his wheelchair off the ship .
The hijackers escaped the vessel and boarded a jet , but U.S. fighter planes forced it to land in Italy and the hijackers were captured .
Launched in 1946 in the Netherlands , the Achille Lauro was acquired 20 years later by the Neapolitan shipping dynasty .
It first transported Italian immigrant workers to and from Australia and was outfitted for pleasure cruises in 1970 .
The liner rammed a fishing boat in 1971 off Italy , killing a Neapolitan fisherman .
And on Dec. 2 , 1981 , fire broke out aboard ship off the Canary Islands .
Panicked passengers jumped into the sea , and two of them drowned .
A bid to salvage the near-bankrupt airline Iberia appeared doomed Thursday after overnight talks between management and pilots ended in total disagreement over pay cuts .
Management and representatives of the carrier 's two main unions had reached a tentative agreement Tuesday on a viability plan that entailed a wage freeze , salary cuts averaging 8.5 percent and a reduction of some 3,500 jobs through early retirements and pay-offs .
Acceptance by the pilots would have paved the way for the plan to be implemented .
The plan was considered crucial if the European Commission is to consider allowing the Spanish government to grant Iberia a 130 billion peseta -LRB- dlrs 1 billion -RRB- capital injection .
Iberia chairman Javier Salas said the state-owned company would hold meetings with other unions Thursday to evaluate the situation in view of the pilots ' rejection .
It was not immediately clear whether the lack of an across-the-board agreement meant a much more drastic plan touted last week by Iberia -- involving 5,200 job cuts and the sale of company assets -- might be implemented .
That proposal triggered an one-day wildcat strike that paralyzed Spain 's airports and affected more than 100,000 travelers here and abroad .
Negotiations with the pilots reached a dead end as Iberia demanded a salary reduction of 15 percent based on 1992 earnings .
The pilots insisted that an existing wage agreement through 1995 must be implemented before the 15 percent salary cut could be enforced .
`` The company has presented a generic plan that does not guarantee the future of Iberia and only concentrates on disproportionate salary cuts , '' said Armando Guajardo of the pilots ' union SEPLA .
`` Management has let the situation rot to such an extent so that it could enforce such a plan worked out in advance , '' he said .
SEPLA said the company needed a complete overhaul and not just a reduction in salaries and staff .
He said SEPLA had sent a letter to Iberia warning of drastic action by the pilots if the current wage agreement was broken .
Pilots represent some 5 percent of the 24,000-strong staff .
Salas has warned that the company would be technically bankrupt by March 1995 .
Iberia has posted losses since 1990 .
It ended last year 67 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 530 million -RRB- in the red while losses for this year are expected to top 40 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 300 million -RRB- .
Unions are to decide Thursday if a strike called several weeks ago for Friday still holds .
The company has said it would continue to operate all its flights on that day .
Police Minister Moshe Shahal recommended Thursday that Israel bar entrance to Palestinians living in the West Bank and Gaza until their self-rule government proved capable of preventing attacks on Israelis .
Shahal spoke to Israel radio a day after a Palestinian axed a 19-year-old woman soldier to death and two days after Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin said he wanted to begin separating Palestinians and Israelis .
Talk of dismantling small , isolated settlements was also growing this week , as Islamic militants opposed to the Israel-PLO peace process escalate attacks on Israelis .
Thirty-two Israelis have been killed since Oct. 1 .
`` There is no alternative other than to demand separation , '' Shahal said .
`` Separation means that we do not have to open the territory out of economic and employment concerns until the Palestinians prove that they can prevent attacks . ''
Tens of thousands of Palestinians work in Israel and lose their only means of livelihood when barred from jobs during the border closings imposed in the wake of attacks on Israelis .
The latest closing , which is gradually being lifted , sealed off the West Bank and Gaza following the Oct. 19 bombing of a Tel Aviv bus that left 22 civilians dead .
Despite the strict restrictions on West Bank and Gaza residents entering Israel , Wednesday 's Palestinian assailant managed to sneak through army roadblocks into the northern Israeli town of Afula .
Shahal said the permanent separation should be part of the second stage of the autonomy accord with the Palestinians .
The second phase includes elections of a Palestinian governing council and the expansion of self-rule beyond Gaza and the West Bank town of Jericho .
Negotiations over the next stage are to resume next week in Cairo , Egypt .
The Cabinet is expected to discuss the upcoming talks during its weekly meeting Sunday , Shahal added .
Police ousted hunger-striking politicians from government offices but the reformed East German communists declared Thursday they would continue their protest against a whopping 67-million-mark -LRB- dlrs 43-million -RRB- tax levy .
The Party of Democratic Socialism , or PDS , said 11 people , including party president Lothar Bisky and Gregor Gysi , leader of the party 's 30 members of parliament , were fasting Thursday .
The protest spread to the eastern cities of Dresden and Schwerin , where hundreds of party members and sympathizers demonstrated Thursday morning at state legislatures .
The party claims the government is trying to tax it into bankruptcy and political death , but authorities accused the PDS of over-simplifying a complex financial issue and of reneging on laws passed by the East German parliament in 1990 .
PDS leaders began a hunger strike Wednesday afternoon in two government offices in Berlin to protest the tax bill .
Late Wednesday , police removed the protesters , carrying some of them out .
The PDS members moved to their party offices at the Berlin city legislature and said the hunger strike would continue indefinitely under the motto `` We wo n't be taxed out of existence -- No expropriation of the PDS . ''
The Party of Democratic Socialism was formed in 1990 out of the remnants of the collapsed East German Communist Party .
It got only 2.4 percent of the national vote in December 1990 in the first united German parliamentary elections , and appeared in danger of passing into history .
But in the Oct. 16 national elections , the PDS grabbed 20 percent of votes in eastern Germany and 4.4 percent nationally , mostly on resentment among eastern Germans who feel they are second-class citizens in united Germany .
Chancellor Helmut Kohl attacked the PDS as a group of `` red-painted fascists , '' and the party has been battered by accusations that Gysi was an informant for the East German secret police when he acted as defense lawyer for dissidents .
The news magazine Focus this week devoted its cover story to Gysi , calling him `` Der Blender '' -- The Phoney -- and a `` clever demagogue . ''
The tax levy is for a corporate tax in the first half of 1990 -- before German unification -- when the PDS as successor of the communists still held vast assets around the country .
East German political groups entrusted their assets to an independent commission that is supposed to determine how much of the property they can keep and how much is national property .
The PDS wanted its tax levy to be paid from its assets held by the independent commission , but the commission refused .
The Treuhandanstalt , the trustee agency that is selling off East German state assets , said the independent commission was following the letter of the 1990 treaty of German unification and a law passed by the democratically elected East German parliament before German unification .
`` The -LRB- PDS -RRB- is fleeing into the pose of a victim when its active cooperation would be appropriate , '' said Wolf Schoede , spokesman of the trustee agency .
China has agreed to allow the United States to open an office of the Drug Enforcement Administration in Beijing , a senior U.S. official announced Thursday .
Timothy Wirth , undersecretary of state for global affairs , is in Beijing for talks with Chinese officials on population , environment , women 's issues and narcotics .
His job was created under the Clinton administration , and Wirth said he came to China because `` what happens in China is going to affect everybody in the world . ''
He said the Chinese government had agreed in principle to the opening of the DEA office , and the U.S. side was looking for an apartment for the American official .
Under Chinese government regulations , foreign government employees in Beijing must live in one of four diplomatic compounds , which have long waiting lists .
Wirth said U.S. cities are seeing a resurgence of heroin use , with major supplies of `` very cheap and very pure '' heroin from Burma showing up in Los Angeles and New York .
`` China has the most influence with the government of Burma .
We have very little influence with the government of Burma , '' he said .
`` We want very much to engage the government of China in focusing on the narcotics problem and the Burma problem in particular . ''
Southwest China borders Burma .
The `` Golden Triangle '' region where the borders of Burma , Thailand and Laos converge produces most of the world 's heroin .
Wirth said China 's population and environmental problems can have worldwide consequences , but China can learn from some of the mistakes the United States has made as well as benefit from its technology and know-how .
For instance , he said , the U.S. experience has shown that use of catalytic converters and unleaded gasoline in cars can substantially improve air quality , one of China 's worst pollution problems .
Wirth said he also planned to look into China 's population policies , particularly at a new law promoting mother and child health that includes eugenics clauses .
`` We remain deeply concerned , as does most of the world , about any programs that involve coercive abortion policies , '' said Wirth , who was to meet with the head of China 's family planning commission on Friday .
An explosive thrown during a clash between political rivals killed one person on polling day Thursday , during a state election considered to be a severe test for Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao .
Police said they also killed three militants of the Peoples War Group , an anarchist organization that carried out a series of sabotage incidents in the final weeks of the campaign to disrupt the voting .
At least 29 people were killed in land mine explosions blamed on the group .
Aruna Bahugana , a senior police officer , reported that an election official was dragged out of his polling booth and stabbed .
Cases also were reported of looting ballot boxes .
The violence came during elections to the state assembly of Andhra Pradesh , Prime Minister Rao 's home state .
There were no reports of election trouble in the neighboring state of Karnataka .
Voting for state legislatures in the two south Indian states was seen as an important bellwether for Congress , which already has suffered setbacks in the north and must retain its support in the south .
A loss in Rao 's own state of Andhra Pradesh could unleash rivalries in the governing party that he suppressed with difficulty last year .
Results will be announced Dec. 9 for elections in Andhra Pradesh , Karnataka and two other states that voted last month .
The voting is staggered to allow police forces to move from one to another to protect polling stations .
The Congress campaign in Andhra Pradesh was thrown into disarray by the promise of an aging film star-turned-politician , N.T. Rama Rao , to sell rice to the poor at two rupees per kilogram -LRB- three cents per pound -RRB- -- six times less than the market rate .
Pursuing free market reforms , Rao could offer no subsidies to match his opponent 's challenge .
Rama Rao , 72 , who built a popular image by playing Hindu deities in classic films in the local Telugu language , campaigned with the help of his young crowd-pulling wife , whom he married last year .
The prime minister put his own prestige at stake by campaigning hard in his state , but his party 's prospects were hurt by infighting among the local politicians .
