NATO foreign ministers met Thursday to begin laying the groundwork for the entry of former Warsaw Pact foes as new members in the coming years .
But their two-day meeting was likely to be overshadowed by the crisis in Bosnia that has put extraordinary strains on the relationship between the United States and its European allies .
During the talks , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher was expected to tell the allies the Clinton administration has swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
It marks a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the European allies , led by Britain and France .
The change in U.S. policy will help heal an unprecedented rift within the alliance over Bosnia .
Seeking to mend fences , Christopher told the allies :
`` Let me stress one important fact : The crisis in Bosnia is about Bosnia and the former Yugoslavia .
It does not diminish NATO 's enduring importance . ''
The deep splits within the alliance were highlighted by a letter from Germany 's ambassador to NATO that accused the United States of sowing mistrust among the allies .
The letter from Ambassador Hermann von Richthofen accused the United States of acting behind the backs of its allies .
`` The alliance is divided and in crisis , '' concluded Richthofen 's cable to his Foreign Ministry .
The letter was leaked to a leading German newspaper , the Suddeutsche Zeitung , which published extracts .
Opening the meeting , Willy Claes , the new secretary-general of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization , appealed for unity .
`` We are now being put to -LRB- the -RRB- test , and I have every confidence that our solidarity will see us through now has it has in even darker circumstances . ''
The foreign ministers are anxious their talks not be entirely hijacked by the Bosnian crisis .
They intend to order a study that would set out the terms and conditions for the acceptance of East European countries as new members .
`` We have a moral duty not to squander this historic opportunity to anchor the new democracies of central and eastern Europe permanently in the West , '' Claes said .
The decision to authorize the study will mark a cautious move forward in drawing former adversaries in Eastern Europe who are appealing for membership .
`` Today , we take an important step in the process that will lead to NATO expansion , '' Christopher said .
The study -- dubbed an `` owner 's manual '' for NATO membership -- will take a year to complete .
It will not name candidates for membership , nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
Instead , it will focus on such questions as whether NATO troops will need to be based in new member states ; how much enlargement will cost ; how to integrate the newcomers army into NATO 's command structure
To counter Russian worries about an eastward expansion of NATO , the allies intend later Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Russia and agree to hold regular talks with Moscow on security matters .
Despite attempts to keep the focus on new members , the Bosnian crisis will no doubt occupy a large amount of the ministers ' time .
At a breakfast with British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd , Christopher reviewed the warning U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali delivered Wednesday that unless warring Serbs and Muslims cooperate with the U.N. mission the peacekeepers might be withdrawn .
Hurd said he may go to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
Officials said French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe may join him .
`` We will redouble our efforts to find a diplomatic solution , '' Christopher said .
The latest American approach centers on a call for an international peace conference that would let Bosnian Serbs seek changes in the peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
That plan would require them to cut their holdings in Bosnia from 70 percent to 49 percent .
The Clinton administration , officials say , is also leaning toward approval of political ties between Serbs in Bosnia and Serbia proper -- a big step toward their aim of a Greater Serbia .
On Friday , Christopher will meet with here his counterparts from France , Germany , Britain and Russia to discuss new plans to revive their moribund peace plan for Bosnia .
France and Britain have been criticized in the U.S. Congress for refusing to let the United Nations use the Western military alliance 's air power to the full .
In turn , Congress has forced the Clinton administration to seek a lifting of the arms embargo against Bosnia 's Muslim-led government , something the European NATO allies oppose for fear it would escalate the fighting .
An earthquake with a preliminary magnitude of 5.0 rocked the tourist island of Bali Thursday , an official said .
There were no immediate reports of casualties .
Jumadi , a spokesman of the Meteorology Agency of Bali , said the quake jolted the provincial capital of Denpasar and the neighboring islands of West Nusa Tenggara at 11:59 a.m. -LRB- 0359 GMT -RRB- .
The quake 's epicenter was 117 kilometers -LRB- 73 miles -RRB- away in the Indian Ocean , or about 1,100 kilometers -LRB- 688 miles -RRB- southeast of Jakarta .
A quake of magnitude 5 is capable of causing considerable damage .
Scottish driver David Coulthard , one of the hottest new stars of Formula One racing , has left the Williams Formula One team to sign with rival McLaren , according to British news reports Thursday .
Williams , however , could still try to block the move , The Times reported .
Coulthard , 23 , emerged as a rising star after he was promoted from test driver following the death of Ayrton Senna .
He was paired with Damon Hill for the rest of the season until Nigel Mansell returned from the Indy car series to race in the final three races .
Coulthard 's best performance was a second-place finish behind Hill in the Portuguese Grand Prix .
The Williams team has been debating whether to sign Coulthard or Mansell for next season .
The Times reported that Coulthard , 23 , signed for McLaren before the Australian Grand Prix last month and is set to be paired next season with Finnish driver Mika Hakkinen .
A spokeswoman for McLaren said Thursday that she could not confirm or deny the report until speaking with team boss Ron Dennis .
According to The Times , Williams could seek to have Coulthard 's contract with McLaren ruled invalid at a meeting of the Formula One Contract Recognition Board in Geneva , Switzerland , on Friday .
Williams argues that the deal was signed while Coulthard was still under option to Williams , The Times said .
Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Soskovets left for home on Thursday , concluding a five-day visit to Japan .
Soskovets visited Oita Prefecture , western Japan , before his departure , and proposed that the prefecture and Russian President Boris Yeltsin 's home province of Sverdlovsk establish sister ties during a meeting with Gov. Morihiko Hiramatsu , officials said .
Oita is the home province of Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama .
During his visit from Nov. 27 , Soskovets and Deputy Premier and Foreign Minister Yohei Kono signed a joint press release , confirming a resolution by both governments to work toward conclusion of a peace treaty as well as promising efforts on a number of issues ranging from fishing cooperation to deferment of Russian debts .
Soskovets also agreed to increase trade and economic exchanges between the two nations .
Michael Jackson is trying to end his 5-month-old marriage to Lisa Marie Presley , tabloids in New York and London reported Thursday .
The pop superstar 's manager called the reports `` an outrageous , 100 percent , total lie ! ''
The New York Daily News blamed the alleged breakup on the strain of a bi-coastal relationship , saying Jackson was angered by Presley 's refusal to leave California and live with him in New York .
`` Michael told me they 're splitting , '' the Daily News quoted an unidentified close associate of Jackson as saying .
`` He does n't want to live in California .
He said it 's bad vibes , bad luck for him there . ''
That contradicted a report in London 's Daily Mirror , which claimed Jackson wanted more space and did n't want his wife tagging along with him to New York , where he keeps an apartment in the luxurious Trump Tower .
Jackson spokesman Lee Solters denied the couple were going separate ways , but acknowledged that he had n't spoken with Jackson recently , the News said .
Solters did not return a call to The Associated Press early Thursday .
Jackson 's manager , Bob Jones , heatedly denied talk of a split .
`` This is an outrageous , 100 percent , total lie !
People just do n't want to give these kids a chance .
You have my word that this is simply somebody 's sick fantasy , '' Jones said in Thursday 's New York Newsday .
In the past , Jones and Solters denied the secret wedding had taken place even weeks after it happened .
`` Michael is here in Chicago , recording with R Kelly .
Lisa Marie is in Los Angeles .
She can not be with him when he works .
All his energy has to go into his recording .
When he finishes this album , they will be together , '' Jones said .
Jackson married Elvis Presley 's daughter last spring in the Dominican Republic .
At the time , many speculated that the union was a public relations ploy to improve Presley 's singing career and Jackson 's image , which was tarnished by two child-molestation investigations .
Prosecutors decided not to press charges .
J. Randy Taraborelli , who wrote the 1991 biography `` Michael Jackson : the Magic and the Madness , '' told the U.S. television program `` Hard Copy '' that lawyers were already working on nullifying the marriage .
The Philippine economy , showing continued improvement , expanded by 5.5 percent in this year 's first nine months from January-September last year , officials reported Thursday .
The National Economic and Development Authority said that in the third quarter alone , gross national product grew by 5.9 percent from a year earlier , compared with 2.2 percent growth in the same period of 1993 .
The Economic Planning Agency said the latest quarter 's performance bettered the 5.6 percent annual growth in the second quarter and the 4.9 percent in the first quarter .
`` Strong domestic production combined with continued higher net inflows of incomes from abroad led to the accelerated growth during the period , '' the agency said .
President Fidel Ramos attributed the growth , after years of sluggish performance , to the liberalization of the economy and other reforms such as breaking up cartels in such sectors as telecommunications , shipping and insurance .
He also cited recent moves deregulating foreign exchange trading , opening the banking industry to more foreign banks and improving revenue collection .
Ramos said the growth so far indicated that the economy would expand by 5.5 percent for the entire year , with the fourth quarter getting a further boost from good weather and Christmas spending .
GNP grew by only 2.3 percent in all of 1993 .
`` I am very confident of sustainable progress and sustainable development in the long term , '' Ramos said .
The industrial and agricultural sectors showed impressive performances , the planning agency said .
Agriculture , including fishery and forestry , posted an all-time high growth of 9 percent in the third quarter , compared with a 1.4 percent decline in the same quarter last year .
Ramos said the manufacturing sector 's 4.4 percent growth in January-September , compared to its 0.5 percent decline in 1993 , makes it the `` engine for increased output and employment . ''
A plan to salvage the near-bankrupt airline Iberia appeared doomed Thursday after talks between management and pilots ended in total disagreement over pay cuts .
Management and representatives of the carrier 's two main unions reached a tentative agreement Tuesday on a plan that entailed a wage freeze , salary cuts averaging 8.5 percent and a reduction of some 3,500 jobs through early retirements and buy-outs .
Acceptance by the pilots , who make up 5 percent of the airlines 24,000 employees , would have paved the way for the plan to be implemented .
The plan was considered crucial if the European Union is to allow the Spanish government to grant Iberia a 130 billion peseta -LRB- dlrs 1 billion -RRB- capital injection .
Iberia chairman Javier Salas said the state-owned company would hold meetings with other unions Thursday to evaluate the situation in view of the pilots ' rejection .
Iberia last week touted a more drastic plan that would cut 5,200 jobs and sell company assets .
The proposal triggered a one-day strike that paralyzed Spain 's airports and affected more than 100,000 travelers here and abroad .
Negotiations with the pilots reached a dead end in overnight talks as Iberia demanded a salary reduction of 15 percent based on 1992 earnings .
The pilots insisted that an existing wage agreement through 1995 must be carried out before the 15 percent salary cut could be enforced .
`` The company has presented a generic plan that does not guarantee the future of Iberia and only concentrates on disproportionate salary cuts , '' said Armando Guajardo of the pilots ' union SEPLA .
SEPLA said the company needed a complete overhaul and not just a reduction in salaries and staff .
Salas has warned that the company would be technically bankrupt by March 1995 .
Iberia has posted losses since 1990 .
It ended last year 67 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 530 million -RRB- in the red while losses for this year are expected to top 40 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 300 million -RRB- .
Unions are to decide Thursday if a strike called several weeks ago for Friday still holds .
A botulism outbreak , caused by poorly prepared fish , has killed five people in the past 10 days in the Georgian capital , officials said Thursday .
An additional 60 people have been hospitalized , including several in critical condition , said Nikolai Shavdia , chief sanitary doctor at Tbilisi 's Republic Hospital .
All five people who died had eaten home-smoked fish bought at a local market , Shavdia said .
Others fell ill after eating home-canned meat , also from city markets .
Power and natural gas shortages in the former Soviet republic have rendered many residents unable to cook at home , forcing them to go to markets for prepared foods .
`` The situation is very difficult , '' Shavdia said .
`` We just can not control all the homemade food for sale in the markets and kiosks . ''
Police , who are planning a series of market raids , say they will concentrate on those selling prepared fish or meat .
Botulism is a kind of food poisoning , usually caused by bacteria in improperly canned food .
Modern preserving methods have almost eliminated the disease in most parts of the world .
Coastal police said they seized two tons of explosives and ammunition from a Chinese fishing boat Thursday and claimed they may have been intended for sabotaging Taiwan 's elections Saturday .
Five Chinese men were arrested and the explosives , 5,000 detonators and 250 meters -LRB- 825 feet -RRB- of fuse were taken from the boat about 25 miles -LRB- 40 kms -RRB- off northern Taiwan , police said .
The boat was taking on water after being damaged in strong winds , they said , and the men gave themselves up when the boat was intercepted .
On Saturday , Taiwan will hold its largest-scale elections to choose a governor , provincial assembly , and mayors and city councils of Taipei and Kaohsiung .
Wu Tung-ming , director of the Investigation Bureau , told the legislature two weeks ago that the government was investigating the possibility that China might try to sabotage the elections by offering money to candidates or fomenting public disorder .
Officials have said China fears possible election victories by the pro-independence opposition .
China regards Taiwan as a renegade province and opposes moves toward Taiwanese independence .
`` It is the largest amount of ammunition seized in recent years , and we suspect that it may have been meant for use in disturbing social order during the elections , '' Yang Wen-ning , chief of the Tamsui squad , said in an interview .
The five men , Xiao Qingxiang , 34 , Xiao Liangyung , 22 , Xiao Wenlung , 44 , Xiao Qingguo , 29 , and Gong Guoyun , 21 , were likely to be sent to the Taipei District Court for further investigation Thursday night , police said .
They told police they were asked by unidentified men to deliver the ammunition to Taiwanese smugglers for a reward of 10,000 yuan -LRB- U.S. dlrs 1,175 -RRB- .
They said they left China 's Fujian province Wednesday night and were unaware what the ammunition was for .
Taiwanese gangsters have been smuggling small batches of guns and ammunition from China since Taiwan allowed indirect contacts with China in 1987 .
Most smuggled items are drugs , wine and farm products .
Taiwan is the seat of the ruling Nationalists who fled the Communist takeover of China in 1949 .
British officials will meet leaders of the IRA 's allies in Sinn Fein next week , in the first official face-to-face contact between the two sides since the IRA cease-fire , the government announced Thursday .
The time and location of the talks has not been set , said a spokesman at Prime Minister John Major 's office .
Britain will be represented by Quentin Thomas , a junior minister in the Northern Ireland Office .
Sinn Fein has indicated that Martin McGuinness , the party 's second-ranking leader , will head its delegation .
Major 's spokesman , who spoke on condition of anonymity , said Britain had not changed its mind about excluding Sinn Fein from an investment conference in Belfast , despite pressure from American politicians to the contrary .
The first talks are expected to concentrate on conditions for Sinn Fein entering into all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland .
British officials have indicated they will press for the IRA to surrender at least some of its weaponry .
On Wednesday , Adams and John Hume , Northern Ireland 's most respected politician , issued a statement pressing Britain to begin talking with Sinn Fein .
`` There should be no more stalling , '' they said .
A series of meetings and joint statements last year by Adams and Hume , leader of the Catholic-based Social Democratic and Labor Party , helped pave the way for the IRA 's open-ended truce .
Britain has refused to invite Sinn Fein officials to the foreign investment forum in Belfast on Dec. 13-14 .
President Clinton plans to send Commerce Secretary Ron Brown at the head of a U.S. delegation , but a congressmen visiting Ireland says Clinton should rethink that if Britain keeps shunning Sinn Fein .
`` Everyone seems to be acting in good faith except the British , '' U.S. Rep. Peter King -LRB- R-N.Y. -RRB- , said Wednesday in Dublin , the Irish capital .
The Achille Lauro smoldered on a placid sea Thursday , a day after a raging fire forced the nearly 1,000 people aboard to take to lifeboats and abandon the cruise ship off Somalia .
Two people were reported dead from the Italian liner , which gained notoriety in 1985 when Palestinian terrorists hijacked and killed a wheelchair-bound American passenger .
After a night aboard the oil tanker that picked them up , hundreds of passengers began transferring aboard an armada of commercial vessels and two U.S. Navy ships for passage to nearby ports , including Mombasa in Kenya , the Seychelles and Djibouti .
The operation was '' very organized , '' said Cmdr. T. McCreary , spokesman for the U.S. Navy 's Central Command , based in Bahrain . ''
Folks down there have a pretty good handle on the situation , '' he said .
The transfer was expected to last most of the day .
At mid-morning on Thursday , the empty , scarred Achille Lauro was still afloat , listing badly to port .
White steam nd gray smoke poured from its port side and smaller streams came drifting out of the lower starboard deck .
Though her name was still visible on the stern , the cruise ship 's blue and white paint was scorched and mottled , the white stars on her two smokestacks blackened by heat and soot .
Although crippled , the Achille Lauro appeared in no danger of sinking quickly .
The ship was listing at about 20 degrees , John Briand , captain of the oil tanker Lima , told the BBC .
The fire started Wednesday , apparently in the passenger area , but the cause was not known , said the ship 's owner , Starlauro of Genoa , Italy .
But Dmitrios Skapinkais , the Greek captain of the Treasure Island , said the liner 's captain , who came aboard to use his ship 's radiotelephone , said the fire started in the engine room .
Eight people were injured in the fire .
About 60 crewmembers fought the fire before abandoning the 23,478-ton ship 210 kilometers -LRB- 130 miles -RRB- south of the Horn of Africa .
The pilot of a plane carrying an Associated Press reporter and cameramen put the ship 's position at 160 miles east of the small Somali fishing village of Eil .
Capt. Ferdinando Lolli , a port official in Rome , said the ship was carrying 581 passengers and 404 crew .
Most of the crew was Italian , and the passengers mainly South African , German , Dutch and British .
Late Wednesday evening , Italian Coast Guard officials reported that everyone on the Achille Lauro was accounted for .
Starlauro identified the dead as a Briton and a German .
The Panamanian oil ship Hawaiian King was one of the first ships to arrive at the scene and took on about 800 people , said a coast guard official in Rome , Adm. Eugenio Sicurezza .
`` Quite a few people were injured in the transfer -- there 's a few broken bones and some pretty tortured souls , '' Briand said , adding that many of the rescued passengers were elderly .
Many had to spend the night on the Hawaiian King 's deck , Briand said , and other ships sent over food , blankets and toiletries .
Two U.S. warships , the USS Gettysburg and USS Halyburton , arrived overnight and dispatched helicopters to ferry water , food and medical supplies to the survivors , McCreary said .
The Achille Lauro left Genoa on Nov. 19 , stopped in Israel , and its next port of call was to be Durban , South Africa , on Friday , said Carla Gotta , a spokeswoman for the cruise ship 's owner .
The terrorists who hijacked the Achille Lauro in 1985 shot American Leon Klinghoffer and pushed him in his wheelchair off the ship .
The hijackers escaped the vessel and boarded a jet , but U.S. fighter planes forced it to land in Italy and the hijackers were captured .
Launched in 1946 in the Netherlands , the Achille Lauro was acquired 20 years later by the Neapolitan shipping dynasty .
It first transported Italian immigrant workers to and from Australia and was outfitted for pleasure cruises in 1970 .
The liner rammed a fishing boat in 1971 off Italy , killing a Neapolitan fisherman .
And on Dec. 2 , 1981 , fire broke out aboard ship off the Canary Islands .
Panicked passengers jumped into the sea , and two of them drowned .
Wimbledon 's Vinnie Jones , renowned as one of the most physical players in the Premier League , will make his international debut later this month with Wales .
The English-born Jones was named Thursday to the Welsh squad for the European Championship qualifier against Bulgaria in Cardiff on Dec. 14 .
Jones , who turns 30 next month , qualifies for Wales because his grandfather , who died in 1979 , was born in Ruthin , Clwyd .
Jones is known as the `` hard man '' of English soccer .
He was sent off for the eighth time in his career last month and has amassed 136 disciplinary points in the last four seasons .
His call-up to the Wales team came on the same day a national newspaper published a survey of referees labeling him as `` the dirtiest player of all . ''
Wales manager Mike Smith hopes Jones can help inspire a team that has suffered successive humiliating defeats to Moldova and Georgia .
An investigation into the April 7 murder of 10 Belgian peacekeepers in the Rwandan capital of Kigali by `` out-of-control '' government soldiers blames the United Nations for the carnage .
Released this week , the report cited inadequate rules of self-defense for U.N. soldiers in Rwanda saying these made them mere `` cops walking a beat . ''
Also , the U.N. provided insufficient backup for the Belgians in the form of Bangladeshi soldiers whose `` operational value and availability '' the report questioned .
At 2.40 a.m. on April 7 , 10 Belgian U.N. peackeepers were sent for guard duty to the home of Rwandan Prime Minister Agathe Uwilingiyimana in Kigali .
There , they were surrounded by Rwandan soldiers who took their arms and then shot and killed each Belgian soldier at about 9 a.m.
Ms. Uwilingiyimana , who left her residence , was also killed .
The Belgians were murdered by `` out-of-control Rwandan soldiers who were agitated '' by radio broadcasts railing against Belgians , Rwanda 's former colonial rulers , according to the Belgian army report .
The murders came a day after a plane carrying Rwandan President Juvenal Habyarimana and Cyprien Ntaryamira , his Burundi counterpart , were shot down .
This ignited ethnic strife in which hundreds of thousands of Rwandans , mostly Tutsis , died and spawned an exodus of some two million people into neighboring Zaire .
Three world record-holders are in the running for the International Athletic Foundation 's male athlete-of-the-year award .
The IAF said Thursday that the field had been narrowed to pole vaulter Sergei Bubka of the Ukraine , distance runner Noureddine Morceli of Algeria and Cuban high jumper Javier Sottomayor .
The three women 's finalists are heptathlete Jackie Joyner-Kersee of the United States , distance runner Sonia O'Sullivan of Ireland and Russian sprinter Irina Privalova .
The winners will be announced Friday in conjunction with the annual IAF gala .
Police ousted hunger-striking politicians from government offices but the former East German communists vowed Thursday to continue their protest against a 67-million-mark -LRB- dlrs 43-million -RRB- tax levy .
The Party of Democratic Socialism said 11 people , including party president Lothar Bisky and Gregor Gysi , leader of the party 's 30 members of parliament , were fasting Thursday .
PDS leaders began their hunger strike Wednesday afternoon .
Police removed them late Wednesday , carrying some of them out .
The PDS members then moved to party offices at the Berlin city legislature and said the hunger strike would continue indefinitely .
The protest spread to the eastern cities of Dresden and Schwerin , where hundreds of party members and sympathizers demonstrated Thursday morning at state legislatures .
The party , formed in 1990 out of remnants of the collapsed East German Communist Party , claims the government is trying to tax it into bankruptcy .
Authorities accuse the PDS of over-simplifying a complex financial issue and of reneging on laws passed by the East German parliament in 1990 .
The corporate levy covers the first half of 1990 -- before German unification -- when the PDS as successor to the communists still held vast assets around the country .
East German political groups entrusted their assets to an independent commission that is to determine how much they can keep and how much is national property .
The PDS wanted its levy to be paid from its assets held by the independent commission , but the commission refused .
In the Oct. 16 national elections , the PDS grabbed 20 percent of votes in eastern Germany and 4.4 percent nationally , mostly on resentment among eastern Germans who feel they are second-class citizens in the united Germany .
Two more journalists have been assassinated in Algeria , security forces said Thursday .
Nearly 30 journalists have been killed since they became targets of Islamic militants two years ago .
The latest victims were Ahmed Issaad , a reporter for state television , and Nasseredine Lekhal , a journalist with the state-run daily El-Massa .
They were stabbed to death Wednesday in Boufarik , south of Algiers , security forces said .
More than 11,000 people have been killed in a three-year insurgency pitting Muslim fundamentalist militants against the army-backed government .
The militants , depicting the media as government pawns , have designated journalists as a prime target of their assassination campaign , along with foreigners and intellectuals .
Nearly 30 journalists been murdered since May 1993 .
An estimated 200 Algerian journalists have left the country because of the killings and harsh government action against newspapers which violate strict security regulations .
