Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak arrived Thursday on a previously unannounced visit for talks with President Hafez Assad on the Middle East peace process .
Assad greeted Mubarak at Damascus Airport and the two drove straight to the Ash-Shaeb , or People 's Palace , for closed-door discussions .
Mubarak 's visit came a few days ahead of a scheduled trip to the region by U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher , his sixth this year in an effort to break the deadlock in the Syrian-Israeli negotiations .
These have been stalled since February over Syria 's demand that Israel declare its willingness to make a complete withdrawal from the Golan Heights .
Israel captured the strategic plateau in southwestern Syria in the 1967 Middle East war and annexed it in 1981 .
Israel has offered a partial withdrawal phased over several years .
The Israelis want Assad to agree to a complete normalization of relations , rather than just an end to 46 years of hostilities , and discuss the nature of the peace agreement before addressing the question of the Golan .
Mubarak , who has been a key mediator in the three-year-old peace process and is a frequent visitor to Damascus , will also discuss other regional issues with Assad , officials reported .
Government-run media continued what has become a daily media barrage of criticism of Israel .
Al-Baath , newspaper of the ruling Baath Party , said that Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin `` wants to maintain tension and war in the region , disguised as peace .
... He also works to blackmail the U.S.A. ''
A Russian ultimatum demanding an end to Chechnya 's civil war expired today amid signs that Moscow was preparing to send troops into the breakaway southern republic .
A trickle of heavily loaded cars and trucks left the capital this morning as nervous civilians continued to head for the countryside , fearing an attack by Russian soldiers .
Central Grozny was virtually empty following another nerve-jangling night of intermittent small arms fire from jumpy fighters around the city .
A single military jet roared over the capital as the Russian deadline passed .
Later , heavy machine-gun fire rang out from the city center .
The fighting pits forces loyal to Chechen President Dzhokar Dudayev , who has declared Chechnya independent from Russia , against rebels whom Dudayev says are armed and led by Moscow .
Russian President Boris Yeltsin ordered warring Chechens to lay down their arms and release all prisoners by this morning or face Russian military intervention .
The ultimatum has been met with defiance by Chechens .
Russian media reported several transport planes have brought weapons and troops to the border of Chechnya , in the Caucasus Mountains region of southern Russia .
The conflict is the latest to underline the tensions among scores of ethnic groups in the former Soviet Union .
The Caucasus region has been especially fractious , with recent fighting in the Ossetia and Abkhazia regions of Georgia and the Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan .
For Moscow , which governs dozens of republics and regions in the Russian Federation , Chechnya has become a test of whether it is willing to use military might to hold the country together .
No other region has gone as far as Chechnya and declared independence .
Yeltsin spokesman Vyacheslev Kostikov in Moscow said measures to resolve the Chechen conflict had `` begun to be implemented . ''
He did not elaborate .
On Wednesday , opposition jets carried out a second day of air raids on the outskirts of Grozny , while Dudayev 's forces posted armed volunteers around the city .
A 22-year-old woman walking down a dark street suddenly found a naked , newly born baby being thrust into her hands .
She chased the young woman who had come up from behind and pressed the baby on her -- without saying a word -- but quickly lost her , Shiniichi Kawana of the Kanagawa Police Station said Thursday .
The umbilical cord still was attached to the infant girl , believed less than a day old at the time is was handed over Wednesday night in an area near Yokohama , south of Tokyo , Kawana said .
He said the baby was not even wrapped in a towel .
The baby now is all right in a hospital , he added .
He did not identify the woman to whom it was passed .
Overshadowed by the Bosnian crisis , NATO foreign ministers met Thursday to begin laying the groundwork for the entry of former Warsaw Pact foes as new members in coming years .
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher was using the two-day meeting to try to smooth extraordinary strains in U.S.-European ties .
He was expected to tell the allies that the Clinton administration has swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
It marks a major policy switch by Washington under pressure particularly from Britain and France .
Seeking to mend fences , Christopher told the allies :
`` Let me stress one important fact : The crisis in Bosnia is about Bosnia and the former Yugoslavia .
It does not diminish NATO 's enduring importance . ''
`` We will redouble our efforts to find a diplomatic solution , '' he said .
Apart from inevitably dealing with Bosnia , the foreign ministers of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization will move cautiously order a study to set out the terms for letting East European countries join .
`` We have a moral duty not to squander this historic opportunity to anchor the new democracies of central and eastern Europe permanently in the West , '' NATO secretary-general Willy Claes said .
The study will take a year to complete .
It will not name candidates for membership , nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
It will focus on such questions as whether NATO troops will need to be based in new member states ; how much enlargement will cost ; how to integrate the newcomers army into NATO 's command structure
To counter Russian worries about an eastward expansion of NATO , the allies intend later Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Russia and agree to hold regular talks with Moscow on security matters .
On Friday , Christopher intends to lay out the U.S. approach to the Bosnian war in a meeting with British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd and foreign ministers Alain Juppe of France , Andrei V. Kozyrev of Russia and Klaus Kinkel of Germany .
