A Japanese seminarian who was reported missing has called his superior , saying he was safe in the central Philippine city of Cebu , another seminarian said Thursday .
Norihito Sako , 39 , of Sapporo , was reported missing Nov. 20 after failing to return to Manila from a visit to Pampanga province , where he was helping victims of the June 1991 Mount Pinatubo eruptions .
Fellow seminarian Edgar Zamudio said Sako called the director of the Claret Formation Center , the Rev. Carlos Rivas , Wednesday from Cebu , 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- southeast of Manila .
Zamudio said Rivas left for Cebu immediately after receiving the call from Sako and did n't tell the other seminarians why the Japanese went to Cebu .
`` As far as we know , he is in Cebu and he is alive , '' Zamudio said , adding that Sako had visited that city several times previously .
Sako has finished theology studies at Sophia University in Tokyo and belongs to the Diocese of Yokohama .
In May 1993 , he came to Manila for graduate studies at the Jesuit-run Ateneo de Manila University , leading to possible ordination as a priest in 1995 .
Indonesia will become an oil importer in the next 20 years as domestic consumption overtakes declining production , the U.S. Embassy said Thursday .
Petroleum Report , issued annually by the embassy , said domestic consumption could exceed production as soon as the early part of the next decade .
The report said Indonesia , which produced an average of 1.5 million barrels of crude oil daily in l993 , lowered its crude exports by 3 percent to 776,000 barrels a day this year .
Daily consumption of petroleum fuels rose 7 percent to 262 million barrels last year .
However , the report said oil and gas will continue to play a prominent role in Indonesia 's economy in years to come .
Indonesia , the third oldest oil producer in the world after the United States and Russia , has an estimated 71.86 billion barrels of crude oil reserves .
Of that amount , 10.41 billion barrels -- 8.09 billion onshore and 2.32 billion offshore -- are proven and probable , the report said .
Cpl. Kenneth E. Ruiz , the last of three Marines to be tried in the May 1 stabbing death of a fellow Marine , has been sentenced to life in prison , the U.S. military said Thursday .
The 23-year-old Ruiz , of Linden , Calif. , was found guilty Wednesday of premeditated murder in the killing of Sgt. Michael A. Allen at Iwakuni Marine Corps Air Station near Hiroshima , a military statement said .
Cpl. Michael R. Stelling of Springfield , Md. , and Lance Cpl. Mark D. Jimenez of Lamont , Calif. , already have been sentenced in the stabbing .
Stelling was sentenced to 40 years and Jimenez to 30 .
In both cases , the full sentences of life in prison were reduced in line with pre-trial agreements .
Prosecutors at Ruiz ' trial said the three Marines lured Allen to a secluded part of the air station and stabbed him repeatedly .
They then kicked Allen into a drainage ditch and left him to die , the release said .
According to the military newspaper Stars and Stripes , Jimenez testified at his trial that the three killed Allen because they thought he was giving investigators information about a Hispanic gang to which all four Marines belonged .
Prosecutors had called for a life sentence , saying Ruiz was the driving force behind the conspiracy .
But at the trial Ruiz denied that : `` We all conspired to cover up the murder .
There were no leaders and no followers , just three idiots who became criminals . ''
NATO foreign ministers on Thursday approved an American proposal for a blueprint setting out the terms and conditions for the entry of former Warsaw Pact foes as new members in the coming years .
The ministers endorsed a 12-month program to consider financing , structure , nuclear and other issues related to the expansion of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization to include Central and East European democracies .
Anxious not to upset Russia , the foreign ministers , according to an allied source , emphasized that the alliance was `` not trying to create a hostile bloc . ''
A subsidiary of Japan 's Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. said Thursday it has agreed to buy German picture tube plants owned by Finland 's Nokia Consumer Electronics .
Matsushita Electronics Corp. would not disclose the amount it will pay for Esslingen , Germany-based Nokia Display Technics GmbH , a wholly owned Nokia subsidiary .
Nokia announced in March that it would withdraw from the picture-tube business and shut down its Esslingen and Straubing picture-tube facilities by the end of 1994 .
Under the agreement , Matsushita Electronics will acquire Nokia Display 's fixed assets , a Matsushita official said .
Nokia will lay off the current work force at the plants by the end of December , but Matsushita Electronics likely will rehire many of the workers , though it is not obligated to do so under the terms of the deal , he said .
Matsushita said the acquisition is aimed at extending supplies of cathode-ray tubes to Matsushita Group factories and to other television makers in Europe .
With the purchase , Matsushita Electronics will have four production bases outside Japan .
Matsushita Electronics is a Japanese maker of semiconductors and cathode-ray tubes .
Its shares are n't listed on the nation 's stock exchange .
Its parent , Matsushita Electric Industrial , is the world 's largest maker of consumer electronics .
KABUL , Afghanistan -LRB- AP -RRB- - With a brief lull in the civil war , the United Nations is trying to send a large relief convoy into Kabul for the first time in six months , an official said Thursday .
A truck convoy carrying hundreds of tons of food , medicine and plastic sheeting recently left from neighboring Pakistan and is now south of the besieged city .
U.N. officials are trying to negotiate safe passage across the front line in south Kabul , said a U.N. official who requested anonymity .
Opposition leader Gulbuddin Hekmatyar controls the main roads leading into the city and no large convoys can reach Kabul without his approval .
And as winter descends on war-torn Kabul , the food situation is expected to deteriorate .
At present , the city 's food is being supplied mostly by small-scale traders who cross the front line daily to buy flour , wood and gasoline from merchants in opposition-held territory to the south and the east of Kabul .
There 's enough food available , but prices have skyrocketed .
If the U.N. effort is successful , the convoy could reach Kabul this weekend .
It would be the first U.N. relief convoy to reach the capital since June .
Hekmatyar 's forces tightened their blockade last winter and food supplies were running low until U.N. Secretary Boutros Boutros-Ghali made a personal appeal to Hekmatyar , who then eased the roadblocks .
But many Afghans are critical of the United Nations , which removed its international staff from Kabul when heavy fighting erupted in January .
A small staff made up entirely of Afghans now handles the limited U.N. operation in Kabul , while the U.N. 's international staff remains in Pakistan .
There were sporadic bursts of gunfire along the front line in southern Kabul on Thursday .
But compared to the usual salvos of rockets and mortar fire , the city has been relatively peaceful for the last week .
President Burhanuddin Rabbani 's government controls most of the capital .
But nine separate Islamic factions remain locked in a bitter battle that broke out after the groups ousted a Communist government in 1992 .
