A moderate quake struck the Ionian Sea island of Levkas Thursday , causing some damage but no injuries .
The Salonica University Seismological Institute said the quake had a preliminary magnitude of 5.2 and its epicenter on the seabed near Levkas , 300 kilometers -LRB- 186 miles -RRB- southwest of this northern city .
It occurred at 9:17 a.m. -LRB- 0717 GMT -RRB- .
It was followed a few minutes later by a quake with a preliminary magnitude of 4.6 .
Local authorities said some buildings were slightly damaged by the initial tremor , but there were no injuries .
It was the second quake to hit the Levkas region in two days .
A quake with a preliminary magnitude of 5.3 hit the area Tuesday but caused little damage .
The region is considered to be earthquake prone .
Officials at the Athens Seismological Institute , located in the capital , said they thought the tremors following Tuesday 's quake to be aftershocks .
A quake with a moment magnitude of 2.5 to 3 is the smallest generally felt by people .
A magnitude 5 can cause moderate damage while a 6 can cause severe damage under a populated area .
