President Boris Yeltsin ordered the government to sell a minority stake in Russia 's largest state television and radio company .
The government will keep a controlling 51 percent interest , however .
Ostankino , once called commonwealth television , is broadcast throughout the former Soviet Union .
Its Moscow broadcasting tower was the scene of the worst fighting during the political uprising in October 1993 .
Twelve major companies and organizations are buying the 49 percent stake in Ostankino .
They include ITAR-Tass , Menatep , Stolichny and Inkombank commercial banks , Aeroflot International Airlines and the Avtovaz car manufacturer .
Yeltsin 's decree Wednesday said the new venture , called Russian Public Television , would inherit Ostankino 's nationwide Channel One .
Ostankino chief Alexander Yakovlev , who was the architect of `` glasnost '' under former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev , told the ITAR-Tass news agency that the sale would help make Russia 's television independent .
Yeltsin 's opponents have complained that state television favors the government and offers biased coverage of political events -- charges that Russian broadcast executives deny .
In a pre-emptive strike against rival Fox , NBC wants federal regulators to make it easier for U.S. media companies to get financing from foreign investors -- if existing foreign ownership limits are not enforced .
`` If the rules on foreign investment and foreign ownership change , then they should change for everyone , not just for Fox , '' NBC said in a petition to the Federal Communications Commission on Wednesday .
The FCC , in a separate proceeding , is reviewing whether Fox 's acquisition of six TV stations , using money from a foreign corporation , that made up the foundation of the network violated foreign ownership limits .
The provisions limit a foreign company or individual from owning more than 25 percent of a broadcast station .
NBC says the FCC has not granted any waivers of the limits since their creation 60 years ago .
If the agency decides to give Fox a waiver from such restrictions , all broadcast companies should be allowed waivers , Richard Cotton , NBC senior vice president and general counsel , said in an interview .
The FCC approved the acquisition of those stations from Metromedia Inc. in 1986 .
The stations are in Washington , New York , Los Angeles , Chicago , Dallas and Houston .
The NBC petition builds on a complaint filed earlier this year by the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People , which asserted that Fox violated federal foreign ownership restrictions .
According to Fox disclosures to the FCC this summer , all but 1 percent of the dlrs 600 million used to purchase the stations was put up by News Corp. , which is based in Australia .
Chairman Rupert Murdoch , who became a U.S. citizen to buy the stations , owns stock representing 76 percent of the voting rights of Fox Television .
The remaining 24 percent is held by News Corp.
The key question facing the FCC is who owns the stations -- Murdoch or News Corp.
But Preston Padden , Fox Broadcasting Co. 's president of network distribution , said it does n't matter because Murdoch controls News Corp. `` It all leads back to a U.S. citizen -- Rupert Murdoch , '' he said .
Padden said in an interview : `` We do n't have a waiver .
We have n't asked for a waiver .
We do n't intend to ask for a waiver .
We do n't need a waiver . ''
The ownership of Fox stations complies with the restrictions , Padden said .
NBC 's filing -- the latest in a series of assaults against Fox -- is an attempt to sabotage a competitor , Padden asserted .
NBC said that if the FCC determines that Fox violated foreign ownership limits , Fox should not be given a waiver from the restrictions unless competitors are also allowed waivers .
`` What if we want a foreign partner ? ''
asked one NBC official , speaking on the condition of anonymity .
Cotton said NBC 's petition is not motivated by a desire to get an infusion of foreign capital , but to `` level the playing field , '' between NBC and Fox , Cotton said .
Cotton and other NBC officials say that the FCC , in an attempt to help nurture a fourth network , has given Fox breaks from broadcast regulations over the last several years .
`` Enough is enough , '' Cotton said .
`` The same rules should apply to all competitors . ''
Queen Elizabeth II will visit South Africa in March , returning there for the first time since she made her 21st birthday broadcast from Cape Town in 1947 .
In a statement on Thursday , Buckingham Palace said the queen and her husband , Prince Philip , will be in South Africa from March 19 to March 25 .
As Princess Elizabeth , the queen accompanied her parents , King George VI , who died in 1952 , and Queen Elizabeth , now the 94-year-old Queen Mother , when they visited South Africa in 1947 .
She turned 21 in Cape Town and broadcast from there dedicating herself to the service of Britain and now 51-nation Commonwealth of its ex-colonies .
As international hostility grew to apartheid , no British sovereign visited South Africa after 1947 .
Philip represented the queen at the installation of President Nelson Mandela , South Africa 's first black president , in April .
The queen 's daughter , Princess Anne , was there Nov. 22-Nov .
The death toll from Mount Merapi 's eruption last week has risen to 52 , with many more deaths expected among the 29 victims in critical condition , an official said Thursday .
Bambang Pramudia , an official at the Sardjito hospital in Jogjakarta , said little could be done for those badly burned by a cloud of steam and gas that spewed suddenly from the 2,968-meter -LRB- 7,952-foot -RRB- volcano on Nov. 22 .
`` Those who do survive will need major plastic surgery for burns , '' he said .
The volcano 's activity has begun to show signs of subsiding , said Atje Purbawinata of Jogjakarta 's geology office , but villagers have been told to stay at emergency shelters until the situation was really safe .
Purbawinata said heavy rains have stopped the search for other victims believed trapped inside destroyed homes .
More than 5,000 people have been evacuated from villages devastated by the eruption , which demolished homes , flattened forests , destroyed crops and wiped out livestock .
Tons of ash were dumped on the surrounding area and some lava poured out .
Merapi , considered one of the world 's most active volcanoes , is one of 129 in Indonesia , a sprawling archipelago that lies along what is known as the Pacific Ring of Fire .
Merapi has been active throughout the year .
Its last fatal eruption occurred in 1976 , when 28 people were killed and 1,176 left homeless .
Its most destructive eruption was in 1672 , when about 3,000 people were believed killed .
