The first international political summit on AIDS opened Thursday with appeals to governments to protect victims ' dignity and provide more money to combat the disease .
`` I am issuing a general call to arms , '' U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali told officials from 42 nations .
`` We are not meeting here simply to issue a further warning , but to declare a planetary emergency ... Every day , AIDS kills children , destroys families , drains economies , threatens communities .
We must act without delays . ''
Twelve prime ministers , 17 health ministers and other Cabinet officials met to strengthen political commitments to fight AIDS and expand cooperation between developed and developing nations .
A non-binding declaration to be signed Thursday evening pledges to promote international cooperation in research , partnerships between public and private sectors and increased safeguards for blood transfusions .
Participants will vow to reach out to children and `` empower women ... to reduce their vulnerability '' by engaging them more in policy-making .
The summit was one of the focal points of World AIDS Day , being observed around the world with education programs and fund-raising events .
Australians attended special church services in memory of the 3,500 compatriots killed by AIDS .
In South Africa , where the disease is spreading rapidly , health officials and politicians wrapped a huge red ribbon around St. George 's Cathedral in Cape Town as part of efforts to increase awareness about AIDS .
In China , a group with no government ties took to Beijing streets to distribute pamphlets about AIDS prevention .
It 's rare for an independent group to be allowed to organize high-profile public activities such as passing out leaflets .
Federico Mayor , head of the U.N. Educational , Scientific and Cultural Organization where the one-day Paris summit was held , said nations must spend more to fight AIDS rather than rely on private charities .
`` In our budgets we have funds to pay the price of war , but we have made no provision for the cost of the fight against AIDS , '' Mayor said .
Boosted spending `` must be accompanied by ethical surveillance to prevent or check any measures -- including legislative ones -- that would tend to exclude or discriminate against people who are ill from the disease , '' he said .
Respect for AIDS sufferers was a common theme at the summit , attended by several AIDS activist groups .
`` To us on the front lines , people living with HIV and AIDS and affected and vulnerable communities must have the right to assemble and form associations to fight the epidemic , '' said Richard Burzynski , an HIV sufferer with the AIDS rights group Icaso .
`` This means that all laws which deny the freedom of people to cross borders because of HIV must be abolished , '' Burzynski said .
`` This means all laws which criminalize or discriminate against homosexuals , drug users , migrants and refugees , and sex workers must be abolished . ''
Governments tend to ignore or marginalize sexual minorities , worsening rather than addressing the AIDS epidemic , said the International Gay and Lesbian Association .
High-risk populations must be accepted and educated , the association said .
The World Bank , the world 's biggest donor in the campaign against AIDS , Thursday pledged dlrs 150 million annually to combat the disease in developing countries .
The bank , which has already extended dlrs 600 million to anti-AIDS projects , mostly in the Third World , said the new aid would be in the form of low-interest , 40-year loans .
France recently announced it would increase its aid to international agencies that fight AIDS by more than tenfold to 132 million francs -LRB- dlrs 25 million . -RRB-
Currently , however , more than 90 percent of the money pledged to fight AIDS goes toward helping only the 8 percent of those afflicted in developed countries .
Some 17 million people are known to have been infected with the HIV virus , about two-thirds in Africa .
Elements of the French media pronounced the summit a failure even before it began .
The daily Liberation criticized the final declaration as `` banal , '' predicted that little new funding would be generated , and said the French were rebuffed in efforts to lure U.S. Vice President Al Gore , British Prime Minister John Major and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl to the summit .
When it comes to having fun , the Irish are still Number One in the European Union .
But what 's more , they are getting better at enjoying themselves than other Europeans , the EU statistics agency Eurostat said Thursday .
It issued figures showing the Irish -- who topped the fun meter in the 1980s -- continue to outspend the rest on entertainment , recreation , education and culture .
The average Irish household devotes 12.1 percent of its consumer spending on these four areas `` that could loosely be described as the ` fun index ' , '' said Eurostat .
In the second half of the 1980s , the Irish scored 10.6 .
On the latest index , Britons are second -- at 10.2 percent , barely up from 9.5 -- followed by the Dutch and Danes , both virtually unchanged at 10.1 percent .
Across the 12-nation EU , the 380,000 Luxembourgers have the least good time , devoting only 4.1 percent of their consumer spending to things considered fun .
The Eurostat figures are part of wider survey into consumer spending .
Without giving a margin or error , it reports figures for 1992 which show that :
- Italians spend most on clothes and shoes -LRB- 9.9 percent of their total consumer outlays -RRB- and the Danes least -LRB- 5.3 percent -RRB- .
- Germans spend most on cars -LRB- 5.4 percent -RRB- and the Irish least -LRB- 3.3 percent -RRB- -- EU citizens ' spending on food , beverages and tobacco is dropping .
The average per EU household has gone to 19.1 percent of spending , down from 20.8 percent in the 1985-89 period .
The Greeks top this department .
Up to 36.7 percent of their consumer spending goes to food , drink and a smoke `` but the Irish are n't far behind -LRB- 34.8 percent -RRB- .
Third are the Portuguese -LRB- 33.6 percent -RRB- with the British -LRB- 21.6 percent -RRB- next . ''
