He was a caring corner grocer , a Korean immigrant and church deacon who gave advice to neighborhood boys and organized an anti-crime petition drive .
Then Moon Hwang went from crusader to victim : Police say he was beaten to death behind his one-story brick store by a gang of teen-agers out for money .
They did n't know he carried none .
Their take : two loaves of bread and a bag of bean sprouts .
Eighteen-year-old Richard Simons and six juveniles , all members of a gang that called itself the Black Gangsta Family , have been charged with murder , robbery and conspiracy in the Nov. 18 attack .
Prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz said Wednesday that he would seek to try the juveniles as adults .
Police said the assailants used a BB gun to shoot out a light that illuminated the gravel-and-dirt parking lot behind the store .
When Hwang and his wife closed the store about 8 p.m. and headed to their car , police said , the youths attacked in the darkness .
Hwang 's wife , Young , ran for help and escaped unhurt .
Hwang , beaten over the head , died two days later .
Police were n't sure what the murder weapon was .
Hwang , 54 , had no money because he timed his deposits to avoid carrying cash at dangerous times , police said .
One of the juveniles also is charged with killing a 15-year-old girl less than a day later .
Le-Ann Washington was shot in the forehead from point-blank range after arguing with the youth as she walked home from a mall .
On Wednesday , Bolf 's Market was still closed , the neon `` Fresh Fruit , Produce '' sign still lit , the newspapers inside now almost 2 weeks old .
Neighbors in this working-class community of 16,000 people 5 miles -LRB- eight kilometers -RRB- west of Atlantic City fondly remembered a man who cared about his customers and stuck to his principles , refusing to sell cigarettes and condoms to minors .
`` He would have father-and-son talks with the younger customers who came in , '' said Patrick Lee , a liquor store owner who met Hwang through the Korean Chamber of Commerce of Atlantic County , which Hwang founded .
`` He cared about local children and how they acted , '' Lee said .
`` He 'd say , ` You should n't do this ' and ` You should n't do that . '' '
Hwang cared about his fellow merchants , too .
In October , he sent a letter and a petition with 55 signatures to the Atlantic City police chief listing four violent incidents , including the Oct. 15 killing of a convenience store worker in Atlantic City .
Later , he met with Atlantic City police officials and persuaded them to patrol Korean-owned stores more frequently .
His motives were far from selfish -- his store is in Pleasantville .
Conservatives ' hopes of avoiding a potentially destructive duel between their top presidential hopefuls were dashed Thursday by a parliamentary report saying a primary could not be organized before the April election .
The report by a 36-member legislative commission increased the chances that Premier Edouard Balladur and Paris Mayor Jacques Chirac will compete for conservative votes all the way into first-round presidential voting on April 23 .
They are likely to be joined by a candidate from the center-right Union for French Democracy , as well as far-right and far-left candidates and the probable Socialist Party candidate , Jacques Delors .
A two-candidate runoff on May 7 will determine the successor to Socialist President Francois Mitterrand .
Many conservatives fear that the bitter infighting between Balladur and Chirac , both members of the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic , will ensure Delors ' victory .
Delors , who steps down next month as chief executive of the European Union , has pulled ahead in recent opinion polls .
The parliament commission , composed of lawmakers from both main conservative parties , said it would be impossible to organize a primary that would satisfy all candidates and produce broadly accepted results .
`` In the absence of any legislation ... it would inevitably give rise to endless challenges and uncontrollable arguments , '' the commission 's report said .
`` The result on public opinion would be disastrous , and the winner 's legitimacy would be seriously affected . ''
The commission had studied the feasibility of drafting a primary law or of arranging a primary without legislation .
It examined problems related to voter lists , financing and access to the media .
Given the unfeasibility of a primary , the right 's prospects for success `` depend on the willingness of the candidates to endorse unity and guarantee it publicly , '' the report said .
Interior Minister Charles Pasqua had been struggling in recent weeks to lay the ground work for a primary , but said Thursday the problem now lay with the political parties .
One of Pasqua 's allies , Parliament member Jean-Jacques Guillet , denounced the commission report as `` an assassination '' arranged in advance by those who opposed the idea of a primary .
Balladur , who has yet to officially declare his candidacy , said after learning of the report that it remained essential for the right to find a candidate who could unify all factions of the governing coalition .
The study -- dubbed an `` owner 's manual '' for NATO membership -- will take a year to complete .
It will not name candidates for membership , nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
Instead , it will focus on such questions as whether NATO troops will need to be based in new member states ; how much enlargement will cost ; how to integrate the newcomers army into NATO 's command structure
To counter Russian worries about an eastward expansion of NATO , the allies intend later Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Russia and agree to hold regular talks with Moscow on security matters .
Russian officials have registered apprehension about the movement of NATO 's territory farther east , and alliance leaders have gone out of their way to try to strengthen separate ties with Moscow .
`` Russia is a part of Europe , '' said the NATO source , who insisted on anonymity .
`` You can not have a security system without the participation of Russia . ''
The ministers , he said , emphasized the importance of `` increasing the momentum '' of consultations between NATO and Russia .
The United States had initially proposed a six-month study of enlargement , but the Europeans , mindful of Moscow 's concerns , extended it to 12 months .
`` We should avoid premature enlargement that gives the impression that we seek a redivision of the European continent , '' said French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe , according to a spokesman .
The allies do not intend to identify candidates for membership , nor set a date for admission .
But the NATO source said , `` Central European states would be first . ''
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and Slovakia are considered front-runners .
Despite attempts to keep the focus on new members , the Bosnian crisis will no doubt occupy a large amount of the ministers ' time .
During the talks , Christopher was expected to tell the allies the Clinton administration has swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
It marks a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the European allies , led by Britain and France .
The change in U.S. policy will help heal an unprecedented rift within the alliance over Bosnia .
At a breakfast with British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd , Christopher reviewed the warning U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali delivered Wednesday that unless warring Serbs and Muslims cooperate with the U.N. mission the peacekeepers might be withdrawn .
Hurd said he may go to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
Officials said French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe may join him .
The latest American approach centers on a call for an international peace conference that would let Bosnian Serbs seek changes in the peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
That plan would require them to cut their holdings in Bosnia from 70 percent to 49 percent .
The Clinton administration , officials say , is also leaning toward approval of political ties between Serbs in Bosnia and Serbia proper -- a big step toward their aim of a Greater Serbia .
On Friday , Christopher will meet with here his counterparts from France , Germany , Britain and Russia to discuss new plans to revive their moribund peace plan for Bosnia .
France and Britain have been criticized in the U.S. Congress for refusing to let the United Nations use the Western military alliance 's air power to the full .
In turn , Congress has forced the Clinton administration to seek a lifting of the arms embargo against Bosnia 's Muslim-led government , something the European NATO allies oppose for fear it would escalate the fighting .
Hyatt International Corporation on Thursday signed an agreement with the Greek state to build and operate a casino , a five-star hotel and conference center in Salonica , northern Greece .
The casino , which will be able to seat 2,000 people at a time , is expected to be completed by mid-1996 .
The 150-room hotel and conference center are expected to be completed the following year .
The Chicago-based corporation 's Regency Casinos will operate the casino that will be built near Salonica 's airport .
The hotel and conference hall will be a five-minute drive away , on the grounds of the city 's American Farm School .
The chairman of Hyatt 's board , Jay A. Pritzker , said he expected the total investment to come to about dlrs 120 million or dlrs 125 million .
This includes 7.8 billion drachmas -LRB- dlrs 33 million -RRB- paid up front as a license fee that will come to 1.2 billion drachmas -LRB- dlrs 5 million -RRB- annually .
The state will also receive 30 percent of the casino 's revenues .
The license has a 12-year exclusivity period and is of indefinite duration .
Hyatt is also bidding for a license to operate a casino in Athens , Pritzker told a news conference .
`` We hope to expand and build more of these projects in Greece , '' he said .
The casino and hotel in Salonica will employ 1,000 people , Greece 's tourism minister , Dionysis Livanos , said .
U.S. ambassador Thomas Niles said he was `` delighted '' at the American investment in northern Greece and that he hoped more would follow .
`` This is a very important project for Hyatt and the U.S. economic relationship with Greece and for the region for where the project is going , '' Niles said .
`` The area of northern Greece has an enormous opportunity to become a major transport , telecommunications and economic center of this region , that would include the countries of the southern Balkans , '' he said .
The EU executive Commission said Thursday it will approve plans by France 's Chanel SA for a watch retail network after the fashion and luxury goods maker agreed to change its distribution rules .
In a statement in the EU Official Journal , it said Chanel has agreed , among others , to drop plans to grant retailers `` exclusive '' market rights .
Under EU rules , Chanel 's competitors have a month to comment on the Commission 's decision .
Svetla Dimitrova , the European champion in the 100-meter hurdles , has been suspended by the Bulgarian Athletics Federation .
Federation chairman Plamen Krastev said Thursday that Dimitrova was sanctioned because she had left Bulgaria for Austria without leaving the federation an address where she could be reached .
Austrian track officials said they had seen Dimitrova training in Vienna several weeks ago but had no other details on her whereabouts .
`` We are sending a message to the International Amateur Athletic Federation that Dimitrova is suspended , '' Krastev said .
`` According to IAAF rules , we have to know at any moment the place where our athletes can be reached . ''
IAAF spokesman Christopher Winner said the Bulgarians appeared to be referring to an IAAF `` guideline '' which recommends that a national federation know the whereabouts of an athlete for possible random drug tests .
`` The IAAF is not involved in what appears to be an internal disagreement between the federation and the athlete , '' Winner said .
Krastev said Dimitrova , 24 , is in the process of getting divorced from her trainer , Ilian Pishtikov .
Pishtikov told Bulgarian newspapers that Dimitrova had been enticed to go to Vienna by her Austrian manager , Harald Edletzberger .
Several years ago , Edletzberger invited another Bulgarian top athlete , Lyudmila Ninova , who left Bulgaria and now lives in Austria .
`` This man -LRB- Edletzberger -RRB- is trying to make money from the results of our years-long hard training , '' Pishtikov said .
`` The Bulgarian Athletics Federation has informed the IAAF that it does n't want any more its athletes to be represented by Harald Edletzberger , '' Krastev said .
Dimitrova won seven races on the Mobil Grand Prix circuit this year and finished second in the overall standings behind Jackie Joyner-Kersee of the United States .
A Russian ultimatum demanding an end to Chechnya 's civil war expired early Thursday amid signs that Moscow was preparing to send troops into the breakaway southern republic .
A trickle of heavily loaded cars and trucks left the capital as nervous civilians continued to head for the countryside , fearing an attack by Russian soldiers .
Central Grozny was virtually empty following another nerve-jangling night of intermittent small arms fire from jumpy fighters around the city .
A single military jet roared over the capital as the Russian deadline passed .
Later , heavy machine-gun fire rang out from the city center .
The fighting pits forces loyal to Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , who has declared Chechnya independent from Russia , against rebels who Dudayev says are armed and led by Moscow .
President Boris Yeltsin ordered warring Chechens to lay down their arms and release all prisoners by Thursday morning or face Russian military intervention .
Chechens have defied the ultimatum .
In Freedom Square outside the presidential building , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches while a tank maneuvered into position .
Chechen elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots , danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
Russian media reported troop movements around the borders of Chechnya , in the Caucasus Mountains region of southern Russia .
The Interfax and ITAR-Tass news agencies said Russian army units would support Interior Ministry forces to `` ensure stability in the region , safety of the population and avert the spread of the conflict . ''
The conflict is the latest to underline the tensions among scores of ethnic groups in the former Soviet Union .
The Caucasus region has been especially fractious , with fighting in the Ossetian and Abkhazian regions of Georgia and the Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan .
For Moscow , which governs dozens of republics and regions in the Russian Federation , Chechnya has become a test of whether it is willing to use military might to hold the country together .
No other region has gone as far as Chechnya and declared independence .
Moscow openly supports Dudayev 's opponents politically , but denies offering military assistance .
After Dudayev 's forces captured Russian fighters Saturday , Moscow said mercenaries were fighting on both sides .
In Moscow , Yeltsin spokesman Vyacheslev Kostikov said Moscow had begun `` a series of measures '' to resolve the crisis .
`` All necessary measures are being taken to save the Russian soldiers , '' he said , referring to those captured on Saturday .
He did not elaborate .
Most of those fleeing Grozny went only a few kilometers -LRB- miles -RRB- to stay with relatives in the countryside .
`` Already , the majority of people have left the city , '' said 43-year-old Lyuba Ishkirchira , a Russian woman married to an ethnic Bashkir .
`` I have no relatives to go to , and my father and mother are ill here -- I can not leave them . ''
Grozny 's central bazaar , which once thronged with thousands of people , was nearly empty on Thursday .
A few old women trudged through the mud and wet leaves in search of bread .
Although the Chechens are fighting among themselves , many agreed that they have one thing in common : Distrust of Russia .
`` I do n't like the opposition or Dudayev , but I 'll fight the Russians , '' said one restaurant owner who refused to give his name .
Wrapped in an old leather coat and a thick , gray scarf , a 60-year-old Chechen woman walking among the bazaar 's empty stalls said Russia would have a tough time trying to overrun Chechnya .
`` Whoever fights the Muslims never wins , '' Tamara Ofsayeva said .
Bebeto is laid up with a bad cold and Romario 's hair is falling out .
As Deportivo de La Coruna and Barcelona prepare for a titans ' battle Saturday , their respective Brazilian aces are ailing .
The match is vital for both teams .
Deportivo , with 18 points , lies behind leader Real Madrid on goal difference .
Barcelona , the four-year defending champion , is two points back at No. 4 and still smarting from its first defeat at home in 10 months against Sevilla last week .
That result followed the humiliating defeat by Turkey 's Galatasaray in European Champions League play which left Barcelona 's path to the cup 's quarterfinals in danger .
Both Deportivo and Barcelona place much stock in their respective Brazilian World Cup aces , Bebeto and Romario .
But on Saturday Deportivo at least will be without its top striker who was Wednesday ordered to stay indoors for at least two weeks while antibiotics work on a chest cold .
The news was welcomed by Barcelona goalkeeper Carlos Busquets .
`` Bebeto is a magnificent player and it 's one less problem for us , '' he said .
But while Barcelona 's star Romario is likely to be physically fit for the game , he told a Brazilian daily this week that life at the top is wasting him .
`` It 's now that I 'm feeling the pressure of the responsibility I took on in the U.S. -LRB- World Cup -RRB- , '' Romario told the Journal de Brasil .
`` I promised to win a fourth world title for Brazil and that brought a lot of pressure on me .
I 'm stressed out . ''
`` The worst part is that there 's nothing I can do ... my hair is falling out non-stop , '' he said .
Romario , the league 's top scorer last season with 30 goals , has only managed to score three in 12 rounds so far , nine less than he had at the same point last season .
But under stress or not , Romario like his other teammates still had to endure a training session Wednesday reported to have been the longest and most excruciating since coach Johan Cruyff took over Barcelona .
Cruyff is undoubtedly aware that although it is early days yet a defeat Saturday could allow Real Madrid and Deportivo to steal ahead and seriously impair Barcelona 's chances of winning a fifth title .
Madrid on Saturday travels north to play a Real Sociedad struggling at No. 17 in the 20-team division and still recovering from the sacking of long-time coach Welshman John Toshack last week .
While Madrid 's three defeats so far this season have been in away games , Sociedad has only managed to win one game at home out of six .
One club likely to be hoping Madrid , Deportivo and Barcelona all trip up is No. 3 Zaragoza which lies a point behind the leaders going into its bout Sunday against No. 12 Sporting de Gijon .
Saturday sees two other first division games with Athletic de Bilbao traveling to Atletico de Madrid and Valencia hosting Albacete .
Other 13th-round games Sunday are : Oviedo-Betis ; Valladolid-Celta ; Tenerife-Logrones ; Compostela-Racing de Santander and Sevilla-Espanol .
Russian prisons are inhuman and torturous , with underfed inmates crammed into stinking , standing-room-only cells , a U.N. report said Thursday .
It said conditions in pre-trial remand centers -- where first time offenders accused of petty crimes may wait for five years for a court appearance -- were even worse than labor camps for hardened convicts .
`` The oppressive heat , lack of oxygen , and the odors of sweat , excrement and disease created by gross overcrowding are overpowering , '' said Nigel Rodley , the author of the report and the U.N. 's special investigator on torture .
At the invitation of the Russian government , Rodley spent two weeks in the Moscow and St. Petersburg area in summer .
He visited four remand centers , two police headquarters , one labor camp , one juvenile center and one hospital for seriously ill prisoners .
The Russian government estimates there are 500,000 prisoners in about 528 prisons and penal colonies throughout the country .
Russia has the highest rate of detentions in the world , above the United States .
Rodley , a British human rights expert , said the rocketing crime rate following the end of Communist control had worsened acute overcrowding .
He criticized Russian authorities for trying to respond to public concern about crime by throwing petty offenders into jail .
He recommended that President Boris Yeltsin should issue a presidential decree to release 71,000 non-violent , first-time offenders to try to ease the overcrowding .
`` It 's a radical proposal because it 's a radical problem which needs to be addressed urgently , '' Rodley told journalists .
He said beatings and maltreatment were widespread .
Rodley said even reading accounts of atrocious conditions did not prepare him for the appalling reality .
`` The conditions are cruel , inhuman and degrading ; they are torturous , '' he wrote about cells in Moscow 's notorious Butryskaya prison .
`` There is virtually no daylight .
There is insufficient room for everyone to lie down , sit down or even stand up at the same time . ''
Butryrskaya prison was constructed in 1771 .
There has been very little refurbishment since then .
Built for 3,500 prisoners , it now holds 6,300 .
`` The food , not always available because of the indebtedness of the institutions -- is primitive , of a fat-saturated soupy nature .
It is consumed in the cell and is excreted in the cell , '' the report said .
In another Moscow detention center , Matrosskaya Tishina No. 1 , conditions in quarantine cells for sick prisoners were atrocious .
`` Despite the fact that several of the inmates had open , festering sores , severe fungal infections with decaying flesh , and extensive rashes , they reported that they had not seen a doctor in over a week , '' Rodley wrote .
He said conditions at a high-security labor camp he visited were better than those in the pre-trial remand centers .
He said the main problem seemed to be boredom among inmates because the economic crisis meant factories on the camp were not operational .
He said a labor colony for young criminals he visited was humanely run .
However , he was surprised to find 15 and 16 year-olds there sentenced to several years for stealing a bicycle or computer fraud .
A team from the International Monetary Fund arrived in Cairo on Thursday to evaluate Egypt 's progress in implementing its economic reform program .
Relations between Egypt and the Washington-headquartered organization have been strained over IMF demands that Egypt devalue its currency and lower interest rates to boost economic growth .
The government -- backed by many in the business community -- opposes devaluation , saying it will damage the nation 's already troubled export effort and worsen inflation .
The pound currently is trading at about 3.38 to the dollar , and consumer prices have been rising despite efforts to hold inflation below 10 percent this year .
Sources close to the talks said they expected the IMF team to put the contentious issues aside for the time being and concentrate on structural problems , such as Egypt 's export policies , customs regulations , tax system , and anti-inflation program .
The team , headed by IMF Associate Director Saleh Nasouli , is to stay until Dec. 19 to review the extended credit facility approved in 1991 , IMF officials said .
The disagreement has held up action by the so-called Paris Club of Western donor nations , which has pledged to write off some dlrs 4 billion of Egyptian debt once the nation has fulfilled its promises to the IMF .
The debt write-off had been expected in June 1994 .
The delay is costing Egypt some dlrs 350 million a year in interest payments , analysts say .
Egypt also is at odds with the World Bank over the slow speed of privatizing dozens of government-owned companies .
Some 314 companies have been reorganized under holding companies to prepare them for sale , but only a handful have been sold .
