Volume was 394.6 million shares .
Fed up with bogus bomb threats against schools , Moscow teachers threatened to hold classes on weekends or even holidays to make up for every lesson lost to pranks , a daily newspaper said Thursday .
Seven high schools in the Russian capital had to close Tuesday while police searched for explosive devices allegedly planted on their premises , Moskovsky Komsomolets reported .
No bombs were found .
With bombs exploding in Moscow almost every day , police so far have taken phone calls about bombs at schools seriously .
But their patience is running thin .
Some officers say they waste time searching through school premises since no bomb threat has ever turned out to be real , the newspaper said .
In most cases , students seeking fun or an extra day off from school were behind the threats , police said .
Schools are going to get tougher with practical jokers , Moskovsky Komsomolets said .
Besides moving classes to weekends and holidays , school administrators vowed to expel pupils found to be behind bomb threats .
