Aetna International Inc. 's application to form a joint venture insurance company in China is still pending , but Aetna President Michael A. Stephen was optimistic that his company would enter the Chinese market .
Aetna International , a part of Aetna Life and Casualty of the United States , applied in May to form a Shanghai joint venture insurance company with China Pacific Insurance Co.
If approved , Aetna would become only the third foreign insurer allowed an operating presence in China .
Stephen said Thursday he has not been given any indication of the application 's fate , but added that he was `` basically optimistic '' about his company 's prospects in the world 's most populous nation .
`` We 're continuing to be patient and to build relationships as we position ourselves to be active players when the markets open up , '' he said .
Both Stephen and Douglas Henck , senior vice president for Asia Pacific operations at Aetna International , felt Chinese authorities understood the need to reform and open the country 's financial services sector but still were gathering information before making a decisive move .
`` If China wants to play a full role in the world , it has to reform several of its industries and the financial services industry is one , '' said Stephen .
The People 's Insurance Co. of China now has a 98 percent share of China 's insurance market .
Neither of the Aetna executives saw the opening of financial markets as a threat to the Chinese company .
While it might lose market share to foreign companies or joint ventures , the total market will grow and PICC 's revenues will increase , they said .
In Taiwan , Stephen said , Aetna became the first foreign company to receive an unrestricted license to sell life insurance in 1987 .
Although the major Taiwanese life insurer lost about 5 percentage points of its then 60 percent market share , it benefited along with Aetna from overall market growth , he added .
`` It 's important to remember that Asian insurance markets are n't mature , '' said Stephen .
Unlike the U.S. or some European markets , Asian countries still have plenty of room for expansion , he said .
Another possibility is the privatization of state pension funds , he said .
Although Chinese officials did n't indicate they were contemplating such a move , Stephen said he thought this was an area in which Aetna 's expertise could make a real contribution to China 's welfare .
Australia 's devastating drought will cut economic growth by nearly 1 percent , bump up food prices and more than halve production of winter crops , a top official said Thursday .
Primary Industries Minister Bob Collins also delivered more bad news for farmers , saying there was little chance the drought would break this summer .
The drought will cause national income to fall by dlrs 2.9 billion -LRB- dlrs US 2.2 billion -RRB- this year , equivalent to a 0.7 percent drop in economic growth , now running at more than 6 percent a year , he said .
Winter crop yields are expected to plummet by 54 percent to 13 million tons .
Earlier forecasts had predicted a 40 percent reduction to around 17 million tons .
Wheat production is expected to drop by more than 50 percent to its lowest level since 1972 .
`` These figures provide a stark illustration of the economic impact of this drought and I regret to say it shows no sign of breaking , '' Collins told Parliament .
British officials will meet the IRA 's allies in Sinn Fein next week , the first official face-to-face contact between the two sides since the IRA cease-fire , the government announced Thursday .
The first meeting was proposed for Wednesday in Belfast , but the time and location has not been set , said a spokesman at Prime Minister John Major 's office .
The announcement came three months to the day after the IRA began observing a cease-fire .
That cease-fire has been marred only by the murder of a postal worker in a robbery carried out by IRA members on Nov. 10 .
British officials have said they will be pressing for a surrender of IRA weapons , but Sinn Fein argues that this is impossible before reaching an overall political settlement .
`` How we will take the gun out of Irish politics is by bringing forward agreement on political structures , '' said Sinn Fein 's Northern Ireland chairman , Mitchel McLaughlin .
`` Those who are talking surrender terms are being unrealistic , and I think are playing dangerous games with what is a genuine opportunity for peace in Ireland . ''
But John Taylor , a member of the Ulster Unionist Party , Northern Ireland 's largest party , said : `` No one can enter into meaningful political talks , and carry the threat of renewed violence under the table . ''
Britain will be represented by Quentin Thomas , an official in the Northern Ireland Office .
Sinn Fein said Martin McGuinness , the party 's second-ranking leader , will head its delegation .
Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams will be in Washington next week .
The White House announced Wednesday that Adams would meet with National Security Adviser Anthony Lake , the highest level of contact accorded to Adams in the United States .
Major 's spokesman , who spoke on condition of anonymity , said Britain had not changed its mind about excluding Sinn Fein from an investment conference in Belfast , despite pressure from American politicians to the contrary .
On Wednesday , Adams and John Hume , Northern Ireland 's most respected politician , issued a statement pressing Britain to begin talking with Sinn Fein .
`` There should be no more stalling , '' they said .
A series of meetings and joint statements last year by Adams and Hume , leader of the Catholic-based Social Democratic and Labor Party , helped pave the way for the IRA 's open-ended truce .
Britain has refused to invite Sinn Fein officials to the foreign investment forum in Belfast on Dec. 13-14 .
President Clinton plans to send Commerce Secretary Ron Brown at the head of a U.S. delegation , but a congressmen visiting Ireland says Clinton should rethink that if Britain keeps shunning Sinn Fein .
`` Everyone seems to be acting in good faith except the British , '' U.S. Rep. Peter King -LRB- R-N.Y. -RRB- , said Wednesday in Dublin , the Irish capital .
Former heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield , who hopes to fight again despite being on the medical suspension list because of a heart problem , has fired his manager .
Shelly Finkel , who has been in Holyfield 's camp since 1984 and at the forefront since Holyfield fired business manager Ken Sanders in 1991 , received a termination letter Monday .
Finkel , who still manages a handful of fighters , most notably Pernell Whitaker , said Wednesday he was neither surprised nor bitter about the split , although he said the manner in which the firing was handled was unusual .
`` The letter basically said , ` I wo n't be using your services .
You 've been a great manager and a real good friend , ' and had all these compliments , '' Finkel said .
`` There 's no hard feelings on my part .
I 've seen it coming .
It was n't appropriate -LRB- to continue -RRB- because I 've been against him fighting again .
I 'm sure it caused a gulf between us . ''
Holyfield could not be reached for comment Wednesday and his spokesman , Ron Bell , declined to comment .
Holyfield hopes to be removed from boxing 's medical suspension list and licensed by the Nevada State Athletic Commission after recently passing heart tests at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester , Minn.
Russian prisons are inhuman and torturous , with underfed inmates crammed into stinking , standing-room-only cells , a U.N. report said Thursday .
It said conditions in pre-trial remand centers -- where first time offenders accused of petty crimes may wait for five years for a court appearance -- were even worse than labor camps for hardened convicts .
`` The oppressive heat , lack of oxygen , and the odors of sweat , excrement and disease created by gross overcrowding are overpowering , '' said Nigel Rodley , the author of the report and the U.N. 's special investigator on torture .
At the invitation of the Russian government , Rodley spent two weeks in the Moscow and St. Petersburg area in summer .
He visited four remand centers , two police headquarters , one labor camp , one juvenile center and one hospital for seriously ill prisoners .
The Russian government estimates there are 500,000 prisoners in about 528 prisons and penal colonies throughout the country .
Russia has the highest rate of detentions in the world .
Rodley , a British human rights expert , said the rocketing crime rate following the end of Communist control had worsened acute overcrowding .
He criticized Russian authorities for trying to respond to public concern about crime by throwing petty offenders into jail .
He recommended that President Boris Yeltsin should issue a presidential decree to release 71,000 non-violent , first-time offenders to try to ease the overcrowding .
`` It 's a radical proposal because it 's a radical problem which needs to be addressed urgently , '' Rodley told journalists .
He said beatings and maltreatment were widespread .
Rodley said even reading accounts of atrocious conditions did not prepare him for the appalling reality .
`` The conditions are cruel , inhuman and degrading ; they are torturous , '' he wrote about cells in Moscow 's notorious Butryskaya prison .
`` There is virtually no daylight .
There is insufficient room for everyone to lie down , sit down or even stand up at the same time . ''
Butryrskaya prison was constructed in 1771 .
There has been very little refurbishment since then .
Built for 3,500 prisoners , it now holds 6,300 .
`` The food , not always available because of the indebtedness of the institutions -- is primitive , of a fat-saturated soupy nature .
It is consumed in the cell and is excreted in the cell , '' the report said .
The number of Americans filing the first time for state unemployment benefits dropped last week to the lowest level in two months .
The Labor Department reported Thursday that initial jobless claims totaled a seasonally adjusted 317,000 in the week ended Nov. 26 , the smallest number since Sept. 24 .
Initial claims dropped 12,000 from 329,000 in the previous week , the biggest decrease since July 30 .
That figure was revised upward from the 326,000 initially reported .
The same report showed the four-week moving average of jobless claims declining for the first time in eight weeks .
The average was 326,250 , down 1,250 from the previous week 's revised 327,500 .
The initial report , released last week , put the figure at 326,750 .
The four-week average had not declined since Oct. 1 .
Many analysts consider the four-week average a better indicator of hiring trends than the weekly number because it smooths out weekly fluctuations and is less volatile .
The most reliable indicator , the monthly employment report showing hiring levels for November , is scheduled for release Friday .
Last month , unemployment dipped to a four-year low and hourly wages rose at the fastest pace in 11 years , among the factors that prompted the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates for a sixth time this year .
The October jobless rate was 5.8 percent , down from 5.9 percent a month earlier .
Most economists expect the same number for November .
An increase in the number of initial claims was reported in 48 states and territories in the week ended Nov. 19 .
Four reported decreases , while the number was unchanged in one .
State figures are reported a week behind the national ones .
