The government has protested to the producers of a U.S. television comedy over what it called racist and sexist remarks about Filipino women .
The Department of Foreign Affairs said Thursday it objected to a line in the show `` Frasier '' where a co-star says his wife is getting a face lift for dlrs 25,000 .
The co-star 's father replies : `` For an extra five grand -LRB- dlrs 5,000 -RRB- you can get a whole new wife from the Philippines . ''
`` Our people are not chattel , '' the department quoted Raul Rabe , the Philippines ' ambassador in Washington , as saying in a letter to David Angel , Peter Casey , David Lee and Cris Floyd , the Los Angeles-based executive producers .
He urged them to `` exert all effort to ensure that this particular feature is not inflicted upon your viewers . ''
Portions of the show featuring the controversial line had been shown in promotional previews , the department said .
It aired in the United States on Tuesday .
Rabe said the reference to Filipino women `` is not only unfair to a people who have done so much for the United States as its oldest ally in Asia , it diminishes the significant contributions that the large economically upscale Filipino-American community has made to the very fabric of this -LRB- American -RRB- nation . ''
In a separate protest letter to KNBC-Channel 4 in Los Angeles , the Philippine Consulate there said a Philippine law passed in 1991 bans the mail-order bride business and other similar practices .
It said the episode shows the `` insensitivity and ignorance '' of the writers and `` perpetuates the kind of blindly negative stereotyping of other peoples and cultures reminiscent of a less enlightened period in American television and media . ''
A dispatcher at KNBC before business hours Thursday said no one was available for comment .
NATO foreign ministers on Thursday approved an American proposal to draw up a blueprint setting out conditions for the entry of former Warsaw Pact foes as new members in the coming years .
The ministers endorsed a 12-month study to consider how to expand the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization to include Central and East European democracies .
Issues will include financing , integrating the newcomers ' armies and nuclear issues , officials said .
Anxious to ease Russian fears about the expansion , the foreign ministers emphasized the alliance was not trying to create a hostile bloc .
`` Having just overcome the division of Europe , we have no desire to see the emergence of new lines of partition , '' the ministers said in a draft of their final communique .
The plan to open up to the East was planned as the centerpiece of the two-day meeting .
But the unprecedented strains between the United States and its European allies over the crisis in Bosnia overshadowed the talks .
In an effort to heal the divisions , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher was expected to tell the allies the Clinton administration has swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
That marks a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the Europeans , led by Britain and France .
Seeking to mend fences , Christopher told the allies :
`` Let me stress one important fact : The crisis in Bosnia is about Bosnia and the former Yugoslavia .
It does not diminish NATO 's enduring importance . ''
The deep splits within the alliance were highlighted by a letter from Germany 's ambassador to NATO that accused the United States of sowing mistrust among the allies .
The letter from Ambassador Hermann von Richthofen accused the United States of acting behind the backs of its allies .
`` The alliance is divided and in crisis , '' concluded Richthofen 's cable to his Foreign Ministry .
The letter was leaked to a leading German newspaper , the Suddeutsche Zeitung , which published extracts .
Opening the meeting , Willy Claes , the new NATO secretary-general , appealed for unity .
`` We are now being put to -LRB- the -RRB- test , and I have every confidence that our solidarity will see us through . ''
The foreign ministers are anxious their talks not be entirely hijacked by the Bosnian crisis .
They ordered a study that would set out the terms for the acceptance of East European countries as new members .
It should be ready when the ministers meet in Brussels a year from now .
The United States had initially proposed a six-month study of enlargement , but the Europeans , mindful of Russia 's fears of isolation , extended it to 12 months .
`` We should avoid premature enlargement that gives the impression that we seek a redivision of the European continent , '' said French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe , according to a spokesman .
The study will not name candidates for membership -- although Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and Slovakia are considered front-runners -- nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
`` It is premature to discuss the timeframe for enlargement or which particular countries would be invited to join the alliance , '' the draft communique said .
Instead , the study will focus on such questions as whether NATO troops will need to be based in new member states ; how much enlargement will cost ; how to integrate the newcomers army into NATO 's command structure
To counter Russian worries about NATO 's eastward expansion , the allies intend later Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Moscow and agree to hold regular talks on security .
Despite attempts to keep the focus on new members , the Bosnian crisis was taking a large amount of the ministers ' time .
On Friday , Christopher will meet here with his counterparts from France , Germany , Britain and Russia to discuss new plans to revive their moribund peace plan for Bosnia .
British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said he may go to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , this weekend .
Officials said French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe may join him for talks with the Serbs .
The latest American approach centers on a call for an international peace conference that may allow Bosnian Serbs seek changes in the peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
That plan requires them to cut their holdings in Bosnia from 70 percent to 49 percent .
The Clinton administration , officials say , is also leaning toward approval of political ties between Serbs in Bosnia and Serbia proper -- a big step toward their aim of a Greater Serbia .
France and Britain have been criticized in the U.S. Congress for refusing to let the United Nations use the Western military alliance 's air power to the full .
In turn , Congress has forced the Clinton administration to seek a lifting of the arms embargo against Bosnia 's Muslim-led government , something the European NATO allies oppose for fear it would escalate the fighting .
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations has decided to accept Vietnam as its seventh member , officials at the organization 's Secretariat said Thursday .
The Secretariat 's foreign office in Jakarta , Indonesia , confirmed the decision after the Vietnamese government said it expected to enter ASEAN next year .
Vietnam has long sought membership in anticipation of trade and investment benefits from closer ties to the more developed ASEAN economies .
Earlier Thursday , a Vietnamese Foreign Ministry spokesman , Ngo Van Hoa , told a news conference that ASEAN Secretary-General Ajit Singh announced the decision in a recent interview with a Malaysian newspaper , the Star .
Asked if Vietnam had received any direct notification of the decision from ASEAN , Hoa only smiled and said , `` I am asking you to read between the lines . ''
But he indicated that Vietnam regards the decision as official and final .
Again quoting the Star , he said ASEAN officials made the decision at a meeting in Brunei Nov. 3-5 , with the actual admission to take place next July when ASEAN foreign ministers hold their regular meeting .
Vietnam hopes for economic benefits from membership , but its admission also would dramatize the extent to which former Cold War divisions have melted away in the region .
ASEAN was formed in 1967 at the height of the Cold War as a buffer against the spread of communism in Asia , represented by Vietnam and China .
It has become influential and active only in recent years since shifting its focus more heavily to economic cooperation .
The current members are Brunei , Indonesia , Malaysia , the Philippines , Singapore and Thailand .
Americans ' income surged 1.4 percent in October , the ninth straight increase and the biggest jump in eight months .
The Commerce Department also reported Thursay that spending rose 0.7 percent in October , the strongest showing since it advanced 0.9 percent in August .
Disposable income -- income after taxes -- also climbed 1.4 percent in October .
The overall income gain was the largest since it rose 1.7 percent in February .
Income last fell in January , when it slipped 0.6 percent .
The increases reported Thursday for both income and spending were higher than many analysts predicted .
In September , personal income increased 0.6 percent and spending rose just 0.2 percent .
Consumer spending , which accounts for two-thirds of the nation 's gross domestic product , was up for the sixth straight month and eight of the last nine .
The combination of incomes and spending meant that Americans ' savings rate -- savings as a percentage of disposable income -- climbed to 4.7 percent in October , from 4.1 percent the previous month .
The savings rate was the highest since April 1993 when it was 5 percent .
Flashy dressing is all right in the Senate , but men must wear a jacket and definitely should n't wear women 's clothes .
That was the message delivered Thursday night to Sen. Jim McKiernan , who turned up for a legislative session wearing a woman 's jacket .
During one of many votes on a package of bills relating to the world trade organization , McKiernan , who is noted for his flashy sartorial sense and his colorful ties , entered the chamber without a jacket .
The move sparked a mild and friendly reprimand from the temporary chairman of committees , Sen. Grant Chapman .
McKiernan accepted the rebuke and was wearing a jacket when he returned for the next vote , but he appeared to have it wrong again .
`` While I appreciate Senator McKiernan 's efforts to find a jacket , I would appreciate if he could find a male jacket before the next division , '' Chapman said to cries of `` Hear , hear ! ''
McKiernan protested , and said there was nothing in the Senate rules related to the color or `` gender '' of the jacket a senator may wear .
McKiernan said the first incident was an innocent mistake because the voting bells had caught him too far from his room , giving him little time to return and pick up his jacket .
On the second occassion , Sen. Sue West offered him her jacket .
McKiernan expressed regret about one point -- his dress sense was offended by the combination of the striped gray women 's jacket , red ribbon and his multi-coloured tie .
`` It clashed something dreadful with my tie , '' he said .
Fighting broke out again overnight around a U.N. `` safe area '' in northwest Bosnia , after it became clear that the peace mission by U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali had failed .
Unfazed by the prospect of a complete withdrawal of all peacekeepers , Bosnia 's rebel Serbs refused even to meet with the U.N. chief to discuss a nationwide cease-fire .
Maj. Herve Gourmelon , a U.N. spokesman , said heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire erupted late Wednesday around the town of Bihac , where the Muslim-led government is trying to hold off rebel Serb forces .
Fighting continued early today , along with some shelling .
The Bosnian army commander , Gen. Rasim Delic , pledged that despite recent heavy losses , Bihac would not fall into Serb hands and the government army would win the war .
His comments , published in a Sarajevo newspaper today , underscored the government 's unwillingness to compromise further to reach a cease-fire and a comprehensive peace .
In Brussels , Belgium , Secretary of State Warren Christopher told NATO allies that the Clinton administration now agrees with its European allies that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the war .
Christopher and Douglas Hurd , the British foreign secretary , said they may go to Belgrade , the Yugoslav capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
`` We will redouble our efforts to find a diplomatic solution , '' Christopher said .
At a breakfast with Hurd , Christopher reviewed the warning U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali delivered Wednesday that unless warring Serbs and Muslims cooperate with the U.N. mission , the peacekeepers might be withdrawn .
The threat reflects a growing frustration as the Serbs continue their assaults and the government refuses new concessions .
More than 350 peacekeepers are still being held hostage and the West is divided about how to respond .
Boutros-Ghali said he will not recommend a pullout `` for the time being . ''
But he said `` it will become impossible '' to sustain support for the peacekeepers in the Security Council unless the Serbs and the government agree to talk peace and cooperate with the United Nations .
In New York , French U.N. Ambassador Jean-Bernard Merimee said `` there is no question '' of a withdrawal now , `` but if the situation continues to deteriorate , it will be more difficult to keep the troops there . ''
A withdrawal by peacekeepers would likely lead to more fighting and could be dangerous for the departing troops , as both Bosnian Serbs and government forces rush U.N. camps to seize equipment before it can be destroyed .
It also would cause widespread hardship because the United Nations feeds an estimated 3 million people across the former Yugoslavia .
Most are in Bosnia .
More than 200,000 people are dead or missing in the 2 -LCB- - year conflict launched by Serbs after Bosnia 's Muslim-Croat majority voted to declare independence from Serb-led Yugoslavia .
Serbs have rejected a peace plan that would reduce their war-won land holdings to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
Boutros-Ghali 's visit followed admissions from top U.S. and NATO officials that they ca n't force a solution to the conflict without a huge ground force no one is willing to provide .
As insurance against further NATO bombings , Serbs have taken more than 400 U.N. soldiers hostage .
Forty-five Britons were released Wednesday , but some Canadian , French , Russian and Ukrainian peacekeepers have been held now for a week .
More than 100 Dutch troops have been held hostage since Saturday .
Lowry Nelson Jr. , a former professor of comparative literature at Yale University , died following surgery in Tallinn , where he was doing research .
Nelson , who lived in Bethany , Conn. , died Nov. 12 , the New Haven -LRB- Conn. -RRB- Register reported .
The cause was thromboembolism , according to The New York Times .
Nelson was instrumental in forming the Comparative Literature Department at Yale .
Before retiring in June after 31 years at Yale , he published and edited several books on poetry and literary theory .
He received his doctorate from Yale in 1961 , and taught at Harvard and the University of California at Los Angeles before returning to Yale in 1963 .
Nelson was born in Provo , Utah , on May 21 , 1926 , and received a bachelor 's degree from Harvard in 1947 .
He is survived by two sisters , Ann Nelson of Charlotte , N.C. , and Janet Nelson Friedell of Lexington , Ky.
Services were held in Kentucky and a memorial service is planned at Yale in the spring .
The Times said Nelson was in Estonia doing research on the Russian Symbolist poet Vyacheslav Ivanov .
He specialized in literature from the 13th to the early 20th centuries .
