The latest American approach centers on a call for an international peace conference that may allow Bosnian Serbs seek changes in the peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
That plan requires them to cut their holdings in Bosnia from 70 percent to 49 percent .
The Clinton administration , officials say , is also leaning toward approval of political ties between Serbs in Bosnia and Serbia proper -- a big step toward their aim of a Greater Serbia .
The NATO study would set out the terms for the acceptance of East European countries as new members .
It should be ready when the ministers meet in Brussels a year from now .
The study will not name candidates for membership -- although Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and Slovakia are considered front-runners -- nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
Instead , the study will focus on such questions as whether NATO troops will need to be based in new member states ; how much enlargement will cost ; how to integrate the newcomers army into NATO 's command structure
To counter Russian worries about NATO 's eastward expansion , the allies intend later Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Moscow and agree to hold regular talks on security .
German officials confirm NATO has asked them to contribute jet fighters to U.N. mission in Bosnia .
A Bulgarian diplomat , a stockbroker and two rabbis were among 23 suspects accused of laundering more than dlrs 100 million in drug proceeds .
The defendants were part of a money laundering cell that enabled tens of millions of dollars to flow between major U.S. and European cities , said Carlo A. Boccia of the Drug Enforcement Administration .
During an investigation , authorities seized dlrs 5 million .
They arrested all but four of those named in a complaint that was sealed until Wednesday .
The organization operated in New York , Los Angeles , Houston , Chicago and Miami in the United States as well as in Germany , Switzerland , Italy , Puerto Rico and Colombia , authorities said .
According to court documents , the leaders of the organization in the United States were Richard Spence , a businessman who was formerly a New York City firefighter ; lawyer Harvey Weinig ; and Robert Hirsch , Weinig 's law partner .
Hirsch has pleaded guilty to money laundering and other charges in a plea bargain with prosecutors .
Authorities allege that the three arranged for the pickup of narcotics proceeds from street corners and hotel rooms .
Among those allegedly sent as couriers were police Officer Michael T. Kalanz ; firefighter Charles Bruno ; hospital administrator Gary Salerno ; Los Angeles-based stockbroker Donald J. Hayden ; and rabbis Alexander Schwartz and Menashe Leifer .
Also arrested was Latchezar Christov , an honorary consul general for the Republic of Bulgaria .
Those arrested were charged with conspiracy and money laundering .
Pope John Paul II repeated his desire to visit Israeli during a meeting Thursday with Foreign Minister Shimon Peres , but he again declined to commit himself to a date , Vatican officials said .
The pope and Peres met for 30 minutes , with the Israeli renewing a long-standing invitation for a visit .
Speaking to Israel radio after the meeting , Peres said the pope would visit Israel '' before the end of the century . ''
A Vatican statement said they discussed issues linked to the Middle East peace process , including relations with Palestinians , Lebanon and the '' future '' of Jerusalem .
On Jerusalem , a city holy to Jews , Christians and Muslims , the Vatican has insisted that access to religious sites be assured through international guarantees .
In a television interview broadcast by an Italian religious station earlier this week , Peres re-affirmed the Israeli position that Jerusalem will always be Israel 's capital and that politically the issue was closed .
But Peres said '' if we are talking about religious issues , we are ready to listen . ''
Earlier , Peres presented his book '' The New Middle East , '' which has come out in Italian , to an audience of Italians and Israeli officials .
NATO has asked Germany to contribute fighter planes to the U.N. mission in Bosnia , officials confirmed Thursday .
The move would engage Germany 's military in its first hot war in 49 years .
Chancellor Helmut Kohl was likely to intervene personally in any decision .
The request is highly sensitive because of Germany 's postwar pacifist tradition , and the history of Nazi atrocities in the Balkans , a defense spokesman said .
By the same token , it would be difficult for Germany to turn down the request because of its repeated assertions that it wants to bear its share of international peacekeeping actions .
The fighter planes would be part of the force that has bombed Serb targets to stop attacks on U.N. protected zones or peacekeepers .
The German planes would replace British fighters that apparently will be transferred elsewhere .
A July decision of the German supreme court enabled the military to engage in peacekeeping missions outside NATO .
Kohl has pushed for Germany to take on new responsibilities so it can gain more power in international affairs .
German forces were deployed as supply troops in Somalia last year , but the Bosnia action would be their first deployment in a combat situation .
