Air services are soon to begin between Dubai and the Comoros following the signing Thursday of a memorandum of understanding between the two governments .
The national airline , Emirates , is expected to operate the service .
Unions extracted concessions from Premier Silvio Berlusconi 's government Thursday in exchange for calling off a general strike .
The agreement , reached during all-night talks , was a big step toward gaining support from the leftist opposition in the Senate for approval of the deficit-reducing budget .
`` The pension war is over , '' said Berlusconi told a news conference after emerging from a meeting with his Cabinet and union leaders .
The unions declared themselves satisfied with the settlement and revoked a strike set for Friday which would have been the second general strike in six weeks .
The agreement restores so-called old age pensions giving the green light to people with 35 years of work under their belt to receive full pension benefits .
It also includes measures that will increase social security benefits for large or poor families and provide more assistance to Italy 's less industrialized southern regions .
However , Berlusconi insisted the government had not backed down on its austerity plan and still intended to cut 50 trillion lire -LRB- dlrs 31 billion -RRB- of the country 's dlrs 100 billion budget-deficit as planned .
`` I have always said that not one , not two , not even 10 strikes would have modified the figures -LRB- of the budget cuts -RRB- , '' said Berlusconi .
As part of the agreement the government pledged to turn its attention to a full-scale permanent pension reform that would bring Italy 's generous welfare and pension system in line with other European countries .
The reforms must be approved by June 30 if the accord between the government and unions is respected .
`` More money is taken out of the social security safe than what gets put in ... and it 's not possible to continue like this , '' Berlusconi said .
`` We are talking about a very satisfactory agreement that concludes a complex dispute , '' Giancarlo Fontanelli leader of the UIL union told the ANSA news agency .
The budget is being discussed in the Senate after it was approved by the Chamber of Deputies on Nov. 16 .
The Berlusconi government has a comfortable majority in the chamber but falls just short in the Senate .
In a further challenge to the crumbling U.N. bid to stop fighting in Bosnia , Serb forces on Thursday detained peacekeepers , blocked humanitarian supplies and fired missiles at Sarajevo .
In embattled northwest Bosnia , where Serb forces have nearly surrounded the Muslim enclave of Bihac , machine-gun and small-arms fire raged a day after a failed peace mission by U.N. chief Boutros Boutros-Ghali .
Military intervention by the allies on behalf of the besieged Muslim-led government grew more unlikely .
In Brussels , Belgium , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher told NATO allies the Clinton administration now agrees with European allies that diplomacy is the best way to deal with the war .
U.N. spokesman Alexander Ivanko said in Zagreb , Croatia , that Bosnian Serb units crossed into Croatia and kidnapped seven Ukrainian peacekeepers .
They took the soldiers and a U.N. armored carrier into Bosnian Serb-held territory , he said .
The Ukrainians ' observation point is now occupied by the Serbs , Ivanko said , and the United Nations has not been able to make contact with its troops .
More than 400 other U.N. soldiers are detained by the Serbs as insurance against further NATO airstrikes following three allied bombing raids on Serb targets last week .
In Sarajevo , U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Serbs ignored 21 requests to allow food and fuel supply convoys to pass through Serb-held territory .
He said U.N. supplies were running low in government-held eastern Bosnian enclaves and in Bihac .
Humanitarian convoys were also blocked .
In downtown Sarajevo , two buildings of the Interior Ministry were hit by anti-tank missiles .
Four people were wounded .
Sarajevo 's airport remained closed because Serbs denied flight clearance , ruling out any relief flights to the besieged Bosnian capital .
Neither side seemed ready for peace .
The Bosnian government rejected a cease-fire plan proposed by Boutros-Ghali during a brief visit on Wednesday , and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic refused even to meet with the U.N. chief .
The intransigence on both sides led Boutros-Ghali to suggest for the first time that the U.N. peacekeeping mission might have to end .
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic told Boutros-Ghali that his government would negotiate only after Serbs accepted a peace plan that they repeatedly have rejected .
He reiterated his government 's offer of a three-month cease-fire , but Serbs want something more permanent .
Comments by the Bosnian army commander , Gen. Rasim Delic to the Sarajevo daily Oslobodjenje underscored the government 's unwillingness to compromise further .
He said Bihac would not fall , and that the Bosnian army eventually would win the war .
Bosnian Serbs snubbed Boutros-Ghali altogether .
Radovan would not come to the Sarajevo airport to meet him , and Boutros-Ghali refused to enter Serb-held territory for the meeting .
But the U.N. chief executive will be in Geneva between Friday and Sunday to `` continue his intensive diplomatic efforts for a peaceful solution , especially for a cease-fire '' in Bosnia , his spokeswoman Therese Gastaut said .
Maj. Herve Gourmelon , a U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , said heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire broke out around Bihac late Wednesday and in the predawn hours Thursday .
Ivanko said later that Bosnian Serb forces kept the heat on the government 's hard-pressed 5th Corps , with significant fighting reported to the southwest and south of the Bihac pocket .
But there was no immediate information on any changes in the frontlines .
Serbs are holding 30-40 percent of the U.N.-declared `` safe area '' consisting of Bihac town and its environs .
One civilian was killed near the Bihac stadium by small-arms fire , while a number of shells exploded near the Bihac hospital , badly injuring one person , Ivanko said .
In Brussels , Christopher and Douglas Hurd , the British foreign secretary , said they may go to Belgrade , the Yugoslav capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
`` We will redouble our efforts to find a diplomatic solution , '' Christopher said .
Some senior Western officials are proposing that the Bosnian Serbs be allowed links to Serb-led Yugoslavia , which they long have desired .
That would be a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal , a Greater Serbia .
At a breakfast with Hurd , Christopher reviewed the Boutros-Ghali 's warning that that unless warring Serbs and Muslims cooperate with the U.N. mission , the peacekeepers might be withdrawn .
The threat reflects a growing frustration as the Serbs continue their assaults and the government refuses new concessions .
Bosnian Serbs have rejected a peace plan that would reduce their holdings in Bosnia to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
More than 200,000 are dead or missing in the 31-month conflict begun by Serbs who rebelled when Muslims and Croats voted for independence from Serb-led Yugoslavia .
Under a furious lobbying barrage from the Clinton administration and a small army of corporate executives , the Senate stood on the verge Thursday of ratifying a sweeping expansion of global free trade .
The climatic vote will not occur until the end of a second full day of debate , but supporters were claiming they now had an ample number of votes for the agreement itself and , more importantly , a small cushion for the three-fifths majority they need on a budget waiver .
`` By the time the vote is actually taken tonight , we expect GATT will pass , '' said presidential press secretary Dee Dee Myers .
While administration officials and Senate supporters said their vote counts showed victory in their grasp , they did not let up in their lobbying efforts .
President Clinton met at the White House with a group of mostly undecided senators in an attempt to build the victory margin .
Opponents , while conceding that the momentum was not going their way , did not let up in their efforts , either .
A group of two-dozen protesters , one dressed as a lame-duck , chanted outside the White House as senators arrived for breakfast with Clinton .
Sen. Fritz Hollings of South Carolina said that the new trade agreement was a bad deal that , by lowering trade barriers , would subject American workers to even more unfair competition from low-wage countries , further weakening the country 's economic standing .
`` The reality is that we are in decline .
Everybody knows that , '' said Hollings , whose home-state textile industry will be one of the biggest losers in the deal .
`` Wake up , Washington . ''
However , GATT supporters said that the Senate 's choice on the last day of the 103rd Congress was between continuing to hold a position of economic leadership in the global economy or retreating behind protectionist barriers .
The House endorsed the accord , negotiated under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade , by a 288-146 vote on Tuesday .
Thirty-three other countries already have ratified the 124-nation accord and supporters said other countries are poised to act before Jan. 1 if the Senate follows the House .
According to an Associated Press survey , GATT proponents appeared on the verge of victory , when counting those who were leaning in favor but not firmly committed .
The AP head count had 60 senators for or leaning for waiving budget rules , 26 against or leaning against and 14 undeclared .
Opponents ' only hope was to change enough senators ' minds to muster 41 votes in favor of the procedural hurdle imposed by Sen. Robert Byrd .
Under Senate rules , the implementing bill must offset all of the projected dlrs 43 billion in lost tariff revenues over the first decade of the accord .
To make up for the lost tariffs , the administration is cutting farm subsidies and raising revenue with a number of measures , including changing the minimum rate on savings bonds and auctioning licenses for a new generation of wireless broadcast services .
Byrd said the bill falls dlrs 14.5 billion short and some senators , while declaring themselves in favor of free trade , said they would not vote to bust the budget .
Byrd and others also complain that a new Geneva-based World Trade Organization , created to referee trade disputes , will inevitably infringe on U.S. sovereignty .
The administration is predicting 500,000 new American jobs as a result of increased U.S. export sales under GATT .
In addition to bringing foreign tariffs closer to U.S. levels , it reduces barriers to trade in agricultural goods and services and protects U.S. intellectual property , such as computer programs , from being pirated .
Opponents charge the trade agreement would simply make it easier for big companies to move more jobs to low-wage countries , including Third World nations where child labor is prevalent .
ISLAMABAD , Pakistan -LRB- AP -RRB- - The main opposition party on Thursday accused Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto 's government of paying bribes to win the support of key politicians .
The opposition leader , Nawaz Sharif , and Ms. Bhutto have been making charges and counter-charges of corruption for months , and the attacks have become increasingly personal .
Both have denied allegations of wrongdoing and none of the charges has been proven in court .
Sharif told a news conference that Ms. Bhutto , her husband Asif Zardari , and President Farooq Leghari all took part in a scheme that set aside 260 million rupees -LRB- dlrs 8.5 million -RRB- of government money for personal use and for paying bribes .
`` The trail of corruption leads to the very top , including Farooq Leghari , Benazir Bhutto and Asif Zardari , '' Sharif said .
Sharif claimed a large chunk of the money was used to buy the support of independent legislators in the Northwest Frontier Provincial Assembly .
Sharif 's conservative Pakistan Muslim League headed a coalition that controlled the province until a number of independents defected earlier this year to support Ms. Bhutto 's liberal Pakistan People 's Party .
Ms. Bhutto 's coalition now controls the province , and Sharif said her party paid bribes to get the independents to switch sides .
Ms. Bhutto is on a trip to London and was not immediately available for comment .
She has said repeatedly that her party is not guilty of corruption and has put a stop to abuses initiated by Sharif when he was prime minister from 1990-93 .
Even Pakistani politicians acknowledge that the country 's political system is riddled with graft , though they inevitably accuse their opponents of the worst offenses .
Ms. Bhutto 's government arrested Sharif 's father , Mohammed Sharif , last month on charges of fraud and tax evasion .
Ms. Bhutto also said that the Sharif business empire , one of the largest in Pakistan , was built through extensive fraud .
Sharif 's accusations Thursday were seen largely as a response to Ms. Bhutto 's charges against him and his family .
