In Sarajevo , U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Serbs ignored 21 requests to allow food and fuel supply convoys to pass through Serb-held territory .
He said U.N. supplies were running low in government-held eastern Bosnian enclaves and in Bihac .
Humanitarian convoys were also blocked .
In downtown Sarajevo , two buildings of the Interior Ministry were hit by anti-tank missiles .
Four people were wounded .
Sarajevo 's airport remained closed because Serbs denied flight clearance , ruling out any relief flights to the besieged Bosnian capital .
Neither side seemed ready for peace .
The Bosnian government rejected a cease-fire plan proposed by Boutros-Ghali during a brief visit on Wednesday , and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic refused even to meet with the U.N. chief .
The intransigence on both sides led Boutros-Ghali to suggest for the first time that the U.N. peacekeeping mission might have to end .
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic told Boutros-Ghali that his government would negotiate only after Serbs accepted a peace plan that they repeatedly have rejected .
He reiterated his government 's offer of a three-month cease-fire , but Serbs want something more permanent .
Comments by the Bosnian army commander , Gen. Rasim Delic to the Sarajevo daily Oslobodjenje underscored the government 's unwillingness to compromise further .
He said Bihac would not fall , and that the Bosnian army eventually would win the war .
Bosnian Serbs snubbed Boutros-Ghali altogether .
Radovan would not come to the Sarajevo airport to meet him , and Boutros-Ghali refused to enter Serb-held territory for the meeting .
But the U.N. chief executive will be in Geneva between Friday and Sunday to `` continue his intensive diplomatic efforts for a peaceful solution , especially for a cease-fire '' in Bosnia , his spokeswoman Therese Gastaut said .
Maj. Herve Gourmelon , a U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , said heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire broke out around Bihac late Wednesday and in the predawn hours Thursday .
Ivanko said later that Bosnian Serb forces kept the heat on the government 's hard-pressed 5th Corps , with significant fighting reported to the southwest and south of the Bihac pocket .
But there was no immediate information on any changes in the frontlines .
Serbs are holding 30-40 percent of the U.N.-declared `` safe area '' consisting of Bihac town and its environs .
One civilian was killed near the Bihac stadium by small-arms fire , while a number of shells exploded near the Bihac hospital , badly injuring one person , Ivanko said .
In Brussels , Christopher and Douglas Hurd , the British foreign secretary , said they may go to Belgrade , the Yugoslav capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
`` We will redouble our efforts to find a diplomatic solution , '' Christopher said .
Some senior Western officials are proposing that the Bosnian Serbs be allowed links to Serb-led Yugoslavia , which they long have desired .
That would be a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal , a Greater Serbia .
At a breakfast with Hurd , Christopher reviewed the Boutros-Ghali 's warning that that unless warring Serbs and Muslims cooperate with the U.N. mission , the peacekeepers might be withdrawn .
The threat reflects a growing frustration as the Serbs continue their assaults and the government refuses new concessions .
Bosnian Serbs have rejected a peace plan that would reduce their holdings in Bosnia to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
More than 200,000 are dead or missing in the 31-month conflict begun by Serbs who rebelled when Muslims and Croats voted for independence from Serb-led Yugoslavia .
American manufacturing surged in November to its strongest level in 10 years , said a widely followed survey of manufacturers released Thursday .
The National Association of Purchasing Managers said its index of manufacturing growth rose to 61.2 percent in November from 59.7 percent in the previous month .
It is the fifteenth consecutive month of growth and the highest reading of the index since February 1984 .
A reading above 50 percent indicates the manufacturing economy is expanding , while a reading below 50 percent indicates a decline .
Factory production advanced to its highest level since December 1983 , indicating that factories are buzzing to keep up with demand .
The production index rose to 66.7 percent from 64.2 percent in October .
The NAPM report 's prices-paid index dipped in November to 77.9 percent from 79.9 percent in October , indicating that manuacturers saw fewer price increases for the raw materials they need .
But the decline was due to seasonal factors , the NAPM said .
The price index was at its second highest level in six years .
The highest level was in October .
The purchasing managers assocation , based in Tempe , Ariz. , surveys managers at more than 300 industrial firms nationwide .
The data , which represents the latest evidence on how the economy is performing , is widely followed by economists and the financial markets .
U.S. construction spending rose 0.9 percent in October , the second straight gain , but the advance was limited to non-residential and government spending .
Residential spending , nearly half of construction outlays , fell .
The Commerce Department said Thursday that spending on residential , non-residential and government projects totaled dlrs 518.1 billion at a seasonally adjusted annual rate , up from a revised dlrs 513.4 billion in September .
The initial September estimate was dlrs 515.1 billion .
Spending had slipped 0.3 percent in August .
But in October , it still was 8.4 percent higher than a year earlier .
Residential spending , 45.4 percent of construction outlays , dropped 1.3 percent to a dlrs 235.2 billion rate , lowest since dlrs 232.3 billion last February .
This sector has been curbed by six interest-rate increases engineered by the Federal Reserve this year to slow the economy and contain inflation .
Spending on single-family homes slipped 0.8 percent , the fifth consecutive decline as rising mortgage rates continued to dampen consumer demand .
Thirty-year mortgages averaged 8.93 percent in October , up from 8.68 percent in September and 6.74 percent a year earlier .
They averaged 9.25 percent last week , highest since 9.27 percent in August 1991 , according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
The often-volatile multi-family spending plunged 12.2 percent , nearly wiping out a 13.9 percent surge a month earlier .
Non-residential outlays rose 0.9 percent , to a dlrs 101.7 billion rate .
The increase was led by a 0.9 percent advance in spending on industrial buildings , a 0.6 percent gain in `` other commercial '' that includes shopping centers and a 5.7 percent boost in hotel and motel outlays .
Government spending increased for the sixth straight month , rising 4.2 percent to a dlrs 137.6 billion rate .
Outlays for public housing and redevelopment were up 14.6 percent ; schools , 8.7 percent .
City Fathers have decided to spice up this town 's night life by letting bars stay open as late as 4 a.m.
`` We have to compete with cities like Berlin where cafes can stay open until whenever .
They are big competition , '' Joop Brouwer of the city 's restaurant and cafe owners ' interest group , said Thursday .
`` We want to have more offerings for our tourists . ''
Council members voted Wednesday to permit cafes and bars to push back closing times by an hour , so that the latest they can stay open is 4 a.m. on weekends and 3 a.m. during the week .
`` Lots of tourists come to Amsterdam and this will allow them more possibilities when going out in the evenings , '' said city council spokesman Martin Lekkerkerker .
The new regulations , effective Jan. 1 , were also sought by locals tired of their neighborhood bars closing down just when they wanted another beer .
`` Most young people do n't go until after midnight these days , '' said Brouwer .
`` Cafes and bars are empty sometimes during the early evening hours and by the time customers come in later , owners have to close . ''
There are about 2,850 cafes in the city , said Lekkerkerker .
Bosnian Serbs crossed into Croatia and kidnapped U.N. peacekeepers today , in a further challenge to the United Nations ' crumbling efforts to keep control .
A day after U.N. chief Boutros Boutros-Ghali 's failed peace mission , the Serbs also repeatedly ignored a U.N. request to allow convoys with food and fuel to pass through Serb-held territory , the United Nations said .
Serbs also fired missiles at Sarajevo and traded heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire with government troops around embattled Bihac , the U.N. declared `` safe area '' in northwest Bosnia .
The seven Ukrainian peacekeepers kidnapped in Croatia , along with a U.N. armored carrier , were taken to Serb-held territory , U.N. spokesman Alexander Ivanko said in Zagreb , Croatia .
The Ukrainians ' observation point is now occupied by Serbs , Ivanko said , and the United Nations has been unable to contact its troops .
More than 400 other U.N. soldiers are detained by the Serbs .
In Sarajevo , U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Serbs failed to respond to 21 requests to allow the passage of its convoys .
He said food and fuel supplies for the United Nations were running low in government-held eastern Bosnian enclaves and in Bihac .
Sarajevo 's airport remained closed because Serbs denied flight clearance , ruling out any relief flights to the besieged Bosnian capital .
In downtown Sarajevo , two Interior Ministry buildings were hit by anti-tank missiles .
Four people were wounded .
In the Bihac area , Bosnian Serb forces kept the heat on the government 's hard-pressed 5th Corps , with significant fighting reported to the southwest and south of the Bihac pocket , Ivanko said .
But there was no immediate information on any changes in the front lines .
Serbs are holding 30 percent to 40 percent of the so-called safe area .
The Bosnian army commander , Gen. Rasim Delic , pledged that despite recent losses , Bihac would not fall into Serb hands and the government would win the war .
His comments , published in a Sarajevo newspaper today , underscored the government 's unwillingness to compromise further to reach a cease-fire and a comprehensive peace .
Boutros-Ghali has warned that the U.N. may have to withdraw its peacekeepers if fighting continues , but the Serbs -- who refused to even meet with the secretary-general Wednesday -- seem unfazed by that prospect .
A withdrawal would likely lead to more fighting and could be dangerous for the departing troops , as both Bosnian Serbs and government forces rush U.N. camps to seize equipment before it can be destroyed .
It also would cause widespread hardship because the United Nations feeds an estimated 3 million people across the former Yugoslavia .
Most are in Bosnia .
In Brussels , Belgium , Secretary of State Warren Christopher told NATO allies today that the Clinton administration now agrees with its European allies that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the war .
Christopher and Douglas Hurd , the British foreign secretary , said they may go to Belgrade , the Yugoslav capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
`` We will redouble our efforts to find a diplomatic solution , '' Christopher said .
Russia 's foreign minister , Andrei Kozyrev , said in Paris today that diplomatic alternatives remained to be explored .
`` We see some elements which could be promoted , tendencies which are encouraging , '' Kozyrev told a news conference .
But NATO continues to prepare for the possibility of more airstrikes against the Serbs .
Today it asked Germany to contribute fighter planes .
The move would engage Germany 's military in its first hot war in 49 years .
More than 200,000 people are dead or missing in the 2 -LCB- - year Bosnian conflict launched by Serbs after Bosnia 's Muslim-Croat majority voted to declare independence from Serb-led Yugoslavia .
Serbs have rejected a peace plan that would reduce their war-won land holdings to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
In a sweeping cost-cutting effort , Chemical Banking Corp. said Thursday that it will eliminate 3,700 positions , sell off most of its New Jersey operations and put nearly dlrs 1 billion in bad realty loans on the block .
The actions will cost the nation 's fourth largest banking company approximately dlrs 410 million before taxes in the fourth quarter ending Dec. 30 .
That includes dlrs 260 million for severance and eliminating certain facilities and dlrs 150 million for the cost of selling bad realty loans .
Chemical said the moves , which were expected , will reduce expenses by dlrs 440 million , with dlrs 210 million of the savings realized this year and dlrs 230 million recorded next year .
The cost-cutting program will allow Chemical to get out of businesses that do n't generate enough revenues and concentrate investments on areas that yield bigger profits .
To this end , Chemical said it will spend dlrs 180 million over the next two years on `` high growth businesses , '' including corporate and investment banking and national consumer services such as mortgage lending and credit cards .
The workforce reductions account for 9 percent of the bank 's 42,500 employees worldwide and will be achieved through attrition and layoffs .
Around half of the planned job cuts , to be carried out over the next two years , will occur in Chemical 's New York headquarters .
The other half will come from operations in Texas , where Chemical owns a bank , and from other locations around the world .
The reductions do not include employees who work for Chemical Bank New Jersey , based in East Brunswick , according to spokesman Ken Herz .
The bank will sell 60 percent of the operation , retaining branches located in the northeast quadrant of the state nearest to New York City .
Chemical Bank New Jersey has 140 branches and employs over 2,000 people .
Herz declined to comment about whether the bank is in talks with potential buyers for the operation .
Chemical also wants to sell its 40 percent stake in the CIT Group Holdings Inc. , a New Jersey-based lending company .
Dai-ichi Kangyo Bank of Japan owns the other 60 percent of CIT .
Chemical has been struggling to reduce its expense base ever since it merged with Manufacturers Hanover Corp. in 1992 .
The bank eliminated 6,200 jobs after the merger and closed more than 80 overlapping branches .
In January , the bank announced that it would close another 50 branches because many customers are banking by telephone , computer or at automated teller machines , rather than at branches .
Three Italians working for a wood company have been kidnapped by separatist guerrillas in the northern Angolan enclave of Cabinda , an army spokesman said Thursday .
According to Col. Manuel Paiva , the three employees of the Trivestral timber processing company were seized Tuesday by a group of soldiers about 40 kilometers -LRB- 24 miles -RRB- from the capital , Cabinda , on the road to the town of Tandu Zinze .
Paiva said the fighters belonged to FLEC-Renovada -- one of the four factions of the Cabinda Enclave Liberation Front , which wants independence for the tiny , oil-rich province 380 kilometers -LRB- 235 miles -RRB- north of Luanda , separated from Angola proper by Zaire .
He did not release the trio 's names but said the army 's 15,000-strong force in the enclave were trying to locate them .
He said he assumed they were still alive .
Trivestral is a company which fells and processes tropical wood from Cabinda 's jungles .
Paiva said FLEC-Renovada , which recently has been fighting alongside the larger National Union for the Total Independence of Angola , or UNITA , counted between 150 and 200 men in the province .
Angola 's war erupted on the eve of independence from Portugal in 1975 .
Fighting , mainly between the government and UNITA , has killed a half-million Angolans and left millions more threatened by starvation and disease .
UNITA and FLEC have both taken foreign hostages in the past .
Last month , a UNITA ambush killed two Portuguese working in the northern provinces for Angolan state companies .
A Jerusalem court on Thursday barred eight Jewish extremists from entering the Temple Mount after they illegally prayed at the holy site earlier this week and were kicked out by angry Muslim guards .
The eight may not visit the Temple Mount during Jewish holidays for the next six months , ruled Magistrate 's Court Judge Miriam Mizrahi .
The Temple Mount is among the flashpoints of the Arab-Israeli conflict .
The raised platform , once site of the Jewish Temple that was destroyed in A.D. 70 , today houses Al Aqsa Mosque , the third holiest shrine of Islam .
Jewish extremists demand that Israel expel the Muslims from the Temple Mount and rebuild the temple there .
Generally , Jews can visit the Temple Mount , but can not pray there in groups .
On Tuesday , Jewish extremists from the group `` Hai Vekayam '' -LRB- Alive and Well -RRB- held a Jewish prayer session on the Temple Mount .
They were grabbed by Muslim guards and worshipers and kicked out amid curses .
The leader of the group , Yehuda Etzion , said Thursday that Jews must demonstrate their presence on the Temple Mount .
`` The right of Jews to pray on the Temple Mount is interpreted by us as an obligation and not just a right , '' Etzion told Israel radio .
Etzion was a leader of an underground ring that waged a four-year campaign of terror against Palestinians in the 1980s , including car bombings that maimed two West Bank mayors .
He served four years in prison for conspiracy in an aborted plot to blow up the Dome of the Rock Mosque , which is also on the Temple Mount .
