NATO foreign ministers on Thursday agreed to try to restart negotiations to end the war in Bosnia .
They also approved a proposal to study how to expand the alliance to include former Warsaw Pact foes .
The plan to open up to the East was to be the centerpiece of the two-day meeting .
But unprecedented strains between the United States and its European allies over the crisis in Bosnia overshadowed the talks .
After a turnaround in U.S. policy , NATO ministers also agreed to relaunch diplomatic efforts to end the Bosnian war -- steering away from Washington 's previous calls to step up air strikes on the Serbs and end the ban on arms supplies to the Muslim-led government in Bosnia .
In an effort to heal the divisions , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
`` An agreement has been reached on the idea of relaunching the negotiations , '' French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe told reporters .
The latest American approach centers on a call for an international peace conference that may allow Bosnian Serbs seek changes in the peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
That plan requires them to cut their holdings in Bosnia from 70 percent to 49 percent .
The Clinton administration , officials say , is also leaning toward approval of political ties between Serbs in Bosnia and Serbia proper -- a big step toward their aim of a Greater Serbia .
Juppe said he hoped a meeting Friday with Christopher and the foreign ministers of Germany , Britain and Russia would launch `` a new initiative '' to end the fighting .
Juppe added he will travel to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , on Sunday with British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd for talks with President Slobodan Milosevic .
However , in an apparent attempt to beef up its air power over Bosnia , NATO has asked Germany to add its warplanes to the allied forces on hand in case air strikes are called against the Serbs .
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said his government was considering the request .
The ministers endorsed a 12-month study to consider how to expand the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization to include East European democracies .
Issues will include financing , integrating the newcomers ' armies and nuclear issues , officials said .
Anxious to ease Russian fears about the expansion , the foreign ministers emphasized the alliance was not trying to create a hostile bloc .
`` Having just overcome the division of Europe , we have no desire to see the emergence of new lines of partition , '' the ministers said in their final communique .
The study will not name candidates for membership -- although Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and Slovakia are considered front-runners -- nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
Instead , the study will focus on such questions as whether NATO troops will need to be based in new member states ; how much enlargement will cost ; how to integrate the newcomers army into NATO 's command structure
To counter Russian worries about NATO 's eastward expansion , the allies intend on Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Moscow and agree to hold regular talks on security .
They 're magazine cover boys , the hottest team -- and the hottest ticket -- around .
They 're collecting nicknames , national attention and notoriety , just like the Pittsburgh Steelers of the '70s .
Suddenly , the Steelers are chic again , the team to beat in the American conference of the U.S. National Football League , the favorites to be the NFC 's 11th consecutive victim in the Super Bowl .
Tired of living forever in the 1970s , they 're forging a new identity in the '90s and , even , catchy new nicknames .
The `` Steel Curtain '' defense is retired , along with the four U.S. Pro Football Hall of Famers who made it special .
Now , Pittsburgh is rallying around , and America is learning all about , a new , dominating , colorful , full-of-characters Steelers ' defense -- the Steel Trap .
Jack Lambert is out , Greg Lloyd is in .
Jack Ham finally can enjoy his retirement ; the Steelers have another sacking , attacking , havoc-wrecking linebacker , Kevin Greene .
The widely circulated weekly magazine Sports Illustrated is in on the secret , slapping Steelers defensive lineman Brentson Buckner across this week 's cover as he mauls a Los Angeles Raiders ' ballcarrier .
`` Wait until my dad goes to buy it and sees his son 's picture on the cover , '' Buckner said .
`` Is he going to be surprised . ''
With four consecutive victories , seven in their last eight , the AFC 's best record and its best defense , the Steelers -LRB- 9-3 -RRB- are proving just as surprising .
Driven and dominant again , they finally may be capable of returning to ... dare the words be said ?
As Pittsburgh resident Fred Rogers might say , `` Can you say Super Bowl ? ''
`` There 's a lot of similarities here to what we had going in San Francisco , '' said cornerback Tim McKyer , who played in two Super Bowls with the 49ers .
`` We 're a closeknit team , everybody gets along ... and we feel like we 're going to win in the fourth quarter . ''
Or , as McKyer said when he signed with the Steelers last summer : `` I 'm here to win a championship . ''
Apparently , so are the Steelers who walked around their locker room Wednesday with black-and-gold T-shirts proclaiming `` January 29 , 1995 '' on the front and `` We Believe '' on the back .
The significance of Jan. 29 , 1995 ?
Super Bowl XXIX will be played that day in Miami .
`` But I do n't think these guys are worried about championships , '' Lloyd said .
`` We know what 's ahead of us ... and it wo n't come unless we take it game-to-game , week-to-week .
We all realize that if you play well , -LRB- championships -RRB- come . ''
NATO on Thursday asked Germany to send fighter planes to patrol the skies over Bosnia in a mission that would put the German military into its first hot war since World War II .
It will be a thorny decision for Chancellor Helmut Kohl and his aides , who have shied from involvement in Bosnia-Herzegovina because of the history of Nazi atrocities in former Yugoslavia , and anti-German sentiment among many Serbs .
It will also be a difficult request for Germany to turn down because of Kohl 's repeated assertions that his nation , seeking more international influence , must bear its share of peacekeeping responsibilities .
Lt. Col. Joe Cato , spokesman for NATO 's European military headquarters in Casteau , Belgium , said that the Supreme Allied Commander in Europe `` has requested -LRB- that -RRB- the German armed forces provide some combat aircraft to support NATO air operations over parts of former Yugoslavia . ''
NATO requested German Tornado planes equipped with electronic gear that can locate and identify radar sites , and rockets designed to destroy such sites , a German defense official said , speaking on background .
The Tornado planes could help prevent Serb attacks on NATO planes patrolling Bosnia to enforce the U.N. humanitarian mission , and also could protect supply flights to Sarajevo , the official said .
He and other officials could not confirm a report in the weekly Rheinische Merkur newspaper that the German planes would replace fighters that Britain planned to withdraw .
A July decision of the German constitutional court enabled the government to engage in peacekeeping missions outside the NATO area for the first time .
German supply troops were involved in missions in Somalia and Rwanda .
`` Whether we , after the constitutional court ruling , should really choose former Yugoslavia as the place to step up our engagement , is something I believe we should consider very carefully , '' Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said in Brussels , Belgium .
Kohl has said Germany can not send peacekeepers to former Yugoslavia because of the bitter memories over the hundreds of thousands of Serbs , Jews and others murdered by the German army and SS officers .
Earlier this week , Kohl described the Serb attacks and the NATO allies ' inability to stop them as a `` disgrace for civilized Europe . ''
Kohl added that he morally was in favor of lifting the embargo on arms shipments to the Muslim-led Bosnian government , but felt he had to support the embargo out of solidarity with European colleagues who have troops on the ground .
France , Britain and other governments oppose lifting the embargo because they fear it will expand the fighting and could bring Bosnian Serb reprisals against their soldiers .
