President Clinton will name retiring Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell to be a special adviser for economic initiatives in Ireland , White House officials said Thursday .
The appointment will be part-time , and not tied directly to peace talks between Britain and Ireland , officials said .
British Ambassador Robin Renwick , after a visit to the White House Thursday , said Mitchell 's appointment will `` help with economic involvement and the future of Northern Ireland and to help support the peace process . ''
Renwick lauded the appointment , saying the U.S. effort to bring investment and jobs to Northern Ireland `` is absolutely vital to the future of Northern Ireland . ''
White House officials , speaking on condition of anonymity , stressed that Mitchell 's appointment does not mean the United States is getting directly involved in the peace process .
They said he will try to improve the country 's economic condition , a development that would aid the peace effort .
The appointment likely will not exclude Mitchell from other work after leaving office .
He has reportedly been considered for the post of U.S. baseball commissioner .
Mitchell , who has been involved in Irish issues for years , did not run for re-election .
His efforts to pass President Clinton 's health care legislation this year failed .
Mitchell will be a special adviser to the president and the secretary of state .
