In addition to being majority leader , Mitchell has served on the Senate Finance Committee and its subcommittee on international trade .
An elderly Briton who collapsed while being evacuated from the burning Achille Lauro was one of the two people killed on the cruise ship , officials said Friday .
The Foreign Office identified the dead Briton as Arthur Morris , 68 , who -- like many of the 581 passengers -- lived in South Africa .
A German passenger also died after fire broke out Wednesday in the cruise ship .
One British newspaper report said Morris hit his head while trying to get to a lifeboat .
Other reports said he collapsed from stress .
One of the first British survivors to reach a rescue ship described how passengers , many still in evening dress , waited on the deck for hours as the fire billowed out of control , children sobbing and some passengers panicking .
Tony Webb , 44 , who won the cruise as a competition prize , said his 2-year-old son Michael clung to him terrified as they looked back from a lifeboat `` at the Achille Lauro and the sight was amazing . ''
`` The flames were leaping up and there was smoke all around , '' Webb , who now lives in Cape Town , said in an interview by radio with London 's Daily Telegraph .
`` The fire was so big you had to fight through smoke which poured down towards the cabins . ''
Webb added , `` As we waited the smoke became thicker and thicker .
The crew were wonderful .
They tried to keep us all calm .
At about 8 a.m. the captain said the fire was too strong and we would have to abandon the ship . ''
Some 75 British passengers were taken on board a Greek cargo ship , Chios , on Thursday , the British news agency Press Association reported .
Petankis Pringis , radio officer on the Chios , said most were in good spirits and would be telephoning relatives .
`` Their relatives should not be worried .
They are better here than on the Achille Lauro , '' said Pringis .
When Irmgard Moeller went to prison 22 years ago for blowing up three American soldiers , the United States was fighting a war in Vietnam .
When she walked out Thursday , she heard the same anti-war songs .
Just about everything else was different .
`` It still feels unreal , '' she said after stepping out the blue steel prison gate into the crisp air of this Baltic city , freed early from a life sentence .
About 200 supporters waved red flags , chanted revolutionary slogans and presented flowers as Germany 's longest-held female prisoner walked free , wearing jeans , a black leather jacket and a red sweater .
`` I have to think first about what I 'll do in future , '' Moeller told reporters as she hugged friends and leftist activists , bearing Christmas presents and flowers .
The fall of communism has blunted the leftist cause , for which Moeller had remained a powerful symbol .
Gone is East Germany , where many terrorists on the run had found refuge .
United Germany is slowly assuming a more assertive role in world affairs , and its soldiers have served in peace missions abroad .
With NATO now asking for German fighter planes for the skies over Bosnia , the country 's military involvement abroad could again send leftists into the streets .
Moeller , her activities subject to approval by a probation officer for the next five years , promised to work for the release of other jailed terrorists .
`` The others must not stay in prison as long as I have , '' she said .
`` Free all political prisoners , '' the crowd chanted and carried banners with the same message .
As she was driven away in her lawyer 's car , a loudspeaker mounted on a van blared out `` Internationale , '' the revolutionary socialist hymn .
Moeller 's release could lead to freedom for the seven other Red Army Faction serving long sentences .
Unlike some other previously released former Red Army Faction members , Moeller did not renounce her terrorist past .
But authorities could be hoping that her release will cement a truce with the leftist group that once had been seen as a possible threat to democracy .
Three years ago , then President Richard von Weizsaecker said it was time to start a dialogue with former terrorists and to try to reintegrate them into society .
After killing a German official in 1991 and blowing up a prison in 1993 , the Red Army Faction said it was ending its 20-year campaign of violence , during which it often targeted the American military and other symbols of what it called `` imperialism . ''
Moeller was convicted of driving one of the explosives-laden cars that blew up in a parking lot at U.S. Army Headquarters in Heidelberg on May 24 , 1972 .
The bomb killed Capt. Clyde R. Bonner and two enlisted men , Charles L. Peck and Ronald A. Woodward .
Moeller was arrested six weeks after the attack and sentenced to life in prison , plus 15 years .
The Red Army Faction issued a statement after the bombing , calling it a protest against the U.S. military involvement in Vietnam .
Moeller was freed because of her poor health , although she has shown no remorse and refused to cooperate with psychiatric evaluations to determine if she was still dangerous .
A court in the state of Schleswig-Holstein , where the prison is located , determined that she was not likely to commit another violent crime .
The state prosecutor 's office agreed .
The U.S. State Department and relatives of the victims objected to her release , but many Germans feel 22 years was long enough for Moeller , regardless of the seriousness of her crimes .
Most prisoners sentenced to life in Germany are released after 15 years .
There was no domestic protest , and newspaper articles about the case in the past weeks have focused on Moeller 's history and prison conditions .
`` While we recognize the independence of German courts , we are disappointed that an unrepentant terrorist who murdered three U.S. soldiers has been freed from prison , '' said a U.S. State Department statement issued in Washington .
`` Prior to this parole , the United States formally reiterated to the government of Germany our view that convicted terrorists should serve their full prison terms . ''
In a 1992 interview with the magazine Der Spiegel , Moeller was asked if she felt sympathy for the victims of Red Army Faction violence .
` I ca n't deal with this so personally and individually , '' she replied .
A striking , dark-haired woman when she went to jail , Moeller 's pale complexion , lined face and streaks of gay hair speak of the life behind bars .
She is suffering from skin , eye and other ailments .
Moeller lived through 12 hunger strikes and was the only survivor in the night of Oct. 18 , 1977 , when three other Red Army Faction leaders -- Andreas Baader , Jan-Carl Raspe and Gudrun Ensslin , committed suicide in the top-security Stammheim prison in Stuttgart .
Discovered with four stabs in her chest , Moeller has always claimed the terrorists were the victims of state violence .
The planned European Union-wide police force will not have its marching orders this year , as the dozen governments ended talks Thursday by failing to agree on rules for Europol .
Despite growing public concern about organized crime and international drug trafficking , justice and interior ministers here for a meeting again spent it squabbling over details on how to coordinate their police forces .
The ministers have already missed an October deadline for adopting a convention for the Netherlands-based Europol .
Germany has sought an FBI-style agency , independent and with a long arm to track individuals or organizations .
But France wants national police forces to have easy access to Europol data , and would limit the exchange of information between member states .
British officials are reluctant to feed sensitive information to a data bank that authorities in other member states can inspect any time .
Crime fighting remains the responsibility of individual governments , who have agreed to work together on the subject .
Their lack of progress has caused frustration among EU officials , who remain powerless on the matter .
Commissioner Padraig Flynn , the EU 's justice and immigration chief , railed against the ministers Thursday , criticizing their slow pace .
`` We have made no progress '' on Europol , he told reporters after the meeting .
`` There are some very obvious questions and they have to be faced up to . ''
Flynn also complained that governments have not yet fixed immigration rules , and that `` nothing has happened '' with a plan to seal the union 's external frontiers .
Both are necessary to allow free movement for people inside the trade bloc , a prime goal of the group 's border-free , single market that took effect Jan. 1 , 1993 .
Riddick Bowe may have sold some extra tickets by punching Larry Donald at a prefight press conference .
If he was trying to scare the mild-mannered former Olympian , Donald said it did n't work .
`` When most big guys try to intimidate someone , they become intimidated , '' Donald said .
`` I think that 's what happened in this case . ''
Donald skipped a final prefight press conference Wednesday , two days after being hit twice by Bowe at a similar gathering in Los Angeles .
`` It 's very hard to be in the room with a former world heavyweight champion when he pulls a stunt like that , '' Donald said .
Instead , Donald held his own press conference next door to the main event , where his manager , Steve Nelson , tried to get Bowe to apologize for Monday 's incident in Los Angeles .
`` The lack of class demonstrated by Riddick Bowe does not allow Larry to lower himself by appearing with him , '' Nelson said .
`` Riddick Bowe violated all rules of proper conduct as a boxer and a member of the human race . ''
Bowe , who will fight Saturday for only the second time since losing his heavyweight titles last November to Evander Holyfield , was n't in an apologetic mood .
`` I 'm getting tired of being Mr. Nice Guy , '' Bowe said .
`` People mistake my kindness for weakness .
I told him not to say anything to me .
He just kept running his lips . ''
Although Bowe 's left-right combination in Los Angeles did n't land fully on Donald , it did cut the 1992 Olympian on the inside of his mouth .
It also left the mild-mannered fighter puzzled about his first foray into big-time boxing .
`` I 'm upset , '' Donald said .
`` Every time I turn around and I see the tape of it , it makes me upset . ''
Donald , undefeated in 16 professional fights , said he and his handlers decided at the last minute to skip the press conference as a protest of Bowe 's actions .
Donald said the punches by Bowe came without warning as the two were talking about the fight .
`` I was shocked , '' said Donald , who did not fight back .
`` I always think before I react .
I ca n't remember the last time I lost my temper . ''
Marc Ratner , executive director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission , said no action would be taken by the commission since the incident occurred in California .
Bowe is a 4-1 favorite to beat Donald in the scheduled 12-round fight Saturday at Caesars Palace .
Bowe , 34-1 , has fought only once since losing to Holyfield , getting a no-decision after hitting Buster Mathis Jr. while he was down in their August fight .
Donald , who lost in the quarterfinals of the Barcelona Olympics , is 16-0 with 12 knockouts and is ranked No. 5 by the WBC .
Despite its public ban on war aid to Bosnian Serbs , Yugoslavia has assisted in a crucial attack on northwest Bosnia , according to Bosnian , Serb , and U.N. reports .
The reports released this week raise doubts about Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic 's commitment to the aid cutoff he announced in August to pressure Bosnian Serbs into accepting a peace plan .
The attack on Bihac in northwest Bosnia called NATO 's bluff to use large-scale force against the Serbs .
It has led to a rapid deterioration in the United Nations ' authority , and on Wednesday , U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali said the 24,000 peacekeepers might have to be withdrawn .
In October , the Bosnian army 's 5th Corps broke out of the Bihac area where government forces are completely surrounded by Serb-held territory in Croatia and Bosnia .
They pushed the Serbs back in a surprise attack to the east and south .
But the Serbs counter-attacked furiously , and now control 30-40 percent of the U.N.-declared Bihac `` safe area , '' which encompasses the town of Bihac and environs .
Fighting there is continuing .
Classified U.N. reports , claims by the Bosnian government , and reports by media and reliable sources in Yugoslavia all suggest that fighters and supplies from Yugoslavia have been involved in the Bihac combat .
`` It is so obvious that ... Serbs received new weapons , fresh troops ... and fuel to move ` dry ' tanks , '' charged Gen. Jovan Divjak , a Serb who serves as deputy commander of the Bosnian army .
`` Otherwise , they would n't have been able to put Bihac under such strong pressure . ''
Bosnian government officials said intelligence reports indicated fuel and ammunition trucks had crossed the border into Bosnia from Serbia , the main republic in Yugoslavia , and that armor , helicopters and rockets all had been provided .
In a visit to Sarajevo on Tuesday , Charles Thomas , the U.S. representative on a five-nation group seeking peace in Bosnia , told reporters that Milosevic 's clampdown was generally successful , but that the border was `` somewhat porous . ''
Several hundred international monitors are assigned to check the roughly 500-kilometer -LRB- 300-mile -RRB- Yugoslav-Bosnian border for violations .
Their reports so far have revealed no violations .
But reports from Yugoslavia and from U.N. observers indicate that Milosevic may have used the involvement of Serbs from Croatia to get assistance to the Bihac combatants .
While Milosevic said he was cutting off help to the Bosnian Serbs , he did not make a similar pledge regarding the Croatian Serbs .
Classified U.N. reports shown to The Associated Press in Sarajevo say that U.N. observers had noticed armed men crossing the border between Serb-held territory in Croatia and Bosnia in vehicles with Belgrade licenses .
The presence of fighters from Yugoslavia in Bosnia also was reported in Milosevic 's Serbia .
The Svet weekly , based in the northern Serbian town of Novi Sad , said a special Serbian police unit of up to 1,000 men headed by a top police officer had joined the fighting .
The weekly said the policemen crossed into Bosnia as civilians , and traveled through Bosnia to Croatia , where they received weapons and uniforms .
A senior Serbian police official denied the Svet report .
But reliable sources in Belgrade confirmed that Yugoslav army and police detachments actively took part in the fighting .
Svet also claimed that the only other republic in Yugoslavia , Montenegro , had shipped a large supply of fuel to Bosnian Serbs .
Under a furious lobbying barrage from the Clinton administration and a small army of corporate executives , the Senate stood on the verge Thursday of ratifying a sweeping expansion of global free trade .
The climatic vote will not occur until the end of a second full day of debate , but supporters were claiming they now had an ample number of votes for the agreement itself and , more importantly , a small cushion for the three-fifths majority they need on a budget waiver .
`` By the time the vote is actually taken tonight , we expect GATT will pass , '' said presidential press secretary Dee Dee Myers .
While administration officials and Senate supporters said their vote counts showed victory in their grasp , they did not let up in their lobbying efforts .
President Clinton met at the White House with a group of mostly undecided senators in an attempt to build the victory margin .
Sen. Kent Conrad said the president told senators `` they will regret the vote the rest of their lives '' if they oppose GATT .
Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen warned the accord 's defeat would have an `` adverse reaction '' in both the stock and bond markets , Conrad said .
Opponents , while conceding that the momentum was not going their way , did not let up in their efforts , either .
A group of two-dozen protesters , one dressed as a lame-duck , chanted outside the White House as senators arrived for breakfast with Clinton .
Sen. Fritz Hollings of South Carolina said that the new trade agreement was a bad deal that , by lowering trade barriers , would subject American workers to even more unfair competition from low-wage countries , further weakening the country 's economic standing .
`` The reality is that we are in decline .
Everybody knows that , '' said Hollings , whose home-state textile industry will be one of the biggest losers in the deal .
`` Wake up , Washington . ''
However , GATT supporters said that the Senate 's choice on the last day of the 103rd Congress was between continuing to hold a position of economic leadership in the global economy or retreating behind protectionist barriers .
The House endorsed the accord , negotiated under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade , by a 288-146 vote on Tuesday .
Thirty-three other countries already have ratified the 124-nation accord and supporters said other countries are poised to act before Jan. 1 if the Senate follows the House .
According to an Associated Press survey , GATT proponents appeared on the verge of victory , when counting those who were leaning in favor but not firmly committed .
The AP head count had 60 senators for or leaning for waiving budget rules , 26 against or leaning against and 14 undeclared .
Opponents ' only hope was to change enough senators ' minds to muster 41 votes in favor of the procedural hurdle imposed by Sen. Robert Byrd .
Under Senate rules , the implementing bill must offset all of the projected dlrs 43 billion in lost tariff revenues over the first decade of the accord .
To make up for the lost tariffs , the administration is cutting farm subsidies and raising revenue with a number of measures , including changing the minimum rate on savings bonds and auctioning licenses for a new generation of wireless broadcast services .
Byrd said the bill falls dlrs 14.5 billion short and some senators , while declaring themselves in favor of free trade , said they would not vote to bust the budget .
Byrd and others also complain that a new Geneva-based World Trade Organization , created to referee trade disputes , will inevitably infringe on U.S. sovereignty .
The administration is predicting 500,000 new American jobs as a result of increased U.S. export sales under GATT .
In addition to bringing foreign tariffs closer to U.S. levels , it reduces barriers to trade in agricultural goods and services and protects U.S. intellectual property , such as computer programs , from being pirated .
Chrysler Corp. increased its dividend 60 percent Thursday , announced it would buy back dlrs 1 billion in stock and relaxed its anti-takeover defenses , three of four steps proposed by the company 's largest shareholder .
Billionaire Kirk Kerkorian , who owns 9 percent of Chrysler , also had asked the company to split its stock , but no split was announced .
The quarterly dividend was increased to 40 cents a share from 25 cents .
The company had announced 5-cent increases twice in the past year .
The stock repurchase program will start after the first of the year .
`` We remain committed to enhancing shareholder value , and this is a very effective method for doing so , '' Chrysler Chairman Robert J. Eaton said in the announcement .
The company 's `` poison pill '' anti-takeover provision was modified so that it is not triggered until a stockholder acquires 15 percent of the outstanding shares .
The previous trigger was 10 percent .
Kerkorian has asked federal regulators ' permission to increase his stake in the company to up to 15 percent .
Eaton said the `` poison pill ' change was prompted by Kerkorian 's actions , but that the other measures had been under consideration for some time .
The company also announced it was increasing its five-year capital spending program to dlrs 22.9 billion from the current level of dlrs 20.8 billion .
Nigeria 's budget for 1995 will be based on crude oil sales estimated at dlrs 16 a barrel , the government-owned Daily Times newspaper reported Thursday .
Oil provides 80 percent of government earnings and more than 90 percent of foreign exchange revenue for the West African nation .
This year 's budget of dlrs 4.87 billion was based on a crude oil price of dlrs 14 a barrel , though actual sales averaged dlrs 17 a barrel .
The government has yet has to publish the report of a commission that found that dlrs 12.2 billion made from extra oil sales during the Gulf War has not been accounted for .
Nigeria produces 1.9 million barrels of oil daily , and exports 1.5 million of that .
A Pennsylvania company has found evidence of soil and groundwater contamination at U.S. Navy base on this British colony scheduled to close next year .
Curtis Kimbel , environmental director of Naval Air Station Bermuda , said petroleum products apparently leaked from some of the base 's 130 underground storage tanks .
The tanks stored jet fuel , diesel fuel and heating oil .
The 1,200-acre base , which opened during World War II , is scheduled to close next Sept. 1 .
RT Environmental Services Inc. of King of Prussia , Pa. has been drilling and performing other tests for the last two months under a $ 480,000 contract with the Bermuda government , which will inherit the base property .
A report from RT is expected in two weeks and the government has n't commented on the findings .
But Kimbel and other Navy officials said RT has shared information with them .
`` Their preliminary results have shown some soil contamination and some potential groundwater contamination , '' said Cmdr. Mike Donnelly , the Navy 's public works officer .
Donnelly said the Navy will study RT 's report before deciding how much cleanup is required .
The Navy 's policy is to eliminate known risks to health and safety .
Under an agreement with Great Britain , the Americans have occupied the land rent-free , also running Bermuda 's commercial airport on the base free of charge .
The Navy has placed a $ 140 million price tag on improvements it has made to the Naval Air Station and another smaller base on the island .
But Bermuda argues that the money spent will be more than offset by the cost of environmental damage and of demolishing or maintaining base buildings .
Liverpool fans , take heart .
Ian Rush has rediscovered his scoring touch .
After a drought of seven games without a goal , the Welshman scored three times in Liverpool 's 3-1 victory over Premier League leaders Blackburn in the League Cup on Wednesday night .
Rush 's hat trick came in his 600th appearance for Liverpool and brought his career total with the club to 329 goals .
Of those , 46 have come in the League Cup , just three short of Geoff Hurst 's all-time record .
Blackburn striker Mike Newell led the accolades for the 33-year-old Rush .
`` I 've watched Rushie as a Liverpool fan and he 's just a born scorer , '' he said .
`` What he did out there was a lesson in finishing for all of us .
He 's showed again that you can never write him off .
He 's proved over the last 10 years that he 's the No. 1 striker in the country . ''
Blackburn manager Kenny Daglish paid tribute to his former teammate at Anfield .
`` A lot of people have been saying he 's a bad player this season , but this will bring them to their senses , '' Daglish said .
