NATO foreign ministers approved an American proposal today to study expanding the alliance to include central and east European countries .
Anxious to ease Russian fears about the expansion of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization , the foreign ministers emphasized the alliance was not trying to create a hostile bloc .
`` Having just overcome the division of Europe , we have no desire to see the emergence of new lines of partition , '' the ministers said in a draft of their final statement .
The plan to move toward expanding NATO was planned as the centerpiece of two-day meeting .
But the unprecedented strains between the United States and its European allies over the crisis in Bosnia overshadowed the talks .
In an effort to heal the divisions , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
That marks a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the Europeans , led by Britain and France .
With the policy turnaround , ministers agreed to relaunch diplomatic efforts to end the Bosnian war .
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe told reporters he hoped a meeting Friday with Christopher and the foreign ministers of Germany , Britain and Russia would launch `` a new initiative '' to end the fighting .
Juppe added he will travel to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , on Sunday with British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd for talks with President Slobodan Milosevic .
Christopher has also said he may go .
At the same time , in an apparent attempt to beef up its air power over Bosnia , NATO has asked Germany to add its warplanes to the allied forces in case airstrikes are called against the Serbs .
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said his government was considering the request .
The request is highly sensitive because of Germany 's postwar pacifist tradition , and the history of Nazi atrocities in the Balkans during World War II .
The foreign ministers were anxious their talks not be entirely hijacked by the Bosnian crisis .
They ordered a study that would set out the terms for the acceptance of east European countries as new members .
It should be ready when the ministers meet in Brussels a year from now .
The United States had initially proposed a six-month study of enlargement , but the Europeans , mindful of Russia 's fears of isolation , extended it to 12 months .
The study will not name candidates for membership -- although Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and Slovakia are considered front-runners -- nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
Instead , the study will focus on such questions as whether NATO troops will need to be based in new member states , how much enlargement will cost and how to integrate the newcomer 's army into NATO 's command structure .
To counter Russian worries about NATO 's eastward expansion , the allies intend later today to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Moscow and agree to hold regular talks on security .
Princess Diana comforted a 4-year-old girl dying of AIDS on Thursday and joked with a man who has had the disease for 11 years , continuing a commitment to raise AIDS-awareness .
The princess , resuming more public engagements two years after her separation from Prince Charles , visited the new Mortimer Market Clinic in London on World AIDS day .
Chatting with one patient , Chris Keegan , who was diagnosed with AIDS in 1983 , she teased him that his tie and shirt not matching .
`` You obviously have n't seen my socks , '' replied Keegan , and proceeded to show her them .
`` She has a remarkable talent ... of being able to engage people , talk to them and comfort them , '' said National Aids Trust chairman Mike Adler , who accompanied Diana on her tour of the clinic .
Diana made headlines in 1987 when she opened London 's first Aids ward , and was photographed shaking hands with patients .
The publicity helped decrease the pariah status of AIDS-afflicted patients in Britain .
The new clinic , the Mortimer Market Center , is expected to become Europe 's largest clinic for the treatment of sexually-transmitted diseases , administering to 80,00 patients a year .
Diana was attending a rock concert to raise funds for AIDS research at London 's Wembley arena on Thursday night .
