Clashes among rival political groups left at least four persons dead and 20 injured Thursday in two states elections considered tests of Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao 's popularity .
The clashes occurred mostly in Andhra Pradesh , the home state of Rao , where leftist guerrillas called for a boycott of the elections in their northern stronghold to protest successive corrupt governments .
In the neighboring state of Karnataka , one political activist was killed when a mob hurled rocks at him while he tried to mobilize voters .
The election was considered to be peaceful by Indian standards , where dozens of people have in the past been killed on the day of the balloting .
More than half of the 38 million voters cast their ballots across the two states Thursday .
In Andhra Pradesh , police said they also killed three militants of the Peoples War Group , a rebel group fighting for poor farmers that carried out a series of sabotage incidents in the final weeks of the campaign to disrupt the voting .
Two of the deaths in the state were blamed on explosives hurled during clashes political rivals .
The third death occurred when a truck carrying crude bombs and activists of the Telugu Desam Party overturned while being chased by police .
Four of the 38 bombs exploded and killed one person and injured another , police said .
Police received many cases of villagers looting ballot boxes .
Voting for state legislatures in the two south Indian states was seen as an important bellwether for Congress , which already has suffered setbacks in the north and must retain its support in the south .
A loss in Rao 's own state could unleash rivalries in the governing party that he suppressed with difficulty last year .
Results will be announced Dec. 9 for elections in Andhra Pradesh , Karnataka and two other states that voted last month .
The voting is staggered to allow police forces to move from one to another to protect polling stations .
Pro-Iranian guerrillas in Lebanon once fired Israeli-made shells at northern Israel , Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin said Thursday .
The lesson , he told his ruling Labor party 's central committee , was `` be careful about who you sell weapons to . ''
He stressed the extremist Islamic movements financed by Iran were Israel 's worst enemies .
`` For the sake of employment , we , the state of Israel , once sold weapons to Iran , '' Rabin said .
He did not specify when the sales took place .
Israel was accused during the Iran-Contra scandal of selling weapons to Teheran as part of an arms-for-hostages deal and during the Iran-Iraq war of the 1980s .
Hezbollah , the militia fighting Israeli soldiers in south Lebanon since 1984 , has since fired Israeli-made 120mm shells at Israel , and four struck near the towns of Margaliot and Manara , Rabin said .
He did not say when the shells were fired or whether they caused any casualties .
It was the first time Rabin admitted Israel sold arms to enemy nations .
But weapons experts have previously suggested the possibility , given Israel 's financially troubled arms industries and some illegal deals uncovered in the past .
`` The most important thing is n't the existence of the defense industries but who we sell to , '' Rabin said .
State-owned defense firms , once a symbol of Israeli self-sufficiency and industrial prowess , are losing about dlrs 1 billion annually because of declining orders worldwide .
