Sunburned and scattered on an improvised armada of U.S. Navy ships and cargo boats in the Indian Ocean , the nearly 1,000 survivors of a blaze that swept through the Achille Lauro began the first leg Thursday of their return home .
The fire broke out Wednesday morning , reportedly in the engine room , on the bad luck cruise ship -- the Achille Lauro was hijacked in 1985 and an American passenger killed by Palestinian terrorists .
Passengers and crew who escaped the blaze by scrambling into lifeboats were transferred Thursday to 10 ships that would take them to Kenya or Djibouti .
Many of the survivors , some dressed in evening or bed clothes , had spent hours aboard the deck of the oil tanker Hawaiian King and other merchant ships that had plucked them to safety immediately after the evacuation .
Two elderly passengers died -- an Englishman during the evacuation and a German man of a heart attack .
Eight people were injured .
Starlauro , the Achille Lauro 's owners , said in Naples they were trying to determine if the German died because of the fire or if he had the attack before the early-morning blaze .
`` The fire was so big you had to fight through smoke which poured down toward the cabins , '' one survivor , Tony Webb , was quoted as telling the London Daily Telegraph .
Webb , a 44-year-old Briton who now lives in Cape Town , South Africa , had taken his wife and 2-year-old son on the cruise after winning a contest .
He said he was still wearing his dinner jacket after a ship dance .
`` People were in their evening suits and dressing gowns , '' the paper quoted Webb as saying .
Children screamed and people clung to each other as the Achille Lauro listed .
With his son Michael holding on to him in terror Webb looked back and saw flames `` leaping up and there was smoke all around . ''
'' The crew was wonderful , '' Webb said .
`` They tried to keep us all calm .
At about 8 a.m. , the captain said the fire was too strong and we would have to abandon the ship . ''
Starlauro , the cruise ship 's owners , said an SOS was sent at just before 7 a.m. local time .
It was unclear what time the fire began .
`` Quite a few people were injured in the transfer -LRB- Wednesday -RRB- -- there 's a few broken bones and some pretty tortured souls , '' John Briand , captain of the oil tanker Lima , told the BBC .
The Achille Lauro 's captain , Giuseppe Orsi , talking by phone Thursday aboard the Hawaiian King , told Italy 's transport minister in Rome that survivors ' morale was high but that clothing was needed .
Two Navy ships , the USS Gettysburg and the Halyburton , took on a total of 208 survivors Thursday .
'' Many had tears of relief '' as they came aboard the Gettysburg , that ship 's commander , Capt. Pete Smith said .
They were offered '' a hot shower , the crew were feeding them ... -LRB- and -RRB- donating clothes for them to wear , as a lot abandoned ship in nightclothes . ''
Many had bad sunburn after being exposed for hours on the deck of the Hawaiian King , Navy officials reported .
By Thursday evening , survivors were spread aboard a total of 10 ships .
Five vessels were headed for Djibouti , on the Horn of Africa ; and five for Mombasa , Kenya , with the first due , the Liberian-registered Bar Du , in Djibouti , at 2 p.m. local time -LRB- 1100 gmt -RRB- , the Italian Coast Guard reported Thursday evening .
Others were due in later Friday or Saturday .
The ship had carried 581 passengers and 404 crew .
Most of the crew was Italian , and the passengers mainly South African , German , Dutch or British .
RAI state TV said the Italian state airline , Alitalia , would dispatch jumbos to fly out the survivors , except for South Africans , to Italy once they reached port and had a chance to rest .
The Achille Lauro set sail Nov. 19 from Genoa , Italy ; stopped in Haifa , Israel , and then plied on to Africa 's east coast .
The ship had been bound for South Africa .
The Italian liner itself Thursday still hung on , although listing badly to port .
White steam and gray smoke poured out of port side and smaller plumes of smoke drifted out of the lower starboard deck .
The pilot of a plane carrying Associated Press cameramen and a reporter put the ship 's position at 160 miles east of the small Somali fishing village of Eil .
Heat and soot blackened the Achille Lauro 's two smokestacks , and its blue-and-white paint was scorched and mottled .
The ship 's captain reportedly has put the fire 's origin in the engine room , apparently contradicting the company 's initial assertion that the blaze began in the passenger area .
Starlauro 's director-general , Franco Zuccherino , told RAI TV Thursday that the fire 's dynamics were yet to be determined .
`` We have to talk extensively with the captain '' first , Zuccherino said .
Governments worldwide must improve crop production or face food shortages due to population growth , dwindling water supplies and shrinking amounts of cultivable land , scientists said Thursday .
`` At the moment there is no shortfall but looking 20 years down the road we see a different picture , '' Randolph Barker , the new head of the International Irrigation Management Institute told scientists at the 10th anniversary of the organization .
`` There is an alarming complacency that everything is all right on the food front .
But we must learn to make more food with less land and water , and the research must start now because science takes time , '' said Roberto Lenton , the outgoing director-general .
`` The nightmare of world hunger that was stopped by the green revolution in agricultural production in the 1960s may return to haunt us , '' said M.S. Swaminathan , chairman of institute .
Global population is projected to total 7.1 billion by the year 2010 , compared to 5.2 today , according to the World Bank .
The amount of water available for irrigation is declining due to increased demands from growing population .
At present , 80 percent of the water is for irrigation , but competition is increasing from household and industrial consumers .
The Consultative Group on International Agricultural Research , the world body co-ordinating research on food production , is organizing a global initiative on increased water management to solve the problem .
The irrigation institute , headquartered in Colombo , has been designated the convening center .
Computer hackers claiming to represent a shadowy terrorist group breached security codes at a news agency Thursday and sent a message boasting their strength and disavowing links with an alleged police-led crime ring .
Magistrates seized computer disks at the agency , Adnkronos , forcing them to temporarily suspend transmission of news to Italian newspapers and other subscribers .
The message -- signed by the `` Falange Armata , '' or Armed Phalanx -- said the group has an arsenal and connections that could `` make the Irish Republican Army shudder . ''
It said the group planned to carry out more attacks in 1995 .
The group has taken credit for many bombings and attacks in the past , but authorities have never proven it was an authentic terrorist cell .
Italian media reports have linked the Falange Armata to an alleged murder and robbery ring led by several police officers in Bologna and surrounding cities .
But the computer message said it had no ties to the gang .
The message appeared on computer screens after journalists turned on their terminals , said Carlo Bassi , head of foreign news for the agency .
`` It really is worrisome that someone could crack into the system like this , '' said Bassi .
`` Is showed that it is not far-fetched to think that people could break in and begin sending fake stories . ''
Nick Faldo of England fired eight birdies Thursday en route to a six-under 66 and a two-stroke lead after the first round of the Million Dollar Challenge .
A second-place finisher three times in the tournament with golf 's richest first prize -- dlrs 1 million -- Faldo rekindled the precision of his record 77-week run as the world 's top-rated player on a blustery day at the Gary Player Country Club course .
In second place were U.S. Open champion Ernie Els of South Africa and Bernhard Langer of Germany , both at four-under-par 68 and three strokes ahead of British Open champion Nick Price of Zimbabwe and Americans Corey Pavin and Tom Lehman .
Another threesome -- American Hale Irwin , Mark McNulty of Zimbabwe and Colin Montgomerie of Scotland -- sat a shot back at even par , one stroke ahead of South African David Frost , the only three-time winner of the tournament being held for the 14th straight year at Sun City .
Seve Ballesteros of Spain , having trouble off the tees , finished four over par at 76 , still four strokes better than Vijay Singh of Fiji , who had a disastrous back nine to limp home with an 80 .
The 12-member field includes six of the world 's 10 top rated players and 11 of the top 20 , including Price , the defending champion and world 's best player this year .
Both Langer and Ballesteros have won the tournament twice previously , while McNulty also is a former champion .
Despite its promise to stop delivering military aid to Bosnian Serbs , Yugoslavia has assisted in a crucial attack on northwestern Bosnia , according to Bosnian , Serb , and U.N. reports .
The reports released this week raise doubts about Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic 's commitment to the aid cutoff he announced in August to pressure Bosnian Serbs into accepting a peace plan .
The attack on Bihac in northwest Bosnia called NATO 's bluff to use large-scale force against the Serbs .
It has led to a rapid deterioration in the United Nations ' authority , and on Wednesday , U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali said the 24,000 peacekeepers might have to be withdrawn .
In October , the Bosnian army 's 5th Corps broke out of the Bihac area where government forces are completely surrounded by Serb-held territory in Croatia and Bosnia .
They pushed the Serbs back in a surprise attack .
But the Serbs counterattacked furiously , and now control 30 percent to 40 percent of the U.N.-declared Bihac safe haven , which encompasses the town of Bihac and its environs .
Fighting there is continuing .
Classified U.N. reports , claims by the Bosnian government , and reports by media and reliable sources in Yugoslavia all suggest that fighters and supplies from Yugoslavia have been involved in the combat in Bihac .
`` It is so obvious that ... Serbs received new weapons , fresh troops ... and fuel to move ` dry ' tanks , '' charged Gen. Jovan Divjak , a Serb who serves as deputy commander of the Bosnian army .
`` Otherwise , they would n't have been able to put Bihac under such strong pressure . ''
Bosnian government officials said intelligence reports indicated fuel and ammunition trucks had crossed the border into Bosnia from Serbia , the main republic in what remains of Yugoslavia , and that armor , helicopters and rockets all had been provided .
In a visit to Sarajevo on Tuesday , Charles Thomas , the U.S. representative on a five-nation group seeking peace in Bosnia , told reporters that Milosevic 's clampdown was generally successful , but that the border was `` somewhat porous . ''
Several hundred international monitors are assigned to check the roughly 500-kilometer -LRB- 300-mile -RRB- Yugoslav-Bosnian border for violations .
Their reports so far have revealed no violations .
But reports from Yugoslavia and from U.N. observers indicate that Milosevic may have used the involvement of Serbs from Croatia to get assistance to the Bihac combatants .
While Milosevic said he was cutting off help to the Bosnian Serbs , he did not make a similar pledge regarding the Croatian Serbs .
Classified U.N. reports shown to The Associated Press in Sarajevo say that U.N. observers had noticed armed men crossing the border between Serb-held territory in Croatia and Bosnia in vehicles with Belgrade licenses .
The presence of fighters from Yugoslavia in Bosnia also was reported in Milosevic 's Serbia .
The Svet weekly , based in the northern Serbian town of Novi Sad , said a special Serbian police unit of up to 1,000 men headed by a top police officer had joined the fighting .
The weekly said the policemen crossed into Bosnia as civilians , and traveled through Bosnia to Croatia , where they received weapons and uniforms .
A senior Serbian police official denied the Svet report .
But reliable sources in Belgrade confirmed that Yugoslav army and police detachments actively took part in the fighting .
Svet also claimed that the only other republic in Yugoslavia , Montenegro , had shipped a large supply of fuel to Bosnian Serbs .
