Carlos Graca , this island nation 's new premier , on Thursday declared his private wealth and property to justice officials as part of an anti- corruption campaign that was a key election pledge .
Attorney General Silvestre Leite said Graca had listed details of his personal income from sources at home and abroad and had urged other members of his government to follow suit .
Graca , a 62-year-old doctor , campaigned for and won Oct. 2 elections on a ticket that focussed heavily on stamping out corruption on these idyllic but poor islands of 120,000 people .
The move , which is supposed to permit justice officials to spot any irregularities in politicians ' accounts , was unprecedented in Sao Tome and rare for most of the rest of Africa .
Earlier this year , former Trade Minister Alzemiro dos Prazeres was accused of diverting dlrs 20,000 from his ministry 's coffers .
Sao Tome has a legally fixed minimum salary of 10,000 dobras -LRB- dlrs 12.50 -RRB- but many islanders earn even less .
The former government 's popularity slumped in the October poll and Graca 's Liberation Movement for Sao Tome and Principe , a formerly Marxist party that now calls itself Social Democrat , returned to power .
It had established a one-party state in Sao Tome after independence from Portugal in 1975 but then allowed first multi-party elections in 1991 and went into opposition .
National Hockey League officials began arriving Thursday in a downtown hotel for talks they hope will solve the labor dispute and save the North American ice hockey season .
`` I am always hopeful , '' commissioner Gary Bettman said Thursday as he walked past television cameras and into an elevator .
`` It 's fair to say that with each passing day , the meeting that is coming up is more crucial , '' Boston Bruins general manager Harry Sinden said Wednesday .
To show how serious the negotiators are : They have reserved room space in a Chicago hotel for three days .
Both sides agree that the latest meetings are pivotal .
`` There is an urgency , '' said Troy Loney , player representative of the New York Islanders .
`` The meetings here in Chicago in the next couple of days are vital to find out whether there 's going to be a season or not , '' said Jeremy Roenick of the Chicago Blackhawks .
`` We have to make sure we let everybody know we did n't strike .
The owners locked us out . ''
`` It 's getting to the point where they are going to have to make a decision -LRB- on the Collective Bargaining Agreement -RRB- , '' a management source told The Associated Press .
The owners lockout has forced a work stoppage that is now in its 62nd day .
So far , 347 games have been called off .
The schedule is already down from 84 to 60 games , following the cancellation of 24 for each of the 26 teams .
Owners have said they will accept no less than a 50-game schedule .
A settlement beyond the middle of December would sorely test that ideal , given the fact that players need at least two weeks to get ready for the season .
The main issue is the owners ' desire for a salary cap , a limit each team could spend on player salaries , as a way to control costs .
They have amended that to a `` luxury tax '' -- meaning teams could spend over a set limit , but must pay an additional `` tax '' into a pool that smaller-market teams could utilize to strenghen their rosters .
At one time strongly opposed to any kind of cap , players have softened their stance on a salary cap for first-year or rookie players .
But they still have n't come to terms on the numbers .
Reportedly , owners would like a maximum cap for rookie salaries set at around dlrs 750,000 a season , while players would prefer around dlrs 1.5 million .
Players on Thursday were expected to present the owners with their thoughts on other major issues such as free agency and salary arbritration .
The contentious luxury tax issue is another story , however .
`` If the tax is on the table , there 's trouble , '' Loney said .
It may not get to that point if the negotiators can find a way to put a drag on rising salaries in other areas .
`` We just have n't finished the review process of anything outside of the tax , '' Sinden told The Canadian Press on Wednesday .
`` Until we do , I do n't think Bettman can make any statement about the tax .
`` It depends if we can slow down the problems the league is trying to correct .
But that has not been determined because we have not reached agreement on all these points .
We have not had a chance to add it up . ''
Until now , owners have insisted on a tax of team payrolls that go over the average team salary and give the money to those under the prescribed limit .
The players have been against such a tax , believing it has the same effect as a salary cap .
Players reportedly would accept a diminished version of the payroll tax if owners share the burden by taxing gate receipts .
The decision to support the expansion of the alliance came on the opening day of a two-day conference of allied foreign ministers whose talks were likely to be overshadowed by the crisis in Bosnia .
`` Today , we take an important step in the process that will lead to NATO expansion , '' said U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher in addressing his counterparts at the opening session .
`` The United States believes it is time to begin the process -- to begin deliberate consideration of the practical requirements for adding new members to the alliance , '' he said in the text of his speech .
The decision to authorize the study , though , is a cautious move forward in drawing former adversaries anxious for membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
`` We have a moral duty not to squander this historic opportunity to anchor the new democracies of central and eastern Europe permanently in the West , '' said NATO Secretary-general Willy Claes .
The study -- dubbed an `` owner 's manual '' for NATO membership -- will take a year to complete .
It will not name candidates for membership , nor will it set a deadline for admittance .
Instead , it will focus on such questions as whether NATO troops will need to be based in new member states ; how much enlargement will cost ; how to integrate the newcomers army into NATO 's command structure
To counter Russian worries about an eastward expansion of NATO , the allies intend later Thursday to endorse a sweeping military cooperation program with Russia and agree to hold regular talks with Moscow on security matters .
Russian officials have registered apprehension about the movement of NATO 's territory farther east , and alliance leaders have gone out of their way to try to strengthen separate ties with Moscow .
`` Russia is a part of Europe , '' said the NATO source , who insisted on anonymity .
`` You can not have a security system without the participation of Russia . ''
The ministers , he said , emphasized the importance of `` increasing the momentum '' of consultations between NATO and Russia .
The United States had initially proposed a six-month study of enlargement , but the Europeans , mindful of Moscow 's concerns , extended it to 12 months .
`` We should avoid premature enlargement that gives the impression that we seek a redivision of the European continent , '' said French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe , according to a spokesman .
The allies do not intend to identify candidates for membership , nor set a date for admission .
But the NATO source said , `` Central European states would be first . ''
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and Slovakia are considered front-runners .
Despite attempts to keep the focus on new members , the Bosnian crisis will no doubt occupy a large amount of the ministers ' time .
During the talks , Christopher was expected to tell the allies the Clinton administration has swung behind their view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian conflict .
It marks a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the European allies , led by Britain and France .
The change in U.S. policy will help heal an unprecedented rift within the alliance over Bosnia .
At a breakfast with British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd , Christopher reviewed the warning U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali delivered Wednesday that unless warring Serbs and Muslims cooperate with the U.N. mission the peacekeepers might be withdrawn .
Hurd said he may go to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , this weekend to preach reconciliation .
Officials said French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe may join him .
The latest American approach centers on a call for an international peace conference that would let Bosnian Serbs seek changes in the peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
That plan would require them to cut their holdings in Bosnia from 70 percent to 49 percent .
The Clinton administration , officials say , is also leaning toward approval of political ties between Serbs in Bosnia and Serbia proper -- a big step toward their aim of a Greater Serbia .
On Friday , Christopher will meet with here his counterparts from France , Germany , Britain and Russia to discuss new plans to revive their moribund peace plan for Bosnia .
France and Britain have been criticized in the U.S. Congress for refusing to let the United Nations use the Western military alliance 's air power to the full .
In turn , Congress has forced the Clinton administration to seek a lifting of the arms embargo against Bosnia 's Muslim-led government , something the European NATO allies oppose for fear it would escalate the fighting .
Gulf Daily News , Manama , Bahrain , on Bosnia :
Bosnian Serbs were ... on the verge of military victory in Bihac -- and five major world powers seeking a peace settlement seem powerless to stop them .
The statement issued after ... French talks feebly demanded an immediate cease-fire -- and Washington , Moscow , Paris , London and Bonn are clinging to a facade of unity .
Pledges to continue diplomatic efforts are now not enough .
An ultimatum is needed followed by strong NATO intervention to save Bihac and prevent the resulting massacre .
This could be preceded by an extension of the U.N.-declared `` safe area '' around the town , using NATO air power to enforce it .
For this , European allies would need to plough in extra ground troops .
Without such drastic action the Western alliance 's already discredited policy in Bosnia will completely collapse .
Jerusalem Post on Bosnia :
The new sniping between Europeans and the United States over the humiliation of the United Nations in Bosnia is a disturbing sign of how deeply this cancerous war has eaten into the monolithic Atlantic alliance .
What has also emerged from the fall of the Bihac `` safe area '' is that European states have been tilting steadily toward a Russian , rather than American , foreign policy perspective .
This is a development which has implications far beyond the mess in what was once Yugoslavia .
The grand coalition of over 30 states that converged to liberate Kuwait from the grasp of -LRB- Iraq 's -RRB- Saddam Hussein now seems as far away as the Cold War itself .
le Figaro , Paris , on Bosnia :
The conflict in Bosnia has revealed the true state of relations between the United States and Europe in the area of defense .
It 's no exaggeration to say the divergences are deep , for the basic reason that the U.S. administration does n't consider its strategic interests threatened by the torching of Bosnia .
The Europeans , in contrast , fear that the rewards given to the aggressor will encourage him to pursue his policy of ethnic cleansing in Kosovo and Macedonia .
... It is high time to engage in a deep reflection on NATO , and that the Europeans and Americans become aware of the danger of this family quarrel .
Nihon Keizai Shinbun , Tokyo , on guns :
Recent shooting incidents like the one in which a waitress was shot in the head in a restaurant robbery are on the rise in Japan .
... What really points up the seriousness of the problem is that now it is n't just gangsters , but ordinary citizens who are being targeted .
What 's really terrifying about guns is that , compared with the powerful effort and will to kill required to murder with a knife or sword , there 's very little psychological deterrent for someone killing from a distance with a gun .
Serious discussion is needed to make sure that Japan , which was the safest country in the world , does not become a gun society like America .
The Australian , Sydney , Australia , on Japan 's `` comfort women '' :
Japan 's rejection of the recommendation by the International Commission of Jurists that it should pay compensation to surviving `` comfort women '' forced into sexual slavery during World War II is regrettable .
It indicates a return to the attitude that predominated among Japan 's immediate postwar generations -- to disguise the past by contriving not to discuss it -- and represents a setback for the gradual attempts of recent years to reflect on the war through more open , honest and mature debate .
The Geneva-based ICJ took 19 months to find that up to 200,000 women -- mainly from Korea but also from the Philippines , Taiwan and China -- were forced to work as prostitutes in military brothels .
However , the Japanese government rejected the report within 24 hours , saying it did not recognize the ICJ and would not be responding to its findings .
If Japan is serious about properly mending its international relationships , and participating fully in the regional economy on any footing other than economic mastery , it needs to do more to acknowledge its wartime record .
Making due reparations to survivors of brutality in the occupied countries should be part of that .
The Financial Times , London , on the European Union :
In the hearts of Europe 's policy makers , hope springs eternal .
Faster-than-expected recovery from recession has revived the idea that a group of countries centered on Germany could attain economic and monetary union as early as 1997 .
Yet there is an unfortunate corollary to the improved prospects for the European `` core . ''
Economic divergences in the Continent 's periphery , particularly the European Union 's southern members , are increasing at a disconcerting pace .
Action to cope with the south 's economic challenges has been half-hearted or curbed by political difficulties or both .
The south 's structural weaknesses can not be overcome without painful measures , particularly in reforming labor markets and welfare systems .
... Yet without such restructuring , the task of adjustment will become still more difficult .
If growth migrates permanently from the south , the EU is unlikely to be robust enough to enlarge itself to the east .
Al-Arab , Doha , Qatar , on the European Union :
The European Union 's steps to reinstate its own independent decision-making by rebuffing U.S.-diktat and shedding off the Israeli hegemony is laudable .
The newest evidence of this orientation is the opening by the EU of a new chapter of understanding with Syria by lifting the arms embargo imposed in 1986 .
The EU move would restore the Continent 's key Mideast role , which had dwindled .
The strong words by Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres on the European move unveils Israel 's intention to dictate its own version of the settlement conditions on Syria .
The lifting of the arms embargo on Syria caused serious dissatisfaction for the Israelis , who wanted to pressure Syria .
The German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel , who is also the present EU chairman , should be praised for asserting that the statements of Peres are offending to the entire Europe , a key aid-donor to the Middle East peace process and the Palestinian national self-rule authority .
Kinkel 's response is a strong-worded message to various sides , especially Israel and the United States .
A solid knock by Navjot Sidhu and Sachin Tendulkar helped India establish a comfortable 230 for four against West Indies on the opening day of the second test , which was otherwise marred by mobs that hurled rocks .
The game was stopped twice -- for a total of one hour -- as West Indies skipper Courtney Walsh led his team off the field as the crowd in this central Indian city hurled soft drink bottles , fruit and rocks on to the field .
Referee Raman Subba Row blamed the local authorities for poor crowd control .
Police later ringed the field .
It was not immediately clear why the crowd became irate .
`` We are lucky that no one was seriously hurt , '' Row said .
Stuart Williams was hit before lunch , while Phil Simmons at deep extra cover region was hit with a piece of fruit just after tea .
In the morning , India , which is 1-0 in the three-test series , won the toss and opted to bat .
Sidhu and Tendulkar established a splendid 177 partnership in about three hours .
Sidhu scored 107 , his sixth test century .
His strokes were confident as he hit a total of 17 fours .
But he offered a simple catch to wicketkeeper Murray off Carl Hooper .
Tendulkar was unbeaten with 81 and at the end of the day , he had hit a dozen boundaries off 155 balls in just over three hours .
Venkatapathy Raju came in to bat as the night watchman after Sidhu was sent to the stands , but he could not stay long and ell to paceman Walsh caught by Brian Adams for two .
Off-spinner Hooper struck as soon as he pressed into the attack .
Bowling a good line and turning the ball just enough to beat the bat , he dislodged Manoj Prabhakar and Vinod Kambli in quick succession .
Speakers and activists at a 42-nation summit on AIDS pleaded Thursday for compassion for homosexuals , drug users and prostitutes often shunned by politicians and the public .
Governments should redouble their efforts to end discrimination against these groups , at high risk of becoming infected with the HIV virus that causes AIDS , participants said .
`` All laws which deny the freedom of people to cross borders because of HIV must be abolished , '' said Richard Burzynski , an HIV sufferer with a Canada-based AIDS rights group , ICASO .
`` This means all laws which criminalize or discriminate against homosexuals , drug users , migrants and refugees , and sex workers must be abolished . ''
Governments tend to ignore or isolate homosexuals , worsening rather than addressing the AIDS epidemic , the International Gay and Lesbian Association said in a statement .
Homosexuals must be accepted , educated and protected by legislation , the group said .
Officials of the 42 participating nations endorsed a declaration pledging to strengthen cooperation between developed and Third World countries and to fight discrimination against those suffering from AIDS .
`` We are not meeting here simply to issue a further warning , but to declare a planetary emergency , '' said U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali .
`` Every day , AIDS kills children , destroys families , drains economies , threatens communities .
We must act without delays . ''
The non-binding declaration says signatories will act to `` ensure that all persons living with HIV\/AIDS are able to realize the full and equal enjoyment of their fundamental rights and freedoms . ''
The declaration promised efforts to provide health care , jobs , education and housing to people with HIV or AIDS .
It also supported `` empowerment of women '' by raising their economic and social status and including them in decision-making .
The summit was a focal point of World AIDS Day , observed around the world with education programs and fund-raising events .
Australians attended special church services commemorating 3,500 compatriots killed by AIDS .
In the Ivory Coast , where AIDS is the leading killer of young men , 2,000 people marched through Abidjan with banners declaring , `` Condoms for life ; AIDS for death . ''
In South Africa , where the disease is spreading rapidly , health officials and politicians wrapped a huge red ribbon around St. George 's Cathedral in Cape Town as part of efforts to increase AIDS awareness .
In Paris , hundreds of teen-agers visited a `` village '' set up across the Seine river from the Eiffel Tower , with scores of stands offering brochures , condoms and other educational material .
About 50 members of the AIDS group Act Up lay on the Champs Elysees to show solidarity with HIV victims .
They blocked traffic for several minutes before leaving the boulevard .
At the summit , there were numerous calls for more AIDS spending , starting with Federico Mayor , head of the U.N. Educational , Scientific and Cultural Organization .
`` In our budgets we have funds to pay the price of war , but we have made no provision for the cost of the fight against AIDS , '' Mayor said .
Funding `` must be accompanied by ethical surveillance to prevent or check any measures ... that would tend to exclude or discriminate against people who are ill from the disease , '' he said .
The World Bank , the biggest donor in the campaign against AIDS , pledged dlrs 150 million annually to combat the disease in developing countries .
Britain announced an allocation of 230 million pounds -LRB- dlrs 358 million -RRB- on AIDS services for 1995 .
Currently , however , more than 90 percent of the money pledged to fight AIDS goes toward helping only the 8 percent of those afflicted in developed countries .
Some 17 million people are known to have been infected with the HIV virus , about two-thirds in Africa , the World Health Organization says .
Up to 40 million will have been infected by 2000 , and 10 million will have died , according to WHO , co-sponsor of the summit with the French government .
Some French media pronounced the summit a failure even before it began .
The daily Liberation criticized the final declaration as `` banal , '' predicted that little new funding would materialize , and noted that senior U.S. , British or German leaders rebuffed summit invitations .
