Michel Saleh of Lebanon in a Toyota Celica swept into the lead in the Dubai International Rally on Thursday .
The first day of the two-day 1994 FIA Middle East Championship produced a double early blow and a quick exit for the two national stars , who had been expected to dominate the event .
Middle East champion Mohammed bin Sulayem of Dubai in a Ford Cosworth slipped five minutes off the pace while Sheik Suhail bin Khalifa al-Maktoum went out with mechanical problems .
At the end of four stages , Saleh led by 2 minutes and 12 seconds over Qatar 's Nasser Khalifa al-Attiyah in a Toyota , with Victory Rally Team 's Khalifa al-Mataywi in another Toyota Celica only two seconds back in third place .
Saleh completed the four stages in 29 minutes , 27 seconds .
Sharjah 's Sheik Abdullah al-Qassimi in a Mitsubish Galant , with 34:14 , held fourth place and Germany 's national champion Karl-Heinz Lerch in a Ford Cosworth was fifth at 34:24 .
Middle East Group N champion Abdullah Bakhashab of Saudi Arabia was sixth in his Toyota , two seconds behind .
British women 's national champion Stephanie Simmonite in a Volkswagon Golf was 11th in 43:32 .
The U.N. mediator for Angola was in Zaire Thursday trying to persuade UNITA rebel officials to return here for the first time in two years and help oversee a truce and power-sharing deal to end 19 years of war .
U.N. officials said Alioune Blondin Beye had left for Zaire late Wednesday , delaying a planned visit Thursday to New York where he was to brief the U.N. Security Council on the shaky 10-day-old truce .
Both UNITA and the government have accused each other of violating the cease-fire called Nov. 22 , two days after a peace treaty was signed in Lusaka , Zambia .
But there has been a general reduction in fighting across the war-ravaged nation and the U.N. mission here has deployed its first military observers to six sites .
A 7,000-strong U.N. peace keeping force has been promised to anchor the treaty that should lead to power sharing between government and rebels .
But blue helmeted troops will only be deployed once the truce is seen to be holding .
Angola 's war erupted on the eve of independence from Portugal in 1975 , has killed a half-million Angolans and left millions more threatened by starvation and disease .
Peace accords in 1991 brought a brief respite but UNITA lost multiparty elections a year later , cried foul and returned to war .
Beye , broker of the year-long talks in Lusaka that produced the accord , last week announced UNITA officials would return to Luanda for the first time since losing the elections .
But the rebels did not show , citing logistics difficulties .
Leaders of UNITA -- the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola -- have been on the run since their main base in the central city of Huambo fell to the government early November .
Rebel chief Jonas Savimbi has not been seen in public for months , prompting rumors he had been killed or wounded in a government attack , or that he was seriously ill and was being treated in Zaire or Morocco .
The U.N. mission in Angola has posted military observers in six cities : Uige , Huambo , Luena , Menongue , Saurimo and Lubango .
Government sources working closely with the U.N. mission say initial plans foresee deploying 7,450 blue helmeted peace keepers .
The largest contingents are to be posted in the war-torn north and center .
The central provinces of Huambo , Bie , Benguela and Cuanza-Sul will receive 2,000 peacekeepers , while Luanda and the north will get 1,800 , according to the plans .
The rebels ' former southern headquarters , Jamba , is also to be a peace keeping base , the sources said .
Guy Debord , an avant-garde essayist who influenced the upheavals of French society in the late 1960s , has committed suicide .
Town officials in the village of Champot where Debord lived announced an investigation Thursday into the suicide .
No details about how Debord took his life Wednesday were disclosed .
Little-known outside France , Debord denounced what he called `` the show-biz society '' and declared that performing arts should be based on powerful emotions , passions and sexual desire .
His ideas were influential among theoreticians and essayists who achieved prominence in the May 1968 student-led cultural revolt that shook French society .
Relief pitcher Mitch `` Wild Thing '' Williams is getting a new life in American Major League Baseball with the California Angels .
Williams has n't pitched since a disappointing stint with the Houston Astros ended in his release May 31 .
He was 1-4 with six saves and a 7.65 ERA in 25 appearances last season .
The Angels said Wednesday that Williams agreed to a non-guaranteed contract .
It calls for a base salary of dlrs 500,000 , with dlrs 2 million in performance bonuses .
Under his previous 3-year deal , he made dlrs 2.5 million in 1994 .
Williams , 30 , is best known for allowing a three-run , game-winning home run by Toronto 's Joe Carter 's in the sixth and final game of the 1993 World Series while pitching for the Philadelphia Phillies .
It was his last pitch for the Phillies , the team he helped win the NL East championship and league playoffs in 1993 with 43 saves .
He was traded to the Astros in the offseason .
Williams has a career big-league record of 44-55 in 592 appearances , three of them starts , with 192 saves and a 3.51 ERA .
He started his career with the Texas Rangers in 1986 and pitched three years for them before joining the Chicago Cubs in 1989 .
Ernesto Zedillo becomes president Thursday , promising profound political and legal reforms to match the market-opening that resulted in a free trade agreement with the United States and Canada .
The 42-year-old U.S.-trained economist caps an unlikely journey when he assumes the red , green and white presidential sash to start a six-year term as leader of this country of 90 million .
Military bands struck up martial waltzes and Mexican mariachi musicians got set for a huge street fiesta , as hundreds of soldiers and eight armored personnel carriers guarded the post-inaugural parade route .
Not all wanted to celebrate the national holiday declared for the occasion .
`` Out with Zedillo ! ''
and `` Zedillo No ! ''
more than 4,000 demonstrators , some of them with sticks and machetes , shouted in downtown Mexico City .
The protesters , mostly farmers in straw sombreros , raised banners of the leftist Democratic Revolution Party , traditionally the biggest opponent of 65 years of uninterrupted rule by the Institutional Revolutionary Party , or PRI .
But police did not intervene and the site of the protest was more than a mile from the ornate Chamber of Deputies .
Zedillo , his wife and five children headed in a slow-moving bus , followed by dozens of jogging and well-armed security agents to the chamber , where U.S. Vice President Al Gore , Cuba 's Fidel Castro and hundreds of others gathered .
Meanwhile , eight military bands trumpeted and marched about the Zocalo square while hundreds of police in crisp blue uniforms and white gloves stood attention as a graying Castro and others entered the chamber .
Zedillo , who shined shoes as a boy in Mexicali , achieved a Yale doctorate in economics .
Bypassed once for his party 's presidential nomination , he was thrust into the campaign by the March 23 assassination of Luis Donaldo Colosio , first choice of the ruling PRI .
He won the presidency Aug. 21 in the most credible elections ever held in Mexico , pledging to use the near-absolute powers of Mexico 's presidency to weaken his own office .
He says he will give greater independence to the congress , the courts and local governments and end the practice of having the president handpick all top PRI candidates .
Zedillo , former budget and planning minister under President Carlos Salinas de Gortari , signaled he would continue his predecessor 's free-market economic policies -- a commitment underlined by the Cabinet choices announced Wednesday .
Leading negotiators of the North American Free Trade Agreement were named heads of treasury , trade and foreign policy .
Seven other free-market economists also were named to the 25-person cabinet .
Gore , one of 63 foreign dignitaries attending , said 1994 brought `` unprecedented progress in the bilateral relationship between the United States and Mexico ... and we look forward to even greater improvement in the year ahead . '
Zedillo also showed signs of a political opening with the appointment of a conservative opposition party member , Antonio Lozano , as attorney general .
The post is crucial for Zedillo , who made fighting government corruption a major part of his campaign .
Lozano 's appointment marks the first time a Cabinet post has been given to an opposition party member , and it `` opens the possibility of an important change , '' said Carlos Castillo Pedraza , leader of the National Action Party .
Despite Zedillo 's moves , discontent remains .
A protest was planned today by leftist supporters of the Zapatista National Liberation Army rebels of southern Mexico .
That rebellion , stalled since January by a cease-fire , is one of the toughest problems unresolved .
Share prices were lower on the London Stock Exchange Thursday .
The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 41.8 points or 1.36 percent at 3039.6 .
The Financial Times 30-share index was down 22.6 points , or 0.96 percent , at 2340.2
Volume was 722.3 million shares , compared to 681.7 million shares Wednesday .
President Clinton will ask for an additional dlrs 25 billion for the military budget to help improve the readiness of forces and the quality of life for the troops , Pentagon officials said .
Clinton was slated to announce support for the increase at the White House later in the day , the officials said , speaking on condition of anonymity .
The money , which would have to be approved by the new Republican-controlled Congress , would help cover a dlrs 40 billion shortfall over five years that had been created by a congressionally required pay raise , and by inflation , the officials said .
`` It focuses , however , on the issue of readiness -- making sure the force is able to conduct and win the nation 's wars , '' one of the senior officials said .
The move is also expected to help Clinton quell Republican charges that the administration has , through its budget cuts , hurt the nation 's defense posture .
The Pentagon officials said it was unclear to them exactly where the administration hoped to glean the additional funds .
It comes just two weeks after the Army announced that due to operations in Rwanda , Haiti and elsewhere , had left three of the Army 's 12 divisions far below their peak readiness levels .
The new funds are expected to cover several initiatives that would also improve such things as housing and other quality-of-life programs , building on an recent announcement by Defense Secretary William Perry that more money would be put into such things , a second official said .
Perry and the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff , Gen. John Shalikashvili , were to be present for the announcement .
`` This means that there will be more flying hours for pilots , more steaming hours for ships , '' which helps the force remain ready to conduct combat operations at a moment 's notice , the second official said .
They said the announcement will not include decisions about potential weapons program cuts that were being pondered by Deputy Defense Secretary John Deutch , and that had been expected to be revealed this month .
Deutch had been looking at the potential for canceling , stretching out or cutting back 10 major weapons programs , including such things as the Air Force 's F-22 fighter jet , the Army 's Commance helicopter , the TSSAM Tri-service Standoff Attack Missile and the Marine 's AAAV Advanced Amphibious Assault Vehicle .
This year , the administration 's Pentagon 's fiscal 1995 budget amounted to dlrs 264 billion .
NATO asked Germany on Thursday to send fighter planes to patrol the skies over Bosnia in a mission that would place the German military in a combat role for the first time since World War II .
It will be a thorny decision for Chancellor Helmut Kohl and his aides , who have shied away from involvement in Bosnia-Herzegovina because of the history of Nazi atrocities in former Yugoslavia and anti-German sentiment among many Serbs .
But it will also be a difficult request for Germany to turn down because of Kohl 's repeated assertions that his nation , seeking more international influence , must bear its share of peacekeeping responsibilities .
One official said he assumed Kohl supported the mission or the request would n't have been made in the first place .
But support was n't clear in parliament , which would probably have to approve the mission with a simple majority .
Lt. Col. Joe Cato , spokesman for NATO 's European military headquarters in Casteau , Belgium , said that the Supreme Allied Commander in Europe `` has requested -LRB- that -RRB- the German armed forces provide some combat aircraft to support NATO air operations over parts of former Yugoslavia . ''
NATO requested German Tornado planes equipped with electronic gear that can locate and identify radar sites and rockets designed to destroy such sites , a German defense official said , speaking on background .
The Tornado planes could help prevent Serb attacks on NATO planes patroling Bosnia to enforce the U.N. humanitarian mission and also could protect supply flights to Sarajevo , the official said .
Supply flights to Sarajevo from Italy were broken off after Serbs fired missiles at two British Tornados last week .
German officials could not confirm a report in the weekly Rheinische Merkur newspaper that the NATO request came after Britain decided to withdraw its fighters from the Bosnia mission .
A July decision of Germany 's highest court gave the government the green light for the first time in the postwar era to engage in peacekeeping missions outside the NATO area .
But `` whether we ... should really choose former Yugoslavia as the place to step up our engagement is something I believe we should consider very carefully , '' Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said in Brussels , Belgium .
Kohl has said Germany can not send ground troops to former Yugoslavia because of the bitter memories over the hundreds of thousands of Serbs , Jews and others murdered by the German army and SS officers .
The opposition Social Democrats , in a statement , opposed any German combat mission in Bosnia , saying it would n't have a pacifying effect .
`` Every Serbian family mourns a victim of the Germans .
I have to ask whether it makes a difference if we 're on the ground or in the air , '' said Walter Kolbow , a defense expert for the party .
