Former National Basketball Association player Rolando Blackman has signed with AEK Athens after being released by the New York Knicks , the Greek club 's president said Thursday .
Blackman signed the one-year dlrs 400,000 contract in the United States last week and it was announced in Athens , Michalis Lefakis said .
The 1.98-meter -LRB- 6-foot-6 -RRB- shooting guard spent the last two seasons with the Knicks after 11 seasons with the Dallas Mavericks .
`` I did n't come here to end my career but to continue it ... I 'll try to be my team 's top scorer in every game , '' the 35-year-old player told reporters after his arrival in Athens Wednesday .
Blackman became a free agent in July when the Knicks declined to renew his contract .
He averaged a career-low 7.3 points in 55 games last season .
Over 13 seasons in the NBA he averaged 18.0 points .
AEK is 10th in the 14-team standings at 2-5 .
Olympiakos Piraeus is first with a 7-0 mark .
Long-time traditional rivals Corinthians and Sao Paulo get another chance to square off Friday -- in an all-Brazilian semifinal of the CONMEBOL Cup .
The rivalry has long stirred the passions of `` paulista '' fans : Corinthians , the favorite of the masses , versus Sao Paulo , considered the team of the elite .
Kickoff in Friday 's first leg of South America 's equivelent to the UEFA Cup , top clubs that did not qualify for the Copa Libertadores , is scheduled for 9 p.m. -LRB- 2300 GMT -RRB- at Pacaembu Stadium .
The winner of this series faces Penarol of Uruguay or Universidad of Chile in the final .
But the CONMEBOL Cup has taken a lesser importance to the Brazilian national championship , now in the quarterfinal phase .
Both teams played Wednesday night and face deciding games this weekend .
Sao Paulo , which just sold all-star forward Muller to Japan , has found its `` glue '' in midfielder Sierra .
The Chilean star is the team 's playmaker and field general , a position vacant since the departure of Rai to Paris-Saint Germain last year .
On Wednesday , Palhinha scored an 81st-minute goal to give Sao Paulo a 1-0 victory over Guarani in the opening game of their quarterfinal series .
The return match is Saturday .
Corinthians struggled to a 1-1 tie with Bragantino on Wednesday , with Tupazinho scoring the equalizer in the 94th minute .
The teams play again Sunday , with the winner advancing to the semifinals .
Neither coach announced his starting squad , although both were expected rest some key players for the weekend .
Corinthians : Ronaldo , Paulo Roberto , Pinga , Henrique , Branco , Ze Elias , Luisinho , Boiadeiro , Marcelinho , Viola , Marques .
Sao Paulo : Zetti , Pavao , Junior Baiano , Murilo , Andre , Axel , Alemao , Sierra , Cafu , Juninho , Ailton -LRB- Palhinha -RRB- .
Russia 's prisons are overcrowded and inhumane , with underfed inmates crammed into stinking , standing-room-only cells , a U.N. report said Thursday .
Conditions in pre-trial detention centers -- where first-time offenders accused of petty crimes can wait up to five years for a court appearance -- are even worse than labor camps for hardened convicts , the report said .
`` The oppressive heat , lack of oxygen , and the odors of sweat , excrement and disease created by gross overcrowding are overpowering , '' said Nigel Rodley , the U.N. 's special investigator on torture , who wrote the report .
At the invitation of the Russian government , Rodley spent two weeks visiting prisons near Moscow and St. Petersburg , including four pre-trial centers , two police headquarters , one labor camp , one juvenile center and one hospital for seriously ill prisoners .
The Russian government estimates there are 500,000 prisoners in about 528 prisons and penal colonies throughout the country .
Russia has the highest rate of detentions in the world .
Rodley said the skyrocketing crime rate following the end of communist control has worsened already serious overcrowding in prisons .
He criticized Russian authorities for responding to public concern about crime by throwing petty offenders into jail .
He called on President Boris Yeltsin to issue a presidential decree releasing 71,000 non-violent , first-time offenders to ease the overcrowding .
`` It 's a radical proposal because it 's a radical problem which needs to be addressed urgently , '' Rodley said at a news conference .
He said beatings and maltreatment were widespread .
`` The conditions are cruel , inhuman and degrading ; they are torturous , '' he wrote about cells in Moscow 's Butryskaya prison .
`` There is virtually no daylight .
There is insufficient room for everyone to lie down , sit down or even stand up at the same time . ''
Butryrskaya prison was constructed in 1771 .
Built for 3,500 prisoners , it now holds 6,300 .
`` The food , not always available because of the indebtedness of the institutions -- is primitive , of a fat-saturated soupy nature .
It is consumed in the cell and is excreted in the cell , '' the report said .
In another Moscow detention center , Matrosskaya Tishina No. 1 , conditions in quarantine cells for sick prisoners were atrocious .
`` Despite the fact that several of the inmates had open , festering sores , severe fungal infections with decaying flesh , and extensive rashes , they reported that they had not seen a doctor in over a week , '' Rodley wrote .
BRASILIA , Brazil -LRB- AP -RRB- - Financial markets rose Thursday after newspapers reported that Central Bank President Pedro Malan would be the new finance minister .
President-elect Fernando Henrique Cardoso , who takes office Jan. 1 , denied there had been a formal appointment .
But major Brazilian newspapers ran the story Thursday and reported the appointment as a done deed .
`` Malan is confirmed in Finance , '' read the headline in Rio 's Jornal do Brasil .
The daily Folha de Sao Paulo said the appointment was sealed at a meeting Wednesday night at Cardoso 's house in Brasilia , the capital .
The stock market in Sao Paulo , Brazil 's biggest city and financial center , rose 3.5 percent in Thursday morning trading before slipping back to a 2.2 percent rise at midday .
Malan , 51 , is a former director of the Interamerican Development Bank , Brazil 's delegate to the World Bank and the country 's chief negotiator with private foreign creditors .
More importantly , he helped to elaborate the anti-inflation plan that Cardoso enacted as finance minister , before quitting to run for the presidency .
The Real Plan , named for the dollar-pegged currency created on July 1 , cut inflation from 50 percent a month in June to 3 percent .
Its success gave Cardoso a first-ballot victory in the Oct. 3 election .
Cardoso has promised to maintain the plan 's guidelines , which include a balanced budget and reduced spending .
He also said he hoped to retain his economic advisers , whom he called `` geniuses . ''
Malan flew to Rio on Thursday and declined to confirm or deny his appointment .
But he admitted that he was a possible choice .
Pepsi-Cola International and its large Latin American bottling partner announced plans to invest more than dlrs 400 million to expand manufacturing and distribution capabilities and to market Pepsi-Cola products in Brazil .
Pepsi and Buenos Aires Embotelladora SA said the marketing effort began Thursday with the launch of a multi-media advertising campaign .
The two-year investment plan , which was started this year , involves three new bottling plants , in Sao Paulo , Rio de Janeiro and Porto Alegre .
Production already has started at the plants .
Additional facilities will be built elsewhere in southern Brazil in the near future , a news release said .
Pepsi 's emphasis on Brazil represents an effort to tap a market expected to have high potential for growth .
Brazil is ranked as the fourth largest soft drink market behind the United States , Mexico and Germany .
Authorities are investigating whether more than one inmate was involved in the bludgeoning death of serial killer Jeffrey Dahmer , according to a published report .
The Milwaukee Journal Thursday quoted an unidentified prison official as saying that `` surprising '' facts have yet to be disclosed and that the killer did not act alone .
He did not elaborate , the paper said .
Dahmer , who admitted to killing 17 young men and boys , died Monday after being found in a pool of blood in a gymnasium bathroom at the Columbia Correctional Institution .
He was assigned to clean the bathroom while on a work detail .
Another inmate , Jesse Anderson , died Wednesday of injuries he sustained the same morning .
The Journal quoted the source as saying that a conspiracy is n't thought to involve prison employees .
Rather , other inmates are being investigated , including two brought to the gym for a recreation period when the bodies were discovered , the source said .
Columbia County Sheriff James D. Smith said Wednesday that eight people were in the prison 's recreation area around the time of the attacks , including two guards , a recreation director and other inmates , and he had n't yet narrowed the list of suspects .
Dahmer died within minutes of receiving two major blows to the head , a coroner said Wednesday .
Dahmer probably was hit a total of four or five times in all , Columbia County Coroner C. Keith Epps said .
Dahmer , 34 , had confessed to killing 17 young men and boys , mutilating and sometimes cannibalizing or eating his victims .
He had been behind bars since July 1991 , when a handcuffed man escaped from him and led Milwaukee police to an apartment full of body parts .
Anderson , 37 , was sentenced to life in prison for killing his wife in August 1992 .
Dahmer was found in a pool of blood in a staff bathroom ; Anderson in a locker room adjoining a basketball court .
A bloody broom handle was found near Dahmer , but investigators have said his head might have been beaten against a wall or the floor .
He was n't pronounced dead until he was taken to a hospital .
Arsenal striker Paul Merson agreed Thursday to check into a rehabilitation clinic for treatment of his self-confessed cocaine habit .
Merson , 26 , admitted in a newspaper interview last week that he regularly spent 150 pounds -LRB- dlrs 230 -RRB- a night supporting his addiction .
He also said he had run up large gambling debts .
`` Paul Merson was very frank about those problems , '' English soccer officials said in a statement following a meeeting with the player .
`` They are considerable .
Taking drugs -- to which we are all bitterly opposed -- is only one of them , and arguably not the biggest .
In our view , a complex and unprecedented situation demands that the first priority must be rehabilitation . ''
The statement said Merson agreed to enter a clinic selected by the Football Association for a period of treatment of at least six weeks .
He will not be allowed to play during that time .
Following treatment , he will be subject to monitoring and random tests for up to 18 months .
When he returns to soccer will depend on the agreement of medical specialists , FA officials and Arsenal .
A rebel Serb assembly that met Thursday was expected to endorse an economic agreement with Croatia despite two days of artillery duels between the two sides .
Croatia 's army and Serbs lobbed artillery shells at each other most of the past two days , said U.N. spokesman Paul Risley .
The two sides have had thousands of skirmishes and larger confronations since ending their 7-month war with an uneasy , U.N.-patrolled truce in January 1992 .
On Wednesday , the Croatian army fired 33 shells at Serb-held territory over a six-hour period , U.N. spokesman Alexander Ivanko said .
Artillery duels continued Thursday in the same locations close to Knin , Risley said .
Reporters in the nearby Croatian port of Split saw unusual activity by Croatian army helicopters .
Negotiations between the two sides have been stalled , but the Serbs ' self-styled government late Wednesday recommended that the assembly meeting in this Croatian Serb stronghold approve the deal .
If accepted , it would be the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their seven-month war in 1991 .
The draft agreement under discussion at the closed-door Knin meeting calls for restoration of water and electricity supply and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital Belgrade .
Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220 mile -RRB- highway are controlled by Croatian Serbs .
The deal , supported by powerful Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic and drafted with the help of international negotiators , was viewed as a possible step toward the gradual reintegration of the Serb Krajina region into Croatia .
Croatian Serb leaders rejected the economic accord two weeks ago .
Now , after meeting Milosevic , they have dropped those objections .
However , the session started amid fresh threats of possible new warfare between Croatia and rebel Serbs .
Croatia is chafing at Serb control over one-third of its territory , and holds out the option of taking the territory back by force .
And Croatian officials warned they were ready to intervene in the Bihac pocket in northwestern Bosnia when rebel Serbs from Croatia crossed the border to fight Bosnia 's Muslim-led army .
They say the fighting proves that Croats must look out for their own security .
Nevertheless , officials in Knin seemed in a positive mood .
`` I expect the assembly to approve the agreement , '' Milan Babic , the Croatian Serb `` foreign minister '' told reporters before the session .
He said that `` economic relations will not prejudge political solution . ''
U.N. sources in Knin said that Borislav Mikelic , the rebel Serb prime minister , was expected to sign the agreement at a local U.N. headquarters on Friday .
Croatian officials refused to sign the agreement Thursday because the first Yugoslavia , called The Kingdom of the Serbs , Croats and Slovenes , was formed Dec. 1 , 1918 .
The Croats are expected to sign at U.N. headquarters in Zagreb , the Croatian capital , on Friday .
Croatian authorities , who reject any reminder of former Yugoslavia , have already endorsed the agreement .
Thousands of peacekeepers have been deployed between the warring sides in the disputed territories since a tenuous cease-fire was reached in January 1992 .
But international efforts toward lasting peace have failed over what seemed to be irreconcilable differences .
Gasoline prices and the salaries of government workers will go up by 20 percent , the military government said Thursday .
A statement said the government had been subsidizing pump prices of fuel despite increased prices on the international market .
`` Regrettably , this situation is no longer tenable , especially when the government needs to generate optimum resources to pursue the rebel war , '' the statement explained .
Last week , the government launched a huge offensive against southern-based rebels who have been fighting to overthrow the government since 1992 .
Gasoline goes up by 20 percent to 1,650 leones -LRB- dlrs 2.75 -RRB- a gallon -LRB- 3.8 liters -RRB- immediately , while government workers will get pay rises from January .
President Hafez Assad on Thursday again held Israel responsible for the deadlock in peace talks with Syria .
Speaking in a joint news conference after talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak , Assad said `` the situation of peace talks on the Syrian track is still unchanged and no progress has been made . ''
The Syrian leader said Israel was `` making demands that Syria can never accept . ''
He did not specify the demands .
Mubarak 's visit came a few days ahead of a scheduled trip to the region by U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher , his sixth this year in an effort to break the deadlock in the Syrian-Israeli negotiations .
These have been stalled since February over Syria 's demand that Israel declare its willingness to make a complete withdrawal from the Golan Heights .
Israel captured the strategic plateau in southwestern Syria in the 1967 Middle East war and annexed it in 1981 .
Israel has so far only offered a partial withdrawal phased over several years .
Damascus has rejected that .
In reply to a question , Assad denied that `` any side has discussed with Syria the question of deploying U.S. forces in the Golan . ''
President Clinton assured Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin last month that he would consider sending U.S. troops to the Golan as part of an international peacekeeping force .
Egyptian sources , speaking on condition of anonymity , said Mubarak had been expected to brief Assad on the outcome of his recent tour of European capitals , where he sought financial aid for the Palestinian National Authority .
Mubarak flew back to Egypt after the news conference .
The U.N. mediator for Angola was in Zaire Thursday trying to persuade UNITA rebel officials to return here for the first time in two years and help oversee a truce and power-sharing deal to end 19 years of war .
U.N. officials said Alioune Blondin Beye had left for Zaire late Wednesday , delaying a planned visit Thursday to New York where he was to brief the U.N. Security Council on the shaky 10-day-old truce .
Both UNITA and the government have accused each other of violating the cease-fire called Nov. 22 , two days after a peace treaty was signed in Lusaka , Zambia .
But there has been a general reduction in fighting across the war-ravaged nation and the U.N. mission here has deployed its first military observers to six sites .
A 7,000-strong U.N. peace keeping force has been promised to anchor the treaty that should lead to power sharing between government and rebels .
But blue helmeted troops will only be deployed once the truce is seen to be holding .
Angola 's war erupted on the eve of independence from Portugal in 1975 , has killed a half-million Angolans and left millions more threatened by starvation and disease .
Peace accords in 1991 brought a brief respite but UNITA lost multiparty elections a year later , cried foul and returned to war .
Beye , broker of the year-long talks in Lusaka that produced the accord , last week announced UNITA officials would return to Luanda for the first time since losing the elections .
But the rebels did not show , citing logistics difficulties .
Leaders of UNITA - the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola - have been on the run since their main base in the central city of Huambo fell to the government early November .
Rebel chief Jonas Savimbi has not been seen in public for months , prompting rumors he had been killed or wounded in a government attack , or that he was seriously ill and was being treated in Zaire or Morocco .
The U.N. mission in Angola has posted military observers in six cities : Uige , Huambo , Luena , Menongue , Saurimo and Lubango .
Government sources working closely with the U.N. mission say initial plans foresee deploying 7,450 blue helmeted peace keepers .
The largest contingents are to be posted in the war-torn north and center .
The central provinces of Huambo , Bie , Benguela and Cuanza-Sul will receive 2,000 peacekeepers , while Luanda and the north will get 1,800 , according to the plans .
The rebels ' former southern headquarters , Jamba , is also to be a peace keeping base , the sources said .
Yasser Arafat 's government on Thursday took control of the health and taxation systems in the West Bank , broadening Palestinian autonomy despite a pall cast on peacemaking by a series of Islamic terror attacks .
The move completed the initial stage of handing over day-to-day affairs in the West Bank to Palestinians .
It also came amid growing calls in Israel for shutting off Palestinians from Israel because of a series of attacks in which 32 Israelis have been killed since early October .
About 1,000 people gathered Thursday in the northern Israeli town of Afula for the funeral of the latest victim , 19-year-old woman soldier Liat Gabai , who was axed to death on Wednesday .
A suspect detained Wednesday , Wahib Abu Rub , 24 , from the West Bank town of Qabatiyah , has told interrogators he was from the Islamic Resistance Movement or Hamas , Israel radio said .
The same group claimed the Oct. 19 Tel Aviv bus bombing that killed 22 people .
`` I killed the soldier , '' Abu Rub confessed on Israel television , as he was led by police to a West Bank court Thursday .
Police Minister Moshe Shahal responded by calling Thursday for completely shutting off the West Bank and Gaza Strip from Israel .
`` There is no alternative other than to demand separation , '' Shahal said .
`` Separation means that we do not have to open the territory out of economic and employment concerns until the Palestinians prove that they can prevent attacks . ''
A closure could also bring further violence , by preventing thousands of Palestinian day workers from entering Israel to earn a living .
Palestinian and Israeli leaders have blamed growing support for Islamic radicals on economic troubles in the PLO-run Gaza Strip .
Despite the violence , talks were expected to begin next week on stage two of the autonomy given Gaza and the West Bank town of Jericho last May -- redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank and Palestinian elections .
Israel 's concern for the safety of 120,000 Jewish settlers has prompted some officials to propose skipping the interim phase altogether and negotiating the final status of these territories now , rather than in 1996 .
Still , a gradual hand over of responsibilities to Palestinians proceeded in the West Bank where two ceremonies were held marking the transfer of the health and tax systems .
The PLO has since August also taken charge of education , tourism and welfare in the West Bank .
`` What we have completed gives the Palestinians a first entrance to the West Bank , '' said West Bank military governor Brig. Gen. Gadi Zohar , signing over the tax department to Palestinian Finance Minister Mohammed Nashashibi in Ramallah .
In Brussels , foreign donors this week released dlrs 125 million pledged earlier , mostly to help the Palestinians meet running costs for a few months .
Deputy Finance Minister Atef Alawneh said he hoped to collect dlrs 300-400 million annually in taxes , and remarked , `` we can not depend for the rest of our lives on the donor countries and the foreign investors in building our Palestinian state . ''
George Rishmawi , a Beit Zahour textile factory owner , once jailed by Israel for boycotting military government taxes was hopeful about what he called the start of `` a new era .
We have paid the Israelis enough .
They ripped us off .
They were thieves with licenses . ''
Egypt wants to buy 12 more Apache helicopters from McDonnell Douglas Helicopter Systems here in a deal valued at dlrs 318 million , federal officials said .
The Pentagon notified Congress on Wednesday of Egypt 's request .
Lawmakers have about a month after convening in January to approve the proposed sale .
If there are no objections from Congress , negotiations would begin between the U.S. Army and Egypt on the final price and delivery dates .
The Army is responsible for the sale of Apaches to foreign governments under U.S. foreign military-sales regulations .
This is Egypt 's second Apache order .
The country has taken delivery of all 24 Apaches ordered in January 1990 .
A total of 104 Apaches , which are the U.S. Army 's main attack helicopter , have been sold to Egypt , Saudi Arabia , United Arab Emirates , Israel and Greece .
Navjot Sidhu and Sachin Tendulkar combined for a 177-run partnership and helped India establish a comfortable 230 for four Thursday , the opening day of the second test against the West Indies which was marred by a rock - and bottle-throwing crowd .
The match was stopped twice -- for a total of one hour -- as West Indies skipper Courtney Walsh took his team off the field in the face of flying soft drink bottles , fruit and rocks .
Referee Raman Subba Row blamed the local authorities for poor crowd control .
Police later ringed the field .
It was not immediately clear why the crowd became irate .
`` We are lucky that no one was seriously hurt , '' Row said .
Stuart Williams was hit before lunch , while Phil Simmons at deep extra cover region was hit with a piece of fruit just after tea .
In the morning , India , which won the opener of the three-test series , won the toss and opted to bat .
Sidhu scored his sixth test century , including 17 fours , and Tendulkar added an unbeaten 81 in sharing a three-hour third-wicket stand .
Sidhu was out for 107 offering a simple catch to wicketkeeper Murray off Carl Hooper .
Tendulkar had a dozen boundaries off 155 balls in just over three hours .
Venkatapathy Raju came in to bat as the night watchman after Sidhu was sent to the stands , but he could not stay long and fell to paceman Walsh caught by Brian Adams for two .
Off-spinner Hooper struck as soon as he pressed into the attack .
Bowling a good line and turning the ball just enough to beat the bat , he dislodged Manoj Prabhakar and Vinod Kambli in quick succession .
Ernesto Zedillo , a mild-mannered economist whose rise to power capped a tragic and tumultous year of rebellion and political assassination , was sworn in Thursday as the 63rd president of Mexico .
`` I assume the duties of president with honor , '' said Zedillo after taking up the red-green-and-white presidential sash in a ceremony before 1,500 Mexican and foreign leaders at the ornate Chamber of Deputies .
Zedillo vowed that the Mexican army will maintain the cease-fire in Chiapas state , where Indian rebels are threatening to resume fighting that erupted Jan. 1 at a cost of more than 145 lives .
`` The Mexican army will unilateraly maintain the cease-fire , '' promised Zedillo , wearing a dark suit and silk tie in his first address to the nation .
`` There will not be violence in Chiapas . ''
He added that he hoped the guerrilla fighters would not renew their violent campaign , saying Mexico must unite in a common fight to eradicate the poverty that sowed rebellion and open a dialogue for peace .
Zedillo promised to launch a war on poverty that would bring greater prosperity to millions of his 90 million compatriots untouched by the free-trade economic reforms of his predecessor .
Former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari , who negotiated the North American Free Trade Agreement with the United States and Canada , was loudly applauded as Zedillo paid him tribute .
`` Carlos Salinas de Gortari will always have my gratitude and the appreciation of the people of Mexico , '' said Zedillo after taking up the presidential sash , which he will hold through the end of the century .
`` Mexico has prospered and our fathers achieved great advances .
But those are n't enough .
Millions of Mexicans are lacking the basics .
Millions live on the margin , millions live in undignified poverty , '' said Zedillo .
Outside the hall where Zedillo spoke , military bands struck up martial waltzes and Mexican mariachi musicians warmed up a huge street fiesta on the parade route to the National Palace , festive in red and green bunting .
Hundreds of soldiers and eight armored personnel carriers guarded the route on a national holiday when not all wanted to celebrated .
`` Out with Zedillo ! ''
and `` Zedillo No ! ''
more than 4,000 anti-government demonstrators shouted , some of them brandishing sticks and machetes , during a protest a mile away in downtown Mexico City .
The protesters , mostly farmers in straw sombreros , raised banners of the leftist Democratic Revolution Party , a vocal opponent of Mexico 's dominant rule by the Institutional Revolutionary Party .
But police did not intervene .
U.S. Vice President Al Gore , one of 63 foreign dignitaries attending , said 1994 brought `` unprecedented progress in the bilateral relationship between the United States and Mexico ... and we look forward to even greater improvement in the year ahead . '
Cuba 's Fidel Castro also was on hand along with most Latin American leaders , inspiring a protest by about 50 opponents of his Communist government .
Zedillo has promised to further the economic reforms of Salinas , who negotiated NAFTA , sold off hundreds of money-losing state businesses , and turned the economy around from an inflationary crisis of the 1980s .
Zedillo , a former Mexicali shoeshine boy achieved a Yale doctorate in economics .
Bypassed once for his party 's presidential nomination , he was thrust into the campaign by the March 23 assassination of Luis Donaldo Colosio , first choice of the Institutional Revolutionary Party , or PRI .
He won the presidency Aug. 21 in the most credible elections ever held in Mexico , pledging to use the near-absolute powers of Mexico 's presidency to weaken his own office and give his own party greater independence .
`` As president I will not intervene in the affairs of the PRI , '' he said of his party , which has governed for 65 years .
Zedillo also said he will give greater independence to the congress , the courts and local governments and end the practice of having the president handpick all top PRI candidates .
Zedillo , former budget and planning minister under Salinas , signaled he would further free-market polices by his Cabinet choices announced Wednesday .
Mexico 's leading negotiators of NAFTA were named heads of treasury , trade and foreign policy .
Seven other free-market economists also were named to the 25-person cabinet .
President Clinton on Thursday proposed spending dlrs 25 billion more for the military to help improve the readiness and working conditions of U.S. forces around the world .
Flanked by the nation 's top military officers , Clinton announced support for the increase which would be spread over five years .
The proposal will be presented to the new Republican-controlled Congress next year .
Republicans have promised to increase defense spending while cutting back on other programs .
`` I have pledged that throughout the life of this administration our military will remain the best trained , best equipped , the best fighting force on earth , '' Clinton said at the White House .
`` We ask much of our military and we owe much to them , '' Clinton said .
The president disputed a suggestion that his request for additional Pentagon spending was an acknowledgement that he had cut too much last year .
He said the request was because of unanticipated deployments to the Persian Gulf , Haiti and elsewhere .
The money would help cover a dlrs 40 billion shortfall over five years that had been created by a congressionally required pay raise , and by inflation , the officials said .
The move is also expected to help Clinton quell Republican charges that the administration has , through its budget cuts , hurt the nation 's defense posture .
Pentagon officials said it was unclear to them exactly where the administration hoped to glean the additional funds .
The announcement came just two weeks after the Army announced that due to operations in Rwanda , Haiti and elsewhere , had left three of the Army 's 12 divisions far below their peak readiness levels .
The new funds are expected to cover several initiatives that would also improve such things as housing and other quality-of-life programs , building on an recent announcement by Defense Secretary William Perry that more money would be put into such things , a second official said .
Perry and the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff , Gen. John Shalikashvili , were to be present for the announcement .
`` This means that there will be more flying hours for pilots , more steaming hours for ships , '' which helps the force remain ready to conduct combat operations at a moment 's notice , a Pentagon official said , speaking on condition of anonymity .
Officials said the announcement does not cover decisions about potential weapons program cuts that were being pondered by Deputy Defense Secretary John Deutch , and that had been expected to be revealed this month .
Deutch had been looking at the potential for canceling , stretching out or cutting back 10 major weapons programs , including such things as the Air Force 's F-22 fighter jet , the Army 's Commance helicopter , the TSSAM Tri-service Standoff Attack Missile and the Marine 's AAAV Advanced Amphibious Assault Vehicle .
This year , the administration 's Pentagon 's fiscal 1995 budget amounted to dlrs 264 billion .
