Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev said Thursday the ministry 's central office and general staff will be trimmed , but not by 30 percent as reported earlier .
Grachev said the number of deputy defense ministers would be reduced , and several other areas of the ministry 's infrastrure would be reorganized , according to the Interfax news agency .
The cuts will take place in the near future , `` but not by 30 percent as the mass media reported earlier , '' Grachev was quoted as saying .
According to newspaper reports last week , President Boris Yeltsin has drafted a decree ordering deep cuts in the defense ministry 's central office .
The draft decree has received preliminary approval of the Cabinet and Yeltsin 's Security Council , the daily Nezavisimaya Gazeta reported Tuesday , quoting well-informed sources .
Yeltsin has already ordered cuts in the army rank and file .
The army , which numbered 3.7 million men during the Cold War , is down to 1.9 million and is scheduled to gradually hit 1.5 million .
Grachev said the reductions in the central office will be carried out by uniting several departments of the Defense Ministry and other `` organizational rearrangements '' to prevent duplication of labor .
French petroleum group Total signed a three-year , dlrs 1 billion contract Thursday with China 's Sinochem on cross sales of petroleum and chemical products like resins , inks , adhesives and paints .
Michel Chevet , Total 's representative in China , also stated that Total signed a frame contract to supply crude oil to Unipec , a joint subsidiary of Sinochem and Sinopec of China .
The supplies in 1995 will be 60,000 barrels per day .
Total meanwhile entered into a memorandum of understanding with the city of Dalian indicating its full backing for an oil terminal project in which Total will hold 24 percent .
The terminal will be able to receive crude oil from the Middle East and supply a nearby refinery in which Total has a 20 percent stake .
It involves an overall investment of dlrs 100 million .
Start-up is expected during 1995 , with Total to supply 50 percent of the crude oil requirements and receive 50 percent of the export products .
The joint venture involves Sinochem , the Ministry of Chemical Industry and two Chinese municipalities .
