U.S. agricultural exports are expected to hit a record dlrs 45 billion in 1995 , an increase of dlrs 1.5 billion over this year , the U.S. Agriculture Department says .
If this estimate holds , the total would top the previous record of dlrs 43.8 billion in 1981 .
Although the new General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade pact is not cited as a cause , the world trade accord has been promoted as a boost to future U.S. agricultural exports .
A report by the House Ways and Means Committee said exports could be as much as dlrs 8.5 billion higher by the time GATT is fully implemented in 2005 .
USDA estimates that agricultural imports for the upcoming year also will set a record , at dlrs 28 billion , up dlrs 1.6 billion from 1994 .
That makes the projected agricultural trade surplus dlrs 17 billion for 1995 .
Wheat and coarse grain exports are expected to rise 13 percent in volume .
However , due to expected lower prices for corn , the overall value of grain exports is forecast to increase only 8 percent .
Prices for wheat are expected to stay strong through next year , according to the USDA forecast .
Soybean exports will also mark a gain in volume , up 28 percent from 1994 , although low prices again will hold down value , it says .
Other high-value products -- including fruit , vegetables , red meat and poultry -- also are seen making export gains in 1995 .
A bid to salvage the near-bankrupt airline Iberia was stalled Thursday after overnight talks between management and the powerful pilots union ended in a stalemate over pay cuts .
Management and representatives of the carrier 's two main unions had reached a tentative agreement Tuesday on a viability plan that entailed a wage freeze , salary cuts averaging 8.5 percent and a reduction of some 3,500 jobs through early retirements and pay-offs .
The viability plan is considered crucial if the European Commission is to consider allowing the Spanish government to grant Iberia a 130 billion peseta -LRB- dlrs 1 billion -RRB- capital injection .
However , a similar plan to bailout out Air France faces a court challenge .
Management of the state-owned company held talks Thursday with all of its unions -- except the pilots .
The pilots union , meanwhile , said it would meet Friday with rank-and-file to evaluate the situation .
It was not immediately clear whether the lack of an across-the-board agreement meant a much more drastic plan touted last week by Iberia -- involving 5,200 job cuts and the sale of company assets -- might be implemented .
That proposal triggered an one-day wildcat strike on Monday that paralyzed Spain 's airports and affected more than 100,000 travelers here and abroad .
The wildcat action apparently prompted unions to cancel a strike called several weeks ago for Friday .
Airline officials said flights would operate normally .
Negotiations with the pilots reached a dead end as Iberia demanded a salary reduction of 15 percent based on 1992 earnings .
The pilots insisted that an existing wage agreement through 1995 must be implemented before the 15 percent salary cut could be enforced .
`` The company has presented a generic plan that does not guarantee the future of Iberia and only concentrates on disproportionate salary cuts , '' said Armando Guajardo of the pilots union SEPLA .
`` Management has let the situation rot to such an extent so that it could enforce such a plan worked out in advance , '' he said .
SEPLA said the company needed a complete overhaul and not just a reduction in salaries and staff .
He said SEPLA had sent a letter to Iberia warning of drastic action by the pilots if the current wage agreement was broken .
Pilots represent some 5 percent of the 24,000-strong staff .
Salas has warned that the company would be technically bankrupt by March 1995 .
Iberia has posted losses since 1990 .
It ended last year 67 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 530 million -RRB- in the red while losses for this year are expected to top 40 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 300 million -RRB- .
President Clinton pledged Thursday to seek a dlrs 25 billion increase in military spending over the next six years to improve the living conditions and readiness of U.S. troops around the world .
Flanked by Defense Secretary William Perry and the Joint Chiefs of Staff , Clinton also said he would ask Congress for an emergency increase in this year 's defense budget to pay for unanticipated military deployments .
The measures would be presented to the new Republican-controlled Congress next year .
Republicans have called for increased defense spending .
`` I have pledged that throughout the life of this administration our military will remain the best trained , best equipped , the best fighting force on earth , '' Clinton said at a White House announcement .
`` We ask much of our military and we owe much to them . ''
Clinton disputed a suggestion that his request for additional Pentagon spending was an acknowledgement that he had cut too much last year .
He said the request was mostly because of unanticipated deployments to the Persian Gulf , Haiti and elsewhere .
`` We have seen the military having to deal with an amazing variety of challenges , '' Clinton said .
Clinton did not say how much extra money he would request for the Pentagon this year .
Without some increase , he said , the Pentagon would have to curtail training and find cuts elsewhere .
The dlrs 25 billion in additional spending beginning next year is designed to cover a projected dlrs 40 billion shortfall over five years that had been created by a congressionally required pay raise , and by inflation .
This fiscal year 's Pentagon 's budget was dlrs 264 billion .
Congressional Republicans have criticized Clinton for defense cuts they say have eroded military readiness , and the House Republican agenda proposes a dlrs 60 billion increase in defense spending .
Clinton 's announcement was an effort to answer the criticism and counter the Republican budget proposal .
The president also seemed determined to answer Republican Sen. Jesse Helms ' recent suggestion that he was not fit to be commander in chief .
In announcing his new spending initiative , Clinton rattled off a list of military actions he has ordered as president , including use of troops to help restore Haiti 's democracy and deployment of U.S. forces to Kuwait to counter an Iraqi troop buildup along the Iraq-Kuwait border .
`` Saddam Hussein got the message , '' Clinton said .
And in a holiday season reassurance to U.S. troops , Clinton guaranteed they will receive pay increases approved by Congress .
The amount of the increase is tied to inflation ; the last raise was about 2 percent .
Clinton said the increased spending next year and beyond would provide other `` quality of life '' improvements for U.S. forces and their families , including better housing , child care and family support services .
Clinton 's announcement came just two weeks after the Army announced that three of its 12 divisions had fallen below peak readiness levels because money that would have gone to training exercises had been diverted to pay for operations in Rwanda , Haiti and elsewhere .
Clinton said nothing about potential weapons program cuts being pondered by Deputy Defense Secretary John Deutch .
Deutch has been looking at the potential for canceling , stretching out or cutting back 10 major weapons programs , including such things as the Air Force 's F-22 fighter jet , the Army 's Commance helicopter , the TSSAM Tri-service Standoff Attack Missile and the Marine 's AAAV Advanced Amphibious Assault Vehicle .
Serb fighters kidnapped more U.N. peacekeepers and pressed the stranglehold on the `` safe area '' of Bihac Thursday , underscoring their contempt for U.N. authority in Bosnia .
The Bosnian Serbs did , however , agree to meet Yasushi Akashi , the top U.N. envoy , on Friday in Pale , their stronghold east of Sarajevo .
They had refused to meet U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali on Wednesday because he insisted talks be held in Sarajevo , capital of the internationally recognized government of Bosnia-Herzegovina .
They agreed to the Akashi meeting after Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose , the U.N. commander in Bosnia , traveled to Pale for talks with Radovan Karadzic and other Bosnian Serb leaders .
In addition to trying to calm the Bihac front , Rose is also concerned about the fate of more than 400 of his soldiers being held hostage by the Serbs as insurance against further NATO airstrikes .
Alexander Ivanko , a U.N. spokesman , said the latest kidnappings occurred Tuesday when Bosnian Serb units crossed the border into Croatia and seized seven Ukrainian peacekeepers .
They took the soldiers and a U.N. armored carrier into Bosnian Serb-held territory , and the United Nations has not heard from its troops since .
The Ukrainians ' observation point is now occupied by the Serbs , allowing for the unimpeded movement into Bosnia of equipment and personnel from Serb-held Croatia .
Serb fighters from the two countries have joined forces in the Bihac offensive .
Rose 's talks in Pale were to have focused on Bihac and its demilitarization .
But there appeared to be no narrowing of differences that could end the siege .
Momcilo Krajisnik , leader of the so-called Bosnian Serb assembly , again rejected a three-month cease-fire , which the Bosnian government wants , saying Serbs would accept only a permanent cease-fire , leading to a formal end of war .
The Sarajevo government fears any permanent cease-fire agreement would cement Serb territorial gains of 70 percent .
An international peace plan , which the Bosnians have accepted and the Serbs rejected , would force Serbs to settle for 49 percent of the country .
With new U.S. support for Europe 's position that diplomacy , not further NATO airstrikes , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian war , French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and his British counterpart , Douglas Hurd , planned to meet Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade Sunday .
Milosevic is considered responsible for the violent breakup of Yugoslavia .
But he continues to wield the power , including with the Bosnian Serbs , with whom he allegedly broke ties last summer after they again rejected the international peace plan .
Senior Western officials now talk of altering that plan to allow the Bosnian Serbs confederal links with Yugoslavia , a right the plan already gives Bosnian Croats with Croatia .
Critics say that is appeasement and a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal , a Greater Serbia .
But Krajisnik said possible linkage with Yugoslavia was not as important as changing the proposed territorial maps , the Bosnian Serb news agency SRNA reported .
Continuing the squeeze on the Bosnian government , Serbs again denied U.N. requests to supply the Bihac enclave and other vulnerable U.N.-patrolled sites with food and supplies .
Monique Tuffelli , the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees staffer in the Bihac enclave , said food stocks would last only another week .
`` We have run out almost of everything , '' she said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press .
The last UNHCR food convoy reached Bihac on Oct. 1 .
Between May and October , Serbs allowed only a dozen to pass through their territory .
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said food and fuel supplies for peacekeepers were running increasingly short in the government-held eastern Bosnian enclaves , as well as Bihac .
Heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire erupted around Bihac late Wednesday and early Thursday , along with heavy fighting southwest and south of the Bihac pocket , U.N. officials said .
Two civilians were killed in Bihac Wednesday by gunfire , Ms. Tuffelli said , but overall the area was calmer Thursday morning with only sporadic shelling and small arms fire .
Bosnian radio and Bihac regional officials painted a different picture by Thursday afternoon .
Radio said Serbs intensified their attacks later in the day on Bihac , Cazin and Velika Kladusa , all government-held towns in the Bihac enclave .
Hamdija Kabiljagic , the regional mayor , also reported increased fighting along the perimeters of Bihac and shelling of the town itself .
He accused the United Nations of deliberately downplaying the situation .
There was no U.N. confirmation of the reported afternoon upsurge in fighting .
In downtown Sarajevo , Serbs targeted two government buildings with anti-tank missiles , wounding four people .
Sarajevo 's airport remained closed , and the humanitarian airlift suspended , because Serbs had not given security guarantees and are able to threaten planes ' approach route with surface-to-air missiles .
NATO on Thursday moved closer than ever to admitting its former Warsaw Pact adversaries into the alliance by ordering aides to set out the criteria for membership in the years ahead .
But , in an extraordinary session , Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev strongly criticized the alliance for going ahead with its plans for expansion .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told grim-faced group of foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
The Russian had been invited to the allies ' meeting to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow .
The special ties had been put together to try to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
Moscow backed off from a threat to send troops Thursday into the breakaway Chechnya republic , where leaders defied a Russian ultimatum and called on armed volunteers to defend their capital .
Air attacks continued on the outskirts of Grozny , the Chechen capital , and a Russian delegation arrived from Moscow and began talks with Chechen officials .
Meanwhile , residents continued to flee the mainly Muslim city of 300,000 people in the Caucasus Mountains of southern Russia .
The city has become a war zone between forces loyal to Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , who declared independence from Moscow in 1991 , and Chechen rebels trying to topple him .
Dudayev accuses Moscow of arming and leading the rebels , who launched an offensive last week that began with helicopters and escalated in recent days to jet fighters .
Russia says it offers the rebels only political support .
It refuses to recognize independence for Chechnya , which was incorporated into the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
President Boris Yeltsin threatened on Tuesday to impose a state of emergency in Chechnya if both sides did not surrender prisoners and stop fighting by Thursday morning .
On Thursday evening , Yeltsin 's office issued an altered text of the ultimatum saying `` there was some disagreement in the media in interpreting certain clauses . ''
The reissued document skipped all reference to a state of emergency .
Trying a different tack , Yeltsin offered limited amnesty Thursday to Chechens who `` voluntarily lay down arms by Dec. 15 . ''
`` The use of force in Chechnya is doomed to failure , '' said Sergei Yushenkov , head of the Russian parliament 's Defense Committee , who led the delegation to Grozny and met briefly with Dudayev , according to an aide in Moscow .
In another sign that Russia sought to avoid direct confrontation , Defense Minister Pavel Grachev told reporters in Moscow that some Russian servicemen who `` carried out certain military tasks for material compensation '' from anti-Dudayev forces had been brought back to central Russia .
He said more would be evacuated .
Grachev insisted such servicemen were volunteers who were not in Chechnya on Army orders .
Dudayev 's government captured up to 70 Russians in fighting last weekend and alleges that some were Army officers and soldiers .
Chechen officials initially threatened to execute them ; Dudayev said Thursday they would be tried in court .
Despite Moscow 's softened tone , it still appeared to be beefing up troops on the borders of Chechnya , according to media reports .
Dudayev , who held a news conference in the basement of his presidential palace as jets roared overhead , remained defiant , calling Yeltsin 's government a `` satanic power . ''
Looking tired under neon lights , Dudayev said his house had been bombed Thursday morning after the deadline on Yeltsin 's ultimatum passed .
A small military air base near Grozny also was hit in an air raid Thursday and a woman 's corpse was seen .
The ITAR-Tass news agency said two women were killed and fuel depots were burning .
Opposition air raids on the two previous days destroyed aircraft at military and civilian airports .
In Freedom Square outside Dudayev 's offices , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches while a tank maneuvered into position .
Elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
Grozny 's central bazaar , once thronged , was nearly empty .
Although life has gotten tougher and the economy is in shambles , many Chechens feel united in one thing : distrust of Russia .
`` I do n't like the opposition or Dudayev , but I 'll fight the Russians , '' said a restaurant owner who refused to give his name .
Many Russians are content to let the Chechens go their own way , according to a poll Thursday by the International Opinion Research Center .
The poll of 3,250 said 74.2 percent said Russia should recognize Chechnya 's independence , while 5.5 percent said it should n't and 20.3 said they could n't answer .
The firm said the poll 's margin of error was 1 percent .
