The poll of 3,250 said 74.2 percent said Russia should recognize Chechnya 's independence , while 5.5 percent said it should n't and 20.3 said they could n't answer .
The firm said the poll 's margin of error was 1 percent .
An 82-year-old man who guarded his garden shed with a shotgun was ordered Thursday to pay 3,633 pounds -LRB- dlrs 5,704 -RRB- to a burglar he wounded .
Six years ago Ted Newbury of Ilkeston , central England , fired a 12-gauge shotgun from about five feet -LRB- 1.5 m -RRB- away at Mark Revill , 27 , tearing a hole in his right arm and injuring his chest .
Doctors said Revill , 27 , can not straighten his fingers , had lost some feeling in his hand and still had pain in his chest .
`` To fire a gun when you have no idea who is there is a highly dangerous thing to do , '' Justice Richard Rougier told Newbury , a retired hospital porter .
`` To poke a shotgun through a hole and fire it with the knowledge that there are people outside constitutes negligence to the point of recklessness . ''
The judge awarded a total of 12,100 pounds -LRB- dlrs 18,995 -RRB- to Revill , who had filed suit for compensation for his injuries , medical expenses and hardship finding work .
But since Revill was found to be two-thirds at fault , Newbury was ordered to pay only 4,033 pounds -LRB- dlrs 6,332 -RRB- .
But the judge also ordered Revill to pay 400 pounds -LRB- dlrs 628 -RRB- to Newbury for his shock and distress .
The judge noted that Newbury , who was fearful of burglars , had reinforced the shed with metal plates , padlocks and holes wide enough to fit his shotgun .
Newbury , who had been sleeping in the shed for four years , was awakened by Revill and another intruder in March 1988 .
The judge said it was `` a shattering experience '' for Newbury to be awakened and hear one of the intruders say , `` If you are in there , you old bastard , we are having you . ''
However , the judge added , `` Mr. Newbury has to face the obvious question as to why he did not scare off the intruders by some less drastic means .
He could have switched on the light . ''
Revill had been jailed for six months after pleading guilty to trespass and other offenses .
Newbury had been acquitted of weapons offenses in a jury trial .
`` I still ca n't understand what has happened .
I will have to get an explanation from my solicitor -LRB- lawyer -RRB- , '' Newbury said Thursday after the hearing .
`` All I was trying to do was to protect my belongings . ''
NATO asked Germany on Thursday to send fighter planes to patrol the skies over Bosnia in a mission that would place the German military in a combat role for the first time since World War II .
Defense Minister Volker Ruehe said Germany must take on the mission but the foreign minister , Klaus Kinkel , raised doubts about it .
If Chancellor Helmut Kohl decides to accept , it could mean a bruising battle in the new parliament , where Kohl holds the narrowest of majorities .
The liberal opposition said it opposed any combat role in the Balkans .
Germany has shied from direct involvement in Bosnia-Herzegovina because of the history of Nazi atrocities in former Yugoslavia and anti-German sentiment among many Serbs .
But Germany 's credibility in NATO could be threatened if it refuses the mission , given Kohl 's repeated assertions that his nation , seeking more international influence , must bear its share of peacekeeping responsibilities .
NATO requested German Tornado planes equipped with electronic gear that can locate and identify radar sites , and rockets designed to destroy such sites , a German defense official said , speaking on background .
The Tornado planes could help prevent Serb attacks on NATO planes patrolling Bosnia to enforce the U.N. humanitarian mission and also could protect the air bridge to Sarajevo , the official said .
The need for the specialized planes was highlighted last week , when supply flights to Sarajevo from Italy were broken off after Serbs fired missiles at two British Tornados .
German officials could not confirm a report in the weekly Rheinischer Merkur newspaper that the request to Germany was made because Britain wanted to withdraw its fighters from the Bosnia mission .
German acceptance of the mission could mean a greater say for Germany in NATO 's policy toward Bosnia .
German officials have ceded key decisions to nations like France and Britain , which have ground troops in Bosnia .
In an interview distributed by the Defense Ministry , Ruehe said that if Germany turns down the mission , `` we lose the right to intelligently take part in the discussion on Bosnia-Herzegovina . ''
But ground troops are out of the question , Ruehe said .
German soldiers would be `` part of the problem , not the solution '' because of the bitter memories over the hundreds of thousands of Serbs , Jews and others murdered by the German army and SS officers .
The opposition Social Democrats said any German combat mission in Bosnia was unacceptable .
`` Every Serbian family mourns a victim of the Germans .
I have to ask whether it makes a difference if we 're on the ground or in the air , '' said Walter Kolbow , a defense expert for the party .
A July decision of Germany 's highest court gave the government the green light for the first time in the postwar era to engage in peacekeeping missions outside the NATO area .
But a majority of parliament must approve each mission .
`` Whether we ... should really choose former Yugoslavia as the place to step up our engagement is something I believe we should consider very carefully , '' Foreign Minister Kinkel said in Brussels , Belgium .
