Bosnian Serbs detained more peacekeepers , denied resupply convoys and fired missiles at Sarajevo on Thursday in a further challenge to the United Nations ' crumbling bid to keep control .
A day after U.N. chief Boutros Boutros-Ghali 's failed peace mission , defenders and attacking Serbs also traded heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire around embattled Bihac .
U.N. spokesman Alexander Ivanko said in Zagreb , Croatia , that Bosnian Serb units had made an incursion across the border into Croatia and kidnapped seven Ukrainian peacekeepers .
They took the soldiers and a U.N. armored carrier into Bosnian Serb-held territory .
The Ukrainians ' observation point is now occupied by the Serbs , Ivanko said , and the United Nations has not been able to make contact with its troops .
More than 400 other U.N. soldiers are detained by the Serbs .
In Sarajevo , U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Serbs failed to react to 21 requests for convoy passage through Serb-held territory .
He said food and fuel supplies for the United Nations were running increasingly short in government-held eastern Bosnian enclaves and in Bihac .
Humanitarian convoys were also blocked .
In downtown Sarajevo , two buildings of the Interior Ministry were hit by one and three anti-tank missiles respectively , and four people were wounded .
Sarajevo 's airport remained closed because Serbs denied flight clearance , ruling out any relief flights to the besieged Bosnian capital .
Intransigence by both sides led Boutros-Ghali to suggest for the first time Wednesday that the U.N. peacekeeping mission might have to end .
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic told Boutros-Ghali that his government would negotiate only after Serbs accepted a peace plan they repeatedly have rejected .
He reiterated his government 's offer of a three-month cease-fire .
Serbs want something more permanent .
Comments by the Bosnian army commander , Gen. Rasim Delic to the Sarajevo daily Oslobodjenje underscored the government 's unwillingness to compromise further .
He said Bihac would not fall , and that the Bosnian army eventually would win the war .
Bosnian Serbs snubbed Boutros-Ghali altogether .
Their leader , Radovan Karadzic , refused to come to the Sarajevo airport to meet him , and Boutros-Ghali rejected entering Serb-held territory for the meeting .
But the U.N. chief executive will be in Geneva Friday through Sunday to `` continue his intensive diplomatic efforts for a peaceful solution , especially for a cease-fire '' in Bosnia , his spokeswoman Therese Gastaut said .
Maj. Herve Gourmelon , a U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , said heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire broke out around Bihac late Wednesday and in the predawn hours Thursday .
Ivanko said later that Bosnian Serb forces kept the heat on the government 's hard-pressed 5th Corps , with significant fighting reported to the southwest and south of the Bihac pocket .
But there was no immediate information on any changes in the frontlines .
Serbs are holding 30-40 percent of the U.N.-declared `` safe area '' consisting of Bihac town and its environs .
One civilian was killed near the Bihac stadium by small-arms fire , while a number of shells exploded near the Bihac hospital , badly injuring one person , Ivanko said .
NATO ministers meeting in Brussels on Thursday were to hear a proposal from U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher for a new international conference on former Yugoslavia at which the Serbs could make demands for new peace proposals .
Already , senior Western officials are proposing that the Bosnian Serbs be allowed links to Serb-led Yugoslavia , which they long have desired .
That would be a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal , a Greater Serbia .
Bosnian Serbs have rejected a peace plan that would reduce their holdings in Bosnia to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
More than 200,000 are dead or missing in the 31-month conflict launched by Serbs who rebelled against a Muslim-Croat vote to declare independence from Serb-led Yugoslavia .
A rebel Serb assembly met Thursday in a session likely to endorse an economic agreement with Croatia despite two days of fighting .
Croatia 's army and Serbs lobbed artillery shells at each other most of Wednesday and Thursday , said U.N. spokesman Paul Risley .
The two sides have had thousands of skirmishes and larger confrontations since ending their 7-month war with an uneasy , U.N.-patrolled truce in January 1992 .
On Wednesday , the Croatian army fired 33 shells at Serb-held territory over a six-hour period , U.N. spokesman Alexander Ivanko said .
Artillery duels continued Thursday in the same locations close to Knin , Risley said .
Negotiations between the two sides have been stalled , but the Serbs ' self-styled government late Wednesday recommended that the assembly meeting in this Croatian Serb stronghold approve the deal .
If accepted , it would be the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their seven-month war in 1991 .
The draft agreement under discussion at the closed-door Knin meeting calls for restoration of water and electricity supply and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital Belgrade .
Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220-mile -RRB- highway are controlled by Croatian Serbs .
The deal , supported by powerful Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic and drafted with the help of international negotiators , was viewed as a possible step toward the gradual reintegration of the Serb Krajina region into Croatia .
Croatian Serb leaders rejected the economic accord two weeks ago .
After meeting Milosevic , they dropped those objections .
But the session started amid fresh threats of possible new warfare between Croatia and rebel Serbs .
Croatia is chafing at Serb control over one-third of its territory , and holds out the option of taking the territory back by force .
