Britain on Thursday announced its face-to-face showdown with the IRA 's political allies , at last confronting the difficult issues that imperil a budding peace in Northern Ireland .
Peace talks next Wednesday between teams from Britain 's Northern Ireland Office and the Sinn Fein party will be the first formal , publicly acknowledged meeting between the two sides since the conflict over British rule of Northern Ireland ignited in 1969 .
The meeting will mark the transition from an at-a-distance `` peace process '' -- begun last December when the British and Irish governments offered Sinn Fein a place in talks if the IRA laid down its arms -- to deeply problematic negotiations .
Prime Minister John Major 's private secretary , Roderic Lyne , informed Sinn Fein of the British decision in a fax to the party leader , Gerry Adams .
`` The exploratory talks will be a vital step in the process of consolidating a lasting peace in Northern Ireland through a common commitment to exclusively peaceful methods and the democratic process , '' Lyne wrote .
Leading the Sinn Fein team will be Martin McGuinness , a former IRA commander who engaged Britain in secret contacts from 1990 to November 1993 .
The outlawed group began an open-ended truce Sept. 1 .
Leading the British side will be Quentin Thomas , a soft-spoken intellectual who has advised the government on political matters in Northern Ireland since 1988 but shied from the public eye .
He has been a keen backer of the doctrine of denying Sinn Fein public contact in advance of a lasting IRA cease-fire .
`` Sinn Fein must be accorded the same equality of treatment and parity of esteem afforded all other political parties , '' said Adams , who next week will be in Washington to meet National Security Adviser Tony Lake and other U.S. officials .
The peace talks are likely to take place at Stormont east of Belfast , the impressive setting for Northern Ireland 's Protestant-dominated parliament from the state 's foundation in 1921 to 1972 .
Britain abolished the assembly because of its inability to draw Catholic support in the midst of the worst violence Northern Ireland had ever seen .
Since then Britain has tried but failed to draw moderate Catholics into a reformed power-sharing government alongside Protestants , while shunning Sinn Fein and its working-class Catholic supporters because of the party 's IRA roots .
The gap between Wednesday 's historic meeting and the creation of a round-table forum for Protestant politicians to sit down alongside Sinn Fein is wide .
The Rev. Ian Paisley , leader of the province 's hard-line Democratic Unionist Party , said it was wrong for Britain to talk with `` the men of blood . ''
But the larger , more moderate pro-British party , the Ulster Unionists , said the time was right to test whether Sinn Fein had renounced IRA violence for good .
`` We are now at the right stage to enter the next phase of this development , which is to establish if Sinn Fein really is to become a normal political party , '' said John Taylor , an Ulster Unionist lawmaker who survived an IRA assassination bid in 1972 .
`` They will have to learn that in the political arena , they have got to compromise , '' Taylor said , adding , `` We want to convert their cease-fire into real peace . ''
British officials have indicated they will press Sinn Fein for a surrender of IRA arms .
For the first time , McGuinness said Thursday that the future of the IRA arsenal would be discussed .
Previously he has suggested that Sinn Fein could not discuss the handover of weapons and explosives -- most of them hidden in underground bunkers in the Irish Republic -- because Sinn Fein had no authority over the IRA .
But Sinn Fein sees `` demilitarization '' of all sides as the end result of a political settlement , not a precondition for negotiating one .
`` There is an awful lot of hard work ahead of us , '' McGuinness said .
But Kozyrev said he read the ministers ' statement on membership and immediately called Russian President Boris Yeltsin .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' he said impromptu remarks that were broadcast to reporters at the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
In the past , Moscow has strongly opposed any move by NATO to draw in its one-time partners in the Warsaw Pact , the defunct Eastern military alliance led by the Soviet Union .
