An American collector paid more than dlrs 2.3 million Thursday for a `` lost '' manuscript by 19th century composer Robert Schumann , a record price for a music manuscript .
The manuscript of Schumann 's second symphony , auctioned by Sotheby 's , contains a lost passage for the bassoon .
New York collector Robin Lehman paid 1,486,500 pounds -LRB- dlrs 2,334,000 -RRB- for the manuscript , bidding by telephone through London dealer James Kirkman , a Sotheby 's statement said .
Some scholars had believed the manuscript , written in 1846-47 , destroyed during Allied bombing raids on Leipzig during World War II .
In fact , it was sold into private hands in 1950 .
Sotheby 's would not name the seller .
The manuscript is so heavily marked with revisions and deletions that on some pages , new passages had been pasted over .
One passage was lost that way , although Schumann said he favored it .
In an 1846 letter to Felix Mendelssohn , who conducted the symphony 's first performance in Hamburg , Schumann said he had a `` particular fondness '' for `` my melancholy bassoon in the Adagio . ''
It was not known what he meant until recently , when the passage was discovered underneath a pasted-in revision in the manuscript .
Schumann , who died in 1856 from what is today believed syphilis , discusses in the letter how the symphony reflected the state of his mind .
`` I wrote the symphony ... when I was still half-sick ; it seems to me that one must hear this in it , '' he wrote .
The previous record for a musical manuscript was set in 1989 for Schumann 's piano concerto in A Minor , which sold for 880,000 pounds -LRB- dlrs 1,382,000 -RRB- , Sotheby 's said .
The largest single price paid for a group of musical works was for manuscripts of nine Mozart symphonies , which brought in 2,350,000 pounds -LRB- dlrs 3,700,000 -RRB- in 1987 , it said .
