Lane Tarleton sold his sewing factory this week , rather than face the foreign competition that GATT is expected to bring .
Adobe Apparel Inc. made T-shirts , sweatshirts and dresses for companies like Russell Corp. , maker of the Russell Athletics brand .
Tarleton said Wednesday he was lucky to have found a buyer for his Greenwood company in an industry he called `` a dying breed . ''
`` I have spent the last five years trying to build a company , and in my opinion the government has destroyed the sewing machine industries by approving two things : NAFTA and GATT , '' he said , referring to the global General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and the North American Free Trade Agreement signed this year between the United States , Mexico and Canada .
Most textile and apparel shops are n't expected to close their doors if the Senate approves the GATT on Thursday .
The House of Representatives passed the measure Tuesday .
Even healthy companies , such as Arkwright Mills in Spartanburg , expect the 124-nation trade pact to hurt , although they acknowledge parts of it could help the industry .
`` I think it 's about the best they could have done , '' said Earl Gowan , a payroll clerk at Arkwright for 53 years .
Other workers interviewed Wednesday said they had faith that expanded trade would keep their jobs from heading overseas .
`` We really do n't know what 's going to happen , but we 're hoping it 's going to bring more jobs to the South , '' said Reba Rothrock , 65 , a 25-year veteran at Arkwright .
The mill 's president and treasurer , MacFarland Cates , expects his family-owned company will have to fight off competition from the Far East , long a producer of inexpensive cloth .
GATT aims to lower tariffs worldwide , including those in the United States on imported cloth and on other foreign-made goods .
It also would phase out quotas on imported textiles , another move expected to eliminate U.S. jobs .
Still , the agreement gives the industry a weapon it has wanted for years , making it illegal for garments assembled in China to be exported to the United States under the `` Made in Hong Kong '' label .
For that reason , Cates and many others in the textile and apparel industries would like to see the treaty approved by this Congress .
They feel it would offer at least some protection .
`` I 'd love to see GATT killed , '' he said .
But given the choice between this or a version without the rule of origin amendment , `` I 'd rather see them pass this now . ''
Arkwright 's 300 workers make cloth used in sportswear , surgical towels , work gloves , even horse blankets .
Twenty years ago , foreign competition forced it to close two of its three mills and cut most of its 1,200 workers .
Those who are left now make twice as much cloth , and Cates says that efficiency will be the company 's key to survival .
He hopes to expand by modernizing equipment and producing small orders that larger companies ignore .
`` We 've tried to build in efficiency , quality and flexibility so we can jump around and fill different niches .
We think that maybe we 're in a better position to fight than some of the larger companies , '' Cates said .
Yasser Arafat 's government took control of tax collection and health care in the West Bank on Thursday , the latest step in transferring management of Palestinians ' day-to-day affairs to the PLO .
In recent months , the Palestine Liberation Organization , which runs the 6-month-old autonomy arrangement in the Gaza Strip and Jericho , has taken charge of education , tourism and welfare in the West Bank .
Taxes and the health system complete the initial stage of self-rule , though Israeli troops still occupy all the West Bank except Jericho .
The handover came amid mounting calls in Israel for barring Palestinians from Israel following a series of attacks claimed by Islamic militant groups .
Thirty-two Israelis have been killed since early October .
About 1,000 people gathered Thursday in the northern Israeli town of Afula for the funeral of the latest victim , Liat Gabai , a 19-year-old woman soldier who was axed to death on Wednesday .
A suspect from the West Bank who was detained Wednesday told interrogators he was from the Islamic Resistance Movement , or Hamas , Israel radio said .
The same group claimed the bombing of a Tel Aviv bus that killed 22 people .
`` I killed the soldier , '' Wahib Abu Rub said on Israel television , as he was led by police to a West Bank court Thursday .
Police Minister Moshe Shahal responded by calling for a complete closure of the West Bank and Gaza Strip once troops redeploy in the West Bank .
`` There is no alternative other than to demand separation , '' he said .
`` Separation means that we do not have to open the territory ... until the Palestinians prove that they can prevent attacks . ''
A closure could also lead to further violence by preventing thousands of Palestinian workers from entering Israel to earn a living .
Palestinian and Israeli leaders have blamed economic troubles in the Gaza Strip for the growing support for Islamic radicals .
Despite the violence , talks between Israel and the PLO were expected to begin next week on the interim stage of autonomy -- redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank and Palestinian elections .
Israel is worried that the PLO can not guarantee the safety of the 120,000 Jewish settlers once the army pulls out of Palestinian towns as stipulated in their peace accord .
There are calls to renegotiate the agreement , including a proposal Wednesday by Deputy Foreign Minister Yossi Beilin to skip the interim phase altogether and begin talks now on the final status of the West Bank , Gaza Strip and Jerusalem .
The success of any Palestinian arrangement may hinge on its ability to extract revenue .
Atef Alawneh , the Palestinian deputy finance minister , said he eventually hoped to raise dlrs 300 million to dlrs 400 million annually in taxes , much more than the sum raised by Israel .
During the six-year uprising against Israeli occupation , many Palestinians refused to pay taxes .
Israel retaliated by denying tax evaders documents such as drivers ' licenses and travel papers .
Alawneh said tax debts going back to the Israeli era would not be forgiven , and only fines and interest would be canceled .
A Bulgarian diplomat , a stockbroker , two rabbis and a Swiss couple were among 23 people accused of laundering more than dlrs 100 million in drug proceeds .
Carlo A. Boccia of the Drug Enforcement Administration said the defendants had a common motivation -- `` greed , a true example of how drug profits do corrupt at all levels of society . ''
Boccia , special agent in charge of the New York office , said Wednesday that the defendants were part of a money laundering cell that enabled tens of millions of dollars to flow between major U.S. cities and Germany , Switzerland and Italy .
Boccia joined U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White , New York FBI head William A. Gavin and Police Commissioner William Bratton in condemning the alleged participation of otherwise respected professionals in the drug trade .
`` Money became the narcotic , '' Gavin said .
`` It shows the pervasive influence of drugs in our society . ''
`` It is white-collar crime at its worst , '' White said , likening the defendants ' alleged deeds to those of street dealers .
`` The range of professions involved in this was surprising and somewhat depressing , '' said White , noting that a lawyer who was arrested practiced often at the federal courthouse in Manhattan .
A federal complaint charged 23 defendants with participating in a major international ring that laundered tens of millions of dollars in the last year alone .
Among the group was an assistant manager at Citibank .
The organization operated in New York , Los Angeles , Houston , Chicago and Miami in the United States as well as in Germany , Switzerland , Italy , Puerto Rico and Colombia , authorities said .
During the probe , investigators seized dlrs 5 million .
They arrested all but four of those named in a complaint , which was sealed until Wednesday .
According to court documents , the leaders of the organization in the United States were Richard Spence , a businessman who was formerly a New York City firefighter ; lawyer Harvey Weinig ; and Robert Hirsch , Weinig 's law partner .
Hirsch , 41 , has pleaded guilty to money laundering and other charges in a plea bargain with prosecutors .
White charged that the three arranged for the pickup of narcotics proceeds from street corners and hotel rooms .
Also arrested were Leon Weinmann and his wife , Rachel , of Switzerland , who were lured to the United States for a meeting .
The complaint charged that the Zurich couple received cash and wire transfers and remitted them to bank accounts .
Swiss authorities have blocked about a half dozen accounts at several banks in Zurich at the request of U.S. officials in connection with the case , Zurich prosecutor Marc Ziegler said Thursday .
He said the authorities asked the banks , which he declined to name , to provide information on the accounts .
Among those allegedly sent as couriers were police Officer Michael T. Kalanz , firefighter Charles Bruno , hospital administrator Gary Salerno , Los Angeles-based stockbroker Donald J. Hayden and rabbis Alexander Schwartz and Menashe Leifer .
Also arrested was Latchezar Christov , an honorary consul general for the Republic of Bulgaria .
Those arrested were charged with conspiracy and money laundering .
