Governments must target bringing down rapidly increasing numbers of women with AIDS , discarding stereotypes that it 's mostly a gay men 's disease , according to politicians and activists at Thursday 's international AIDS summit .
Officials from 42 countries pledged to bolster the status of women and ensure their participation in drawing up and implementing AIDS policy .
The deadly disease is spreading more rapidly among women , who suffer social , sexual and economic oppression , said Hiroshi Nakajima , director general of the World Health Organization .
WHO statistics show that three men for every two women become infected by the HIV virus that causes AIDS .
But by the year 2000 , the rates will even out .
Although women are contracting HIV at a faster pace , most prevention methods still target men , U.S. Secretary of Health Donna Shalala said .
`` We must work together to reduce the vulnerability of women to HIV and AIDS by empowering them to protect themselves against infection -- both with and without reliance on their sexual partners , '' Shalala said .
The United States has doubled the amount of research money spent on microbe-killing vaginal creams or gels that are currently in the testing stage , Shalala said .
British physician Eileen Rubery said efforts have gained momentum over the last two years to develop a microbicide that women could apply before having sex .
The cream has been tested in Thailand but caused itching and inflammation after frequent use , Rubery said .
It has been modified and is again being tested in hopes that a cheap , mass-market alternative to condoms will provide more women with protective choices against AIDS .
Yolanda Simon , an AIDS sufferer from Trinidad , urged politicians around the world to increase care not just for women , but their families .
American activists said the U.S. health program fails to take women 's family responsibilities into account , and that more women need to be involved in the administration of such programs .
But Phill Wilson , an AIDS victim from Los Angeles , said men should not be left out .
`` Women and AIDS is a co-gender issue .
It 's a sexuality issue , '' he said .
`` It 's as much about homophobia and how gay men are forced to hide their sexuality from their -LRB- heterosexual -RRB- partners . ''
Male education is needed because men are also responsible for having safe sex , Wilson said , especially in countries where women know little about protective measures or are unable to ask their partners to use them .
