Germany was asked by NATO on Thursday to send fighter planes to patrol the skies over Bosnia , in a mission that could involve the German military in combat for the first time since World War II .
Defense Minister Volker Ruehe said Germany must accept the mission , but Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel raised doubts .
It will be a thorny decision for Chancellor Helmut Kohl , who has shied from involvement in Bosnia-Herzegovina because of the history of Nazi atrocities in former Yugoslavia and anti-German sentiment among Serbs .
It will be a difficult request for Germany to turn down , however , because of Kohl 's repeated assertions that his nation , seeking more international influence , must bear its share of peacekeeping responsibilities .
Support was n't clear in parliament , which would probably have to approve any such mission .
Lt. Col. Joe Cato , spokesman for NATO 's European military headquarters in Casteau , Belgium , said Germany has been asked to `` provide some combat aircraft to support NATO air operations over parts of former Yugoslavia . ''
NATO requested German Tornado planes equipped with electronic gear that can locate and identify radar sites and rockets designed to destroy such sites , a German defense official said , speaking on condition of anonymity .
The Tornado planes could help prevent Serb attacks on NATO planes patrolling Bosnia to protect the U.N. humanitarian mission , and also could protect supply flights to Sarajevo , the official said .
The need for the specialized planes was highlighted last week , when supply flights to Sarajevo from Italy were called off after Serbs fired missiles at two British Tornados .
German acceptance of the mission could mean a greater say for Germany in NATO policy toward Bosnia .
German officials have ceded key decisions to nations such as France and Britain , which have ground troops in Bosnia .
If Germany turns down the mission , `` we lose the right to intelligently take part in the discussion on Bosnia-Herzegovina , '' Ruehe , the defense minister , said in comments distributed by the Defense Ministry .
But ground troops are out of the question , Ruehe said .
German soldiers would be `` part of the problem , not the solution , '' because of the bitter memories over the hundreds of thousands of Serbs , Jews and others murdered by the German army and SS officers .
The opposition Social Democrats said any German combat mission in Bosnia was unacceptable .
`` Every Serbian family mourns a victim of the Germans .
I have to ask whether it makes a difference if we 're on the ground or in the air , '' said Walter Kolbow , a defense expert for the party .
A July decision of the German constitutional court enabled the government to engage in peacekeeping missions outside of NATO countries for the first time .
German supply troops were involved in missions in Somalia and Rwanda .
`` Whether we , after the constitutional court ruling , should really choose former Yugoslavia as the place to step up our engagement , is something I believe we should consider very carefully , '' Kinkel , the foreign minister , said in Brussels , Belgium .
Russia on Thursday upset NATO 's plans for expanding its membership to former Warsaw Pact foes by claiming the move would create a new division in Europe .
In an extraordinary session , Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev departed from a prepared speech to criticize the allies for ordering aides to draw up the terms and conditions for future membership .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told a group of grim-faced foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
The Russian had been invited to the meeting to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow .
The special ties had been designed to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
But Kozyrev refused to agree to the documents .
He said he read the ministers ' statement on membership and immediately called Russian President Boris Yeltsin .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' he said impromptu remarks that were broadcast to reporters at the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
Willy Claes , the alliance 's new secretary-general , sought to respond to Kozyrev 's remarks .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO .
... There is nothing new , '' he told the Russian just before he left NATO headquarters .
`` We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst only added to the alliance 's woes .
There have been unprecedented strains in recent weeks between the United States and its European allies over the crisis in Bosnia .
In an effort to heal the wounds , Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It was a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the Europeans , led by Britain and France .
In the past , Moscow has strongly opposed any move by NATO to draw in its one-time partners in the Warsaw Pact , the defunct Eastern military alliance led by the Soviet Union .
The Europeans in particular have been uneasy about pushing expansion for fear of upsetting Russia , still a formidable military power at the edge of allied territory .
In an effort to overcome Russian objections , the allies had agreed to develop a `` far-reaching relationship , corresponding with Russia 's size , importance and capabilities . ''
They had insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc threatening Russia .
`` Having just overcome the division of Europe , we have no desire to see the emergence of new lines of partition , '' the ministers said in a statement .
A senior U.S. official , speaking a few hours before Kozyrev 's outburst , said , `` The Russians are undoubtedly ambivalent about this . ''
He spoke on condition of anonymity .
NATO has been anguishing in recent years over whether -- and when -- to open its doors to its former foes in Eastern Europe .
Poland , Hungary and others have repeatedly demanded coveted membership cards and the security guarantees that would go with it .
In an effort to meet their demands -- but without upsetting Russia , the allies thought they had found a good formula .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
`` We took significant , concrete steps toward ... expansion '' of the alliance , Christopher said afterward .
The move was intended to be a cautious one .
No list of front-runners for membership will be made ; no date set for the first admissions will be set .
But Kozyrev accused NATO of trying to make a fresh division on the European continent .
Some members of Partnership for Peace , he said , were destined to become members , while others would remain behind .
`` Not all countries will be able to obtain membership at the same time , '' he said .
`` There needs to be some sort of clarification . ''
Secretary of State Warren Christopher confessed Thursday that the United States and its allies had mismanaged the war in Bosnia .
He said they all had lessons to learn from the debacle .
As the NATO foreign ministers moved to expand NATO to countries in Central and Eastern Europe , Christopher found himself cast in the embarrassing role of explaining the Clinton administration 's decision to forgo force in favor of diplomacy to try to rein in the Serbs .
`` All of us ought to try to learn lessons from the experience in Bosnia , '' he told reporters , while trying to focus their attention on NATO 's future rather than the faltering attempt to quiet the conflict in the former Yugoslav republic .
Stoutly maintaining NATO had fulfilled the peacekeeping assignment given it by the United Nations , Christopher said the purpose in expanding the alliance and revamping the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe , a 53-nation East-West group , was to forestall other threats to peace on the continent .
A senior U.S. official put it more bluntly .
`` While Bosnia is burning we are trying to concentrate on the larger structural issues that may prevent other Bosnias , '' he said .
NATO 's projected expansion eastward would embrace the territory between Germany and Russia , where two world wars were fought in this century .
On Friday , Christopher intends to get formal approval from France , Britain , Germany and Russia for a new diplomatic initiative to try to draw the Bosnian Serbs into negotiations with the Muslims and Croats in Bosnia .
It calls for a cease-fire around Bihac , the northwestern Muslim enclave that Serbs are pummeling , a pledge to cease hostilities throughout the country for three to six months and then an international peace conference .
The lure for the Serbs , who control about 70 percent of Bosnia , is an opportunity to press their demand for cross-border political ties to Serbia .
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd made plans to fly to Belgrade next weekend to push the initiative .
Christopher 's aides said he did not intend to accompany them .
At the same time , NATO is considering contingency plans to withdraw the 24,000 U.N. peacekeepers now in Bosnia , hundreds of whom have been detained by the onrushing Serbs .
Christopher said an evacuation would require ground troops and the United States `` would have a role in that . ''
However , he said President Clinton had not decided specifically what American troops might do to extricate the peacekeepers .
Looking backward , Christopher faulted the United Nations for deciding in 1991-92 to deal with the conflict in Bosnia as a humanitarian crisis .
`` NATO has done very well in what it was asked to do , '' he said .
And looking ahead , Christopher said the United States would not shrink from any new conflicts in Europe .
`` We believe the United States should be involved in the resolution of such crises in the future , '' he said .
NATO Secretary-General Willy Claes defended the alliance he has just taken over .
`` Before accepting a new peacekeeping mission coming from the United Nations or coming from the CSCE we will look very carefully to the conditions , to the roles of the game , before saying once again yes , '' the Belgian diplomat said at a news conference .
At this juncture , `` on Bosnia we certainly are of one mind today , '' Claes insisted .
Evicted by police from government offices , hunger-striking leaders of East Germany 's reformed communists expanded protests on Thursday against a whopping tax levy they say would ruin them financially .
Some 3,000 sympathizers held rallies and sit-ins in Berlin , Schwerin and Dresden on Thursday in support of the fast begun on Wednesday by Party of Democratic Socialism -LRB- PDS -RRB- lawmakers .
The party claims the government is trying to exact its political death with the 67 million mark -LRB- dlrs 43 million -RRB- bill , which was assessed by Berlin tax authorities based on real estate sales in the first half of 1990 .
At the time , just months before German unification , the PDS as successor to the communists held vast assets .
A large portion of those assets are now controlled by an independent federal commission that is supposed to determine how much of the property they can keep and how much belongs to the people .
The PDS asked the commission to pay the tax bill , but it refused , saying it would be violating its legal mandate in doing so .
A court ruled Thursday that the PDS would only have to pay 3 million marks -LRB- dlrs 1.8 million -RRB- security for the moment , pending further attempts to settle the dispute .
But party leaders said they would not pay .
Leaders of other political parties accused the PDS , which was formed in 1990 out of the remnants of the collapsed East German Communist party , of trying to stir up public sympathy by falsely painting itself a victim .
In Berlin , protesters gathered outside federal Interior Ministry offices to protest the police expulsion of PDS leaders from government offices on Wednesday night .
They were also angered by Interior Minister Manfred Kanther 's threat to charge the politicians with trespassing .
The PDS lawmakers moved to their party offices at the Berlin city legislature and said the hunger strike would continue indefinitely under the motto `` We wo n't be taxed out of existence -- No expropriation of the PDS . ''
The party won 20 percent of the vote in eastern Germany in Oct. 16 national elections , thanks mainly to resentment among eastern Germans who feel they have been demoted to second-class status in united Germany .
Chancellor Helmut Kohl has attacked the PDS as a group of `` red-painted fascists , '' and the party has been battered by accusations that its parliamentary leader , Gregor Gysi , was an informant for the East German secret police when he acted as defense lawyer for dissidents .
Speakers and activists at a 42-nation summit on AIDS pleaded Thursday for compassion for homosexuals , drug users and prostitutes often shunned by politicians and the public .
Governments should redouble their efforts to end discrimination against these groups , at high risk of becoming infected with the HIV virus that causes AIDS , participants said .
`` All laws which deny the freedom of people to cross borders because of HIV must be abolished , '' said Richard Burzynski , an HIV sufferer with a Canada-based AIDS rights group , ICASO .
`` This means all laws which criminalize or discriminate against homosexuals , drug users , migrants and refugees , and sex workers must be abolished . ''
Governments tend to ignore or isolate homosexuals , worsening rather than addressing the AIDS epidemic , the International Gay and Lesbian Association said in a statement .
Homosexuals must be accepted , educated and protected by legislation , the group said .
Officials of the 42 participating nations endorsed a declaration pledging to strengthen cooperation between developed and Third World countries and to fight discrimination against those suffering from AIDS .
`` We are not meeting here simply to issue a further warning , but to declare a planetary emergency , '' said U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali .
`` Every day , AIDS kills children , destroys families , drains economies , threatens communities .
We must act without delays . ''
The non-binding declaration says signatories will act to `` ensure that all persons living with HIV\/AIDS are able to realize the full and equal enjoyment of their fundamental rights and freedoms . ''
The declaration promised efforts to provide health care , jobs , education and housing to people with HIV or AIDS .
It also supported `` empowerment of women '' by raising their economic and social status and including them in decision-making .
The summit was a focal point of World AIDS Day , observed around the world with education programs and fund-raising events .
Australians attended special church services commemorating 3,500 compatriots killed by AIDS .
In the Ivory Coast , where AIDS is the leading killer of young men , 2,000 people marched through Abidjan with banners declaring , `` Condoms for life ; AIDS for death . ''
In South Africa , where the disease is spreading rapidly , health officials and politicians wrapped a huge red ribbon around St. George 's Cathedral in Cape Town as part of efforts to increase AIDS awareness .
In Paris , hundreds of teen-agers visited a `` village '' set up across the Seine river from the Eiffel Tower , with scores of stands offering brochures , condoms and other educational material .
A peaceful march led by the AIDS group Act Up through the Left Bank drew an estimated 4,500 people .
Earlier , about 50 Act Up activists lay on the Champs Elysees and blocked traffic for several minutes .
At the summit , there were numerous calls for more AIDS spending , starting with Federico Mayor , head of the U.N. Educational , Scientific and Cultural Organization .
`` In our budgets we have funds to pay the price of war , but we have made no provision for the cost of the fight against AIDS , '' Mayor said .
Funding `` must be accompanied by ethical surveillance to prevent or check any measures ... that would tend to exclude or discriminate against people who are ill from the disease , '' he said .
The World Bank , the biggest donor in the campaign against AIDS , pledged dlrs 150 million annually to combat the disease in developing countries .
Britain announced an allocation of 230 million pounds -LRB- dlrs 358 million -RRB- on AIDS services for 1995 .
Currently , however , more than 90 percent of the money pledged to fight AIDS goes toward helping only the 8 percent of those afflicted in developed countries .
Some 17 million people are known to have been infected with the HIV virus , about two-thirds in Africa , the World Health Organization says .
Up to 40 million will have been infected by 2000 , and 10 million will have died , according to WHO , co-sponsor of the summit with the French government .
Some French media pronounced the summit a failure even before it began .
The daily Liberation criticized the final declaration as `` banal , '' predicted that little new funding would materialize , and noted that senior U.S. , British or German leaders rebuffed summit invitations .
Ernesto Zedillo , a mild-mannered economist whose rise to power capped a tragic and tumultous year of rebellion and political assassination , was sworn in Thursday as the 63rd president of Mexico .
Taking the red , green and white sash of office , the 42-year-old economist promised to expand democracy and prosperity for this nation of 90 million .
`` Our most important challenge is to provide dignified living conditions for every Mexican family , '' Zedillo said .
The new president also vowed to use the North American Free Trade Agreement `` to help generate the jobs we need and raise living standards . ''
He spoke in the ornate Chamber of Deputies before 1,500 Mexican officials and foreign leaders , including Vice President Al Gore and Cuba 's President Fidel Castro .
Zedillo promised to start a war on poverty and maintain a cease-fire with Indian rebels in southern Chiapas state .
He said Mexico must unite to eradicate the poverty that led to the rebellion .
Former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari , who negotiated NAFTA with the United States and Canada , was loudly applauded as Zedillo paid him tribute .
Outside the hall , military bands struck up waltzes and mariachi musicians warmed up a huge street fiesta on the parade route to the National Palace , festive in red and green bunting .
But not everyone wanted to celebrate .
`` Out with Zedillo ! ''
and `` Zedillo No ! ''
shouted more than 4,000 anti-government demonstrators , some brandishing sticks and machetes , at a protest in downtown Mexico City .
The protesters , mostly farmers in straw sombreros , raised banners of the leftist Democratic Revolution Party , the biggest opponent to 65 years of rule by the Institutional Revolutionary Party .
Zedillo , a former Mexicali shoeshine boy , received a doctorate in economics from Yale .
Bypassed once for his party 's presidential nomination , he was thrust into the campaign by the March assassination of Luis Donaldo Colosio , first choice of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party , or PRI .
He won the presidency Aug. 21 in the most credible elections ever held in Mexico .
Zedillo has pledged to use the near-absolute powers of Mexico 's presidency to weaken his own office .
He says he will give greater independence to the congress , the courts and local governments as well as the PRI itself .
He says he will end the practice of having the president handpick all top PRI candidates .
Zedillo , former budget and planning minister under Salinas , is sure to continue his predecessor 's free-market economic policies -- a commitment underlined by the Cabinet choices announced Wednesday .
Leading negotiators of NAFTA -- the trade pact with the United States and Canada -- were named heads of treasury , trade and foreign policy .
Seven other free-market economists also were named to the 25-person cabinet .
Gore said 1994 was a year of `` unprecedented progress in the bilateral relationship between the United States and Mexico ... and we look forward to even greater improvement in the year ahead . '
Zedillo also showed signs of a political opening with the appointment of a conservative opposition party member , Antonio Lozano , as attorney general .
The post is crucial for Zedillo , who made fighting government corruption a major part of his campaign .
Last week , a deputy attorney general investigating the Sept. 28 assassination of his own brother , a top PRI official , resigned angrily , charging that top government and party officials were involved in a cover-up .
Lozano 's appointment marks the first time a Cabinet post has been given to an opposition party member , and it `` opens the possibility of an important change , '' said Carlos Castillo Pedraza , the president of the National Action Party .
On Tuesday , Zedillo reached out to the left as well , meeting with leaders of the Democratic Revolution Party and promising reforms to help make Mexico more democratic .
Salinas never met publicly with leaders of that main leftist opposition during his administration .
The party apparently responded by pulling some 4,000 protesters out of the capital 's main plaza Wednesday , indicating an effort to avoid the confrontations that marred Salinas ' inauguration in 1988 .
The demonstrators were protesting alleged vote fraud in recent state elections .
Despite Zedillo 's moves , other discontent remains .
A protest was planned Thursday by leftist supporters of the Zapatista National Liberation Army rebels of southern Mexico .
That rebellion , stalled since January by a cease-fire , is one of the toughest problems facing the new president .
Sunburned and scattered on an improvised armada of U.S. Navy ships and cargo boats in the Indian Ocean , the nearly 1,000 survivors of a blaze that swept through the Achille Lauro began the first leg Thursday of their return home .
The fire broke out Wednesday morning in the engine room on the bad luck cruise ship .
The Achille Lauro was hijacked in 1985 and an American passenger killed by Palestinian terrorists .
Passengers and crew who escaped the blaze by scrambling into lifeboats were transferred Thursday to 10 ships that would take them to Kenya or Djibouti .
Many of the survivors , some dressed in evening or bed clothes , had spent hours aboard the deck of the oil tanker Hawaiian King and other merchant ships that had plucked them to safety immediately after the evacuation .
Two elderly passengers died -- an Englishman during the evacuation and a German man of a heart attack .
Eight people were injured .
Starlauro , the Achille Lauro 's owners , said in Naples they were trying to determine if the German died because of the fire or if he had the attack before the early-morning blaze .
`` The fire was so big you had to fight through smoke which poured down toward the cabins , '' one survivor , Tony Webb , was quoted as telling the London Daily Telegraph .
Webb , a 44-year-old Briton who now lives in Cape Town , South Africa , had taken his wife and 2-year-old son on the cruise after winning a contest .
He said he was still wearing his dinner jacket after a ship dance .
`` People were in their evening suits and dressing gowns , '' the paper quoted Webb as saying .
Children screamed and people clung to each other as the Achille Lauro listed .
With his son Michael holding on to him in terror Webb looked back and saw flames `` leaping up and there was smoke all around . ''
'' The crew was wonderful , '' Webb said .
`` They tried to keep us all calm .
At about 8 a.m. , the captain said the fire was too strong and we would have to abandon the ship . ''
Starlauro , the cruise ship 's owners , said an SOS was sent at just before 7 a.m. local time .
A ship officer told Italian television that the fire broke out around 2 a.m. and took several hours to reach passenger areas .
`` Quite a few people were injured in the transfer -LRB- Wednesday -RRB- -- there 's a few broken bones and some pretty tortured souls , '' John Briand , captain of the oil tanker Lima , told the BBC .
The Achille Lauro 's captain , Giuseppe Orsi , talking by phone Thursday aboard the Hawaiian King , told Italy 's transport minister in Rome that survivors ' morale was high but that clothing was needed .
He later said the fire began in the engine room and crews struggled to contain the blaze .
`` But then a piston exploded and the flames spread all over the place , '' said Orsi .
`` From what I saw -LRB- the ship -RRB- is gone , '' he said .
Two Navy ships , the USS Gettysburg and the Halyburton , took on a total of 208 survivors Thursday .
`` Many had tears of relief '' as they came aboard the Gettysburg , that ship 's commander , Capt. Pete Smith said .
They were offered '' a hot shower , the crew were feeding them ... -LRB- and -RRB- donating clothes for them to wear , as a lot abandoned ship in nightclothes . ''
Many had bad sunburn after being exposed for hours on the deck of the Hawaiian King , Navy officials reported .
By Thursday evening , survivors were spread aboard a total of 10 ships .
Five vessels were headed for Djibouti , on the Horn of Africa ; and five for Mombasa , Kenya , with the first due , the Liberian-registered Bar Du , in Djibouti , at 2 p.m. local time -LRB- 1100 gmt -RRB- , the Italian Coast Guard reported Thursday evening .
Others were due in later Friday or Saturday .
The ship had carried 581 passengers and 404 crew .
Most of the crew was Italian , and the passengers mainly South African , German , Dutch or British .
RAI state TV said the Italian state airline , Alitalia , would dispatch jumbos to fly out the survivors , except for South Africans , to Italy once they reached port and had a chance to rest .
The Achille Lauro set sail Nov. 19 from Genoa , Italy ; stopped in Haifa , Israel , and then plied on to Africa 's east coast .
The ship had been bound for South Africa .
The Italian liner itself Thursday still hung on , although listing badly to port .
White steam and gray smoke poured out of port side and smaller plumes of smoke drifted out of the lower starboard deck .
Tug boats arrived at the ship Thursday to possibly tow it to port , Italian media reported .
The pilot of a plane carrying Associated Press cameramen and a reporter put the ship 's position at 160 miles east of the small Somali fishing village of Eil .
Heat and soot blackened the Achille Lauro 's two smokestacks , and its blue-and-white paint was scorched and mottled .
The ship 's captain reportedly has put the fire 's origin in the engine room , apparently contradicting the company 's initial assertion that the blaze began in the passenger area .
Starlauro 's director-general , Franco Zuccherino , told RAI TV Thursday that the fire 's dynamics were yet to be determined .
`` We have to talk extensively with the captain '' first , Zuccherino said .
England 's Del Harris reached his first semifinal of a major squash tournament Thursday , defeating countryman Simon Parke at the dlrs 96,000 Qatar International .
Harris , once the world No. 7 but now ranked No. 20 , will play Jansher Khan , the world 's No. 1 , in the semifinals on Friday .
Harris beat Parke , who had downed No. 2 Peter Marshall in the first round , 15-14 , 15-9 , 15-13 .
Khan , the defending champion , beat veteran New Zealander Ross Norman 15-6 , 15-10 , 15-13 .
The last two quarterfinals of the day were marathon affairs from which Australia 's Rodney Eyles and England 's Chris Walker emerged victorious .
Eyles , ranked four in the world , defeated No. 5 ranked Scotsman Peter Nicol 15-5 , 13-15 , 15-6 , 12-15 , 15-7 .
Walker , ranked No. 6 , beat world No. 3 Brett Martin of Australia 17-16 , 9-15 , 17-15 , 9-15 , 15-12 .
Bread prices increased 11 times Thursday as the government started implementing a market-reform plan aimed at freeing prices and slashing the deficit .
The government ordered bread prices increased from 6 drams -LRB- 1.3 cents -RRB- to 66 drams -LRB- 15 cents -RRB- per kilogram -LRB- 2.2 pounds -RRB- .
But bread rationing remained in force , with a daily norm of 350 grams -LRB- 12 ounces -RRB- per person in the capital and 250 grams -LRB- 9 ounces -RRB- in the countryside .
Armenia is one of the poorest of the former Soviet republics , with an average monthly salary of about dlrs 7 .
Its economy has been severely hit by an economic blockade imposed by Azerbaijan as part of a six-year war over the enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh .
Armenia 's only source of energy is a natural-gas pipeline from Georgia that has been repeatedly bombed .
The government has vowed to gradually deregulate prices to meet requirements for international loans .
Armenia hopes to get dlrs 250 million to dlrs 300 million in credits from the International Monetary Fund , World Bank and some Western governments over the next year .
