Holding 55 Canadian peacekeepers hostage in Bosnia is unacceptable and little progress is being made to win their release , Prime Minister Jean Chretien said Thursday .
Still , it was not a mistake for Canada to renew its six-month commitment to UN peacekeeping in the war-torn former Yugoslav republic , the prime minister said .
The current mandate runs out at the end of March .
`` I do n't think that it 's a mistake when our country is doing something for peace .
It might be difficult , it might be complicated , it might be dangerous .
`` But I have to tell you that the Canadians have a great reputation not to be afraid to do something for peace . ''
Earlier in a speech to the French Senate , Chretien said NATO allies will try to solve the crisis in talks in Budapest next week with former Soviet bloc countries at the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe .
The talks will look for a way `` to master this destructive spirit rooted in intolerance , '' he said .
Chretien is only the second foreign leader ever invited to speak to the French Senate .
He took advantage of the opportunity to send a discreet message to the French that Canada is a bilingual country that works .
`` The French language continues to flourish in Canada and a multitude of Canadians are adopting it as their second language , '' Chretien said .
But the prime minister 's remarks -- which did not refer once to the forthcoming Quebec referendum on separation -- were overshadowed by concerns about UN peacekeeping in the former Yugoslavia .
After his speech , Chretien said it was not acceptable that Bosnian Serbs , who are detaining some 400 peacekeepers , refused to meet UN Secretary General Butros Butros-Ghali when he visited the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo Wednesday .
The prime minister also did n't quarrel with calling the detained troops hostages .
`` They are detained , you can call it hostages ... But I would not fight on the meaning of words here . ''
The prime minister hopes the peacekeepers will be released soon , but `` we 're not making progress at this time . ''
Speaking in the ornate Senate chamber , Chretien downplayed national unity in favor of expanding world trade and stressing the importance of Canada-France relations .
He suggested it 's time to consider a free trade agreement between the North American trading bloc -- Canada , the United States and Mexico -- and the European Union .
Chretien also promised a more modest summit when the Group of Seven leading industrial democracies meet next June in Halifax .
Such meetings are sometimes criticized as expensive photo opportunities which accomplish little .
La Francophonie , a group of the world 's French-speaking countries , could also get more involved in politics , Chretien said .
He noted the organization did little to avert a bloodbath in Rwanda and a military coup in Haiti , both member countries .
While avoiding any direct references to Canadian unity , the prime minister still sent a subtle but powerful message to Quebec separatists .
Quebec politicians have also been wooing the French in the pre-referendum period -- Premier Jacques Parizeau visits in January , International Affairs Minister Bernard Landry was there last month .
But Chretien said three times in his speech that Canada and France share a common cause , referring to peacekeeping , world organizations and trade .
Asked later why he did n't mention the referendum that Parizeau has promised to hold next year , Chretien said : `` I do n't think it was appropriate for me to come and , you know , wash our linen here . ''
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl was the first foreign leader to speak to the French Senate and Russian President Boris Yeltsin is expected to be the next .
Rene Monory , president of the Senate , sidestepped a question about whether Parizeau will get a similar invitation .
`` It 's the office that has decided the invitation of Mr. Chretien , because I know he is the prime minister of the country , '' he said .
Earlier Thursday , Chretien told a conference on AIDS that `` as AIDS continues to ravage every corner of the world , there can be no doubt that we must all work even harder and more urgently . ''
But he announced little new action , saying Canada would maintain and possibly increase its efforts in Africa against the disease .
Most of Canada 's $ 11 million international financial assistance concerning AIDS is already directed towards Africa .
Moscow backed off from a threat to send troops Thursday into the breakaway republic of Chechnya , where leaders defied a Russian ultimatum and called on armed volunteers to defend their capital .
Air attacks continued on the outskirts of Grozny , the Chechen capital , and a Russian delegation arrived from Moscow and began talks with Chechen officials .
Residents continued to flee the mainly Muslim city of 300,000 people in the Caucasus Mountains of southern Russia .
The city has become a war zone between forces loyal to Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , who declared independence from Moscow in 1991 , and Chechen rebels trying to topple him .
Dudayev accuses Moscow of arming and leading the rebels , who launched an offensive last week that began with helicopters and escalated in recent days to jet fighters .
Russia says it has given the rebels only political support .
It refuses to recognize independence for Chechnya , which was incorporated into the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
President Boris Yeltsin threatened Tuesday to impose a state of emergency in Chechnya if both sides did not surrender prisoners and stop fighting by Thursday morning .
On Thursday evening , Yeltsin 's office issued an altered text of the ultimatum , saying `` there was some disagreement in the media in interpreting certain clauses . ''
The reissued document made no reference to a state of emergency .
Trying a different tack , Yeltsin offered limited amnesty Thursday to Chechens who `` voluntarily lay down arms by Dec. 15 . ''
In another sign of Russia 's desire to avoid direct confrontation , Defense Minister Pavel Grachev told reporters in Moscow that some Russian soldiers who `` carried out certain military tasks for material compensation '' from anti-Dudayev forces had been brought back to central Russia , and more would be evacuated .
Grachev insisted the soldiers were volunteers and were not in Chechnya on army orders .
Dudayev 's government captured up to 70 Russians in fighting last weekend and alleged that some were army officers and soldiers .
Chechen officials initially threatened to execute them , but Dudayev said Thursday they would be tried in court .
Despite Moscow 's softened tone , it still appeared to be beefing up troops on the borders of Chechnya .
A tired-looking Dudayev held a defiant news conference in the basement of his presidential palace as jets roared overhead , calling Yeltsin 's government a `` satanic power . ''
Dudayev said his house had been bombed Thursday morning .
A small military air base near Grozny also was hit in an air raid Thursday and a woman 's corpse was seen .
The ITAR-Tass news agency said two women were killed and fuel depots were burning .
In Freedom Square outside Dudayev 's offices , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches .
Chechen elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
A United Nations protest to Bosnian Serbs for detaining peacekeepers and attacking a Canadian camp sparked a response from the Serb 's top general , a Canadian military spokesperson said Thursday .
Maj. Rita LePage , Canadian military spokesperson in Zagreb , Croatia , said Lt.-Gen .
Bertrand Guillaume de Lapresle , UN commander in former Yugoslavia , and his deputy commander , Canadian Maj.-Gen .
Raymond Crabbe , received two letters from the Serbs .
The letters came from Gen. Ratko Mladic , Serb army commander , and one of his assistants .
Earlier this week , Lapresle and Crabbe had themselves sent letters to the Serbs protesting the holding of UN troops and a Serb rocket attack on the Canadian peacekeeping camp in Visoko on Sunday , which damaged a building .
Canadian officials declined to comment on the letters ' contents saying the Serb letters came at a `` sensitive '' time .
But military sources said the response was too general to satisfy UN leaders as they try to restart serious talks on releasing 400 UN troops , including 55 Canadians .
