Canadian peacekeepers serving with the United Nations in Bosnia-Herzegovina are detained by Bosnian Serbs after NATO planes bomb Serb positions in Bosnia and Croatia .
Here are some key dates surrounding the detention :
Nov. 19 -- UN Security Council extends NATO air authority to Croatia after Serb warplanes flying from an air base in Udbina , in Serb-controlled Croatia , launch air strikes on the UN-declared safe haven of Bihac in northwest Bosnia .
Nov. 21 -- NATO planes bomb the Udbina airport and two Serb missile sites in Bosnia near Bihac .
Nov. 22 -- Serbs fire surface-to-air missiles at two NATO jets flying over Serb-held Banja Luka , in northwest Bosnia , and set villages ablaze and send civilians fleeing in the Bihac pocket in retaliation for NATO air strikes .
Nov. 23 -- Serbs detain some 250 UN peacekeepers , including 55 Canadian troops near their base in Visoko , Bosnia , hours after renewed NATO air strikes against Serb positions near Bihac in Bosnia and Croatia .
Nov. 24 -- UN officials attempt to negotiate the release of the Canadians and the other UN peacekeepers in talks with Serb leaders .
Bosnian Muslim-led government troops block attempt to transfer 150 non-essential personnel from the Canadian base at Visoko to Kiseljak , some 15 kilometres away .
Nov. 25 -- NATO jets fly over Serb positions near Bihac but due to darkness drop no bombs as Serb forces advance into the enclave , controlled by the Muslim-led government army .
Serbs allow some of the detained Canadians to carry out work at their observation posts .
Muslims lift blockade of Canadian camp .
Nov. 26 -- Canadian troops come under fire three times .
No one is injured : a convoy of buses carrying Canadians to Visoko from Split , Croatia , is hit by five mortars ; two rifle grenades hit Canadian headquarters in Knin in Serb-controlled Croatia ; mortar round lands near Canadian vehicle in Knin area .
Nov. 27 -- Between six and 10 rockets fired by Bosnian Serbs land near the Canadian camp in Visoko .
Shrapnel from two rockets damages a camp building where Canadian soldiers are sleeping .
No one is injured .
Negotiations to free the detained Canadians continue .
Nov. 28 -- The UN commander in Bosnia , Lt.-Gen .
Sir Michael Rose , and Col. Bill Brough , commander of the Canadian battalion in Visoko , fail to win release of the Canadians .
A Serb offer to let the Canadians return to base if they 're replaced by another 55 Canadians is rejected .
Nov. 30 -- a Bosnian Serb threat to shell the Canadian camp within 48 hours passes without incident .
However , the peacekeepers increase security and place sandbags around sleeping quarters .
Dec. 1 -- Bosnian Serbs respond to letters from Canadian and UN commanders protesting the detention of 55 Canadian peacekeepers , but military sources say the response was too general to satisfy the UN as it tries to restart serious talks on releasing 400 UN troops , including the Canadians .
The government complained to the Spanish ambassador Thursday about `` intrusive '' checks on Gibraltar citizens entering Spain .
The intensity of car and body searches by Spanish border police reportedly can cause delays of several hours .
David Davis , the Foreign Office minister for Europe , called in Spanish ambassador Alberto Aza Arias , according to a Foreign Office statement that described the checks as having `` seriously interfered with cross-border traffic and daily life in Gibraltar . ''
Davis told Arias `` the checks were intrusive and could not seriously be presented as a search for drugs and tobacco , '' the statement said .
`` Mr. Davis warned the checks could damage prospects for practical cooperation between the Gibraltar and Spanish authorities in a number of important areas of mutual concern , '' the Foreign Office statement said .
Spain claims sovereignty over the 5.8-square-kilometer -LRB- 2.25-square-mile -RRB- territory of limestone rock at the southern tip of the Iberian peninsula .
Gibraltar 's approximately 30,000 residents want continued allegiance to Britain , which since 1704 has held the strategic territory overlooking the mouth of the Mediterranean Sea .
Britain 's determination to retain Gibraltar has proved a chronic sore point in British-Spanish relations .
British-Spanish talks on Gibraltar 's future have been stalled since 1989 over the issue of who should control its airport .
Amnesty International accused the upcoming Summit of the Americas Thursday of paying too little attention to punishing human rights abuses in the hemisphere .
The human rights group also challenged the idea that trade and democracy alone can bring about respect for human rights .
Despite the advent of democracy to all Western Hemisphere countries except Cuba , `` The human rights records of far too many of the countries , including the United States , remain tarnished and dismal , '' said William Schulz , executive director of Amnesty International USA .
`` Most discouragingly , it appears as if the whole topic of human rights may receive the shortest of shrifts at the summit . ''
Human rights is one of many issues mentioned in the declaration to be signed next week by President Clinton and 33 other presidents from the Americas .
But the major focus of the summit , hosted by Clinton in Miami , will be the leaders ' pledge to create a hemisphere-wide free-trade area .
Mike Canning , a spokesman for the State Department office organizing the summit , rebutted Amnesty 's criticism .
Consultations among summit nations to produce the presidents ' communique `` more than adequately recognized the importance of protecting human rights , '' he said .
`` It 's not just something mentioned in passing .
This is something that the countries and the leaders are going to take very seriously at the summit . ''
But Argentine human rights activist Emilio Fermin Mignone , participating in the Amnesty International news conference , said the draft communique does not call for an end to impunity for the perpetrators of human rights abuses such as kidnappings , torture , rape and murder .
He called on Clinton and the other leaders to `` eliminate a tacit acceptance of impunity in the hemisphere . ''
Many countries that have switched from military dictatorships to democracy -- including Brazil , Argentina , Chile and Uruguay -- have amnesty laws or arrangements that permit human rights abusers to avoid prosecution , he noted .
Violators linked to mass killings or other notorious abuses in Peru , Colombia and El Salvador also went free , Schulz said .
Human rights groups have cited numerous Latin countries for gross human rights violations .
`` Sometimes children are killed simply because they are seen as a nuisance , a tragedy repeated again and gain for the street children of Brazil , Guatemala and Colombia , '' said an Amnesty report prepared for the Miami summit .
The report accuses the United States of police brutality and criticizes it for using the death penalty .
Guatemalan rights activist Carmen Angelica Valenzuela , a former professor and physician in Guatemala City , spoke Thursday of her abduction and torture by members of the Guatemalan army in 1990 , saying the military apparently considered her subversive .
She said Guatemala 's armed forces are `` directly responsible for the most brutal campaign of terror in the Western Hemisphere . ''
Yasser Arafat 's government on Thursday took control of the health and taxation systems in the West Bank , broadening Palestinian autonomy despite a pall cast on peacemaking by a series of Islamic terror attacks .
The move completed the initial stage of handing over day-to-day affairs in the West Bank to Palestinians .
It also came amid growing calls in Israel for shutting off Palestinians from Israel because of a series of attacks in which 32 Israelis have been killed since early October .
About 1,000 people gathered Thursday in the northern Israeli town of Afula for the funeral of the latest victim , 19-year-old woman soldier Liat Gabai , who was axed to death on Wednesday .
A suspect detained Wednesday , Wahib Abu Rub , 24 , from the West Bank town of Qabatiyah , has told interrogators he was from the Islamic Resistance Movement or Hamas , Israel radio said .
The same group claimed the Oct. 19 Tel Aviv bus bombing that killed 22 people .
Abu Rub admitted to the slaying in an interview on Israel television .
Speaking as he was led to the Nazareth court Thursday , he said he wanted to prove to fellow Palestinians he was n't collaborating with Israel .
`` They accused me of being a traitor .
I wanted to prove that I was n't , '' he said .
`` I killed the soldier to prove to my people I am a decent man . ''
Police Minister Moshe Shahal responded by calling Thursday for completely shutting off the West Bank and Gaza Strip from Israel .
`` There is no alternative other than to demand separation , '' Shahal said .
`` Separation means that we do not have to open the territory out of economic and employment concerns until the Palestinians prove that they can prevent attacks . ''
A closure could also bring further violence , by preventing thousands of Palestinian day workers from entering Israel to earn a living .
Palestinian and Israeli leaders have blamed growing support for Islamic radicals on economic troubles in the PLO-run Gaza Strip .
Despite the violence , talks were expected to begin next week on stage two of the autonomy given Gaza and the West Bank town of Jericho last May -- redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank and Palestinian elections .
Israel 's concern for the safety of 120,000 Jewish settlers has prompted some officials to propose skipping the interim phase altogether and negotiating the final status of these territories now , rather than in 1996 .
Still , a gradual hand over of responsibilities to Palestinians proceeded in the West Bank where two ceremonies were held marking the transfer of the health and tax systems .
The PLO has since August also taken charge of education , tourism and welfare in the West Bank .
`` What we have completed gives the Palestinians a first entrance to the West Bank , '' said West Bank military governor Brig. Gen. Gadi Zohar , signing over the tax department to Palestinian Finance Minister Mohammed Nashashibi in Ramallah .
In Brussels , foreign donors this week released dlrs 125 million pledged earlier , mostly to help the Palestinians meet running costs for a few months .
Deputy Finance Minister Atef Alawneh said he hoped to collect dlrs 300-400 million annually in taxes to try to overcome dependency on donor nations .
Russia on Thursday upset NATO 's plans for expanding its membership to former Warsaw Pact foes by claiming the move would create a new division in Europe .
In an extraordinary session , Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev departed from prepared remarks to criticize the allies for agreeing to a U.S. initiative to draw up the terms and conditions for future membership .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told a group of grim-faced foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
Afterward , Portuguese Foreign Minister Jose Manuel Durao Barroso said Kozyrev `` threw a bucket of cold water on the meeting . ''
The Russian had been invited to the meeting to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow .
The special ties had been designed to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
But Kozyrev refused to agree to the documents .
He said he read the ministers ' statement on membership and immediately called Russian President Boris Yeltsin .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' he said impromptu remarks that were broadcast to reporters at the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
Willy Claes , the alliance 's new secretary-general , sought to respond to Kozyrev 's remarks .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO .
... There is nothing new , '' he told the Russian just before he left NATO headquarters .
`` We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst only added to the alliance 's woes .
There have been unprecedented strains in recent weeks between the United States and its European allies over the crisis in Bosnia .
In an effort to heal the wounds , Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It was a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the Europeans , led by Britain and France .
In the past , Moscow has strongly opposed any move by NATO to draw in its one-time partners in the Warsaw Pact , the defunct Eastern military alliance led by the Soviet Union .
The Europeans in particular have been uneasy about pushing expansion for fear of upsetting Russia , still a formidable military power at the edge of allied territory .
In an effort to overcome Russian objections , the allies had agreed to develop a `` far-reaching relationship , corresponding with Russia 's size , importance and capabilities . ''
They had insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc threatening Russia .
`` Having just overcome the division of Europe , we have no desire to see the emergence of new lines of partition , '' the ministers said in a statement .
NATO has been anguishing in recent years over whether -- and when -- to open its doors to its former foes in Eastern Europe .
Poland , Hungary and others have repeatedly demanded coveted membership cards and the security guarantees that would go with it .
In an effort to meet their demands -- but without upsetting Russia , the allies thought they had found a good formula .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
`` We took significant , concrete steps toward ... expansion '' of the alliance , Christopher said afterward .
The move was intended to be a cautious one .
No list of front-runners for membership will be made ; no date set for the first admissions will be set .
But Kozyrev accused NATO of trying to make a fresh division on the European continent .
Some members of Partnership for Peace , he said , were destined to become members , while others would remain behind .
He said the Russians too `` do not exclude the possibility of wanting to become members of NATO . ''
He insisted `` There needs to be some sort of clarification . ''
