Russia wants its key western partners to back a confederation of Bosnian Serbs with neighboring Serbia itself , Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev said Thursday .
`` We do support the suggestion that the ` Contact Group ' comes out with an unambiguous recognition '' of Bosnian Serbs ' right to forge political links with the government in Belgrade , Kozyrev told reporters .
The foreign ministers of the Contact Group nations -- Russia , France , Britain , Germany and the United States -- meet here on Friday to debate the way forward in Bosnia .
On Thursday , the United States swung behind the European view that diplomacy is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It thus sought to heal a rift with the European allies over NATO 's use of force in Bosnia .
Kozyrev met here with this NATO counterparts .
Speaking to reporters as he left the NATO headquarters , he said a Serb confederation would be akin to the confederation of Croatia and the Muslim-led government in Sarajevo .
The latter is part of the current Contact Group peace plan for Bosnia that Bosnian Serbs have refused to accept .
Kozyrev said if Croatia and the government in Sarajevo can link up politically , `` the Bosnian Serbs have ... equal right to confederate with Serbia .
Earlier , French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said he hoped Friday 's meeting of the Contact Group would launch `` a new initiative '' to end the fighting .
Juppe will travel to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , on Sunday with British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd for talks with President Slobodan Milosevic .
Rewards given to North Korea for promising to freeze its nuclear program could lead to nuclear blackmail from other rogue nations such as Iran , senators contended in a hearing Thursday .
The Clinton administration 's chief negotiator with North Korea , Robert Gallucci , countered that the agreement reached on Oct. 21 has already stopped the North Korean nuclear weapons program and `` achieves more than we and the international community thought possible '' when talks began in early 1993 .
But Gallucci met a skeptical audience in the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on East Asian and Pacific affairs .
`` I have serious reservations about giving North Korea the benefit of the doubt , '' said subcommittee Chairman Charles Robb .
Robb said the agreement to supply North Korea with oil and new nuclear power reactors in exchange for shutting down its current nuclear program was a `` fundamental shift '' in the U.S. policy of penalizing nations that violate international nuclear proliferation accords .
`` Some have even characterized this as nuclear blackmail '' that might encourage such countries as Iran to demand similar favors for not developing nuclear weapons programs , he said .
Republican Sen. Frank Murkowski a leading critic of the agreement with North Korea , faulted the administration for giving North Korea years before it will have to open up two radioactive waste sites to international inspectors .
The sites are thought to provide a key to whether Pyongyang has diverted plutonium for nuclear weapons .
`` Why did n't we insist that they come clean ? ''
But Murkowski , the likely next chairman of the subcommittee when the Republicans take over Congress next year , did not suggest , as he has in past interviews , that he might try to block the accord .
`` I 'm not sitting here saying we should cancel the agreement , '' he said .
Under the agreement , an international group headed by South Korea and Japan is to supply the North with two light water nuclear reactors , worth about dlrs 4 billion , that are less susceptible to plutonium extraction .
The United States will provide 150,000 tons of heavy oil next year and 500,000 tons a year after that to compensate North Korea for shutting down its existing 5-megawatt gas graphite reactor and scuttling plans to build 50 - and 200-megawatt reactors .
The United States also agreed to remove some trade barriers and take initial steps toward opening diplomatic contacts .
North Korea also agreed not to reprocess 8,000 spent fuel rods and to eventually open up all facilities to International Atomic Energy Agency inspections .
Gallucci stressed that all major technology for the nuclear reactors will be withheld until North Korea allows the inspections , ship the spent fuel rods out of the country and dismantles its current reactor program .
`` We entered into this agreement without any uncertainty or delusions about past North Korean behavior .
The agreement framework is not based on trust , '' he said .
Gallucci acknowledged that U.S. negotiators made concessions on the inspections issue , but said they did not harm U.S. security interests .
Russians , angry at having to pay for U.S. visa applications even if they are rejected , lashed out Thursday at `` the latest insult '' to would-be visitors to the United States .
Ambassador Thomas Pickering announced the $ 20 application fee on Wednesday as part of changes intended to improve an application process that has been criticized as rude and humiliating .
The fee , charged on top of the price of a visa , took effect Thursday .
`` I wonder why we 're trying so hard to go to this ` wonderful ' country , America , when its embassy has so little respect for us , '' said Sergei Tumbasov , a construction engineer hoping to go to Virginia on business .
Tumbasov said no one told him about the fee until he arrived at the embassy Thursday morning , not even the consular officer he spoke to the day before .
The application fee , equal to nearly a week 's wages for the average Russian , is especially painful for the more than 100 visa applicants who are rejected every day at the U.S. Embassy .
`` This unexpected fee is the final insult in an absolutely absurd process , '' said Dr. Marina Orlova , an eye doctor from the prestigious Fyodorov Clinic .
She was turned away for failing to prove she would return to Russia .
`` Who do they think we are ?
We 're doctors , professionals , '' she said .
If Orlova returns with documents to support her application , she has to pay another $ 20 fee .
That does n't include the fee for the visa itself , which is $ 20 for one entry , or $ 120 for a multiple-entry permit .
`` The system is made for the mafia .
No one else can afford it , '' Orlova added loudly , prompting a guard to ask her to leave the crowded sidewalk in front of the embassy .
An average of 550 people apply for visas at the U.S. Embassy every day , and about 133,000 people have applied in the past year , according to the embassy .
The consular office is n't big enough to hold the crowd of waiting applicants , many of whom wait for hours outdoors , even in Moscow 's bitter December weather .
Vladimir Gulagin , a technical consultant planning a business trip to New York , brushed falling snow off a suitcase full of documents Thursday .
Gulagin was refused a visa on Tuesday and was told to return with further documentation .
He was not told , however , about the new fee .
`` It 's a good thing I had borrowed money from my wife this morning , '' Gulagin said .
`` I spent most of my paycheck yesterday , getting all these documents copied . ''
The steps announced Wednesday by Pickering include an `` express lane '' and easier processing for business visa applications .
Vasily Ignatkin , head of the visa department at the Diplomatic Corps Administration Bureau , welcomed the changes , but said it would be `` some time before any serious improvements are evident . ''
Those in line outside the embassy were skeptical .
`` It 's all talk , '' Tumbasov said .
`` They 're trying to comfort us while they ask us for more money . ''
Russia upset NATO 's plans for expanding its membership to former Warsaw Pact foes Thursday by claiming the move would create a new division in Europe .
In an extraordinary session , Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev departed from a prepared speech to criticize the allies for ordering aides to draw up terms and conditions for future membership .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
The Russian had been invited to the meeting to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow .
The special ties had been designed to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
But Kozyrev refused to agree to the documents .
He said he read the ministers ' statement on membership and immediately called Russian President Boris Yeltsin .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' he said impromptu remarks that were broadcast to reporters at the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
Willy Claes , the Western military alliance 's new secretary-general , sought to respond to Kozyrev 's remarks .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO .
... There is nothing new , '' he told the Russian just before he left NATO headquarters .
`` We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst only added to the alliance 's woes .
There have been unprecedented strains in recent weeks between the United States and its European allies over the crisis in Bosnia .
In an effort to heal the wounds , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It was a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the Europeans , led by Britain and France .
In the past , Moscow has strongly opposed any move by NATO to draw in its one-time partners in the Warsaw Pact , the defunct Eastern military alliance led by the Soviet Union .
The Europeans in particular have been uneasy about pushing expansion for fear of upsetting Russia , still a formidable military power at the edge of allied territory .
In an effort to overcome Russian objections , the allies had agreed to develop a `` far-reaching relationship , corresponding with Russia 's size , importance and capabilities . ''
They had insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc threatening Russia .
`` Having just overcome the division of Europe , we have no desire to see the emergence of new lines of partition , '' the ministers said in a statement .
NATO has been anguishing in recent years over whether -- and when -- to open its doors to its former foes in Eastern Europe .
Poland , Hungary and others have repeatedly demanded coveted membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
In an effort to meet their demands -- but without upsetting Russia , the allies thought they had found a good formula .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
The latest assassinations of two journalists in Algeria was carried out by gunmen who forced them out of their homes , then shot and decapitated them , Algerian television reported Thursday .
The killings bring the number of journalists slain to 27 since the profession became a target of Islamic extremists 18 months ago , according to the New York-based Committee to Protect Journalists .
Ahmed Issaad , a reporter for the state television , and Nasseredine Lekhal , a journalist for the state-run daily El-Massa , were earlier reported by security services to have been stabbed to death in Boufarik , south of Algiers .
Three other people were also slain , including the vice president and a member of Boufarik 's municipal council , appointed to replace fundamentalists elected but later banned from office .
TV footage showed the victims ' bullet-riddled , headless bodies .
More than 11,000 people have been killed in a three-year insurgency pitting Muslim fundamentalist militants against the army-backed government .
The toll sharply increased in November , with more than 400 people killed in the bloodiest month since the start of the insurgency .
Most of the known victims for November were extremists killed by security forces , ordered to step up their campaign to `` eradicate terrorists '' after a failed government effort to negotiate with fundamentalists .
The militants , depicting the media as government pawns , have designated journalists as a prime target of their assassination campaign , along with foreigners and intellectuals .
An estimated 200 Algerian journalists have left the country because of the killings and harsh government action against newspapers which violate strict security regulations .
