President Ernesto Zedillo promised Thursday to maintain the tenuous cease-fire in southern Mexico and fight a war on the crushing poverty that inspired the rebellion .
Zedillo sought in his inaugural address before 1,500 foreign and local dignitaries to be a voice of reconciliation in a country shaken by kidnappings , assassination and the New Year 's Day rebellion in Chiapas .
`` This year Mexican spirits have been saddened by the events in Chiapas , by the violence and even more so by conditions of deep-rooted injustice ; by the conditions of extreme poverty and neglect that fuels that violence , '' he said .
But Zedillo , who had not yet publicly said how he would handle the Chiapas rebellion , signaled he intended to try to restart peace talks last held in March .
The rebels rejected one peace plan by Zedillo 's predecessor , Carlos Salinas de Gortari , and broke off talks with the government in October .
`` I am convinced that it is possible to achieve a new negotiation in Chiapas that will lead us to a just honorable and definitive peace , '' Zedillo said to loud applause in the Chamber of Deputies , where he took his oath .
`` There will be no violence by the government and I am confident that neither will there be by those who dissent .
The Mexican army will maintain its unilateral cease-fire . ''
Zedillo was the campaign manager for the ruling party 's first candidate , Luis Donaldo Colosio , and assumed the candidacy after Colosio 's March 23 assassination in Tijuana .
Six months later , another top political figure , ruling party secretary-general Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu , was assassinated .
`` The brutal assassinations of two of Mexico 's most outstanding public figures have deeply hurt our citizens .
Some seeds of concern and doubt regarding some institutions , have divided the people of Mexico , '' he said .
Both killings raised speculation of a political conspiracy to silence reformist voices in government since the victims were relative moderates within the Institutional Revolutionary Party .
`` Thus far , the investigations have not been to the entire satiafaction of society .
We the people of Mexico want to be sure we know the truth .
At this moment I am specifically directing the attorney general of the republic to significantly intensify the investigations , '' Zedillo said .
`` We will not rest until justice has been served , '' he said .
Mexico 's new president , Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon , is a bookish , mild-mannered economist with little experience in the rough and tumble of Mexican politics .
He was a poor public speaker and lacked charisma when he was first pushed into the race .
But he appears to have had some intensive coaching since his election last summer and his inaugural speech Thursday was well delivered .
Colleagues give Zedillo , 42 , high marks as an economist , administrator and negotiator and say that unlike former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari , whom he succeeds , he prefers conciliation to confrontation .
He is more comfortable at home , analyzing a difficult economic problem , or sharing a meal with Patricia Nilda Velasco , his wife of 21 years , than attending a diplomatic reception .
His first exposure to politics came when the first presidential candidate of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party , Luis Donaldo Colosio , named him campaign manager .
Zedillo ran for the presidency only after Colosio , a charismatic crowd pleaser , was shot dead March 23 at a Tijuana rally .
The new candidate looked downright bewildered when he began campaigning .
`` I certainly never thought I 'd be here , never in my life , '' Zedillo said recently .
But his party , which has not lost a presidential election in 65 years , geared up its huge machine and got him elected Aug. 21 .
The Zedillos , who have five children , have long lived in Lomas de Las Quebradas , a middle-class neighborhood at the foot of a towering dormant volcano , on Mexico City 's southern edge .
He understands what poor people go through .
He was one of them for years .
Born in Mexico City on Dec. 27 , 1951 , Zedillo was the second of six children of Rodolfo Zedillo Castillo , a poor electrician , and Martha Alicia Ponce de Leon , who abandoned her studies to become a homemaker .
Work was scarce and word was jobs were available along the U.S. border .
So the family moved to Mexicali and the muddy neighborhood of Pueblo Nuevo , just yards from the California border .
Mrs. Zedillo was the mainstay of the struggling family .
To make ends meet , she sold candy at a neighborhood movie house , and the children could watch movies free on Saturdays .
Zedillo shined shoes and sold newspapers on the streets , learning to speak a `` Spanglish '' variant called `` pocho . ''
Few of his childhood dreams became reality .
One was to become a big league baseball player , he confided to a friend .
Instead , he went on to become a straight-A student .
After he finished high school , he and his elder brother Luis Eduardo moved to Mexico City in 1966 , sharing a tiny apartment in a low-income project .
Zedillo studied economics at the National Polytechnic Institute , the so-called poor man 's university .
Still poor , the rest of the family moved back to Mexico City in search of a better life .
The death of his mother a few months later came as a terrific blow -- she was only 38 .
Zedillo joined Mexico 's ruling party in 1967 , and party bosses helped him get bigger and better scholarships that allowed postgraduate work at the University of Bradford , England , and the University of Colorado .
He also taught at the Polytechnic , where he met his future wife .
A few weeks after their wedding , they left for New Haven , Conn. , where he earned a master 's , then a doctorate in economics at Yale in 1978 .
Back in Mexico City , Zedillo worked for the Bank of Mexico -- the nation 's federal reserve .
He then moved to the Treasury Department and then the Department of Budget and Planning .
There he became friends with Salinas and other young technocrats , most of them Ivy League graduates bent on modernizing Mexico .
In open contempt for U.N. authority in Bosnia , Serb fighters kidnapped more international peacekeepers and pressed their stranglehold on a town in the northwest on Thursday .
In a small sign of willingness to negotiate , however , Bosnian Serbs agreed to meet Yasushi Akashi , the top U.N. envoy , on Friday in Pale , their stronghold east of Sarajevo .
The Serbs snubbed U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali on Wednesday because he insisted talks be held in Sarajevo , capital of the Muslim-led , internationall recognized governmment .
Bosnian Serb fighters on Tuesday crossed the border into Croatia and seized seven Ukrainian peacekeepers , taking them and a U.N. armored carrier into Bosnian Serb-held territory , Alexander Ivanko , a U.N. spokesman , said Thursday .
He said the United Nations has not heard from the troops since .
The Ukrainians ' observation point is now occupied by the Serbs , allowing for the unimpeded movement into Bosnia of equipment and personnel from Serb-held Croatia .
Serb fighters from the two countries have joined forces in the Bihac offensive .
The Serbs have taken more than 400 U.N. peacekeepers hostage as insurance against further NATO airstrikes since allied planes bombed Serb positions in Bosnia and Croatia three times last week .
Continuing the squeeze on the Bosnian government , Serbs again denied U.N. requests to supply the Bihac enclave and other vulnerable U.N.-patrolled sites with food and supplies .
Monique Tuffelli , the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees staffer in the Bihac enclave , said food stocks would last only another week .
`` We have run out almost of everything , '' she said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press .
The last UNHCR food convoy reached Bihac on Oct. 1 .
Between May and October , Serbs allowed only a dozen to pass through their territory .
The Serbs agreed to the Akashi meeting after Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose , the U.N. commander in Bosnia , traveled to Pale for talks with Radovan Karadzic and other Bosnian Serb leaders .
Rose 's talks in Pale were to have focused on Bihac and its demilitarization , but there appeared to be no narrowing of differences that could end the siege .
Momcilo Krajisnik , leader of the so-called Bosnian Serb assembly , again rejected a three-month cease-fire , which the Bosnian government supports , saying Serbs would accept only a permanent cease-fire leading to a formal end of war .
The Sarajevo government fears a permanent agreement would cement the Serb hold over 70 percent of the country .
An international peace plan , which the Bosnians have accepted and the Serbs rejected , would force Serbs to settle for 49 percent .
With new U.S. support for Europe 's position that diplomacy , not further NATO airstrikes , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian war , French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and his British counterpart , Douglas Hurd , planned to meet Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade on Sunday .
Milosevic is considered responsible for the violent breakup of Yugoslavia .
But he still has influence with the Bosnian Serbs , despite his breaking with them last summer after they rejected the international peace plan .
Senior Western officials now talk of altering that plan to allow the Bosnian Serbs to establish confederal links with Yugoslavia .
The plan also gives Bosnian Croats the right to set up a confederation with Croatia .
Critics , however , say that is appeasement and a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal , a Greater Serbia .
But Krajisnik said possible linkage with Yugoslavia was not as important as changing the proposed territorial maps , the Bosnian Serb news agency SRNA reported .
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said food and fuel supplies for peacekeepers were running increasingly short in the government-held eastern Bosnian enclaves , as well as Bihac .
Heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire erupted around Bihac late Wednesday and early Thursday , along with heavy fighting southwest and south of the Bihac pocket , U.N. officials said .
Two civilians were killed in Bihac Wednesday by gunfire , Ms. Tuffelli said , but overall the area was calmer Thursday morning with only sporadic shelling and small arms fire .
Bosnian radio and Bihac regional officials painted a different picture by Thursday afternoon .
Radio said Serbs intensified their attacks later in the day on Bihac , Cazin and Velika Kladusa , all government-held towns in the Bihac enclave .
Hamdija Kabiljagic , the regional mayor , also reported increased fighting along the perimeters of Bihac and shelling of the town itself .
He accused the United Nations of deliberately downplaying the situation .
There was no U.N. confirmation of the reported afternoon upsurge in fighting .
In downtown Sarajevo , Serbs targeted two government buildings with anti-tank missiles , wounding four people .
Sarajevo 's airport remained closed , and the humanitarian airlift suspended , because Serbs had not given security guarantees and are able to threaten planes ' approach route with surface-to-air missiles .
A fireworks warehouse exploded in a town in southern Brazil , killing at least one person and wounding about a dozen others , a fire official said Thursday .
The explosion occurred at 9:30 p.m. -LRB- 1130 GMT -RRB- Wednesday on a block of small shops in the downtown business district of Uruguaiana , a city of 120,000 people near the border with Argentina .
The blast leveled five one-story buildings and damaged 10 stores .
Two people are believed missing under the wreckage , said Sgt. Paulo Flores of the Uruguaiana fire department .
`` The explosion was felt more than 30 blocks away , '' Flores said .
Earlier , a Uruguayan fire official who helped contain the blaze said as many as 10 people were killed and 20 were hurt in the blast .
Brazilian , Argentine and Uruguayan firemen continued to fight several fires around the blast site on Thursday afternoon .
