Proponents of the world-trade agreement chant a mantra of impressive-sounding figures : a dlrs 744 billion global tax cut , dlrs 150 billion a year in added U.S. economic growth , up to 500,000 new American jobs .
But some of the pact 's most important provisions deal with ideas , not numbers .
For the first time in its 47-year history , the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade will include basic rules protecting patents , copyrights and other so-called intellectual property .
That 's a powerful catalyst for more exports and investment in some of America 's most dynamic industries .
With the sweeping deal to liberalize commerce , the 124 nations in GATT not only agree to slash import duties and other trade barriers , they pledge to prosecute sales of knock-off drugs , purloined software , pirated videos and the like .
That may sound trivial .
But U.S. companies that make idea-intensive products lose tens of billions of dollars annually in potential export revenues because thieves are stealing their stuff .
GATT should especially be welcomed in places like Research Triangle Park , N.C. , and northern New Jersey , where many pharmaceutical manufacturers are concentrated , and California 's Silicon Valley and the Seattle area , home to numerous software makers and other high-tech firms .
Such industries are significant creators of new , high-paying jobs .
They 're also among the most aggressive exporters .
`` Some of GATT 's biggest winners are high-tech industries , those that are our most globally competitive and make world-leading products , '' says C. Michael Aho , international economist for Prudential Securities Inc. `` The rules provide a more certain framework for them and should open markets overseas . ''
For companies like Merck and Co. to develop a world-class medication or Intel Corp. to devise a faster computer chip , hundreds of millions of dollars must be spent on research and testing .
The GATT provisions , which require many countries to enact their first intellectual property protection laws , will encourage more American investment in new products , says David Walters , chief economist at the U.S. Trade Representative 's office .
Companies partly base their research and development budgets on expected rate of return and market size .
`` If you 're a pharmaceutical company investing lots of money in developing a new drug , you have X number of years to recoup your R and D costs , '' Walters says .
`` If a country rips off your patent and pays you next to nothing , getting minimum standards of intellectual property protection is very important .
If you 're a software developer , it 's also real important . ''
The U.S. government estimates that American drug makers lose roughly dlrs 5 billion annually from piracy worldwide -- a big percentage of the nearly dlrs 28 billion worth of products they 're expected to sell overseas this year .
`` If you look at any of the top-ten selling products in the world market , you can assume they are copied , '' said Tom Bombelles , a trade expert for the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America .
With GATT 's new Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property rules , or TRIPS , he said , `` our companies over the long run can save several billion a year in lost sales . ''
One disadvantage is that many developing countries , which are the fastest-growing markets , get 10 years to comply .
Still , executives at Pfizer Inc. are happy that foreign copycats eventually wo n't be able to sell knockoffs of products like Diflucan , the world 's leading anti-fungal drug and a medication widely used by cancer and AIDS patients .
`` It enables us to continue funding research , '' said Lou Clemente , a senior vice president at New York-based Pfizer .
`` As the company is more successful , there 's going to be more employment in the United States . ''
Other prominent beneficiaries will be producers of computer software -- a U.S.-dominated industry since its inception .
Overseas piracy of personal computer applications such as word processors and spreadsheets alone cost American makers dlrs 6 billion in 1993 , says the Software Publishers Association , a Washington-based trade group .
Exports of such programs , by comparison , were about dlrs 4.5 billion last year and total worldwide sales were dlrs 8 billion .
`` There are n't many businesses that can function when they 're suffering theft that nearly equals revenues , '' says association counsel Mark Traphagen .
`` For smaller companies , it becomes a practical question whether they want to export and suffer serious piracy . ''
Moscow backed off from a threat to send troops Thursday into the breakaway Chechnya republic , where leaders defied a Russian ultimatum and called on armed volunteers to defend their capital .
Air attacks continued on the outskirts of Grozny , the Chechen capital , claiming at least a few civilian lives .
And a Russian delegation arrived from Moscow and began talks with Chechen officials .
Meanwhile , residents continued to flee the mainly Muslim city of 300,000 people in the Caucasus Mountains of southern Russia .
The city has become a war zone between forces loyal to Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , who declared independence from Moscow in 1991 , and Chechen rebels trying to topple him .
Dudayev accuses Moscow of arming and leading the rebels , who launched an offensive last week that began with helicopters and escalated in recent days to jet fighters .
Russia says it offers the rebels only political support .
It refuses to recognize independence for Chechnya , which was incorporated into the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
President Boris Yeltsin threatened on Tuesday to impose a state of emergency in Chechnya if both sides did not surrender prisoners and stop fighting by Thursday morning .
On Thursday evening , Yeltsin 's office issued an altered text of the ultimatum saying `` there was some disagreement in the media in interpreting certain clauses . ''
The reissued document skipped all reference to a state of emergency .
Trying a different tack , Yeltsin offered limited amnesty Thursday to Chechens who `` voluntarily lay down arms by Dec. 15 . ''
`` The use of force in Chechnya is doomed to failure , '' said Sergei Yushenkov , head of the Russian parliament 's Defense Committee , who led the delegation to Grozny and met briefly with Dudayev .
In another sign that Russia sought to avoid direct confrontation , Defense Minister Pavel Grachev told reporters in Moscow that some Russian servicemen who `` carried out certain military tasks for material compensation '' from anti-Dudayev forces had been brought back to central Russia .
He said more would be evacuated .
Grachev insisted such servicemen were not in Chechnya on Army orders .
Dudayev 's government captured up to 70 Russians in fighting last weekend and alleges some were Army officers and soldiers .
Chechen officials initially threatened to execute them ; Dudayev said Thursday they would be tried in court .
Despite Moscow 's softened tone , it still appeared to be beefing up troops on the borders of Chechnya , according to media reports .
Dudayev , who held a news conference in the basement of his presidential palace as jets roared overhead , remained defiant , calling Yeltsin 's government a `` satanic power . ''
Dudayev said his house had been bombed Thursday morning .
A small military air base near Grozny also was hit in the air raid Thursday .
And missiles hit a residential district at Katayama , about 20 kilometers -LRB- 12 miles -RRB- from town , according to duty surgeon Aslanbek Otsalayev at Grozny 's main hospital .
Two women 's corpses were at the hospital , and Otsalayev said four people , including a 1-year-old , were killed and at least six wounded .
In Freedom Square outside Dudayev 's offices , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches while a tank maneuvered into position .
Elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
Although the economy is in shambles , many Chechens feel united in one thing : distrust of Russia .
`` I do n't like the opposition or Dudayev , but I 'll fight the Russians , '' said a restaurant owner who declined to be identified .
Many Russians are content to let the Chechens go their own way , according to a poll Thursday by the International Opinion Research Center .
The poll of 3,250 people said 74.2 percent believe Russia should recognize Chechnya 's independence , while 5.5 percent said it should n't and 20.3 said they could n't answer .
The margin of error was 1 percent .
