The reissued document skipped all reference to a state of emergency .
Trying a different tack , Yeltsin offered limited amnesty Thursday to Chechens who `` voluntarily lay down arms by Dec. 15 . ''
`` The use of force in Chechnya is doomed to failure , '' said Sergei Yushenkov , head of the Russian parliament 's Defense Committee , who led the delegation to Grozny and met briefly with Dudayev .
In another sign that Russia sought to avoid direct confrontation , Defense Minister Pavel Grachev told reporters in Moscow that some Russian servicemen who `` carried out certain military tasks for material compensation '' from anti-Dudayev forces had been brought back to central Russia .
He said more would be evacuated .
Grachev insisted such servicemen were not in Chechnya on Army orders .
Dudayev 's government captured up to 70 Russians in fighting last weekend and alleges some were Army officers and soldiers .
Chechen officials initially threatened to execute them ; Dudayev said Thursday they would be tried in court .
Despite Moscow 's softened tone , it still appeared to be beefing up troops on the borders of Chechnya , according to media reports .
Dudayev , who held a news conference in the basement of his presidential palace as jets roared overhead , remained defiant , calling Yeltsin 's government a `` satanic power . ''
Dudayev said his house had been bombed Thursday morning .
A small military air base near Grozny also was hit in the air raid Thursday .
And missiles hit a residential district at Katayama , about 20 kilometers -LRB- 12 miles -RRB- from town , according to duty surgeon Aslanbek Otsalayev at Grozny 's main hospital .
Two women 's corpses were at the hospital , and Otsalayev said four people , including a 1-year-old , were killed and at least six wounded .
In Freedom Square outside Dudayev 's offices , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches while a tank maneuvered into position .
Elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
Although the economy is in shambles , many Chechens feel united in one thing : distrust of Russia .
`` I do n't like the opposition or Dudayev , but I 'll fight the Russians , '' said a restaurant owner who declined to be identified .
Many Russians are content to let the Chechens go their own way , according to a poll Thursday by the International Opinion Research Center .
The poll of 3,250 people said 74.2 percent believe Russia should recognize Chechnya 's independence , while 5.5 percent said it should n't and 20.3 said they could n't answer .
The margin of error was 1 percent .
CHICAGO -LRB- AP -RRB- - Soybean futures steepened their slide Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as nervous speculators cashed out .
Wheat , corn and oat futures rose modestly .
Soybean traders have become increasingly doubtful of the market 's ability to remain above dlrs 5.50 a bushel in light of this year 's record-large harvest .
Soybeans have been propped up by strong world demand for soybean oil and other vegetable oils , but those markets have been volatile this week .
`` This market stayed up a lot longer than everybody thought it would , '' said Jack Salzieder , marketing consultant with Commodity Services Inc. in West Des Moines , Iowa .
Soybean prices have fallen for three straight days .
Salzieder said soybean prices could be poised for a drop similar to wheat prices , which have plunged about 9 percent since early October .
In trading Wednesday , wheat for December delivery rose 2 1-2 cents to dlrs 3.74 3-4 a bushel ; December corn rose 1 cent to dlrs 2.14 a bushel ; December oats rose 2 cents to dlrs 1.08 a bushel ; January soybeans fell 6 3-4 cents to dlrs 5.56 3-4 a bushel .
Tennis great Martina Navratilova says she 's right where she wants to be : traveling and playing for fun after 22 years of pressure and high-stakes competition .
`` Now I will rest more .
I will travel the world , but will keep on playing tennis for pleasure , '' said Navratilova before her first public matches since retiring last month after a first-round loss in the Virginia Slims Championships in New York .
Navratilova , 38 , was joined in Florence by one of the rising stars of women 's tennis : 14-year-old Martina Hingis , the reigning Wimbledon junior 's champion .
They were scheduled to play a match dubbed the `` generations game . ''
The Czech-born Hingis , who lives in Switzerland , made her professional debut in October .
Navratilova said she has considered teaching tennis , but has `` not yet developed my own method . ''
`` Why did I not retire last year ? ''
`` My heart told me that 1994 was the year to call it a day .
I might be wrong when I take decision with the head , but certainly not when they come from the heart . ''
Earlier , Navratilova and Hingis played on opposite sides in a mixed-doubles match .
Navratilova was teamed with Italian film producer Mario Cecchi Gori and Hingis played alongside retired Italian soccer star Giancarlo Antognoni .
The 31st Chess Olympiad began in Moscow 's Cosmos Hotel on Thursday with a record 122 national sides competing in the men 's event and 78 countries in the separate women 's section .
Each men 's team has four players and each women 's team three .
The Olympiad was originally to be held in Thessalonika , Greece , but the event was canceled because of financial difficulties .
The World Chess Federation was then helped by world chess champion Garry Kasparov , who rallied financial support to hold the event in Moscow .
The backing came even though last year he had set up an entirely new organization , the Professional Chess Association , with Britain 's Nigel Short .
Kasparov also heads the Russian team , which is favored to win , followed closely by the English national side which boasts Nigel Short , Kasparov 's last challenger for the world title , on board one .
Kasparov , however , was rested for the first of the 14 games and will only play when the Russian side begins to face the strongest opposition .
The Russians dropped half a point when Yevgeny Bareev was held to a surprising draw .
Notable absentees from the Olympiad include Anatoly Karpov , the current FIDE world champion , Gata Kamsky of the United States and Viswanathan Anand of India .
Kamsky and Anand declined invitations as they are currently preparing for the final elimination of the PCA World Championship Cycle for the right to meet Kasparov .
That event will be held in Las Palmas in April .
Karpov , however , would not play below Kasparov on the Russian side and also does not participate .
In the women 's section , the favorites are the Hungarians , who boast two of the three Polgar sisters , Zsusza and Sofia .
The third sister , Judit , is representing Hungary in the men 's event as she is currently the top player in Hungary .
Results of first round after six hours of play :
England-Mongolia 3-0 -LRB- 1 to finish -RRB-
United States-South Africa 3.5-0 .5
Holland-Tajikistan 3-0 -LRB- 1 to finish -RRB-
