Yasser Arafat 's government on Thursday took control of health and taxation in the West Bank , broadening Palestinian autonomy despite a pall cast on peacemaking by Islamic terror attacks .
The move completed the initial stage of handing over day-to-day affairs in the West Bank to Palestinians .
It also came amid growing calls in Israel for shutting off Palestinians from Israel because of a series of attacks in which 32 Israelis have been killed since early October .
About 1,000 people gathered Thursday in the northern Israeli town of Afula for the funeral of the latest victim , 19-year-old woman soldier Liat Gabai , who was axed to death Wednesday .
A suspect detained Wednesday , Wahib Abu Rub , 24 , from the West Bank town of Qabatiyah , has told interrogators he was from the Islamic Resistance Movement or Hamas , Israel radio said .
The same group claimed the Oct. 19 Tel Aviv bus bombing that killed 22 people .
Abu Rub admitted to the slaying in an interview on Israel television .
He said as he was led to the Nazareth court Thursday that he wanted to prove to fellow Palestinians he was n't collaborating with Israel .
`` They accused me of being a traitor .
I wanted to prove that I was n't , '' he said .
`` I killed the soldier to prove to my people I am a decent man . ''
Police Minister Moshe Shahal responded by calling Thursday for completely shutting off the West Bank and Gaza Strip from Israel .
`` There is no alternative other than to demand separation , '' Shahal said .
`` Separation means that we do not have to open the territory out of economic and employment concerns until the Palestinians prove that they can prevent attacks . ''
A closure could also bring further violence , by preventing thousands of Palestinian day workers from entering Israel to earn a living .
Palestinian and Israeli leaders have blamed growing support for Islamic radicals on economic troubles in the PLO-run Gaza Strip .
Despite the violence , talks were expected to begin next week on stage two of the autonomy given Gaza and the West Bank town of Jericho last May -- redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank and Palestinian elections .
Israel 's concern for the safety of 120,000 Jewish settlers has prompted some officials to propose skipping the interim phase altogether and negotiating the final status of these territories now , rather than in 1996 .
Still , a gradual hand over of responsibilities to Palestinians proceeded in the West Bank , where two ceremonies were held marking the transfer of the health and tax systems .
Since August , the Palestine Liberation Organization also has taken charge of education , tourism and welfare in the West Bank .
`` What we have completed gives the Palestinians a first entrance to the West Bank , '' said West Bank military governor Brig. Gen. Gadi Zohar , signing over the tax department to Palestinian Finance Minister Mohammed Nashashibi in Ramallah .
In Brussels , Belgium , foreign donors this week released dlrs 125 million pledged earlier , mostly to help the Palestinians meet running costs for a few months .
Deputy Finance Minister Atef Alawneh said he hoped to collect dlrs 300-400 million annually in taxes to try to overcome dependency on donor nations .
Russia protested NATO 's plan on Thursday for expanding its membership to east European countries and backed out of a program to improve cooperation between Moscow and the alliance .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev departed from a prepared speech to criticize the allies .
He said their decision earlier Thursday to draw up the terms and conditions for future NATO membership would create a new division in Europe .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told a group of grim-faced foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization .
Afterward , Portuguese Foreign Minister Jose Manuel Durao Barroso said Kozyrev `` threw a bucket of cold water on the meeting . ''
The Russian had been invited to the meeting to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow .
The special ties had been designed to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
But Kozyrev refused to agree to the documents .
He said he read the ministers ' statement on membership and immediately called Russian President Boris Yeltsin .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' he said in impromptu remarks that were broadcast to reporters .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
Willy Claes , the alliance 's new secretary-general , sought to respond to Kozyrev 's remarks .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO .
... There is nothing new , '' he told the Russian minister just before he left NATO headquarters .
`` We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst only added to the alliance 's woes .
There have been unprecedented strains in recent weeks between the United States and its European allies over the crisis in Bosnia .
In an effort to heal the wounds , Secretary of State Warren Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It was a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the Europeans , led by Britain and France .
In the past , Moscow has strongly opposed any move by NATO to enlist former members of the Warsaw Pact , the defunct Eastern military alliance led by the Soviet Union .
In an effort to overcome Russian objections , the allies had agreed to develop a `` far-reaching relationship , corresponding with Russia 's size , importance and capabilities . ''
They also insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc threatening Russia .
`` Having just overcome the division of Europe , we have no desire to see the emergence of new lines of partition , '' the ministers said in a statement .
NATO has been anguishing in recent years over whether -- and when -- to open its doors to its former foes in central and eastern Europe .
Poland , Hungary and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
In an effort to meet their demands , but without upsetting Russia , the allies thought they had found a good formula .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
`` We took significant , concrete steps toward ... expansion '' of the alliance , Christopher said afterward .
The move was intended to be a cautious one .
No list of front-runners for membership would be made ; no date set for the first admissions would be set .
But Kozyrev accused NATO of trying to make a fresh division on the European continent .
Some members of Partnership for Peace , he said , were destined to become members , while others would remain behind .
`` Not all countries will be able to obtain membership at the same time , '' he said .
`` There needs to be some sort of clarification . ''
After eight years of turbulent talks to draw up the new world trade accord , countries around the globe now are rushing the mammoth agreement through their national parliaments .
Nearly 40 countries , including most of southeast Asia , have ratified the 124-nation pact .
About 40 more -- including trade giants Japan , the European Union and Canada -- have indicated they will do so by the end of the year .
Three countries -- Switzerland , Liechtenstein and Cyprus -- have already told the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade that domestic politics will prevent them from ratifying the accord this year .
But their absence alone wo n't stop the pact from taking effect as scheduled on Jan. 1 .
All that is needed is for the all the big traders to come on board as founding members of the World Trade Organization -- GATT 's more powerful successor body that implement the accord .
The mostly low-key approach in many countries contrasts sharply with the loud and energetic opposition the accord raised in the United States , where The U.S. Senate was debating the pact for two days .
A vote was expected Thursday night .
The agreement is considered the most ambitious attempt ever to free world trade and is expected to boost global income by dlrs 510 billion by the year 2005 .
It reduces customs duties on hundreds of thousands of products , liberalizes trade in service industries , protects against copyright theft and patent abuse and cuts protection of farm goods and textiles .
Most governments object to at least some provisions because previously protected industries -- such as agriculture in Europe and textiles in the United States -- will suffer .
But all participating countries agreed not to upset the carefully crafted compromises with amendments .
The ratification situation in some of the main trading nations is as follows : -- European Union : Britain , Ireland , Greece and Germany have approved it .
The eight other EU members are meant to do so before foreign ministers meet Dec. 19-20 to approve the deal on behalf of the entire trade bloc .
France and Portugal still have some qualms , but the EU Commission , the union 's executive body , said there are no real obstacles .
An internal dispute between the Commission and member states over negotiating powers , which slowed national ratification , has been settled .
-- Japan : A key parliamentary committee has approved the deal , and full passage is likely in the next few days .
The government placated rice farmers , upset at potential competition from imports , with a six-year , 7.2 trillion yen -LRB- dlrs 74 billion -RRB- compensation package .
-- South Korea : The ruling Democratic Liberal party , which has a big majority , plans to push the accord through the national assembly next week .
Opposition politicians and farmers accuse the government of making too many concessions under U.S. pressure to open the rice market .
There have been frequent violent demonstrations against the accord .
-- India : There was strong opposition from both left - and right-wing parties , especially to provisions that give foreign multinationals stronger patent claims to Indian seeds and medicines .
The opposition , however , seems to have run out of steam and legislative passage appears more or less certain , though no date has been set .
-- Canada : Hopes to ratify the accord by the end of the year .
-- Mexico : Under former President Salinas de Gortari , who is one of three candidates for the directorship of the WTO , Mexico was one of the first countries to ratify the trade accord .
-- South America : Chile has ratified the accord and Argentina hopes to do so before the end of the year .
In Brazil , parliamentary passage is likely to be in February , not because the accord is contested but because of delays caused by this year 's election .
-- China : In order to join the WTO , Beijing first has to enter GATT .
Western concerns about China 's market reform programs and a possible flood of Chinese exports mean GATT membership talks are unlikely to finish by the end of the year .
Congressional clearance of a new world trade accord is expected to encourage ratification by other countries , enabling the mammoth export-boosting pact to enter into force as planned Jan. 1 .
Around the world , big and small nations alike are trying to rush the 22,000 page GATT agreement through national parliaments , often in low-key processes that contrast with the rocky ride through the U.S. legislature .
Others who have been waiting for U.S. leadership , will also follow suit .
Forty to 50 Dominican prisoners ordered released by the courts but still behind bars rioted Thursday , burning mattresses and clothes in a call to be let out .
`` We want justice , we want liberty , '' the inmates shouted .
The uprising at the La Victoria prison 14 kilometers -LRB- 9 miles -RRB- north of the capital city began at 9 a.m. and continued late in the afternoon as police tried to negotiate with the inmates .
No injuries were reported .
An estimated 130 of La Victoria 's 4,000 prisoners were declared innocent or ordered released by the courts , including this country 's supreme court , months ago but remain in jail .
Some were jailed only on the orders of police , without charges against them .
Human rights groups and the inmates ' families have demanded the release of the prisoners , known locally as `` the disrespected . ''
President Joaquin Balaguer has said the prisoners should remain behind bars , arguing that the decisions to release them were tainted by corruption .
He created a committee to review the cases .
The committee , headed by Attorney General Efrain Reyes Duluc , recommended in June that 30 of the prisoners be freed .
But they remain jailed .
Balaguer recently pardoned Jose Guillermo Chiari , a Panamanian pilot who was serving a five-year sentence on a conviction of trafficking 163 kilograms -LRB- 359 pounds -RRB- of cocaine .
His appeal was scheduled to go to court here Friday .
Retired Gen. Colin Powell , a child of Jamaican immigrants who worked his way up to become America 's military chief , returned `` home '' Thursday to receive one of Jamaica 's highest honors .
His wife , Alma , his three children and two grandchildren watched as Governor-General Sir Howard Cooke draped a green sash with the insignia of the Order of Jamaica over Powell 's neck .
`` Every Jamaican , at home and in the diaspora , sees in your achievement the embodiment of the best in us and an indicator that nothing is beyond the capacity of the Jamaican people , '' Prime Minister P.J. Patterson said .
Patterson and others recounted Powell 's climb from the South Bronx to Vietnam soldier , Army general , U.S. National Security Adviser , and chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff .
Even before Powell 's retirement in September 1993 , he had been frequently mentioned as a possible contender for the U.S. presidency in 1996 .
Patterson described General Powell as `` a beacon of hope and a source of inspiration . ''
In an emotional but controlled response , Powell , 57 , reminded those attending that he was an American citizen and that the award was purely honorary .
`` But let it be clear to all present that I consider myself a Jamaican , '' he said to prolonged applause .
`` A true son of Jamaica . ''
Speaking for the millions of Caribbean descendants in the United States , Britain and Canada , Powell said that old-country values of hard work , education and family helped him and others succeed .
`` Wherever we went in the world we always have this home , even if we never had been born here , because our parents instilled in us the love of this country , the love of the people of this country , but most importantly , a love of the values that fuel this country , '' he said .
His three children had never been to Jamaica before this week , Powell said , `` but now we continue the tradition .
Now they know what it means to be a Jamaican and to come home . ''
Later Thursday , Powell received a honorary degree from the University of the West Indies .
In an interview with The Associated Press , Powell said he was going to enjoy his retirement for a while and finish his memoirs .
`` And then , '' he added , `` I will see what to do with the rest of my life . ''
The Order of Jamaica , the equivalent of a knighthood in the British system , entitles him to be called `` The Honorable . ''
It is highest honor that can be given to non-Jamaicans .
Serb fighters kidnapped more U.N. peacekeepers and pressed the stranglehold on the `` safe area '' of Bihac Thursday , underscoring their contempt for U.N. authority in Bosnia .
The Bosnian Serbs did , however , agree to meet Yasushi Akashi , the top U.N. envoy , on Friday in Pale , their stronghold east of Sarajevo .
They had refused to meet U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali on Wednesday because he insisted talks be held at Sarajevo airport , in the capital of the internationally recognized government of Bosnia-Herzegovina .
Fighting between government forces and allied Serbs from Bosnia and neighboring Croatia continued in the Bihac area Thursday , prompting a warning from Croatian Defense Minister Gojko Susak .
`` Croatia will not wait for the fall of Bihac , '' Susak told reporters in the capital Zagreb .
`` We are monitoring the situation , and if Croatia 's judgment is that Bihac is about to fall , Croatia will intervene . ''
The fall of Bihac would effectively unite Serb territory in northern Bosnia with Serb-held land in Croatia .
The Zagreb government would view that as a greater threat to its sovereignty , even as it increasingly talks of using force to regain control over the one-third of Croatia occupied by its Serbs since a truce halted their 1991 war .
The Akashi meeting was arranged during talks in Pale between Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose , the U.N. commander in Bosnia , and Radovan Karadzic and other Bosnian Serb leaders .
Rose went to Pale to discuss a possible cease-fire and demilitarization of Bihac , as well as the fate of more than 400 peacekeepers held hostage by the Serbs as insurance against further NATO airstrikes .
Alexander Ivanko , a U.N. spokesman , said the latest kidnappings occurred Tuesday when Bosnian Serb units crossed the border into Croatia and seized seven Ukrainian peacekeepers .
They took the soldiers and a U.N. armored carrier into Bosnian Serb-held territory , and the United Nations has not heard from its troops since .
The Ukrainians ' observation point is now occupied by the Serbs , allowing for the unimpeded movement into Bosnia of equipment and personnel from Serb-held Croatia .
However , there appeared to be no narrowing of differences that could end the Bihac siege .
Momcilo Krajisnik , leader of the so-called Bosnian Serb assembly , again rejected a three-month cease-fire , which the Bosnian government wants , saying Serbs would accept only a permanent cease-fire as a prelude to a formal end of war .
The Sarajevo government fears any permanent cease-fire agreement would cement Serb territorial gains of 70 percent .
An international peace plan , which the Bosnians accept and the Serbs reject , would force Serbs to settle for 49 percent of the country .
With new U.S. support for Europe 's position that diplomacy , not further NATO airstrikes , is the best way to deal with the Bosnian war , French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and his British counterpart , Douglas Hurd , planned to meet Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade Sunday .
Karadzic later criticized the planned meeting , saying Milosevic `` did not start the war , and he can not finish it . ''
The Bosnian Serb leader insisted that Juppe and Hurd come to Pale , adding , `` We can not accept to be treated like a rebel group . ''
Nonetheless , Milosevic , who is considered responsible for the violent breakup of Yugoslavia , continues to wield the most power , even with the Bosnian Serbs , whom he rejected last summer over their repeated refusal to accept the peace plan .
Senior Western officials now talk of altering that plan to allow the Bosnian Serbs confederal links with Yugoslavia , a right the plan already gives Bosnian Croats with Croatia .
Critics say that is appeasement and a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal , a Greater Serbia .
But Krajisnik said changing the proposed territorial maps was the crucial element to Serb acceptance of the plan , the Bosnian Serb news agency SRNA reported .
Continuing the squeeze on the Bosnian government , Serbs again denied U.N. requests to supply the Bihac enclave and other vulnerable U.N.-patrolled sites with food and supplies .
Monique Tuffelli , the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees staffer in the Bihac enclave , said food stocks would last only another week .
The last UNHCR food convoy reached Bihac on Oct. 1 .
`` We have run out almost of everything , '' she said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press .
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said food and fuel supplies for peacekeepers were also running short in the government-held eastern Bosnian enclaves , as well as Bihac .
Heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire erupted around Bihac Thursday , with sporadic shelling on its outskirts , said Maj. Herve Gourmelon , another U.N. spokesman .
A mortar round slammed into a house in the center of town Thursday morning , but there were no casualties , he added .
Bosnian Serb television showed close-up video of the city limits sign for Velika Kladusa , a government outpost north of Bihac , indicating how close they were to the town .
In downtown Sarajevo , Serbs targeted two government buildings with anti-tank missiles , wounding four people .
Sarajevo 's airport remained closed , and the humanitarian airlift suspended , because Serbs had not given security guarantees and are able to threaten planes ' approach route with surface-to-air missiles .
Showing more contempt for U.N. authority , Bosnian Serb fighters kidnapped more U.N. peacekeepers Thursday and tightened their stranglehold on the `` safe area '' of Bihac .
