Incomes are growing so rapidly that free-spending Americans are n't keeping up -- and therefore the savings rate is improving , new figures show .
A flurry of reports Thursday points to a remarkably strong economy with `` no dark clouds , '' said one private analyst .
A day after reporting that the economy expanded in the third quarter more rapidly than earlier estimates , the Commerce Department released data that suggest the fourth quarter got off to a quick start .
Americans ' income surged 1.4 percent in October , the biggest jump in eight months and the ninth straight gain , the department said .
With millions more Americans employed and being paid more , analysts expect a strong Christmas shopping season that got off to a brisk start last week .
Spurred by a big gain in average hourly earnings and bonus pay for auto workers , the income advance easily outpaced consumer spending -- which rose 0.7 percent in October for its strongest showing since a 0.9 percent rise in August .
`` These are very strong numbers , '' said economist Eugene Sherman of the Wall Street firm of M.A. Schapiro and Co. `` It 's a very positive figure on the income side , so much so that people saved more money .
And you know how much Americans hate to save . ''
`` Everything is doing remarkably well , '' he added .
`` There are n't any dark clouds . ''
Analysts said new sales figures show the Christmas season began strongly for retailers , helping to overcome a weak early November when warmer weather held down clothing purchases .
Many analysts predict a 6 percent sales increase for the holiday season .
In other reports : -- Construction spending rose 0.9 percent in October , the second straight gain , although the advance was limited to non-residential and government spending .
The Commerce Department said residential spending , nearly half of construction outlays , fell .
-- The Labor Department said the number of Americans filing the first time for state unemployment benefits dropped last week to the lowest level in two months .
-- American manufacturing surged in November to its strongest level in 10 years and its 15th straight month of growth , said a widely followed survey by the National Association of Purchasing Managers .
Financial markets were lower .
At midafternoon , the Dow Jones industrial average was down more than 20 points and the yield on the 30-year U.S. Treasury bond , which moves in the opposite direction of its price , was up to 8.02 percent .
The Commerce Department said the income gain was the largest since it rose 1.7 percent in February .
Income last fell in January , when it slipped 0.6 percent .
In September , personal income increased 0.6 percent and spending rose just 0.2 percent .
Disposable income -- income after taxes -- also climbed 1.4 percent in October .
Americans ' savings rate -- savings as a percentage of disposable income -- rose to 4.7 percent in October , from 4.1 percent the previous month .
The new rate is the highest since April 1993 , when it was 5 percent .
Consumer spending , which accounts for two-thirds of the nation 's gross domestic product , was up for the sixth straight month and eight of the last nine .
On Wednesday , the government reported that the economy expanded at a 3.9 percent annual rate in the third quarter of 1994 despite rising interest rates and is on target for its best yearly performance in six years .
The figure was revised upward from a 3.4 percent estimate a month earlier .
`` The current quarter is off to a brisk start and fourth quarter consumer spending could rise at around a 3.5 percent rate , '' said Bruce Steinberg of Merrill Lynch and Co.
But , he added , `` that pace is unsustainable . ''
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates six times this year , most recently on Nov. 15 .
Analysts expect the next boost to come Feb. 1 when Fed policy-makers conclude a two-day meeting .
Ernesto Zedillo was sworn in as president Thursday , vowing to broker peace with Indian rebels , work for his country 's impoverished millions and phase out Mexico 's one-party rule .
Zedillo , who was honored with a parade by thousands of rifle-carrying soldiers backed by armored carriers , smartly saluted the army and navy marching bands as new commander-in-chief and 63rd president of Mexico .
`` We want a homeland of peace , '' declared Zedillo , 42 , a Yale-trained economist , in an inaugural address promising greater prosperity for all Mexicans .
The oath was taken at a simple midday ceremony .
Departing President Carlos Salinas de Gortari transferred over the green , red and white sash of the office before 1,500 dignitaries including U.S. Vice President Al Gore and Cuba 's Fidel Castro .
The dignitaries were then taken in a caravan of gleaming black limousines to the National Palace , trailing Zedillo 's luxury car , guarded by jogging security agents and showered by confetti thrown from balconies .
`` We think he will be a good president ! ''
said Carmen Valencia , a 60-year-old housewife and exuberant ruling party supporter out for the national holiday .
`` He came from below and understands poverty . ''
More than 10,000 anti-government demonstrators , however , rallied at the Monument of the Revolution and shouted slogans against the Institutional Revolutionary Party , or PRI , which has governed Mexico for 65 years .
`` Out with Zedillo ! ''
the protesters shouted , jamming the plaza and raising banners calling for a civil insurgency near the monument , which commemorates Mexico 's bloody 1910-20 revolution .
Many of the protesters were civil supporters of the Zapatista National Liberation Army , a guerrilla force that rebelled on Jan. 1 in the impoverished southern state of Chiapas .
Others were backers of Mexico 's leftist Democratic Revolution Party , the biggest opponent to PRI rule and the free-market reforms Salinas undertook during his six years in office .
The crowd at the Monument to the Revolution grew by the hour , although police made no moves to intervene .
Some protesters , mostly farmers in straw hats , had clubs and machetes .
Some residents were wary of the new administration .
The past year was marked by an unresolved Indian rebellion in Chiapas , the March 23 slaying of the first PRI presidential candidate , Luis Donaldo Colosio , kidnappings and drug feuds .
`` We are all a little bit skeptical , '' said taxi driver Juan Angel Mendoza .
`` They all say the same thing and nothing happens .
But who knows , maybe Zedillo will be different . ''
The 42-year-old president , who will guide Mexico until the year 2000 , promised to expand democracy and prosperity while stripping away many of the powers that have made presidential power nearly absolute .
`` The time has come to do away with centralism , '' vowed Zedillo in the ceremony at the ornate Chamber of Deputies , the lower house of Congress .
Zedillo pledged to balance the power of the presidency with greater independence for the courts , the congress and state governments , as well as for his own party .
Zedillo promised to launch a war on poverty and maintain a cease-fire with the Chiapas rebels .
`` Our most important challenge is to provide dignified living conditions for every Mexican family , '' he said , and vowed to use the free trade agreement with Canada and the United States `` to help generate the jobs we need and raise living standards . ''
Bypassed once for his party 's presidential nomination , Zedillo was thrust into the campaign by Colosio 's assassination , the first major political killing in decades .
He went on to win the presidency Aug. 21 in the most credible elections ever held in Mexico .
Zedillo , former budget and planning minister under Salinas , is sure to continue his predecessor 's free-market economic policies -- a commitment underlined by the Cabinet choices announced Wednesday .
Leading negotiators of NAFTA -- the North American Free Trade Agreement -- were named heads of treasury , trade and foreign policy .
Seven other free-market economists also were named to the 25-person cabinet .
Gore said 1994 was a year of `` unprecedented progress in the bilateral relationship between the United States and Mexico ... and we look forward to even greater improvement in the year ahead . '
Zedillo also showed signs of a political opening with the appointment of a conservative opposition party member , Antonio Lozano , as attorney general .
