Stock investors worried that higher interest rates will continue to lure investors out of stocks and into fixed-income investments , like bonds .
The benchmark 30-year U.S. Treasury bond fell nearly dlrs 5 per dlrs 1,000 face value early in the session but then recouped , trading down about 60 cents for a yield of 8.00 percent late in the day .
But the stock market did not recover with bonds .
Investors were nervous ahead of Friday 's scheduled release of November nonfarm payroll and unemployment data .
Analysts expect the report to show a growth of about 250,000 in nonfarm jobs , and a steady unemployment rate of 5.8 percent .
A higher payroll figure or drop in the jobless rate could set stocks up for another tumble , analysts said .
Retailing stocks fell on weak November sales figures .
Overseas stock markets were lower .
Tokyo 's Nikkei index lost 0.3 percent , and the DAX index in Frankfurt fell 0.1 percent .
In London , the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 41.8 points , or 1.36 percent , to close at 3,039.6 .
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 38.36 to 3,700.87 .
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by about 11 to 5 on the New York Stock Exchange , with 684 up , 1,563 down and 689 unchanged .
Big Board volume totaled 285.92 million shares as of 4 p.m. -LRB- 2100 GMT -RRB- , against 298.66 million in the previous session .
The NYSE 's composite index fell 2.37 to 246.04 .
Standard and Poor 's 500-stock index fell 4.77 to 448.92 .
The Nasdaq composite index rose 9.28 at 741.04 .
At the American Stock Exchange , the market value index fell 2.67 to 431.19 .
Former President Daniel Ortega was hospitalized in Cuba after suffering a minor heart attack , his Sandinista party announced Thursday .
Ortega was in `` satisfactory '' condition at a specialized hospital in Havana , the Cuban capital , a party statement said .
Ortega , 49 , president from 1985 to 1990 , is secretary-general of the Sandinista party and a leading contender for the party 's presidential nomination in 1996 .
Ortega was hospitalized `` after a heart attack that he suffered approximately three months ago was detected during a medical checkup , '' the statement said .
It said doctors were carrying out further tests .
Ortega , a prominent figure among world leftists , went to Cuba a week ago for undisclosed reasons .
He has been embroiled in a power struggle over the past six months for leadership of the party .
Former Vice President Sergio Ramirez and other Sandinista officials have formed a faction calling for party reforms .
The leftist Sandinistas came to power in 1979 .
Ortega was part of a ruling three-man junta until being elected sole president in 1984 and assuming office in 1985 .
He lost a 1990 re-election bid to President Violeta Chamorro .
With many players taking a tough stance , the National Hockey League Players Association went back to the bargaining table Thursday still hoping to find labor peace .
`` Many of the players -- I 'd say 90 per cent -- feel we 've given up too much already and we 're not going to give up any more , '' said Chicago 's Jeremy Roenick .
`` I hope people realize how much the players have given up to get hockey back on the ice . ''
Although initially opposed to any kind of salary cap , players have softened their stance on entry-level salaries .
But the two sides are still deeply divided on salaries for other players .
Reportedly , owners would like a maximum cap for first-year players set at around dlrs 750,000 a season , while players would prefer around dlrs 1.5 million .
Players were expected to present the owners with their thoughts on other major issues , including free agency and salary arbritration .
`` The players wo n't have a salary cap , '' said Los Angeles Kings captain Wayne Gretzky , who was in Michigan with a team of NHL players for an exhibition against Detroit 's International Hockey League team Thursday night .
`` Everything else is negotiable .
In fact , we could start playing hockey right now if the owners would throw out the salary cap . ''
Gretzky and a group of other NHL players locked out of North American rinks start a tour of Scandanavia Sunday .
Until now , owners have insisted on a taxing teams whose payrolls exceed the average team salary , giving the money to teams under the prescribed limit .
The players have been against this so-called luxury tax , believing it has the same effect as a salary cap .
Since team owners locked out the players on Oct. 1 , 347 games have been canceled .
Only 60 games remain on the schedule .
Researchers have isolated a genetic switch that separates the boys from the girls .
It turns off the female in the human embryo and starts biological changes that eventually put hair on the chest .
Dr. Michael Weiss of the University of Chicago said the new study advances the understanding of the complex cascade that determines whether people are male or female and sheds new light on how this process can sometimes go awry .
In research to be published Friday in the journal Science , Weiss and his team use sophisticated imaging techniques to explore on an atomic level the biological pathway to manhood .
Their research report traces the development of maleness , from the turning on of the SRY gene , which is on the Y chromosome , to the work of another gene , called MIS , that removes the female parts of the original embryo .
Weiss said that science has long known that everybody at conception is female , but the precise biological mechanism that changes an embryo to male is still incompletely understood .
Solving the puzzle on molecular level may answer questions about other basic cellular changes , such as the development of cancer .
`` If we can understand the general switches involved in sex determination , then we could possibly relate that to other basic processes , such as how organs differentiate or how cancer arises , '' he said .
For the first weeks after conception , all mammal embryos start forming the basic female structures -- uterus , fallopian tubes and vagina .
`` The embryo destined to become a boy begins as a female , '' Weiss said in an interview .
`` It lays down first female structures and not male structures at a phase when the embryo looks like a recognizable mammal , with toes , fingers and eyes and a heart .
This is 35 to 40 days into human gestation . ''
After that , he said , a gene called SRY switches on to start the embryo on its way toward manhood .
The new study shows that SRY also triggers the work of another gene , called MIS , that dissolves the female parts of the original embryo .
`` SRY is the master switch , '' said Weiss .
`` For the first time we have shown that SRY can activate a male specific pattern of gene expression leading to activation of MIS , which is the key signaling molecule for half of the male pathway . ''
Sex determination in mammals originates with the chromosome of the sperm that fertilizes the egg .
Male sperm can carry one of two chromosomes , X or Y. The Y chromosome is the male element that carries the SRY gene .
The female egg has an X chromosome .
If the egg is fertilized with the father 's X chromosome , then the embryo continues its development as a female .
But if the egg is fertilized with Y , then the SRY gene sets off a series of changes that eventually creates a male .
Deaths from drunken driving accidents in the United States have dropped by nearly one-third over the last 12 years as states raised their drinking ages and grass-roots campaigns raised awareness of the problem , the government said Thursday .
Last year , 17,461 people were killed in alcohol-related traffic accidents , down 31 percent from 25,165 in 1982 , the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported .
In 1982 , alcohol accounted for 57.3 percent of traffic deaths ; that had declined to 43.5 percent by 1993 , said the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration , which collected the data .
The number of intoxicated drivers involved in fatal accidents dropped 33 percent , from 21,780 in 1982 to 14,589 in 1993 .
The agency attributed the drop in deaths to improved law enforcement , states ' raising their drinking ages to 21 and lowering their legal limits for intoxication , fewer people drinking , social pressure against driving drunk and heightened public awareness because of groups that include Mothers Against Drunk Driving .
All states now have a drinking age of 21 .
The standard for intoxication in 45 states is a blood-alcohol level of .10 percent .
For a 72-kilo -LRB- 160-pound -RRB- man , that amounts to about five drinks within an hour on an empty stomach .
Toronto 's Mats Sundin set up the opening goal as Djurgarden edged Brynas 3-2 Thursday to take a three-point lead in the Swedish Elite League .
Djurgarden , which will play Wayne Gretzky 's NHL All Star team in an exhibition Dec. 9 at Stockholm 's Globe Arena , improved to 12-3-4 .
Sundin , who was traded to the Maple Leafs from Quebec in the off-season , assisted on Ola Josefsson 's power-play goal at 18:52 in the first period .
Sundin now has five goals and two assists in seven games for his old Swedish team .
He was cleared to play again in Sweden last month .
Djurgarden 's victory , before a sellout crowd of 13,840 , snapped a three-game losing streak to Brynas at the Globe Arena .
No NHLer scored in Thursday 's six games .
Lulea remained in second place despite losing 4-2 at Vasteras .
Mikael Renberg , who led all NHL rookies in scoring with the Philadelphia Flyers last season , was pointless after scoring in two straight games .
The independent counsel who investigates U.S. government officials will bring no criminal charges in the search of Bill Clinton 's passport files during the 1992 presidential campaign , he said Thursday .
Joseph diGenova , who has been investigating the matter for nearly two years , said his report will exonerate the former Bush administration officials who had been the subject of his probe .
`` No question about it , '' he said .
A three-judge federal panel appointed diGenova nearly two years ago , after President Bush 's attorney general , William Barr , found possible evidence of criminal intent in the search of the Democratic presidential candidate 's passport files .
Late in the campaign , rumors had surfaced that while Clinton was a student in England , he had sought information on how to renounce his U.S. citizenship .
The unfounded rumors triggered Freedom of Information Act requests from the news media and an inquiry from a Republican House member , Rep. Gerald Solomon of New York .
Sources said the counsel will conclude that the case should never have been referred to the Justice Department in the first place , and that the investigation was bungled by State Department Inspector General Sherman Funk and his staff .
DiGenova 's report , expected to be submitted in the next two weeks to the three-judge panel that appointed him , will fault Funk for overzealousness that drove his staff to do sloppy work , said one source familiar with the case who spoke on condition of anonymity .
Funk defended his investigation and said he had `` no choice '' in whether to refer the matter to the Justice Department .
`` Right or wrong , we had grounds for believing there was a violation . ''
The report also is expected to raise questions about the use by members of Congress of their positions to launch politically motivated inquiries , such as the search of Clinton 's files .
And it is likely to show that James A. Baker III , then White House chief of staff , knew about the file search and could have cut it off almost immediately , but did not , two sources familiar with the investigation said .
