Monique Tuffelli , the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees staffer in the Bihac enclave , said food would last only another week .
The last UNHCR food convoy reached Bihac on Oct. 1 .
`` We have run out almost of everything , '' she said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press .
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said food and fuel supplies for peacekeepers were also running short in the government-held eastern Bosnian enclaves , as well as Bihac .
Heavy machine-gun and small-arms fire erupted around Bihac on Thursday , with sporadic shelling on its outskirts , said Maj. Herve Gourmelon , another U.N. spokesman .
A mortar round slammed into a house in the center of town Thursday morning , but there were no casualties , he added .
Bosnian Serb television showed close-up video of the city limits sign for Velika Kladusa , a government outpost north of Bihac , indicating how close they were to the town .
In downtown Sarajevo , Serbs targeted two government buildings with anti-tank missiles , wounding four people .
Sarajevo 's airport remained closed and the humanitarian airlift suspended .
That was because Serbs had not given security guarantees and are able to threaten planes ' approach route with surface-to-air missiles .
American schoolchildren face widespread fear , violence , weapons in school , victimization and poor communication with teachers and parents , according to a new survey .
While violence in schools is not as pervasive as news media make it out to be , said pollster Humphrey Taylor on Thursday , `` the levels are obviously totally unacceptable . ''
`` The survey suggests to me the need to stamp out the first signs of violence before they become commonplace , to have zero tolerance for violent behavior and to do whatever more is necessary to keep weapons out of school , '' said Taylor , chairman and chief executive officer of Louis Harris and Associates , which conducted the poll .
Parents delude themselves if they think their children talk to them about such problems , the results show .
Only 13 percent of parents interviewed thought their children do n't confide in them about school problems but more than 37 percent of the students said they hardly ever or never speak to their parents about them .
The results were released at a forum cosponsored by MetLife , which commissioned the survey , and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce Center for Workforce Preparation .
`` It 's easy for me to stand here and say these things , but very tough to achieve them , '' said Humphrey .
Harry P. Kamen , his counterpart at MetLife , stressed the need for more involvement by parents .
`` Fifty-eight percent of all students believe their parents never exchange notes with a teacher or school official , '' he said .
`` Two in five students who have been victims of violence say their parents never talk to the school staff , not even by telephone . ''
More than 1,000 parents with at least one child in public school and 2,500 students in grades three through 12 were interviewed by telephone in a one-month period beginning in April .
The poll had a possible sampling error of 3 percent for the students and 4 percent for the parents .
In the month preceding the survey , `` a sizable proportion of public school students have had personal experiences with angry scenes or confrontations -LRB- 44 percent -RRB- , and physical fights -LRB- 24 percent -RRB- , '' the report said .
In that month , 5 percent of all students surveyed said they had been threatened at least once with a gun and 7 percent with a knife .
Among students with mostly A 's and B 's , 4 percent had been threatened with a gun and 3 percent with a knife .
