A congressman is accusing U.S. gun manufacturers of decieving the public in ads aimed at getting women to arm themselves .
Rep. Charles Schumer , a New York Democrat , said ads that have appeared in several magazines seek to frighten women into believing they can increase their safety by buying a handgun .
`` The tragedy is ... that nothing could be further from the truth , '' Schumer said .
`` Study after study has proven that a gun in the home simply increases the chance that an innocent person will be killed by that gun . ''
The National Rifle Association denounced Schumer 's comments Thursday , urging women to `` ignore scare tactics . ''
Schumer said he would file a complaint against the advertising tactics with the Federal Trade Commission .
`` In its battle for the hearts of American women , the gun ban lobby has forgotten that American women have minds too , '' NRA lobbyist Tanya K. Metaksa said .
`` As women , we not only have the right and the obligation to make our own decisions about safety and security -- we have the intelligence to do so . ''
Schumer said he remains confident that most Americans support gun control , including two measures passed last year -- the Brady Law , which requires a waiting period for firearms purchases or the ban on some assault-style weapons included in the dlrs 30 billion anti-crime legislation passed this year .
`` Yes , a new Congress will convene in January .
Yes , Republican leadership is hostile to gun legislation .
And , yes , the Brady law and the assault weapons ban are in jeopardy , '' Schumer said .
`` Those of you who like a good political fight , welcome to Round Two .
The fight over rational gun laws is not over . ''
Gun manufacturers began advertising directed at women in the 1980s after the male market became saturated and gun sales declined , according to `` Female Persuasion , '' a report released during Schumer 's news conference by the Violence Policy Center .
The group used a full-age Colt 's Manufacturing Co. ad that features a woman tucking a girl into bed .
`` Self-protection is more than your right , '' the ad said .
`` It 's your responsibility . ''
Colt 's officials were not immediately available for comment .
Democratic Rep. Nita Lowey said gun manufacturers are simply looking for new ways to sell guns .
`` It 's clear that the National Rifle Association and the gun manufacturers have a new target , which is American women .
This is a cynical marketing strategy designed to promote gun ownership by preying on women 's legitimate fears of violence , '' said Lowey , who led a protest of 25 female representatives last year against the National Rifle Association 's `` Refuse to be a Victim '' campaign .
The NRA launched the campaign in 1993 to advertise a three-hour self-defense seminar for women .
Draped in rubber armor , bristling with guns , the `` Krajina Express '' must be one of the Serbs ' oddest weapons in the Bosnian war .
All aboard -- if you dare .
The train , similar to those employed in both world wars , has three combat cars and three freight cars hooked to the front to protect it from mine blasts .
It chugs to the front line , aims and fires and then quickly retreats .
But on Tuesday , the train took a direct hit from a missile fired by Bosnian government defenders of Bihac , the U.N.-designated `` safe area '' in northwest Bosnia .
The 20-man crew survived and the damage was minor , since a thick rubber curtain absorbed most of the blast .
The car was loaded with ammunition and the train could have exploded .
`` We were lucky , '' said Djuro , whose shrapnel wound to the leg was the only injury .
A hundred yards long , roofless and loaded with guns , the `` Krajina Express '' -- named for the Krajina region of neighboring Croatia -- is an example of the firepower Serbs are throwing at defenders of Bihac .
The United Nations says Croatian Serbs have joined the fighting in the Bihac area , helping anti-government forces corner the Bosnian army 's powerful 5th Corps .
Serb troops say they are determined to punish the 5th Corps for an October offensive that routed them out of the Bihac region .
The Serbs counter-attacked in early November and now control 30 percent to 40 percent of the area .
`` The 5th corps is in a desperate position and they will fight to the end , '' said Savo Bursac , who operates a 40 mm anti-aircraft gun .
`` I do n't expect them to surrender , and they have nowhere to go . ''
He said the train crew never would have gotten involved had the 5th Corps not attacked Bihac .
`` This is to teach them a lesson and to end the war . ''
Capt. Blagoje Guska , commander of the train , said it had been fired upon but never hit before the missile attack Tuesday .
The train usually draws no fire and crew members blamed overconfidence for getting hit .
It rolled back quickly from the dangerous position south of Bihac .
`` That was our fault , '' said Djuro , who declined to give his last name .
`` We went too close and stayed there exposed for too long . ''
The motor on a triple-barrel , anti-aircraft machine gun was destroyed .
A small fire was quickly extinguished and Djuro got a lift to a nearby hospital .
Earlier , on its first of three runs that day , the train followed its standard procedure of appearing suddenly , firing its deadly barrage and quickly retreating .
Approaching from the south , it halted about two miles from Bihac and its guns joined the tank and howitzer fire on the region .
The first shells were fired by a self-propelled cannon , aimed at what was said to be Bosnian army trenches on a remote hill .
Then , missiles that had been taken off of jet fighters and refitted to the train were unleashed .
On its third raid , another anti-tank missile fired at the train hit a house about 200 yards away , setting it ablaze .
The house was empty and there were no casualties .
Runs toward the government line are interspersed with breaks back at the train 's base about three miles from Bihac .
On one run back to the base , small trucks followed with hot soup and fresh bread for lunch .
Morale was boosted by a short visit from Bosnian Serb army deputy commander Gen. Manojlo Milovanovic , who is directing the Bihac campaign .
Later , they sat around an open fire , playing accordion and singing .
` We are like family and we will be together till the end of this war , '' said Guska .
About 50 Dominican prisoners ordered released by the courts but still behind bars rioted Thursday , burning mattresses and clothes in a call to be let out .
`` We want justice , we want liberty , '' shouted the inmates at the La Victoria prison 14 kilometers -LRB- 9 miles -RRB- north of the capital city .
The eight-hour uprising was quelled only after police sprayed some 20,000 gallons of water into the cells and the country 's Human Rights Commission president , Virgilio Almanzar , asked the inmates to stop .
No injuries were reported .
Santo Domingo prosecutor Alexis Joaquin Castillo was scheduled to meet with the inmates Friday to evaluate their legal status .
An estimated 130 of La Victoria 's 4,000 prisoners were declared innocent or ordered released by the courts , including this country 's supreme court , months ago but remain in jail .
Some were jailed only on the orders of police , without charges against them .
Human rights groups and the inmates ' families have demanded the release of the prisoners , known locally as `` the disrespected . ''
President Joaquin Balaguer has said the prisoners should remain behind bars , arguing that the decisions to release them were tainted by corruption .
He created a committee to review the cases .
The committee , headed by Attorney General Efrain Reyes Duluc , recommended in June that 30 of the prisoners be freed .
But they remain jailed .
Balaguer in August pardoned Jose Guillermo Chiari , a Panamanian pilot who was serving a five-year sentence on a conviction of trafficking 163 kilograms -LRB- 359 pounds -RRB- of cocaine .
His appeal was scheduled to go to court here Friday .
Reports from Bosnian and Serb sources as well as the United Nations indicate Yugoslavia assisted in a crucial attack on northwest Bosnia , despite its public ban on war aid to Bosnian Serbs .
Together with the involvement of Serbs from across the border in Croatia , Yugoslav assistance in men and material provided to the fuel-short and outnumbered Bosnian Serbs appears to have been a key factor in their favor .
The attack on Bihac this month called NATO 's bluff to use large-scale force against the Serbs .
It has led to a rapid deterioration in the United Nations ' authority , and on Wednesday , U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali said the 24,000 peacekeepers might have to be withdrawn .
Slobodan Milosevic , the powerful president of Serbia , announced in August that the border with Bosnia was being sealed to all but humanitarian aid to pressure Bosnian Serbs into accepting a peace plan .
Although there have been regular claims by Milosevic 's foes that he was cheating on the ban , several hundreds international monitors sent to patrol the 300-mile border reported seeing no violations .
The international community generally took Milosevic at his word , and allowed an easing of economic sanctions in October .
The ban hurt Bosnian Serbs , supplied through the 2 -LCB- - year-old war by Belgrade .
In October , the Bosnian army 's 5th Corps broke out of the Bihac area where government forces are completely surrounded by Serb-held territory in Croatia and Bosnia .
They pushed the Serbs back in a surprise attack to the east and south .
But the Serbs counter-attacked furiously in early November and now control 30 percent to 40 percent of the U.N.-declared Bihac `` safe area , '' which encompasses the town of Bihac and its environs .
U.N. reports , and sources in Yugoslavia lend support to Bosnian army claims that Yugoslav aid helped turn the tide at Bihac .
Bosnian government officials said intelligence reports indicated fuel and ammunition trucks had crossed the border into Bosnia from Serbia , the main republic in Yugoslavia , and that armor , helicopters and rockets all had been provided .
`` It is so obvious that ... Serbs received new weapons , fresh troops ... and fuel to move ` dry ' tanks , '' charged Gen. Jovan Divjak , a Serb who serves as deputy commander of the Bosnian army .
`` Otherwise , they would n't have been able to put Bihac under such strong pressure . ''
Reports from Yugoslavia and from U.N. observers indicate that Milosevic may have used the involvement of Serbs from Croatia to get assistance to the Bihac combatants .
While Milosevic said he was cutting off help to the Bosnian Serbs , he did not make a similar pledge regarding the Croatian Serbs .
Classified U.N. reports shown to The Associated Press in Sarajevo say that U.N. observers had seen armed men crossing the border between Serb-held territory in Croatia and Bosnia in vehicles with Belgrade licenses .
The presence of fighters from Yugoslavia in Bosnia also was reported in Milosevic 's Serbia .
The Svet weekly , based in the northern Serbian town of Novi Sad , said a special Serbian police unit of up to 1,000 men headed by a top police officer had joined the fighting .
The weekly said the policemen crossed into Bosnia as civilians , and traveled through Bosnia to Croatia , where they received weapons and uniforms .
A senior Serbian police official denied the Svet report .
But reliable sources in Belgrade confirmed that Yugoslav army and police detachments actively took part in the fighting .
Svet also reported that the only other republic in Yugoslavia , Montenegro , had shipped a large supply of fuel to Bosnian Serbs .
Toronto 's Mats Sundin set up the opening goal as Djurgarden edged Brynas 3-2 Thursday to take a three-point lead in the Swedish Elite League .
Djurgarden , which will play Wayne Gretzky 's National Hockey League All Star team in an exhibition Dec. 9 at Stockholm 's Globe Arena , improved to 12-3-4 .
Sundin , who was traded to the Maple Leafs from Quebec in the off-season , assisted on Ola Josefsson 's power-play goal at 18:52 in the first period .
Sundin now has five goals and two assists in seven games for his old Swedish team .
He was cleared to play again in Sweden last month .
Djurgarden 's victory , before a sellout crowd of 13,840 , snapped a three-game losing streak to Brynas at the Globe Arena .
No NHL player scored in Thursday 's six games .
Lulea remained in second place despite losing 4-2 at Vasteras .
Mikael Renberg , who led all NHL rookies in scoring with the Philadelphia Flyers last season , was pointless after scoring in two straight games .
The American dollar advanced broadly on Thursday , hitting a seven-week high vs. the Japanese yen , as a set of strong economic numbers helped fuel expectations that the Federal Reserve will again raise U.S. interest rates .
In a reversal of the trend for much of the year , currency traders are no longer dumping the dollar on signs of an accelerating economy because they 're confident the Fed will take steps to control inflation .
Attitudes have shifted since the central bank 's 0.75-percentage point hike on Nov. 15 , analysts say .
`` Strong data has helped the dollar because people feel the Fed is willing to mount a response to any inflation threat , '' said Amy Smith , senior currency strategist for the IDEA market analysis firm .
`` It may be a bit optimistic , but it 's driving trading at the moment . ''
Previously , such numbers prompted Treasury bond market sell-offs that dampened demand for the U.S. currency .
Data released Thursday by the National Association of Purchasing Management indicated U.S. manufacturing rose last month to the strongest level in 10 years .
U.S. retailers reported robust sales for late November .
The Commerce Department said , meanwhile , that Americans ' incomes rose by a stronger-than-expected 1.4 percent and spending climbed 0.7 percent in October .
Bond prices dipped on the reports , but the decline appeared to have little impact on the currency market , in large part because of the newfound confidence in the Fed .
`` The linkage with the bond market is cut , '' said Dave Glowacki , senior trader at NBD Bank in Detroit .
`` Bond investors who wanted to sell have sold .
We 're back to the normal way of doing things .
When the numbers point to a stronger economy , you buy the currency . ''
Market participants said large U.S. investment funds and institutions were heavy buyers of dollars on Thursday .
Against the yen , that helped offset selling by Japanese companies that have accrued big stockpiles of dollars from exports to the United States .
Belal Khan , senior dealer for the Bank of Tokyo in New York , said U.S. investors increasingly are pulling out of Japan 's stagnant stock market and repatriating funds , while Japanese investors have shown a greater appetite for U.S. assets .
`` U.S. interest rates are looking very attractive and the U.S. markets are attracting capital , '' he said .
`` The dollar has found a bottom and is moving higher . ''
In late New York trading , the dollar was quoted at 99.34 yen , the highest level since Oct. 13 , up from 98.93 late Wednesday .
In London , the dollar rose to 99.35 yen from 98.89 .
The dollar also was changing hands late in New York at 1.5733 German marks , up from 1.5693 .
In London , the dollar traded at 1.5743 marks , up from 1.5686 .
David Durst , a vice president at Bear , Stearns and Co. , said a good deal of the dollar buying was spurred by upward revisions of estimates for November U.S. employment data , which the Labor Department reports on Friday .
Economists are expecting the report to show creation of 260,000 to 290,000 jobs last month , up from earlier projections of 230,000 to 250,000 , he said .
Other late dollar rates in New York , compared with late Wednesday : 1.3295 Swiss francs , up from 1.3265 ; 5.3915 French francs , up from 5.3820 ; 1,614 Italian lire , down from 1,617 ; and 1.3776 Canadian dollars , up from 1.3763 .
The British pound traded at dlrs 1.5669 , up from dlrs 1.5650 .
In London , the pound fell to dlrs 1.5655 from dlrs 1.5673 .
Days after an Arizona State University student acknowledged fabricating a column depicting the stoning of a paralyzed man in Israel , parts of her resume also appear to be fictitious .
Mary Leigh Summerton , 27 , could face expulsion for a gut-wrenching account of a European Jewish quadriplegic who was supposedly stoned to death at the Wailing Wall in Israel for using a mechanical device -- his wheelchair -- on the Sabbath .
The story , which appeared in the Nov. 15 issue of the campus newspaper as a guest column , apparently was an embellished version of a tale a feminist member of the Jerusalem City Council told students on the summer trip .
She said she published the article in The State Press in order to enter the Hearst competition , a college journalism contest that recognizes superior published articles .
Now , Summerton faces a hearing for violating ASU 's code of conduct .
Criminal behavior , plagiarism and cheating are included in code-of-conduct standards and can be punished by measures from probation to expulsion .
Summerton , a former reporter and editor for The State Press , has been at Arizona State since the summer of 1993 working on a bachelor 's degree in journalism .
On her resume , however , she claims to already have bachelor 's and master 's degrees in chemistry from the University of Miami in Florida .
But Summerton never enrolled at the University of Miami , let alone received any degrees , said Sandra Bouie , who works in the registrar 's office there .
She also attended ASU for one semester in the fall of 1990 -- the same time her resume places her at the University of Miami , working on her master 's degree .
Maricopa County Community College District personnel records show Summerton never had a job there although she often told other students he worked as a lab instructor at Mesa Community College .
And while she did work at Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center in Phoenix from Feb. 25 , 1991 , to March 10 , 1994 , it was not as a chemist as she claims on her resume but as an assistant to the pharmacist .
The senior journalism student also claims on her resume to be a contributing writer to the Journal of Chemical Education , a well-known academic journal for chemists , teachers and students .
`` Not only did she not write for us , the job she names is fictitious , '' said Debora Bittaker , assistant editor of the journal .
Summerton also claims she is from Florida , but school records show she graduated from Arizona 's Tolleson High School in 1985 .
`` Obviously , fidelity to the truth is not one of her strong points , '' said Jeffrey Ross of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith , who led an expedition of 18 college journalists to Poland and Israel this past summer .
`` At least there 's a pattern .
Otherwise , the whole thing is inexplicable . ''
Summerton did not return telephone calls from The Associated Press on Thursday seeking comment on her resume discrepancies .
Ernesto Zedillo was sworn in as president Thursday , vowing to broker peace with Indian rebels , work for his country 's impoverished millions and phase out Mexico 's one-party rule .
As the 42-year-old economist was taking his oath of office , more than 10,000 people shouted slogans against him at a rally protesting his Institutional Revolutionary Party 's 65-year rule .
Rock-throwing protesters clashed with riot police , who responded by firing tear gas .
At least 50 people were injured .
Zedillo , who was honored with a parade by thousands of rifle-carrying soldiers backed by armored carriers , smartly saluted the army and navy marching bands as new commander-in-chief and 63rd president of Mexico .
`` We want a homeland of peace , '' he declared in an inaugural address promising greater prosperity for all Mexicans .
He took the oath of office at a simple midday ceremony .
Departing President Carlos Salinas de Gortari transferred over the green , red and white sash of the office before 1,500 dignitaries including U.S. Vice President Al Gore and Cuba 's Fidel Castro .
The dignitaries were then taken in a caravan of gleaming black limousines to the National Palace , trailing Zedillo 's luxury car , guarded by jogging security agents and showered by confetti thrown from balconies .
`` We think he will be a good president ! ''
said Carmen Valencia , a 60-year-old housewife and exuberant ruling party supporter out for the national holiday .
`` He came from below and understands poverty . ''
Protesters had a different message .
`` Out with Zedillo ! ''
they shouted as they jammed the plaza surrounding the Monument of the Revolution commemorating Mexico 's bloody 1910-20 revolution .
They raised banners calling for a civil insurgency .
Later , hundreds marched toward the National Palace where Zedillo was greeting his new Cabinet and other supporters and were blocked by a barricade guarded by helmeted riot police .
A Red Cross spokesman said about 50 people were injured when protesters threw rocks , bottles and other debris at police , who responded with tear gas .
Thick black smoke billowed in from of the National Lottery building as protesters set at least two vehicles ablaze -- a police jeep and an old truck owned by the ruling party , or PRI .
Protesters threw rocks at firefighters trying to put out the flames .
Many of the protesters were civil supporters of the Zapatista National Liberation Army , a guerrilla force that rebelled on Jan. 1 in the impoverished southern state of Chiapas .
Others were backers of Mexico 's leftist Democratic Revolution Party , the biggest opponent to PRI rule and the free-market reforms Salinas undertook during his six years in office .
Some residents were wary of the new administration .
The past year was marked by an unresolved Indian rebellion in Chiapas , the March 23 slaying of the first PRI presidential candidate , Luis Donaldo Colosio , kidnappings and drug feuds .
`` We are all a little bit skeptical , '' said taxi driver Juan Angel Mendoza .
`` They all say the same thing and nothing happens .
But who knows , maybe Zedillo will be different . ''
The new president , who will guide Mexico until the year 2000 , promised to expand democracy and prosperity while stripping away many of the powers that have made presidential power nearly absolute .
`` The time has come to do away with centralism , '' vowed Zedillo in the ceremony at the ornate Chamber of Deputies , the lower house of Congress .
Zedillo pledged to balance the power of the presidency with greater independence for the courts , the congress and state governments , as well as for his own party .
Zedillo promised to launch a war on poverty and maintain a cease-fire with the Chiapas rebels .
`` Our most important challenge is to provide dignified living conditions for every Mexican family , '' he said , and vowed to use the free trade agreement with Canada and the United States `` to help generate the jobs we need and raise living standards . ''
Bypassed once for his party 's presidential nomination , Zedillo was thrust into the campaign by Colosio 's assassination , the first major political killing in decades .
He went on to win the presidency Aug. 21 in the most credible elections ever held in Mexico .
Zedillo , former budget and planning minister under Salinas , is sure to continue his predecessor 's free-market economic policies -- a commitment underlined by the Cabinet choices announced Wednesday .
Leading negotiators of NAFTA -- the North American Free Trade Agreement -- were named heads of treasury , trade and foreign policy .
Seven other free-market economists also were named to the 25-person cabinet .
Gore said 1994 was a year of `` unprecedented progress in the bilateral relationship between the United States and Mexico ... and we look forward to even greater improvement in the year ahead . '
Zedillo also showed signs of a political opening with the appointment of a conservative opposition party member , Antonio Lozano , as attorney general .
Draped in rubber armor , bristling with guns , the `` Krajina Express '' must be one of the Serbs ' oddest weapons in the Bosnian war .
All aboard -- if you dare .
The train , similar to those employed in both world wars , has three combat cars and three freight cars hooked to the front to protect it from mine blasts .
It chugs to the front line , aims and fires and then quickly retreats .
But on Tuesday , the train took a direct hit from a missile fired by Bosnian government defenders of Bihac , the U.N.-designated `` safe area '' in northwest Bosnia .
The 20-man crew survived and the damage was minor , since a thick rubber curtain absorbed most of the blast .
The car was loaded with ammunition and the train could have exploded .
`` We were lucky , '' said Djuro , whose shrapnel wound to the leg was the only injury .
A hundred yards -LRB- meters -RRB- long , roofless and loaded with guns , the `` Krajina Express '' -- named for the Krajina region of neighboring Croatia -- is an example of the firepower Serbs are throwing at defenders of Bihac .
The United Nations says Croatian Serbs have joined the fighting in the Bihac area , helping anti-government forces corner the Bosnian army 's powerful 5th Corps .
Serb troops say they are determined to punish the 5th Corps for an October offensive that routed them out of the Bihac region .
The Serbs counter-attacked in early November and now control 30 percent to 40 percent of the area .
`` The 5th Corps is in a desperate position and they will fight to the end , '' said Savo Bursac , who operates a 40mm anti-aircraft gun .
`` I do n't expect them to surrender , and they have nowhere to go . ''
He said the train crew never would have gotten involved had the 5th Corps not attacked Bihac .
`` This is to teach them a lesson and to end the war . ''
Capt. Blagoje Guska , commander of the train , said it had been fired upon but never hit before the missile attack Tuesday .
The train usually draws no fire and crew members blamed overconfidence for getting hit .
It rolled back quickly from the dangerous position south of Bihac .
`` That was our fault , '' said Djuro , who declined to give his last name .
`` We went too close and stayed there exposed for too long . ''
The motor on a triple-barrel , anti-aircraft machine gun was destroyed .
A small fire was quickly extinguished and Djuro got a lift to a nearby hospital .
Earlier , on its first of three runs that day , the train followed its standard procedure of appearing suddenly , firing its deadly barrage and quickly retreating .
Approaching from the south , it halted about two miles -LRB- three kilometers -RRB- from Bihac and its guns joined the tank and howitzer fire on the region .
The first shells were fired by a self-propelled cannon , aimed at what was said to be Bosnian army trenches on a remote hill .
Then , missiles that had been taken off of jet fighters and refitted to the train were unleashed .
On its third raid , another anti-tank missile fired at the train hit a house about 200 yards -LRB- meters -RRB- away , setting it ablaze .
The house was empty and there were no casualties .
Runs toward the government line are interspersed with breaks back at the train 's base about three miles -LRB- five kilometers -RRB- from Bihac .
On one run back to the base , small trucks followed with hot soup and fresh bread for lunch .
Morale was boosted by a short visit from Bosnian Serb army deputy commander Gen. Manojlo Milovanovic , who is directing the Bihac campaign .
Later , they sat around an open fire , playing accordion and singing .
` We are like family and we will be together till the end of this war , '' said Guska .
