Egyptian and U.S. students clashed Thursday on the campus of the American University in Cairo , and officials later said four Americans involved in the incident were leaving the country .
Students and witnesses said the fight started after U.S. embassy officials arrived at the downtown campus to investigate an incident a day earlier near the campus in which four American students allegedly roughed up the Egyptian president of the Student Union , Mustafa Najam .
They said some 250 students gathered to demand that the diplomats leave the campus , shouting that they had no right to interfere in student affairs .
The diplomats were unable to leave until Egyptian police were summoned to break up the protesters , who also were shoving each other , they said .
They insisted on anonymity .
At least two students , both believed to be Egyptians , were taken to a nearby hospital for treatment of injuries , they said .
There were no reports of arrests .
The university , chartered in Washington , D.C. , was founded 75 years ago to foster Western-style education in the Middle East .
The university has an enrollment of more than 3,500 in graduate and undergraduate programs .
More than half are Egyptians .
Among the foreigners are many American and British students who come to study Arabic .
The reason for the confrontation between Najam and the American students was not immediately known , but the resulting tensions apparently contributed to Thursday 's problems .
Theoren Fleury created three of five goals but his Finnish club Tappara of Tampere lost 6-5 to Assat of Pori Thursday in the Finnish Hockey League .
Assists by the Calgary Flames star brought Tappara within two in the last period , and his goal at 13:27 made it 6-5 .
But Kari Takko , a former NHL goaltender for the Minnesota North Stars , held firm , turning away 17 shots in the period .
It was the 12th consecutive loss for last-placed Tappara -LRB- 3-18-2 -RRB- .
Fleury is the second most effective NHL player in the league , with 10 points -LRB- 4 goals and 6 assists -RRB- in only six games .
Swede Michael Nylander , Fleury 's preseason linemate for the Flames , has 20 points -LRB- 8-12 -RRB- in 10 games .
On Thursday , Nylander scored and assisted on both goals for JyP HT of Jyvaskyla .
But TuTo of Turku took its third win in a row , 3-2 , with the second successive overtime winner by Risto Siltanen , a defenseman for Edmonton Oilers in the early 1980s .
Teppo Numminen , a Winnipeg defenseman , assisted on the clincher .
Geoff Sanderson of Hartford scored for HPK Hameenlinna , assisted by Jarkko Varvio of Dallas , cutting the deficit to 4-2 as Lukko of Rauma won 5-2 away .
The success story of Canadian lefthander Boris Rousson , the former AHL Binghampton goaltender , continues in Lukko .
He is now 13-2-1 since arriving .
Mikko Makela , an NHL veteran returning to the league to play for the Boston Bruins after seasons in Finland and Sweden , made it 4-1 with an empty-net goal as Ilves of Tampere downed reigning champion and league leader Jokerit of Helsinki 5-1 .
Jokerit lost for only the fourth time in 24 games , but still leads the league with 39 points ahead of Lukko , 32 , and IFK of Helsinki , 31 .
On Saturday , Jokerit will meet the '' Ninety-Nine All-Stars '' , assembled by Wayne Gretzky in Helsinki .
On Sunday , the overseas stars play Ilves in Tampere .
Nordic navigation authorities agreed on stiffer rules Thursday that would require stronger hinges and better monitoring of cargo doors on ferries .
The rules , which still must be approved by maritime officials , were drafted in the wake of the Estonia ferry disaster , which sank Sept. 28 after its door locks failed .
More than 900 people died .
Insurance companies and ferry lines at the time acted quickly to weld shut the doors and visors on ships .
But only the Finnish government issued a blanket order for weldings .
The navigation authorities from Sweden , Finland , Norway and Denmark , meeting in Helsinki , agreed on rules that would require hinges on all ferries to be reinforced or replaced , the Swedish news agency TT reported .
Inspectors had found the weak point to be locks and hinges , rather than the plates that hold them , said Joakim Heimdahl , an official from the Nordic Sea Navigation Board .
`` In many cases , one can see certain sections need replacing or reinforcing , '' Heimdahl said , referring to ship inspections in the past two months .
Agreement by the navigation board was the first hurdle .
The proposals were referred to the Nordic Marine Safety Inspection Board , which meets Dec. 13 , TT reported .
Michael Jackson is trying to end his 5-month-old marriage to Lisa Marie Presley , news reports in New York and London said Thursday .
But the official word from one half of the celebrity couple is that the reports are simply false .
`` Once again , the media is being very irresponsible and spreading false rumors , '' Mrs. Jackson-Presley said in a statement .
`` Michael and I are very happily married .
... These rumors , in spite of their wishful and destructive thinking , are totally unfounded and false . ''
The separation speculation comes just after the couple 's six-month anniversary .
Jackson biographer Christopher Andersen said he first heard rumors of a split on Tuesday .
`` I had heard their lawyers were actually talking annulment , '' said the author of `` Michael Jackson Unauthorized . ''
Lisa Marie and Michael were married in a secret ceremony in the Dominican Republic in May , but rumors about the marriage were n't confirmed until August .
Speculation that the marriage is at best a union of convenience and at worst a publicity ploy started immediately .
`` Are Michael and Lisa Marie friends ?
Sure -- they 've been friends for a long time .
But that 's not a marriage , '' Andersen said .
The current rumors come in several versions .
Andersen says the marriage was `` a scam '' from Day 1 , and now Lisa Marie wants out .
Gossip columnist Liz Smith intimates Michael viewed the nuptials as a `` public relations coup , '' but Lisa Marie fell in love and now Michael wants out .
Another Jacksonphile , author J. Randy Taraborrelli , blames the split on Lisa 's refusal to move to the East Coast and live with Michael in his Trump Tower apartment in New York .
Whatever the reason , it seems only a few people expect the Jacksons to be exchanging the traditional silverware on their 25th anniversary .
Or , for that matter , paper on anniversary No. 1 .
`` I did say the marriage would be over by the end of the year , '' Andersen said .
`` Not that I want to say I told you so . ''
