Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220 mile -RRB- highway are controlled by Croatian Serbs .
It is the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their six-month war in 1991 .
The United Nations , in a statement , announced the agreement would be signed on Friday : by the Croats at U.N. headquarters in Zagreb in the morning , and by the Serbs at U.N. headquarters in Knin in the afternoon .
The diplomatic moves coincided with battlefield action .
On Wednesday , the Croatian army fired 33 shells at Serb-held territory over a six-hour period , U.N. spokesman Alexander Ivanko said .
The artillery duels continued Thursday in the same area near Lake Peruca , about 30 kilometers -LRB- 18.6 miles -RRB- southeast of Knin , the self-proclaimed capital of Serb-held Croatia , said Paul Risley , another U.N. spokesman in Zagreb .
Reporters in the Croatian port of Split , just west of Knin , also reported unusual activity by Croatian army helicopters .
But Croatian Serbs denied there was any serious trouble Thursday .
Bosnian Serb media claimed that regular Croatian army troops , backed by Bosnian Croats , had attacked Serb positions in Bosnia , about 50 kilometers -LRB- 31 miles -RRB- northeast of Lake Peruca , across the border .
The United Nations could not confirm that .
There have been thousands of skirmishes and larger confronations between the Croats and their Serb minority since their six-month war ended with an uneasy , U.N.-patrolled truce in January 1992 .
Croatia 's Defense Minister Gojko Susak denied his troops were involved in any fighting Thursday .
But he suggested to reporters in Zagreb that the time was nearing to take up arms against rebel Serbs , who hold one-third of Croatia .
`` Croatia today wants and can regain the territories , '' Susak said .
`` We have restrained so far . ''
But he warned that `` in the next few months Croatia will have to do what every sovereign country would do to regain its territories . ''
Susak did not find such rhetoric incongruous with the economic agreement .
`` We are viewing this agreement as a step forward towards normalization .
But we are not going to wait endlessly for this to happen , '' he said .
Negotiations between the two sides on the economic agreement had been stalled .
But the Serbs ' self-styled government late Wednesday recommended that the assembly meeting in Knin approve the deal .
Croatian authorities had already endorsed the agreement .
Supported by powerful Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic and drafted with the help of international negotiators , the accord was viewed as a possible step toward the gradual reintegration of the Serb areas , called the Krajina , into Croatia .
Thousands of peacekeepers have been deployed between the warring sides in the disputed territories since the January 1992 cease-fire .
But international efforts toward lasting peace have failed over what seemed to be irreconcilable differences .
