Lucien Bouchard , a central and charismatic leader of Quebec 's separatist movement , had his left leg amputated Thursday .
His emergency hospitalization throws into doubt the role the Bloc Quebecois leader will play in next year 's critical referendum on separation .
French-speaking Quebec has long sought some form of sovereignty or separation from the rest of Canada , which is largely English-speaking .
Bouchard , 55 , was in serious but stable condition Thursday at Montreal 's Saint-Luc Hospital , where he was hospitalized Tuesday for a blood clot in his leg .
Bouchard 's doctor , Patrick D'Amico , said in a statement that Bouchard developed an infection on his leg after being hospitalized .
`` This situation necessitated two operations to drain and amputate the leg and control the infection , '' said D'Amico .
Widely considered the most compelling Quebec separatist leader , the charismatic Bouchard 's absence from the upcoming referendum battle would be a blow to forces seeking Quebec 's secession .
Quebec Premier Jacques Parizeau prevailed on Bouchard to show the same courage he has regularly displayed in the political arena .
`` Our prayers are with you , '' said a shaken Parizeau .
`` I hope this will soon be just a bad dream .
Hold on old friend . ''
A Bloc Quebecois spokesman refused to provide more details on Bouchard 's condition .
Bouchard is with him now , '' Marthe Lawrence , Bouchard 's spokesperson , said from the hospital .
`` The family wishes no further statement for the moment . ''
Bouchard became leader of the Opposition after his fledgling party swept Quebec in the 1993 federal election , winning 54 out of 75 seats in the province .
A ferry carrying more than 400 people collided with a freighter and sank before dawn Friday , the Philippine coast guard reported .
The ship sank near the town of Maragondon , about 35 miles southwest of Manila in Cavite province near the mouth of Manila Bay .
There was no immediate word whether anyone was rescued .
The ship was coming from Tagbilaran , capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- southeast of Manila .
News reports said the Singapore-registered freighter , with a crew of 26 , did not sink .
Russia 's prisons are overcrowded and inhumane , with underfed inmates crammed into stinking , standing-room-only cells , a U.N. report said Thursday .
Conditions in pre-trial detention centers -- where first-time offenders accused of petty crimes can wait up to five years for a court appearance -- are even worse than labor camps for hardened convicts , the report said .
`` The oppressive heat , lack of oxygen , and the odors of sweat , excrement and disease created by gross overcrowding are overpowering , '' said Nigel Rodley , the U.N. 's special investigator on torture , who wrote the report .
At the invitation of the Russian government , Rodley spent two weeks visiting prisons near Moscow and St. Petersburg , including four pre-trial centers , two police headquarters , one labor camp , one juvenile center and one hospital for seriously ill prisoners .
The Russian government estimates there are 500,000 prisoners in about 528 prisons and penal colonies throughout the country .
Russia has the highest rate of detentions in the world .
Rodley said the skyrocketing crime rate following the end of communist control has worsened already serious overcrowding in prisons .
He criticized Russian authorities for responding to public concern about crime by throwing petty offenders into jail .
He called on President Boris Yeltsin to issue a presidential decree releasing 71,000 non-violent , first-time offenders to ease the overcrowding .
`` It 's a radical proposal because it 's a radical problem which needs to be addressed urgently , '' Rodley said at a news conference .
He said beatings and maltreatment were widespread .
`` The conditions are cruel , inhuman and degrading ; they are torturous , '' he wrote about cells in Moscow 's Butyrskaya prison .
`` There is virtually no daylight .
There is insufficient room for everyone to lie down , sit down or even stand up at the same time . ''
Butyrskaya prison was constructed in 1771 .
Built for 3,500 prisoners , it now holds 6,300 .
`` The food , not always available because of the indebtedness of the institutions -- is primitive , of a fat-saturated soupy nature .
It is consumed in the cell and is excreted in the cell , '' the report said .
In another Moscow detention center , Matrosskaya Tishina No. 1 , conditions in quarantine cells for sick prisoners were atrocious .
`` Despite the fact that several of the inmates had open , festering sores , severe fungal infections with decaying flesh , and extensive rashes , they reported that they had not seen a doctor in over a week , '' Rodley wrote .
