GATT trade accord clears U.S. Congress with Senate approval .
The U.S. dollar opened at 99.40 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market Friday , up 0.39 yen from Thursday 's close .
The U.S. Senate approved and sent to President Clinton on Thursday night the historic 124-nation GATT trade agreement that will slash tariffs worldwide .
More than 300 Cuban women and children who came here as refugees marched peacefully through the capital Thursday calling on the United States to let them in .
`` We are in this country because we fled from Cuba , a place without hope where the words `` war '' and `` hate '' are constantly in schools , books and television , '' one of the children said in a speech delivered in front of the main government building .
`` We want to know this world which promises a future full of hope . ''
Hundreds of Cubans have fled to this tiny British territory just 70 miles -LRB- 110 kilometers -RRB- south of Cuba since early August , when riots in Havana prompted Cuban President Fidel Castro to say he would not prevent people from leaving .
The approximately 1,175 Cubans who remain represent about 4 percent of the 30,000 residents of this tourist resort and offshore banking center .
The local government is housing them in a tented camp and trying to persuade the United States to accept them .
The United States is already hosting thousands of Cubans in refugee camps .
The Cubans here organized the march to ask for U.S. visas for the elderly and families with young children .
The Caymans ' chief immigration officer was scheduled to brief the refugees Friday on the status of the territory 's talks with the United States and their immigration options , government spokeswoman Pat Ebanks said .
The government has said it would screen all refugees and provide shelter to those who fled political persecution .
It said if the United States did n't accept the others , it would repatriate them as long as the Cuban government would guarantee their safety .
After the screening , the Cayman government decided to grant asylum to a small , as-yet-undetermined number of political refugees , Ebanks said .
Twenty-four refugees have asked to return to their communist homeland and will be flown back , probably within the next two weeks , Ebanks said .
The Cuban government has assured that they will be given safe passage home , she said .
The Caymans sent back nine Cubans who had asked to return in October .
Meanwhile , 55 British policemen arrived Wednesday to relieve local officers who have been working 12-hour shifts to guard the refugees .
Queen Elizabeth II will visit South Africa in March , returning there for the first time since she made her 21st birthday broadcast from Cape Town in 1947 .
As Princess Elizabeth , the queen accompanied her parents , King George VI , who died in 1952 , and Queen Elizabeth , now the 94-year-old Queen Mother , when they visited South Africa in 1947 .
She turned 21 in Cape Town and broadcast from there , dedicating herself to the service of Britain and the now 51-nation Commonwealth of its former colonies .
As international hostility toward apartheid grew , no British sovereign subsequently visited South Africa .
KINGSTON , Jamaica -LRB- AP -RRB- -- Retired Gen. Colin Powell , a child of Jamaican immigrants who worked his way up to become America 's military chief , returned Thursday to receive one of Jamaica 's highest honors .
His wife , Alma , his three children and two grandchildren watched as Governor-General Sir Howard Cooke draped a green sash with the insignia of the Order of Jamaica over Powell 's neck .
The equivalent of a knighthood in the British system , the Order entitles Powell to be called `` The Honorable . ''
It is the highest honor that can be given to non-Jamaicans .
`` Every Jamaican , at home and in the diaspora , sees in your achievement the embodiment of the best in us and an indicator that nothing is beyond the capacity of the Jamaican people , '' Prime Minister P.J. Patterson said .
Patterson and others recounted Powell 's climb from a poor New York City neighborhood to Vietnam soldier , Army general , National Security Adviser , and chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff .
Even before Powell 's retirement from the military in September 1993 , he had been frequently mentioned as a possible contender for the presidency in 1996 .
