Smokers are 50 percent more likely to suffer from impotence than nonsmokers , the U.S. government said Thursday .
Researchers at the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said the rate may be even slightly higher , because some men in the study may have been unwilling to acknowledge the sexual disorder .
`` It 's more bad news for smokers , '' said Dr. David Mannino of the CDC 's National Center for Environmental Health .
Researchers estimate that up to 10 million U.S. men are impotent .
Smoking had long been suspected as a factor , along with diet , diabetes , aging , alcohol and medication .
The study was based on a survey of 4,462 U.S. Army Vietnam veterans between the ages of 31 and 49 .
Of that number , 1,162 said they never smoked ; 1,292 said they were former smokers ; and 2,008 said they currently smoked .
Among nonsmokers , 2.2 percent said they suffered persistent impotence , compared to 2 percent of former smokers and 3.7 percent of current smokers .
Researchers said the difference in the rate of impotence reported by nonsmokers and former smokers was statistically insignificant .
There would be a 68 percent difference in the rate of impotence reported by smokers and nonsmokers except that Mannino said the risk dropped to 50 percent when other factors such as drug abuse , race , age and vascular disease were taken into account .
The report , published in the December issue of the American Journal of Epidemiology , is the first to show that smoking alone is a risk factor for impotence , said Dr. Robert J. Krane , head of Boston University Medical Center 's urology department .
Krane was among a group of researchers trying to examine a possible link between smoking and impotence in men over age 50 .
Most cases of impotence occur among older men .
He said it was particularly striking that the survey participants were younger men .
`` It 's quite impressive that we see a difference in this younger age group , '' he said .
Mannino said the study did not examine why smoking could lead to impotence , but earlier research has shown that smokers are more likely to develop vascular disease , which plays a role in sexual dysfunction .
`` You need good blood vessels to maintain an erection , '' he said .
Other evidence points to the numerous compounds in cigarette smoke , such as carbon monoxide , which can relax the blood vessels or affect the nervous system and thus prevent an erection .
Neither years spent smoking nor the number of cigarettes smoked daily appeared to predict whether a smoker would be impotent , but Mannino said that could change as the men age .
`` This is in relatively young men , '' he said .
`` They may develop more of a problem '' as they continue to smoke .
About 50 Dominican prisoners ordered released by the courts but still behind bars rioted Thursday , burning mattresses and clothes in a call to be let out .
No injuries were reported .
`` We want justice , we want liberty , '' shouted the inmates at the La Victoria prison 14 kilometers -LRB- 9 miles -RRB- north of the capital city .
The eight-hour uprising was quelled only when police sprayed about 20,000 gallons -LRB- 76,000 liters -RRB- of water into the cells and the country 's Human Rights Commission president , Virgilio Almanzar , asked the inmates to stop .
Santo Domingo prosecutor Alexis Joaquin Castillo was scheduled to meet with the inmates Friday .
An estimated 130 of La Victoria 's 4,000 prisoners were declared innocent or ordered released by the courts months ago , but they remain in jail .
Some were jailed only on the orders of police , with no charges against them .
Human rights groups and the inmates ' families have demanded the release of the prisoners , known locally as `` the disrespected . ''
President Joaquin Balaguer has said the prisoners should remain behind bars , arguing that the decisions to release them were tainted by corruption .
He created a committee to review the cases .
U.S. Olympic silver medalist Picabo Street had the fastest time Thursday in the final tuneup for the opening women 's World Cup downhill ski race of the season .
Street beat Canadian Kate Pace by 31-hundredths of a second on the third day of training .
Street , who coasted through the finish and nonchalantly missed the final gate , was timed in 1 minute , 45.66 seconds as the 26th starter .
For the first time , downhillers in the top seed of 15 can select their starting numbers from 1 through 30 , and most of the favorites chose numbers in the 20s for the training runs .
Pace , who won the 1993 world championship downhill , had a time of 1:45.97 .
Anja Haas of Austria was third at 1:46.02 , followed by Olympic champion and defending World Cup downhill titlist Katja Seizinger of Germany at 1:46.03 .
Switzerland 's Chantal Bournissen , who led the first training run Tuesday , was fifth at 1:46.46 .
Melanie Suchet of France was sixth at 1:46.55 , and Swiss veteran Heidi Zeller-Baehler , winner of the giant slalom in the season-opening races last weekend , was seventh at 1:46.56 .
Street said she `` went way wide '' on a turn in the top part of the course .
`` But I carried my speed OK through there .
I took a pretty tight line after that and things were coming at me faster , but I was ready for it . ''
`` The course probably wo n't be a whole lot faster tomorrow , '' Street said .
`` It will be a matter of who can clean up their mistakes and find a couple more tenths . ''
Pace was pleased with her result , after placing ninth and 13th in the two previous training runs .
`` Finally , '' she said .
`` I have n't been able to follow my game plan because of the loose snow on the course , but there was no loose snow or fresh snow overnight , and the course was perfect today . ''
Hilary Lindh of Juneau , Alaska , the 1992 Olympic silver medalist in downhill who posted her first World Cup win last February , was 17th in 1:47.02 .
