Chechnya has been a thorn in Russia 's side since the early 19th century , when the Russian Empire rapidly expanded through the Caucasus Mountains , gobbling up small countries and ethnic enclaves .
Many of the small nations gave in , thankful for Russian protection against hostile neighbors .
In the Russian mind , Chechnya still evokes images of warriors , savages and criminals -- and also victims of Russian and Soviet persecution .
There is a religious divide as well ; Chechens are Muslims , Russians Christians .
For 50 years , the Chechens held out against Russian domination , capitulating in 1859 .
The dark-haired mountaineers often existed by raiding their neighbors for food , and Russian military camps quickly became targets .
In one well-known poem that is required reading in many Russian schools , poet Mikhail Lermontov referred to `` the evil Chechen -LRB- who -RRB- crawls up the bank '' of the Terek River .
After the Chechen surrender , Russian Cossacks were encouraged to settle nearby to work the fertile lands and keep the peace .
But the fragile balance between Russian and Chechen was shattered under dictator Josef Stalin .
He first dispersed the Cossacks in an early purge .
Then , during World War II , he accused Chechens of supporting the Nazis and deported the entire nation , sending almost 400,000 people to Central Asia .
When they were allowed to return after Stalin 's death , Chechens found their homes destroyed and their land seized by former neighbors , mostly Russians or Ossetians .
Only Soviet repression kept the ethnic conflict from boiling over .
With the Soviet breakup , age-old hostilities have flared again .
The capital , Grozny , has become a war zone between forces loyal to Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , who declared independence from Moscow in 1991 , and Chechen rebels trying to topple him .
Russian troops are stationed in neighboring Ossetia and Ingushetia , but Chechnya has told Moscow to stay away .
Russia on Thursday backed off from a threat to send troops after Chechnya defied a Russian ultimatum and called on armed volunteers to defend the capital .
Air attacks continued on the outskirts of Grozny on Thursday , claiming at least a few civilian lives .
And a Russian delegation arrived from Moscow and began talks with Chechen officials .
Meanwhile , residents continued to flee the mainly Muslim city of 300,000 people .
As Chechen clans fight each other ; the region 's industries have come to a standstill , and living standards have plunged .
Crime is up , and Russians say it is spilling out of Chechnya .
They accuse Chechens of stealing cattle and cars from nearby Cossack villages .
In Moscow , police say Chechen mafia clans are among the strongest , and avoid arrest by hiding in Chechnya .
Then this summer , there was a string of hostage-takings in southern Russia , some carried out by Chechen gunmen who tried to escape into Chechnya .
In July , when several terrorists hijacked a busload of people near the border , Dudayev said Russian police would not be allowed to follow if they tried to escape to Chechnya .
Russian police then tried to seize the terrorists before they could escape , and four hostages were killed .
`` Chechens ... are fiercely independent and aggressive , like ancient Vikings , '' said Vasily Varenik , a historian in Rostov-on-Don .
`` It wo n't be easy to find a solution . ''
