The United States should resist any temptation to deal with organized crime in Russia or China , says a security expert recalling World War II contacts with the Italian Mafia .
`` The time may come when American national interests may clash most seriously with Russian or Chinese interests , '' and `` individuals in our government might then be tempted to form alliances with Russian or Chinese organized crime , as their predecessors did on Sicily in the 1940s , '' said Brian R. Sullivan , a fellow at the National Defense University 's Institute for Strategic Studies .
`` That probably would be a very bad idea , '' said Sullivan , mentioning the spread of crime in post-Soviet Russia and Triads `` reportedly gaining unprecedented strength '' in Chinese mainland cities and among overseas Chinese .
Sullivan spoke at a forum on organized crime sponsored by the American Bar Association and other legal groups .
It began Thursday and was continuing Friday .
`` Weighing the gains and losses ... it seems that American interests were far more damaged by the Mafia over the years than they were served , '' said Sullivan , who has closely studied Italy .
`` And the damage continues , particularly given heavy Mafia involvement in drug trafficking . ''
Preparing for the allied invasion of Italy in 1943 in the campaign to overthrow the Rome-Berlin Axis , U.S. Naval Intelligence opened contact with Sicilian organized crime `` including with Italian-American criminals who had been deported from the United States ... -LRB- and -RRB- men who could be considered both well-informed and anti-Fascist , '' Sullivan said .
`` After the invasion , American authorities employed the same men and their associates , '' he continued , affording them access to arms `` to begin highly lucrative black market operations .
The modern Mafia began to form . ''
In postwar Italy , the Vatican and U.S. administrations supported Italy 's Christian Democrats against the Communists `` in every way possible , '' Sullivan said , turning a blind eye to Christian-Democrat connections with organized crime that finally brought down seven-time Prime Minister Giulio Andreotti in 1992 .
`` There is reason to believe that the Italian Mafia benefited greatly from American government support in 1943-45 and again in 1947-48 , '' he said .
Even today , `` the outcome of the war against the Mafia '' remains uncertain , Sullivan said .
But a lesson to be drawn from the vigorous anti-Mafia efforts of the late prosecutors Giovanni Falcone and Paolo Borsellino is that feared crime syndicates become powerful because of government support and turn vulnerable when they lose it , he added .
With the Mafia on the defensive , Falcone and Borsellino were both assassinated in 1993 .
A senior Federal Bureau of Investigation official , Jim E. Moody , told the gathering Italy has new laws to deal with organized crime that are as effective as laws in the United States .
Public outrage over the Falcone and Borsellino killings demanded their enactment , he said .
An unmanned Ariane rocket carrying an American communications satellite crashed into the Atlantic Ocean 15 minutes after blastoff Thursday due to failure in the third-stage engine , which was using a new fuel mix .
Technicians at the Arianespace launching pad on the edge of the South American jungle said that the third-stage engine inexplicably lost pressure 218 kilometers -LRB- 135 miles -RRB- above Earth .
The failure indicated continuing problems in the third stage .
In January , a third-stage breakdown forced engineers to explode a rocket in mid-flight .
A Turkish and a European telecommunications satellites were also destroyed .
Six perfect launches followed .
Thursday 's crash was the seventh in 70 launches since the European Space Agency 's commercial Arianespace program lifted off 15 years ago .
It should not shake Ariane 's dominance as the world 's most successful launcher of lucrative private satellites .
`` We hope to get back into operation very quickly , '' said Charles Bigot , Arianespace 's chief executive officer .
An investigation was opened immediately and a news conference scheduled for Friday to explain the initial findings .
Liftoff was on schedule at 7:38 p.m.
The first two stages fired perfectly and controllers confidently expected another of what have become almost routine shots for the Ariane launchers .
The third stage also lit properly , but then mysteriously sputtered and went out .
Officials said that the third stage was a new type using a new oxygen-hydrogen mixture to maximize performance .
The rocket took down with it a 2,985-kilogram -LRB- 3.3-ton -RRB- PanAmSat-3 telecommunications satellite built by Hughes Space and Communications in El Segundo , California .
Belonging to PanAmSat of Greenwich , Conn. , the satellite would have channeled telephone , fax and television communications for most of North and South America , Europe and Africa over 15 years .
It would have traveled in geostationary orbit over the mid-Atlantic .
January 's accident was blamed on a turbo-pump failure freezing the third-stage rocket motor .
That failure followed 26 straight successful launches in which the European rocket distanced itself from its competitors , the United States and China .
The Arianes have put 94 satellites in orbit and have a backlog of 38 .
Anti-government demonstrators pelted riot police with rocks and burned a police jeep Thursday to protest the inauguration of President Ernesto Zedillo .
At least 58 people were injured in the violence , which marred a festive national holiday , according to a Red Cross spokesman who refused to give his name .
He said 30 of the injured were taken to a Red Cross hospital and 28 were treated at the scene .
Five of the injured were reported in serious condition .
The violence erupted after a rally by 10,000 anti-government demonstrators scattered from the downtown Monument of the Revolution .
Hundreds of rowdy youths ran up against a column of riot police at a major intersection near the Zocalo , the city 's main plaza .
For more than an hour , shirtless youths heaved a steady stream of stones against plastic shields of riot police , who stood shoulder to shoulder blocking the route to a post-inaugural military parade attended briefly by Zedillo .
A government official telephoned The Associated Press and said the violence was an isolated incident caused by `` a small group of provocateurs . ''
He did not elaborate .
At one point , a handful of demonstrators wielding stout wooden clubs charged against the plastic shields of a phalanx of riot police , who counterattacked , forcing hundreds to flee .
Protesters also torched a truck that bore the symbol of Zedillo 's Institutional Revolutionary Party , or PRI .
Police clubbed one young man and tore his shirt off after his burst through the phalanx of helmeted and baton-wielding officers .
Another man in a straw sombrero stumbled , bleeding from the head .
There was no immediate report on police injuries .
The protesters , ranging from city residnents to farmers in straw hats , raised banners of the leftist Democratic Revolution Party , a vocal opponent of the PRI 's monopoly on power .
JoAnne Carner and Jim Albus were one of three teams tied for the lead Thursday after the first-round of the JCPenney Classic , a mixed-team event that pairs male and female pros .
Playing a best-ball format , Carner , 55 , and Albus , 54 , had a 7-under-par 64 on the Innisbrook Resort 's Copperhead Course .
They were tied with the teams of Jane Geddes and Brian Claar and Marta Figueras-Dotti and Brad Bryant .
Eight other teams were at 6-under .
`` Oh , yeah ! ''
`` Two over-50 players against players in their late 20s and early 30s .
I think that 's pretty good . ''
Carner was aided by an early-week lesson from Albus , the former club pro who never played the Professional Golf Assocation Tour .
`` I used to give 15 lessons a day , '' Albus said .
`` But that was the first one in about three years .
And I never gave one to a player like JoAnne . ''
But she says it 's done wonders for her game .
`` I look up now and the ball is going right where I aimed it , '' Carner said .
The Carner-Albus team had a seven-birdie , no-bogey round .
Carner made birdie putts from 12 , 25 and 6 feet , while Albus drained birdie putts from 15 , 12 , 12 and 3 feet .
Forty-six of the 52 teams were under par and 27 teams were within three strokes of the lead .
The format Friday changes to alternate-stroke before returning to best-ball Saturday and finishing with alternate-stroke on Sunday .
One stroke behind the co and leaders at 6 and under 65 were : Judy Dickinson and Jay Sigel , Dana Dormann and Fred Funk , Amy Alcott and Robin Freeman , Chris Johnson and Neal Lancaster , Gail Graham and Dave Barr , Beth Daniel and Davis Love III , Vicki Goetze and Steve Striker and Nancy Ramsbottom and Mike Sullivan .
The players are all members of the PGA Tour , the Ladies Professional Golf Association , or the Senior Professional Golf Association .
The U.S. Senate overwhelmingly approved and sent to President Clinton the historic 124-nation GATT trade agreement that will slash tariffs worldwide .
Clinton called Thursday night 's vote a `` victory for America '' and said he hopes it is a harbinger of cooperation between his Democratic administration and the opposition Republicans who soon will assume control of Congress .
The Senate gave final congressional approval to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade on a vote of 76-24 .
The House of Representatives had approved the accord on Tuesday .
The Senate had voted 68-32 just minutes earlier to waive its own budget rules and remove a key procedural hurdle to passage .
Sixty votes were needed in the earlier vote .
Clinton had worked throughout the day to convince wavering lawmakers to support the deal , and he exulted in its passage .
`` Let 's make the GATT vote the first vote of a new era of cooperation , '' said Clinton , who was joined by Democrats and Republicans alike in a victory celebration on the south lawn of the White House .
`` America 's best days are ahead of us . ''
Retiring Senate Democratic Leader George Mitchell said the vote sends a signal to the world that America and its workers remain the world 's leaders .
`` We do not fear competition ; we welcome it .
We do not shrink from the future ; we welcome that , '' Mitchell said .
On the crucial budget waiver vote , the accord was supported by 31 Republicans and 37 Democrats and was opposed by 15 Republicans and 17 Democrats .
Senate Republican Leader Robert Dole said his office was still getting up to 2,000 calls a day protesting the agreement .
Dole said he had decided to support agreement , even with its flaws , because the alternative of defeat would be far worse .
`` The bottom line is we just ca n't isolate ourselves from the rest of the world , '' Dole said before the Senate began voting .
The trade agreement cuts tariffs by an average of 38 percent worldwide .
For the first time , it extends GATT rules to such new areas as reduction of trade-distorting agriculture subsidies , lowering trade barriers in service industries such as banking , and clamping down on copyright piracy .
It also creates a more powerful World Trade Organization to referee trade disputes and eliminates the one-country veto that a losing nation could use to block an adverse ruling .
Supporters said the agreement , by cutting the border taxes Americans have to pay while at the same time lowering barriers U.S. businesses and farmers face overseas , would provide a tremendous boost to the U.S. economy .
The Clinton administration estimated this would create a half-million new jobs and mean an annual increase of dlrs 150 billion in U.S. economic growth a decade from now , when the deal is fully implemented .
That extra growth would put dlrs 1,700 more a year in the pockets of the average American family , the administration said .
However , opponents charged that the WTO represented a dangerous encroachment on U.S. sovereignty .
They said that seven previous GATT negotiating rounds to lower trade barriers have not cured America 's chronic trade deficit nor stopped the hemorrhage of manufacturing jobs overseas .
They warned that in textiles alone , one of America 's most protected industries , 1 million jobs could be lost .
`` We are not leading in world trade .
We are losing , '' Sen. Ernest Hollings , a Democrat from South Carolina , a leading textile state , said during floor debate .
`` The reality is that we are in decline .
Everybody knows that . ''
The administration was anxious for a healthy bipartisan victory margin as a way to show that a Democratic White House will be able to work next year with the first Republican-controlled Congress in four decades .
The Senate vote followed a surprisingly large 142-vote margin of victory in the House on Tuesday .
Before the congressional action , only 36 other nations had approved GATT .
But many other nations were simply waiting to see what the United States did .
The agreement is scheduled to go into effect on Jan. 1 .
The debate over the WTO came during the first outgoing session of Congress in 12 years .
It was forced by Hollings , who used his power as a chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee to block a vote before the November elections .
A diverse group of opponents worked down to the wire to defeat the deal , taking out newspaper ads and mobilizing opponents to telephone lawmakers .
