An unmanned Ariane rocket carrying an American communications satellite crashed into the Atlantic Ocean 15 minutes after blastoff Thursday due to failure in the third-stage engine , which was using a new fuel mix .
Technicians at the Arianespace launching pad on the edge of the South American jungle said that the third-stage engine inexplicably lost pressure 218 kilometers -LRB- 135 miles -RRB- above Earth .
The failure indicated continuing problems in the third stage .
In January , a third-stage breakdown forced engineers to explode a rocket in mid-flight .
A Turkish and a European telecommunications satellites were also destroyed .
Six perfect launches followed .
Thursday 's crash was the seventh in 70 launches since the European Space Agency 's commercial Arianespace program lifted off 15 years ago .
It should not shake Ariane 's dominance as the world 's most successful launcher of lucrative private satellites .
`` We hope to get back into operation very quickly , '' said Charles Bigot , Arianespace 's chief executive officer , who apologized to the dlrs 150 million satellite 's owners .
An investigation was opened immediately and a news conference scheduled for Friday to explain the initial findings .
Liftoff was on schedule at 7:38 p.m.
The first two stages fired perfectly and controllers confidently expected another of what have become almost routine shots for the Ariane launchers .
The third stage also lit properly , but then mysteriously sputtered and went out .
Officials said that the third stage was a new type using a new oxygen-hydrogen mixture to maximize performance .
The rocket took down with it a 2,985-kilogram -LRB- 3.3-ton -RRB- PanAmSat-3 telecommunications satellite built by Hughes Space and Communications in El Segundo , California .
Belonging to PanAmSat of Greenwich , Conn. , the satellite would have channeled telephone , fax and television communications for most of North and South America , Europe and Africa over 15 years .
It would have traveled in geostationary orbit over the mid-Atlantic .
January 's accident was blamed on a turbo-pump failure freezing the third-stage rocket motor .
That failure followed 26 straight successful launches in which the European rocket distanced itself from its competitors , the United States and China .
The Arianes have put 94 satellites in orbit and have a backlog of 38 .
George Foreman got him mad and Eddie Futch set him straight .
Now , Riddick Bowe says , he 's ready to answer critics who have questioned both his weight and his desire .
`` It 's just like during the Olympics when they said he 's lazy and he 's crazy , '' Bowe said .
`` People think I 'm no longer hungry .
That 's not true . ''
Bowe returns to the ring Saturday for only the second time since losing his heavyweight titles to Evander Holyfield when he meets unbeaten former Olympian Larry Donald in a scheduled 12-round bout .
It 's somewhat of a crossroads fight for the former champion , who is trying to shake the complacency that came with the titles and the accompanying fat bank account .
`` The luxury mentality is gone , '' said Bowe 's manager , Rock Newman .
`` Somewhere he has gotten it back .
He has to grab the bull by the horns -LRB- take the initiative -RRB- and this is what he has done . ''
Bowe , who weighed 247 pounds -LRB- 112 kilos -RRB- for his aborted return to the ring in August against Buster Mathis Jr. , claims to be in his best shape since beating Holyfield in November 1992 to win the titles .
On Thursday , Bowe weighed in at 241 pounds -LRB- 109 kilos -RRB- , a drop of six pounds -LRB- 3 kilos -RRB- from his last fight .
Donald was at 228 pounds -LRB- 103 kilos -RRB- .
If Bowe is in the shape he claims to be , it 's because of a talk from Futch , his 83-year-old trainer , coupled with the shock of seeing the 45-year-old Foreman knock Michael Moorer out to win two-thirds of the title .
`` The Foreman fight really ticked me off , '' Bowe said .
`` It 's unfortunate Michael Moorer is dumber than all outdoors .
Why would you stand in front of George Foreman like that ?
After watching Foreman beat Michael Moorer , I became more determined . ''
Futch had earlier threatened to leave Bowe 's New Orleans training camp unless the former champion rededicated himself to his training efforts .
Futch said Bowe was n't following a program prescribed by physical therapist Mackey Shilstone as closely as he should .
`` I said , ` If you do n't care about yourself , why should I care about you ?
I am here for you , '' ' Futch said .
The message seems to have sunk in for Bowe , who many thought would hold the heavyweight titles a long time after handing Holyfield his first loss .
Instead , Bowe defended the title with two quick knockouts over Jesse Ferguson and Michael Dokes , then lost them last November in a close 12-round decision .
`` I still think I won that fight , '' Bowe said .
`` I wanted to knock Evander Holyfield out so bad because no one had ever done that .
If I had just used my jab , he could n't touch me .
I allowed him to get too close to me . ''
The 27-year-old Bowe , 34-1 with 29 knockouts , came into the Holyfield rematch 11 pounds heavier than he was when he won the title .
Although both he and Futch said the extra weight was simply a result of Bowe continuing to grow , it seemed to take a toll on him during the fight .
`` As long as I 'm in shape , I beat all the heavyweights out there , '' Bowe said .
`` They can only hope I 'm fat and come in out of condition . ''
Bowe not only has to beat Donald , a 1992 Olympian who is 16-0 as a pro , he has to look good doing it .
After planned fights against Lennox Lewis and Moorer fell apart because of losses by the two fighters , Bowe finds himself effectively shut out of chances against either Foreman or WBC champion Oliver McCall .
Bowe , though , is the No. 1 contender in the lightly regarded WBO , and could face Herbie Hide for that title in the spring .
Winning that title could give him the leverage needed to get the big fights .
`` I do n't care what title it is as long as it indicates I 'm the heavyweight champion of the world , '' Bowe said .
`` I know I 'm the best heavyweight in the world and to see these guys out there as heavyweight champions , its ludicrous . ''
Ernesto Zedillo began his term as Mexico 's president by vowing to clean up the justice system , fight poverty , strengthen democracy and renew efforts to end a Indian revolt in southern Mexico .
Zedillo , who rose from youth as a shoeshine boy to earn an economics doctorate from Yale , was sworn in Thursday before 1,500 Mexican and foreign officials at the Chamber of Deputies .
He received the green , white and red presidential slash from former President Salinas de Gortari to begin a six-year-term at the helm of this nation of 90 million .
`` We think he will be a good president ! ''
said Carmen Valencia , a 60-year-old housewife .
`` He came from below and understands poverty . ''
About 80 protesters among a crowd of hundreds clashed with riot police , hurling rocks and burning two vehicles after the ceremony .
Police responded with tear gas .
A Red Cross spokesman said 58 people were injured .
The protesters had emerged from a peaceful gathering by about 10,000 at the Monument of the Revolution in downtown Mexico City .
They shouted `` Out with Zedillo ! ''
and called for an end to the 65-year rule of his Institutional Revolutionary Party , or PRI .
Zedillo , 42 , said one of his first acts would be to introduce a constitutional amendment for a `` profound transformation '' of the justice system , now subservient to politicians and often accused of corruption .
He also vowed to balance the overwhelming power of the presidency by strengthening congress and local governments and to end the presidential practice of dominating PRI affairs .
`` If he fulfills what he said about not interfering with the party , then it will be a a great parting of the waters for reforms in the PRI , '' said Augustine Basave , a former PRI congressman from Monterrey .
On the economic front , Zedillo promised to follow in the free-market footsteps of Salinas , who signed the North American Free Trade Agreement , slashed inflation and privatized hundreds of state-owned companies .
`` I shall continue to apply those principles in order to preserve our national sovereignty and promote Mexico 's legitimate interests in a world of keen competition ... '' he said .
The ceremony was attended by representatives of 63 nations , including Vice President Al Gore , Cuban President Fidel Castro and Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez .
`` Mexico has certainly prospered , '' said Zedillo .
But he added , `` We can not feel fully satisfied .
Many millions of Mexicans lack the bare essentials . ''
The bookish Zedillo would not have been at the helm of one of the most powerful presidencies in the world had it not been for the March 23 assassination of Luis Donaldo Colosio , the hand-picked successor to Salinas .
Many Mexicans say they doubt the official theory of a lone gunman .
Another killing shook the nation in September , when PRI secretary-general Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu was gunned down .
Prosecutors charged that senior members of the ruling party were involved , possibly as an effort to stop reforms .
`` The brutal assassinations of two of Mexico 's most outstanding public figures have deeply hurt our citizens , '' Zedillo said .
`` Thus , the investigations have not been to the entire satisfaction of society .
We ... want to be sure that we know the truth . ''
One of Zedillo 's biggest challenges comes from the southern state of Chiapas , where Indian guerrillas have refused to end a rebellion that has been stalled since a Jan. 12 cease-fire .
`` I am convinced that it is possible to achieve a new negotiation in Chiapas that will lead us to a just , honorable and definitive peace , '' he said .
He promised the army would maintain the unilateral cease-fire .
In a bargaining session that raised hopes of saving the season , National Hockey League players Thursday gave ground on at least one issue and both sides agreed in principle on several others .
The owners and union met for about eight hours in wide-ranging discussions aimed at ending the 62-day lockout .
Among the issues on the table are the rookie salary cap , salary arbitration and free agency .
Since the owners locked players out on Oct. 1 , the season has dwindled down to 60 games , with 24 games stripped from each team .
It has been generally acknowledged there must be a labor agreement in place by mid-December to assure a season .
Neither side would characterize Thursday 's talks , but the Canadian Press reported the union had dropped its desired salary ceiling to dlrs 1.25 million from dlrs 1.5 million for first-round players , while the NHL remained at dlrs 700,000 .
On salary arbitration , the NHL wants to retain its right to have an arbitrator 's decision to be non-binding on the team -- rather than paying the awarded salary , a team could allow the player to become an unrestricted free agent .
