Cuba loosened the shackles on its economy another notch Thursday when it allowed some surplus clothes and other goods to be sold at free-market prices .
But Cuban reporters contacted by phone said the selection and the customers were reportedly skimpy at newly established shops .
The measure appeared to have far less immediate impact than the recent legalization of a limited free market in foodstuffs -- one of a series of reforms that has helped the Communist government stabilize its once-plummeting economy .
