Russia has decided not to proceed with a threatened lawsuit that could have sought hundreds of thousands of dollars from Nova Scotia fishermen who blockaded a Russian ship last year .
`` It certainly is a relief that they 're not pursuing it , '' said Cliff Fanning of the Eastern Fishermen 's Federation .
In July 1993 , fishermen from Fanning 's group and the South West Nova Scotia Fixed Gear Association blockaded the fish-carrying freighter Pioner Murmana as it unloaded at the Continental Seafoods plant in Shelburne , N.S. , in July 1993 .
Hemmed in by fishing boats , the freezer ship could n't move for seven days .
Ivan Vidaneev , Russia 's fishery agent in Nova Scotia , said the Russian government company that owns the Pioner Murmana consulted a Nova Scotia law firm but then decided against the suit .
Vidaneev said he believes there was enough publicity during the blockade to ensure that the Canadians responsible for the losses to the Russian government could be identified .
