But Thursday night , he signalled that tax hikes were the way to go by endorsing Willis ' remarks .
Trade Minister Bob McMullan said Friday that Australians would vote for a government that introduced higher taxes if it was the right decision for the country .
`` If we make a decision whether it 's about taxes or something else that 's on the face of it unpopular but good for the country , they 'll vote for it , '' he said .
But Alexander Downer , the leader of the opposition Liberal-National Party coalition , vows to fight any tax increases .
He obviously relishes a chance to campaign against the Labor Party 's purported `` tax-and-spend '' policies .
Long - and short-term rates on the Australian financial markets jumped when the growth figures came out , reflecting fears that overheated growth would spur inflation , prodding the government to increase interest rates to cope with it .
The Reserve Bank meets against next week , and many economists are expecting another increase in interest rates , which would be the third in recent months .
That would raise the average monthly mortgage rate by dlrs 114 -LRB- dlrs 87 U.S. -RRB- .
Keating , Willis , McMullen and other administration leaders insist they 've got the situation well in hand and the public need not worry .
