A United Nations protest to Bosnian Serbs for detaining peacekeepers and attacking a Canadian camp sparked a response from the Serbs ' top general , a spokeswoman said .
Officials declined to comment Thursday on the contents of two Serb letters , saying they came at a `` sensitive '' time .
But sources said the response was n't specific enough for UN leaders trying to restart talks on releasing more than 400 UN troops , including 55 Canadians .
The letters -- from Gen. Ratko Mladic , Serb army commander , and one of his assistants -- went to Lt.-Gen .
Bertrand Guillaume de Lapresle , UN commander in the former Yugoslavia , and his deputy , Canadian Maj.-Gen .
Raymond Crabbe , said Canadian spokeswoman Maj. Rita LePage .
Earlier this week , Lapresle and Crabbe wrote to the Serbs protesting the holding of UN troops and a Serb rocket attack on the Canadian camp in Visoko on Sunday , which damaged a building .
Prime Minister Jean Chretien , in Paris on Thursday for a world conference on AIDS , said the troops ' detention is unacceptable but little progress has been made in efforts to win their release .
`` They are detained , you can call it hostages .
... But I would not fight on the meaning of words here . ''
Earlier , in a speech to the French Senate , Chretien said NATO allies will try to solve the crisis in talks in Budapest next week with former Soviet bloc countries .
Meanwhile , UN officials tried to schedule talks near Sarajevo on releasing the peacekeepers .
Lapresle and Yasushi Akashi , the top UN civilian envoy in Bosnia , were to meet today with Mladic and Radovan Karadzic , political leader of Bosnia 's Serbs , at the Bosnian Serb headquarters of Pale .
In Sarajevo , Reuters quoted UN officials as saying they believed Lt.-Gen .
Sir Michael Rose , the UN commander in Bosnia , had won pledges in talks with Serb leaders in Pale to release the detained peacekeepers .
The report could not be confirmed .
Jan-Dirk Merveldt , a UN spokesman in Zagreb , Croatia , said Rose was optimistic the detainees would be released soon and quoted Rose as saying Karadzic promised action on the detainees , perhaps by today .
But Merveldt also said promises from Karadzic have not been kept in the past .
Optimism was dampened when Bosnian Serb forces were reported to have crossed into Croatia on Tuesday , kidnapped seven Ukrainian peacekeepers and took them to Serb-held territory .
Serbs also blocked food convoys , fired missiles at the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo and traded fire with government troops around Bihac , a UN-designated safe haven in northwest Bosnia .
The 55 Canadians have been held for more than a week at various locations near Visoko .
A camp supply vehicle reached the Canadians on Wednesday night with books , mail and personal items .
Life at the Canadian camp gradually returned to normal Thursday , a day after a Serb threat to shell the camp passed without incident .
But the camp stayed at the high alert level of orange Thursday , which requires personnel to wear flak jackets and helmets when outside .
In Brussels , NATO foreign ministers gathered to seek terms for a ceasefire as western allies argued over how NATO and the UN should handle the war .
Officials in Bonn confirmed that NATO has asked Germany to contribute fighter planes to patrol over Bosnia .
That would put Germany 's military in its first combat role in 49 years .
The judge in the O.J. Simpson case dismissed three jury prospects Thursday who acknowledged hearing that Nicole Brown Simpson 's sister has publicly branded Simpson a killer .
`` I think I heard Simpson 's sister-in-law say he was going to kill her ... Nicole , '' one of the three prospective alternate jurors told Superior Court Judge Lance Ito .
All three were dismissed as Ito continued his search for 15 alternate jurors to join the 12 jurors who have already been selected to hear the case .
In recent days , a feud has erupted between the Simpson defense and relatives of Simpson 's ex-wife and her friend Ronald Goldman , who were knifed to death outside her condominium June 12 .
Simpson , a former football legend , television sports commentator and movie star , has pleaded innocent to murder charges in the slayings .
Defense lawyers Robert Shapiro and Johnnie Cochran Jr. have accused Ms. Simpson 's sister , Denise Brown , of orchestrating an effort to deny Simpson a fair trial by repeatedly accusing him in media interviews of killing her sister .
On Thursday , Shapiro said he would try to limit his public comments to temper the `` media madness . ''
`` In the spirit of trying to accomplish what we all want , we are going to take the high road , '' Shapiro said outside court .
`` We no longer are going to be talking to the press on a daily basis .
... We hope everybody else takes the road with us . ''
In New York , a judge rebuked Ito for scheduling a hearing on DNA evidence at a time when Simpson 's DNA expert , Peter Neufeld , is supposed to be representing a murder defendant in his courtroom .
Justice Harold Rothwax rebuffed Neufeld 's renewed effort to delay the trial and ordered the lawyer to appear in his court Monday .
Rothwax criticized Ito for ordering Neufeld to appear at the DNA hearing in Los Angeles on Dec. 12 .
`` It 's inexplicable to me that Judge Ito would issue an order that he refused to issue two weeks ago , '' Rothwax said , adding that he believed Ito had done so at Shapiro 's request .
`` It 's clear to me that what Mr. Shapiro is trying to do is put Mr. Simpson 's interests before the interests of the people of New York , '' Rothwax said .
Neufeld hired lawyer William Kunstler to represent him in the tug-of-war , and Kunstler said he 'll ask a federal judge on Friday to throw out Rothwax 's order .
