Citizens in the Maldives archipelago voted Friday to elect a new 48-member Parliament which has little say in the Indian Ocean islands ' administration that is controlled by the President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom .
Forty lawmakers will be elected by the 109,072 voters in the daylong poll , while Gayoom will appoint eight others .
The results of the elections , held once in five years , will be known in six days , since the ballot boxes have to be ferried by boats from 19 atolls to the capital Male for counting .
Gayoom , who has ruled the nation comprising 1,196 Indian Ocean coral islands since 1978 , has promised to share powers with parliament , but there has n't been any transfer so far .
Serving his fourth term in office , Gayoom has instead banned political parties and crushed all forms of opposition to him by banishing dissenters to uninhabited islands .
But for the first time , many of the 248 candidates contesting the polls were publicly canvassing for votes this year , promising democracy , said a Maldivian diplomat in Colombo .
The candidates had put up banners and posters , promising to fight for the rights of the people , said a Colombo-based Maldivian diplomat on condition of anonymity .
`` Voting commenced peacefully at 7:30 am -LRB- 0200 gmt -RRB- and will go on until 5:30 pm -LRB- 1200 gmt -RRB- with a break for Friday prayers .
There have been no problems so far , '' Election Commissioner Abdullah Rashid told The Associated Press on telephone from Male .
Only 220 islands in the Maldives are inhabited by 200,000 people who are predominantly Muslim .
The islands are located 640-kilometers -LRB- 400-miles -RRB- south west of Sri Lanka .
About 55 islands have been developed as tourist resorts , which provide most of the nation 's earnings .
The country also exports fish and garments .
The Maldives remained a sultanate until 1897 when it was colonized by the British .
It won independence in 1965 .
China 's leaders are united behind an economic plan for 1995 to control the rapidly growing economy and curb runaway inflation , the country 's newspapers reported Friday .
The announcement that reforms would continue with no major changes followed four days of closed meetings on economic problems by top Communist Party leaders .
`` China will continue to strengthen macroeconomic control over the national economy in order to seek a sustainable , rapid and healthy economic development next year , '' the Xinhua News Agency said in summing up the meeting of the Communist Party Central Committee and the State Council , or Cabinet .
The latest announcement was placed on front pages of all major newspapers Friday .
Continuing policies include strict control of bank credit , the reports said .
China 's leaders already had announced that controlling inflation , now running over 20 percent , and reforming failing state enterprises would be top goals for the new year .
State-run industries account for about half of China 's industrial output , and just under half of them have been losing money .
Fearing social instability , the government has so far stopped short of massive layoffs or cutting social services tied to state jobs .
The growth rate this year has been over 11 percent .
Other priorities listed in the latest economic plan included more spending on agriculture to ensure adequate food production .
In an editorial on Friday , the People 's Daily , the mouthpiece of the party , outlined some of the economic problems facing China .
The gap is growing between rich industrial areas and poor , rural inland areas , it noted .
In addition , high inflation for the past two years has aroused concern throughout society , it said , warning that while some inflation during rapid economic growth was unavoidable , too much was dangerous .
