`` I understand now what it takes to be an Olympic champion and World Cup champion .
These guys -LRB- the Norwegians -RRB- have worked very hard and hopefully in a few years I 'll be the same caliber as they are , '' said American Todd Lodwick , who posted jumps of 112 and 112.5 meters to top the Americans in that phase .
`` This is the first time I 've ever been on a World Cup podium and it 's pretty damn exciting . ''
The Norwegian victory produced a double for Knut Tore Apeland , who won the individual event on Tuesday .
His teammate , 1994 Olympic individual champion Fred Boerre Lundberg , added the team gold to the bronze he won Tuesday .
`` You never know in cross-country , '' Lundberg said .
`` You could break a ski or ski off the track , but , yes , if everything was OK we were quite sure of winning . ''
Japan 's Takanori Kono and Tsuguhara Ogiwara won the jumping phase Thursday afternoon with 463.6 points to Norway 's 460.1 and 448.4 for Lodwick and teammate Ryan Heckman .
Under the scoring system used for Nordic combined , jump points are converted into a time penalty used for the start of the cross-country race .
That meant that Norway would start 11 seconds behind Japan , with the Americans another 35 seconds behind .
Midway through Norway 's second 1.2-kilometer lap , Lundberg went past Ogiwara on an uphill section and began to pull away .
At the end of 15 kilometers , the Norwegians were almost a minute ahead .
Norway completed both events in an adjusted time of 35 minutes , 31.1 seconds .
Japan hit the finish in 36:30.2 and the United States in 38:14.1 .
Making the biggest move among the 13 teams was Finland , which moved from ninth in the jumps to fourth overall , 44 seconds behind the United States .
The Finns posted the fastest time in the relay .
The Czech Republic , Switzerland , a second Japanese team , Austria , France and Germany rounded out the top 10 .
China for the first time listed its top 300 joint-stock companies on Friday , with Shanghai Petrochemical Co. at the top .
The list is based on a survey of the performance of the nearly 20,000 joint-stock companies across China , the China Daily said .
The newspaper did n't spell out in detail how it made the rankings but said profits and gross assets were the two major gauges of the companies ' performance .
The Fujian Jiuzhou Group Co.
Ltd. was the top joint-stock company in the trade sector , the report said .
Included in the list were 23 companies whose annual sales exceeded 2 billion yuan -LRB- dlrs 235 million -RRB- last year .
Of the 300 top joint stock companies , 107 ranked among the China 's 500 largest enterprises .
The shares of 51 percent of the 300 companies are listed in Shenzhen or Shanghai .
Some of the companies have issued shares only to staff members or business partners .
The report quoted Hong Hu , a State Commission for Economic Restructuring official , as saying the survey showed the vitality of the shareholding system , paving the way for the reform of China 's state-owned enterprises .
Regular monitoring of the share-holding system will help improve companies ' economic performance and will make investors in China 's fledgling stock markets more confident , Fu Fengxiang of the China Securities Regulatory Commission said .
Michael Jackson is trying to end his 6-month-old marriage to Lisa Marie Presley , news reports in New York and London said Thursday .
But the official word from one half of the celebrity couple is that the reports are simply false .
`` Once again , the media is being very irresponsible and spreading false rumors , '' Mrs. Jackson-Presley said in a statement .
`` Michael and I are very happily married .
... These rumors , in spite of their wishful and destructive thinking , are totally unfounded and false . ''
The separation speculation comes just after the couple 's six-month anniversary .
Jackson biographer Christopher Andersen said he first heard rumors of a split on Tuesday .
`` I had heard their lawyers were actually talking annulment , '' said the author of `` Michael Jackson Unauthorized . ''
Lisa Marie and Michael were married in a secret ceremony in the Dominican Republic in May , but rumors about the marriage were n't confirmed until August .
Speculation that the marriage is at best a union of convenience and at worst a publicity ploy started immediately .
Jackson was under investigation for child molestation .
The case was dropped in September .
`` Are Michael and Lisa Marie friends ?
Sure -- they 've been friends for a long time .
But that 's not a marriage , '' Andersen said .
The current rumors come in several versions .
Andersen says the marriage was `` a scam '' from Day 1 , and now Lisa Marie wants out .
Gossip columnist Liz Smith intimates Michael viewed the nuptials as a `` public relations coup , '' but Lisa Marie fell in love and now Michael wants out .
Another Jacksonphile , author J. Randy Taraborrelli , blames the split on Lisa 's refusal to move to the East Coast and live with Michael in his Trump Tower apartment in New York .
Whatever the reason , it seems only a few people expect the Jacksons to be exchanging the traditional silverware on their 25th anniversary .
Or , for that matter , paper on anniversary No. 1 .
`` I did say the marriage would be over by the end of the year , '' Andersen said .
`` Not that I want to say I told you so . ''
The once grand idea of U.N. peacekeeping as a global 911 appears to be fading as the United Nations closes shop in Somalia and faces humiliation in Bosnia .
With the United Nations in apparent retreat , observers are saying that future peacekeeping is likely to shy away from where it is needed most : the front lines .
Bosnia is a `` bucket of cold water on ambitious plans for peacekeeping , '' said Richard Betts , professor of political science at Columbia University .
`` I think there is a great future for peacekeeping that does not matter very much , and a very shaky future for messier operations . ''
That seemed apparent this week .
As Serb militiamen held hundreds of peacekeepers hostage and pounded a U.N.-declared safe haven in Bosnia , the Security Council met in New York , but high on its agenda was the Golan Heights , not Bosnia .
The quick meeting extending the mandate for the Israeli-Syrian border mission highlighted a U.N. success -- a mission where both sides want peace and the border is quiet .
The council talks later dragged on about Bosnia , but without direct action .
`` Peacekeeping is the role of referee , '' said Dan Plesch , director of the British-American Security Information Council in London .
`` You can separate warring parties who want to be separated . ''
But in instances like Bosnia and Somalia , where the sides are n't willing to stop fighting , the United Nations is refusing to order its peacekeepers to separate the sides .
Such a direct role would be war , not peacekeeping , council members say .
Many observers say missions like those in Golan and Cyprus -- with clear and limited objectives such as monitoring borders or delivering aid to war zones -- are likely to expand in the coming years .
`` But we will also see peacekeeping used by the United States and other powers as a way of repackaging war , '' Plesch said .
He cited Haiti and Georgia as examples .
The United States pushed the Council to authorize military intervention in Haiti , offering its own soldiers to lead the mission that will give way to a U.N. peacekeeping force .
Russia would like to do much the same in Georgia .
It has already sent its own troops to the former Soviet republic , but is pressing the United Nations to take over the mission .
While Bosnia -- with 24,000 soldiers or almost a third of all U.N. peacekeepers -- would prove the greatest U.N. peacekeeping failure if it collapses , the United Nations has lost face on other missions .
It was unable to foster peace in Somalia , and decided this fall to wind down its two-year mission .
In Liberia , observers have been abused and humiliated by the warring factions .
U.N. officials bristle at criticisms that peacekeeping has been ineffective and say the problem is that world leaders are not willing to commit the troops or money to ambitious peacekeeping operations .
The world body is being made a scapegoat for the lack of global will to act , said Kofi Annan , the head of U.N. peacekeeping .
`` It is absolutely unfair when member states do not want to take the risks , when they do not want to commit the resources , but blame the U.N. for failure to act , '' Annan said .
U.N. peacekeeping costs have ballooned to $ 3.8 billion for the year ending April 1994 , but by October , members still owed the world body $ 1.6 billion for peacekeeping .
There are some 80,000 U.N. peacekeepers worldwide .
U.N. missions involved only about 10,000 soldiers in 1987 .
With a more isolationist Congress coming into power in Washington , it is unlikely the United States -- which pays about a third of the peacekeeping budget -- would be willing to pay for additional operations that are not directly in the U.S. interest .
`` There may be other Bosnias , but I do n't think there will be another UNPROFOR , '' said William Durch , a senior associate at the Henry L. Stimson Center in Washington .
`` If the West is not willing to act on its own doorstep why would it do it elsewhere ? ''
UNPROFOR is the peacekeeping mission in former Yugoslavia .
Lewis MacKenzie , a veteran of nine peacekeeping operations and the former head of the Sarajevo operation , points out that despite its shortcomings , the U.N. mission in Bosnia still ensures that millions of people receive food every day .
And the retired major-general says that despite the problems , there is still a need for peacekeeping .
`` People who talks about the loss of credibility will be on bended knees before the U.N. at the next crisis , '' MacKenzie said .
A parole board on Thursday rejected Sirhan Sirhan 's ninth attempt to be freed from a life sentence for assassinating presidential candidate Robert F. Kennedy in 1968 .
Sirhan , who attended the hearing under guard but without wearing handcuffs or other restraints , showed no emotion at the denial after two hours of hearing and deliberations .
The panel said he would be reconsidered for parole in two years .
Parole is normally granted to inmates deemed to have been sufficiently rehabilitated .
Sirhan , now 50 , shot Kennedy as the New York senator walked through the pantry of the Ambassador Hotel in Los Angeles on June 5 , 1968 .
Kennedy , whose brother , President John F. Kennedy , was assassinated in 1963 , had just won California 's Democratic presidential primary and finished thanking supporters moments before he was shot .
He died the next day .
Sirhan , a Christian Arab born in Jerusalem , said later that he was mad at Kennedy for supporting a shipment of 50 Phantom jets to Israel .
In 1969 , Sirhan was sentenced to die in California 's gas chamber , but the state Supreme Court declared unconstitutional the death penalty law in effect then .
That left Sirhan with a life sentence and the right to seek parole .
Sirhan is jailed at a special housing unit at California State Prison-Corcoran , 200 miles -LRB- 320 kilometers -RRB- north of Los Angeles .
Cris Carter turned Warren Moon 's short pass into a 65-yard touchdown in overtime Thursday night , giving the Minnesota Vikings a 33-27 victory over the Chicago Bears and a tie for the lead in the NFC Central .
Moon 's second scoring pass to Carter , 5:46 into the extra period , came two plays after Kevin Butler missed a 40-yard field goal that would have given the Bears -LRB- 8-5 -RRB- their second overtime win in two weeks and a two-game lead in the division .
Instead , the Vikings -LRB- 8-5 -RRB- took control of the division , thanks to their season sweep of the Bears .
After the Bears drove to the Minnesota 23 , Butler was wide left on his kick .
Then Moon and Carter went to work .
On second down , Moon threw into the flat to Carter .
He spun away from linebacker Joe Cain , straddled the sideline for a few steps and avoided a desperation tackle attempt by Shaun Gayle at the 10 .
He stumbled into the end zone standing .
`` It was curl pattern trying to set up a field goal , '' Carter said .
`` Warren made a good throw . ''
Said Moon : `` Cris did a great job lulling the linebacker .
I did n't get it out there as far as I would have liked .
It was a great individual effort . ''
Minnesota snapped a three-game losing streak , handing Chicago its first loss in five games and its first defeat in eight games this season with Steve Walsh as the starting quarterback .
Walsh , returning home on his 28th birthday , threw two touchdowns , but his first quarter interception was returned 54 yards by rookie Dewayne Washington to give the Vikings a 7-0 lead .
The Bears led 24-16 on Walsh 's second TD pass , a 15-yarder to Greg McMurtry with 1:30 left in the third quarter .
But the Vikings rallied with Fuad Reveiz 's fourth field goal and Moon 's 1-yard fourth-down TD pass to Carter , the NFL 's leading receiver , and a 2-point conversion pass to Andrew Jordan for a 27-24 lead with 4:12 left in regulation .
Butler tied it with 1:55 left , and had a chance for his second game-winning overtime kick in two weeks .
But his 40-yard kick just sailed wide left .
Minnesota , meanwhile , has thrived in the season 's last month under Dennis Green , who never has lost to the Bears in six games since he became head coach in 1992 .
Green is 6-3 in December , including a 4-1 finish last year after the Vikings entered the final month 5-6 .
There were four lead changes in the second half , the first on Jeff Graham 's 61-yard punt return that gave Chicago a 14-13 lead 2:05 into the third quarter .
Chicago led 17-16 before Qadry Ismail fumbled a kick return to set up Walsh 's 15-yard TD pass to McMurtry .
Walsh finished 24 of 33 for 233 yards -- his highest total of the season -- along with the two TDs and interception .
The Bears ' 27 points were the most they 've scored this season .
A ferry carrying more than 500 people collided with a Singapore-registered freighter and sank before dawn Friday in Manila Bay , killing at least 17 people , the Coast Guard reported .
Coast Guard spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Amado Samante said 449 other passengers had been rescued and the search was continuing for others .
The dead included 11-month-old Jade Gonzales , said his mother Imelda , 26 .
She said another son , aged five , was fine but her 3-year-old son was missing .
Another survivor , Erwin Maravilla , described the terrifying scene after the two ships hit .
`` We were sleeping .
Suddenly we heard a crash .
I grabbed my two children , but when the ferry sank we were sucked under the water with it .
A piece of metal hit my arm , and I lost hold of my two kids , '' he said , adding that his wife was also missing .
`` I was lucky to be able to swim to the surface .
Otherwise I would be dead , '' he said .
He was one of the first group of survivors plucked from the sea by a navy patrol .
The 12,500-ton , Singapore-registered Kota Suria , with a crew of 26 , suffered damage to its port bow but was joining the rescue effort , carrying 230 of those saved .
There was no immediate cause reported for the accident , which occurred in calm seas under clear night skies .
The 2,452-ton ferry , the Cebu City , sank 30 minutes after the collision .
Maximo Calamba , 38 , who survived the accident with wife Veneranda , 30 , and one-year-old son Marcelo , complained that the ferry crew failed to inform them about the approaching freighter and did not help people evacuate the ship after the collision .
`` There was no alarm .
We were thrown off our cots and everybody was on their own , '' Calamba said .
`` When we were rescued by the Suria I could still hear crying out for help . ''
Cargo containers and rubber rafts were floating at the scene , but it was unclear whether there were people aboard , said radio station DZRH , reporting from an airplane overhead .
At least eight patrol boats , a search and rescue ship and several other inter-island ferries were trying to recover survivors , it said .
The Cebu City had a capacity of 800 passengers , said a spokesman for the Williams Lines shipping company .
In December of 1987 the Philippines suffered the worst-ever peacetime ferry disaster , when 3,537 people died in the collision of the ferry Dona Paz with the oil tanker Vector off Mindoro Island , about 130 kilometers -LRB- 80 miles -RRB- south of Manila .
The Cebu City sank near the mouth of Manila Bay near the town of Maragondon , about 50 kilometers -LRB- 35 miles -RRB- southwest of Manila in Cavite province .
It had left the port of Manila bound for Tagbilaran , capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- southeast of Manila .
If fighting intensfies in Bosnia , the Swedish government is prepared to withdraw its U.N. peacekeepers at short notice , news reports said Friday .
`` If the fighting increases , we could end up in a situation where there is no alternative but to withdraw the U.N.-peacekeepers , '' Swedish Foreign Minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen told the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet .
`` As every responsible government we have drawn up plans for this , '' Hjelm-Wallen added .
Peacekeepers from several countries are virtually hostage in several parts of Bosnia and there are reports that their food and fuel supplies are running low .
`` This shows how serious the situation is , '' Hjelm-Wallen said .
Sweden has 1,256 peacekeepers in Bosnia , most are based near Tuzla and form part of the joint Nordic batallion NORDBAT .
Hjelm-Wallen will participate at a meeting in Brussels later Friday , where members of the North Atlantic Cooperation Council will discuss the Bosnian situation .
NACC is a body that groups NATO members and countries that have joined NATO 's Partnership for Peace .
Sweden is part of the PFP-initiative .
Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson has refused to comment how fast a Swedish withdrawal could take place , but said that there are contingency plans for a rapid withdrawl .
These include flying out the peacekeepers from Tuzla airport .
The issue is closely monitored with neighboring Norway and Denmark , Carlsson said .
Lucien Bouchard , a central and charismatic leader of Quebec 's separatist movement , had his left leg amputated two days after being hospitalized for a blood clot that became infected .
Bouchard 's emergency hospitalization throws into doubt the role the Bloc Quebecois leader will play in next year 's critical referendum on separation .
French-speaking Quebec has long sought some form of sovereignty or separation from the rest of Canada , which is largely English-speaking .
Bouchard , 55 , was in serious but stable condition Thursday after two operations at Montreal 's Saint-Luc Hospital .
Radio-Canada reported late Thursday that doctors first amputated Bouchard 's foot and then his leg .
Bouchard 's doctor , Patrick D'Amico , said in a statement that the separatist leader developed an infection on his leg after being hospitalized on Tuesday .
`` This situation necessitated two operations to drain and amputate the leg and control the infection , '' said D'Amico .
Radio-Canada and CTV , a Canadian television network , reported that Bouchard has a rare flesh-eating disease which has been linked to about a dozen deaths in Britain , one in Canada and few in other countries .
His doctors were reportedly conferring with specialists in Britain .
The rapidly-spreading disease is caused by a virulent form of streptococcus bacteria that enters the body through a cut or a wound and produces an infection .
Widely considered the most compelling Quebec separatist leader , the charismatic Bouchard 's absence from the upcoming referendum battle would be a blow to forces seeking Quebec 's secession .
Quebec Premier Jacques Parizeau prevailed on Bouchard to show the same courage he has regularly displayed in the political arena .
`` Our prayers are with you , '' said a shaken Parizeau .
`` I hope this will soon be just a bad dream .
Hold on old friend . ''
A Bloc Quebecois spokesman refused to provide more details on Bouchard 's condition .
Bouchard is with him now , '' Marthe Lawrence , Bouchard 's spokesperson , said from the hospital .
`` The family wishes no further statement for the moment . ''
Bouchard became leader of the opposition after his fledgling party swept Quebec in the 1993 federal election , winning 54 out of 75 seats in the province .
At Milwaukee , the Cleveland Cavaliers overcame a career-high 34 points by Todd Day to beat the Milwaukee Bucks 93-87 Thursday night .
Mark Price scored 17 points and Chris Mills added 15 as the Cavaliers held Milwaukee to just 30 second-half points in winning their fourth straight game .
Day had 23 points in the first quarter for the Bucks , who lost their fifth in a row .
The Cavaliers took advantage of Milwaukee 's poor shooting for a 25-5 run that gave Cleveland an 84-73 lead with 7:26 left .
Milwaukee rallied to cut the lead to 91-87 with 37 seconds left .
At Dallas , Rodney Rogers scored 20 points and Brian Williams had 15 points and 13 rebounds as the Denver Nuggets beat the Dallas Mavericks .
The Nuggets , who snapped a three-game losing streak , led by 22 points in the third quarter .
Dallas pulled to within 86-80 with 1:22 to play on Jim Jackson 's basket , but that was as close as the Mavericks would come .
The Nuggets , who were without injured starters Reggie Williams and Bryant Stith , halted the Mavericks ' three-game winning streak .
Denver 's Dikembe Mutombo had 13 points , 14 rebounds and four blocked shots .
Jim Jackson paced the Mavericks with 26 points and Popeye Jones added 11 points and a career-high 22 rebounds .
At Salt Lake City , Doug West hit two free throws with 47 seconds left Thursday night to give the Minnesota Timberwolves their second win of the season .
Minnesota , which broke a seven-game losing streak , outscored Utah 8-3 over the final two minutes .
West , who finished with 18 points , also scored on a slam dunk with 1:23 left .
J.R. Rider led Minnesota with 19 points .
Karl Malone paced the Jazz with 24 points , but had four turnovers and just five rebounds .
A lawyer is suing a restaurant that he claims served him a double espresso instead of decaffeinated coffee .
Donald Horowitz said Thursday that the mix-up last December at the Teggiano Restaurant put him in the hospital with a rapid heart beat .
After a few sips , `` I developed chest pains and my heart started racing , '' he said .
Horowitz , 58 , who had a heart attack in 1991 , claims he still has heart trouble because of the espresso .
He said he wants to serve notice on restaurants that such mix-ups will not be tolerated .
His lawsuit , filed Tuesday in Superior Court in Bergen County , names the South Hackensack restaurant and its insurance company .
It seeks unspecified damages .
Restaurant owner Luigi Bruno denied the claims .
He said his decaffeinated and regular coffees are kept apart to prevent mix-ups .
Horowitz said he was offered a `` trifling sum of money '' to settle the dispute but decided to file his lawsuit instead .
Japan 's lower house of parliament passed the GATT world trade accord Friday , virtually assuring the world 's second-largest economy would adopt the landmark deal .
It also passed a six-year , 7.2 trillion yen -LRB- dlrs 74 billion -RRB- package of subsidies and aid to rural areas to quell farmers ' opposition to the accord , which opens Japan 's rice market for the first time .
After heavy U.S. pressure during GATT negotiations , four percent of the staple is to come from overseas starting in 1995 .
The vote , which was not formally counted , came after the U.S. Senate , Congress ' upper house , approved the deal Thursday night by an overwhelming 76-24 vote .
President Clinton hailed the Senate vote as a `` victory for America '' which would create millions of new jobs .
The accord , passed Tuesday by the House of Representatives , now needs his signature .
Japanese trade minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said with U.S. approval of the deal , which slashes tariffs by 38 percent worldwide , other nations are much more likely vote in favor .
He predicted Japan 's upper house would follow the more powerful lower chamber 's lead and approve the accord in time for it to take effect as planned Jan. 1 .
Approval was expected next week .
In Canberra , Australian trade minister Bob McMullan called the U.S. Senate passage `` great news for Australia and the world economy generally . ''
The parliament there was conducting debate Friday in moving closer to approving the deal .
Under the plan , the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade will be superseded Jan. 1 by the stronger World Trade Organization as the world 's main arbiter of trade disputes .
Vietnam 's inflation rate rose to 13.2 percent during the first 11 months of the year , a report said Friday .
Retail prices increased by 1.7 percent for the period ending Nov. 30 due in part to heavy floods in the Mekong River region , Vietnam 's biggest rice-growing area , the Saigon Newsreader reported .
The floods caused temporary shortages and speculation that led to higher rice prices .
Vietnam had hoped to keep inflation at less than 10 percent this year , but prices exceeded the target in October .
Government officials have set a new goal of keeping inflation below 14 percent in 1994 , the paper reported .
Official newspapers have tried to justify the higher than expected price increases .
They report , for example , that higher prices for rice mean better incomes for the four-fifths of the nation 's people who live by farming .
International lenders such as the World Bank have praised Vietnam 's success in reigning in inflation , which reached 775 percent in 1986 .
Free market reforms since then have encouraged farmers and businessmen to produce more food and consumer goods to meet domestic demand .
Inflation stood at 5.2 percent in 1993 .
Vietnam 's National Assembly has targeted a maximum inflation rate of 10 percent next year .
Australia will pay Aborigines dlrs 13.5 million -LRB- U.S. dlrs 10 million -RRB- for damage British nuclear testing did to their land , the government said Friday after a decade of negotiations .
Above-ground atomic test blasts were detonated on the vast Maralinga lands under British scientists ' direction in the 1950s and 1960s .
Aborigines were evicted from the land and have since fought to have the area cleaned up so they could return .
Under the settlement , however , Australian primary industries minister Bob Collins said some of the 30,890-square-mile -LRB- 80,000 square kilometer -RRB- area in northern South Australia would remain closed indefinitely due to dangerous levels of plutonium .
The settlement will fund new outstations in Maralinga as well as health services , roads , water supplies and employment programs , Collins said .
An outstation is a cabin or settlement in the outback with a water pump as the main amenity .
Collins said `` it 's been a very sad chapter in our history and I 'm pleased to say that in human terms , at least one important bit of it has been brought to a close . ''
The compensation is separate from the massive five-year task of cleaning up the land , expected to start early next year .
Its cost is estimated at dlrs 104 million -LRB- U.S. dlrs 79 million -RRB- .
Archie Barton , administrator of the Maralinga Tjarutja lands , said Friday 's announcement ended `` 10 years of frustration , mental and physical strain on our older people . ''
The bomb tests were kept secret until the early 1980s .
Negotiations began after they became public .
An earlier British government settlement of 20 million pounds -LRB- U.S. dlrs 12.7 million -RRB- for the rehabilitation of the Maralinga lands signaled the end of its involvement in the compensation battle .
Floris Jan Bovelander scored twice from first-half penalty corners to guide defending champion the Netherlands to a 3-1 victory over Australia on Friday and a place in the final of the World Cup field hockey tournament .
Bovelander fired the ball home in the fifth and 20th minutes and Jacques Brinkman added a stylish third goal with 3:50 remaining .
Top seed Australia got its only goal from Paul Gaudoin following a penalty corner 12 minutes into the second half .
Bovelander took his tally for the tournament to five goals and also had a third penalty corner strike controversially disallowed in the second half after it was ruled the ball had not struck the backboard .
The Dutch , who advanced through the preliminary round unbeaten , dominated the semifinal for long periods and did not allow the Australian forwards room in which to be creative .
Erik Jazet was outstanding in defense , while captain Marc Delissen was a dynamo in midfield .
The Netherlands now will play either Germany or Pakistan in Sunday 's final , while top seeded Australia failed to emulate its 1986 World Cup triumph .
The Dutch now are unbeaten in their last 27 internationals .
They sealed their victory with a brilliant flowing attack .
Teun de Nooijer and Taco van den Honert set up Brinkman with some slick stickwork and the inside-forward finished the move with an emphatic shot .
`` We have a young team and a lot of people in Holland might be surprised we have made the final , '' said Delissen .
`` We 've proved we are a good side . ''
Australian coach Frank Murray said his squad was `` very disappointed '' .
`` They took their first two opportunities , but I thought we fought very well to get back at them , '' Murray said .
`` We came here to win the tournament and we did n't do that , so we have a lot of soul searching to do . ''
England and India won consolation play-off games earlier Friday that assured them of top six finishes and places in the 1988 World Cup in the Netherlands and next year 's Champions Trophy tournament in Berlin .
India squandered a 2-0 first-half lead and was held to a 2-2 draw by Argentina before winning 4-1 on penalty strokes .
Goalkeeper Anjaparavanda Subbiah was the hero for India , making reflex saves to stop shots from Fernando Falchetti and Fernando Moresi .
He was chaired from the field by his delighted teammates .
`` It is immaterial to us who finishes fifth or sixth , '' said Indian coach Cedric D'Souza .
`` What was important was that we finished in the top six .
This was the most important match for us . ''
Dhanraj Pillay and captain Jude Felix scored the goals for India , while Ferrara and Carlos Retegui replied for Argentina from penalty corners .
Penalty corner conversions by Rob Crutchley in the 13th and 20th minutes gave England a 2-0 halftime lead against South Korea .
Jeon Jong-ha replied with a neat penalty corner variation six minutes after the break , but Russell Garcia converted a penalty stroke eight minutes from fulltime to seal the issue .
The second semifinal between Olympic champion Germany and three-time World Cup winner Pakistan will be played later Friday .
Consolation play-offs are scheduled Saturday with the final and third-place play-off to be played Sunday afternoon .
The 1995 Champions Trophy field hockey tournament will be staged in Berlin in September , the sport 's governing body the Federation Internationale de Hockey -LRB- FIH -RRB- announced Friday .
The tournament will be held from Sept. 23 through Oct. 1 , the FIH said in a statement .
The organization also announced that the 1996 Champions Trophy in Madras , India , would be switched from March to December to prevent a congestion of fixtures .
Berlin replaces Milton Keynes , England , as the 1995 venue .
Delays in the construction of the proposed hockey stadium at Milton Keynes forced England to forfeit the annual event .
Olympic champion Germany , trophy holder Pakistan , the Netherlands and Australia were assured of places in the Champions Trophy , along with England and India , who sealed places with top six finishes at the World Cup in Sydney .
Chinese swimmers who tested positive for performance-enhancing drugs may have been forced to take steroids or not even told what they were taking , U.S. swim officials say .
`` They may -LRB- know -RRB- , but I 'm not sure they have a choice , '' Richard Quick , who will coach the U.S. women at the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta , said Thursday .
`` It was said in East Germany that if you did n't follow the program , using the drugs as part of the program , that you were thrown out .
So you may not have a choice .
And I think the young ones may not even know . ''
Eleven Chinese athletes , seven of them swimmers , tested positive for drugs at the Asian Games at Hiroshima , Japan , in October .
Chinese officials denied their swimming federation encouraged or knew about drug use .
`` This is an act by individuals , '' a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman said Thursday from Beijing , adding his country 's sports authorities practice `` strict prohibition , strict testing and strict punishment '' of drug use .
But Quick does n't believe it .
`` I think the coaches know , '' he said .
`` I think the administrators know .
I think it would be impossible not to know that . ''
The Chinese swimming program has improved rapidly in the 1990s -- a little too rapidly , some say , as coaches from other countries began to suspect that steroids were part of the reason .
Allegations of drug use escalated in September when the Chinese women won 12 of 16 gold medals at the world championships in Rome .
`` It seemed like too much , too fast , '' said Greg Eggert , a board member of the U.S. Swimming organization .
Eggert said 17 countries , including the United States , signed a petition at the world championships asking the International Swimming Federation to develop a more rigorous drug-testing program .
In October , the Chinese women won all 15 of their races at the Asian Games .
Then , seven of them tested positive .
`` I 'm just glad to know that the testing system is working , '' said Skip Kenney , who will coach the U.S. men in Atlanta .
`` I just think that when it 's fair , it just makes it that much more exciting . ''
But John Collins , coach of the Badger Swim Club in Larchmont , N.Y. , said he 's waiting to see if the Chinese change their ways .
`` Everybody knew that they 've been doing it , but we could n't catch them .
So the fact that they 're catching them is great , '' he said .
`` But I do n't know how it 's going to be resolved .
`` Considering the numbers of people caught , it 's obviously the -LRB- Chinese -RRB- federation .
