The U.S. dollar closed at 99.58 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market Friday , up 0.57 yen from Thursday 's close .
Bosnian Serb leaders agreed to meet a top U.N. envoy today even as they ignored demands to free captive U.N. peacekeepers and allow humanitarian aid to be delivered to trapped civilians in northwest Bosnia .
The United Nations has pressing issues to discuss : Attempts to calm fighting in the Bihac region in northwest Bosnia , where Serbs forces have overrun Muslim villages in a U.N.-desigated `` safe area '' ; and the fate of more than 400 of its soldiers being held by the Serbs as insurance against NATO air strikes .
Seven more peacekeepers were seized Tuesday from an observation post in Croatia , across the border from Bihac , said Alexander Ivanko , a U.N. spokesman .
Bosnian Serb units entered Croatia and took the Ukrainian soldiers and a U.N. armored carrier back into Bosnia .
The United Nations has n't heard from the peacekeepers since , Ivanko said .
The observation post is now occupied by the Serbs , which allows them unimpeded movement of equipment and personnel from Serb-held parts of Croatia into Bosnia .
Serb rebels from the two countries have joined in an offensive to drive Muslim-led Bosnian government forces out of the Bihac region .
The fall of Bihac would allow rebel Serbs in Bosnia and Croatia to join their territories .
Croatian Defense Minister Gojko Susak warned Thursday that his country would not let that happen .
`` We are monitoring the situation , and if Croatia 's judgment is that Bihac is about to fall , Croatia will intervene , '' Susak said in Zagreb .
Bosnian Serbs agreed to meet today with top U.N. envoy Yasushi Akashi in Pale , their stronghold east of Sarajevo .
On Wednesday , they refused to meet U.N. chief Boutros Boutros-Ghali because he insisted talks be held in Sarajevo , capital of Bosnia 's internationally recognized government .
The Serbs agreed to today 's meeting after Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose , the U.N. commander in Bosnia , traveled to Pale for talks with Radovan Karadzic and other Bosnian Serb leaders .
But that session produced no apparent narrowing of differences to raise hopes of an end to the 2 -LCB- - year-long war , which has left 200,000 people dead or missing .
Serbs again denied U.N. requests to supply the 70,000 civilians trapped in the Bihac enclave with food and other necessities .
Monique Tuffelli , the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees staffer in Bihac , said food stocks would last only another week .
The last U.N. food convoy reached Bihac on Oct. 1 .
Hamdija Kabiljagic , the regional mayor , reported increased fighting along the perimeters of Bihac and shelling of the town itself Thursday .
Momcilo Krajisnik , leader of the Bosnian Serbs ' self-proclaimed legislature , again rejected a three-month cease-fire , which the Bosnian government wants .
He said Serbs would only accept a permanent cease-fire .
But the Sarajevo government fears a permanent cease-fire would cement Serb dominion over the 70 percent of Bosnia they now control .
An international peace plan the Serbs have rejected would give Serbs 49 percent of the country .
Now that plan seems up for revision , as senior Western officials talk of allowing the Bosnian Serbs links with Serb-dominated Yugoslavia .
In Belgium , Secretary of State Warren Christopher hoped to get formal approval today from France , Britain , Germany and Russia for a new diplomatic initiative to achieve a cease-fire around Bihac , a pledge to stop fighting nationwide for three to six months , and an international peace conference .
The Bosnian civil war began in April 1992 , when Bosnian Serbs rebelled against a vote by Bosnian Croats and Muslims to secede from Serb-dominated Yugoslavia .
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri has tendered his resignation following a stormy Cabinet meeting in which he accused his opponents of trying to paralyze the government , aides said early Friday .
Speaking on condition of anonymity , the aides said the 51-year-old self-made Sunni Muslim billionaire , whose premiership was backed by Syria and Saudi Arabia , offered his resignation in a telephone call late Thursday night to President Elias Hrawi .
Hrawi , a Maronoite Catholic , had not yet accepted or rejected the resignation because it must first be made in writing , presumably later Friday , the aides said .
The resignation was triggered by a heated exchange between Hariri and Housing Minister Mahmoud Abu Hamdan , a SHiite Muslim , the aides said .
They reported that Hariri accused Hamdan and other opponents of seeking to sabotage all government-proposed legislation .
At one point , Hariri fumed that `` the country can not be ruled through militias , '' the aides quoted him as saying .
Hamdan is one of a group of ministers in the 30-member Cabinet who are aligned with Nabih Berri , the Shiite speaker of Parliament and head of the Amal movement , once a powerful militia in Lebanon 's 1975-1990 civil war .
Hariri 's critics accuse him of trying to enrich himself further by grabbing a large share of the multibillion-dollar postwar reconstruction projects for his own companies .
They also claim the tycoon , who has substantial real estate and engineering holdings , is trying to monopolize decision-making by ramming his decisions through the Cabinet , disregarding substantial internal opposition .
Earlier this year , Hariri staged a protest lasting several days during which he refused to attend government meetings as a way of demonstrating his frustration at the slowness of government action on reconstruction .
Hariri was appointed prime minister Oct. 22 , 1992 .
At the time , he was hailed as Lebanon 's savior who would rescue the onetime `` Switzerland of the Middle East '' from economic oblivion .
The Lebanese hoped his image , untarnished by scandal as many of the country 's politicians were , as well as his wealth and his powerful Syrian and Saudi connections would help him achieve what previous governments had not : an economic turnaround to erase the war 's devastation .
His record has been mixed .
Much of war-ravaged central Beirut is being bulldozed as part of a massive reconstruction of the downtown area , designed to make the Lebanese capital once more a financial and trading hub for the region .
But the reconstruction has been slower than expected and Hariri 's critics have constantly accused him of seeking to use his position to line his own pockets .
Hariri built much of his dlrs 3 billion fortune in Saudi Arabia and enjoys a close friendship with the Saudi royal family .
According to a national covenant dating to independence from France in 1943 , Lebanon 's president is traditionally a Maronite Catholic , the Parliament speaker a Shiite and the prime minister a Sunni .
Great Britain fullback Jonathan Davies has signed to play for Australian rugby league team the North Queensland Cowboys next year , the Winfield Cup expansion team announced Friday .
Cowboys chief executive Kerry Boustead said former Welsh rugby union star Davies would join the club from English club Warrington .
Davies last played in Australia in 1991 , when he scored 100 points in 14 appearances for the Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs .
`` We are delighted to have signed him , he 's one of the finest players in the world , '' said Boustead .
The North American Free Trade Agreement has failed so far to deliver on its promise of more U.S. jobs and instead has resulted in a net loss of 10,000 jobs , according to a congressional analysis .
A Joint Economic Committee study requested by Democratic Sen. Byron Dorgan of North Dakota estimates that while NAFTA created roughly 127,000 jobs in its first nine months , increased imports from Mexico have cost 137,000 U.S. jobs .
NAFTA , which went into effect this year , brought the United States , Mexico and Canada into a single trading bloc .
Dorgan issued the study as the Senate ratified the 124-nation accord negotiated under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade .
President Clinton , meanwhile , is expected to announce his intention next week to broaden NAFTA to include Chile and call for a hemispheric trade agreement .
`` NAFTA and GATT are trade agreements that make it easier for American jobs to go where labor is cheap , '' Dorgan said .
`` It 's a bankrupt trade strategy that weakens our country but strengthens corporations who want to employ cheap labor elsewhere and ship their goods here . ''
Commerce Department officials questioned the findings , saying their own analyses show job gains as a result of increased trade with Mexico .
`` We are quite confident that NAFTA has been a net plus for jobs in 1994 , '' said Commerce 's chief economist , Lewis Alexander .
Commerce officials questioned the study 's premise and the assumption that increased imports necessarily translate into job loss .
The officials were reluctant to assign specific job gain numbers from NAFTA , saying it 's very difficult to separate the trade agreement 's effect on jobs from overall trade patterns with Mexico .
Nine-month NAFTA figures released by Commerce last month showed U.S. exports to Mexico hit record levels , rising almost 22 percent over a year earlier .
Imports from Mexico were up almost 23 percent .
But opponents contend that NAFTA backers are ignoring the fact that the United States ' trade surplus with Mexico is shrinking .
After hitting a high of dlrs 5.3 billion in 1992 , the trade surplus is expected to reach dlrs 2.8 billion this year if current trends hold .
The congressional study 's authors themselves expressed some discomfort with pinning job loss numbers at this early stage .
`` It will take at least five to 10 years for the full effects of the agreement to manifest themselves , '' they wrote .
Expectations of another possible increase in U.S. interest rates boosted the U.S. dollar in Tokyo but pulled stock prices slightly lower Friday .
The dollar closed at 99.58 yen , up 0.57 yen from its Thursday close in Tokyo and also above its overnight close in New York at 99.34 yen .
