NATO is ready to start building its program to admit former Cold War foes into the alliance , but the foundation received a strong new jolt from Russia .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev stunned the North Atlantic Treaty Organization foreign ministers on Thursday by backing out of a program tailored to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
Instead of endorsing a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts between NATO and Moscow , as he had been invited to Brussels to do , Kozyrev recited Russia 's worries about the Partnership for Peace program , a U.S. initiative proudly unveiled at a NATO summit last January .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told his dumbfounded audience , which had just agreed to a cautious , year-long project to draw up conditions for new members from the former Soviet bloc .
The foreign ministers were to meet today with their counterparts from Eastern Europe and former Soviet republics to discuss the plan -- and Russia 's opposition .
Some diplomats thought Kozyrev 's message was really intended for the strong nationalist opposition back home in Russia , which fears the West is encroaching on Russia 's sphere of influence .
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jose Manuel Durao Barroso said Kozyrev `` threw a bucket of cold water on the meeting . ''
Since the collapse of the Soviet Bloc , NATO has anguished over whether -- and when -- to open its doors to its former foes in central and eastern Europe .
Poland , Hungary and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
The allies thought in the Partnership for Peace , they had found a formula pleasing both to East European supplicants and the wary Russians -- a sort of halfway house where former Soviet Bloc nations can take part in NATO military exercises and other alliance activities .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project .
But Kozyrev warned that the Partnership threatened to create new divisions in Europe , with some participants destined to become NATO members , while others would remain on the outs .
`` Not all countries will be able to obtain membership at the same time , '' he protested .
Willy Claes , the alliance 's new secretary-general , tried to respond to Kozyrev 's remarks .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO , '' he told the Russian minister just before he left NATO headquarters .
`` There is nothing new .
We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst was only the latest blow to the alliance , which has suffered unprecedented strains in recent weeks over a split between the United States and Europe over how NATO should deal with the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina .
Attempting to heal the rift , Secretary of State Warren Christopher this week made a major policy switch , adopting the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
Test reject John Crawley scored a fiery unbeaten 91 Friday to spearhead England to a four-wicket win over a Sir Donald Bradman XI in a limited-overs cricket match at Bowral , southwest of Sydney .
Crawley , who was left out of the team for the first Test against Australia , clubbed eight fours and a six as England scored a morale-boosting win against the team of young Australians led by former Test captain Allan Border .
The Bradman XI scored 205 for four in its allocated 50 overs and England reached the required total with just seven balls to spare .
Crawley revived England 's hopes after tourists had slumped to 136 for six .
He and Darren Gough added 72 runs off just 57 balls in an unbeaten seventh wicket stand .
Gough finished not out 24 , with one six and two fours .
Earlier , Mike Atherton , Alec Stewart and Mike Gatting all made starts before throwing their wickets away .
For the Bradman XI , Neil Maxwell had the best bowling figures of two for 2-26 from 9.5 overs .
Opener Jason Arnberger had ensured England would face a difficult chase when he top-scored for the home side with 79 against an ineffective attack .
All the batsmen got starts , with Arnberger 's opening partner Jamie Cox scoring 42 , Jimmy Maher 26 and Shane Lee 27 .
Arnberger and Cox shared a century opening stand , the highlight of which was a big six from Cox off the bowling of spinner Shaun Udal .
England next faces the Australian Capital Territory in Canberra on Sunday .
