Japan has agreed with Russia to postpone payments of 100 million dollars , a part of the debts owed by the former Soviet Union to the Export-Import Bank of Japan that falls due on Dec. 31 , the government said Friday .
A new deadline for repayment has been set for Sept. 30 , 1997 .
Japan has signed another deferment agreement for 180 million dollars worth of debts with trade insurance , officials said .
With this agreement , the total debts that Japan has postponed for Russia in 1994 comes to about 280 million dollars .
Vietnamese retail prices rose 13.2 percent during the first 11 months of the year , a report said Friday .
Prices increased by 1.7 percent in November due partly to heavy floods in the Mekong River region , Vietnam 's biggest rice-growing area , the Saigon Newsreader reported .
The floods caused temporary shortages and speculation that led to higher rice prices .
Vietnam had hoped to keep inflation at less than 10 percent this year , but prices exceeded the target in October .
Government officials have set a new goal of keeping inflation below 14 percent in 1994 , the newspaper reported .
Official newspapers have tried to justify the higher-than-expected price increases .
They report , for example , that higher prices for rice mean better incomes for the four-fifths of the nation 's people who live by farming .
International lenders such as the World Bank have praised Vietnam 's success in reigning in inflation , which reached 775 percent in 1986 .
Free-market reforms since then have encouraged farmers and businessmen to produce more food and consumer goods to meet domestic demand .
Inflation stood at 5.2 percent in 1993 .
Vietnam 's National Assembly has targeted a maximum inflation rate of 10 percent next year .
The Asian Development Bank announced Friday it has begun offering a new category of loans at prevailing market rates .
The Manila-based bank said the new fund source , its third lending `` window , '' was opened in response to growing demand for market-based loans .
The bank 's two other loan categories are a pool-based , multi-currency loan window which is predominantly in Japanese yen and a pool-based single-currency window in U.S. dollars .
Lending rates of the windows are based on the cost of pools of borrowing undertaken separately for each window plus a variable lending spread .
The new loan window is linked to the London Inter-Bank Offered Rate .
Borrowers from this window will have the option of having their loans priced at either fixed or floating rates .
The floating rate will be linked to the six-month LIBOR in each loan currency while the fixed lending rate will be set at the time of disbursement .
Loan maturities will range from eight to 15 years , the bank added .
The United States is about to resume an anti-drug intelligence operation with Colombia that the administration suspended seven months ago because of questions about its legality .
An administration official said resumption of the program is imminent , adding that agreement with Peru is close as well .
A congressional study carried out during the summer said that suspension of the program had benefited drug traffickers .
Until last May , ground-based U.S. radar was able to keep tabs on drug flights out of the two Andean countries .
Very few flights were intercepted but authorities in Bogota and Lima were able to use the data to stage raids on cocaine laboratories and storage facilities , officials said .
The United States discontinued the program in May on grounds that U.S. officials could be held liable under international law if Colombia or Peru used the U.S.-supplied data to shoot down civilian aircraft suspected of being used in drug trafficking .
American sensitivities about the downing of innocent aircraft were heightened in April when U.S. F-15 fighters , in a case of mistaken identity , shot down two American helicopters in northern Iraq .
Twenty-six people were killed : 15 Americans , five Kurds , three Turks , two Britons and a Frenchman .
Just two weeks later , nervous administration officials called a halt to the radar operations in Peru and Colombia .
Civilian aircraft is the most common means to send cocaine base from Peru to Colombia for final processing and for ultimate distribution in the United States .
The May decision prompted expressions of outrage from officials in Colombia and Peru , who felt it demonstrated a lack of U.S. resolve .
It also produced a deep rift between the counter-narcotics offices in the Pentagon and the State Department , which vigorously opposed the suspension .
Legislation approved by Congress at the administration 's request this past summer requires the administration to certify that the country receiving the intelligence data has taken measures to protect against innocent loss of life .
An administration official , asking not to be identified , said details of the new arrangement have been completed with Colombia and `` we 're almost there with Peru . ''
The study carried out during the summer by the General Accounting Office , a congressional agency , said the May decision made life easier for the drug traffickers in several ways .
It said they were able to use multiple flights with smaller drug loads than before .
They also began flying during daylight hours instead of the early evening .
In addition , they were able to spend more time on the ground and used more direct air routes instead of the more circuitous ones used previously .
A regional pro-democracy forum adopted a resolution Friday demanding the release of Aung San Suu Kyi and other political prisoners held by Burma 's military junta .
Mrs. Suu Kyi , leader of the pro-democracy opposition to Burma 's military government , has been under house arrest since July 1989 .
She won the 1991 Nobel Peace Prise for her struggle .
The resolution -- adopted by about 200 former heads of state , politicians and scholars from around the world -- called on the Burmese ruling council to unconditionally release Mrs. Suu Kyi and other political prisoners .
The participants in the Forum of Democratic Leaders in the Asia Pacific also pledged to join international efforts to implement United Nations resolutions aimed at restoring democracy in Burma .
The forum says one of its main goals is to fight authoritarian rulers in the Asia-Pacific region who say democracy is a luxury with less priority than economic development .
`` The true development of human beings involves much more than mere economic growth , '' Mrs. Suu Kyi said in a message read by former Philippine President Corazon Aquino to the forum .
`` Mere material assistance is not enough ; the poor must have the sense that they themselves can shape their own future ... in a world where political leadership is often synonymous with tyranny and the rule of a narrow elite . ''
Although the National League for Democracy , led by Mrs. Suu Kyi , won a landslide victory in 1990 elections , the military junta has so far refused to yield power .
In March , the U.N. Human Rights Commission adopted a resolution urging the government in Rangoon to improve human rights conditions and immediately release Mrs. Suu Kyi , who is in her sixth year under house arrest without trial .
`` She is healthy , high-spirited and well-informed , '' said Sein Win , prime minister of Burma 's exile government , the National Coalition Government of the Union of Burma .
He was attending the forum .
`` On the whole , there has been no real change in Burma .
The human rights situation remains the same , '' he said .
The forum drew many human rights advocates , such as former President Oscar Sanchez Arias of Costa Rica and Ed Broadbent , head of the Montreal-based International Center for Human Rights and Democratic Development .
The forum -- co-hosted by Mrs. Aquino and Kim Dae-jung , an eight-time Nobel Peace Prize nominee for his struggle against South Korea 's past authoritarian governments -- ends Saturday after a three-day inaugural conference in Seoul .
A rocket scientist in India 's space program has been arrested on suspicion of passing on secrets , newspapers reported Friday .
Nambi Narayanan was the second space expert to be accused in a spy ring case after the Oct. 20 arrest of a woman who allegedly seduced scientists and blackmailed them to give her designs of rocket engines .
Indian newspapers quoted unidentifed police sources as saying the ring was working for Pakistan , India 's neighbor and arch-enemy .
Narayanan , who helped develop engines for India 's satellite launch vehicles and defense missiles , was arrested Wednesday in Trivandrum on India 's southern coast , reports said .
He was the head of the liquid propulsion laboratory of the Indian Space Research Organization .
Reports said Indian police began an espionage probe after arresting Mariam Rasheda , a citizen of an Indian Ocean archipelago , the Maldives .
Rasehda 's interrogation led to the arrests of a rocket expert and K. Chandrashekaran , a businessman who claimed to represent the Russian space company Glavkosmos , the Indian Express newspaper said .
At least 30 other scientists , businessmen and a top police officer are involved in the affair , reports said .
India and Pakistan have fought three wars since 1947 .
Both are believed capable of producing nuclear weapons .
India is developing its own weapons delivery system , while Pakistan buys M-11 missiles from China .
Indian scientists have worked on rockets to launch communications satellites since 1979 .
But the space laboratories also are involved in developing missile technology .
Under U.S. pressure , Glavkosmos was forced to cancel a deal to supply rocket engines to India in 1992 .
An unbeaten century by Sachin Tendulkar helped India pile up 365 for four at lunch on the second day of the second cricket test against West India in Nagpur .
With Tendulkar not out on 148 , his eighth test century , India consolidated their grip on the match after resuming at an overnight score of 230 for four without losing any wicket .
Skipper Mohammed Azharuddin was batting on 58 , scored off 71 balls and including seven boundaries .
India is 1-0 up in the three test series .
Now that Japan has issued an apology , of sorts , about its attack on Pearl Harbor , some historians say the United States should be declaring its own regrets about its conduct after that fateful day .
They say the two U.S. military leaders blamed for having their guard down when Japanese planes destroyed much of the Pacific Fleet were scapegoats whose names should be cleared .
Rear Adm. Husband E. Kimmel and Lt. Gen. Walter C. Short have been regarded for more than 50 years as sleeping sentries , said British author John Costello .
`` But the record shows that they were really more like two guards who have been blindfolded by the lack of intelligence , told to face the wrong direction , and inadequately armed to fend off an enemy air attack . ''
Costello and two other like-minded historians spoke at the National Archives on Thursday , trying to attract a measure of the public interest aroused by Japan 's debates over its wartime behavior .
Japan apologized Nov. 21 , not for attacking Pearl Harbor , but for failing to warn that it was at war with the United States before attacking .
The surprise attack on Dec. 7 , 1941 , killed 2,403 people , sank or damaged 18 warships , destroyed 188 planes and drew the United States into World War II .
U.S. officials refused as recently as last year to reopen the case of Kimmel and Short , both cited during the war for dereliction of duty and both now dead .
The Kimmel family , 32 retired admirals and two former chairmen of the Joint Chiefs of Staff are among those who have pressed for the commanders ' vindication .
Kimmel , who was commander of the Pacific Fleet , and Short , commander of the Army 's Hawaii department , were blamed in official inquiries for playing down intelligence reports warning of Japan 's intentions and for mounting inadequate reconnaissance .
Costello said his new book , `` Days of Infamy , '' builds on previously reported evidence that the Hawaiian commanders were not given the full benefit of American intelligence .
The commanders indeed shrugged off some 11th-hour signals of trouble , he said .
But they did so because a steady drumbeat of intelligence from Washington had pointed to the Philippines as the likely target for Japan 's move against U.S. forces .
Nine hours after Pearl Harbor , Japan bombed Clark Field in the Philippines , destroying 18 bombers , 55 fighters and 33 other planes .
In the Philippines , Costello said , Gen. Douglas MacArthur had received `` the full diplomatic picture of Japan 's march toward belligerence '' but did nothing .
An independent counsel concluded his investigation of the search of President Clinton 's passport files during the 1992 presidential campaign , saying no criminal charges will be filed .
Joseph diGenova , who has been investigating the matter for nearly two years , said his report will exonerate the former Bush administration officials who had been the subject of his probe .
`` No question about it , '' he said Thursday .
A three-judge federal panel appointed diGenova nearly two years ago , after President Bush 's attorney general , William Barr , found possible evidence of criminal intent in the search of the Democratic presidential candidate 's passport files .
Late in the campaign , rumors had surfaced that while Clinton was a student in England , he had sought information on how to renounce his U.S. citizenship .
The unfounded rumors triggered requests for government documents from the news media and an inquiry from a Republican House member , Rep. Gerald Solomon of New York .
Political appointees at the State Department expedited the search , and State Department Inspector General Sherman Funk concluded after his own investigation that they had sought to use their official access to government records to damage Clinton 's chances against Bush .
Among those criticized in Funk 's report was Elizabeth Tamposi , the assistant secretary of state for consular affairs , who was subsequently fired .
Funk referred the matter to the Justice Department for prosecution , and Barr then sought appointment of an independent counsel .
Japan , the only country that has suffered atomic attacks , expressed displeasure for a second day Friday over a U.S. plan to issue a postal stamp showing a nuclear mushroom cloud .
`` I do n't think the Japanese people will have good feelings toward the design of the stamp , '' Foreign Minister Yohei Kono said .
`` We may convey our feelings to the U.S. side in some form , '' he told a news conference .
The U.S. Postal Service plans to begin selling the stamp next September .
The stamp depicts the explosion of the atomic bomb dropped by U.S. forces on the city of Hiroshima in the closing days of World War II .
Under the mushroom cloud , it says , `` Atomic bombs hasten war 's end , August 1945 . ''
Within five months after the bombing of Hiroshima , about 140,000 of the city 's 340,000 residents died .
Another atomic bombing of Nagasaki three days later killed 70,000 of that city 's 270,000 people .
Several days later , on Aug. 15 , 1945 , Japan surrendered to the Allied Forces .
Survivors of the atomic bombing and anti-nuclear activists expressed anger over the stamp on Thursday .
Sunao Tsuboi , a leader of the 30,000-member Hiroshima Prefectural Confederation of A-Bomb Survivors ' Organizations , called the stamp `` outrageous . ''
`` It makes our blood boil with anger , '' he said .
A 13-year-old Japanese boy hanged himself in his back yard after being bullied by classmates into giving them more than 1 million yen -LRB- dlrs 10,000 -RRB- over three years , reports said Friday .
In a four-page suicide note , Kiyoteru Okouchi said a group of four classmates at Tobu Junior High School had been abusing him and extorting money from him for three years .
His body was found Sunday night hanging from a tree at his home in Nishio , about 270 kilometers -LRB- 170 miles -RRB- west of Tokyo , local police said .
Police would not say how much money Okouchi handed over after the other students repeatedly hit him and dunked his head in a river , but news reports said the total came to 1.1 million yen -LRB- dlrs 11,000 -RRB- .
He took the money from his parents ' house without permission and left a note addressed to his mother acknowledging the debt , Kyodo News Service said .
Bullying remains frequent at Japan 's regimented schools .
Typical targets are children with outstanding grades , physical handicaps , foreign upbringing , or who otherwise do n't conform .
Some students choose suicide rather than continue to face bullying .
Last year , 113 students between the ages of 10 and 19 committed suicide for school-related problems such as bullying and severe punishments from teachers , according to a National Police Agency report .
About the same amount was reported in 1992 .
A total of 23,258 cases of bullying were reported in public schools in 1992 , up from 22,062 cases reported in 1991 , according to the most recent figures available from the Education Ministry .
`` For him , suicide was no doubt the most severe form of retaliation possible , '' said Susumu Abe , a noted critic on educational issues .
`` Japanese children are not given enough instruction about the constraints they should put on their actions toward others . ''
In Japan , children under age of 16 do not face criminal prosecution and are tried only in family courts .
Top Islamic fundamentalist Hamas leader Mahmoud Zahar and PLO chief Yasser Arafat formed a committee Friday to work out differences and prevent violence , said Arafat aide Ahmed Tibi .
`` It was a warm and fruitful meeting between myself and my brother and what we have agreed on is good for both sides , '' Zahar told The Associated Press .
The early morning meeting was the first since a bloody confrontation between Arafat 's police and Islamic activists on Nov. 18 that left 14 dead .
The agreement to establish a committee ended a tense period of uncertainty in the Gaza Strip where many feared a possible civil war .
Tibi said the nine-member committee , that includes Hamas and PLO officials as well as two Israeli Arabs , would meet soon .
