The dollar climbed against the Japanese yen in Tokyo Friday on hopes for another rise in U.S. interest rates .
Stock prices edged lower .
The U.S. currency ended the week at 99.58 yen , up 0.57 yen from its Thursday close in Tokyo and above its overnight finish in New York at 99.34 yen .
After opening at 99.40 yen , trades ranged between 99.38 yen and 99.59 yen .
The dollar continued to rise in Tokyo after its advance Thursday in New York to a seven-week high as a spate of strong economic figures fueled expectations of a further rise in key U.S. interest rates .
Currency dealers said the dollar moved somewhat narrowly as many players awaited the release later in the day of November U.S. employment data .
If the data suggest persistent inflationary pressure in the U.S. economy , dealers believe that prospects for another rate hike may become stronger , thus increasing the return on some dollar-based investments .
The U.S. Federal Reserve raised its key lending rate by 0.75 percentage points Nov. 15 .
On the stock market , the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 15.30 points , or 0.08 percent , ending the week at 18,998.30 .
On Thursday , the average shed 62.02 points , or 0.33 percent .
Stock prices closed lower in quiet trading as many participants sat on the sidelines ahead of the release of U.S. employment figures .
Equity players fear that if the data suggest another increase in U.S. interest rates , Wall Street may again respond negatively , bringing down Tokyo stocks as well .
The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first section fell 3.35 points , or 0.22 percent , to 1,515.85 .
The TOPIX lost 1.21 points , or 0.08 percent , the day before .
Volume on the first section was very thin at an estimated 210 million shares , down from 265.29 million shares Thursday .
Retreating issues outnumbered winners 594 to 402 , while 201 issues were unchanged .
Benchmark No. 164 10-year Japanese government bonds closed at 96.63 yen , up 0.16 yen from Thursday 's close .
Their yield fell by 0.025 percentage point to 4.630 percent .
NATO foreign ministers sought Friday to reassure Russia that their plans for admitting former Warsaw Pact foes would n't create a new division in Europe .
The allies opened daylong talks with counterparts from nearly two-dozen nations in Eastern Europe in a session likely to be dominated by Russia 's unexpected opposition to a plan to expand the alliance in the coming years .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev stunned the ministers Thursday by protesting the plan for drawing up conditions for future NATO membership .
He also backed out of a program to improve cooperation between Moscow and NATO .
`` I think that we 'll all get -LRB- it -RRB- sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd as he entered alliance headquarters for the second day of discussions .
He said ties between Moscow and NATO were `` too important to be lost . ''
Kozyrev 's comments cast a pall over the meeting and over NATO 's attempt to draw its former Warsaw Pact enemies into its alliance .
However , some diplomats suggested he was playing to an audience back in Russia , where the government is contending with a strong nationalist opposition .
Poland 's foreign minister , Andrzej Olechowski , said the foreign ministers would `` explain everything to the Russians -- that -LRB- membership plans -RRB- are n't against them . ''
`` It 's our problem and the alliance 's problem -- not the Russians ' , '' said Czech Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec .
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
In an effort to meet their demands , but without upsetting Russia , the allies thought they had found a good formula .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
In an effort to overcome Russian objections to its eastward expansion , the NATO allies had agreed to a special relationship with Moscow and insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc .
But Kozyrev was n't impressed .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told a group of grim-faced NATO ministers .
Afterward , Portuguese Foreign Minister Jose Manuel Durao Barroso said Kozyrev `` threw a bucket of cold water on the meeting . ''
Kozyrev refused to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow intended to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
He said he read the ministers ' statement on membership and immediately called Russian President Boris Yeltsin .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' Kozyrev said in impromptu remarks that were broadcast to reporters .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
U.S. State Department spokesman Mike McCurry said Kozyrev gave no advance warning that he wanted clarification of the schedule for considering new NATO members next year .
`` I would be tempted to say it has to do with domestic politics in Russia , '' McCurry said .
Willy Claes , the alliance 's new secretary-general , tried to reassure Kozyrev that NATO was n't shifting direction .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO .
... There is nothing new , '' he told the Russian minister just before he left NATO headquarters .
`` We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst only added to the alliance 's woes .
There have been unprecedented strains in recent weeks between the United States and its European allies over Bosnia-Herzegovina .
In an effort to heal the wounds , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It was a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the Europeans , led by Britain and France .
Ernesto Zedillo 's grade school teacher always told her students that one among them might just grow up to be president .
With her former student 's inauguration as Mexico 's newest president on Thursday , Celia Ladron de Guevara no longer has to hedge with words like `` might . ''
Ladron said she always encouraged her students to aspire to greatness -- telling them they could reach the county 's top office if they worked hard .
`` Some of my students would laugh , thinking it was a joke , '' she said .
`` Today they 're no longer laughing . ''
Ladron remembered Zedillo as a poor , skinny boy who always came to class clean and neatly dressed .
`` And he was always first in his class , '' she said .
Zedillo learned the value of hard work early , growing up in a poor family in this city near the U.S. border , she said .
`` To make it , he had odd jobs outside of school , shining shoes , selling newspapers . ''
