A ferry carrying more than 600 people collided with a Singapore-registered freighter and sank before dawn Friday in Manila Bay , killing at least 17 people , the Coast Guard reported .
Coast Guard spokesman Amado Samante said 449 passengers had been rescued and the search was continuing for others .
The 2,452-ton ferry , the Cebu City , sank 30 minutes after the collision .
There was no immediate official report on the cause of the accident , but the company which owned the Cebu City said it had been rammed by the Singapore-registered freighter Kota Suria .
Jacob Cabatuan , a crewman on the ferry , said the Kota Suria 's bow crashed into the Cebu City , destroying the bridge and ripping a one-meter -LRB- three-foot -RRB- hole in the lower deck .
He said ship captain Wesceslao Lampong and several other officers were pinned on the bridge .
Erwin Maravilla , one of the first group of survivors plucked from the sea by a navy patrol , said his family was sleeping .
`` Suddenly we heard a crash .
I grabbed my two children , but when the ferry sank we were sucked under the water with it .
A piece of metal hit my arm , and I lost hold of my two kids , '' he said , adding that his wife was also missing .
`` I was lucky to be able to swim to the surface .
Otherwise I would be dead , '' he said .
The 12,500-ton Kota Suria , with a crew of 26 , was damaged in its bow but joined the rescue effort , carrying 230 of those saved .
President Fidel Ramos ordered an investigation into the cause of the accident , which occurred in calm seas under clear night skies .
Maximo Calamba , 38 , who survived with his wife Veneranda , 30 , and 1-year-old son Marcelo , complained that the ferry crew failed to inform them about the approaching freighter and did not help people evacuate the ship after the collision .
`` There was no alarm .
We were thrown off our cots and everybody was on their own , '' Calamba said .
`` When we were rescued by the Suria I could still hear crying out for help . ''
Cargo containers and rubber rafts were floating at the scene , but it was unclear whether there were people aboard , said radio station DZRH , reporting from an airplane overhead .
At least eight patrol boats , a search and rescue ship and several other inter-island ferries were trying to recover survivors , it said .
The Cebu City had a capacity of 800 passengers , but only 605 people were on board at the time of the accident , said a spokesman for the Williams Lines shipping company .
The Cebu City sank near the mouth of Manila Bay near the town of Rosario , about 50 kilometers -LRB- 35 miles -RRB- southwest of Manila in Cavite province .
It had left the port of Manila bound for Tagbilaran , the capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- southeast of Manila .
Quirimon Tan , William Lines vice president , said each of the dead passengers was covered by 50,000 pesos -LRB- dlrs 2,173 -RRB- in insurance .
He said the company would also pay for medical and funeral expenses .
The Philippines ' worst peacetime ferry disaster was in December 1987 , when 3,537 people died in the collision of the ferry Dona Paz with the oil tanker Vector off Mindoro Island , about 130 kilometers -LRB- 80 miles -RRB- south of Manila .
Air raids continued Friday in Chechnya amid reports that volunteers from throughout the Caucasus were coming to the aid of the restive republic 's embattled president .
The Interfax news agency said there were rocket attacks early Friday on an airfield and two towns east of Grozny , the Chechen capital .
It gave no details .
On Thursday , a small airfield near Grozny was hit in an air raid and four people died in a missile attack at Katayama , about 20 kilometers -LRB- 12 miles -RRB- from Grozny .
Russian newspapers were full of reports that volunteers from neighboring republics in the volatile Caucasus Mountains were arriving in Chechnya to fend off a Russian invasion .
Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev declared his tiny , mostly Muslim republic 's independence from Russia in 1991 .
Dudayev accuses Moscow of arming and leading the rebels who are now trying to topple him .
The rebels began an offensive last week backed by combat aircraft .
Thousands of people have fled the fighting in Grozny , a city of 300,000 people .
President Boris Yeltsin threatened earlier this week to send in troops unless both Dudayev and his opponents stopped fighting and freed their prisoners of war .
Neither side complied and Yeltsin softened his stance to an offer of amnesty to those who `` voluntarily lay down arms by Dec. 15 . ''
Russia says it offers the rebels only political support .
It refuses to recognize independence for Chechnya , which was incorporated into the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
Media reports say there are substantial troop buildups in southern Russia near the Chechen border .
Meanwhile , a delegation from the Russian parliament was in Grozny trying to negotiate the release of 70 Russian captives Dudayev claims were fighting alongside the Chechen opposition .
`` The use of force in Chechnya is doomed to failure , '' Sergei Yushenkov , head of the delegation , said Thursday .
Dudayev says the prisoners are Russian soldiers .
He first threatened to execute them , but now says they will be tried in military courts .
Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has said the prisoners are mercenaries .
Although Chechens are at odds , they are united in their distrust of Russia .
In Freedom Square outside Dudayev 's offices , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches Thursday while a tank maneuvered into position .
Elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
Russians are generally content to let the Chechens go their own way , according to a poll Thursday by the International Opinion Research Center .
The poll of 3,250 people said 74.2 percent believe Russia should recognize Chechnya 's independence , while 5.5 percent said it should n't and 20.3 said they could n't answer .
The margin of error was 1 percent .
