NATO foreign ministers sought today to reassure Russia that the alliance 's plans for admitting former Warsaw Pact foes would n't create a new divide in Europe .
The allies opened daylong talks with their counterparts from Eastern Europe and former Soviet republics in a session likely to be dominated by Russia 's unexpected opposition to a plan to expand the alliance in coming years .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev stunned the ministers Thursday by protesting the plan for drawing up conditions for future NATO membership .
He also announced Russia 's withdrawal from a program to improve military and political cooperation between Moscow and NATO .
`` I think that we 'll all get -LRB- it -RRB- sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd as he entered alliance headquarters for the second day of discussions .
He said ties between Moscow and NATO were `` too important to be lost . ''
Kozyrev 's comments cast a pall over the meeting and over NATO 's attempt to draw its former Warsaw Pact enemies into the alliance .
However , some diplomats suggested he was playing to an audience back in Russia , where the government is contending with a strong nationalist opposition .
Poland 's foreign minister , Andrzej Olechowski , said the foreign ministers would `` explain everything to the Russians -- that -LRB- membership plans -RRB- are n't against them . ''
`` It 's our problem and the alliance 's problem -- not the Russians ' , '' said Czech Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec .
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
In an effort to meet their demands , but without upsetting Russia , the allies thought they had found a good formula .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the terms , costs and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
In an effort to ease Russian fears about its eastward expansion , the NATO allies had agreed to a special relationship with Moscow and insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc .
But Kozyrev was n't impressed .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told a group of grim-faced NATO ministers .
He said he read the ministers ' statement on membership and immediately called Russian President Boris Yeltsin .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' Kozyrev said in impromptu remarks broadcast to reporters .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
U.S. State Department spokesman Mike McCurry said Kozyrev gave no advance warning that he wanted clarification of the schedule for considering new NATO members next year .
`` I would be tempted to say it has to do with domestic politics in Russia , '' McCurry said .
Willy Claes , the alliance 's new secretary-general , tried to reassure Kozyrev that NATO was n't shifting direction .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO .
... There is nothing new , '' he told the Russian minister just before he left NATO headquarters .
`` We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst only added to the alliance 's woes .
There have been unprecedented strains in recent weeks between the United States and its European allies over Bosnia-Herzegovina .
In an effort to heal the wounds , Secretary of State Warren Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It was a major policy switch by Washington under pressure from the Europeans , led by Britain and France .
U.S. intelligence in the late 1950s foresaw that the Soviets would make long-range missiles a focus of their nuclear arms buildup but greatly underestimated the surge once it began , newly declassified records show .
The records , released Friday by the CIA at a Harvard University conference , paint a picture of American intelligence analysts in the early Cold War years struggling to understand Soviet military intentions with little hard information .
The reports , prepared jointly by the CIA and the other main U.S. spy agencies , contain what the CIA called the most sensitive intelligence information ever made public .
Although the CIA and the other U.S. spy agencies failed to recognize fully the 1960s buildup of Soviet missiles capable of striking U.S. soil , they did believe that whatever the size of the Soviet nuclear arsenal , it was not designed for deliberate attack on America .
In fact the analysts generally ascribed much the same motives for the Soviet nuclear buildup as U.S. officials used to justify America 's : to deter the other side from starting a war and to be able to retaliate and survive if deterrence failed .
This can be seen in many of the 80 formerly top-secret National Intelligence Estimates declassified and made public Friday .
The reports cover the years 1954 through 1983 and were declassified as part of a project started in 1992 to release all Cold War-era intelligence assessments that are at least 10 years old .
The question of Soviet capabilities to launch a nuclear attack on America overshadowed all other issues facing U.S. intelligence for many years after World War II .
The United States , which exploded the world 's first nuclear bomb in 1945 , had a monopoly on nuclear power until the Soviets successfully tested their first bomb in 1949 .
From that point the nuclear arms race was on .
In early 1957 , intelligence forecasts put little stock in the threat of a buildup of Soviet intercontinental ballistic missiles , or ICBMs .
Long-range bombers were seen as the main threat in the 1950s and 1960s , although the newly released records show U.S. intelligence greatly overestimated the bomber buildup .
A special top-secret report on Sept. 18 , 1957 , informed President Eisenhower and his national security advisers that the Soviets probably had conducted their first flight tests of ICBMs , the first on Aug. 21 and the second on Sept. 7 .
In a follow-up special report to the president on Dec. 10 , the intelligence agencies said they had concluded that ICBM development was `` an extremely high priority in the USSR '' and may already be a rush building program .
As late as 1963 , U.S. intelligence reported it was `` still unable to identify positively any ICBM launching facilities '' other than those at the Tyuratam test range .
In fact the first Soviet ICBMs became operational in 1960 .
By 1965 , evidence indicated the Soviets had 224 ICBMs with launch units , but the intelligence reports indicated confusion and disagreement about the scope and pace of the missile production efforts in the USSR .
A year later , in 1966 , U.S. intelligence began doubting its earlier projections .
In 1967 , the U.S. forecasts of future Soviet ICBM deployments were adjusted upward and it was predicted that by 1968 the Soviets would have as many of the long-range missiles as the United State would have -- about 1,000 .
As it turned out , the Soviet ICBM force peaked in the 1970s at about 1,400 missiles ; it now is about half that .
The U.S. force peaked at 1,000 and is now about 500 .
The United States always held an edge in sea-based and air-delivered nuclear arms .
