Tensions at the Canadian peacekeepers ' camp in Visoko , near Sarajevo , eased today after a Serb threat to shell the camp was not carried out Wednesday .
The camp remained at the high alert level of orange , which requires personnel to wear flak jackets and helmets when outside .
But about 100 clerks and other non-essential personnel returned to the camp from nearby Kiseljak .
They had slept in Kiseljak for the past four nights .
On Thursday , LePage said the Serbs ' top commander , Gen. Ratko Mladic , had reponded in letter to a UN protest over the detained peacekeepers and an attack last Sunday on the Canadian peacekeepers ' camp in Visoko , near Sarajevo .
His reponse went to Lt.-Gen .
Bertrand Guillaume de Lapresle , UN commander in the former Yugoslavia .
Officials declined to comment Thursday on the contents of Mladic 's letter , saying they came at a `` sensitive '' time .
But sources said the response was n't specific enough for UN leaders .
Prime Minister Jean Chretien , in Paris on Thursday for a world conference on AIDS , said the troops ' detention is unacceptable but little progress has been made in efforts to win their release .
`` They are detained , you can call it hostages .
... But I would not fight on the meaning of words here . ''
Earlier , in a speech to the French Senate , Chretien said NATO allies will try to solve the crisis in talks in Budapest next week with former Soviet bloc countries .
Optimism was dampened when Bosnian Serb forces crossed into Croatia on Tuesday , kidnapped seven Ukrainian peacekeepers and took them to Serb-held territory .
What if you were a nation that , after decades of not collecting income and other kinds of taxes , decided to start taxing your citizens and businesses again ?
And let 's say your new tax system was frequently criticized , generally disliked by the public , plagued by protesters and still struggling two years after adopting a controversial new tax policy .
Where to go for help ?
Maybe a country with two solid centuries of experience in the fine art of collecting taxes .
One that hauls in more than a trillion dollars a year .
Internal Revenue Service Ogden Service Center , meet State Tax Service , headquarters Moscow .
A delegation of three high-ranking Russian finance and taxation officials toured the Ogden IRS center Wednesday for a closer look at America 's sophisticated , automated and oft-excoriated system of income tax collection .
Rolling through the center more swiftly than a 1040 Short Form , the delegation observed the flow of work and walked through small canyons of computer hardware merrily going about the business of transferring personal income to federal government .
It was an impressive sight , said Vladilen Vorontsov , head of the Russian Federation State Tax Service 's accounting , reporting and analysis department .
`` Russia is undergoing dramatic changes economically , politically and in terms of its new tax policy and administration , '' said Vorontsov , a slender bespectacled man in his late 50s with gray hair and a flawless pinstripe suit .
The country is entering the third year of a new tax system adopted after the collapse of the Soviet Union 's communist economy , he explained .
The conversion is difficult because of Russia 's present economic situation .
He was accompanied by Alla Zubkova , deputy head of the Russian Federation 's budget department , and Maria Reoutova , head of the STS ' accounting , tax statistics and information division .
The Russian officials were scheduled to wrap up their Ogden visit Thursday with sessions on statistical analysis and tours of the Freeport Center and the U.S. Postal Service building in downtown Ogden .
Vorontsov , who served as spokesman for the trio during an interview , said the delegation found the visit informative and helpful but added there is little chance the new Russian tax system will be modeled after its American counterpart .
For one thing , he said , the Russian system is much simpler with only about a dozen taxes of any kind at the federal level .
Instead , it draws the bulk of its revenues from corporate rather than individual income taxes , which provide only about 10 percent of the federation 's tax collections .
`` Like anyone else , Russians are unwilling to pay taxes , '' Vorontsov noted .
`` The negative attitude is very deep , and I think one of the reasons is our people have had very little tax education .
`` It will take us quite some time before our taxpayers understand each -LRB- tax -RRB- is a contribution to a civilized society , '' Vorontsov said .
Among the revelations from the CIA 's newly declassified reports on Soviet nuclear forces : -- In 1963 , the U.S. government was worried that the Soviets might develop an `` orbital bombardment '' system -- one or more satellites with a nuclear bomb aboard .
The fear was that they would `` de-orbit '' the nuclear warhead and detonate it about 150,000 feet above Earth -- a burst that `` would cause severe damage to cities '' over a large part of the United States , `` primarily by means of fire . ''
The analysts doubted that the Soviets would actually try this , but they cautioned that Moscow was technically able to do it `` at any time . ''
This concern remained at least until the late 1960s , according to the reports .
-- In 1979 , the intelligence agencies predicted the Soviets would suffer 120 million casualties , including 85 million deaths , in a U.S. nuclear retaliatory strike , assuming minimal warning in Moscow .
They foresaw 100 million casualties , including 60 million killed , if the Soviets had time to occupy urban bomb shelters .
If all shelters were occupied and the Soviets had time to fully evacuate other areas , casualties would number 40 million , including 15 million deaths .
The report contained no comparable estimates of U.S. casualties .
-- Six months after President Ronald Reagan made his March 1983 `` Star Wars '' speech starting a crash research effort on a global shield against Soviet nuclear missiles , U.S. intelligence agencies foresaw a possibly disastrous Soviet response .
If the United States actually developed such a missile shield and the Soviets had none , a Sept. 12 , 1983 , report said , the Soviets might attack it militarily .
They might also clandestinely place nuclear or germ weapons in U.S. and allied cities and threaten to use them in the event of war .
Air raids continued Friday in Chechnya amid reports that volunteers from throughout the Caucasus were coming to the aid of the restive republic 's embattled president .
The Interfax news agency said there were rocket attacks early Friday on an airfield and two towns east of Grozny , the Chechen capital .
It gave no details .
On Thursday , a small airfield near Grozny was hit in an air raid and four people died in a missile attack at Katayama , about 20 kilometers -LRB- 12 miles -RRB- from Grozny .
Russian newspapers were full of reports that volunteers from neighboring republics in the volatile Caucasus Mountains were arriving in Chechnya to fend off a Russian invasion .
Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev declared his tiny , mostly Muslim republic 's independence from Russia in 1991 .
Dudayev accuses Moscow of arming and leading the rebels who are now trying to topple him .
The rebels began an offensive last week backed by combat aircraft .
Thousands of people have fled the fighting in Grozny , a city of 300,000 people .
President Boris Yeltsin threatened earlier this week to send in troops unless both Dudayev and his opponents stopped fighting and freed their prisoners of war .
Neither side complied and Yeltsin softened his stance to an offer of amnesty to those who `` voluntarily lay down arms by Dec. 15 . ''
Russia says it offers the rebels only political support .
It refuses to recognize independence for Chechnya , which was incorporated into the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
Media reports say there are substantial troop buildups in southern Russia near the Chechen border .
Meanwhile , a delegation from the Russian parliament was in Grozny trying to negotiate the release of 70 Russian captives Dudayev claims were fighting alongside the Chechen opposition .
`` The use of force in Chechnya is doomed to failure , '' Sergei Yushenkov , head of the delegation , said Thursday .
Dudayev says the prisoners are Russian soldiers .
He first threatened to execute them , but now says they will be tried in military courts .
Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has said the prisoners are mercenaries .
Although Chechens are at odds , they are united in their distrust of Russia .
In Freedom Square outside Dudayev 's offices , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches Thursday while a tank maneuvered into position .
Elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
Russians are generally content to let the Chechens go their own way , according to a poll Thursday by the International Opinion Research Center .
The poll of 3,250 people said 74.2 percent believe Russia should recognize Chechnya 's independence , while 5.5 percent said it should n't and 20.3 said they could n't answer .
The margin of error was 1 percent .
NATO foreign ministers sought Friday to reassure Russia that their plans for admitting former Warsaw Pact foes would n't create a new division in Europe .
The ministers opened daylong talks with counterparts from more than 20 East European nations , including Russia , in a session likely to be dominated by Moscow 's unexpected opposition to a plan to expand the Western alliance in the coming years .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev stunned the ministers Thursday by protesting the plan for drawing up conditions for future NATO membership .
He also backed out of a program to improve cooperation between Moscow and NATO .
`` I think that we 'll all get -LRB- it -RRB- sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said before Friday 's talks .
He said ties between Moscow and NATO were `` too important to be lost . ''
Kozyrev 's comments clouded NATO 's attempt to draw in its former Warsaw Pact enemies .
However , some diplomats suggested he was playing to a domestic audience in Russia , where the government faces a strong nationalist opposition .
Poland 's foreign minister , Andrzej Olechowski , said the foreign ministers would `` explain everything to the Russians -- that -LRB- membership plans -RRB- are n't against them . ''
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the defense guarantees that would go with it .
To deal with the demands without upsetting Russia , the allies last January backed a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , providing for closer ties without membership .
Russia is among 23 nations enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part in NATO military exercises and other activities .
On Thursday , the allies went further by ordering aides to draft a study of the terms and conditions for expanding NATO eastward .
Meanwhile , the allies granted Russia a special relationship and denied they were forming a hostile bloc .
But Kozyrev told grim-faced NATO ministers : `` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion . ''
He refused to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow intended to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' Kozyrev said in impromptu remarks .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
NATO secretary-general Willy Claes immediately tried to reassure Kozyrev that NATO was n't shifting direction .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO .
... There is nothing new , '' he told the Russian minister Thursday .
`` We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst added to the woes of an alliance long strained by U.S.-European disputes over dealing with the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina .
In an effort to mend the rift , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It was a major policy switch by Washington under pressure particularly from Britain and France .
