In renewed fighting between left-wing guerrillas and the police in a southern Indian state , six rebels were killed in separate attacks on Friday , a news agency said .
The Peoples War Group , an organization fighting for poor farmers , has carried out a series of attacks to disrupt Thursday 's voting to elect a new legislature in Andhra Pradesh state .
During the final week of campaigning , about 30 people , mostly policemen , have been killed in land mine explosions blamed on the group .
Three rebels were killed when they tried to disrupt voting on Thursday .
On Friday , three rebels were killed in a gun battle with the police in Karimnagar province , while three others were killed in as many different encounters elsewhere in the state , United News of India said .
The area is about 1,500 kilometers -LRB- 930 miles -RRB- south of New Delhi .
The group has been leading a peasants ' rebellion against rich landowners and attacked the police in the state for several years .
Great Britain has canceled half the debt owed it by Vietnam while giving Hanoi more time to pay back the remaining amount , a British diplomat said Friday .
Britain formally reduced Vietnam 's debt from dlrs 26 million to dlrs 13 million in an agreement signed in Hanoi Thursday , said Martin Garrett , second commercial secretary at the British embassy .
The debt consists of principal and interest arising from unpaid bills to British exporters dating as far back as the late 1970s .
The agreement was a de facto condition for a British aid package of dlrs 75 million in grants and soft loans , Garrett said .
Britain will make the funds available as soon as Vietnam identifies the projects it wants to finance , he said .
Britain joins other European countries that have taken similar steps to ease Vietnam 's debt burden .
France agreed in July to cancel dlrs 229 million in Vietnamese debt , while Germany wrote off dlrs 101 million in old loans in August .
Britain agreed in principle to cancel half its Vietnamese debt at a meeting of creditor nations in November 1993 .
It played a leading role then in persuading other countries to do the same , Garrett said .
The diplomat gave no details about the new repayment terms for the remaining loans , except to say that Vietnam would have several years to pay them back .
Western countries such as Britain are eager to help Vietnam as it replaces socialist central planning with a free market .
Vietnam 's 72 million people and its average economic growth rate of 7.3 percent during each of the past three years make it an increasingly attractive economic market for them .
Prime Minister Jean Chretien of Canada on Friday proposed a broad free-trade agreement between the world 's two largest trading blocs , Western Europe and North America .
In a speech to French businessmen , Chretien welcomed the growth of regional trading blocs , such as the European Union and the U.S.-Canada-Mexico alliance forged by the North American Free-Trade Agreement -LRB- NAFTA -RRB- .
`` Yet this also entails its share of risk , and I am particularly sensitive to defensive and protectionist attitudes that might lead the major regional blocs to withdraw timidly into their own shells , '' he said .
`` We must overcome the trade disputes that weigh down our relations and create unnecessary fears , '' he said .
`` We should look carefully at the idea of a global trade liberalization agreement between NAFTA and the European Union . ''
He said Canada , which sends 80 percent of its exports to the United States , had experienced a stagnation of its trade relations with Europe .
`` We must re-energize our economic relations immediately , '' he said , urging closer cooperation in technology , entertainment industries and tourism .
`` We must strengthen one another 's competitive capacity on American , European , Asian and international markets , '' he said .
`` This is the best way to energize relations between Canada and France , and Canada and Europe , and to fight the temptation of isolation . ''
He noted that France and Canada were well placed to influence transatlantic trade policy , because France holds the rotating presidency of the EU for the first half of 1995 and Canada will host next year 's Group of Seven economic summit .
Chretien was to meet later Friday with President Francois Mitterrand and Premier Edouard Balladur .
With pleas to end vote-rigging and campaign violence , Taiwan wrapped up weeks of fierce campaigning for a local election Saturday that confronts the island 's rulers with their sternest electoral test in 45 years .
The elections , a milestone in Taiwan 's seven-year shift from virtual dictatorship to democracy , could profoundly affect the future of this economically powerful but diplomatically isolated island .
Victory for the opposition in the races for island governor and mayors of the two main cities would be a severe blow to President Lee Teng-hui 's prospects for another term in 1996 , when Taiwan holds its first direct presidential election .
It also could buffet Taiwan 's fragile relationship with Communist China , its longtime rival .
Where Lee 's Nationalists cling to the old doctrine of reunification with China , the opposition Democratic Progressive Party advocates Taiwanese independence , something China has vowed to resist by force .
So although the election is largely a local affair , it has sparked heated debate among Taiwanese about their identity , the island 's international isolation and the Chinese giant across the Taiwan Straits .
On Thursday , to cries of outrage from the DPP , heads of three major chambers of commerce placed newspaper ads warning that Taiwan 's dollar and the island 's appeal to investors would plummet if pro-independence forces gained power .
The DPP may profit from a split in the Nationalist vote caused by the recently formed New Party , which quit the Nationalists , claiming they had abandoned the ideology of reunification .
The Nationalists have ruled Taiwan since 1949 when they fled Mao Tse-tung 's Communists on mainland China .
They ruled Taiwan by martial law until 1987 before embarking on a bloodless democratic revolution that culminates Saturday in the first election of a governor .
Voters also will choose a provincial assembly , local councilors , and mayors for Taipei and Kaohsiung , which have n't elected their mayors since 1967 and 1979 respectively .
The DPP 's Chen Shui-bian is thought to be a front-runner to become the capital 's mayor , while Nationalist James Soong has a 50-40 lead over the DPP 's Chen Ting-nan in the gubernatorial race , according to the most recent surveys .
Newspapers predict that up to 70 percent of Taiwan 's 13.8 million eligible voters will turn out .
The 11,825 polling stations open at 8:00 a.m. -LRB- 0000 GMT -RRB- , and results are expected about eight hours after polls close at 4 p.m. -LRB- 0800 GMT -RRB- .
The campaign has been characterized by an almost carnival atmosphere marred by violence that has left some Taiwanese unnerved by the democratic experience .
`` We all have a responsibility to make the poll a success , '' the China News said in an editorial Friday .
`` Otherwise the nation 's political transformation from authoritarianism to pluralism will suffer a severe setback . ''
Premier Lien Chan instructed officials Thursday to guard against violence , newspapers said .
Some 50,000 policemen are being mobilized .
Officials also have appealed to people not to take bribes for votes -- a problem rampant in past elections and this one too .
On Friday , governmemt-controlled TV stations ran advertisements showing vote-buyers being led away handcuffed .
The Justice Ministry says courts have received some 400 complaints of campaign abuses .
On Wednesday the DPP filed a lawsuit accusing the Nationalists of spending at least 150 million Taiwan dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 5.6 million -RRB- to buy votes for Huang Ta-chou , Taipei 's incumbent Nationalist mayor who has lagged in opinion polls .
The Nationalists said the money was payment for volunteers distributing campaign leaflets .
President Lee , who is credited with steering Taiwan toward democracy since he took office in 1988 , visited Huang 's campaign office Friday to lend support .
Huang led a convoy through Taipei 's streets , with supporters waving flags and lighting firecrackers .
The people of a remote Siberian village have sacrificed their windows -- and dishes and light bulbs -- for the cause of peace .
The military last month began blowing up strategic missile silos concealed in the wilderness around Shila as part of nuclear disarmament accords with the United States .
The ITAR-Tass news agency said the latest silo explosion also blew out windows and shattered crockery and lights for miles around .
Residents of Shila , who were n't warned about the upcoming blast , were indignant , it said .
Shila is in the region of Krasnoyarsk , 3,400 kilometers -LRB- 2,100 miles -RRB- east of Moscow .
`` Asian values '' are no excuse for corrupt and despotic rule , Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim of Malaysia said Friday .
He said that while the West is guilty of `` patronizing and condescending postures , '' the term `` Asian values '' too often is used to justify `` autocratic practices and denial of basic rights and civil liberties . ''
He called this Asian attitude `` altogether shameful . ''
Ibrahim 's speech to a symposium on `` ` Asian Values ' and the Media 's Role in Society '' was a spirited contribution to the debate that has raged in recent years between East and West over the merits of their respective societies .
That debate pits advocates of free speech , individual liberties and human rights against some Asian leaders who say such rights are not applicable in their countries , which are still struggling for stability and human rights of a different sort , like freedom from hunger and disease .
Although Malaysia has been prominent in accusing the West of hitting Asia with double standards , Ibrahim sought to show that the arguments on both sides are flawed .
He said Asians , in their growing self-confidence over their economic performance , had not shown `` a proportionate awareness '' of their shortcomings .
`` In all honesty , we must admit that we are still struggling to eradicate the vestiges of the so-called Oriental despotism , '' he said .
Asia has to `` vigorously develop and fortify the institutions of civil society ... promote the rule of laws rather than of men , and foster the cultivation of a free and responsible press , '' he said .
Ibrahim also took issue with the notion promoted by some governments , including that of his neighbor , Singapore , who justify their harsh penal codes and detention without trial on the grounds that social stability outweighs individual rights .
`` It is certainly wrong to regard society as a kind of false god upon whose altar the individual must constantly be sacrificed , '' he said .
`` No Asian tradition can be cited to support the proposition that in Asia the individual must melt into the faceless community . ''
