Police evicted hunger-striking leaders of East Germany 's reformed communists from their own offices in the Berlin parliament building early Friday , so they resumed their interrupted slumber in a theater .
The leaders of the Party of Democratic Socialism -LRB- PDS -RRB- began the fast Wednesday to protest a 67 million mark -LRB- dlrs 43 million -RRB- tax levy they called an unjust political attempt to bankrupt and destroy them .
The politicians , seven including the intellectually agile parliamentary leader Gregor Gysi , initially occupied two federal offices but were removed by police on Wednesday night .
Some 3,000 sympathizers held rallies and sit-ins in Berlin , Schwerin and Dresden on Thursday in support of the party leaders , who were sleeping on cots in their parliamentary offices when police roused and evicted them shortly after midnight .
The parliament 's president , Hanna-Renate Laurien , condemned `` this hunger strike spectacle '' as `` an abuse of the parliament building . ''
The hunger strikers groggily repaired to a theater across from their party headquarters in east Berlin .
The levy the party is fighting was assessed by Berlin tax authorities based on property sales in the first half of 1990 .
At the time , just months before German unification , the newly created PDS held vast assets as successor to the communists .
A large portion of those assets are now controlled by an independent federal commission that is supposed to determine how much of the property they can keep and how much belongs to the people .
The PDS asked the commission to pay the tax bill .
The commission refused , but its board raised questions about why Berlin tax authorities had assessed the PDS in the first place .
A court ruled Thursday that the PDS would only have to pay 3 million marks -LRB- dlrs 1.8 million -RRB- security for the moment , pending further efforts to try to settle the dispute .
But party leaders said they would not pay .
The party won 20 percent of the vote in eastern Germany in Oct. 16 national elections , thanks mainly to resentment among eastern Germans who feel they have been demoted to second-class status in united Germany .
Chancellor Helmut Kohl has attacked the PDS as `` red-painted fascists , '' and Gysi , a lawyer , has been battered by accusations that in decades past he betrayed the secrets of his dissident clients to the East German secret police .
Thousands of teachers demonstrated outside Ukrainian government headquarters Friday to protest rising prices and shrinking salaries .
The three-day strike in Kiev is the most visible sign yet of the increasing unpopularity of an austerity plan President Leonid Kuchma says will eventually put Ukraine on the road to economic health .
Teachers braved freezing temperatures to brandish placards saying , `` Let -LRB- government -RRB- ministers try and live on teachers salaries ! ''
Around seventy per cent of Kiev 's 60,000 teachers boycotted classes in protest of an average monthly salary that is the equivalent of about dlrs 10 .
They have threatened a full strike on January 16 unless something is done to halt the deterioration of the school system .
`` The last time we saw new text books was over four years ago , '' grumbled Viktor Sichenko , principal of a Russian language school in the Moskva district of Kiev .
Many prices have recently been freed as part of Kuchma 's reforms .
As a result , the cost of basics like food , transport , housing and energy has skyrocketed for Ukraine 's 52 million people .
State employees , who make up the vast majority of this former Soviet republic 's work force , saw their real wages fall by up to 60 per cent in 1993 , according to the International Monetary Fund .
