Businessmen in Bangladesh are making an appeal to the government and opposition parties to end a nine-month-long political crisis that has disrupted the economy .
The Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry will meet on Sunday to discuss ways of getting rival politicians to negotiate an end to the crisis , Salman Rahman , a spokesman for the federation told reporters Friday .
`` We will tell the politicians that their conflict is hurting the economy .
They must resolve their dispute as soon as possible , '' said Rahman .
An offer by the federation to mediate was rejected by the opposition parties last month .
The opposition wants Prime Minister Khaleda Zia to resign and set up a caretaker government to conduct general elections immediately .
Elections are not due until 1996 .
Mrs. Zia has agreed to share power with the opposition in an interim government to oversee balloting at the end of her five-year term in 1996 , but the offer has been rejected .
After a boycott of Parliament by all opposition lawmakers since March failed to persuade the government , the opposition resorted to strikes and street demonstrations .
The federation estimates that each day of closure due to strikes cost the economy 1,500 million takas -LRB- dlrs 38 million -RRB- in production , sales and export losses .
Last month , opposition parties enforced at least four one-day strikes and they have planned another 48-hour strike next week .
Bangladesh is one of the poorest nations with an average annual per capita income of dlrs 215 .
`` We will tell the government and the opposition that the political instability will ruin the economy and take it behind by 100 years , '' Rahman said .
The leftist-dominated parliament on Friday easily rejected President Lech Walesa 's veto against increased personal income tax rates for 1995 .
With a 327-93 vote with two abstentions , the powerful lower chamber , or Sejm , exceeded by 45 votes the two-thirds majority required to override presidential vetoes .
The vote proved the strength of the government coalition of former communists and Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 's Polish Peasants ' Party , which dominate the chamber .
During the debate Thursday , the lawmakers and finance ministry officials said accepting the veto would have reduced 1995 government revenues by about 13 trillion zlotys -LRB- dlrs 542 million -RRB- , further decreasing next year 's limited spending in the deficit-ridden budget .
Walesa vetoed last week the increase of tax rates from 20 to 21 percent , from 30 to 33 and from 40 to 45 percent .
The higher rates were temporarily raised for 1994 , but the government had promised to return to previous levels in 1995 .
According to Walesa , higher taxes threatened the stability of the tax system and of the economy and hampered long-term planning in enterprises .
Walesa argued that the society had expected lower taxes , as promised in earlier parliament decisions and pointed out that the government should improve tax collecting , rather than reach into the pockets of pensioners , unemployed and modestly earning employees .
Leftist lawmakers said the veto protected those earning the most and was designed to prop up Walesa 's dwindling popularity in face of next year presidential elections .
In a last-minute deal aimed at swiftly throwing out Walesa 's veto , the government received support from the 42-deputy Labor Union party caucus , which has roots in the Solidarity trade Union , but gradually becomes the most leftist parliamentary group .
Japan 's current account surplus dropped 19 percent in October from the same month last year to dlrs 8.9 billion , in the third straight month of decline , the Finance Ministry announced Friday .
The current account is a broad measure of a country 's international economic flows , including trade , services and tourism .
It registers a surplus when more money comes into a country than goes out .
Japan 's current account surplus was dlrs 11.03 billion in October 1993 .
Even though the current account has declined for three months in dollar terms , many economists are still hesitant to call it a sustained trend , noting that the surpluses remain large and stem mainly from structural factors .
The trade component of the current account fell 10 percent in the month to dlrs 11.13 billion , as imports rose 24 percent from a year earlier to dlrs 22.19 billion .
Exports rose 10 percent to dlrs 33.32 billion .
Japan 's deficit in services widened by 80 percent to dlrs 1.70 billion from a year earlier as more Japanese tourists went abroad to take advantage of the high value of the yen .
Trade figures in the current account are based on settled contracts , and are different from the more widely circulated trade figures announced separately by the ministry each month based on customs-clearance data .
As many as 10,000 Chinese may be infected with the AIDS virus , and 22 have died of the disease since China discovered its first case in 1985 , an official report said Friday .
By the end of July this year , 1,453 people in China had tested positive for the AIDS virus , HIV .
Of those , 1,174 were Chinese citizens , 31 were overseas Chinese and 230 were foreigners .
But Wang Youfa , of the China Xiehe Medical College , wrote in the Guangming Daily that AIDS tests in China have so far been administered only among high-risk groups .
`` The actual infection rate is far higher .
Chinese experts estimate that the -LRB- Chinese -RRB- mainland currently as 5,000 to 10,000 HIV carriers , '' Wang said .
He urged better control of the deadly disease , but proposed no specific measures .
Most Chinese still have little knowledge of the disease and how it is spread .
Some believe that they can catch it through dirty bed sheets or from underwear laundered by hotels or laundromats .
AIDS is most commonly spread through sexual contact , contaminated needles shared by drug users , infected blood or blood products and from pregnant women to their offspring .
The Chinese government long has characterized AIDS as a disease that strikes only foreigners or fringe groups such as drug users and homosexuals .
Prevention measures were directed at foreigners coming to China and at Chinese with frequent contacts with foreigners .
Chinese health officials were shocked in 1990 when they discovered 146 HIV-positive drug users in southwest China 's Yunnan province .
Since then , the figure has ballooned to 1,133 cases , or 79 percent of the national total , Wang said .
The province borders Burma , which produces much of the world 's heroin , and has China 's most serious drug problem .
The report said the infection rate among Yunnan 's intravenous drug users was as high as 78 percent .
Drug users account for 66 percent of the HIV carriers .
The virus has spread to 22 of China 's 39 provinces , Wang said .
Of the 40 Chinese citizens who have developed full-blown AIDS , 22 have already died , he said .
Non-Chinese citizens with the HIV virus are deported from China .
In some disturbing trends , 19 people were infected by their spouses , and eight are less than 15 years old , Wang said .
He added that outside of Yunnan , sexual relations was the main mode of transmission .
Previous reports have also said that contaminated blood products accounted for more than a dozen AIDS victims .
