Air raids continued today over Chechnya , and Russian media reported that volunteers from throughout the Caucasus were coming to aid the separatist republic 's embattled president .
The Interfax news agency reported rocket attacks early today on an airfield and two towns east of Grozny , the Chechen capital .
It gave no details .
On Thursday , a small airfield near Grozny was hit in an air raid and four people died in a missile attack at Katayama , about 12 miles from Grozny .
The city of 300,000 has become a war zone between forces loyal to Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , who declared independence from Moscow in 1991 , and Chechen rebels trying to topple him .
Dudayev accuses Moscow of arming and leading the rebels , who launched an offensive last week that began with helicopters and escalated in recent days to jet fighters .
Thousands of people have fled the fighting .
Russia says it has given the rebels only political support .
It refuses to recognize independence for Chechnya , which was incorporated into the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
Russian newspapers today were filled with reports that volunteers from neighboring republics in the volatile Caucasus Mountains were arriving in Chechnya to fend off a Russian invasion .
The reports could not be confirmed .
President Boris Yeltsin threatened to send in troops unless both Dudayev and his opponents stopped fighting and freed their prisoners .
But as neither side complied , Yeltsin on Thursday offered amnesty to those who `` voluntarily lay down arms by Dec. 15 . ''
In spite of Yeltsin 's more conciliatory tone , there are substantial Russian troop buildups near the Chechen border , Russian media have reported .
In Freedom Square outside Dudayev 's offices Thursday , several hundred volunteer fighters cradling Kalashnikov rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches while a tank maneuvered into position .
Elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
Chechnya has oil reserves and is considered important in securing Russia 's hold in the Caucasus region .
But Moscow also considers Chechnya a destabilizing force for the rest of the country .
Chechen criminal gangs are notorious in the Russian capital , and this year Chechen gunmen were blamed for many of the rash of hijackings in southern Russia .
A beautiful Russian Orthodox cross an Idaho man secreted out of the communist country 27 years ago is returning to the faithful in Boise .
`` It really needs to go home , '' Quinten Crockett said .
`` It means a lot to me .
But it means more to them . ''
On Sunday , Crockett will give the cross to the St. Seraphim of Sarov Russian Orthodox Church in Boise during a special service .
`` The cross in our church is a very powerful symbol of our victory over sin , '' said the Rev. David Moser , St. Seraphim 's minister .
`` We tend to look at things that have survived the ravages of times and persecutions as kind of special .
They are a symbol of our ability to overcome trial . ''
Crockett bought the cross on the Russian black market 27 years ago .
A man approached him with an offer to sell religious icons , but only for American money .
They agreed on a purchase price : $ 10 .
The cross 's history is uncertain .
But many similar icons were taken from Russian Orthodox churches and hidden during the Russian Revolution .
Tiny figures in relief depict the crucifixion of Christ .
On the back are words scratched in old Slavic , a language all but gone in Russia .
Crockett knew all religious materials were considered property of the state and would be confiscated when he left the country .
But he outsmarted border guards by stuffing the 18-inch icon down his pants and covering the top with his untucked shirt .
Crockett kept the cross as a memento of his trip and of the people he met in the Soviet Union .
`` The same spirit I feel in the Mormon Temple , I felt in the Orthodox churches , '' said Crockett , who is LDS .
The cross is believed to have come from a small country church .
`` And it 's going to go to a little church , '' Crockett said .
`` It 's time .
It 's like if someone had an old , original Book of Mormon and was n't sharing it with anyone . ''
NATO foreign ministers sought Friday to reassure Russia that their plans for admitting former Warsaw Pact foes would n't create a new division in Europe .
The allies opened daylong talks with counterparts from nearly two-dozen nations in Eastern Europe in a session likely to be dominated by Russia 's unexpected opposition to a plan to expand the alliance .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev stunned the ministers Thursday by protesting the plan for drawing up conditions for future NATO membership .
He also backed out of a program to improve cooperation between Moscow and NATO .
`` I think that will all get sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd before Friday 's talks .
He said ties between Moscow and NATO were `` too important to be lost . ''
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher met separately with Kozyrev for more than an hour Friday to discuss the dispute as well as the situation in Bosnia .
They `` worked toward a clarification of some of the issues the foreign minister raised last night , '' said State Department spokesman Mike McCurry .
Although NATO and East European officials intended to answer Kozyrev 's questions at the meeting , McCurry said it was unlikely the Russian would change his mind immediately and agree on the new cooperation plan .
Willy Claes , secretary-general of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization , opened the formal session by saying : `` The division of Europe has ended .
We have worked ... to ensure that it never returns . ''
Kozyrev 's comments cast a pall over the meeting and over NATO 's attempt to draw its former Warsaw Pact enemies into its alliance .
However , some diplomats suggested he was playing to an audience back in Russia , where the government is contending with a strong nationalist opposition .
Poland 's foreign minister , Andrzej Olechowski , said the foreign ministers would `` explain everything to the Russians -- that -LRB- membership plans -RRB- are n't against them . ''
`` It 's our problem and the alliance 's problem -- not the Russians ' , '' said Czech Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec .
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
The Russian outburst pushed , at least temporarily , the crisis in Bosnia off the ministers ' agenda .
Christopher , Hurd and Kozyrev were meeting later in the day with Foreign Ministers Alain Juppe of France and Klaus Kinkel of Germany to try to revive the peace process in Bosnia .
Christopher wants formal approval from the others for a new diplomatic initiative to try to draw the Bosnian Serbs into negotiations with the Muslims and Croats in Bosnia .
It calls for a cease-fire around Bihac , the northwestern Muslim enclave that Serbs are pummeling , a pledge to cease hostilities throughout the country for three to six months and then an international peace conference .
The lure for the Serbs , who control about 70 percent of Bosnia , is an opportunity to press their demand for cross-border political ties to Serbia .
`` The essence of any peace plan is a very substantial Bosnian Serb withdrawal ... and continuance of Bosnia-Herzegovina within its own borders , '' Hurd told reporters .
Juppe and Hurd plan to fly to Belgrade this weekend to push the initiative .
The NATO allies , in trying to meet East Europeans demands for membership without upsetting Russia , thought they had found a good formula .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
To overcome Russian objections to its eastward expansion , NATO had agreed to a special relationship with Moscow and insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc .
But Kozyrev was n't impressed .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told a group of grim-faced NATO ministers .
Kozyrev refused to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow intended to ease Russia 's fears .
McCurry said Kozyrev gave no advance warning he wanted clarification of the schedule for considering new NATO members next year .
`` I would be tempted to say it has to do with domestic politics in Russia , '' McCurry said .
