Swiss pharmaceutical giant Ciba-Geigy AG said Friday that it has signed an agreement with three Chinese partners to develop and market a new drug to combat malaria .
The new drug will combine two anti-malarial substances -- artemether and benflumetol -- which work together to produce a `` highly effective '' treatment that can be administered over a short time , Ciba said .
Benflumetol was developed at the Beijing Institute of Microbiology and Epidemiology in Beijing ; artemether is an existing treatment .
`` In developing this new drug with our Chinese partners , we will meet an urgent medical need in many countries , '' a company statement said .
The disease afflicts between 300 and 500 million people a year , killing about 2 million of them , the World Health Organization says .
The company said the drug could be brought to market as early as 1997 .
China has already conducted clinical trials , and further tests are planned in Africa , East Asia and Europe in the next two or three years , Ciba said .
Ciba , Switzerland 's largest chemical and pharmaceuticals group , said it signed the agreement with the Beijing institute and the Kunming Pharmaceutical Factory in Kunming and CITIC Technology Inc. of Beijing .
The venture will produce the active substances for the new drug .
Ciba 's facility in Changping , near Beijing , will make the finished product for export markets , the Kunming factory will make the drug for the Chinese market , Ciba said .
Their luxury cruise cut short by an inferno of smoke and fire , nearly 1,000 weary passengers and crew members of the abandoned Achille Lauro steamed toward safe ports Friday in a motley fleet of warships and cargo freighters .
Two elderly passengers died and eight were injured after fire erupted in the engine room of the Achille Lauro before dawn Wednesday and spread to engulf the ship , despite efforts by the crew to contain it .
`` The fire was so big you had to fight through smoke which poured down toward the cabins , '' survivor Tony Webb was quoted as telling London 's Daily Telegraph .
`` At about 8 a.m. , the captain said the fire was too strong and we would have to abandon ship , '' added Webb , 44 , a Briton living in Cape Town , South Africa .
Passengers clad in evening clothes and bed dress clambered aboard life boats and rafts and evacuated the ship , followed sometime later by the fire-fighting team and , finally , the captain , Giuseppe Orsi .
`` From what I saw , -LRB- the ship -RRB- is gone , '' Orsi said by radio from one of the rescue ships Thursday .
The Achille Lauro was adrift in the Indian Ocean off Somalia on Friday , listing badly to port and still smoldering , its troubled history apparently nearing an end .
The ship 's name burst into headlines in 1985 when the Achille Lauro was hijacked by Palestinian terrorists who killed a wheelchair-bound American and dumped his body overboard .
The terrorists escaped the vessel and boarded a jet , but U.S. fighter planes forced it to land in Italy and the hijackers were captured .
Eight cargo vessels and two American warships , the USS Gettysburg and Halyburton , carried the Achille Lauro 's surviving passengers and crew members toward Djibouti , Mombasa in Kenya and Muscat , Oman .
Most were heading for Mombasa but none of the rescue ships was expected to dock before Sunday .
The opposition felt it was being denied equal TV time in Taiwan 's local election campaign , so it has taken the law into its own hands .
The result is TNT , a pirate station that does daily battle with the ruling Nationalist Party from the bedroom of a rented Taipei apartment .
It 's part of an explosion in pirate TV and radio broadcasting , always lively though sometimes abusive , by critics who feel the Nationalists have been too slow in relaxing their 45-year grip on the electronic media .
TNT -- Taiwan News Telecommunication -- is funded by the Democratic Progressive Party , the main opposition , which claims Taiwan 's three major networks are biased toward Nationalist candidates .
Those networks are controlled by the Nationalists , the military and the provincial government .
There are others transmitting on cable , including some that support the DPP and one that supports the New Party , a Nationalist splinter .
But Mike Chang , who founded TNT with some friends , says their station is the first in Taipei to broadcast over the airwaves .
`` We had to break through the media domination by the Nationalist Party , which we think is not good for society , '' he said in an interview during a break from presenting Thursday night .
They broadcast on channel 12 , hoping to net viewers who stray from 11 , the government channel , Chang said .
He does not know how many viewers TNT has , but TNT radio , which began in March , claims 300,000 regular listeners among Taipei 's 2.6 million people .
Chang charges that instead of educating the public about the election issues and candidates , the Nationalists `` are doing a lousy job , insulting the people . ''
The polls for governor and for mayors of Taiwan 's two largest cities are the sternest electoral test for the Nationalists since they fled to Taiwan from Communist China in 1949 .
Never before have Taiwanese elected their governor and the last mayoral elections in Taipei and Kaohsiung were in 1967 and 1979 respectively .
Pirate stations would have been unthinkable before the Nationalists lifted martial law in 1987 and initiated Taiwan 's shift from virtual dictatorship to democracy .
Today , they are forums for Taiwanese to oppose everything from Nationalist policies to nuclear power stations .
But being a pirate is not without risks .
In July , police raided 14 pirate radio stations , including TNT , and confiscated their equipment .
So far , however , the TV station has been left alone .
Chang suspects the government does n't want a repeat of the riots that followed the July raids .
Chang said TNT is editorially independent but shares many DPP points of view , including its support for making Taiwan independent , as opposed to the Nationalist doctrine of reunification with the mainland .
TNT TV follows DPP candidates on the campaign trail and at DPP rallies .
The station also invites academics and commentators to a daily discussion show , with viewers phoning in .
A bedroom serves as a studio shared by TV and radio , with black drapes providing a backdrop .
Chang and his guests sit around tables pushed together and covered with a table cloth that has seen better days .
As they talk , Ah Gui , the lone cameraman , dashes between two cameras on tripods .
Chang claims the government 's licensing laws are too stringent .
`` We would like to follow the law , '' he says , `` but the law must be reasonable . ''
