Outbreaks of easily preventable and treatable diseases often kill dozens of people in Nigeria , where an economic crisis fueled by corruption has broken down health services .
Yellow fever was wiped out by vaccination before independence from Britain in 1960 but has been resurgent since .
Masked anarchists defending a squatter camp hurled paving stones and Molotov cocktails early Friday at police trying to evict them , injuring 22 officers , city authorities said .
The five-hour struggle against some 100 leftist rioters ended about 4 a.m. after police used an armored vehicle to break through a perimeter barricade the anarchists had erected .
Police , who also used water cannon against the bandana-masked demonstrators , were trying to enforce a court order to remove the camp , but left the scene without succeeding .
The squatters had built a head-high barrier of doors , window frames , tables , shopping carts and two of the seven disputed mobile homes at a square in the city 's Karolinen quarter .
Parts of the barricade were set on fire and police used water cannon to extinguish the blazes .
NATO foreign ministers sought Friday to reassure Russia that their plans for admitting former Warsaw Pact foes would n't create a new division in Europe .
The ministers opened daylong talks with counterparts from more than 20 East European nations , including Russia , in a session likely to be dominated by Moscow 's unexpected opposition to a plan to expand the Western alliance in the coming years .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev stunned the ministers Thursday by protesting the plan for drawing up conditions for future NATO membership .
He also backed out of a program to improve cooperation between Moscow and NATO .
`` I think that we 'll all get -LRB- it -RRB- sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said before Friday 's talks .
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher met separately with Kozyrev for more than an hour Friday to discuss the dispute and the situation in Bosnia .
Later , foreign ministers from Britain , France and Germany were to join them to discuss a U.S. initiative to revive efforts for a negotiated settlement to the Bosnian war .
Willy Claes , secretary-general of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization , opened the main session saying : `` The division of Europe has ended .
We have worked ... to ensure that it never returns . ''
Kozyrev 's comments clouded NATO 's attempt to draw in its former Warsaw Pact enemies .
However , some diplomats suggested he was playing to a domestic audience in Russia , where the government faces a strong nationalist opposition .
Poland 's foreign minister , Andrzej Olechowski , said the foreign ministers would `` explain everything to the Russians -- that -LRB- membership plans -RRB- are n't against them . ''
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the defense guarantees that would go with it .
To deal with the demands without upsetting Russia , the allies last January backed a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , providing for closer ties without membership .
Russia is among 23 nations enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part in NATO military exercises and other activities .
On Thursday , the allies went further by ordering aides to draft a study of the terms and conditions for expanding NATO eastward .
Meanwhile , the allies granted Russia a special relationship and denied they were forming a hostile bloc .
But Kozyrev told grim-faced NATO ministers : `` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion . ''
He refused to endorse a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts with Moscow intended to ease Russia 's fears of an eastward drive by the alliance .
`` This communique raises more questions than it answers , '' Kozyrev said in impromptu remarks .
`` We have to understand what are the intentions of the other partners . ''
Claes immediately tried to reassure Kozyrev that NATO was n't shifting direction .
`` It is no change in strategy or policy of NATO .
... There is nothing new , '' he told the Russian minister Thursday .
`` We are not willing to organize new divisions in Europe . ''
Kozyrev 's outburst added to the woes of an alliance long strained by U.S.-European disputes over dealing with the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina .
In an effort to mend the rift , Christopher swung behind the European view that diplomacy , not force , is the best way to deal with the conflict .
It was a major policy switch by Washington under pressure particularly from Britain and France .
