PLO chief Yasser Arafat met with an Islamic opposition leader in Gaza Friday and formed a reconciliation committee to work out future differences and prevent violence .
The meeting between Arafat and Hamas leader Mahmoud Zahar ended two weeks of tense uncertainty in the Gaza Strip , sparked by a bloody confrontation between PLO police and Islamic activists on Nov. 18 that left 15 dead .
`` Both sides agreed this morning that the most important thing is to try and overcome obstacles and conquer this crisis , '' said Arafat advisor Ahmed Tibi .
`` The Palestinians can not achieve peace without being unified , '' he added .
Arafat faced off against the Islamic Resistance Movement , or Hamas , after Israel demanded that he crack down on militants responsible for attacks that left 32 Israelis dead in October and November alone .
Hamas and the more extremist Islamic Jihad organization oppose the peace accord that Arafat signed with the Palestinians .
But Arafat ca n't afford to ignore the grassroots support for the militant groups , especially among the poor , and is trying to woo them into participating in his self-rule government .
Tibi said Friday 's meeting was the start of a `` real dialogue between the sides . ''
Another Israeli-Arab who served as a mediator , Sheikh Abdullah Nimr Darwish , called the meeting `` a gate of hope for the Palestinians . ''
Darwish said that Hamas no longer rejected an Arafat-appointed judiciary probe into the Nov. 18 violence and had agreed to drop accusations blaming the Palestinian Authority for the clashes until investigators published their results .
`` It was a warm and fruitful meeting between myself and my brother and what we have agreed on is good for both sides , '' Zahar told The Associated Press .
Tibi said the nine-member committee , that includes Hamas and PLO officials as well as two Israeli Arabs , would meet Saturday .
A ferry carrying more than 600 people collided with a Singapore-registered freighter and sank before dawn Friday in Manila Bay , killing at least 34 people , the Coast Guard reported .
Coast Guard spokesman Amado Samante said 451 passengers had been rescued .
The bodies of 34 people who had drowned had also been recovered , he said .
The search for the remaining passengers was called off late in the day because of darkness and was to resume Saturday morning .
William Lines , which own the 2,452-ton ferry , the Cebu City , said the ferry had 608 people on board .
There was no immediate official report on the cause of the accident , but the ferry 's owner said it had been rammed by the Kota Suria .
Eugene Espedido , vice president of the company , said it was preparing a request for the coast guard to detain the freighter and its crew .
Jacob Cabatuan , a crewman on the ferry , said the Kota Suria 's bow crashed into the Cebu City , destroying the bridge and ripping a one-meter -LRB- three-foot -RRB- hole in the lower deck .
He said ship captain Wesceslao Lampong and several other officers were pinned on the bridge .
Erwin Maravilla , one of the first survivors plucked from the sea by a navy patrol , said his family was sleeping at the time of the accident .
He lost both of his two children and his wife , he said .
`` I was lucky to be able to swim to the surface .
Otherwise I would be dead , '' he said .
The 12,500-ton Kota Suria , with a crew of 26 , was damaged in its bow but joined the rescue effort , carrying 230 of those saved .
President Fidel Ramos ordered an investigation into the cause of the accident , which occurred in calm seas under clear night skies .
Maximo Calamba , 38 , who survived with his wife Veneranda , 30 , and 1-year-old son Marcelo , complained that the ferry crew failed to inform them about the approaching freighter and did not help people evacuate the ship after the collision .
`` There was no alarm .
We were thrown off our cots and everybody was on their own , '' Calamba said .
`` When we were rescued by the Suria I could still hear crying out for help . ''
Radio station DZRH , reporting from an airplane overhead , said at least eight patrol boats , a search and rescue ship and several other inter-island ferries were involved in the rescue effort .
William Lines said the Cebu City had a capacity of 800 passengers .
It sank near the mouth of Manila Bay near the town of Rosario , about 50 kilometers -LRB- 35 miles -RRB- southwest of Manila in Cavite province .
It had left the port of Manila bound for Tagbilaran , the capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- southeast of Manila .
Quirimon Tan , William Lines vice president , said each of the dead passengers was covered by 50,000 pesos -LRB- dlrs 2,173 -RRB- in insurance .
He said the company would also pay for medical and funeral expenses .
In a quirk of timing , the Securities and Exchange Commission on Friday approved William Lines ' initial public offering .
The company is selling 235 million shares for between 9.65 pesos -LRB- 41 U.S. cents -RRB- and 15.15 pesos -LRB- 65 cents -RRB- a share .
An analyst who asked not to be named said the accident would probably not drag down the stock issue .
The Philippines ' worst peacetime ferry disaster was in December 1987 , when 3,537 people died in the collision of the ferry Dona Paz with the oil tanker Vector off Mindoro Island , about 130 kilometers -LRB- 80 miles -RRB- south of Manila .
Congressional clearance of a new world trade accord is expected to encourage ratification by other countries , enabling the mammoth export-boosting pact to enter into force as planned Jan. 1 .
Around the world , big and small nations alike are trying to rush the 22,000 page GATT agreement through national parliaments , often in low-key processes that contrast with the rocky ride through the U.S. legislature .
Nearly 40 countries , including the United States and most of southeast Asia , have ratified the 124-nation pact .
About 40 more -- including trade giants Japan , the European Union and Canada -- have indicated they will do so by the end of the year .
Four countries -- Switzerland , Liechtenstein , Cyprus and Poland -- have already told the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade that domestic politics will prevent them from ratifying the accord this year .
But this wo n't stop the pact from taking effect as scheduled on Jan. 1 .
All that is needed is for the all the big traders to come on board as founding members of the World Trade Organization -- GATT 's more powerful successor body that implement the accord .
The agreement is considered the most ambitious attempt ever to free world trade and is expected to boost global income by dlrs 510 billion by the year 2005 .
It reduces customs duties on hundreds of thousands of products , liberalizes trade in service industries , protects against copyright theft and patent abuse and cuts protection of farm goods and textiles .
Most governments object to at least some provisions because previously protected industries -- such as agriculture in Europe and textiles in the United States -- will suffer .
But all participating countries agreed not to upset the carefully crafted compromises with amendments .
The ratification situation in some of the main trading nations is as follows : -- European Union : Britain , Ireland , Greece and Germany have approved it .
The eight other EU members are meant to do so before foreign ministers meet Dec. 19-20 to approve the deal on behalf of the entire trade bloc .
France and Portugal still have some qualms , but the EU Commission , the union 's executive body , said there are no real obstacles .
An internal dispute between the Commission and member states over negotiating powers , which slowed national ratification , has been settled .
-- Japan : A key parliamentary committee has approved the deal , and full passage is likely in the next few days .
The government placated rice farmers , upset at potential competition from imports , with a six-year , 7.2 trillion yen -LRB- dlrs 74 billion -RRB- compensation package .
-- South Korea : The ruling Democratic Liberal party , which has a big majority , plans to push the accord through the national assembly next week .
Opposition politicians and farmers accuse the government of making too many concessions under U.S. pressure to open the rice market .
There have been frequent violent demonstrations against the accord .
-- India : There was strong opposition from both left - and right-wing parties , especially to provisions that give foreign multinationals stronger patent claims to Indian seeds and medicines .
The opposition , however , seems to have run out of steam and legislative passage appears more or less certain , though no date has been set .
-- Canada : Hopes to ratify the accord by the end of the year .
-- Mexico : Under former President Salinas de Gortari , who is one of three candidates for the directorship of the WTO , Mexico was one of the first countries to ratify the trade accord .
-- South America : Chile has ratified the accord and Argentina hopes to do so before the end of the year .
In Brazil , parliamentary passage is likely to be in February , not because the accord is contested but because of delays caused by this year 's election .
-- China : In order to join the WTO , Beijing first has to enter GATT .
Western concerns about China 's market reform programs and a possible flood of Chinese exports mean GATT membership talks are unlikely to finish by the end of the year .
Harassed and humiliated by Serbs , the United Nations on Friday dispatched a senior envoy to try to end detention of hundreds of peacekeepers and a freeze on U.N. movements in Bosnia .
Officials hoped that Yasushi Akashi , the top U.N. official in former Yugoslavia , would have more success than his boss , Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali , who was rebuffed in even trying to meet with the Bosnian Serbs on Wednesday .
Akashi arrived Friday morning in Sarajevo for meetings with Bosnian government officials , and was to continue on to the Bosnian Serb headquarters at Pale , outside Sarajevo , later in the day .
Akashi 's talks would follow a meeting Thursday between Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and the U.N. commander for Bosnia , Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose .
A U.N. source said Karadzic promised to try to help , but added that such promises often are empty .
Spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi wanted to discuss fighting around the government enclave of Bihac with Karadzic , as well as an end to restrictions on the movement of U.N. troops .
Thant said Bihac , scene of heavy fighting for weeks , was quiet overnight .
But strong Serb forces , which have seized 30-40 percent of the U.N.-declared `` safe zone '' encompassing the town of Bihac and environs , remained in the area .
The United Nations has said the Serbs , from both Croatia and Bosnia , appeared strong enough to capture Bihac if they wanted .
There were signs that frontlines south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , allied with Muslim-led government forces against the Serbs , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
A Croat militia and the Bosnian army took Kupres from the Serbs in a joint attack last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Croatian Serb forces also had shelled his forces across the border near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
Alexander Ivanko , a U.N. spokesman , said Thursday that Bosnian Serb units in the Bihac area crossed the border into Croatia and seized seven Ukrainian peacekeepers from an observation post Tuesday .
They took the soldiers and a U.N. armored carrier into Bosnian Serb-held territory .
More than 400 of the 24,000 U.N. soldiers in Bosnia are being detained by the Serbs as insurance against further NATO airstrikes .
NATO struck three times last week , but the attacks did nothing to stop the Serb assault on Bihac .
The Serbs also have been ignoring U.N. requests to send supply convoys across territory they hold .
Monique Tuffelli , the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees staffer in Bihac , said Thursday that food stocks would last only another week .
`` We have run out almost of everything , '' she said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press .
The Serbs repeatedly have rejected an international peace plan .
With the threat of international force appearing to dissipate , their position is hardening .
Momcilo Krajisnik , leader of the Bosnian Serbs ' self-proclaimed legislature , rejected a three-month cease-fire , which the Bosnian government wants .
He said Serbs would only accept a permanent cease-fire .
The Sarajevo government fears a permanent cease-fire would cement Serb territorial gains of 70 percent of Bosnia .
The peace plan they rejected would give the Serbs 49 percent of the country .
Senior Western officials now talk of altering that plan to allow the Bosnian Serbs links with Serb-dominated Yugoslavia .
Opponents say that would be a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal of a `` Greater Serbia . ''
A Russian journalist said Friday he received a fax from a group threatening Russians abroad if Moscow does not recognize the independence of a rebellious southern territory .
Igor Pavlov , head of the Copenhagen office of Russia 's Novosti news agency , got a letter from a `` North Caucasian Liberation Army '' demanding recognition of `` the Chechnya Republic 's independence without any conditions . ''
Chechnya , a territory in Russia 's Caucasus Mountains , sought independence from Russia in 1991 but was rejected .
Fighting broke out last week between its president , Dzhokhar Dudayev , and opponents who he says are backed by Moscow .
In Denmark , the journalist said he received the English-language Wednesday evening , which included a number indicating it came from Copenhagen 's central railway station .
The note said , in verbatim , `` We will consider the Russian officials as non-officials representations and hence as our military targets '' if the recognition is not granted .
The one-page printed fax was signed `` K.K.K.O. 130 .
Police said the sign-off possibly could be initials for the North Caucasian Liberation Army .
Police in Copenhagen said they heard the group has been active in other countries , but not in Denmark until now .
They would give no details .
`` Of course we take this threat seriously , '' a senior police officer said , speaking on condition of anonymity .
No one has been arrested .
The Russian embassy and the Aeroflot air carrier office in Copenhagen had not received similar threats , police said .
The domestic intelligence agency said it was investigating the case but declined to comment .
The note also demanded `` Russia 's recognition of the North Caucasian Federation 's official borders '' and `` the help of the United Nations to the Caucasian people 's return to their native country from where they were expelled 130 years ago . ''
The government outmaneuvered angry opposition lawmakers Friday to pass a 54.8 trillion won -LRB- dlrs 68.5 billion -RRB- budget for 1995 just three hours before its deadline .
The budget , 15.9 percent higher than the current year 's , includes a 9.9 percent increase in defense spending while hugely raising subsidies for farmers , who are angry over agricultural concessions by South Korea in the new world trade agreement .
Approval followed two weeks of political bickering over an opposition demand that the government indict former presidents Chun Doo-hwan and Roh Tae-woo for engineering a 1979 military coup that put Chun in power .
Roh succeeded him as president in 1988 .
The opposition Democratic Party had boycotted the National Assembly over the issue .
The ruling Democratic Liberal Party waited until Friday , the legal deadline , to pass the budget .
Chun and Roh , while still generals , established a junta to rule the country after the death of their mentor , President Park Chung-hee .
The government fears their prosecution would trigger serious political unrest .
With Speaker Hwang Nak-joo kept in his office by opposition politicians who blocked the door , Vice Speaker Lee Chun-koo appeared in a spectators ' gallery , convened a plenary session and announced approval of the budget .
It took only 30 seconds .
Opposition Democrats angrily protested , but there was no violent scuffle -- a set-piece parliamentary scene during past governments .
Earlier Friday , the Democratic Liberals unilaterally pushed the government-drawn budget bill through an assembly budget deliberation committee after cutting 150 billion won -LRB- dlrs 187.5 million -RRB- .
The ruling party controls 171 of the 299 National Assembly seats .
Hours before the assembly 's planned action on the budget , the Democrats abandoned their boycott and returned to try to block its passage .
Defense , up to 11.07 trillion won -LRB- dlrs 13.8 billion -RRB- , takes a 20 percent share of the budget , reflecting South Korea 's preoccupation with threats from North Korea .
South Korea also increased public works spending by 22 percent to 6.77 trillion won -LRB- dlrs 8.36 billion -RRB- -- much of it to tackle the country 's worsening traffic congestion .
But the highlight of the budget is a rise of nearly 40 percent in farm subsidies to cushion farmers and fishermen against the opening of South Korea 's markets under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade .
Subsidies in the new budget total 8.06 trillion won -LRB- dlrs 1.01 billion -RRB- -- about 1.34 million won -LRB- dlrs 1,680 -RRB- a year for each of the nation 's 6 million farmers and fishermen .
The government hopes to pass the GATT deal through Parliament this month .
The opposition has vowed to block it .
Farmers have staged violent protests over the government 's decision to open farm markets to foreign products .
The government has used farm subsidies to buy rice at prices five or six times higher than in the United States and other countries .
Also Friday , the assembly approved a government plan to buy 1.5 million tons of rice this year , 115,200 tons more than last year .
Farmers fear the new trade accord might threaten their livelihood .
South Korea produces 4.75 million tons a year of rice , the nation 's main staple food .
