Legislators across the political spectrum said Friday they doubted Germany would accept NATO 's request to send fighter planes to patrol the skies over Bosnia .
NATO on Thursday asked Germany to send six to eight Tornado fighters equipped with electronic radar-suppression gear and rockets to destroy radar sites .
They would protect allied planes involved in the U.N. humanitarian mission in Bosnia .
In July , the nation 's high court ruled that combat missions overseas were legal , but must be approved by parliament , where Chancellor Helmut Kohl 's coalition has a wafer-thin majority and the opposition is leery of military adventure .
Defense Minister Volker Ruehe spoke out for the mission , but Klaus Rose , the chief of the defense committee in parliament for Kohl 's party , called the
request `` problematic '' because NATO 's goals in Bosnia are n't clear .
The German military has n't been in combat since the disastrous Nazi era , when German troops and SS commandos killed hundreds of thousands of Serbs , Jews and others in the Balkans .
`` Given the historical component , we 're going to have to think clearly about whether we want our first combat mission to be against the Serbs , '' said Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel , whose Free Democrats are junior partners in Kohl 's coalition .
Kinkel said he doubted there was parliamentary support for the mission .
Kohl said he would take his time in deciding whether to push for the mission .
Australian Nicole Lowien shot a bogey-free 6-under-par 66 Friday and took a one-shot lead after the first round of the Mizuno Ladies Golf Tournament , the season 's final event on the Japan LPGA tour .
Lowien , still winless in her six years as a professional in Japan , birdied Nos. 1 , 5 , 6 and 7 and eagled the 529-yard , par-5 14th hole on the Kumamoto Chuo Country Club course in southern Japan .
Nayoko Yoshikawa and Taiwan 's Huang Bie-shyun were one shot off the pace at 67 .
Michiko Hattori , Mayumi Murai and Aiko Takasu were grouped at 68 .
Ikuyo Shiotani , currently second on the Japan LPGA money list , shot a 70 and was in a group of seven players that included Marie-Laure De Lorenzi of France .
Mayumi Hirase , who leads the money list , made a slow start with a 1-over-par 73 , and was tied with Hiromi Kobayashi , a regular on the U.S. LPGA Tour .
Ayako Okamoto turned in a 5-over-par 77 .
The 60 million yen -LRB- dlrs 600,000 -RRB- tournament offers a top prize of 10.8 million yen -LRB- dlrs 108,000 -RRB- .
Police arrested 11,000 people heading toward Bhopal Friday to take part in a demonstration marking the 10th anniversary of the world 's worst industrial accident , organizers said .
The people were taken off trains at various stations outside this central Indian city and charged for traveling without tickets -- a common practice in India usually punishable by a fine or a few hours in jail .
`` Shame on you , government , '' said Abdul Jabbar Khan , of the Gas Victims Organization .
On Dec. 2 , 1984 , a cloud of toxic chemicals leaked from a pesticide plant owned by the Indian subsidiary of Union Carbide Corp. , of Danbury , Conn.
About 4,000 people died that night , and 3,000 more deaths were later attributed to the effects of the gas .
A half-million people are still seeking compensation .
Chief Minister Digvijay Singh , who is the chief executive of Madhya Pradesh state , admitted that many people were arrested on trains moving toward the city .
But Singh could not confirm the number and said he was not sure the arrests were related to the planned anniversary rally .
Tens of thousands of people routinely travel without tickets on Indian railroads every day , but few are caught and arrested .
Meanwhile , Khan led a march of 3,000 people from a city park to a square near the state legislature on Friday .
Police barricaded the roads and red police vans patrolled the area .
The city administration banned the assembly of people around the legislature .
Khan said his group planned a bigger demonstration Saturday and called for a one-day strike in the city .
He said his main demand was to clear the logjam that has blocked compensation for the victims .
