Legislators across the political spectrum said Friday they doubted Germany would accept NATO 's request to send fighter planes to patrol the skies over Bosnia .
NATO on Thursday asked Germany to send six to eight Tornado fighters equipped with electronic radar-suppression gear and rockets to destroy radar sites .
They would protect allied planes involved in the U.N. humanitarian mission in Bosnia .
In July , the nation 's high court ruled that combat missions overseas were legal , but must be approved by parliament , where Chancellor Helmut Kohl 's coalition has a wafer-thin majority and the opposition is leery of military adventure .
Defense Minister Volker Ruehe spoke out for the mission , but Klaus Rose , the chief of the defense committee in parliament for Kohl 's party , called the
request `` problematic '' because NATO 's goals in Bosnia are n't clear .
The German military has n't been in combat since the disastrous Nazi era , when German troops and SS commandos killed hundreds of thousands of Serbs , Jews and others in the Balkans .
`` Given the historical component , we 're going to have to think clearly about whether we want our first combat mission to be against the Serbs , '' said Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel , whose Free Democrats are junior partners in Kohl 's coalition .
Kinkel said he doubted there was parliamentary support for the mission .
Kohl said he would take his time in deciding whether to push for the mission .
Japan 's economy expanded at a robust annual rate of 3.7 percent in the July-September quarter , the Economic Planning Agency reported Friday .
The 0.9 percent increase from the previous quarter in Japan 's gross domestic product , a broad indicator of what a country produces within its own borders , prompted the normally cautious EPA to predict a `` full-scale recovery '' by the end of the current fiscal year next March .
Private economists remain somewhat more cautious , however , saying the fast pace of expansion may not last and that structural drags on the economy , including mountains of bad debt , may hold Japan 's recovery to a slow pace .
EPA Vice Minister Tsutomu Tanaka told reporters that domestic demand during the quarter grew strongly , helped by a one-year income tax cut that the government implemented in June as well as by Japan 's record summer heat wave .
The EPA , the government 's economic forecasting agency , has so far only tentatively talked about Japan 's economy heading toward recovery .
Tanaka 's statements Friday mark a much more bullish assessment than government officials have so far been willing to make .
Tanaka said it 's still difficult to predict how strongly the Japanese economy will grow , noting that the yen 's strength and the pace of growth in capital outlays must both be watched .
The surprising upturn of capital outlays , which account for roughly 20 percent of Japan 's GDP and have been the major drag on the economy in recent years as companies retreated from the heavy investments made during the late 1980s , was seen as a good sign .
But private analysts say it 's doubtful that the strong gains in personal consumption and capital spending seen in the latest quarter can be sustained during the current quarter .
The report definitely points to recovery but `` let 's not get carried away , '' said Mineko Sasaki-Smith , senior economist with Morgan Stanley Japan Ltd.
The scenario of a gradual upturn still remains most likely , she said .
The strong growth in the July-September quarter followed a relatively mild 0.2 percent expansion in the April-June quarter , which works out to 0.7 percent growth at an annual pace .
Share prices on the London Stock Exchange were lower at midday Friday .
At noon GMT , the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was 3,022.6 , down 17 points .
Volume was 204.9 million shares .
China 's leaders are united behind an economic plan for 1995 to control the rapidly growing economy and curb runaway inflation , the country 's newspapers reported Friday .
The leaders announced after a four-day , closed-door national working conference on the economy that reforms would continue with no major changes , the newspapers said .
The reports gave no hints of the content of the debates about the extent and timing of reform that were expected at the gathering of top national leaders , provincial chiefs and officials from around the country .
In recent years , government targets for cooling the economy often have been ignored at the provincial and local levels , where officials want to make the most of growth opportunities .
An editorial Friday in the Communist Party newspaper People 's Daily called on party committees and governments at all levels to `` safeguard the authority '' of national economic policies and actually implement them .
Slogans such as `` deepen reform , '' `` maintain stability , '' and `` strengthen macro-economic control , '' were typically numerous in news reports in the state-controlled press .
But there were no new figures .
The reports did not give any new target for reducing inflation , now running at more than 20 percent .
It was possible that officials did not want to set targets that might not be met , or that they could not agree on new ones .
`` China will continue to strengthen macroeconomic control over the national economy in order to seek a sustainable , rapid and healthy economic development next year , '' the official Xinhua News Agency said in summing up the conference .
The Xinhua report was spread across the front pages of all major newspapers .
The meeting agreed that the major problems were a lack of agricultural development , poor performance of state enterprises , a breakdown of social order and the growing gap between rich industrial areas and poor , rural inland areas , it said .
In addition , high inflation for the past two years has aroused concern throughout society , it said , warning that while some inflation during rapid economic growth was unavoidable , too much was dangerous .
China 's leaders already had announced that controlling inflation and reforming failing state enterprises would be top goals for the new year .
State-run industries account for about half of China 's industrial output , and just under half of them have been losing money .
Concerned about the possibility of social unrest , the government has so far stopped short of massive layoffs or cutting social services tied to state jobs .
Other priorities listed in the latest economic plan included more spending on agriculture to ensure adequate food production .
Strict control of bank credit will be continued .
The People 's Daily editorial predicted an 11 percent growth rate for 1995 , about the same as this year 's .
In a separate report , the Guangming Daily reported Friday a directive from the State Economic and Trade Commission ordering links be severed between all government and party offices and all commercial and business enterprises before the end of the year .
In recent years , as part of the transition from a centrally planned economy to a market-oriented one , many government economic and trade offices have been transformed into companies .
But for many of these new companies , the change was in name only .
They retained the same staff and maintained the same relationships with government and party organs , giving them an edge over competitors .
The IRA expects negotiations about weapons with the British to include security force arms as well as it own hidden arsenals , the movement 's political allies signalled Friday .
`` We 're prepared , perfectly prepared , to discuss the issue of the amount of weapons that are in circulation in Ireland , both legal and illegal , '' Mitchel McLaughlin , a spokesman for Sinn Fein , said on BBC radio .
Britain and Sinn Fein are to start talks in Belfast on Wednesday , the next big step in the search for a political settlement in Northern Ireland following the 3-month-old cease-fire by the IRA in its battle to end British rule .
Martin McGuinness , a former IRA commander who will lead the Sinn Fein team , has said for the first time that the future of the IRA weapons , mostly hidden over the border in the Republic of Ireland would be discussed .
Michael Mates , a British legislator and former minister sometimes used by the government to argue publicly with Sinn Fein , said the change of heart was `` very good news . ''
`` Only a month ago Martin McGuinness was saying ` if I asked the IRA to hand over their weapons they 'd laugh ' , '' Mates said on the same program .
He maintained that Protestant politicians would not negotiate directly with the Catholic-based Sinn Fein or the IRA `` while behind while behind that organization is still the threat of returning to violence if they do n't get their way . ''
Sinn Fein 's McLaughlin , however , said the IRA would need evidence of real progress in the talks .
Only then , he said , would it be `` realistic to go to those who have weapons and say ` we believe the conditions now exist where it would be possible and practical to take the gun out of Irish politics forever . '' '
Rod McGeoch , who masterminded Sydney 's successful bid to host the 2000 Olympic Games , is to be an adviser to a joint Australia-New Zealand bid to host the rugby union World Cup in 1999 .
Australia and New Zealand plan to combine in opposition to England 's bid to host the World Cup , and New Zealand Rugby Football Union president Eddie Tonks already has had talks with his Australian counterparts .
`` Australia initially came up with the idea of bidding for the Cup and they decided to get this guy -LRB- McGeoch -RRB- involved , '' Tonks said .
`` I met him in Sydney recently and he seems a very professional and impressive man .
`` We 're likely to be guided by him on our presentation to the International Rugby Board . ''
Bids for the right to host the World Cup have to be placed with the IRB by Dec. 31 and the host country will be decided at the board 's March meeting .
McGeoch , a Sydney lawyer , was head of the Sydney 2000 Bid Committee that won the 2000 Olympic Games ahead of Beijing .
Russian lawmakers in Chechnya for negotiations with its defiant president on Friday called on Russia to halt its air strikes against the rebel republic .
`` It is clear that these planes are not English or French but Russian , '' said Ella Pamfilova , a member of parliament and former welfare minister .
`` This is against the law . ''
Other members of the parliamentary delegation also called for an end to the air strikes , warning the conflict could spiral out of control .
Pamfilova spoke while awaiting a meeting with Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev .
She is a part of four-person delegation trying to negotiate the release of 70 Russians captured in the fighting in Chechnya , a tiny , mostly Muslim republic in the Caucasus Mountains of southern Russia .
Dudayev at first threatened to kill the prisoners , whom he identified as Russian soldiers .
He later said they would be tried in military courts .
Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has said the captives are mercenaries .
Dudayev , who declared his fiesty republic 's independence from Russia in 1991 , accuses Moscow of arming and leading the rebels who are now trying to topple him .
The rebels began an offensive last week backed by combat aircraft .
Thousands of people have fled Grozny , a city of 300,000 , this week .
Chechen officials said there was another round of air raids early Friday morning east of Grozny , including one on Shali , home to a tank regiment .
On Thursday , a small airfield near Grozny was hit in an air raid and four people died in a missile attack at Katayama , about 20 kilometers -LRB- 12 miles -RRB- from Grozny .
`` We saw two planes fly over this morning , '' the commander of the air field , Biali Chimayev , said .
`` We 're expecting another attack . ''
Thursday 's raid destroyed an Mi-8 helicopter and four propeller planes but 11 tanks , including five captured form the opposition survived .
Moscow does not recognize the independence of Chechnya , which became part of the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
Officially , the Kremlin says its support for Dudayev 's opposition is political and financial -- not military .
But President Boris Yeltsin threatened earlier this week to send in troops unless the fighting stopped .
He later softened his stance , but there are media reports of Russian troop buildups near the border .
`` Chauvinist forces in Russian are pushing President Yeltsin to act , saying he can not control ` little ' Chechnya , '' warned Vladimir Lysenko , another member of the parliamentary delegation .
Although ultranationalists , like the flamboyant Vladimir Zhirinovsky , constantly lament the loss of Moscow 's empire , most Russians are ready to let the Chechens go their own way .
More than 74 percent of the 3,250 people questioned in a new poll said Russia should recognize Chechnya 's independence .
Only 5.5 percent opposed it and 20.3 percent had no opinion .
The poll , released Thursday by the International Opinion Research Center , had a 1 percent margin of error .
Although Chechens are at odds , they are united in their distrust of Russia .
In Freedom Square outside Dudayev 's offices , several hundred volunteers cradling assault rifles and grenade launchers gathered to hear speeches Thursday while a tank maneuvered into position .
Elders in tall fur hats , tunics and high leather boots danced in a circle , chanting , `` Freedom or death ! ''
Chechnya 's ancient warrior culture holds clan elders in high esteem .
Lysenko , the Russian deputy , warned that the conflict is endangering the lives of the 150,000 ethnic Russians in Chechnya .
In Copenhagen , a Russian journalist said Friday he received a fax from a group threatening Russians abroad if Moscow does not recognize Chechnya 's independence .
The threat was signed `` K.K.K.O. 130 .
year , '' which Danish police said might stand for the North Caucasian Liberation Army .
Police in Copenhagen said they heard the group has been active in other countries .
