Verdy Kawasaki on Friday captured the Japanese Professional Soccer League championship for the second straight year , beating Sanfrecce Hiroshima 1-0 .
More than 50,000 spectators at National Stadium saw 37-year-old Brazilian-born Japanese Ruy Ramos , overcoming a leg injury , fire a shot from just inside the penalty area past goalkeeper Kazumasa Kawano 's head into the goal 35 minutes into the second half .
Verdy , the second-stage champion and the 12-team J-League 's inaugural season champion in 1993 , defeated first-stage champion Sanfrecce 1-0 in the first game of the championship series .
Sanfrecce played aggressively at the start of the first half but Verdy gradually found its rhythm and overpowered Sanfrecce in the rest of the first half , outshooting them 4-1 .
Sanfrecce 's Czech player Cerny had a chance for a score in the 15th minute of the second half but his free kick went over the cross bar .
The 1995 J-League first-stage season starts March 18 .
The trial of three British soldiers accused of killing a Danish woman bogged down in legal complications Friday , with defense attorneys demanding the case be thrown out on a technicality .
The trial was adjourned until Tuesday .
There have been a string of adjournments on legal technicalities since the men were arrested Sept. 13 for slaying Louise Jensen , a 23-year-old tour guide from Hirthshals , northern Denmark , after kidnapping her .
Friday 's move followed a ruling by the three-judge assize court in this south coast resort city that it was competent to hear arguments on a defense motion for dismissal .
The defense claims the confiscation of confidential notes the men had written for their lawyers by a guard in Nicosia 's Central prison , the only one on the east Mediterranean island , was illegal .
State prosecutor Petros Clerides asked for time to consult the attorney general and stressed that such a legal point has never been raised in Cyprus before .
That opened the possibility the case will be referred to the Supreme Court , the republic 's highest court .
That could delay the trial for weeks .
The soldiers are privates Alan Ford , 26 , of Birmingham ; Justin Fowler , 26 , of Falmouth , Cornwall ; and Jeff Parnell , 23 , of Oldbury , West Midlands .
The men , making their eighth court appearance Friday , have yet to enter their pleas on charges of manslaughter .
The original charge of premeditated murder was reduced last month because the prosecution decided it might not be able to prove the men had planned to kill Jensen before they abducted her .
Police said the Britons have admitted kidnapping and killing Jensen in the tourist resort of Ayia Napa Sept. 13 .
Her battered body was found in a shallow grave two days later .
The soldiers were arrested at a police roadblock with bloodstains on their clothes and a blood-covered shovel in their car a few hours after Jensen 's Cypriot boyfriend reported her abduction .
All three serve with the Royal Greenjackets Regiments at the British Sovereign Base of Dhekelia on the island 's south coast .
A 24-hour Spanish-language news network has begun broadcasting in the United States , Spain and Latin America .
TeleNoticias was launched Thursday by a consortium of media companies : Reuters Television Ltd. , Telemundo Group Inc. , Antena 3 of Spain and Artear of Argentina .
The cable network provides continuous news , sports and business information , features and international weather updates with an emphasis on news of importance to Hispanics .
`` Our goal is to provide Spanish-speaking people throughout the world with news and information presented from their own perspective with the highest standards of reporting and production possible , '' said Gustavo Pupo-Mayo , TeleNoticias president .
Reuters , a subsidiary of Reuters Holding PLC of London , and Telemundo , a Spanish-language network , are majority owners of the network based here .
Antena 3 is the first and largest private television network in Spain .
Artear is owned by the Clarin Group , a media consortium that includes Argentina 's largest-circulation daily newspaper .
She arched her back and waved .
For a fraction of a second , she was the gymnastics star who scored the first-ever perfect 10 in the 1976 Montreal Olympic Games .
Then Nadia Comaneci relaxed , took American fiance Bart Conner by the arm and annouced the pair would marry in Romania in 1996 .
After a hectic 10 days in her homeland , the 33-year-old former number 1 gymnast , left Romania Friday , saying she was `` very moved '' by the warm welcome given her five years after she defected in what turned out to be the waning days of Communist rule .
During her stay here , she returned to her hometown , met the president and performed in front of the prime minister .
`` People are more open , they are freer and say what they think , '' said a smiling Comaneci , dressed in jeans and a denim shirt .
`` I know how it was before , '' she said in Romanian , translating for Conner .
Conner , also a gymnast gold medallist , talked about the `` warm and exciting reception '' the couple received , saying the most memorable moment was when he asked Gheorghe Comeneci for his daughter 's hand .
Five years ago , Nadia Comaneci left Romania in a dramatic escape .
It was just one month before the collapse of the regime of dictator Nicolae Ceausescu .
Nadia says she was at a dead end when she left .
Five years later , with a new man , an attractive job promoting underwear and a gym to manage in Norman , Okla. , she says she 's happy .
Premier Edouard Balladur assured world soccer chief Joao Havelange on Friday that France was on course to host a successful World Cup in 1998 .
But Balladur admitted his government 's influence was limited .
`` As for successes on the field , it 's up to our national team to achieve them , '' he said of the squad that failed to reach this year 's finals .
`` I wish them good luck . ''
Havelange met Balladur and senior French soccer officials at the close of a week-long trip in which the president of FIFA visited eight of the 10 cities that will host matches during the 1998 finals .
`` With this meeting , we kick off the operational phase of organization , '' Balladur said .
`` All the essential decisions have been made .
Ten stadiums have been chosen . ''
He said his government has agreed to pay 36 percent of the cost of stadium improvements and infrastructure expansion , up from 30 percent pledged by the Socialist government ousted in 1993 .
The major project is construction of France 's biggest stadium , in the Paris suburb of Saint Denis .
Balladur said the 80,000-seat Grande Stade , venue of the opening and final matches , will go under construction in the spring .
President Boris Yeltsin wants the Budapest summit of the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe to declare that military blocs like NATO have no `` real future , '' a news agency said Friday .
Russia has also proposed that the meeting , slated for Dec. 5-6 , adopt a declaration giving the CSCE the dominant role in ensuring European security , the ITAR-Tass news agency said .
Russia has tried to dilute the role of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization after the collapse of the Warsaw Pact created a political and military vacuum in Europe , causing many former Soviet bloc nations to seek closer ties with the NATO .
In an effort to meet these demands , NATO approved a Partnership for Peace program to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
ITAR-Tass said Russia would seek the adoption of a declaration saying , `` the CSCE has always played and will go on playing the key role in ensuring Europe 's security and stability . ''
The proposed document will also say , `` alignments have no real future . ''
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the Partnership for Peace project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
In an effort to overcome Russian objections to its eastward expansion , the NATO allies agreed to a special relationship with Moscow and insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc .
But Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev said in Brussels on Thursday that NATO 's decision to draw up conditions for granting membership to former Soviet bloc countries would create a new division in Europe .
Kozyrev 's remarks stunned NATO foreign ministers who expected him to endorse the plan .
Yeltsin leaves for Budapest on Sunday and is expected to address the CSCE plenary session Monday afternoon , ITAR-Tass said .
