The government on Friday expelled two foreign journalists from Indonesia , accusing them of working in the disputed territory of East Timor without proper permits .
Irene Slagt , 42 , of the Netherlands , and Jill da Rosemary Jolliffe , 49 , of Australia , entered Dili , the capital of East Timor , on Nov. 28 on tourist visas , a military spokesman said .
`` They were detained while interviewing some people , '' Maj. Laeden Simbolon , a spokesman of the East Timor Military Command , told The Associated Press .
East Timor , a former Portuguese colony annexed by Jakarta in 1976 , is normally closed to journalists , who have to obtain permits from the Information Ministry to report from there .
Such permits are rarely given , but an exception was made when Indonesia hosted the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation summit last month .
Restrictions were reimposed once the 17 APEC leaders returned home .
Indonesia , fighting a pro-independence campaign by guerrillas in East Timor , has often been condemned for reported human rights violations by its troops in the territory .
Simbolon said the two journalists were detained in the regency of Baucau , 65 kilometers -LRB- 40 miles -RRB- east of Dili , on Wednesday .
The left Indonesia early Friday , he said .
It was not immediately clear which publications the two women worked for .
Jolliffe is a Lisbon-based journalist who was to accompany a Portuguese parliamentary mission to East Timor in 1991 .
The trip was called off after Indonesia rejected Jolliffe 's inclusion in the team , accusing her of supporting the East Timor insurgency .
The cancellation of the trip sparked a violent demonstration in Dili on Nov. 12 , 1991 , that was quelled when troops opened fire , killing dozens of people .
To mark the anniversary of the massacre , thousands of East Timorese rampaged through the streets of Dili on Nov. 13 , looting shops , burning cars and smashing windows .
The expulsion of the journalists coincided with the visit of two United Nations envoys to Dili on Friday in preparation for talks on East Timor between the foreign ministers of Indonesia and Portugal on Jan. 9 in Geneva .
Also , a special envoy of Pope John Paul II reached Dili Thursday for a five-day visit .
The Rev. Thomas Michel met with Governor Abilio Jose Osorio Soares and discussed religious life on the island .
East Timor is the only Roman Catholic region in overwhelmingly Muslim Indonesia , a country of 185 million people .
Indonesian troops moved into East Timor a year after Portugal abandoned the territory it had colonized for four centuries .
However , the United Nations still recognizes Portugal as East Timor 's administering power .
Serbs fired missiles at the Bosnian government headquarters Friday in a sign of contempt for senior U.N. officials on a new mission to end harassment of their peacekeeping troops .
The anti-tank missiles were fired just before the arrival of the top U.N. official for former Yugoslavia , Yasushi Akashi .
Akashi , on a mission to end detention of hundreds of peacekeepers and win freedom of movement for U.N. convoys , hoped to have more success with the Serbs than his boss , Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali .
Boutros-Ghali was rebuffed trying to meet with the Bosnian Serbs on Wednesday , and afterwards said intransigence by the warring sides in Bosnia might lead to the end of the U.N. mission .
Akashi arrived Friday morning in Sarajevo for meetings with Bosnian government officials , and was to continue on to the Bosnian Serb headquarters at Pale later in the day .
He left the presidency briefly and the two missiles hit the building just before he returned for meetings .
A third missile hit a building nearby .
There were no immediate reports of injuries .
On Thursday , Serbs fired two anti-tank missiles at the Interior Ministry , wounding four people .
Akashi 's talks with the Serbs would follow a meeting Thursday between Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and the U.N. commander for Bosnia , Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose .
A U.N. source said Karadzic promised to try to help , but added that such promises often are empty .
Spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi wanted to discuss fighting around the government enclave of Bihac with Karadzic , as well as an end to restrictions on the movement of U.N. troops .
Thant said Bihac , scene of heavy fighting for weeks , was quiet overnight .
But strong Serb forces , which have seized 30-40 percent of the U.N.-declared `` safe zone '' encompassing the town of Bihac and environs , remained in the area .
The United Nations has said the Serbs , from both Croatia and Bosnia , appeared strong enough to capture Bihac if they wanted .
There were signs that frontlines south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , allied with Muslim-led government forces against the Serbs , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
A Croat militia and the Bosnian army took Kupres from the Serbs in a joint attack last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Croatian Serb forces also had shelled his forces across the border near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
Alexander Ivanko , a U.N. spokesman , said Thursday that Bosnian Serb units in the Bihac area crossed the border into Croatia and seized seven Ukrainian peacekeepers from an observation post Tuesday .
They took the soldiers and a U.N. armored carrier into Bosnian Serb-held territory .
More than 400 of the 24,000 U.N. soldiers in Bosnia are being detained by the Serbs as insurance against further NATO airstrikes .
NATO struck three times last week , but the attacks did nothing to stop the Serb assault on Bihac .
The Serbs also have been ignoring U.N. requests to send supply convoys across territory they hold .
Monique Tuffelli , the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees staffer in Bihac , said Thursday that food stocks would last only another week .
`` We have run out almost of everything , '' she said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press .
The Serbs repeatedly have rejected an international peace plan .
With the threat of international force appearing to dissipate , their position is hardening .
Momcilo Krajisnik , leader of the Bosnian Serbs ' self-proclaimed legislature , rejected a three-month cease-fire , which the Bosnian government wants .
He said Serbs would only accept a permanent cease-fire .
The Sarajevo government fears a permanent cease-fire would cement Serb territorial gains of 70 percent of Bosnia .
The peace plan they rejected would give the Serbs 49 percent of the country .
Senior Western officials now talk of altering that plan to allow the Bosnian Serbs links with Serb-dominated Yugoslavia .
Opponents say that would be a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal of a `` Greater Serbia . ''
A Utah woman and her late husband have been honored by Israel as `` Righteous Gentiles '' for hiding about a dozen Jews from the Nazis in Amsterdam during World War II .
Uri Oren , the Israeli consul general in Los Angeles , presented Alida Praag with a medal and certificate at the state Capitol on Thursday .
Mrs. Praag and her husband Tom 's names will be inscribed on the Righteous Honor Wall at Yad Vashem in Jerusalem .
`` My husband and I felt it should be done .
It was our sense of what was right , '' Mrs. Praag said , recalling their hiding of between 12 and 14 Jews during the war .
Attending the ceremony Thursday was Peter Epstein of Los Angeles , who was a child in wartime Amsterdam .
He helped bring the Praags to the attention of the Israeli government .
Epstein said his father asked the Praags to take him and his 1-year-old brother , Frank , but they had room only for Frank .
The Epsteins decided to keep their family together and they eventually were sent to the Bergen Belsen concentration camp .
They survived and were liberated by the Russians in May 1945 .
`` Fifty-five years ago , a black cloud covered the world , '' Oren said during the ceremony .
`` But behind every black cloud is a source of light , the righteous among the nations . ''
