Turkey 's army pressed its crackdown on Kurdish rebel bases in the mountains of the southeast , killing 52 of guerrillas , the regional governor 's office here said Friday .
The fighting took place over the last few days in Tunceli and Diyarbakir provinces , it added .
Three soldiers were also killed in the clashes .
The guerrillas have been fighting for autonomy since 1984 .
More than 13,000 people have died in the unrest .
After races were canceled in three countries , the men 's Alpine skiing World Cup is finally expected to begin Saturday at one of the few places in Europe that has the needed snow .
Alberto Tomba ca n't wait .
The three-time Olympic champion has been training on a glacier in Cervinia , Italy , since cancellation earlier this week of a nighttime slalom race in Sestriere .
`` I feel good , in great form .
The most important point at the beginning of the season is to start with the right step , '' Tomba said .
`` Thus I want to finish high in the giant slalom . ''
A giant slalom is scheduled for Saturday , followed by a slalom Sunday on a glacier at Tignes more than 2,600 meters -LRB- 8,500 feet -RRB- above sea level .
After rains canceled the opening races in Saas Fee , Switzerland at the start of November , warm weather and lack of snow has plagued Europe since .
A pair of races in Sestriere were moved to Tignes this weekend , while the opening downhill and super-G set for Val D'Isere , France , on Dec. 3-4 were also wiped out .
The two speed races and another downhill scheduled for Val Gardena , Italy , are still looking for a location .
The International Skiing Federation may reach a decision this weekend .
Val D'Isere , with snow cannons operating and hoping for cold weather , has expressed a desire to take over as many races as possible and the federation is eager to accommodate any place that can handle them .
Another giant slalom set for Alta Badia , Italy , on Dec. 11 is likely to be canceled .
while races in Austria later in December are in jeopardy if snow does not come soon .
When the races do start , some old faces will be seeking new titles .
One of the favorites is Kjetil-Andre Aamodt of Norway , who won the overall World Cup last year by more than 300 points over five-time champion Marc Girardelli , the Austrian-born skier who competes for Luxembourg .
Aamodt did n't win an Olympic title , but took three medals in Lillehammer last February .
The man who did win gold in the giant slalom at Lillehammer , Germany 's Markus Wasmeier , has retired .
While the men are still waiting to ski , the women are entering their second weekend of racing in North America .
A downhill and super-G are set for Vail , Colo. , after a giant slalom and slalom opened the season in Park City , Utah .
The United States Ski Association has offered to take over some of the canceled races in Europe but teams are balking at the idea to travel back-and-forth between the two continents for a few days of skiing .
A group of Beijing Christians subjected to weeks of government harassment issued an appeal Friday to believers worldwide for prayer and support .
`` We call on brothers and sisters in Christ to pray for us , members of the -LRB- church -RRB- body who have suffered abuse , and to be concerned about how the situation develops , '' said the written appeal given to The Associated Press .
It was signed by six Christians who have been active in recent months in urging their church to defy government attempts to remove their senior pastor , Yang Yudong .
Yang , the aging pastor of Gangwashi church , the most popular in Beijing , has long irritated the government with his pro-democracy views and his attempts to distance himself and his congregation from government supervision .
For the second time in two years , the government has had to back down from sacking Yang in the face of opposition from church members , who last year threatened street protests and this year sought international media attention .
The appeal said eight church members have been constantly tailed by plainclothes police since mid-November .
On Nov. 23 , one of them , Liu Fenggang , was beaten and kicked in the face and knocked to the ground by plainclothes police .
Photos showed his jacket ripped from waist to armpit and his face swollen and bruised .
On the same day , Hua Huiqi , also was attacked by plainclothes police , who insulted his beliefs and said they were singling out Christians to beat up , the appeal said .
`` What is the crime in believing in the Lord ? ''
The Nov. 23 incidents were not the first clashes between church members and police and government religious officials .
In recent months , there have been several scuffles at the church over government attempts to dismiss Yang and over a room in the church compound that the government took over for its own use .
Official statistics say there are 7 million to 8 million Christians in China who worship in government-approved churches , but estimates of the number of members of underground churches run from 30 million to 50 million .
Officially , freedom of religion of religion is protected by China 's constitution .
In reality religious believers are frequently subjected to official persecution .
Many Catholic clergy , Protestant lay leaders and Tibetan Buddhists have been imprisoned and in some cases have died in prison because of their religious beliefs .
The People 's Daily , the Communist Party newspaper , on Friday reminded readers that party members are not supposed to believe in religion .
It said that in recent years , growing numbers of party members are turning to religion , which it characterized as a form of superstition .
It said the phenomenon was the result of slack ideological education .
A lawyer filed a request Friday for the release of 34 Vietnamese `` boat people '' who are unable to return home or find resettlement overseas .
Lawyer Pam Baker said some of the Vietnamese have been living in camps in this British colony since the early 1980s .
The 34 boat people , who are ethnic Chinese , are not considered Vietnamese nationals by Vietnam .
Baker said that since the Vietnamese are not able to return to either Vietnam or China , their detention in Hong Kong is illegal .
A court hearing on the case is scheduled for Dec. 16 .
Two weeks ago , the government released 125 boat people after the human rights group Refugee Concern threatened to take legal action on similar grounds .
The Hong Kong government came under severe public criticism after it released those people .
Most Hong Kong people want the government to deport all the 24,000 Vietnamese boat people remaining in the colony .
China has also called on the Hong Kong government to resettle the Vietnamese before Hong Kong reverts to Chinese rule in 1997 .
Refugee Concern said there are about 700 Vietnamese in Hong Kong who are not able to return home because of objections by Vietnam .
The head of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade on Friday hailed the overwhelming Senate majority for a new trade pact as a `` triumph '' which would help make the world a more prosperous place .
`` This is a day for particular celebration , '' GATT Director-General Peter Sutherland told journalists .
`` The successful culmination of this debate proved that common sense still works . ''
The U.S. Senate approved the GATT treaty by 76-24 votes late Thursday -- a much bigger margin than expected .
The House of Representatives cleared the deal earlier in the week .
Congressional approval , uncertain for weeks , was deemed crucial to the entry into force of the World Trade Organization Jan. 1 .
The new body will implement the new accord and have tougher powers than GATT to settle trade disputes .
`` I warmly welcome the vote by the U.S. Senate , '' said European Union Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan , Europe 's chief negotiator in the talks .
He said the 12-nation bloc would complete the approval process by Dec. 20 .
In Japan , Trade Minister Rytaro Hashimoto said U.S. ratification of the deal would encourage other countries to follow suit .
Japan 's powerful lower house of parliament passed the accord early Friday and it will now move to the upper house .
This view was echoed by Hong Kong 's Director-General of Trade , Tony Miller .
`` The world looks to the United States for leadership in promoting free trade under the multilateral regime , '' Miller said .
In Canberra , Austrlian Trade Minister Bob McMullan said the U.S. result was `` great news for Australia and the world economy generally . ''
Sutherland said he expected about 100 of GATT 's 124 member nations to ratify the trade accord by the end of the year .
The agreement is considered the most ambitious attempt ever to free world trade and is expected to boost global income by dlrs 510 billion by the year 2005 .
It reduces customs duties on hundreds of thousands of products , liberalizes trade in service industries , protects against copyright theft and patent abuse and cuts protection of farm goods and textiles .
`` We will have a rules-based system that allows for the development of the world economy and provides an assurance of security , prosperity and reduction of tensions , '' Sutherland said .
` I celebrated last night , '' said the Irish lawyer .
`` It 's a triumph for the organization and the fact that people can react rationally . ''
South Africa 's foreign minister arrived in Taiwan Friday , the first South African minister to visit since Nelson Mandela was sworn in as that country 's president in May .
Alfred Nzo 's three-day visit comes amid continued concern in Taiwan that South Africa might switch diplomatic recognition to Beijing , which supported Mandela 's African National Congress in its fight against apartheid .
China regards Taiwan as a renegade province and it insists that countries wanting diplomatic ties break off relations with Taipei .
Taiwan 's Nationalist government fled here in 1949 after losing a civil war to Chinese Communist forces .
South Africa is one of only 29 countries to defy China 's boycott and maintain diplomatic ties with Taiwan .
