Ford Motor Co. and Germany 's Volkswagen AG have agreed to dissolve their joint venture in Brazil and Argentina within a year .
The joint venture , called Autolatina , was formed in 1987 .
It involves engineering , manufacturing and assembly of cars and trucks at plants both companies brought to the partnership .
They have maintained independent sales operations .
`` When this came into existence in the mid-80s , the economic conditions in both of these countries were extraordinarily difficult -- huge inflation , wage and price controls , '' Ford spokesman Al Chambers said on Thursday .
`` The two companies thought they could remain in business by taking a defensive position and sharing . ''
That 's no longer necessary , and both want to return to being competitors , as they are in other nations around the world , he said .
Chambers said details of the agreement still must be worked out and that the separation will be gradual .
Indonesia plans to introduce new labor laws providing stiffer penalties for violators and better protection for workers , a senior official said Friday .
`` The government is fully aware that the current penalties for violation of labor laws are too lenient , '' said Suwarto , the director general of guidance and control in the Manpower Ministry .
He told The Associated Press that a draft of the new laws has been submitted to President Suharto 's office .
He did not elaborate .
Although the government has admitted its poor record in labor conditions in the past , little has been done to improve them .
Earlier this year the United States threatened to withdraw trade privileges to Indonesia if it did n't improve working conditions and wages for workers .
The present legislation sets a maximum of three months ' imprisonment and a fine of 100,000 rupiahs -LRB- dlrs 45 -RRB- for employers who do not pay their workers the minimum wage .
The government raised the legal minimum wage to 3,800 rupiahs -LRB- dlrs 1.7 -RRB- a day in January this year .
The new laws will provide more legal protection for workers and guarantee their safety `` so that they will be encouraged to increase productivity , '' Suwarto said .
The new laws are to cover the wage system , labor unions , manpower , social insurance , work leave as well as workers ' health , safety and education .
He said 12 of the 95 companies that violated labor laws this year have been prosecuted , most of them either for violating minimum wage regulations or for failure to provide mandatory social insurance , overtime payment , work leave and safe working environments .
Their punishments ranged from fines of 75,000 rupiahs -LRB- dlrs 34 -RRB- to 750,000 rupiahs -LRB- dlrs 344 -RRB- or jail terms of three months .
The remaining 83 companies are expected to be tried soon , said Suwarto .
Greg Norman still believes the World Golf Tour can reach an amicable agreement with the U.S. PGA Tour .
Norman said Friday that he plans a meeting next week with PGA commissioner Tim Finchem that he hopes will resolve the conflict between the new tour and the PGA .
Norman said he had spoken to Finchem overnight , and had repeated his assurance that he would attempt to work in conjunction with the PGA .
`` They are very keen to keep communications open , '' Norman said .
`` He -LRB- Finchem -RRB- asked me to see him when I get home and I will do that .
`` Right now the World Tour and the PGA Tour have a chance of working this thing out . ''
Finchem said Thursday that Norman was re-evaluating his support of the new tour .
`` Greg and I talked today on the telephone and he indicated he would not support any venture that would damage the PGA Tour , our tournaments or their sponsors , '' Finchem said .
`` It was a cordial conversation in which we both agreed that a confrontation would not be in the best interests of the game of golf .
