A double-century stand between Sachin Tendulkar and skipper Mohammad Azharuddhin helped India pile up 546 for nine before declaring the first innings closed Friday on the second day of the test cricket against the West Indies .
The visitors , already 0-1 in the three-match series , are widely seen as having little hope of winning the test .
Just before the game closed at dusk , the West Indies were 15 for 1 , with Stuart Williams back in the stands after scoring 12 runs .
Phil Simmons -LRB- 1 -RRB- and night watchman Anderson Cummins -LRB- 0 -RRB- will now need to help their team notch up 332 runs to avoid a follow-on .
Since morning , the Indian team scored swiftly and added to the overnight score of 230 for four .
Tendulkar bludgeoned the ball and made a superb 179 , his career-best and eighth century in 34 tests .
He cracked 24 fours -- and a sixer off skipper Courtney Walsh -- before he was caught by Brian Lara at square leg .
Azharuddhin , who showed glimpses of his brilliant style , gently stroked his way to 97 .
