In Canberra , Australian Trade Minister Bob McMullan said the U.S. result was `` great news for Australia and the world economy generally . ''
Sutherland said he expected about 100 of GATT 's 124 member nations to ratify the trade accord by the end of the year .
The agreement is considered the most ambitious attempt ever to knock down barriers to free world trade .
The pact is expected to boost global income by dlrs 510 billion by the year 2005 .
It reduces customs duties on hundreds of thousands of products , liberalizes trade in service industries , protects against copyright theft and patent abuse and cuts protection of farm goods and textiles .
`` We will have a rules-based system that allows for the development of the world economy and provides an assurance of security , prosperity and reduction of tensions , '' Sutherland said .
Police arrested 11,000 people headed toward Bhopal Friday for a demonstration marking the 10th anniversary of the world 's worst industrial accident , organizers said .
The people were taken off trains at stations outside Bhopal in central India and charged with traveling without tickets -- a common practice in India usually punishable by a fine or a few hours in jail .
`` Shame on you , government , '' said Abdul Jabbar Khan , of the Gas Victims Organization .
On Dec. 2 , 1984 , a cloud of toxic chemicals leaked from a pesticide plant owned by the Indian subsidiary of the U.S.-based Union Carbide Corp.
About 4,000 people died that night , and 3,000 more deaths were later attributed to the effects of the gas .
A half-million people are still seeking compensation .
Chief Minister Digvijay Singh , chief executive of Madhya Pradesh state , acknowledged that many people were arrested on trains heading toward the city .
But Singh could not confirm the number arrested and said he was not sure the arrests were related to the anniversary rally .
Tens of thousands of people travel without tickets on Indian railroads every day , but few are caught and arrested .
Khan led a march of 3,000 people from a city park to a square near the state legislature today .
Police barricaded the roads and red police vans patrolled the area .
The city administration banned the protesters from assembling around the legislature .
Khan said his group planned a bigger demonstration Saturday and called for a one-day strike in the city .
He said his main demand was clearing the logjam that has blocked compensation for the victims .
Bhopal is located 740 kilometers -LRB- 460 miles -RRB- south of New Delhi .
Melissa Selosia , one of the survivors of a ferry that sank Friday in Manila Bay , killing at least 34 people , escaped by remembering her seaman husband 's advice on what to do in an accident at sea .
The ferry Cebu City sank quickly after colliding in Manila Bay with a large freighter , the Singapore-registered Kota Suria , barely two hours after setting out for the southern Philippines before dawn .
At least 451 of the ferry 's approximately 600 passengers and crew members survived .
`` I was jolted by the crash and I woke up , '' she said .
`` Immediately , I grabbed a life jacket and made for the upper deck and then I jumped into the water . ''
`` I remembered what my husband told me -- to swim away from a sinking boat or else I would be sucked in by the water as it goes down . ''
She wept in a tearful reunion with her husband , her sister and a brother at coast guard headquarters in Manila .
They had heard radio reports of the accident just hours after they sent her off at Manila harbor .
Mrs. Selosia was on her way to Ozamis City on Mindanao Island , 775 kilometers -LRB- 485 miles -RRB- south of Manila , to join her four children for Christmas .
Her husband , Presencio , was to leave for Japan on Dec. 10 for ship duty .
Erwin Maravilla , one of the first survivors plucked from the sea by a navy patrol , was less fortunate .
His wife and two children were missing after they were sucked underwater as the ship slipped into the dark sea .
`` A piece of metal hit my arm and I lost hold of my children , '' Maravilla said .
Most of the survivors clambered onto the Kota Suria while it remained next to the ferry as it was listing .
The survivors said the Cebu City remained afloat for about 15 minutes before it rolled to the left and sank .
Many of the passengers from the lower decks were bathed in oil that gushed out of the engine room .
`` It was every man for himself , '' said Danny Dalugdog , a 24-year-old driver and bodyguard for a job recruiter in Manila .
In the confusion , he said he was separated from his wife , Liza , and his 3-month-old baby , Dennis .
`` I thought they were gone , '' he said .
But he found his wife on the freighter .
Then , as they transferred to a coast guard ship to return to Manila , a passenger called out that he found a baby boy .
`` It turned out to be my son , '' Dalugdog said .
Congressional clearance of a new world trade accord is expected to encourage ratification by other countries , enabling the mammoth export-boosting pact to enter into force as planned Jan. 1 .
Around the world , big and small nations alike are trying to rush the 22,000 page GATT agreement through national parliaments , often in low-key processes that contrast with the rocky ride through the U.S. legislature .
Nearly 40 countries , including the United States and most of southeast Asia , have ratified the 124-nation pact .
About 40 more -- including trade giants Japan , the European Union and Canada -- have indicated they will do so by the end of the year .
Four countries -- Switzerland , Liechtenstein , Cyprus and Poland -- have already told the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade that domestic politics will prevent them from ratifying the accord this year .
But this wo n't stop the pact from taking effect as scheduled on Jan. 1 .
All that is needed is for the all the big traders to come on board as founding members of the World Trade Organization -- GATT 's more powerful successor body that implement the accord .
The agreement is considered the most ambitious attempt ever to liberalize world trade and is expected to boost global income by dlrs 510 billion by the year 2005 .
Most governments object to at least some provisions because previously protected industries -- such as agriculture in Europe and textiles in the United States -- will suffer .
But all participating countries agreed not to upset the carefully crafted compromises with amendments .
The ratification situation in some of the main trading nations is as follows : -- European Union : Britain , Ireland , Greece , Germany amd Luxembourg have approved it .
The seven other EU members are meant to do so before foreign ministers meet Dec. 19-20 to approve the deal on behalf of the entire trade bloc .
France and Portugal still have some qualms , but the EU Commission , the union 's executive body , said there are no real obstacles .
An internal dispute between the Commission and member states over negotiating powers , which slowed national ratification , has been settled .
-- Japan : Japan 's powerful lower house has approved the deal , and passage through the upper house is virtually certain .
The government placated rice farmers , upset at potential competition from imports , with a six-year , 7.2 trillion yen -LRB- dlrs 74 billion -RRB- compensation package .
-- South Korea : The ruling Democratic Liberal party , which has a big majority , plans to push the accord through the national assembly next week .
Opposition politicians and farmers accuse the government of making too many concessions under U.S. pressure to open the rice market .
There have been frequent violent demonstrations against the accord .
-- India : There was strong opposition from both left - and right-wing parties , especially to provisions that give foreign multinationals stronger patent claims to Indian seeds and medicines .
The opposition , however , seems to have run out of steam and legislative passage appears more or less certain , though no date has been set .
-- Canada : Hopes to ratify the accord by the end of the year .
-- Mexico : Under former President Salinas de Gortari , who is one of three candidates for the directorship of the WTO , Mexico was one of the first countries to ratify the trade accord .
-- South America : Chile has ratified the accord and Argentina hopes to do so before the end of the year .
In Brazil , parliamentary passage is likely to be in February , not because the accord is contested but because of delays caused by this year 's election .
-- China : In order to join the WTO , Beijing first has to enter GATT .
Western concerns about China 's market reform programs and a possible flood of Chinese exports mean GATT membership talks are unlikely to finish by the end of the year .
A British aid worker in Rwanda who hid in the jungle for five days after his convoy ran into Zairean gunfire said Friday relief agencies needed better protection .
Don Reid , speaking to reporters at London 's Heathrow Airport , said he was driving in a six-truck convoy run by two charities , ActionAid and Assist , when they were stopped at a checkpoint near the Rutshuru refugee camp in Zaire .
`` The next thing I knew was there were two Zairean soldiers on the inside of my truck , '' said Reid , 43 , a former soldier in the British army .
`` Immediately , in a second , they started firing .
All hell broke loose ... I got out of the truck and just ran like hell . ''
He said the atmosphere in the camps before the shooting was particularly tense with rumors that a Zairean businessman had been robbed .
ActionAid said it would have to withdraw without better protection .
`` For weeks now we have been warning the British government and the Foreign Office that something like this was going to happen , '' said the charity 's international director , Nigel Twosee .
Reid said `` there should be some sort of protection for people on the ground . ''
Reid was found by other other aid workers about 10 miles -LRB- 15 kms -RRB- from where he disappeared .
On Wednesday , U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali proposed a 5,000-strong security force to police the refugee camps .
Japan 's economy grew at a healthy 3.7 percent annual rate in the July-September quarter , the government announced Friday .
It was the latest sign that the world 's second-largest economy may be getting back on track .
The 0.9 percent quarter-to-quarter growth in Japan 's gross domestic product , a broad indicator of what a country produces within its own borders , prompted the government 's Economic Planning Agency to predict a `` full-scale recovery '' by the end of the current fiscal year next March .
Private economists remained somewhat more cautious , however , saying the fast pace of expansion may not last and that structural drags on the economy , including mountains of bad debt , may hold Japan 's recovery to a slow pace .
Still , positive signs have been spreading .
Despite the record-high yen , many export-related companies , including electronics giants , have been reporting higher earnings for the first half of the fiscal year through September .
Also , a survey of 200 top firms released Friday by Japan 's leading economic newspaper , the Nikkei , predicted a 4.3 percent uptick in pretax profits at those firms for the current fiscal year , followed by an 18.1 percent increase in the next fiscal year .
But in another sign that the recovery may remain modest , the survey also showed that even after those two years of higher profits , earnings will still be just 60 percent of their peak in 1990 .
EPA Vice Minister Tsutomu Tanaka told reporters that consumer spending grew strongly during the latest quarter , thanks to a one-year income tax cut this June as well as a summer heat wave .
The record heat triggered a surge in spending on everything from beer to beach wear .
Tanaka said it 's still difficult to predict how strongly the Japanese economy will grow , noting that the yen 's strength and the pace of growth in spending by companies , known as capital outlays , must both be watched .
The strong growth in the July-September quarter followed a relatively mild 0.2 percent expansion in the April-June quarter , which works out to 0.7 percent growth at an annual pace .
The surprising 0.5 percent upturn in capital outlays was seen as a particularly good sign .
It was the first quarter-on-quarter growth in three years in corporate investment in plant and equipment , which accounts for roughly 20 percent of GDP .
Such spending but has been depressed in recent years as companies retreated from the heavy investments made during the late 1980s , putting a drag on economic growth .
But private analysts say it 's doubtful that the strong gains in consumer and corporate spending can be sustained during the current quarter .
The report definitely points to recovery , but `` let 's not get carried away , '' said Mineko Sasaki-Smith , senior economist with Morgan Stanley Japan Ltd.
The scenario of a gradual upturn still remains most likely , she said .
Another positive sign has been the steady improvement in business sentiment this year as measured in the closely watched `` tankan , '' a quarterly report issued by the central bank .
Many analysts are expecting another improvement in sentiment in the report due out Dec. 9 .
Pessimism continues to outweigh optimism , but the gap between them has been narrowing since March , when sentiment improved for the first time in 41\/2 years .
NATO foreign ministers sought Friday to reassure Russia that their plans for admitting former Warsaw Pact foes would n't create a new division in Europe .
But Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev maintained for a second day his strong opposition to a NATO plan for drawing up conditions for adding new members in the coming years .
He told a joint meeting of NATO and East European foreign ministers that Moscow could not develop close ties with the alliance until it spelled out its expansion plans , alliances sources said .
Kozyrev , they said , questioned whether the Western military alliance had changed from its Cold War days .
On Thursday , the Russian stunned NATO ministers by his last-minute refusal to agree to a special cooperation program with the alliance to protest the decision to prepare for a future expansion to the East .
NATO ministers sought to play down Kozyrev 's outburst .
`` We should n't make too much of yesterday 's events , '' U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher told CBS ' `` This Morning '' program .
`` -LRB- The -RRB- Russians will have a chance to analyze what we did ... I think they 'll find it to be responsible and deliberate . ''
Christopher met separately with Kozyrev for more than an hour Friday to discuss the dispute as well as the situation in Bosnia .
`` I think that will all get sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd .
He said ties between Moscow and NATO were `` too important to be lost . ''
Willy Claes , secretary-general of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization , opened the formal session by saying : `` The division of Europe has ended .
We have worked ... to ensure that it never returns . ''
Kozyrev 's comments cast a pall over the two-day meeting and over NATO 's attempt to draw its former Warsaw Pact enemies into its alliance .
However , some diplomats suggested he was playing to an audience back in Russia , where the government is contending with a strong nationalist opposition .
`` The Russians have their internal situation ... This is all a little bit more complicated , '' said German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel .
Other East European nations welcomed the NATO decision to start the process that could lead to them joining the alliance .
`` This is an important milestone on the road to an undivided Europe , '' said Poland 's foreign minister , Andrzej Olechowski .
He said NATO and former communist states should work to overcome Russian `` misinterpretation '' of NATO .
`` We do n't see -LRB- NATO -RRB- as a war machine , so we do n't see how anyone could be concerned , '' Olechowski told reporters .
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
The Russian outburst pushed , at least temporarily , the crisis in Bosnia off the ministers ' agenda .
Christopher , Hurd , Kinkel and Kozyrev were meeting later in the day with French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe to try to revive the peace process in Bosnia .
Christopher wants formal approval from the others for a new diplomatic initiative to try to draw the Bosnian Serbs into negotiations with the Muslims and Croats .
It calls for a cease-fire around Bihac , the northwestern Muslim enclave that Serbs are pummeling , a pledge to cease hostilities throughout the country for three to six months and then an international peace conference .
The lure for the Serbs , who control about 70 percent of Bosnia , is an opportunity to press their demand for cross-border political ties to Serbia .
Juppe and Hurd may fly to Belgrade this weekend to push the initiative .
The NATO allies , in trying to meet East Europeans demands for membership without upsetting a militarily powerful Russia , thought they had found a good formula .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , to bring former foes closer , but without membership .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to go further by ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
To overcome Russian objections to its eastward expansion , NATO had agreed to a special relationship with Moscow and insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc .
But Kozyrev was n't impressed .
`` If the strategy of NATO has changed , then that is something which requires further discussion , '' Kozyrev told grim-faced NATO ministers .
Activists called Friday for an end to violence against women in Asia , which they said ranges from harassment in the workplace to forced prostitution .
More than 100 people -- most of them Asian -- made the call at the end of a two-day Asian Women 's Tribunal aimed at promoting the human rights of a gender often discriminated against in this largely male-dominated region .
`` It is very easy for a Thai soldier or a Thai policeman to rape a woman , '' said Nimalka Fernando of Sri Lanka , the human rights coordinator of the Asia-Pacific Forum on Women , Law and Development .
`` So long as people have the attitude that women are seen as the property of men , violence will continue , '' added Salbiah Ahmad of Nepal , a member of the same group .
The meeting issued a declaration painting a grim picture of the treatment of women in Asia , with reports of migrant workers in a number of countries being sexually abused and Indonesian women being forced to undergo inspections to claim the menstrual leave provided them by law .
Indian Clarence J. Dias , of the International Center for Law in Development , said violence results from the insecurity of men and the pervasiveness of violence on television shows .
`` Everywhere , people are getting the message , ` You are weak if you do n't use violence , ' '' he said .
The meeting called for the criminalization of all acts leading to the sexual slavery of women , holding governments accountable for their failure to protect the human rights of women , and the development of social safety nets to protect the human rights of women .
`` Some violence will always be there , '' Dias added .
`` But hopefully it will change from the violence of the oppressor to the violence of the oppressed when women begin to fight back and begin to say that this must end . ''
An SS concentration camp commander serving a life term for killing 650 Jewish slave laborers was indicted Friday on 144 new charges of murder and abetting murder .
Josef Schwammberger , 82 , who sicked his dog on inmates and shot a rabbi for refusing to work on a Jewish holiday , was sentenced in May 1992 in the last major Nazi trial in Germany .
Prosecutor Kurt Schrimm said the new indictment stemmed from evidence that had surfaced since Schwammberger 's earlier trial , and included mass executions and the the murder of individual prisoners by Schwammberger himself .
During the earlier trial , Schwammberger admitted running the forced labor camps of Rozwadow , Mielec and Przemysl , all in Poland , between 1942 and 1944 .
But he denied killing anyone and said he could n't remember many of the events that were discussed .
Despite Schwammberger 's age , Schrimm said , the court has the duty to punish him for every crime it can prove .
Austrian-born Schwammberger fled to Argentina in 1948 , and was extradited in 1990 .
Earlier this year , Simon Wiesenthal , the Austrian Nazi-hunter , said that with the apparent death of SS commander Alois Brunner in Syria in 1992 , it was unlikely any other major Nazis would be captured or prosecuted .
A 13-year-old Japanese boy hanged himself in his back yard after being bullied by classmates into giving them more than 1 million yen -LRB- dlrs 10,000 -RRB- over three years , reports said Friday .
In a four-page suicide note , Kiyoteru Okouchi said a group of four classmates at Tobu Junior High School had been abusing him and extorting money from him for three years .
His body was found Sunday night hanging from a tree at his home in Nishio , about 270 kilometers -LRB- 170 miles -RRB- west of Tokyo , local police said .
Police would not say how much money Okouchi handed over after the other students repeatedly hit him and dunked his head in a river , but news reports said the total came to 1.1 million yen -LRB- dlrs 11,000 -RRB- .
He took the money from his parents ' house without permission and left a note addressed to his mother acknowledging the debt , Kyodo News Service said .
In a section of the note read on an evening news program , Okouchi detailed the way his classmates beat him and forced him to give them money , and said his happiest times were at home .
`` To my family , thank you so much , '' he wrote .
`` I 'm going away now . ''
Bullying remains frequent at Japan 's regimented schools .
Typical targets are children with outstanding grades , physical handicaps , foreign upbringing , or who otherwise do n't conform .
Some students choose suicide rather than continue to face bullying .
Last year , 113 students between the ages of 10 and 19 committed suicide for school-related problems such as bullying and severe punishments from teachers , according to a National Police Agency report .
About the same amount was reported in 1992 .
A total of 23,258 cases of bullying were reported in public schools in 1992 , up from 22,062 cases reported in 1991 , according to the most recent figures available from the Education Ministry .
`` For him , suicide was no doubt the most severe form of retaliation possible , '' said Susumu Abe , a noted critic on educational issues .
`` Japanese children are not given enough instruction about the constraints they should put on their actions toward others . ''
In Japan , children under age of 16 do not face criminal prosecution and are tried only in family courts .
