Lebanon 's prime minister , once hailed as a savior for a country ravaged by 15 years of civil war , has threatened to resign following charges of government corruption and union demands for pay raises .
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri told the president during a stormy Cabinet meeting Thursday night that he was quitting after more than two years in office .
He planned to sumbit a letter of resignation later Friday , aides said .
Hariri , a 51-year-old billionaire , has long been frustrated by opposition to his economic and reconstruction policies by several Cabinet ministers allied with neighboring Syria , the undisputed power in Lebanon .
His resignation would be a severe setback to efforts to rebuild Lebanon from the destruction of the 1975-90 civil war , which killed 150,000 people , maimed tens of thousands and caused an estimated dlrs 25 billion in damage .
During the night , Syrian and Lebanese officials to talk Hariri out of resigning .
President Elias Hrawi asked him to stay on in the national interest , Press Syndicate head Mohammed Baalbaki said after meeting the president Friday .
The crisis erupted after the government on Thursday night decreed a 20 percent pay raise for workers , which was promptly rejected by the General Federation of Labor Unions .
The federation , which represents 350,000 workers , insists on an 80 percent hike to keep pace with rampant inflation .
The unions staged a one-day warning strike Tuesday to press their demands and threatened to escalate their protests Dec. 5 .
The government has also been beset by corruption allegations , which prompted a heated exchange during Thursday night 's Cabinet session .
Housing Minister Mahmoud Abu Hamdan claimed Hariri , who has a fortune estimated at dlrs 3 billion , would benefit from a real estate deal in Beirut .
Hariri got angry , said he was quitting and stormed out of the Cabinet room , pursued by Hrawi and several ministers trying to talk him out of it .
Hariri was appointed prime minister Oct. 22 , 1992 .
Many welcomed his ascent to power as a harbinger of Lebanon 's return to regional prominence as a financial and trading hub .
But corruption charges have dogged his two-year tenure and his high-handed style has angered opponents .
Swedish divers on Friday planned to survey the wreck of the sunken ferry Estonia , a Baltic Sea tomb for an estimated 800 victims of the tragedy .
The divers , making the first human surveillance of the wreck , intend to scrutizine the condition of the ship , which is resting on its side in 56-84 meters -LRB- 180-280 feet -RRB- of water off Finland 's southwestern coast , the news agency TT reported .
`` The weather conditions are good .
The weather wo n't hinder the work , '' Swedish maritime administration spokesman Lars-Goran Bronow told TT .
The divers were to gather evidence to help authorities decide the feasibility of retrieving the bodies or taking some other action to preserve them .
More than 800 bodies are believed entombed in the wreck , although officials have said they may never know the exact number because of unreliable passenger lists .
Of the estimated 1,049 on the ferry when it sank , 137 survived , according to official figures published Friday by the Finnish police .
Only 94 bodies have been recovered .
Swedish authorities were focusing on three options , none of which included raising the entire wreck .
Divers could scour the wreck to retrieve the bodies they find , or could do that plus flip it over using cables to find more bodies .
The last alternative would be leaving all the bodies and filling the wreck with sand to `` bury '' the victims and protect the wreck from scavengers .
The divers are using a large , floating research platform called SEMI 1 .
The work was scheduled to begin Wednesday , but was delayed due to poor conditions .
The Swedish government , meanwhile , said Friday it has decided to give 3 million kronor -LRB- dlrs 417,000 -RRB- to organizations helping victims ' families , in many cases including orphans .
Engineers striking for higher pay forced the state-run RENFE railway to cancell at least half the trains on most routes Friday in the first of several walk-offs planned for December , RENFE officials said .
National routes were limited to one train per day while the more frequent suburban and regional train service was cut by between 50 and 75 percent .
Further one day strikes are called for the 11th , 22nd , 23rd and 30th of December .
The engineers ' union is demanding a 20 percent wage hike from RENFE , the loss-making public sector railway undergoing permanent restructuring .
RENFE said the strike was peaceful but police in Madrid removed picketers who tried to prevent the departure of a Seville-bound high-speed train .
The railway called on strikers to return to join in negotiations over a labor agreement intended to cover all of RENFE 's workforce .
Algerian distance runner Noureddine Morceli and U.S. heptathlete Jackie Joyner-Kersee were named athletes of the year Friday by the International Athletic Foundation .
Morceli , 24 , set a new world record in the 3,000 meters , was unbeaten in the mile and 1,500 meters and won the men 's IAAF Mobil Grand Prix overall title this season .
Morceli received 3,203 points in voting by 1,500 track and field experts from around the world .
Cuban high jumper Javier Sotomayor , who won the Grand Prix and Goodwill Games titles , finished second with 2,721 points .
Ukrainian pole vaulter Sergei Bubka , who set his 17th outdoor world record , was third with 1,982 .
Joyner-Kersee , the reigning Olympic champion and world record-holder in the heptathlon , topped the women 's voting with 3,067 points .
In 1994 , she won the women 's overall Grand Prix title , took gold in the heptathlon at the Goodwill Games and twice jumped 7.49 meters -LRB- 24 feet , 7 inches -RRB- , matching the second-best mark in history and setting an American record .
Finishing second was Russian sprinter Irina Privalova with 2,356 points , and Ireland 's distance runner Sonia O'Sullivan was third with 2,320 .
The awards were presented at the annual IAF gala by Prince Albert of Monaco and Primo Nebiolo , president of the International Amateur Athletic Federation -LRB- IAAF -RRB- .
Roman Catholic authorities have reached an out of court settlement with a man who was sexually molested by a priest when he was an altar boy , news reports said Friday .
The report was the latest in a rash of sexual abuse cases involving priests in this 97 percent Catholic country .
Church officials and Padraic Ferry , a Dublin attorney who was understood to be involved in the settlement negotiations , refused to comment .
The Connacht Tribune , published in Galway in western Ireland , said the settlement was more than 75,000 Irish pounds -LRB- dlrs 107,250 -RRB- and that the victim , now in his twenties , was 11 years old when he was first assaulted .
The Irish Times of Dublin said the payment was the responsibility of the local bishop .
The Connacht Tribune said the priest had been convicted of sexual assault in 1993 and was sentenced to 10 years in prison , with the final five years suspended if he entered a rehabilitation program .
The judge issued an order forbidding identification of the parish and diocese involved .
The Irish Independent of Dublin reported that the victim served the priest as an altar boy , and that one of the assaults took place on a pilgrimage to Lourdes , France in 1990 .
Cardinal Cahal Daly , the primate of Ireland 's Catholic Church , said in a radio interview on Tuesday that his church had been `` humbled '' by the sexual scandals .
Daly said more cases would surface , `` because we are dealing now with cases going back 10 , maybe 15 , 20 years .
But they should be reported and they should be dealt with . ''
The case of the Rev. Brendan Smyth , 67 , who was convicted 17 counts of indecently assaulting five girls and two boys in Belfast , precipitated the collapse of Ireland 's coalition government last month .
The Labor Party , junior partner in the coalition , was angered by the attorney general 's inaction on an application for the priest 's extradition to Northern Ireland .
Police are investigating allegations that a priest now living in the Irish republic molested a girl in Londonderry , Northern Ireland , five years ago .
The Irish Times reported Tuesday that police are also investigating allegations that a religious brother sexually abused a 50-year-old mentally ill woman at a home in County Cork in southern Ireland .
Besides Smyth , four other Catholic clerics appeared in court this year on molestation charges : a Galway priest and former school principal who pleaded guilty to sexually assaulting an 18-year-old male hitchhiker ; a Servite brother from Northern Ireland who admitted molesting three 11-year-old girls ; a Belfast priest charged with molesting nine boys aged 9 to 15 ; a brother appealing his 18-year sentence for raping six schoolboys in western Ireland .
Searchers recovered 34 bodies from a ferry that sank before dawn Friday with more than 600 people on board after colliding with a Singapore-registered freighter .
Frogmen said more bodies were trapped inside the ship .
Lt. Comdr. Amado Samante , the coast guard spokesman , said at least 451 people on the 2,452-ton Cebu City survived the collision with the 12,500-ton Kota Suria , which is five times bigger , as the ferry was about to sail out of Manila Bay .
The search for the remaining passengers was called off late in the day because of darkness and was to resume Saturday morning .
`` There were more bodies inside the cabins , '' said Seaman Angel Espidido , one of 27 coast guard divers who joined navy frogmen in recovering bodies trapped inside the ferry .
Espidido said he could see the bodies through portholes but the divers were unable to open the doors .
`` Tomorrow we will go back to unlock them , '' he added .
Seaman Hermogenes Guilaran said he recovered the bodies of two elderly women and a boy who were trapped at a railing on the side of the ferry which was lying under 90 feet -LRB- 27 meters -RRB- of water .
William Lines , the ferry operator , said the ship was carrying 608 people .
There was no immediate official report on the cause of the accident , but the ferry 's owner claimed it had been rammed by the Kota Suria .
Eugene Espedido , a vice president of the company , said it was preparing a request for the coast guard to detain the freighter and its crew .
Jacob Cabatuan , a crewman on the ferry , said the Kota Suria 's bow crashed into the Cebu City , destroying the bridge and ripping a one-meter -LRB- three-foot -RRB- hole in the lower deck .
He said ship captain Wesceslao Lampong and several other officers were pinned on the bridge .
The Kota Suria , with a crew of 30 , had its bow badly dented but joined the rescue effort , plucking 230 of those saved .
President Fidel Ramos ordered an investigation into the cause of the accident , which occurred in calm seas under clear night skies .
Samante said about 50 coast guard , navy and commercial sea vessels were involved in the search effort .
William Lines said the Cebu City had a capacity of 800 passengers .
