In the harshest Dutch move yet to repulse a tidal wave of refugees , Parliament Friday authorized the government to automatically bar all asylum seekers arriving overland .
The measure is aimed at stemming a flow of asylum seekers that has severely strained government resources and led to a rightist resurgence in May 's national elections .
`` We do n't want to send people back to face danger , '' said spokesman Tom van der Maas for the right-wing Liberals , one of the three ruling coalition partners .
`` But we need to redirect this inflow of people .
It 's an effort to spread the burden throughout Europe . ''
`` This is an ugly law , '' countered Fronnie Biesma , spokesman for the Dutch Refugee Council .
`` We are just transferring the responsibility to other countries . ''
The legislation takes direct aim at the Netherlands ' international reputation as a safe haven for the persecuted , a label that this year will draw an estimated 55,000 asylum seekers to this nation of 15 million .
The new law would bar any asylum seekers who had traveled through so-called `` safe third countries '' where they could have applied for asylum before reaching the Netherlands .
Virtually assured of becoming law , the legal stratagem is aimed primarily at the `` economic migrants '' who shuttle around Europe in search of the best residency and benefits deal .
In practice , the law will bar the vast majority of asylum seekers , who usually arrive overland by bus , car or train from neighboring Germany or Belgium .
Relatively few come by airplane or ship .
The new law would bar people like 26-year-old Babak Alighorian who left his family back in Iran and applied for political asylum here in April 1993 .
`` This is not good , '' said Alighorian , who arrived in the Netherlands after traveling through Turkey , Bulgaria , Romania , Hungary , Austria , and Germany by car and by bus .
Under the new measure , Alighorian would have been turned back to Germany .
Instead he got a one-year residency permit .
While rejected asylum seekers will still have the right of appeal in civil courts , it is unclear how long that would take and whether the government would support them pending a ruling .
Friday 's lower house passage virtually guarantees upper house approval by early next year .
A list of safe countries will be drawn up by the Justice Ministry once the measure becomes law .
The Dutch measure is a direct response to a similar law passed by the German government last year .
`` Since Germany approved the return of refugees to the safe third country , the number of asylum seekers there has decreased tremendously , while in the Netherlands the number has significantly increased , '' the Justice Ministry said in a statement .
Before the Dutch government began clamping down on asylum applicants in recent years , the country had one of Europe 's most liberal asylum policies and a generous benefit package to match .
But with a new get-tough policy in place since last year , new `` flying squads '' of immigration officers are now policing the border and two asylum centers opened near the German and Belgian borders this fall to turn away bogus applicants .
As of October , the Justice Ministry has received 44,492 asylum applications this year , a rise of more than 16,500 over the same period in 1993 .
The cost to shelter and feed them will be about 1.6 billion guilders -LRB- dlrs 909 million -RRB- this year , according to the National Center for Asylum Seekers .
Yasser Arafat and an Islamic leader formed a committee Friday to work out differences and prevent violence .
Both hailed it as a start to ending two weeks of tension following bloody clashes in the Gaza Strip .
Israel has demanded that Arafat crack down on the Islamic Resistance Movement , or Hamas , which has claimed responsibility for attacks that have killed 32 Israelis since early October .
Hamas and the more radical Islamic Jihad oppose the peace accord that Arafat signed with the Israelis .
Clashes between Muslim militants and PLO police left 15 people dead on Nov. 18 .
But Arafat can not afford to ignore the popular support for the militant groups , especially among the poor , and is trying to persuade them to participate in his self-rule government .
Arafat advisor Ahmed Tibi said Friday 's meeting with Hamas leader Mahmoud Zahar was the start of a `` real dialogue between the sides . ''
`` It was a warm and fruitful meeting between myself and my brother and what we have agreed on is good for both sides , '' Zahar told The Associated Press .
Tibi said the nine-member committee , which includes Hamas and PLO officials as well as two Israeli Arabs , would meet Saturday .
Caterpillar Inc. has appointed a new independent dealership for the Shanghai area , the first such appointment since the company announced plans earlier to expand its presence in China .
The new dealership , Lei Shing Hong Machinery Ltd. , will be headed by C.K. Lau , principal owner of the dealership 's holding company , Hong Kong-based Lei Shing Hong Ltd. , Caterpillar said in a statement Friday .
The sales and service agreement , signed Friday , is effective April 1 .
The new dealership will be based in Kunshan , outside Shanghai , and will cover three east-central provinces -- Jiangsu , Anhui and Zhejiang .
Chinese customers have been served by one independent dealer , China Engineers Ltd. , which covers three southern provinces , and one wholly owned dealership , Caterpillar China Ltd.
Both are based in Hong Kong .
Caterpillar has been selling its heavy equipment to China since 1975 .
It has entered 12 technology transfer agreements and has formed two manufacturing joint ventures in China .
NATO foreign ministers sought Friday to reassure Russia that their plans for admitting former Warsaw Pact foes would n't create a new division in Europe .
But Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev maintained for a second day his strong opposition to a NATO plan for drawing up conditions for adding new members in the coming years .
He told a joint meeting of NATO and East European foreign ministers that Moscow could not develop close ties with the alliance until it spelled out its expansion plans , alliances sources said .
Kozyrev , they said , questioned whether the Western military alliance had changed from its Cold War days .
On Thursday , the Russian stunned NATO ministers by his last-minute refusal to agree to a special cooperation program with the alliance to protest the decision to prepare for a future expansion to the East .
NATO ministers sought to play down Kozyrev 's outburst .
`` We should n't make too much of yesterday 's events , '' U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher told CBS ' `` This Morning '' program .
`` -LRB- The -RRB- Russians will have a chance to analyze what we did ... I think they 'll find it to be responsible and deliberate . ''
Christopher met separately with Kozyrev for more than an hour Friday to discuss the dispute as well as the situation in Bosnia .
`` I think that will all get sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd .
He said ties between Moscow and NATO were `` too important to be lost . ''
Willy Claes , secretary-general of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization , opened the formal session by saying : `` The division of Europe has ended .
We have worked ... to ensure that it never returns . ''
Kozyrev 's comments cast a pall over the two-day meeting and over NATO 's attempt to draw its former Warsaw Pact enemies into its alliance .
However , some diplomats suggested he was playing to an audience back in Russia , where the government is contending with a strong nationalist opposition .
`` The Russians have their internal situation ... This is all a little bit more complicated , '' said German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel .
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would go with it .
Christopher , Hurd , Kinkel and Kozyrev were meeting later in the day with French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe to try to revive the peace process in Bosnia .
Juppe and Hurd may fly to Belgrade this weekend to push the initiative .
On Thursday , the allies decided to conduct a 12-month study of the terms and conditions for expanding the Western military alliance .
To overcome Russian objections to its eastward expansion , NATO had agreed to a special relationship with Moscow and insisted they had no intention of forming a hostile bloc .
It took Joe Montana 's heroics for Kansas City to beat Denver in their first meeting .
This time , Montana is one of many injured Chiefs , and the Broncos are on the upswing .
That puts Chiefs reserve quarterback Steve Bono on the spot Sunday when the Broncos visit Kansas City in the 13th round of the U.S. National Football League season , and Denver quarterback John Elway renews his special relationship with Chiefs coach Marty Schottenheimer .
Denver -LRB- 6-6 -RRB- comes in with playoff hopes still alive after a dismal 0-4 start .
