You follow your philosophy , and my philosophy is you do less so you do it better . ''
Like the Kansas City-Denver matchup , this weekend features mostly intradivisional games , such as Buffalo at Miami and New York at New England in the AFC East Division ; Pittsburgh at Cincinnati in the AFC Central ; Los Angeles at San Diego in the other AFC West matchup , which will be Monday night ; Atlanta at San Francisco and New Orleans at Los Angeles in the NFC West ; Green Bay at Detroit in the NFC Central ; and Dallas at Philadelphia in the NFC East .
Also , Arizona visits Houston , the New York Giants are at Cleveland , Indianapolis travels to Seattle and Washington goes to Tampa Bay .
The long weekend started Thursday night when Minnesota pulled into a tie for first in the NFC Central with a 33-27 overtime victory over Chicago .
Cris Carter scored on a 65-yard touchdown pass from Warren Moon two plays after Kevin Butler missed a potential game-winning field goal from 40 yards .
Denver decided after it fell to a 1-5 record to become more aggressive defensively .
The Chiefs noticed the Broncos have won three in a row by blitzing more .
`` The old adage is if you blitz and you do it efficiently , you will have success , '' Schottenheimer said .
`` If you do n't do it efficiently , you end up getting burned .
Right now , they are doing it very effectively . ''
Elway has recovered from some early season mistakes -- three interceptions for touchdowns -- to become his old self .
He passed for 382 yards two weeks ago , and Denver had just enough last week at home to beat Cincinnati in a game played in a driving wind and a minus-2 wind chill .
`` The goal was to get to .500 and dig ourselves out of the hole , '' Elway said .
`` It seemed like the harder we tried , the worse it got .
At 0-4 , we wanted to start brand new , clean the slate .
At 0-4 , you 're not sure you 're ever going to win a game . ''
The Chiefs acquired Bono for , as Schottenheimer put it , `` a winning performance , '' and he will get his chance .
Bono is eager for the start .
`` I ca n't worry about what rust there is , '' he said .
`` I 'm not expecting a week of practice will shake it off .
I just hope to have a good week of practice and hope we play well on Sunday . ''
San Diego has been in front of the AFC West all year and has an excellent chance to take full control by beating the Raiders .
San Diego can clinch the division with a win over the Raiders and a Kansas City loss to Denver .
The Chargers can clinch a playoff berth with a win over the Raiders and a Kansas City win or tie against Denver and either a Buffalo loss or tie at Miami or a New York Jets loss or tie at New England .
Russian lawmakers who came to Chechnya to negotiate an end to a standoff with Moscow pointed fingers at their own government Friday , saying jets attacking the tiny republic are clearly Russian .
President Boris Yeltsin 's government has denied providiny any military support to the Chechen rebels seeking to topple Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , even as the rebel offensive has escalated from small arms fire to missiles and bombs .
Defense Minister Pavel Grachev says mercenaries are fighting on both sides .
Dudayev , however , who declared independence for his Caucasus Mountain republic in 1991 , flatly accuses Moscow of leading and arming the opposition .
Meanwhile , air raids on the outskirts of Grozny , the Chechen capital , continued Friday for a fourth day .
`` It is clear that these planes are not English or French but Russian , '' said Ella Pamfilova , a member of parliament and Yeltsin 's former social welfare minister .
`` This is against the law . ''
Other members of the four-person parliamentary delegation , which has met briefly with Dudayev , also called for an end to the air strikes , warning the conflict could spiral out of control .
The group is specifically trying to negotiate the release of about 70 Russians -- including , allegedly , some Army soldiers and officers -- who were captured in the fighting in Chechnya , a mostly Muslim republic in southern Russia .
Dudayev at first threatened to kill the prisoners , but later said they would be tried in court .
Since the rebels ' air offensive began last week , thousands of people have fled Grozny , a city of 300,000 .
Chechen officials said there was another round of air raids early Friday east of Grozny , including one at Shali , home to a tank regiment .
On Thursday , a small airfield near Grozny was hit and four people died in a missile attack at Katayama , about 20 kilometers -LRB- 12 miles -RRB- from Grozny , where Dudayev lives .
Dudayev said his home was bombed .
An old bus also was hit by shrapnel , and its floor was covered with sawdust Friday to soak up blood .
`` We saw two planes fly over this morning , '' the commander of the airfield , Biali Chimayev , said .
`` We 're expecting another attack . ''
The raids have destroyed a number of aircraft at civilian and military airports .
Moscow does not recognize the independence of Chechnya , which became part of the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
Yeltsin threatened on Tuesday to send in troops unless the fighting had stopped by Thursday , but when the deadline expired he softened his stance , saying Chechen fighters would be given amnesty if they put down their weapons by Dec. 15 .
Still , there were media reports of Russian troop buildups near the border .
`` Chauvinist forces in Russian are pushing President Yeltsin to act , saying he can not control ` little ' Chechnya , '' warned Vladimir Lysenko , a member of the parliamentary delegation .
Although ultranationalists , like the flamboyant Vladimir Zhirinovsky , constantly lament the loss of Moscow 's empire , most Russians appear ready to let the Chechens go their own way .
More than 74 percent of 3,250 people questioned in a new poll said Russia should recognize Chechnya 's independence .
Only 5.5 percent opposed it and 20.3 percent had no opinion .
The poll , released Thursday by the International Opinion Research Center , had a 1 percent margin of error .
Although Chechens are at odds , they are united in their distrust of Russia .
Lysenko warned that the conflict is endangering the lives of as many as 150,000 ethnic Russians in Chechnya .
In Copenhagen , a Russian journalist said Friday he received a fax from a group threatening Russians abroad if Moscow does not recognize Chechnya 's independence .
The threat was signed `` K.K.K.O. 130 .
year , '' which Danish police said might stand for the North Caucasian Liberation Army .
Police in Copenhagen said they heard the group has been active in other countries .
