The Department of Foreign Affairs said Friday two Filipinos have been arrested in Saipan on charges of trying to smuggle drugs into the island .
The foreign office , quoting a report from the Philippine consulate in Saipan , identified those arrested as construction businessman Ignacio Agbanlog and his employee , Fernando Garzon .
Garzon was arrested shortly after arriving Nov. 24 in Saipan on a flight from Manila , the foreign office said .
It said customs police seized 300 grams -LRB- 10 ounces -RRB- of crystal methamphetamine hydrochloride , called `` ice '' in Saipan and `` shabu '' in Manila .
Agbanlog was arrested in his office in San Vicente in Saipan the following day , it said .
The report did not say why Agbanlog was arrested .
The Superior Court of Saipan has set dlrs 340,000 bail for each of the two .
A hearing has been set sometime this month , the report said .
A former SS concentration camp commander serving a life term for killing 650 Jewish slave laborers was indicted Friday on 144 new charges of murder and abetting murder .
Josef Schwammberger , 82 , who sicked his dog on inmates and shot a rabbi for refusing to work on a Jewish holiday , was sentenced in May 1992 in the last major Nazi trial in Germany .
Prosecutor Kurt Schrimm said the new indictment stemmed from evidence that surfaced during Schwammberger 's earlier trial but could n't be introduced because it was n't included in the request for Schwammberger 's 1990 extradition from Argentina , where he fled in 1948 .
Schwammberger is accused of ordering mass executions and of murdering individual prisoners himself , Schrimm said .
During the earlier trial , Schwammberger admitted running the forced labor camps of Rozwadow , Mielec and Przemysl , all in Poland , between 1942 and 1944 .
But he denied killing anyone and said he could n't remember many of the events that were discussed .
Despite Schwammberger 's age , Schrimm said , the court has the duty to punish him for every crime it can prove .
It could take six months for the judge to examine the charges and the defense 's likely objection to a new trial .
Earlier this year , Simon Wiesenthal , the Austrian Nazi-hunter , said that with the apparent death of SS commander Alois Brunner in Syria in 1992 , it was unlikely any other major Nazis would be captured or prosecuted .
The trial of three British soldiers accused of killing a Danish woman bogged down in legal complications Friday , with defense attorneys demanding the case be thrown out .
The trial was adjourned until Tuesday .
There have been a string of adjournments since the men were arrested Sept. 13 for slaying Louise Jensen , a 23-year-old tour guide from Hirthshals , northern Denmark , after kidnapping her .
Friday 's move followed a ruling by the three-judge court in this south coast resort city that it was competent to hear arguments on a defense motion for dismissal .
The defense claims the confiscation of confidential notes the men had written for their lawyers by a guard in Nicosia 's Central prison , the only one on the east Mediterranean island , was illegal .
State prosecutor Petros Clerides asked for time to consult the attorney general and stressed that such a legal point has never been raised in Cyprus before .
That opened the possibility the case will be referred to the Supreme Court , the republic 's highest court .
That could delay the trial for weeks .
The soldiers are privates Alan Ford , 26 , of Birmingham ; Justin Fowler , 26 , of Falmouth , Cornwall ; and Jeff Parnell , 23 , of Oldbury , West Midlands .
They have yet to enter their pleas on charges of manslaughter .
The original charge of premeditated murder was reduced last month because the prosecution decided it might not be able to prove the men had planned to kill Jensen before they abducted her .
Police said the Britons have admitted kidnapping and killing Jensen in the tourist resort of Ayia Napa Sept. 13 .
Her battered body was found in a shallow grave two days later .
The soldiers were arrested at a police roadblock with bloodstains on their clothes and a blood-covered shovel in their car a few hours after Jensen 's Cypriot boyfriend reported her abduction .
All three serve with the Royal Greenjackets Regiments at the British Sovereign Base of Dhekelia on the island 's south coast .
The wandering skull of a 14th century religious reformer has found its way home to St. Lebuinus Church , courtesy of an anonymous do-gooder .
Geert Groote died of the Black Plague in 1384 , and his remains were interred in the church to be venerated by the faithful .
After six centuries , a skull was all that was left of the penitential preacher known to church historians as Gerardus Magnus .
And even that disappeared 14 years ago , stolen from the church 's reliquary .
Thursday church caretaker Nico Geelen found a box pushed inside the church 's door marked `` Fragile , But Not Hazardous . ''
It contained the skull and a small piece of stone carved with the Latin words meaning `` Here is the head of a deacon and a very holy man . ''
`` I always had the feeling it would come back one day , '' said Geelen , adding that the skull 's authenticity was verified through photos .
Groote made a rebellious name for himself preaching against corruption in the medieval Roman Catholic Church .
One of Deventer 's most famous sons , Groote was educated in Paris but rejected the priesthood by claiming he was not holy enough .
He died at 44 when the Black Death came to Deventer .
Instead of being hidden away , Groote 's skull will now go to the city museum .
Geelen said he did n't think Groote would be too concerned where it ends up , `` so long as his ideas survive . ''
Wayne Gretzky says the difficult part of a six-city Scandinavian tour for his team of locked-out National Hockey League players is done , though the games have n't even started .
`` This is my first and last time to organize a tour , '' Gretzky said Thursday before his squad lost to the International Hockey League 's Detroit Vipers 4-3 .
`` If somebody else wants to put one together , I 'll go but this has been a hell of a lot of work . ''
Among his tasks were finding a plane that could return to North America on moment 's notice should the NHL players and owners strike a deal , getting European teams to agree to play them and finding available dates , arenas and practice times .
The 19 locked out NHLers start the tour on Saturday against the Finnish team Jokerit in Helsinki , followed by games in Tampere , Finland ; Oslo , Norway and Stockholm , Goteborg , Sweden .
The trip ends on Dec. 12 in Malmo , Sweden .
All six dates were sold out as of Thursday .
Peter Karrie , one of the most anonymous celebrities in the world of stage , says his role as the masked phantom in the mega-musical `` The Phantom of the Opera '' fills every moment of his waking hours .
`` Once you have rehearsed the role and adopted it , he is with you all the time , ' said Karrie , the 48-year-old tenor who has portrayed the popular Andrew Lloyd Webber character for the last three years in London and Toronto .
He has appeared more than 1,000 times on stage as the phantom in the award-winning production , which has garnered dlrs 1 billion since it first opened in London 's West End in 1986 .
`` When you wake up in the morning , when you go out shopping , you are thinking about it all the time , '' Karrie , a native of Wales , told Singapore reporters Friday .
He spoke by video-telephone from Toronto where he is currently performing as the phantom .
The 45-minute news conference via satellite was called to announce that Karrie would also be playing the love-stricken phantom when the dlrs 12 million musical opens in Singapore in February .
Although he dominates the nearly three-hour show , Karrie appears in a white mask , wig and cape .
That 's why most autograph seekers are unable to recognize him even when he walks into the dress circle , Karrie said .
`` It would be nice to be recognized sometimes , '' said Karrie .
`` The Phantom of the Opera , '' which opened in Broadway in 1988 and in Toronto in September 1989 , is based on a French novel about a hideously deformed phantom who lurks beneath the stage of the Paris Opera House .
He falls in love with a young soprano and devotes himself to creating a new star for the opera .
The Singapore production will be directed by Harold Prince , winner of 19 Tony awards .
Karrie , when asked what goes into his role , said : `` Some Welsh passion . ''
Asked how he keeps fit for the physically demanding role , Karrie said he uses `` ginseng , '' a Chinese herbal tonic .
`` It is great .
We 've got it over here .
I take some ginseng every day , '' he said with a wink and thumbs-up .
`` I also do some workout in the gym .
And drink lots of water . ''
Karrie , who starred as the phantom for 18 months in the West End , has previously portrayed the heroic lead Jean Valijean in `` Les Miserables , '' Che in `` Evita , '' the American in `` Chess '' and Judas in `` Jesus Christ Superstar . ''
Phantom 's staging in Singapore is also an attempt by local authorities to show the city-state as not just a moneymaking center of commerce but a growing cultural and performing arts hub in the region .
Earlier this year , the popular Broadway production `` Cats '' was performed here following a production of `` Les Miserables . ''
Sol Kerzner , creator of the Sun City gambling complex , may face charges of bribery and corruption dating back eight years , according to news reports Friday .
Justice Ministry attorney Christo Nel said an investigation into a bribe Kerzner offered officials in the former Transkei black homeland in 1986 had been reopened and could result in formal charges .
Kerzner has admitted offering the bribe of 2 million rand -LRB- dlrs 909,000 at the exchange rate at the time -RRB- in return for exclusive gambling rights in the Transkei , one of four homelands granted independence under the apartheid era plan to strip blacks of South African citizenship .
Although no other countries ever recognized the homelands ' sovereignty , their nominal independence allowed Kerzner to build a string of lavish casinos and resorts without violating South African laws against gambling .
After admitting the bribe at a South African judicial inquest in 1989 , he avoided prosecution by staying out of the Transkei .
Former Transkei prime minister George Matanzima was imprisoned in the Transkei for accepting the bribe .
The nation 's first all-race election in April ended apartheid and scrapped the homeland system , with the regions becoming part of South Africa again .
Nel , who was attorney general in the Transkei , said it would take up to six months to complete the investigation and decide if enough of a case existed to press charges .
Kerzner has built a multibillion rand -LRB- dollar -RRB- empire from his hotel and gambling resorts in South Africa and Europe , and plans to open similar complexes in the Bahamas and the United States .
One news report said Kerzner 's ties with top officials of the new African National Congress-led government would allow him to avoid prosecution .
President Nelson Mandela 's office issued a statement in response , denying any possibility of interference with the judicial process .
U.S. congressional clearance of a new world trade accord is expected to encourage ratification by other countries , allowing the mammoth export-boosting pact to take effect as planned on Jan. 1 .
Large and small nations alike are trying to rush the 22,000-page GATT agreement through national parliaments , often in low-key processes compared to the rocky ride through Congress .
Nearly 40 countries , including the United States , have now ratified the 124-nation agreement .
About 40 more -- including Japan , the European Union and Canada -- have said they will do so by year 's end .
The head of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade , Peter Sutherland , said Friday that U.S. passage was a `` triumph '' that will help make the world a more prosperous place .
`` This is a day for particular celebration , '' GATT Director-General Peter Sutherland told journalists .
`` The successful culmination of this debate proved that common sense still works . ''
The U.S. Senate approved the GATT treaty by 76-24 votes late Thursday -- a much bigger margin than expected .
The House of Representatives cleared the deal earlier in the week .
Congressional approval , uncertain for weeks , was deemed crucial for the the World Trade Organization to take effect on Jan. 1 .
The WTO will implement the new accord and have more powers than GATT to settle trade disputes .
`` I warmly welcome the vote by the U.S. Senate , '' said European Union Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan , Europe 's chief negotiator in the talks .
He said the 12-nation bloc would complete the approval process by Dec. 20 .
In Japan , Trade Minister Rytaro Hashimoto said U.S. ratification of the deal would encourage other countries to follow suit .
Japan 's powerful lower house of parliament passed the accord early Friday and it will now move to the upper house .
This view was echoed by Hong Kong 's Director-General of Trade , Tony Miller .
`` The world looks to the United States for leadership in promoting free trade under the multilateral regime , '' Miller said .
In Canberra , Australian Trade Minister Bob McMullan said the U.S. result was `` great news for Australia and the world economy generally . ''
Sutherland said he expected about 100 of GATT 's 124 member nations to ratify the trade accord by the end of the year .
The agreement is considered the most ambitious attempt ever to knock down barriers to free world trade .
The pact is expected to boost global income by dlrs 510 billion by the year 2005 .
It reduces customs duties on hundreds of thousands of products , liberalizes trade in service industries , protects against copyright theft and patent abuse and cuts protection of farm goods and textiles .
`` We will have a rules-based system that allows for the development of the world economy and provides an assurance of security , prosperity and reduction of tensions , '' Sutherland said .
A German man was arrested Friday on charges of having sex with young boys and filming them in pornographic videos he sold abroad , police said .
Nierenz Bernd Karl-Heinz , of Eberswacde , Germany , refused to open the door when police came to his apartment on a tip from neighbors , police said .
They used a key to open the door and said they found four boys -- age 12 and 13 -- hiding in their underpants in the bathroom .
Police reported that the boys said they had sex with Heinz .
Police seized four videos of young Thai boys having sex and a large stack of photographs of them posing nude , police Maj. Nawin Klamsang said in an interview .
Nawin said it was unclear how long Heinz had been living in Thailand but noted that he spoke fluent Thai .
Other officers said Heinz had lured the boys to his home with offers to pay them 20 baht -LRB- 80 cents -RRB- and let them play video games .
If they came again , the boys were offered 100 baht -LRB- dlrs 4 -RRB- to pose nude for a still camera , they said .
And , on subsequent visits , they were paid 100 baht -LRB- dlrs 4 -RRB- to act in pornographic videos , police said .
Heinz is to appear in court within the month .
A substantially bigger-than-expected gain in construction employment helped force the U.S. unemployment rate down to the lowest level in four years .
The Labor Department said a seasonally adjusted 350,000 new workers were added to the nation 's nonfarm payrolls , pushing the unemployment rate to 5.6 percent from 5.8 percent in October .
That is the lowest level since August 1990 .
The jobless rate has been declining all year , dropping 1.1 percent since January .
The nation 's nonfarm payrolls have increased by 1.4 million people this year .
The report suggests the economy is still growing at a robust pace and employment growth remains strong .
However , the government 's chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity pointed in the other direction , falling in October for the first time in 15 months .
The Index of Leading Economic Indicators slipped 0.1 percent in October .
In advance of the unemployment report , most economists were expecting the unemployment rate to remain at 5.8 percent and nonfarm payrolls to increase by about 250,000 workers .
Even the most optimistic analysts were expecting an increase no bigger than 280,000 jobs .
Strong employment growth this year was one of the factors that prompted the central bank to raise short-term interest rates last month for a sixth time this year .
Last month , the central bank raised key rates three-quarters of a percentage point , the largest increase in 13 years .
The large number of new hires was boosted by unexpectedly robust growth in construction employment .
The Labor Department said 71,000 jobs were added to construction industry payrolls in November .
Manufacturing employment also was robust , jumping 51,000 after increases of just over 18,000 in the previous three months .
Gains were recorded in manufacture of durable goods , including lumber , fabricated metals , industrial machinery and electronic equipment .
As expected , most of the new hires were in service industries , including 25,000 in retail trade and a substantial 26,000 increase in the number of government workers .
Some 76,000 Rwandans already in Zaire poured into internationally run refugee camps this week under orders from Zairean police forces after clashes with the local population , the U.N. refugee agency said Friday .
Sylvana Foa , spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees , said the agency was surprised by the numbers of Rwandans outside the camps , which she said were `` already badly overloaded . ''
There are already an estimated 850,000 Rwandans in the camps on the border of Rwanda and Zaire .
The Rwandans , mostly Hutu , fled their country last summer following the takeover of the government by the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front .
Zairean forces ordered the Rwandans into the camps following a clash last week in a village near Goma , Zaire , that left 24 refugees and three Zaireans dead and 77 wounded .
Foa said the violence appeared to have started because of stealing from tradesmen .
As a result of the Zairean order , 45,000 refugees streamed into Kitale camp , 18,000 into Kibumba camp , and 13,000 into Kahindo camp .
Foa said relief workers have begun looking for a site for a new camp to help ease the overcrowding .
Australia opened the World Series one-day cricket campaign in unimpressive fashion Friday with a two-wicket victory over Zimbabwe at the WACA Ground .
Chasing 166-9 to win , Australia limped home after 47.2 overs , losing 4-8 in the closing overs with part-time Zimbabwean spinner Grant Flower picking up three wickets to ensure a tight finish .
Mark Waugh , who strained a groin muscle while bowling his first and only over in the Zimbabwe innings , came in at No. 9 with Michael Slater as a runner and scored an unbeaten six .
Mark Taylor and Slater got the home side off to an ideal start with an opening partnership of 69 at more than four runs an over .
But when the openers departed in the 15th and 16th overs , the runs dried up and Zimbabwe tightened the screws to prolong what always seemed like the inevitable .
Taylor was not happy with Australia 's display .
`` It was a very scrappy performance from both sides , '' he said .
`` There was nothing wrong with the pitch .
At one stage I thought it looked like a 230-run wicket .
`` We lost our way with a lack or urgency and some silly shots . ''
Zimbabwe captain Andy Flower said his side was inconsistent .
`` Our guys bowled well but our batting was not up to scratch and we lost too many wickets in the middle stages after setting up a good platform , '' he said .
Flower said Australia had not seen the best of his side in the opening contest .
`` I honestly believe we can get up around the 250 mark against any of the sides in the competition .
We have the talent to do that , we just need a few of us to get going together . ''
Zimbabwe 's next match is against the Australia A side at the WACA on Sunday .
Japan , the only country that has suffered atomic attacks , expressed displeasure for a second day Friday over a U.S. plan to issue a postal stamp showing a nuclear mushroom cloud .
`` I do n't think the Japanese people will have good feelings toward the design of the stamp , '' Foreign Minister Yohei Kono said .
`` We may convey our feelings to the U.S. side in some form , '' he told a news conference .
The U.S. Postal Service plans to begin selling the stamp next September .
The stamp depicts the explosion of the atomic bomb dropped by U.S. forces on the city of Hiroshima in the closing days of World War II .
Under the mushroom cloud , it says , `` Atomic bombs hasten war 's end , August 1945 . ''
In Washington , Postal Service spokesman Robin Wright said the stamp is part of a series of stamps on World War II .
`` We would be remiss in omitting such a watershed and historically critical event as the use of the atomic bomb , '' he said .
`` Our purpose is to provide a comprehensive history of events of World War II and we are not making a value judgment on any of those events , '' Wright added .
Within five months after the bombing of Hiroshima , about 140,000 of the city 's 340,000 residents died .
Another atomic bombing of Nagasaki three days later killed 70,000 of that city 's 270,000 people .
Several days later , on Aug. 15 , 1945 , Japan surrendered to the Allied Forces .
Survivors of the atomic bombing and anti-nuclear activists expressed anger over the stamp on Thursday .
Sunao Tsuboi , a leader of the 30,000-member Hiroshima Prefectural Confederation of A-Bomb Survivors ' Organizations , called the stamp `` outrageous . ''
`` It makes our blood boil with anger , '' he said .
The government agreed Friday to extend to 1997 the deadline for Russia 's repayment of $ 100 million owned by the former Soviet Union to Japan 's Export-Import Bank .
Notes concerning the agreement were exchanged in Tokyo , the Foreign Ministry said .
Earlier this year , Japan signed a similar deferment agreement with Russia for debts of $ 180 million .
How did Gen. Colin L. Powell , Chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff , relax during the Gulf War ?
Listening to calypso music , the retired American military chief told students at the University of the West Indies .
Powell , 57 , the child of Jamaican immigrants to the United States , received an honorary degree from the institution late Thursday .
Earlier in the day , he accepted the Order of Jamaica , the nation 's equivalent to knighthood in the British system .
Powell told students he was pleased to be included among UWI 's earlier honorees , naming South African President Nelson Mandela , Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and former Jamaican Prime Minister Michael Manley .
`` But there is one name that I have to single out as I look through all of those honorees of the past , '' Powell said .
`` This one person for all those 35 years for me has been an inspiration .
And even during those dark days of Desert Storm when I was alone in my office , pondering matters of war and peace , this person was in the office with me in spirit helping me . ''
The crowd broke up in laughter when Powell named his inspiration -- The Mighty Sparrow , Trinidad 's venerable calypso king .
`` Let it be known far and wide that during the period of Desert Storm when I was in my office , I had my tape recorder with all of my Sparrow records lined up , '' Powell said .
`` And members of my staff and senior generals would come into the office to talk about the issues of the day .
And I would have a smile on my face ... They never quite understood what was coming out of that music box . ''
Army running back Kevin Vaughn ca n't begin to count how many times he 's heard `` Beat Navy '' in his four years at West Point .
`` The underclassmen have to greet us with ` Beat Navy . '
So that 's 1,000 underclassmen greeting you day in and day out , '' Vaughn said before the annual renewal of the legendary U.S. college football rivalry between the American military service academies on Saturday at Veterans Stadium .
`` It 's plastered on the walls and on the roofs of buildings on the campus , '' he said .
`` It 's everywhere .
You ca n't go 10 steps without either seeing it or hearing it . ''
Navy quarterback Jim Kubiak gets the appropriate variation of that greeting every time a plebe passes by at Annapolis .
`` I ca n't tell you how many times I 've heard ` Beat Army ' in my lifetime , '' he said .
`` So many times , I can hear it in my sleep . ''
While other U.S. college football teams judge their season on whether or not they get to a post-season `` bowl '' game , Army and Navy determine their success on whether or not they beat each other .
Since the 1960s , both Army and Navy , once U.S. college football powerhouses , have struggled .
They are unable to recruit top players because of a six-year committment each graduate must make to his branch of the U.S. military as payment for his education .
Most pro teams are not willing to wait six years for a player to become eligible -- especially since they wo n't be playing in that time .
And college football is a stepping stone to the pros .
But the lackluster records have not , and do not , dampen the spirit , intensity or enthusiasm of the Army-Navy rivalry .
It equals any bowl game .
In 94 meetings , Army has won only once more than Navy , 44 victories to 43 , with seven draws .
The Navy `` Midshipmen '' have outscored the Army `` Cadets '' 1,203-1 ,135 -- a difference of only seventh-tenths of a point per game .
Army eked out a 16-14 victory last year .
The Cadets jumped out to a 16-0 lead in the third quarter before Kubiak engineered two touchdown drives and one final drive that ended at the Army 1-yard-line with six seconds to play .
Ryan Bucchianeri then missed an 18-yard field goal attempt that would have given Navy the victory .
`` They might say , ` It 's over with ' and all that , but , you know what ?
That 's still in your mind , and you go to sleep with it every night , '' said Kubiak , who holds Navy career records for completions -LRB- 534 -RRB- and yards -LRB- 5,647 -RRB- .
`` And everybody on our football team wants to change that . ''
Navy has momentum on its side .
After an 0-5 start , it has won three of its last five .
Kubiak said an inexperienced offensive line has begun to play together : After being sacked 31 times in Navy 's first nine games , he was only sacked twice in their last game , a 29-17 victory over Rice .
Army 's season has gone in the opposite direction .
The Cadets opened with a victory over Holy Cross and got consecutive victories over Louisville and The Citadel , but they have also lost games they could have won against Temple , Rutgers , Wake Forest , Air Force and Boston University .
Army coach Bob Sutton said there is one key for his team against Navy 's pass-oriented attack .
`` A big part of this game is tackling , '' he said .
`` They throw a lot of passes where receivers are definitely going to catch the ball .
You have to be able to keep the gains to a minimum . ''
Volkwagen 's worldwide sales are up 7.1 percent in the first 10 months of this year but the automaker is still in early stages of its rebuilding , managing board chief Ferdinand Piech said Friday .
`` We have made about 20 percent of the improvements that we set as our goal , '' Piech told financial analysts .
`` In costs and quality clear progress has been attained , but there still is a lot of work ahead of us to be in the lead in worldwide competition . ''
Volkwagen released Piech 's comments in a statement that put world sales at 2.75 million vehicles through 10 months of 1994 .
The statement did not refer directly to German media reports that Germany 's biggest car maker was still planning large staff cuts .
The company put most of its workers in Germany on a four-day work week early this year , in a pact to avoid big layoffs .
On Thursday , VW denied it was planning to dismiss 50,000 workers worldwide to get down to a payroll of 194,000 .
Piech told the analysts that VW 's planning is dynamic and is reviewed annually .
