Led by a sharp drop for cars and other transportation equipment , orders to U.S. factories fell in October for the first time in three months .
The Commerce Department said Friday that orders declined 0.4 percent in October .
But the government , which originally estimated orders to be down 0.2 percent in September , revised that figure to show a rise of less than 0.1 percent .
New orders , a key gauge of the nation 's manufacturing sector , have risen in 13 of the last 15 months including a 4.7 percent jump in August that was led by auto demand .
They last fell in July , when they were off 2 percent .
Analysts expected orders to fall in October , predicting a decline of 0.6 percent .
Still , other data indicates the economy continues to grow at a solid pace despite higher interest rates .
Earlier Friday , the Labor Department reported a sharp drop in unemployment to 5.6 percent for November .
But the government 's Index of Leading Economic Indicators , the government 's main forecasting gauge , was down 0.1 percent in October .
In the factory report , the Commerce Department said that -- excluding the volatile transportation component -- orders rose 0.9 percent in October .
That indicator was unchanged in September and has risen 16 times in the last 17 months .
Orders for both durable and non-durable goods totaled a seasonally adjusted dlrs 286 billion , down from dlrs 287.2 billion in September .
Shipments , a measure of current production , decreased 0.7 percent to dlrs 284.2 billion in October , the third decline in the last four months and the fifth decrease this year .
Shipments fell 0.7 percent in September .
The backlog of unfilled orders rose 0.4 percent in October to dlrs 450.6 billion , following a 0.2 percent increase the previous month .
The orders backlog is often seen as a measure of whether current facilities and manpower are able to keep up with demand .
Inventories in October rose 0.4 percent to dlrs 388 billion , after a 0.1 percent decrease in September .
Orders for durable goods , items expected to last more than three years , were down 1 percent to dlrs 153.9 billion , after gaining 0.5 percent in September .
Transportation equipment fell dlrs 3.4 billion or 8.8 percent , led by declining car demand .
Orders for non-durable goods were up 0.2 percent at dlrs 132.1 billion .
Increased orders for tobacco , textiles and paper products were partly offset by declines in printing and publishing and petroleum and coal products .
Orders for non-defense capital goods excluding aircraft rose 0.1 percent in October after rising 3.5 percent in September .
These orders often are a barometer of business plans to expand and modernize .
Stefan Edberg rallied after facing match-point in the final set Friday to beat Russian Alexander Volkov 6-4 , 6-2 , 6-7 -LRB- 2-7 -RRB- , 0-6 , 8-6 and give Sweden a 1-0 lead in the Davis Cup final .
Volkov held match point on his serve leading 5-4 when Edberg sent a backhand down the line to send it to deuce .
He went on to break Volkov and then earned the critical break in the final game .
UNITA rebels were expected to arrive under U.N. protection in the Angolan capital Friday to cement a truce and power-sharing deal with the government that would end 19 years of civil war .
A United Nations plane was dispatched early Friday to an undisclosed location in the rebel-held Angolan hinterlands to pick up the UNITA delegation , a government military source told The Associated Press .
It would be the first time the rebels have appeared in Luanda since war resumed two years ago when UNITA -- the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola -- lost Angola 's first democratic elections and returned to arms .
The U.N. mission here set up stringent security measures after rebel representatives canceled a meeting earlier in the week , saying they feared for their lives in the government-held capital .
The two sides were scheduled to begin work Saturday on practical implementation of a treaty their leaders signed two weeks ago in Lusaka , Zambia , said the military official , speaking on condition of anonymity .
At issue are security measures for rebel officials , withdrawal of troops from contested areas and transportation of government and rebel soldiers to demobilization centers .
Although both UNITA and the government have accused each other of violating a cease-fire called Nov. 22 , two days after the treaty was signed , there has been a general reduction in fighting across the war-ravaged nation .
The U.N. mission here has deployed its first military observers to six scattered sites in the vast southern African nation .
If the cease-fire holds , a 7,000-strong U.N. peace keeping force has been promised to secure Angola 's transition to peace .
Angola 's war , which erupted on the eve of independence from Portugal in 1975 , has killed a half-million Angolans and left millions more threatened by starvation and disease .
Peace accords in 1991 brought a brief respite but UNITA lost multiparty elections a year later , cried foul and returned to war .
After initially capturing more than two-thirds of the country , UNITA has recently suffered crushing defeats and rebel leaders have been on the run since their main base in the central city of Huambo fell to the government early November .
Rebel chief Jonas Savimbi has not been seen in public for months , prompting rumors he had been killed or wounded in a government attack , or that he was seriously ill and was being treated in Zaire or Morocco .
Seventy Dutch U.N. peacekeepers detained by Bosnian Serb forces were released Friday , the Defense Ministry announced .
The peacekeepers , who were taken hostage Saturday near Zvornik in eastern Bosnia , left Bosnian Serb territory Friday morning for Zagreb .
The soldiers were in good condition , and none had been physically abused , the ministry said , adding that the soldiers would arrive back in the Netherlands Saturday .
The release of the 70 peacekeepers left 20 still in Bosnian Serb custody in nearby Papraca .
The Dutch peacekeepers were detained along with about 300 other troops , mostly British , as insurance against further NATO airstrikes .
NATO warplanes struck three times last week , but the attacks did nothing to stop the Serb assault on the Bosnian enclave of Bihac .
Police in the apartheid era killed and bombed government enemies and tried to spread the AIDS virus in the black community , the Sowetan newspaper reported Friday .
It based the reports on sworn affidavits it said were given by three policemen who were living in a European country under a witness protection program .
A judicial panel investigating political violence in South Africa has interviewed South African policemen in Denmark .
The Sowetan report , citing confidentiality of the witness protection program , lacked the identities of the policemen , the country they were in and any information on how the newspaper obtained the affidavits .
Allegations of police hit squads date back years , and several judicial inquests have found evidence that some police took part in hit squads but never linked such activities to top officials .
In addition , some policemen have been convicted of what appeared to be politically motivated killings .
The Sowetan report contained details of alleged police activities against black opposition groups that included : -- The 1988 bombing of the South African Council of Churches office in downtown Johannesburg .
A former Cabinet minister allegedly congratulated the police unit involved ; -- Bombing cinemas to prevent the screening of the film `` Cry Freedom , '' which portrayed the relationship between black activist Steve Biko , who died in police custody , and a journalist ; -- Sending former guerrilla fighters infected with the HIV virus that leads to AIDS into the Hillbrow entertainment district of Johannesburg to infect black prostitutes ; -- Supplying arms to the Zulu nationalist Inkatha Freedom Party , which fought a low-level civil war against the African National Congress that killed thousands of blacks .
-- Planning the killing of ANC and civil rights activist Bheki Mlangeni , who died when earphones he received in a mail package exploded as he used them .
There was no immediate comment from police or the Safety and Security Ministry .
Since the nation 's first all-race election in April ended apartheid and brought the ANC to power , President Nelson Mandela has called for reforms in the police department to bring blacks into the white-dominated hierarchy .
The ANC has for years accused police of aiding Inkatha in the political fighting that mostly stopped just before the election .
It also claimed police instigated violence to destabilize the black opposition movement .
The new ANC-led government has proposed granting amnesty to people who admit their roles in political crimes during the apartheid era .
Inkatha and the National Party , which implemented and dismantled apartheid during its 46 years in power until the April vote , oppose full public disclosure of details of the crimes .
In another sign Iran wants to influence the selection of a new spiritual leader for Shiite Muslims , a leading cleric said Friday the choice must be politically aware because Islam is under threat .
Grand Ayatollah Ali Araki died Tuesday at the age of at least 100 .
After his death , the jockeying began to replace him as supreme head of the world 's 100 million Shiite Muslims , who comprise one of Islam 's two main branches .
Traditionally the marja ala , or supreme spiritual leader , has been chosen from the grand ayatollahs -- who number about a dozen -- by theologians in the leading Shiite seminaries in Qom in Iran and the holy city of Najaf in Iraq .
In the past , the marja ala has eschewed involvement in politics .
But in a sermon broadcast on Tehran Radio Friday , Ayatollah Ahmad Jannati said the man who succeeds Araki `` must have a greater political awareness than previous holders of the office . ''
Such a leader , he said , would help resurgent Islam face `` an American-backed Islam . ''
Jannati is a member of key official committees and a close associate of Ayatollah Ali Khamenei , the Iranian government 's choice for spiritual leader .
His comments underlined fears among many Shiites that Iran 's government , by intervening in what has until now been a solely religious matter , is seeking to control religion in Iran and exert authority over Shiites around the world .
Khamenei , 55 , has the qualifications of a middle-ranking cleric , but the radio referred to him as a grand ayatollah several times Wednesday .
There has been no official word that Khamenei had been promoted to grand ayatollah by Iran 's religious establishment .
Iran is promoting Khamenei because it fears that a non-Iranian , the Grand Ayatollah Ali Husseini Seestani , may become the next marja ala.
Seestani , 65 , who lives and teaches in Najaf in Iraq , has steered clear of politics .
Nepal 's minority government is confident of winning the vote of confidence when Parliament meets in two weeks , the prime minister said Friday .
The new communist government is required under the constitution to win the vote because it did not have the required majority in the 205-member House of Representatives .
`` I have talked to all the leaders of other political parties , '' Prime Minister Man Mohan Adhikari said .
`` And they have assured us that they will cooperate . ''
Adhikari needs at least 103 votes .
The main opposition Nepali Congress also said it will ensure that the government does not fail immediately .
The Communist Party of Nepal -LRB- Marxist-Leninist -RRB- won 88 votes , but cobbled together a government with the help of other groups .
`` We need to win the confidence vote , pass legislations and the -LRB- annual -RRB- budget after that .
Therefore , it is a compulsion for us and also for them -LRB- other parties -RRB- to seek a consensus , '' he said .
The Nepali Congress won 83 seats , while the National Democratic Party won 20 seats , the Nepal Workers and Peasants Party four , Nepal Welfare Party three and independents seven seats .
The pro-monarchy Democratic Party is undecided about supporting the government .
After a slow start , Haiti is moving swiftly to solidify its democratic institutions , appointing a new 11-member Supreme Court and formally placing the army-controlled police under civilian command .
In another supportive step , 250 former Haitian boat people were heading home Friday to become members of the internationally supervised interim police force .
The separation of the police and military , stipulated in the 1987 Constitution , was approved by the Senate on Wednesday night but only announced on Friday .
It will become law when it appears in the official government gazette , Le Moniteur .
`` The armed forces reform law is a historic break with our repressive political past , '' Sen. Jean-Robert Martinez told The Associated Press .
The appointment of new Supreme Court is another building block to establishing civil justice in a land that has been ruled by the gun for most of its history .
The new chief justice , Clauzel Debrosse , had been an existing member of the Supreme Court but an opponent of the military overthrow in 1991 of elected President Jean-Bertrand Aristide , who returned to power in October after U.S. military intervention .
`` We wanted to reward Debrosse for his opposition to de facto rule , '' said Martinez , an Aristide supporter .
Aristide , in conformity with the constitution , chose the judges from a Senate list of three for each seat .
The array of judicial moves reflects the desire by Aristide to strengthen civilian authority as rapidly as possible .
Thousands of American and other foreign troops are guaranteeing the peace now , but U.S. Republican leaders are urging the Clinton administration to hasten the pullout of GIs .
The widely popular Aristide , wary of those who overthrew him three years ago , is quickly reassigning senior military officers to overseas posts .
U.S. Embassy spokesman Stanley Schrager confirmed Friday that former Haitian military chief Jean-Claude Duperval was being transferred to a diplomatic post in Brazil and Brig. Gen. Max Mayard was heading to a similar military attache position in Ecuador .
The other two generals during the 1991-4 military rule , Lt. Gen. Raoul Cedras and Brig. Gen. Philippe Biamby , quit and fled to self-imposed exile in Panama two days before Aristide 's return .
Aristide has pledged to slice the size of the army from 7,500 to 1,500 and to create a 4,000-member civilian police force .
The 250 Haitians joining the interim police force Friday were recruited and trained in the refugee tent camp at the U.S. base in Guantanamo Bay , Cuba .
They were among tens of thousands of Haitians who fled their nation under military rule .
Another 750 refugees-turned-police will arrive in Haiti in the next three weeks , Schrager , the U.S. spokesman , told the AP .
`` In coming weeks , they will be used in police support positions by both the Haitian government and the I.P.M. , '' said Paul Browne , spokesman for the 800-member 20-nation International Police Monitor corps that is supervising police work .
Nearly half a century after its launch , the Achille Lauro was drifting silently in the Indian Ocean on Friday , its history of triumphs and tragedy nearing an end .
The 979 surviving passengers and crew members of the Italian liner were heading for three African and Middle Eastern ports aboard 10 rescue vessels after abandoning the blazing ship two days ago .
Still smoldering , listing badly and charred from stem to stern , the Achille Lauro was but a shell of the gleaming blue and white luxury liner that once sailed around the world in 80 days .
But it was for tragedy , not triumph , that the Achille Lauro was best known .
The ship burst into the world 's headlines in 1985 when Palestinian terrorists hijacked it , killed an American Jew , Leon Klinghoffer , and dumped his body overboard in his wheelchair .
The terrorists escaped from the ship and boarded a jet , but U.S. fighter planes forced it to land in Italy and the hijackers were arrested and later tried .
The second fire in the ship 's history began in the engine room before dawn Wednesday and slowly spread to engulf the ship , despite efforts by the crew to contain it .
Two elderly passengers died , one apparently of a heart attack , and eight people were injured as lifeboats and rafts were launched and the ship was abandoned .
The first fire aboard the Achille Lauro came in 1981 off the Canary Islands .
Passengers leaped from the decks into the Atlantic and two died .
Wednesday 's `` fire was so big you had to fight through smoke which poured down toward the cabins , '' one survivor , Tony Webb , was quoted as telling the London Daily Telegraph .
`` At about 8 a.m. , the captain said the fire was too strong and we would have to abandon ship , '' said Webb , 44 , a Briton living in Cape Town , South Africa .
Webb praised the crew and the ship 's captain , Giuseppe Orsi , who was the last to abandon ship .
But two other passengers , interviewed by Britain 's Sky TV on Friday , were critical .
One , Geoffrey Wall , said one of the two victims was killed when the crew dropped an inflated raft on top of a lifeboat carrying about 35 passengers .
And Dennis Basset told Sky TV that the crew failed to alert all of the passengers to the emergency until only minutes before the abandon ship order was sounded .
In a radio telephone call from a rescue ship Thursday , Captain Orsi said he thought the Achille Lauro was finished .
But an official of the ship 's owner , Starlauro of Naples , said Friday that seagoing tugs had been hired to go to the scene and check the ship 's condition .
`` We intend to tow the ship -- to save it at all costs , '' said Sergio Santopaolo .
But Santopaolo acknowledged the final decision will be made only after the tugboat crews evaluate the damage , and that would take at least a couple of days .
`` From what I saw , -LRB- the ship -RRB- is gone , '' Orsi said .
Eight cargo vessels and two American warships , the USS Gettysburg and Halyburton , were carrying the Achille Lauro 's surviving passengers and crew members to Djibouti , Mombasa in Kenya and Muskat in Oman .
Most were heading for Mombasa .
The first ship was expected to dock in Djibouti on Saturday ; the rest were scheduled to make port on Sunday .
Arianespace , the world leader in commercial satellite launching , apologized Friday after a dlrs 150 million U.S. communications satellite crashed into Atlantic , but said the client has signed on for another try .
Charles Bigot , Arianespace 's chief executive , said a failure in the third-stage engine caused an unmanned Ariane rocket to crash 15 minutes after takeoff Thursday from the launch center in French Guiana .
Aboard was a sophisticated communications satellite built by Hughes Space and Communications of El Segundo , Calif. , for PanAmSat , a Greenwich , Conn.-based firm .
The PamAmSat-3 satellite would have channeled telephone , fax and television communications for most of North and South America , Europe and Africa over 15 years .
It would have traveled in geostationary orbit over the mid-Atlantic .
Bigot , answering French reporters ' questions in a live hook-up from the launch center in South America , said it was too early to decide when Ariane launches would resume .
He said preliminary report on the crash was due by mid-December .
He said the lost satellite had been insured , and PanAmSat was preparing a replacement satellite .
Despite the accident , Bigot said PanAmSat 's vice president , Reverge Anselmo , had signed a contract for Arianespace to launch another PanAmSat satellite by the end of 1996 .
Arianespace technicians said the third-stage engine inexplicably lost pressure 218 kilometers -LRB- 135 miles -RRB- above Earth .
In January , a third-stage breakdown forced engineers to explode a rocket in mid-flight .
A Turkish and a European telecommunications satellites were also destroyed .
Six perfect launches followed .
Thursday 's crash was the seventh in 70 launches since the European Space Agency 's commercial Arianespace program lifted off 15 years ago .
It should not shake Ariane 's dominance as the world 's most successful launcher of lucrative private satellites -- the company now holds about 70 percent of the market .
`` We hope to get back into operation very quickly , '' said Bigot , who apologized to the satellite 's owners .
Liftoff was on schedule at 7:38 p.m.
The first two stages fired perfectly and controllers confidently expected another of what have become almost routine shots for the Ariane launchers .
The third stage also lit properly , but then mysteriously sputtered and went out .
Officials said that the third stage was a new type using a new oxygen-hydrogen mixture to maximize performance .
January 's accident was blamed on a turbo-pump failure freezing the third-stage rocket motor .
That failure followed 26 straight successful launches in which the European rocket distanced itself from its competitors , the United States and China .
The Arianes have put 94 satellites in orbit and have a backlog of 38 , representing contracts worth more than 17 billion francs -LRB- dlrs 3.1 billion -RRB- .
In an attempt to repulse incoming refugees , Parliament on Friday authorized the government to automatically bar all asylum seekers arriving overland .
The measure is aimed at stemming a flow of asylum seekers that has severely strained government resources and led to a rightist resurgence in May 's national elections .
`` We do n't want to send people back to face danger , '' said spokesman Tom van der Maas for the right-wing Liberals , one of the three ruling coalition partners .
`` But we need to redirect this inflow of people .
It 's an effort to spread the burden throughout Europe . ''
`` This is an ugly law , '' countered Fronnie Biesma , spokesman for the Dutch Refugee Council .
`` We are just transferring the responsibility to other countries . ''
The legislation takes direct aim at the Netherlands ' international reputation as a safe haven for the persecuted , a label that this year will draw an estimated 55,000 asylum seekers to this nation of 15 million .
Virtually assured of becoming law , the measure is aimed primarily at the `` economic migrants '' who move around Europe in search of the best residency and benefits deal .
In practice , the law will bar the vast majority of asylum seekers , who usually arrive overland by bus , car or train from neighboring Germany or Belgium .
The new law also would bar any asylum seekers who had traveled through so-called `` safe third countries '' where they could have applied for asylum before reaching the Netherlands .
Stocks were mostly higher in early trading Friday morning as bond prices staged a surprised rally on mixed economic reports .
After 30 minutes of trading the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 11.10 but it then lost all the gain to register 3,700.87 at 10.30 a.m. EST -LRB- 1530 GMT -RRB- one hour into the session , unchanged from Thursday 's close .
Advancing issues led decliners by 789 to 664 on the New York Stock Exchange , where volume totaled 34.26 million shares in the first half hour .
Broad-market indexes were higher .
The NYSE composite was up 0.61 at 246.65 .
The American Stock Exchange 's market value index was up 0.34 at 431.53 .
The Nasdaq composite index stood at 741.97 , up 0.78 from a revised Thursday close of 741.19 .
The Labor Department said a seasonally adjusted 350,000 new workers were added to the nation 's nonfarm payrolls , pushing the unemployment rate to 5.6 percent from 5.8 percent in October .
That is the lowest level since August 1990 .
Analysts had expected an increase in nonfarm jobs of about 250,000 , and for the unemployment rate to remain at 5.8 percent .
The jobs data showed a stronger-than expected growth in the economy , but its impact was softened by a drop of 0.1 percent in October in the government 's index of leading indicators , the chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity .
Bonds initially dipped on the jobs report but then quickly rallied , pulling stocks higher with them .
The 30-year U.S. Treasury bond was up about dlrs 6 per dlrs 1,000 face value and yielding 7.95 percent , after the market got mixed reports on the economy .
`` I 'm surprised , '' said Ricky Harrington , technical analyst at Interstate-Johnson Lane in Charlotte , N.C. `` I thought the market would have been down 10-20 points '' on the jobs data .
`` It could be we 've simply reached an oversold condition as far as bonds are concerned , and that might be the reason '' for the rally in both markets , Harrington said .
Harrington did note that average earnings and workweek fell , which could also have offered some comfort to bond traders .
Weak economic data is generally good for bonds because it lessens the likelihood that the Federal Reserve will have to raise interest rates to curb inflation .
Stocks were lower overseas .
Tokyo 's Nikkei index fell 0.1 percent , and Frankfurt 's DAX index was down 0.4 percent .
London 's FT-SE 100 was lower as well .
A prominent Russian historian said Friday that Kremlin archives from the 1950s show China and North Korea were sharply at odds over the number of American POWs they held during the Korean War .
`` Even the countries that fought together and held POWs in their camps in North Korea and China did n't know their exact number , '' said Gen. Dmitry Volkogonov , a historian and adviser to President Boris Yeltsin , told a news conference .
Volkogonov co-chairs the joint Russian-U.S. Commission , which is investigating the fate of American POWs and MIAs .
He said he would turn the document over to the American side at the commission 's session in Washington next week .
Volkogonov cited an account he had found in the archives of a secret meeting in Moscow in the fall of 1952 .
Dictator Josef Stalin had summoned Chinese Premier Zhou Enlai , North Korean leader Kim Il Sung and North Korean military commander Pan Do Huai to the Kremlin to discuss the Korean War .
He asked how many Americans they had captured , Volkogonov said .
`` Zhou Enlai replied that they held 8,000 foreigners , while Kim Il Sung immediately interrupted him , saying the actual number was slightly more than 4,000 , '' Volkogonov said .
`` Stalin tried to clarify that , but none of the participants in these secret talks could tell the exact number of United Nations ' POWs , much less American POWs . ''
He suggested that China and North Korea help clarify the matter .
The Russian-U.S. commission announced last year there was no hope of finding any American POWs alive in the former Soviet Union .
It confined its search to finding the remains of U.S. servicemen and clarifying the circumstances of their deaths .
The commission has also said it found no proof that any captured Americans were brought to the Soviet Union from Korea or Vietnam .
It did confirm that American POWs were interrogated by Soviet troops in North Korea and China during the Korean War .
The commission 's other co-chairman , Malcolm Toon , a former U.S. ambassador to the Soviet Union , has urged the Russians to continue searching archives .
Among the commission 's earlier findings were that several dozen Americans were sent to the Soviet Gulag after the Red Army freed them from the Nazis at the end of World War II .
Soviet authorities arrested those with Slavic or Jewish surnames on assumption they were Russians who had collaborated with the Germans , Volkogonov said .
`` The fates of some were so tragic they deserve to be told by Shakespeare , '' Volkogonov said .
He cited the case of one American , whom he identified only by the last name Oggins , who spent eight years in Soviet camps .
The man was finally shot on Stalin 's personal order in 1952 , days before his term was to expire , for fear he would tell the world what he had been through , Volkogonov said .
Volkogonov said the commission also continues to investigate the fate of American pilots downed in the 1950s while probing the Soviets ' radar defenses .
Earlier this year , the investigators found the remains of one , Capt. John P. Dunham , whose reconaissance plane was shot down by Soviet fighters over the Sea of Japan in 1952 , Volkogonov said .
A jury convicted a Lebanese immigrant Thursday of murdering a Jewish teen-ager in an ambush on the Brooklyn Bridge , rejecting his claim that he was suffering a flashback from his childhood in war-torn Beirut .
Rashid Baz , a livery cab driver , admitted he strafed the van with bullets on March 1 as it drove onto the bridge .
Sixteen year-old Aaron Halberstam was killed and three others were wounded .
Baz 's lawyer , Eric Sears , blamed his client 's `` catastrophic '' childhood in Beirut , where he became a soldier at age 9 .
He said Baz suffers post-traumatic stress syndrome , which climaxed in the bridge shooting .
Baz , 28 , said he fired at the van after its passengers mouthed insults and leveled a gun at him .
`` Let him rot in hell , '' Devorah Halberstam , the dead boy 's mother , said after the verdict .
`` Nobody believed he was insane .
The evidence was overwhelming that he was not .
... I honestly believe his only remorse is that he did n't kill every single boy in that van , '' Mrs. Halberstam said .
Nachum Sosonkin , 18 , a passenger who was shot in the head , testified during the trial that he never heard anyone inside the van say anything to Baz or display a gun .
The jury deliberated one day before convicting Baz of second-degree murder and 14 counts of attempted murder .
Baz , who immigrated from Lebanon at age 18 , faces 25 years to life in prison at his Jan. 18 sentencing .
`` I do n't think my son got a fair trial , '' said Baz 's 52-year-old mother , Suheila .
`` The jury was very harsh . ''
`` But I have high hopes in the American judge and I hope my son will get a fair sentence , considering his illness , '' she told The Associated Press in an interview at her apartment in Beirut .
She did not say what a fair sentence would be .
The shooting occurred as 15 male students , dressed in the distinctive black garb worn by ultra-Orthodox Lubavitcher Jews , returned from a visit to a Manhattan hospital where the Lubavitchers ' leader , Rebbe Menachem Schneerson , was being treated .
The rebbe died in June .
The dead boy 's father , Rabbi David Halberstam , said he believes Baz acted to revenge the Feb. 25 massacre on Israel 's West Bank in which a Jewish settler killed 29 Arabs as they prayed in a mosque .
Baz 's attorney had argued that the shooting was not revenge , but that the massacre might have triggered a deadly flashback .
The prosecution cited testimony by Baz 's uncle , Jamal Akel , that Baz 's problems predated the start of Lebanon 's civil war in 1975 and much of his behavior was shocking -- even in Beirut .
No sooner did a defense attorney try to quell one war of words in the murder case of former U.S. football great O.J. Simpson than another debate erupted involving judges in different states .
A New York judge ordered one of Simpson 's DNA lawyers , Peter Neufeld , to appear in his court for a murder trial despite an order by the Simpson judge for Neufeld to be in Los Angeles .
The order Thursday by New York state judge Harold Rothwax included digs at Neufeld and the Superior Court Judge Lance Ito .
`` I 'm out of sympathy for Mr. Simpson and his attorneys , '' said Rothwax , who claimed that Neufeld 's problems were his own fault and that Ito had waited too long to order the lawyer to appear at the Simpson trial .
Rothwax 's order came hours after lead defense attorney Robert Shapiro said the Simpson team would stop talking to the press except `` when we feel there is a necessity . ''
Simpson , a former football legend , television sports commentator and movie star , has pleaded innocent in the murder of his ex-wife Nicole Brown Simpson and her friend Ronald Goldman on June 12 .
Opening statements in his trial are n't expected until mid-January .
Shapiro and attorney Johnnie Cochran Jr. have accused Nicole Brown Simpson 's sister of orchestrating an effort to deny Simpson a fair trial by repeatedly accusing him of being the killer .
Prosecutor Marcia Clark responded that the families were fed up with defense attempts to discredit witnesses and evidence .
Ms. Brown 's emotional accusations continued to affect the trial Thursday .
Three more prospective alternate jurors were bounced after they said they had heard or been told of her TV interviews .
`` I think I heard Simpson ' sister-in-law say he was going to kill her ... Nicole , '' one prospect said .
Simpson appeared astonished , turned to his lawyers and asked , `` Did she say that ? ''
Three other prospects who had heard of Ms. Brown 's comments were dismissed Wednesday .
The New York Daily News reported Friday that an inmate claims that he overheard Simpson make incriminating statements while talking to his friend Rosey Grier , a former football player who now is a minister .
According to the newspaper , which cited an unidentified source , the inmate reported to a deputy that he overheard the conversation in a visiting room , which has several glass-enclosed cubicles that are open on top .
The deputy then notified Ito .
The newspaper gave no detail on the alleged statements .
Later Friday , Russia 's Yevgeny Kafelnikov faced Magnus Larsson in the second singles with Swedes Jonas Bjorkman and Jan Apell , the ATP Tour 's top-ranked doubles team and recently crowned doubles champions , facing Kafelnikov and Andrei Olhovskiy on Saturday .
After winning the first two sets , the seventh-ranked Edberg appeared enroute to an easy victory .
But buoyed by a partisan crowd of 12,000 , Volkov battled back in the third set , punctuated with a crowd-pleasing ace to take the tiebreaker .
The 27-year-old Volkov then dominated Edberg in the fourth set with devastating passing shots and seemed set to take the match , serving for the victory in the final set .
Having broke Volkov to tie the set , Edberg had the added distraction Russian President Boris Yeltsin entering Olympic Stadium just as the Swede was preparing to start the next game .
Edberg , who had been whistled in derision by the crowd , paced along the baseline as Yeltsin and his entourage took their seats .
The left-handed Volkov was repeatedly rattled in the first two sets , hurling his racket to the ground twice after failing to reach Edberg returns at the baseline .
Edberg was troubled by inconsistent serves .
A victory by Volkov would have been a major boost to the Russians , who were expected to have the edge in the match between Kafelnikov , ranked 11th by the ATP Tour , and Larsson .
Kafelnikov has won seven straight Davis Cup matches since losing in his debut to Germany 's Michael Stich in March 1993 .
Sweden leads Russia 2-0 in Davis Cup competition , but the two have not faced each other since 1982 .
Russia hopes to become the first unseeded team to win the title .
It is only the seventh to reach the final .
The mast on Isabelle Autissier 's yacht snapped in high winds Friday , knocking her out of the BOC Challenge round-the-world yacht race , the South African Press Association reported .
Autissier , the only woman in the race and the leader after the first leg from Charleston , South Carolina , to Cape Town , sent a message to race headquarters in Charleston saying : `` Dismasted .
No danger immediately . ''
An official in Charleston told SAPA the mast broke in winds of 40 knots -LRB- 46 miles per hour or 67 kilometers per hour -RRB- and Autissier , of France , would be unable to continue .
She was in fourth place on the second leg , 1200 miles -LRB- 1900 kilometers -RRB- from Cape Town en route to Sydney , Australia .
After Sydney , the 27,000-mile -LRB- 43,200-kilometer -RRB- race continues to Punta del Este , Uruguay , before finishing in Charleston in the spring .
