Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin on Friday downplayed hints by Syria 's leader that Damascus was losing hope in peace talks with Israel .
`` Be neither alarmed nor unmoved , '' by Hafez Assad 's comments , Rabin told newspaper editors meeting in Tel Aviv .
He added the deadlocked peace efforts with Syria must continue .
Rabin said both Israel and Arab regimes were endangered by an Iranian-backed `` ugly wave of extremist , fundamentalist , terroristic Islam that has swept the Arab and Muslim world . ''
Noting what he termed an upsurge in mosque construction in the United States and Western Europe , Rabin said : `` Today extremist Islam has an international infrastructure . ''
He said most of the Israelis killed by Arabs since the Sept. 1993 autonomy pact with the PLO were victims of Palestinian fundamentalists , sometimes financed by supporters in the United States , or the Iranian-backed Lebanese militia Hezbollah .
Bloodshed in that time has claimed 94 Israelis and 187 Palestinians .
Rabin said Syria should follow the example of the PLO and Jordan , which both reached accords with Israel since Rabin took office in mid-1992 , in establishing a direct dialog with Jerusalem .
But the Syrians can not be forced into peace , he said .
Rabin was responding to Assad 's statement Thursday that the status quo was preferable to formal peace under Israel 's conditions .
Israel and Syria have not fought directly for 21 years except for an air battle during Israel 's 1982 Lebanon invasion .
Both back proxy forces fighting in south Lebanon .
On Friday , Syria 's government-run Al-Thawra daily accused Israel of continuing to pursue `` war and aggression '' to intimidate the Arabs into peace on its terms .
`` If Syria really prefers the present situation over peace , peace can not be forced , '' Rabin said .
`` We can not force it on the Syrians .
The Syrians can not force it on us , and the United States .
understands that coercion and peace contradict each other . ''
Israeli-Syrian negotiations have been deadlocked almost since they started in 1991 .
Syria demands that Israel return the entire Golan Heights captured in 1967 .
Israel has offered only a phased , partial pullback and also demands Syria dismantle Iranian-backed militias in Lebanon .
Secretary of State Warren Christopher is to return to the region Tuesday to resume his shuttle mediation between Damascus and Jerusalem .
Itamar Rabinovich , Israel 's U.S. ambassador and a leading negotiator with the Syrians , said it was up to Christopher to rescue the faltering peace process .
`` It is very important that he be successful in saving the gloomy atmosphere that has formed around the negotiations , '' Rabinovich said on Army radio .
Rabin faces strong opposition in Israel to any peace deal .
Benjamin Begin , a leading lawmaker from the right-wing Likud opposition , told Army radio that military intelligence believed Assad still sought Israel 's destruction .
`` Under such conditions , when this is the Syrian strategy , it is hard to understand why people with even minimal logic could even think about any withdrawal from the Golan , '' said Begin .
Author Robin Moore says he was surprised at how he easily obtained information in the former Soviet Union for his book about the Russian mafia .
Moore , 69 , the author of the `` French Connection '' and `` The Green Berets , '' spoke Thursday at the Litchfield-Morris Rotary about his latest novel , `` The Moscow Connection , '' which grew out of a 1991 visit to Moscow .
`` I was fascinated to find a new era of free speech , '' Moore told the group .
`` It seemed everything could be bought and sold .
You could even buy the KGB -- I did . ''
The latest book is a thinly disguised work of fiction chronicling the rise of the Russian mafia .
It was set in the wake of the failed coup that ended the reign of former Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in 1991 .
The book grew out of an invitation by the Moscow police to do a positive story about the department .
When he got there , Moore said , he found the department so riddled with corruption that a positive story was impossible .
Instead , he made friends with some honest officers who steered him to his latest work with tales of the existence of a Russian mafia .
Moore hopes his book will expose the burgeoning Russian mafia and what he says is its vigorous trade in the nuclear weaponry of the former Soviet Union .
The Register Citizen newspaper in Torrington is serializing the novel .
The Croatian government and leaders of the rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement Friday that , if implemented , could lead to normalized relations between the two enemies .
A six-month war in 1991 -- at the start of the violent breakup of Yugoslavia -- left Serbs in control of one-third of Croatian territory .
There have been thousands of skirmishes and larger confrontations between the two since a January 1992 ceasefire halted the war , including artillery duels southeast of Knin which continued for the third day Friday .
The economic agreement calls for restoring water and electricity supplies and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital Belgrade .
Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220 mile -RRB- highway are controlled by Croatian Serbs .
Representatives of the Croatian government signed the accord Friday morning at U.N. headquarters in Zagreb , with international mediators Lord David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg as co-signers .
The document was then brought to Knin , rebel Serb headquarters , where their leaders signed it .
`` The significance of the agreement is going to depend on the parties to the agreement , '' Owen told The Associated Press in Knin .
The two sides `` have it in their power to implement the agreement if they want to , '' he added .
`` For many people it has been senseless to be deprived of water , electricity , '' Owen said .
`` The basics of economic life can now be made available to all . ''
Croatian Serb representative Borislav Mikelic , though signing the agreement , remained firm in the Serbs ' refusal to accept any reintegration with Croatia .
`` By signing this agreement we once more proved that we are in favor of a peaceful solution to the crisis here and we also showed that we 're interested in the economic progress and economic opening to Europe and the world , '' Mikelic said .
But he refused to discuss the crucial overall political solution , saying , `` This is not the time to talk about it . ''
The self-styled Croatian Serb assembly , after a nearly eight-hour , closed-door session , approved the economic accord late Thursday .
Negotiations between the two sides had been stalled .
But the Croatian Serbs relented after a recent clandestine meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic , the Balkans power broker .
Thousands of peacekeepers have been deployed between the warring sides in the disputed territories since the 1992 cease-fire .
But international efforts toward lasting peace have failed over what seemed to be irreconcilable differences .
This is the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their 1991 war .
Stefan Edberg rallied after facing match-point in the final set Friday to beat Russian Alexander Volkov 6-4 , 6-2 , 6-7 -LRB- 2-7 -RRB- , 0-6 , 8-6 and give Sweden a 1-0 lead in the Davis Cup final .
Volkov held match point on his serve leading 5-4 when Edberg sent a backhand down the line to send it to deuce .
He went on to break Volkov and then earned the critical break in the final game .
`` Maybe he played it a little safe , '' Edberg said about facing match point .
`` I took charge of the match in that game .
I took a few chances and it paid off . ''
`` I needed to kick myself , especially in the fifth set .
I was a little bit depressed .
I had the match in my hand and became defensive ... I felt I was getting closer and closer in every game in the fifth set . ''
Later Friday , Russia 's Yevgeny Kafelnikov faced Magnus Larsson in the second singles .
Swedes Jonas Bjorkman and Jan Apell , the ATP Tour 's top-ranked doubles team and recently crowned doubles champions , were to faced Kafelnikov and Andrei Olhovskiy on Saturday .
After winning the first two sets , the seventh-ranked Edberg appeared enroute to an easy victory .
But buoyed by a partisan crowd of 12,000 , Volkov battled back in the third set , punctuated with a crowd-pleasing ace to take the tiebreaker .
The 27-year-old Volkov then dominated Edberg in the fourth set with devastating passing shots and seemed set to take the match , serving for the victory in the final set .
`` I needed to kick myself , especially in the fifth set , '' Edberg said .
`` I was a little bit depressed .
I had the match in my hand and became defensive ... I felt I was getting closer and closer in every game in the fifth set . ''
Having broke Volkov to tie the set , Edberg had the added distraction Russian President Boris Yeltsin entering Olympic Stadium just as the Swede was preparing to start the next game .
Edberg , who had been whistled in derision by the crowd , paced along the baseline as Yeltsin and his entourage took their seats .
`` I saw a lot of people coming in , but I did n't know it was Yeltsin , '' Edberg said .
`` I just put it aside .
I felt so happy being back in the match . ''
The left-handed Volkov was repeatedly rattled in the first two sets , hurling his racket to the ground twice after failing to reach Edberg returns at the baseline .
Edberg was troubled by inconsistent serves .
A victory by Volkov would have been a major boost to the Russians , who were expected to have the edge in the match between Kafelnikov , ranked 11th by the ATP Tour , and Larsson .
Kafelnikov has won seven straight Davis Cup matches since losing in his debut to Germany 's Michael Stich in March 1993 .
`` I 've been in the same situation .
He 's probably feeling quite depressed tonight , '' Edberg said about Volkov .
`` On the other hand , he was out of the match and came back . ''
Sweden leads Russia 2-0 in Davis Cup competition , but the two have not faced each other since 1982 .
Russia hopes to become the first unseeded team to win the title .
It is only the seventh to reach the final .
Christianity is a `` lifeless corpse '' propped up by the Roman Catholic Church , a senior Iranian cleric said Friday .
`` Today we look around and see that Christianity is truly lacking in divine and religious spirituality , and is an arid and useless movement , '' Ayatollah Ahmad Jannati said in a sermon at Tehran University .
It is `` a lifeless corpse propped up only by the institution of a centralized papacy , '' he said .
Jannati , a senior cleric inside the government , said `` Islam is experiencing a revival '' and possesses `` so much spirituality , so much depth , with such strength for administering the world . ''
Officially , Iran respects both Judaism and Christianity .
But religious minorities in Iran , including a Christian population of about 200,000 , have been allowed to practice only under strict regulations and supervision .
Proselytizing by any religion or Muslim sect other than Iran 's brand of Shiite Islam is also strictly forbidden .
Serbs fired missiles at Bosnian government headquarters today in a sign of contempt for senior U.N. officials trying to end harassment of peacekeeping troops .
The anti-armor missiles landed just before meetings began with the top U.N. official for former Yugoslavia , Yasushi Akashi .
Akashi , on a mission to free hundreds of peacekeepers and end restrictions on U.N. relief convoys , was to talk later with the Serbs , who refused to even meet with his boss , U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali , on Wednesday .
After the rebuff , Boutros-Ghali warned that the intransigence of the warring sides in Bosnia threatened to force the United Nations to end its mission there .
The United Nations has pressing issues to discuss : attempts to calm fighting in northwest Bosnia , where Serbs forces have overrun Muslim villages in a U.N.-desigated `` safe area '' ; and the fate of more than 400 U.N. soldiers being held by the Serbs as insurance against NATO air strikes .
Seventy Dutch peacekeepers who were taken hostage Saturday were released today , the Dutch Defense Ministry reported .
The soldiers were in good condition and had not been physically abused .
It was not immediately clear if the release was tied to Akashi 's mission .
Akashi arrived this morning in Sarajevo for meetings with officials of the Muslim-led Bosnian government .
He left the presidency building briefly before the meetings began and the two missiles hit the structure just before he returned .
A third wire-guided anti-armor missile hit a building nearby .
There were no immediate reports of injuries .
After the meetings with the government , Akashi was to head for talks at Bosnian Serb headquarters in Pale , outside Sarajevo .
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic met with the U.N. commander for Bosnia , Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose on Thursday .
A U.N. source said Karadzic promised to try to help , but added that such promises often are empty .
Spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi wanted to discuss fighting around the government enclave of Bihac in the northwest , and an end to restrictions on the movement of U.N. troops .
Thant said Bihac , scene of heavy fighting for weeks , was quiet overnight .
But strong Serb forces , which have seized 30 percent to 40 percent of the U.N.-declared `` safe zone '' encompassing the town of Bihac and its environs , remained in the area .
The United Nations has said that ethnic Serbs from Croatia and Bosnia appeared strong enough to capture Bihac if they wanted .
There were signs that frontlines south of Bihac were also heating up .
Bosnian Croats , allied with Muslim-led government forces against the Serbs , claimed they captured three villages north of Kupres in central Bosnia .
A Croat militia and the Bosnian army took the town from the Serbs in a joint attack last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Croatian Serb forces also had shelled his forces across the border near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
Seven more peacekeepers were seized Tuesday from an observation post in Croatia , across the border from Bihac , a U.N. spokesman said Thursday .
Bosnian Serb units entered Croatia and took the Ukrainian soldiers and a U.N. armored carrier back into Bosnia , the spokesman , Alexander Ivanko , said .
More than 400 U.N. soldiers are being detained by the Serbs to deter NATO air raids .
NATO struck three times last week , but the attacks did nothing to stop the Serb assault on Bihac .
The Serbs also have been refusing to let U.N. relief convoys pass through Serb-held territory .
Monique Tuffelli , a staffer with the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in Bihac , said Thursday that food stocks would last only another week .
`` We have run out almost of everything , '' she said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press .
The Serbs repeatedly have rejected an international peace plan .
With the threat of international force appearing to dissipate , their position is hardening .
Momcilo Krajisnik , leader of the Bosnian Serbs ' self-proclaimed legislature , rejected a three-month truce , which the Bosnian government wants .
He said Serbs would only accept a permanent cease-fire .
The Sarajevo government fears a permanent cease-fire would cement Serb territorial gains of 70 percent of Bosnia .
The peace plan the Serbs rejected would give them 49 percent of the country .
Senior Western officials now talk of altering that plan to allow the Bosnian Serbs links with Serb-dominated Yugoslavia .
Opponents say that would be a step toward creation of Serb nationalists ' goal of a `` Greater Serbia . ''
Arianespace , the world leader in commercial satellite launching , apologized Friday after a dlrs 150 million U.S. communications satellite crashed into Atlantic , but said the client has signed on for another try .
Charles Bigot , Arianespace 's chief executive , said a failure in the third-stage engine caused an unmanned Ariane rocket to crash 15 minutes after takeoff Thursday from the launch center in French Guiana .
Aboard was a sophisticated communications satellite built by Hughes Space and Communications of El Segundo , Calif. , for PanAmSat , a Greenwich , Conn.-based firm .
The PamAmSat-3 satellite would have channeled telephone , fax and television communications for most of North and South America , Europe and Africa over 15 years , operating in geostationary orbit over the mid-Atlantic .
Bigot , answering reporters ' questions in a live hook-up from the launch center in South America , said it was too early to decide when Ariane launches would resume .
He said a preliminary report on the crash was due by mid-December .
He said the lost satellite had been insured , and PanAmSat was preparing a replacement satellite .
Despite the accident , Bigot said PanAmSat had signed a contract for Arianespace to launch another satellite by the end of 1996 .
`` While we are disappointed , PanAmSat has always recognized the risks inherent to this industry , '' said Fred Landman , PanAmSat 's president .
`` PanAmSat 's aggressive recovery plan reflects our commitment to provide high-quality satellite international services to our customers as soon as possible . ''
Arianespace technicians said the third-stage engine inexplicably lost pressure 218 kilometers -LRB- 135 miles -RRB- above Earth .
In January , a third-stage breakdown forced engineers to explode a rocket in mid-flight .
A Turkish and a European telecommunications satellites were also destroyed .
Six perfect launches followed .
Thursday 's crash was the seventh in 70 launches since the European Space Agency 's commercial Arianespace program lifted off 15 years ago .
It should not shake Ariane 's dominance as the No. 1 launcher of lucrative private satellites -- the company now holds about 70 percent of the market .
`` We hope to get back into operation very quickly , '' said Bigot , who apologized to the satellite 's owners .
Liftoff was on schedule , and the first two stages fired perfectly .
The third stage also lit properly , but then mysteriously sputtered and went out .
Officials said that the third stage was a new type using a new oxygen-hydrogen mixture to maximize performance .
January 's accident was blamed on a turbo-pump failure freezing the third-stage rocket motor .
That failure followed 26 straight successful launches in which the European rocket distanced itself from its competitors , the United States and China .
The Arianes have put 94 satellites in orbit and have a backlog of 38 , representing contracts worth more than 17 billion francs -LRB- dlrs 3.1 billion -RRB- .
Liquidators of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International have taken a new settlement plan for the failed bank to a Luxembourg court , court officials said Friday .
Judge Maryse Welter is to rule Jan. 12 on the plan to repay 250,000 creditors and depositors around the world some dlrs 10 billion , said court registrar Maryse Schumacher .
A creditors ' committee approved the plan in September .
It would provide dlrs 1.8 billion from the bank 's majority shareholders , the government and ruling family of Abu Dhabi .
Liquidators say the plan could repay creditors 30 to 40 cents on the dollar .
But many depositors worry their savings have disappeared in legal costs during the four years it has taken to wind up the bank .
An earlier settlement plan for BCCI depositors was shot down by a Luxembourg judge last year as too favorable to Abu Dhabi .
Abu Dhabi was to have paid dlrs 1.7 billion into a fund for creditors in the earlier deal .
The new deal increases the amount of money and changes the wording to accommodate what technical objections raised by the judges last year .
Schumacher said no creditors opposed the plan during two days of court hearings Wednesday and Thursday .
But a lawyer for Luxembourg 's banking supervisors , the Luxembourg Monetary Institute , argued against what it considers is still too easy a deal for Abu Dhabi .
Banking regulators closed BCCI branches around the world in July 1991 , leaving claims of about dlrs 10 billion .
Officials alleged BCCI was used to launder money for drug dealers and dictators around the globe , but some of the depositors who lost their money blame the troubles on lax regulation by the authorities , including the Bank of England .
Russian lawmakers trying to end a standoff in Chechnya accused their own government today of sending warplanes to attack the breakaway republic .
President Boris Yeltsin 's government has denied providiny military support to rebels trying to topple Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , even as the rebel offensive has escalated from small-arms fire to bombs .
Defense Minister Pavel Grachev says Russian mercenaries are fighting on both sides in Chechnya .
But Dudayev , who declared independence for his tiny Caucasus Mountain republic in 1991 , flatly accuses Moscow of leading and arming the rebels .
Air raids on the outskirts of Grozny , the Chechen capital , continued for a fourth day today .
`` It is clear that these planes are not English or French but Russian , '' said Ella Pamfilova , Yeltsin 's former social welfare minister and one of four members of a parliamentary delegation to Chechnya .
`` This is against the law . ''
Other members of the delegation , which met briefly with Dudayev , demanded an end to the air strikes , warning that the conflict could spiral out of control .
The lawmakers were trying to negotiate the release of about 70 Russians -- said to include Russian soldiers and officers -- captured in the fighting in Chechnya , a mostly Muslim republic in southern Russia .
Since the rebels ' air offensive began last week , thousands of people have fled Grozny , a city of 300,000 .
Chechen officials said there was a new round of air raids early today east of Grozny .
Dudayev said his home was bombed Thursday , but that claim could not be immediately verified .
Moscow does not recognize the independence of Chechnya , which became part of the Russian Empire in the 19th century after a series of long and bloody wars .
Yeltsin threatened Tuesday to send in troops unless the fighting had stopped by Thursday , but when the deadline expired he said Chechen fighters would be given amnesty if they put down their weapons by Dec. 15 .
Still , there were media reports of Russian troop buildups near the border .
`` Chauvinist forces in Russian are pushing President Yeltsin to act , saying he can not control ` little ' Chechnya , '' warned Vladimir Lysenko , a member of the parliamentary delegation .
Although Russian ultranationalists constantly lament the loss of Moscow 's empire , a recent opinion poll showed that most Russians are ready to let the Chechens go their own way .
Lysenko warned that the conflict is endangering the lives of as many as 150,000 ethnic Russians in Chechnya .
World champion Jansher Khan stayed on course for his seventh title of the season Friday when he beat England 's Del Harris in the semi-finals of the dlrs 96,000 Qatar International .
Khan , determined to win the Qatar tournament for the third successive year , totally outclassed Harris , the world ranked 20 , 15-4 , 15-3 , 15-10 in just 36 minutes .
