U.S. congressional clearance of a new world trade accord is expected to encourage ratification by other countries , allowing the mammoth export-boosting pact to take effect as planned on Jan. 1 .
Large and small nations alike are trying to rush the 22,000-page GATT agreement through national parliaments , often in low-key processes compared to the rocky ride through Congress .
Nearly 40 countries , including the United States , have now ratified the 124-nation agreement .
About 40 more -- including Japan , the European Union and Canada -- have said they will do so by year 's end .
The head of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade , Peter Sutherland , said Friday that U.S. passage was a `` triumph '' that will help make the world a more prosperous place .
`` This is a day for particular celebration , '' GATT Director-General Peter Sutherland told journalists .
`` The successful culmination of this debate proved that common sense still works . ''
France added a note of caution about a U.S. provision which would allow it to withdraw quickly from the WTO in the event of three adverse trade rulings deemed unfair .
France may now press the EU to take out a similar safeguard .
`` We have noted with satisfaction that Congress ratified the agreement , '' said a French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman , speaking on the usual condition of anonymity .
`` We are nevertheless concerned with certain aspects of the American application . ''
The U.S. Senate approved the GATT treaty by 76-24 votes late Thursday -- a much bigger margin than expected .
The House of Representatives cleared the deal earlier in the week .
Congressional approval , uncertain for weeks , was deemed crucial for the the World Trade Organization to take effect on Jan. 1 .
The WTO will implement the new accord and have more powers than GATT to settle trade disputes .
`` I warmly welcome the vote by the U.S. Senate , '' said European Union Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan , Europe 's chief negotiator in the talks .
He said the 12-nation bloc would complete the approval process by Dec. 20 .
In Japan , Trade Minister Rytaro Hashimoto said U.S. ratification of the deal would encourage other countries to follow suit .
Japan 's powerful lower house of parliament passed the accord early Friday and it will now move to the upper house .
This view was echoed by Hong Kong 's Director-General of Trade , Tony Miller .
`` The world looks to the United States for leadership in promoting free trade under the multilateral regime , '' Miller said .
In Canberra , Australian Trade Minister Bob McMullan said the U.S. result was `` great news for Australia and the world economy generally . ''
Sutherland said he expected about 100 of GATT 's 124 member nations to ratify the trade accord by the end of the year .
The agreement is considered the most ambitious attempt ever to knock down barriers to free world trade .
The pact is expected to boost global income by dlrs 510 billion by the year 2005 .
It reduces customs duties on hundreds of thousands of products , liberalizes trade in service industries , protects against copyright theft and patent abuse and cuts protection of farm goods and textiles .
`` We will have a rules-based system that allows for the development of the world economy and provides an assurance of security , prosperity and reduction of tensions , '' Sutherland said .
A man threatening to detonate a bomb in a Ukrainian nuclear power plant unless unless he received dlrs 1 million has been arrested , a security service spokesman said Friday .
The man , described only as `` Slav and young , '' was captured Thursday night after two days of telephone negotiations with `` high-level officials '' said Viktor Varenyk , Security Ministry press officer .
Varenyk said intelligence officers had so far failed to find any explosives in any of Ukraine 's five nuclear power plants , but had treated the threats as serious .
The incident was similar to a threat to blow up Lithuania 's main nuclear power plant earlier in November , unless a dlrs 8-million ransom was paid .
The Ignalina plant was shut down , but no explosives were found .
One man was arrested for that blackmail attempt .
The suspect captured in Kiev was taken into custody after police traced a telephone used by the caller , security officials said .
His capture came only hours before he was due to board a Lufthansa flight to Europe where a police trap had been laid for him .
Ukrainian state television showed pictures of a sealed box , said to contain over dlrs 650,000 , and cut diamonds valued at dlrs 350,000 being emptied from a Lufthansa bag .
The blackmailer had demanded to be flown to western Europe together with the loot .
Officials did not disclose where the explosives were alleged to have been planted , but the closest nuclear power station to Kiev is Chernobyl , site of the world 's worst nuclear power accident in 1986 .
Dozens of people died in the aftermath of an explosion in one of the plant 's four reactors and environmental groups say thousands have died since from fall-out of the radioactive cloud that swept across European nations .
The director of Chernobyl , Sergei Parashyn , told The Associated Press that security had been increased and the search was continuing for suspicious devices .
`` You know what happens in Chechnya with kidnaps and ransom demands , so anything is possible , '' he said .
Security at the station has been criticized as lax following the theft of ten nuclear fuel rods earlier this year .
Varenyk , said , `` this incident must , after Chernobyl and what it means to Ukrainians , be treated as more than a normal crime . ''
