A substantially bigger-than-expected gain in construction employment helped force the U.S. unemployment rate down two-tenths of a percent in November to the lowest level in four years .
The Labor Department said a seasonally adjusted 350,000 new workers were added to the nation 's nonfarm payrolls , pushing the unemployment rate to 5.6 percent from 5.8 percent in October .
That is the lowest level since August 1990 .
Labor Secretary Robert Reich called the report `` great news '' and evidence of a continued strong economic recovery .
`` I 've been calling it the Goldie Locks expansion .
It 's not too hot , it 's not too cold .
It 's not hot enough to ignite inflation , but it does n't seem to be cooling off at all , '' he said in an interview with The Associated Press .
`` This is really very impressive , '' said Robert G. Dederick , an economic consultant with Northern Trust Co. in Chicago .
`` The economy continues to surprise us on the up side .
The job market is still very vigorous . ''
Financial markets appeared to welcome the report .
Bond prices advanced , with the yield on the U.S. Treasury 's benchmark 30-year issue falling to 7.95 percent from 8.01 percent late Thursday ; the dollar surged , rising above 100 yen for the first time in nearly two months ; stock prices were mixed in early trading .
The jobless rate has been declining all year , dropping 1.1 percent since January .
The nation 's nonfarm payrolls have increased by 2.6 million people this year .
The report suggests the economy is still growing at a robust pace and employment growth remains strong .
However , the government 's chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity pointed in the other direction , falling in October for the first time in 15 months .
The Index of Leading Economic Indicators slipped 0.1 percent in October .
In another report , the government said orders to U.S. factories fell in October for the first time in three months , led by a sharp drop for cars and other transportation equipment .
In advance of the unemployment report , most economists were expecting the unemployment rate to remain at 5.8 percent and nonfarm payrolls to increase by about 250,000 workers .
Even the most optimistic analysts were expecting an increase no bigger than 280,000 jobs .
Strong employment growth this year was one of the factors that prompted the Federal Reserve to raise short-term interest rates last month for a sixth time this year .
Last month , the central bank raised key rates three-quarters of a percentage point , the largest increase in 13 years .
Higher interest rates are meant to curb inflation , which bothers investors because it lowers the value of their holdings .
Marilyn Schaja , an economist with Donaldson , Lufkin and Jenrette Securities in New York said the report could provide impetus for another round of interest rate increases .
She said with the unemployment rate as low as it is `` we are going to see some inflationary pressures . ''
The large number of new hires was boosted by unexpectedly robust growth in construction employment .
The Labor Department said 71,000 jobs were added to construction industry payrolls in November .
Katharine G. Abraham , commissioner of the Bureau of Labor Statistics , said construction employment benefited from the return of some construction employees in the Southeast who had been unable to work because of heavy rains in October .
A modest 4,000 construction jobs were added in October .
Manufacturing employment also was robust , jumping 51,000 after increases of just over 18,000 in the previous three months .
Abraham said gains were recorded in manufacturing of durable goods , including lumber , fabricated metals , industrial machinery and electronic equipment .
Volkwagen 's worldwide sales are up 7.1 percent in the first 10 months of this year but the automaker is still in early stages of its rebuilding , managing board chief Ferdinand Piech said Friday .
