Seattle Seahawks running back Chris Warren of the Seattle Seahawks was arrested after a car he was driving crashed into a utility pole , injuring him and two teammates .
One player , recently acquired defensive tackle Michael Frier , was critically hurt .
Warren , 27 , the fourth-leading rusher in the U.S. National Football League this season ; rookie running back Lamar Smith , 24 ; and a third player who was not unidentified pending notification of his parents , were taken to Overlake Medical Center in Bellevue after the Thursday night crash .
Frier has a severe neck injury and was listed in critical condition early Friday , said team orthopedic surgeon Pierce Scranton .
He would not say if Frier was paralyzed .
Warren , who suffered two cracked ribs , was treated and released .
Smith had chip fractures in his spine and ankle and was hospitalized overnight .
Warren , driving a Chevy Blazer -- a small truck-like vehicle , was arrested at the scene for investigation of vehicular assault , Sgt. Mark Smith said .
Smith said it appeared Warren was driving too fast for the rain-slicked road .
The crash set the utility pole on fire and the players had to be pulled from the vehicle by passersby and firefighters , Smith said .
Police would not comment on whether drugs or alcohol were involved .
Warren was released on his own recognizance , police dispatcher Jill Roberts said .
The accident happened about 8:40 p.m. near the team 's training center .
`` You read about it , you hear about it , but when it happens to somebody very close it really is a shock , '' Seahawks coach Tom Flores told KIRO radio early today .
`` It 's something that we all have to keep praying for that they all recover . ''
The power line suspended on the pole was severed in the collision , causing a large electrical flash and disabling three substations , said Kristen Wappler , a spokeswoman for Puget Sound Power and Light Co.
The accident knocked out electricity to some 4,500 Puget Power customers for about an hour .
Warren , a fifth-year , Pro Bowl running back , is the first Seahawks player to rush for 1,000 yards in three consecutive seasons .
He started this week as the second-leading rusher in the American conference with 1,096 yards , just 5 yards behind San Diego 's Natrone Means .
He also is second in the AFC in total yards .
The Seahawks play Indianapolis Sunday in the Kingdome .
The accident was the latest in a number of auto accidents involving NFL players this season .
Dallas offensive lineman Erik Williams was lost for the season when he tore knee ligaments in an Oct. 24 crash .
Williams pleaded no contest to drunken driving .
Teammate Shante Carver , a defensive end , also was involved in an accident in October when his speeding truck crashed into a concrete retaining wall .
The U.S. Postal Service on Friday defended its stamp recalling the atomic bombing of Japan saying that it could not omit such a major event from its World War II history series .
The stamp , showing a mushroom-shaped cloud rising from an atomic blast , is one of a set of 10 stamps marking major events of 1945 to be sold on a sheet titled `` 1945 : Victory at Last . ''
Forty stamps have already been issued in similar sets for the 50th anniversary of the 1941-44 war years .
But the atomic bomb stamp is drawing sharp criticism in Japan .
Sunao Tsuboi , acting director of the 30,000-member Hiroshima Prefectural Confederation of A-bomb Survivors Organizations , termed it `` outrageous . ''
Japan surrendered Aug. 15 , 1945 , days after atomic bombs were dropped on the cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki .
`` Atomic bombs hasten war 's end , August 1945 , '' says the caption on the mushroom cloud stamp .
Postal Service spokesman Robin Wright said the World War II series was developed in cooperation with the State and Defense departments to assure historical accuracy .
As far as the atomic bomb stamp , he said , `` we would be remiss in omitting such a watershed and historically critical event as the use of the atomic bomb . ''
`` Our purpose is to provide a comprehensive history of events of World War II , and we are not making a value judgment on any of those events , '' Wright added .
Other stamps in the 1945 set picture U.S. Marines raising the American flag on Iwo Jima , `` Okinawa , the last big battle , '' liberations of Manila and of Holocaust survivors in Europe , Germany 's surrender at Reims , refugees uprooted by war and U.S. celebrations of Japanese surrender .
The 1941 set , titled `` A World at War '' included stamps showing Japanese bombing Pearl Harbor , Hawaii , and President Roosevelt and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill framing the Atlantic Charter .
The 1944 set , titled `` Road to Victory '' included the allied Normandy landings , the liberation of Rome and the battles of Leyte Gulf in the Pacific and the Bulge in Belgium .
Police have seized 16 tons of raw material for the production of drugs and arrested an unspecified number of people , including pharmaceutical managers , police officials said Friday .
The material was bound for illegal laboratories abroad where they were supposed to be used for the production of drugs , among them Rohypnol , a sedative used by drug addicts in the west .
According to published reports , local police have been working for several weeks with West European experts before they cracked down on the drug ring .
But police officials were tight-lipped , referring to an ongoing investigation .
During the swoop , a group of high-ranking officials of the state-run pharmaceutical producer Sopharma , including manager Anton Petrov , were detained .
So were executives of a private company reportedly involved in selling the drugs abroad .
Also in custody was a customs official , newspapers said .
She was said to have prepared the documents necessary for export .
According to media reports , police also arrested two Dutch citizens belived to be part of a ring trying to smuggling the material abroad .
The amount of chemicals already smuggled out of the country was not known .
Adolphe Sax , the saxophone inventor whom President Clinton paid tribute to in June , is being honored here starting Saturday with fanfare marking the centennial of his death .
Concerts , radio broadcasts and roundtable discussions about the future of saxophone teaching are scheduled this month by the French National Conservatory of Music and the Army Museum .
The festivities begin Saturday with performances of works by Poulenc , Offenbach and others .
Sax , who died Feb. 7 , 1894 in Paris , unveiled the revolutionary new instrument in 1844 to great critical acclaim .
Music critics said its rich and varied sounds captured the emotional inflections of the human voice better than any other instrument .
The saxophone has been a longtime favorite among jazz buffs , including Clinton , who made an unscheduled detour to Sax 's birthplace in Dinant , Belgium , three days after D-Day celebrations in France last June .
Joe Montana said a published report of his retirement from the National Football League is wrong , and he angrily criticized the media for reporting an unsubstantiated story .
`` It 's ridiculous , '' the Kansas City quarterback said Friday at Arrowhead Stadium during his weekly news conference .
`` I had n't heard about it until I got here today .
I think , first of all , you guys are going to start having to stand up for what you write .
It hurts the credibility of your field . ''
The New York Daily News reported Friday that Montana would retire at the end of the NFL season .
The newspaper quoted unidentified league sources and did not elaborate .
There was no answer at newspaper 's sports department this morning when an attempt was made to get comment .
Montana sprained a foot in Sunday 's loss to Seattle and rumors started that he would be out for a lengthy period and would not be back next year .
`` I 've got a sprained ankle and some guy writes that I 'm retiring , '' Montana said .
`` I had a hangnail last week and he did n't write about that . ''
`` It 's irritating .
It 's irritating that you have to put people through this .
It 's irritating that I should have to stand up here and go through this , '' Montana said .
He said chances are `` pretty slim '' that he will be able to play against Denver Sunday in Kansas City .
He said the ankle feels better but is still sore .
Asked earlier about the New York Daily News report , Chiefs spokesman Bob Moore said that Montana has always said he would make no decision until after the end of the season .
Moore said `` it is just natural that from now until the end of the season there will be all kinds of speculation about Montana 's future plans . ''
Montana , 38 , spent 14 seasons with the San Francisco 49ers and helped them win four Super Bowls .
After playing just one game in 1991 and 1992 , he was traded to Kansas City in April , 1993 , along with safety David Whitmore and a third-round draft pick in exchange for a first-round draft choice that the 49ers later traded away .
Montana was reported to have considered retirement last season after sustaining a concussion in Kansas City 's AFC championship game loss in Buffalo .
Until last Sunday , this season was relatively injury-free for Montana .
Pope John Paul II on Friday urged Roman Catholic bishops in Iran to perservere in the faith despite the difficulties they face .
Without mentioning Iran 's fundamentalist Muslim government , the pope said he was aware that the bishops ' pastoral work '' often is difficult and regularly hindered for different reasons tied to the present situation . ''
He exhorted the visiting bishops of Tehran and Isfahan to '' keep alive the presence of the Church . ''
Catholics in Iran number about 12,000 , out of a Christian population of 200,000 .
Also Friday , a senior Iranian cleric said in a sermon in Tehran that Christianity is a '' lifeless corpse propped up only by the institution of a centralized papacy . ''
Ayatollah Ahmad Jannati said the Christian religion is '' truly lacking in divine and religious spirituality . ''
Christians in Iran practice under close supervision and strict regulation .
Negotiators trying to save the North American ice hockey season season kept bargaining Friday following an eight-hour session that apparently made progress on some of the key issues in the 63-day lockout .
National Hockey League Management and player union representatives resumed negotiations at a downtown hotel , mindful that a labor agreement probably will have to be in place within two weeks to salvage a 50-game season .
`` I do n't know about a Dec. 15 deadline .
Negotiations are ongoing , '' union head Bob Goodenow said after the sides exchanged proposals Thursday .
`` People have to deal with the realities of the situation , and we 're working on that . ''
Neither side would characterize the talks , but a source told the Canadian Press the session was `` good , but not great . ''
Among the issues discussed were a rookie salary cap , salary arbitration and free agency .
But the major obstacle , the luxury tax , was apparently set aside for the moment .
NHL commissioner Gary Bettman did not speak to reporters following the meetings Thursday .
`` He 's feeling a little bit exhausted right now because they worked very hard .
Both sides worked hard , '' league spokesman Arthur Pincus said .
`` Talking is the only way to make a deal .
So talks continuing has to be taken as that all by itself .
I do n't want to characterize it any more than that . ''
Since the owners locked out the players Oct. 1 , the season has been pared to 60 games , with 24 games stripped from each team .
CP reported the union has dropped its desired salary ceiling to dlrs 1.25 million from dlrs 1.5 million for first-round players , while the NHL remained at dlrs 700,000 .
On salary arbitration , the NHL wants to retain its right to have an arbitrator 's decision to be non-binding on the team .
Rather than paying the awarded salary , a team could allow the player to become an unrestricted free agent .
The league also proposed that only two players per team per year be eligible for salary arbitration .
The NHLPA wants arbitration to be binding .
The two sides agreed that , in an arbitration case , an unrestricted free agent 's contract can not be used to provide comparisons and arrive at a decision , a source told CP .
On free agency , both sides agreed that players shall become unrestricted free agents upon reaching age 28 .
Each team would be allowed to designate one player as a franchise player .
The NHL Players Association agreed to this proposal .
The franchise player could be kept three years beyond his 28th birthday .
The owners want the franchise player to be the highest-paid player on the team , while the NHLPA 's position is that the franchise player would be any player earning the average of the top 26 salaries in the league -- about dlrs 3 million a season .
The Croatian government and leaders of the rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement Friday that could lead to normalized relations between the two enemies .
The pact calls for restoring water and electricity supplies and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital Belgrade .
Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220 mile -RRB- highway are controlled by Croatian Serbs .
Representatives of the Croatian government signed the accord Friday morning at U.N. headquarters in Zagreb , with international mediators Lord David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg as co-signers .
The document was then brought to Knin , rebel Serb headquarters , where their leaders signed it .
`` The significance of the agreement is going to depend on the parties to the agreement , '' Owen told The Associated Press in Knin .
`` For many people it has been senseless to be deprived of water , electricity , '' Owen added .
`` The basics of economic life can now be made available to all . ''
A six-month war in 1991 -- at the start of the violent breakup of Yugoslavia -- left Serbs in control of one-third of Croatian territory .
There have been thousands of skirmishes and larger confrontations between the two since a January 1992 ceasefire halted the war .
The two sides traded artillery fire southeast of Knin for the third day Friday .
Croatian Serb representative Borislav Mikelic , though signing the agreement , remained firm in the Serbs ' refusal to accept any reintegration with Croatia .
`` By signing this agreement we once more proved that we are in favor of a peaceful solution to the crisis here and we also showed that we 're interested in the economic progress and economic opening to Europe and the world , '' Mikelic said .
But he refused to discuss the crucial overall political solution , saying , `` This is not the time to talk about it . ''
The self-styled Croatian Serb assembly , after a nearly eight-hour , closed-door session , approved the economic accord late Thursday .
Negotiations between the two sides had been stalled .
But the Croatian Serbs relented after a recent clandestine meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic , the Balkans power broker .
Thousands of peacekeepers have been deployed between the warring sides in the disputed territories since the 1992 cease-fire .
But international efforts toward lasting peace have failed over what seemed to be irreconcilable differences .
This is the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their 1991 war .
