Italian coast guard says Achille Lauro has sunk .
The Achille Lauro sunk Friday as tug boats were preparing to tow the charred cruise liner , the Italian coast guard said .
The ship , which was listing in waters off Somalia , went under at 1610 gmt , said coast guard Lt. Francesco D'Amico .
He said the ship was not recoverable .
No more information was immediately available , he said .
The Italian coast guard in Rome has been coordinating rescue operations after the ship caught fire en route to South Africa Wednesday .
A state-of-the-art music complex geared to make music more accessible to the general public will open Jan. 12 on the site of the city 's former slaughterhouses .
`` This is not just another concert hall for the city of Paris , '' Toubon said this week .
`` It is expected to promote a new social relationship between music and the general public . ''
La Cite de la Musique , or City of Music , located on the northern edge of the capital , is another of President Francois Mitterrand 's architectural projects that have changed the Paris cityscape in the past decade .
Designed by Christian de Portzamparc at a cost of 1.1 billion francs -LRB- about dlrs 200 million -RRB- , the complex resembles an immense sea shell , with a interior spiral gallery and wide alley leading to several separate concert and work spaces .
`` Our goal is to attract music lovers of all ages , '' said Brigitte Marger , the center 's director .
It will have a 1,100-person concert hall , information and documentation centers , and a music cafe open until 2 a.m.
It will also house France 's acclaimed Ensemble Intercontemporain , a contemporarry music orchestra , headed by Pierre Boulez .
Israel 's prime minister on Friday discounted fears that Syria 's leader was losing hope in peace talks with Israel .
His comments came as Syria appeared to harden its negotiating stance after a nine-month stalemate in peace talks .
On Friday , it accused Israel of thinking more about `` war and aggression '' than peace and stability in the Middle East .
`` Israel is determined to follow its policy of armament and power-building to intimidate the Arabs and push them to accept partial and weak solutions , '' the government-run Al-Thawra newspaper said .
`` Be neither alarmed nor unmoved , '' Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin told newspaper editors meeting in Tel Aviv .
Syria should follow the example of the PLO and Jordan , which both reached accords with Israel since Rabin took office in mid-1992 , in establishing a direct dialogue with the Israeli government , Rabin said .
On Thursday , Syrian leader Hafez Assad said the status quo was preferable to formal peace under Israel 's conditions .
Israeli-Syrian negotiations have been deadlocked over the Golan Heights .
Syria demands that Israel return the entire plateau , which it captured in 1967 .
Israel has offered only a phased , partial pullback .
Israel also demands Syria dismantle Iranian-backed militias in Lebanon .
Secretary of State Warren Christopher is to return to the region Tuesday to resume his shuttle mediation between Damascus and Jerusalem .
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher on Friday dismissed as incorrect reports that NATO had decided to stop enforcing a U.N. no-fly zone over Bosnia .
The ban on military flights is designed to protect the civilians from bombardment in the 31-month war .
`` NATO is continuing to enforce the no-fly zone , '' Christopher said .
He told reporters Serb anti-missile batteries posed a problem .
But , he said , NATO was capable of dealing with them `` and we continue to police the no-fly zone in the effective way we have in the past . ''
