The leader of Quebec 's separatist movement is recovering from surgery to amputate his left leg and is out of danger , a hospital official said Friday .
Lucien Bouchard , a central and charismatic leader of the separatist bloc , had the leg amputated Thursday , two days after being hospitalized for a blood clot that became infected .
Robert Racine , deputy director of Saint-Luc Hospital , denied rumors Friday that Bouchard had taken a turn for the worse .
`` On the contrary it 's all going well , '' said Racine .
`` He 's out of danger . ''
Radio-Canada and CTV , a Canadian television network , reported that Bouchard has a rare flesh-eating disease known as necrotizing fasciitis , which has been linked to about a dozen deaths in Britain , one in Canada and few in other countries .
Bouchard 's emergency hospitalization throws into doubt the role the Bloc Quebecois leader will play in next year 's critical referendum on separation .
French-speaking Quebec has long sought some form of sovereignty or separation from the rest of Canada , which is largely English-speaking .
Radio-Canada reported late Thursday that doctors first amputated Bouchard 's foot and then his leg .
Bouchard 's doctor , Patrick D'Amico , said in a statement that the separatist leader developed an infection on his leg after being hospitalized on Tuesday .
`` This situation necessitated two operations to drain and amputate the leg and control the infection , '' said D'Amico .
The rapidly-spreading flesh-eating disease is caused by a virulent form of streptococcus bacteria that enters the body through a cut or a wound and produces an infection .
Widely considered the most compelling Quebec separatist leader , the charismatic Bouchard 's absence from the upcoming referendum battle would be a blow to forces seeking Quebec 's secession .
Quebec Premier Jacques Parizeau prevailed on Bouchard to show the same courage he has regularly displayed in the political arena .
`` Our prayers are with you , '' said a shaken Parizeau .
`` I hope this will soon be just a bad dream .
Hold on old friend . ''
A Bloc Quebecois spokesman refused to provide more details on Bouchard 's condition .
Bouchard is with him now , '' Marthe Lawrence , Bouchard 's spokesperson , said from the hospital .
`` The family wishes no further statement for the moment . ''
Bouchard became leader of the opposition after his fledgling party swept Quebec in the 1993 federal election , winning 54 out of 75 seats in the province .
Seventy Dutch U.N. peacekeepers detained by Bosnian Serb forces were released Friday , the Defense Ministry announced .
The peacekeepers , who were taken hostage Saturday near Zvornik in eastern Bosnia , left Bosnian Serb territory Friday morning for Zagreb .
The soldiers were in good condition , and none were physically abused , the ministry said , adding that the soldiers would arrive in the Netherlands on Saturday .
The release of the 70 peacekeepers leaves 20 in Bosnian Serb custody in nearby Papraca .
The Dutch peacekeepers were held with about 300 other soldiers , mostly British , as insurance against further NATO airstrikes .
NATO warplanes struck three times last week , but the attacks did nothing to stop the Serb assault on the Bosnian enclave of Bihac .
