After a slow start , Haiti is moving swiftly to solidify its democratic institutions , appointing a new 11-member Supreme Court and formally placing the army-controlled police under civilian command .
In another supportive step , 250 former Haitian boat people were heading home Friday to become members of the internationally supervised interim police force .
The separation of the police and military , stipulated in the 1987 Constitution , was approved by the Senate on Wednesday night but only announced on Friday .
It will become law when it appears in the official government gazette , Le Moniteur .
`` The armed forces reform law is a historic break with our repressive political past , '' Sen. Jean-Robert Martinez told The Associated Press .
The appointment of new Supreme Court is another building block to establishing civil justice in a land that has been ruled by the gun for most of its history .
The new chief justice , Clauzel Debrosse , had been an existing member of the Supreme Court but an opponent of the military overthrow in 1991 of elected President Jean-Bertrand Aristide , who returned to power in October after U.S. military intervention .
`` We wanted to reward Debrosse for his opposition to de facto rule , '' said Martinez , an Aristide supporter .
Aristide , in conformity with the constitution , chose the judges from a Senate list of three for each seat .
The array of judicial moves reflects the desire by Aristide to strengthen civilian authority as rapidly as possible .
Thousands of American and other foreign troops are guaranteeing the peace now , but U.S. Republican leaders are urging the Clinton administration to hasten the pullout of GIs .
The widely popular Aristide , wary of those who overthrew him three years ago , is quickly reassigning senior military officers to overseas posts .
U.S. Embassy spokesman Stanley Schrager confirmed Friday that former Haitian military chief Jean-Claude Duperval was being transferred to a diplomatic post in Brazil and Brig. Gen. Max Mayard was heading to a similar military attache position in Ecuador .
The other two generals during the 1991-4 military rule , Lt. Gen. Raoul Cedras and Brig. Gen. Philippe Biamby , quit and fled to self-imposed exile in Panama two days before Aristide 's return .
Aristide has pledged to slice the size of the army from 7,500 to 1,500 and to create a 4,000-member civilian police force .
The 250 Haitians joining the interim police force Friday were recruited and trained in the refugee tent camp at the U.S. base in Guantanamo Bay , Cuba .
They were among tens of thousands of Haitians who fled their nation under military rule .
Another 750 refugees-turned-police will arrive in Haiti in the next three weeks , Schrager , the U.S. spokesman , told the AP .
`` In coming weeks , they will be used in police support positions by both the Haitian government and the I.P.M. , '' said Paul Browne , spokesman for the 800-member 20-nation International Police Monitor corps that is supervising police work .
IAAF president Primo Nebiolo indicated Friday his federation is prepared to share some of its revenues from the 1996 Atlanta Olympics to help promote track and field in the United States .
`` If the Olympics give us the means , and I believe they will , we will use whatever we get to help the United States , '' Nebiolo said .
`` We want to create a great project in the United States because it has the most fantastic athletes in the world .
This is a nation that should be our athletics locomotive . ''
Nebiolo said any form of aid would be decided in concert with USA Track and Field and the U.S. Olympic Committee .
Nebiolo did not specify how he would help , but International Amateur Athletic Federation spokesman Christopher Winner said the world body could contribute some of its Olympic television and sponsorship revenues to assist USA Track and Field .
`` It 's an IAAF Marshall Plan , '' Winner said , referring to the massive U.S. aid project for Europe after World War II .
Although many of the world 's top track and field stars are Americans , the sport has suffered from a lack of exposure and popularity in the United States .
On another issue , Nebiolo said the timetable for track and field events in Atlanta was still under study and no fixed date had been set to annouce the schedule .
The timetable has been held up by debate over the timing of the men 's marathon .
The IAAF wants to start the race in late afternoon to culminate with the Games ' closing ceremony , but several runners and medical experts have said it would be hazardous to compete at that hour in Atlanta 's notorious heat and humidity .
Most of the 608 passengers aboard the Cebu City were sleeping when a freighter slammed into the ferry Friday in Manila Bay .
The ferry sank a half hour later , a one-meter -LRB- three-foot -RRB- hole in the lower deck .
At least 34 people drowned .
Of the 100 still missing , an unknown number went down with the ship , lying under 30 meters -LRB- 90 feet -RRB- of water .
Divers could see their bodies but could not get to them before dark when the search for survivors was called off for the night .
`` Suddenly we heard a crash , '' Erwin Maravilla said .
`` I grabbed my two children , but when the ferry sank we were sucked under the water with it .
A piece of metal hit my arm , and I lost hold of my two kids . ''
His wife also was among the missing .
Ships in the area plucked 451 people from the sea , many coated with the diesel oil disgorged as the ferry sank .
The freighter , the Singapore-registered Kota Suria , joined in the rescue effort , its bow badly bent .
Survivors complained the crew did little to save people .
The radio room may have been severely damaged because the distress signals came from other ships .
Maximo Calamba , who was rescued with his wife and 1-year-old son , said he heard many cries for help .
`` There was no alarm .
We were thrown off our cots and everybody was on their own . ''
The collision occurred before dawn near the town of Rosario , about 55 kilometers -LRB- 35 miles -RRB- southwest of Manila .
The freighter , five times the ferry 's size , destroyed the bridge and tore a gaping hole in the lower deck .
The captain and his mates were in the bridge , the control section of the ferry , said one crewman , Jacob Cabatuan .
They were among the missing .
The cause of the accident , which occurred in calm seas under clear night skies , is under investigation .
The company that owns the ferry said it was rammed .
Danny Dalugdog , a driver and bodyguard , was separated from his wife and 3-month-old son in the confusion .
`` I thought they were gone . ''
But he found his wife on the freighter .
Then , as they transferred to a coast guard ship to return to Manila , a passenger called out that he found a baby boy .
`` It turned out to be my son , '' Dalugdog said .
A coast guard spokesman , Lt. Cmdr. Amado Samante , said 451 passengers had been rescued and 34 bodies recovered , many children and women .
`` There were more bodies inside the cabins , '' said Angel Espidido , a coast guard diver .
Divers could see the dead through the portholes but were unable to open the doors late Friday .
`` Tomorrow we will go back to unlock them . ''
Cargo containers and rubber rafts floated in the sea , but many survivors apparently never got a chance to use them .
`` I was jolted by the crash and I woke up , '' said Melissa Selosia , who was on her way to going to Mindanao Island , 780 kilometers -LRB- 485 miles -RRB- south of Manila for Christmas with her four children .
`` I grabbed a life jacket and made for the upper deck and then I jumped into the water . ''
She said she swam as quickly as possible from the sinking ferry , recalling her seaman husband 's words that a sinking boat will suck down everything around it .
The ferry 's owner , the William Lines shipping company , said 608 people were on board .
The accident coincided with the company 's initial public stock offering Friday .
The ferry , which can carry 800 people , was en route to Tagbilaran , capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- southeast of Manila .
The worst peacetime ferry disaster occurred in the Philippines in December 1987 when 4,341 people died in the collision of the ferry Dona Paz with the oil tanker Vector off Mindoro Island , 130 kilometers -LRB- 80 miles -RRB- south of Manila .
The Achille Lauro sunk off East Africa Friday as a tugboat was preparing to tow away the charred cruise liner .
The ship , which was listing in waters off Somalia , went under at 1610 gmt , or 7 p.m. local time , said Italian coast guard Lt. Francesco D'Amico .
He said the ship was not recoverable .
'' She was hooked up to the -LRB- tug -RRB- Solano and in 10 minutes , she collapsed -- pfft , she disappeared , '' said Antonio De Rosa , marketing director for Achille 's owner , Starlauro .
'' She was already in bad condition , '' he said , adding it was not immediately clear what caused the ship to go down so suddenly .
De Rosa valued the loss at dlrs 25 million .
The Italian coast guard in Rome has been coordinating rescue operations after the ship caught fire en route to South Africa Wednesday .
Starlauro had hired sea-going tugs to bring the Achille Lauro home .
Swedish divers prowled inside the sunken ferry Estonia for the first time Friday , finding decks `` demolished '' after the ship 's 60-meter plunge to the Baltic Sea floor .
Maritime authorities declined to say whether the divers found any bodies in the wreck , where an estimated 800 people were entombed when the ferry sank on Sept. 28 .
`` It 's extremely demolished , '' Swedish maritime administration spokesman Lars-Goran Bronow told the news agency TT .
`` It happened when the ship turned upside down . ''
The ferry sank in about 30 minutes after a storm ripped off its front cargo door .
Investigators say it capsized and probably rolled over completely before hitting bottom .
It now lies on its side 56-84 meters -LRB- 180-280 feet -RRB- under water off Finland 's southwestern coast .
Divers had examined two of the ship 's six decks as of Friday afternoon .
Weather permitting , teams of six divers plan to work in shifts around the clock for four days surveying the ship 's interior , authorities said .
They will work their way into the bridge , where authorities hope to retreive navigational computers and other records that might provide clues about what happened , Bronow said .
`` The weather conditions are good .
The weather wo n't hinder the work , '' Bronow told TT earlier .
Working in near-freezing water , the divers ' mission is to gather evidence to help authorities decide whether to raise the ship , retreive the bodies or take some other action .
Of the estimated 1,049 people on the ferry , 137 survived , according to the latest figures published Friday by the Finnish police .
Only 94 bodies have been recovered .
The rest are believed in the ship , although officials have said they may never know the exact number because of unreliable passenger lists .
Authorities said they will not disclose any divers ' information about bodies .
Each diver was required to sign a contract barring him from describing the scene to anybody but investigators and officials , Swedish media reported .
`` -LRB- This -RRB- mission does not include bringing anybody to the surface , '' Swedish Communications Minister Ines Uusmann told the newspaper Aftonbladet .
Swedish authorities hope to decide on a course of action by mid-December , and were focusing on several options .
In one , salvagers could scour the wreck to retrieve all the bodies they find , or could do that plus flip it over using cables to find more bodies .
They also could leave all the bodies and fill the wreck with sand to `` bury '' the victims and protect the wreck from scavengers .
The divers are working from a large , floating research platform called SEMI 1 .
The work was scheduled to begin Wednesday , but was delayed because the ships apparently had been given the wrong coordinates for the wreck .
The Swedish government , meanwhile , said Friday it has decided to give 3 million kronor -LRB- dlrs 417,000 -RRB- to organizations helping victims ' families , in many cases including orphans .
Police have seized 16 tons of raw material for the production of drugs and arrested an unspecified number of people , including pharmaceutical managers , police officials said Friday .
The material was headed for illegal laboratories abroad where they were supposed to be used for the production of drugs , among them Rohypnol , a sedative used by drug addicts in the west .
Local police have reportedly been working for several weeks with West European experts before they cracked down on the drug ring .
During the swoop , a group of high-ranking officials of the state-run pharmaceutical producer Sopharma , including manager Anton Petrov , were detained .
So were executives of a private company reportedly involved in selling the drugs abroad .
According to media reports , police also arrested two Dutch citizens belived to be part of a ring trying to smuggling the material abroad .
The amount of chemicals already smuggled out of the country was not known .
