Serbian police have arrested 156 ethnic Albanians , all former police officers , in the restive Kosovo province , the public prosecutor announced Friday .
In the first official confirmation of the crackdown over the past ten days , Serbian prosecutor Miodrag Brkljac said the ethnic Albanians were members of an illegal group which planned `` armed rebellion against '' Serbia .
It was the biggest police raid in Kosovo since 1989 when Serbia revoked the autonomy of its southern province , where ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the 1.9 million population .
Serbian police now keep a firm grip on any ethnic Albanian dissent .
Ethnic Albanian officials , who have formed a parallel structures in Kosovo , staunchly deny that they plan any armed rebellion against Serbia , saying that would be against their peaceful resistance policy .
However , the prosecutor told reporters that the detained ethnic Albanians had formed `` a parallel army , collected information about -LRB- Serbian -RRB- police and the military and planned liquidation of prominent Serbs in Kosovo . ''
Azem Vlasi , representing the arrested , claimed that the detained `` are being physically harassed in order to confess . ''
An independent Serbian human rights organization protested the arrests , saying they show that `` the regime is suppressing the alternative government in Kosovo by violating human rights and intimidating citizens . ''
Serbia regards Kosovo the cradle of its history and culture and has vowed never to give it up to the ethnic Albanians who seek independence .
Human rights groups sharply criticized Russian authorities Friday for carrying out a Turkmen request to detain a leading dissident .
The Federal Counterintelligence Service last week detained Murad Esenov , a correspondent for Radio Liberty and prominent Turkmen activist living in Moscow .
Human rights groups linked Esenov 's detention to a recent crackdown on opposition activity by Turkmen President Saparmurat Niyazov .
According to the group Human Rights Watch-Helsinki , Niyazov called for the arrest and repatriation of several leading critics , including Esenov , in order `` to neutralize the activities of the traitors of the homeland . ''
Human Rights Watch also said Esenov was badly beaten in a street attack in Moscow in October in an attack that may have been politically motivated .
It said he was awaiting extradition in a Moscow jail .
Acting Russian Prosecutor General Alexei Ilyushenko confirmed that Esenov was detained after a delegation from Turkmenistan came to Moscow with a request for his arrest .
But , Ilyushekno told a news conference , the request was not properly documented , and Esenov was only being detained while an investigation is carried out .
Ilyushenko said there were no immediate plans to send Esenov and several other detained Turkmen dissidents back home .
`` Nobody is talking about extraditing them .
They have not been arrested , they have been detained , '' he said .
The Nezavisimaya Gazeta newspaper said Esenov had received phone threats saying that if he did not stop his dissident activity he would be deported to Turkmenistan .
Russia 's constitution forbids extraditing anyone for political activity , but if Turkmen authorities can provide evidence of criminal offenses , Esenov and the other dissidents may be sent back .
Once back in Turkmenistan , the dissidents could face the death penalty .
Niyazov was Turkmenistan 's former Communist Party boss and has been its president since Soviet times .
After a referendum last January , he will be allowed to remain in office until June 21 , 2002 .
Both Azerbaijan and Armenia have also appealed to Russia to extradite opposition leaders in recent months .
