Nick Faldo of England shot eight birdies Friday for a record-tying 64 and a seven-stroke lead after two rounds of the Million Dollar Challenge golf tournament .
Faldo 's 130 total -- 14 under par -- at the halfway point set a tournament record , and the 64 score tied Lee Trevino for lowest round on the par 72 Gary Player Country Club course .
A second-place finisher three times in the tournament with golf 's richest first prize -- dlrs 1 million -- Faldo finished seven shots ahead of British Open champion Nick Price of Zimbabwe and Bernhard Langer of Germany , with U.S. Open champion Ernie Els of South Africa another shot back .
Like in the first round , Faldo 's precision kept him out of trouble and set up repeated birdie putts with the cross-hand grip adopted in September .
He made eight birdies for the second straight day , and shot par the rest of the way to improve over the first-day 66 that included two bogies .
`` That was the best nine holes I have ever played , '' Faldo said of back nine , when he birdied five straight holes and two others for a 29 .
`` I 'm going off now to find some starch and spray myself to see if I can stay in this mode , '' he joked , adding : `` This is as good as I have ever played .
Perhaps my swing had a little more zip in 1989 , but technically I am a better player now . ''
Price , the world 's top rated player this year and defending champion , came back from a poor-putting first round 71 to fire a six-under 66 , while Langer followed his first day 68 with a three-under 69 .
Both were at 137 , one shot ahead of Els , who shot a two-under 70 Friday after a four-under 68 in the first round .
David Frost of South Africa and Tom Lehman of the United States tied at four-under-par 140 , 10 strokes off the pace , followed by Mark McNulty of Zimbabwe and Corey Pavin of the United States at 141 , American Hale Irwin at 142 and Colin Montgomerie of Scotland at 143 .
Seve Ballesteros of Spain at 147 and Vijay Singh of Fiji at 153 brought up the rear .
Faldo said he intended to keep playing aggressively despite his large lead in the 12-player tournament that includes 11 of the 20 top rated golfers in the world .
`` I ca n't afford to get too defensive or some of these guys can shoot a great round and get within a couple of shots tomorrow , '' he said .
But Price , who was back using his favorite putter that was repaired after breaking in transit , gave himself only an `` outside chance '' of closing the gap .
`` Faldo is going to have to make some mistakes before anyone can catch him , '' Price said .
`` It 's really up to him now . ''
Quebec separatist leader Lucien Bouchard had his left leg amputated after being attacked by a strain of flesh-eating bacteria , but is out of danger , doctors said Friday .
Bouchard , who heads the Bloc Quebecois , the main opposition party in Canada 's parliament , was reported in serious condition by officials at Montreal 's Saint-Luc hospital following surgery Friday .
Hospital deputy director Robert Raciot said Friday that reports that the 55-year-old Bouchard was on the verge of death were untrue .
His doctor , Patrick d'Amico , said Bouchard underwent three operations Tuesday to combat the rapid spread of necrotizing fasciitis , a virulent form of streptococcus bacteria .
The bacteria enter the body through a cut or a wound .
He now faces three or four months rehabilitation , doctors said .
Bouchard vowed in a letter to his supporters that he will continue his political career .
News of Bouchard 's illness shook Quebec .
Small groups of people , some bearing Quebec flags , kept an all-night vigil outside the hospital under a light snowfall .
