A beautiful Russian Orthodox cross an Idaho man secreted out of the communist country 27 years ago is returning to the faithful in Boise .
`` It really needs to go home , '' Quinten Crockett said .
`` It means a lot to me .
But it means more to them . ''
On Sunday , Crockett will give the cross to the St. Seraphim of Sarov Russian Orthodox Church in Boise during a special service .
`` The cross in our church is a very powerful symbol of our victory over sin , '' said the Rev. David Moser , St. Seraphim 's minister .
`` We tend to look at things that have survived the ravages of times and persecutions as kind of special .
They are a symbol of our ability to overcome trial . ''
Crockett bought the cross on the Russian black market 27 years ago .
A man approached him with an offer to sell religious icons , but only for American money .
They agreed on a purchase price : $ 10 .
The cross 's history is uncertain .
But many similar icons were taken from Russian Orthodox churches and hidden during the Russian Revolution .
Tiny figures in relief depict the crucifixion of Christ .
On the back are words scratched in old Slavic , a language all but gone in Russia .
Crockett knew all religious materials were considered property of the state and would be confiscated when he left the country .
But he outsmarted border guards by stuffing the 18-inch icon down his pants and covering the top with his untucked shirt .
Crockett kept the cross as a memento of his trip and of the people he met in the Soviet Union .
`` The same spirit I feel in the Mormon Temple , I felt in the Orthodox churches , '' said Crockett , who is LDS .
The cross is believed to have come from a small country church .
`` And it 's going to go to a little church , '' Crockett said .
`` It 's time .
It 's like if someone had an old , original Book of Mormon and was n't sharing it with anyone . ''
