U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali met with the Turkish Cypriot leader Friday in continuing efforts to reunite Cyprus .
Rauf Denktash told reporters after the 50-minute meeting that he understood Boutros-Ghali would instruct his representative on the divided Mediterranean island to organize fresh talks between the opposing Turkish Cypriot and Greek Cypriot sides .
`` We are ready to continue the talks ... with political equality and Swiss-like sovereignty , '' said Denktash .
Denktash met informally with President Glafcos Clerides , leader of the majority Christian Greeks , five times this fall as part of a confidence-building exercise to gain each other 's trust .
They were the first meetings between the two leaders in a year .
Cyprus was unofficially partitioned in 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the northern third of the island following a short-lived coup by supporters of a union with Greece .
Turkish Cypriots declared a breakaway republic in the north in 1983 , but only Turkey recognizes it .
The main sticking points are the Turkish Cypriot demand for recognition of their breakaway state , and their rejection of the U.N. Security Council resolutions demanding the withdrawal of some 35,00 Turkish troops and 50,000 mainland settlers .
