An anti-abortion activist who killed a doctor and his escort in a shotgun attack was sentenced by a federal judge on Friday to life in prison .
The judge sentenced Paul Hill to two life terms for violating the new federal clinic protection law .
Hill faces the death penalty when he is sentenced Tuesday in state court for the same shootings .
Hill , 40 , showed no emotion as U.S. District Judge Roger Vinson handed down the life sentences and a 10-year sentence for wounding a third victim .
The sentences are to run concurrently .
Dr. John Bayard Britton , 69 , and retired Air Force Lt. Col. James Barrett , 74 , died in the shotgun attack July 29 .
Barrett 's wife , June , 69 , was wounded .
Hill was the first person convicted of violating the new federal abortion clinic protection law .
Vinson also ordered Hill to serve an additional five years in prison for firearm violations .
Hill represented himself at both his state and federal trials , offering no evidence and declining to question witnesses .
He was not allowed to argue that the murders were justifiable homicide .
Hill told the judge Friday that he shot the doctor because `` I was trying to prevent Dr. Britton from killing the 30 people he was going to kill that day . ''
He has argued that killing of abortion providers is justified to prevent abortions .
Vinson said he did not doubt Hill 's sincerity about believing he had a higher motive , but disagreed with it .
`` God does not look with favor on the taking of any human life , '' Vinson said .
`` The killing of a person is not intrinsically wrong -- if that person deserves death , '' Hill said in an interview broadcast Thursday on CBS .
`` My actions were to defend the innocent .
Therefore , I am certainly guilty of no crimes .
As a matter of fact , my actions are honorable . ''
Swedish divers looked inside the sunken ferry Estonia for the first time on Friday , finding decks `` demolished '' after the ship 's 200-foot -LRB- 60-meter -RRB- plunge to the Baltic Sea floor .
Maritime authorities declined to say whether the divers found any bodies in the wreck , where an estimated 800 people were entombed when the ferry sank on Sept. 28 .
`` It 's extremely demolished , '' Swedish maritime administration spokesman Lars-Goran Bronow told the news agency TT .
`` It happened when the ship turned upside down . ''
The ferry sank in about 30 minutes after a storm ripped off its front cargo door .
Investigators say it capsized and probably rolled over completely before hitting bottom .
It now lies on its side 180-280 feet -LRB- 56-84 -RRB- meters under water off Finland 's southwestern coast .
Divers had examined two of the ship 's six decks as of Friday afternoon .
Weather permitting , teams of six divers plan to work in shifts around the clock for four days surveying the ship 's interior , authorities said .
They will work their way into the bridge , where authorities hope to retreive navigational computers and other records that might provide clues about what happened , Bronow said .
`` The weather conditions are good .
The weather wo n't hinder the work , '' Bronow told TT earlier .
Working in near-freezing water , the divers ' mission is to gather evidence to help authorities decide whether to raise the ship , retreive the bodies or take some other action .
Of the estimated 1,049 people on the ferry , 137 survived , according to the latest figures published Friday by the Finnish police .
Only 94 bodies have been recovered .
The rest are believed in the ship , although officials have said they may never know the exact number because of unreliable passenger lists .
Authorities said they will not disclose any divers ' information about bodies .
Each diver was required to sign a contract barring him from describing the scene to anybody but investigators and officials , Swedish media reported .
`` -LRB- This -RRB- mission does not include bringing anybody to the surface , '' Swedish Communications Minister Ines Uusmann told the newspaper Aftonbladet .
Swedish authorities hope to decide on a course of action by mid-December , and were focusing on several options .
In one , salvagers could scour the wreck to retrieve all the bodies they find , or could do that plus flip it over using cables to find more bodies .
They also could leave all the bodies and fill the wreck with sand to `` bury '' the victims and protect the wreck from scavengers .
The divers are working from a large , floating research platform called SEMI 1 .
The work was scheduled to begin Wednesday , but was delayed because the ships apparently had been given the wrong coordinates for the wreck .
The Swedish government , meanwhile , said Friday it has decided to give 3 million kronor -LRB- dlrs 417,000 -RRB- to organizations helping victims ' families , in many cases including orphans .
The Danish capital , already filled with bicyclists on city streets , hopes it found a way to get even more people on two wheels -- for free .
Sponsors on Friday showed bikes that people will be allowed to ride at no cost , starting next spring .
Though a previous free-bike program failed before , Danish officials think they 've solved the problem .
Under the new private initiative backed by government officials , bicyclists will have to deposit a 20-kroner coin -LRB- dlrs 3.30 -RRB- at a special rack to pick up one of the 1,000 city-provided bikes .
The money will be returned when the bike is taken back to any one of 200 racks located throughout the city .
`` In a city where everyone is bicycling there 's a need for free bikes , '' said Bente Frost , Copenhagen 's transportation mayor , after her maiden ride on a Bycykel , which means City Bike in Danish .
Thirty percent of Copenhagen residents ride bikes to work during the summer .
Frost said up to 5,000 bicycles would be ready when Copenhagen becomes the European cultural capital in 1996 .
Each year about 27,000 bicycles are stolen in Copenhagen , costing insurance companies 41 million kroner -LRB- dlrs 6.7 million -RRB- .
The city hopes the program will help the environment and curb bicycle thefts .
Would-be thieves are discouraged from stealing the bike for refitting because none of the Bycykel 's parts fit to standard bicycles .
Morten Sadolin , a businessman who helped design the project , said they also planned poster campaigns to tell people that if a Bycykel is seen `` miles outside Copenhagen , it must be stolen . ''
The easily recognizable Bycykel has advertisements from sponsors on the clumsy-looking frame .
It has no speeds and will only be suitable for short distances .
The Copenhagen city council -- interested in reducing air pollution and traffic congestion - is backing the private initiative .
Sadolin said several cities , among them Aspen , Colorado , and Adelaide in Australia , had shown interest .
`` One city at the time , '' he added .
A decision on whether British Formula One driver David Coulthard stays with Williams or drives for McLaren next year is not expected for another two weeks , officials said Friday .
