The once grand idea of U.N. peacekeeping as a global 911 appears to be fading as the United Nations closes shop in Somalia and faces humiliation in Bosnia .
With the United Nations in apparent retreat , observers are saying that future peacekeeping is likely to shy away from where it is needed most : the front lines .
Bosnia is a `` bucket of cold water on ambitious plans for peacekeeping , '' said Richard Betts , professor of political science at Columbia University .
`` I think there is a great future for peacekeeping that does not matter very much , and a very shaky future for messier operations . ''
That seemed apparent this week .
As Serb militiamen held hundreds of peacekeepers hostage and pounded a U.N.-declared safe haven in Bosnia , the Security Council met in New York , but high on its agenda was the Golan Heights , not Bosnia .
The quick meeting extending the mandate for the Israeli-Syrian border mission highlighted a U.N. success -- a mission where both sides want peace and the border is quiet .
The council talks later dragged on about Bosnia , but without direct action .
`` Peacekeeping is the role of referee , '' said Dan Plesch , director of the British-American Security Information Council in London .
`` You can separate warring parties who want to be separated . ''
But in instances like Bosnia and Somalia , where the sides are n't willing to stop fighting , the United Nations is refusing to order its peacekeepers to separate the sides .
Such a direct role would be war , not peacekeeping , council members say .
Many observers say missions like those in Golan and Cyprus -- with clear and limited objectives such as monitoring borders or delivering aid to war zones -- are likely to expand in the coming years .
`` But we will also see peacekeeping used by the United States and other powers as a way of repackaging war , '' Plesch said .
He cited Haiti and Georgia as examples .
The United States pushed the Council to authorize military intervention in Haiti , offering its own soldiers to lead the mission that will give way to a U.N. peacekeeping force .
Russia would like to do much the same in Georgia .
It has already sent its own troops to the former Soviet republic , but is pressing the United Nations to take over the mission .
While Bosnia -- with 24,000 soldiers or almost a third of all U.N. peacekeepers -- would prove the greatest U.N. peacekeeping failure if it collapses , the United Nations has lost face on other missions .
It was unable to foster peace in Somalia , and decided this fall to wind down its two-year mission .
In Liberia , observers have been abused and humiliated by the warring factions .
U.N. officials bristle at criticisms that peacekeeping has been ineffective and say the problem is that world leaders are not willing to commit the troops or money to ambitious peacekeeping operations .
The world body is being made a scapegoat for the lack of global will to act , said Kofi Annan , the head of U.N. peacekeeping .
`` It is absolutely unfair when member states do not want to take the risks , when they do not want to commit the resources , but blame the U.N. for failure to act , '' Annan said .
U.N. peacekeeping costs have ballooned to $ 3.8 billion for the year ending April 1994 , but by October , members still owed the world body $ 1.6 billion for peacekeeping .
There are some 80,000 U.N. peacekeepers worldwide .
U.N. missions involved only about 10,000 soldiers in 1987 .
With a more isolationist Congress coming into power in Washington , it is unlikely the United States -- which pays about a third of the peacekeeping budget -- would be willing to pay for additional operations that are not directly in the U.S. interest .
`` There may be other Bosnias , but I do n't think there will be another UNPROFOR , '' said William Durch , a senior associate at the Henry L. Stimson Center in Washington .
`` If the West is not willing to act on its own doorstep why would it do it elsewhere ? ''
UNPROFOR is the peacekeeping mission in former Yugoslavia .
Lewis MacKenzie , a veteran of nine peacekeeping operations and the former head of the Sarajevo operation , points out that despite its shortcomings , the U.N. mission in Bosnia still ensures that millions of people receive food every day .
And the retired major-general says that despite the problems , there is still a need for peacekeeping .
`` People who talks about the loss of credibility will be on bended knees before the U.N. at the next crisis , '' MacKenzie said .
