Stefan Edberg had to rally from match point in the final set and Magnus Larsson likewise prevailed in five sets Friday , giving Sweden a sweep of opening singles and a 2-0 lead over Russia in the Davis Cup final .
Edberg faced match point trailing 5-4 in the fifth set , but rallied to beat Alexander Volkov 6-4 , 6-2 , 6-7 -LRB- 2-7 -RRB- , 0-6 , 8-6 .
Larsson , ranked 19th by the ATP Tour , followed by overcoming a whistling , foot-stomping home crowd of 12,000 , to beat No. 11 ranked Yevgeny Kafelnikov 6-0 , 6-2 , 3-6 , 2-6 , 6-3 victory .
The opening-day setbacks severely hurt Russia 's chances of becoming the first unseeded team to win the Davis Cup .
On Saturday , Kafelnikov and Andrei Olhovskiy must upset the top-ranked doubles team and recently crowned ATP Tour doubles champions Jonas Bjorkman and Jan Apell to keep their hopes alive and send the best-of-five match to Sunday 's reverse singles .
Friday loss was Kafelnikov 's first in eight Davis Cup matches .
His only other loss was in debut to Germany 's Michael Stich in March 1993 .
In Friday 's first match , Volkov held match point on his serve leading 5-4 when Edberg sent a backhand down the line to send it to deuce .
He went on to break Volkov and then earned the critical break in the final game .
`` Maybe he played it a little safe , '' Edberg said about facing match point .
`` I took charge of the match in that game .
I took a few chances and it paid off . ''
After winning the first two sets , the seventh-ranked Edberg appeared enroute to an easy victory .
But buoyed by the flag-waving , cheering crowd , Volkov battled back in the third set , punctuated with a crowd-pleasing ace to take the tiebreaker .
The 27-year-old Volkov then dominated Edberg in the fourth set with devastating passing shots and seemed set to take the match , serving for the victory in the final set .
`` I needed to kick myself , especially in the fifth set , '' Edberg said .
`` I was a little bit depressed .
I had the match in my hand and became defensive ... I felt I was getting closer and closer in every game in the fifth set . ''
Having broken Volkov to tie the set , Edberg had the added distraction of Russian President Boris Yeltsin entering Olympic Stadium just as the Swede was preparing to start the next game .
Edberg , who had been whistled in derision by the crowd , paced along the baseline as Yeltsin and his entourage took their seats .
`` I saw a lot of people coming in , but I did n't know it was Yeltsin , '' Edberg said .
`` I just put it aside .
I felt so happy being back in the match . ''
Considering the outcome , `` maybe I should thank Boris for coming in , '' he added .
Volkov did not blame Yeltsin for his loss .
`` I could n't have failed to notice when the president arrived , '' he said .
`` -LRB- But -RRB- I can say it interfered with my game as much as rain outside would have , because I had lost my serve by then . ''
The left-handed Volkov was repeatedly rattled in the first two sets , hurling his racket to the ground twice after failing to reach Edberg returns at the baseline .
Edberg was troubled by inconsistent serves .
`` I 've been in the same situation .
He 's probably feeling quite depressed tonight , '' Edberg said about Volkov .
`` On the other hand , he was out of the match and came back . ''
Sweden has beaten Russia in their two previous Davis Cup encounters , but the two have not faced each other since 1982 .
Russia hopes to become the first unseeded team to win the title .
It is only the seventh to reach the final .
The city health department on Friday opened a room where heroin addicts can take their drugs in clean surroundings with fresh needles , the first such experiment in Germany .
Backers of the project , which aims to convince 150 long-term addicts to try methadone or withdrawal treatment and stop the spread of AIDS , had to override objections from national officials who said it could encourage use of illegal drugs .
Similar `` junkie rooms '' have been set up in several European cities to entice addicts out of squalid conditions .
The Swiss cities Basel and Zurich have such places , and in the Netherlands , Rotterdam has a designated place by the central train station where junkies can do whatever they please .
The Frankfurt hard-drugs scene , also centered on the main train station , has been cleaned up in recent years as police forced several hundred foreigners to leave and clamped down on an open drugs market .
But 150 long-term local addicts remain .
The city drugs commissioner , Margarethe Nimsch , opened the so-called Gesundheitraum -- Health Room -- in Frankfurt .
It is in an old factory building far from the train station , and a shuttle bus will carry addicts to the facility , which is next to a counseling office and a hostel for addicts .
`` It is a command of humanity to help addicts out of their misery and not to fence them out , '' Ms. Nimsch said .
Police and prosecutors have agreed to tolerate the project as long as those using it show they are over 18 and addicted but not in a withdrawal or methadone program .
They have to bring their own drugs -- sales on the premises are not permitted -- but fresh syringes are supplied .
The remote location of the `` junkie room '' was an obvious drawback , and it remained to be seen whether addicts would be willing to make the trip .
Police Inspector Roland Ullmann said the project would have to observed for a while to see if it is a success .
`` But one has to have the courage to close such a facility after a year or two if it does n't work , '' Ullmann said .
While the United Nations deliberates whether to continue operations in Bosnia , the Bosnian Serbs basically are deciding the issue .
They 've virtually closed the mission down .
Consider : -- Delivery of humanitarian aid to civilians is basic to the U.N. mission .
But Bosnian Serbs have refused to approve convoys through their territory .
-- Sarajevo depends on the U.N. airlift for 80 percent of its supplies .
For more than a week , the up-again , down-again airlift has not flown because the Serbs refuse to approve flights .
To reinforce the message , the Serbs deployed surface-to-air missiles in the air corridor approaching Sarajevo .
-- More than 400 peacekeepers , including French , British , Dutch , Canadians and Ukrainians , have been taken hostage against future NATO strikes .
Apart from delivering humanitarian aid , the U.N. mission is supposed to enforce agreements , such as those on removal of heavy weapons from the Sarajevo area and on protection of U.N. `` safe areas . ''
Those military functions have been severely curtailed .
The United Nations is unable even to get permission from the Bosnian Serbs to resupply its own units in isolated Muslim enclaves such as Bihac and Srebrenica .
Most of the detained peacekeepers were guarding collection points in the Sarajevo area , where Bosnian Serbs stored heavy guns after last February 's NATO ultimatum to remove such weapons from within 12.5 miles of Sarajevo .
Both the Bosnian Serb and government forces routinely have put banned weapons in the zone .
Apart from bluff and bluster , the U.N. has found no tools to force compliance .
Last week , Bosnian Serb soldiers simply drove up to the nine collection points and surrounded them , trapping the peacekeepers inside .
The presence of U.N. hostages virtually guarantees no NATO air strikes to follow three last week .
U.N. relations with both sides have been touchy , and are getting worse .
The Serbs are in a position to punish the United Nations .
Sources who attended a U.N. staff meeting Thursday quoted the commander for Bosnia , Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose , as saying that the Bosnian Serbs `` have declared war '' on the United Nations .
On Wednesday , Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic refused to meet U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali at the Sarajevo airport .
Boutros-Ghali had come to Sarajevo to warn the two sides that the United Nations might pull out of Bosnia-Herzegovina entirely if they did not cooperate with the peacekeepers .
U.N. officials , speaking on condition of anonymity , say they fear the Bosnian Serbs have decided to step up harassment in hopes the U.N. packs up and leaves .
During the past 2 -LCB- years , the United Nations has faced similar periods of harassment .
But U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , Thant Myint-U , described the current level of hostility as unprecedented .
`` While we will certainly continue operations throughout the country in fulfillment of our various mandates as best we can , this unprecedented level of non-cooperation by the Bosnian Serb party is certainly not making our jobs any easier , '' Thant said .
Thant said the level of harassment is so intense and widespread that the United Nations believes it must have been approved at the highest level , presumably by Karadzic and his military chief , Gen. Ratko Mladic .
Since all U.N. operations here can only be carried out with the approval of the warring sides , absence of cooperation means the mission grinds to a halt .
U.S. Senate Democrats on Friday selected Sen. Thomas Daschle as their minority leader for the next Congress , opting for a young , amiable lawmaker with scant experience in the national limelight .
Republicans chose unopposed Kansas Sen. Bob Dole as majority leader for the second time in his career .
But they moved to the right in dumping Sen. Alan Simpson as whip in favor of younger and more conservative Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi , an ally of Dole 's potential rival for their party 's 1996 presidential nomination .
The Republicans wrested majority control of both Houses of Congress from the Democrats , President Clinton 's party , in the Nov. 8 national election .
The leaders elected Friday will begin official business in January and could affect the tone and politics of the Senate for years to come .
Daschle , a two-term South Dakota Democrat , defeated the more feisty , combative Sen. Christopher Dodd of Connecticut to succeed Majority Leader George Mitchell , who is retiring .
The vote was 24-23 .
`` We will offer constructive alternatives , not gridlock , '' said Daschle .
`` We stand to offer vigorous opposition to extreme proposals .
... We will fight against proposals that are mean spirited . ''
Lott , who also won by a single vote , 27-26 , said he was `` honored that I will be able to serve with our majority leader -LRB- Dole -RRB- ... he 's been such a fantastic leader . ''
He added that `` I also am committed '' to working with the Democratic leadership .
Simpson said Lott `` is what the party has asked for at this time , a change in leadership and change perhaps in style . ''
Simpson had been Dole 's No. 2 man since 1985 .
Now 63 , his relaxed manner is spiced with a sharp , folksy wit that has sometimes gotten him into clashes -- frequently with the press .
His credentials are mostly conservative , although he has favored abortion rights .
Lott , 53 , is an energetic former House of Representatives whip with close ties to the incoming Republican House Speaker , Newt Gingrich .
He is also an ally of Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas who is likely to challenge Dole for the Republican presidential nomination in 1996 .
Lott 's combative style is in tune with the Senate 's growing cadre of younger , more conservative Republicans .
Since March , Daschle , 46 , has been campaigning for the Democratic leadership job methodically and behind the scenes .
His work for agriculture and veterans programs has gained little public attention for the boyish-looking lawmaker .
Dodd has been in the Senate six years longer than Daschle , and has a higher profile .
A former Peace Corps worker , he is best known for his vocal opposition to the Reagan administration 's policies in Central America and for his support of programs for children .
Negotiations to end the National Hockey League lockout broke off abruptly on Friday when neither side showed any willingness to budge .
`` We did n't have anything more to provide to each other , '' union head Bob Goodenow said .
`` They presented their positions and stated them to us Friday and , likewise , we stated our positions on various issues .
One could say we agreed to disagree on the issues as they were , give it more thought and more work , and see if some ideas could develop before we met again . ''
There had been hope that an eight-hour meeting Thursday would pave the way for the end of the 63-day labor dispute .
But after meeting for only about an hour Friday , collective bargaining talks were tabled until Monday .
`` We 'll be back here in Chicago , '' said commissioner Gary Bettman , the front man in negotiations for the owners .
`` There just was n't anything further that we could productively discuss Friday .
As a result , we agreed to meet on Monday . ''
Management and union representatives had resumed negotiations in Chicago , mindful that a labor agreement probably would have to be in place within two weeks to salvage a 50-game North American ice hockey season .
`` I 'm hoping at some point we get into position to make a deal , '' Bettman said .
`` If you 're asking me ... what makes me think the rhetoric will change , it may not .
`` Time is a factor and the longer this goes on , the more of a factor time becomes . ''
Boston Bruins general manager Harry Sinden , a management hard-liner , said negotiations ended Friday because `` we tapped out on conversation . ''
`` Everybody 's position remained where it was and it did n't go any further , so we called it off , '' Sinden said .
`` We sat on it overnight and there were no new ideas . ''
Since the owners locked out the players Oct. 1 , the season has been pared to 60 games , with 24 games stripped from each team .
Among the issues discussed Thursday were a rookie salary cap , salary arbitration and free agency .
But the major obstacle , the luxury tax , remained in the background .
The Canadian Press reported Thursday that the union dropped its desired salary ceiling for first-round draft picks to dlrs 1.25 million from dlrs 1.5 million for first-round players , while the NHL remained at dlrs 700,000 .
On salary arbitration , the NHL wants to retain its right to have an arbitrator 's decision to be non-binding on the team .
Rather than paying the awarded salary , a team could allow the player to become an unrestricted free agent .
