The International Committee of the Red Cross will continue its humanitarian mission in Bosnia even if UN peacekeepers pull out of the war-torn republic , the organization 's president said Friday .
`` I would regret UNPROFOR leaving because the presence of so many blue helmets has certainly had a deterrent effect to the conduct of war , '' Cornelio Sommaruga said , referring to the United Nations military force in the former Yugoslavia .
Faced with an escalation of the fighting and increased harassment of the peacekeepers by Bosnian Serbs , UN Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali warned this week that the world body 's 23,000 soldiers may be withdrawn unless the warring sides agree to cooperate with the mission .
There has been no indication , however , that a U.N. pullout , which would require a Security Council decision , is imminent .
Countries contributing the bulk of the UN troops , including Britain and France , also have said they would pull their men out if the fighting persists .
`` The ICRC has a mission to protect and assist victims wherever there is a conflict , and this mission is completely independent from the UN , '' Sommaruga said in an interview .
`` We would certainly continue to be there . ''
In the past , there have been serious doubts whether scores of international humanitarian organizations , which have provided massive relief aid to needy Bosnians in the past 21\/2 years , could continue to operate if the peacekeepers withdrew .
But the decision by a major relief supplier such as the ICRC to remain in Bosnia may sway other groups to continue providing assistance in such an event .
Sommaruga said the Geneva-based body already had prepared contingency plans for a possible UN withdrawal .
`` There is no humanitarian operation without problems .
When you are operating in the middle of the war , you will always have problems reaching the victims , '' he said .
`` But in Bosnia we have had more problems than we have normally . ''
In addition to providing food and medical aid , the 130-year-old organization is engaged in tracing , visiting and freeing prisoners of war held by the various warring factions , and in reuniting families dispersed by the conflict .
But Sommaruga indicated that if the fighting worsened considerably , even the ICRC may be forced to reconsider its stand .
`` What would affect our operations would be the way in which the conflict is conducted , '' he said .
The ex-wife of fugitive British businessman Asil Nadir was released Friday after being detained on charges of trying illegally to sell an antique marble fountain , a private television station reported .
Atv said a judge ordered the release of Aysegul Tecimer pending trial .
She was detained on Tuesday when she offeredt o sell the historic piece to undercover police for 2 billion Turkish lire -LRB- dlrs 55,500 -RRB- .
Tecimer , well known in Turkey for her extensive antique and jewelry collection , was also detained earlier this year linked to the alleged sale of a stolen antique Koran .
Nadir , the chairman of the food conglomerate Polly Peck International , escaped to Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus last year after he jumped bail in Britain on charges of stealing dlrs 47 million from the company .
Still angry about NATO 's plans to admit former Warsaw Pact foes , Russia on Friday brushed aside attempts to get it to follow through on plans for close military links with the alliance .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev refused to soften his opposition to a NATO blueprint setting out conditions for the entry of East European countries in the coming years .
He told a closed-door meeting of NATO and East European foreign ministers that Moscow could not move closer to the alliance until it provided more details about its intentions , sources said .
Kozyrev , they said , questioned whether there had been any change in NATO since it was a military machine arrayed against the Soviet Union during the Cold War era .
On Thursday , he stunned U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and other foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization by blasting the plan and backing out of a program for close military and political ties .
He complained NATO 's proposals would create a new division on the European continent .
A day later , Christopher sought to play down the embarrassing incident , which ruined the alliance 's efforts to present a united front on the sensitive issue of expanding NATO territory farther east .
`` We should n't make too much of yesterday 's events , '' Christopher told CBS ' `` This Morning '' program .
He and others expressed confidence Moscow would eventually agree to a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts , which were designed to ease Russia 's fears of being isolated .
`` I think that will all get sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd .
Ties between NATO and Russia , he said , are `` too important to be lost . ''
Despite Russia 's objections , NATO Secretary-General Willy Claes insisted , `` We are not ready to change any words in our decision '' ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the conditions for expansion .
If Russia was miffed about the membership plans , other East European nations were delighted .
`` We think this is an important milestone on the road to an undivided Europe , '' said Poland 's foreign minister , Andrzej Olechowski .
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would be attached .
The allies , though , have been hesitant about moving too quickly to admit their one-time foes for fear of upsetting and isolating Russia , still a formidable military power .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , which was seen as a waiting room for East Europeans eager to join .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to push ahead and ordered a blueprint of terms , costs and conditions for expanding the alliance .
But , mindful of Russia 's worries , they promised not to identify any front-runners for membership nor set any entry dates .
`` The Russians will have a chance to analyze what we did yesterday , and I think they 'll find it to be responsible and deliberate , '' Christopher said .
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and NATO 's top civilian official on Friday denied reports the alliance had agreed to a U.N. request to stop enforcing the no-fly zone over Bosnia .
`` NATO is continuing to enforce the no-fly zone , '' Christopher said .
NATO Secretary General Willy Claes said he knew of no request from the U.N. to halt or scale-down enforcement of the military flight ban which is designed to protect the civilians from bombardment in the 31-month war .
`` We have never received any request , can I be any clearer than that ? ''
Claes told reporters after a meeting here of foreign ministers from NATO and former East bloc nations .
Christopher told reporters Serb anti-missile batteries posed a problem .
But , he said , NATO was capable of dealing with them `` and we continue to police the no-fly zone in the effective way we have in the past . ''
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard in New York also denied reports that the United Nations had formally requested a suspension of the no-fly zone
`` There is no intention of requesting such a suspension , '' he said .
The Croatian government and leaders of the rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement Friday that , if implemented , could lead to normalized relations between the two enemies .
A six-month war in 1991 -- at the start of the violent breakup of Yugoslavia -- left Serbs in control of one-third of Croatian territory .
There have been thousands of skirmishes and larger confrontations between the two since a January 1992 ceasefire halted the war
The economic agreement calls for restoring water and electricity supplies and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital Belgrade .
Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220 mile -RRB- highway are ontrolled by Croatian Serbs .
The signing of the agreement coincided with the fiercest battlefield clashes since the U.N. brokered another cease-fire last March , Alun Roberts , a U.N. spokesman in Knin , said .
Artillery duels continued for the third day Friday in the area of Lake Peruca , about 30 kilometers -LRB- 18.6 miles -RRB- southeast of Knin , the capital of Serb-held territory in Croatia , Alexander Ivanko , another U.N. spokesman , said in Zagreb .
He said six Serb soldiers were reported wounded .
Meanwhile , the Belgrade-based Tanjug news agency quoted Bosnian Serb sources as saying that `` regular Croatian troops supported by HVO -LRB- Bosnian Croat militia -RRB- continued their offensive Friday against Bosnian Serb territories '' in the region between Grahovo and Livno .
It claimed that seven Serb civilians and soldiers had been killed while 3,000 people fled their homes .
There was no U.N. confirmation .
Representatives of the Croatian government signed the economic accord Friday morning at U.N. headquarters in Zagreb , with international mediators Lord David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg as co-signers .
The document was then brought to Knin , rebel Serb headquarters , where their leaders signed it .
`` The significance of the agreement is going to depend on the parties to the agreement , '' Owen told The Associated Press in Knin .
The two sides `` have it in their power to implement the agreement if they want to , '' he added .
`` For many people it has been senseless to be deprived of water , electricity , '' Owen said .
`` The basics of economic life can now be made available to all . ''
But he warned : `` This agreement can easily be blown up literally and metaphorically .
The fighting is continued challenge to it . ''
Croatian Serb representative Borislav Mikelic , though signing the agreement , remained firm in the Serbs ' refusal to accept any reintegration with Croatia .
`` By signing this agreement we once more proved that we are in favor of a peaceful solution to the crisis here and we also showed that we 're interested in the economic progress and economic opening to Europe and the world , '' Mikelic said .
But he refused to discuss the crucial overall political solution , saying , `` This is not the time to talk about it . ''
The self-styled Croatian Serb assembly approved the economic accord late Thursday .
Negotiations between the two sides had been stalled .
But the Croatian Serbs relented after a recent clandestine meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic , the Balkans power broker .
Thousands of peacekeepers have been deployed between the warring sides in the disputed territories since the 1992 cease-fire .
But international efforts toward lasting peace have failed over what seemed to be irreconcilable differences .
This is the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their 1991 war .
