Secretary of State Warren Christopher met Friday with key European foreign ministers , setting the stage for new overtures to the Bosnian Serbs in an effort to end the war in Bosnia .
The meeting with ministers of France , Britain , Russia and Germany came as the Bosnian Serbs tightened their grip on the mostly Muslim Bihac enclave and as the conflict threatened to spread into Croatia .
Two of the ministers , Alain Juppe of France and Douglas Hurd of Britain , plan to carry a peace plan to Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade Sunday in the hope he would recommend it to his allies in Bosnia .
Before the ministers meeting , Christopher told reporters : `` I think it 's important we come out of it unified but also that we come out of it with effective steps . ''
Juppe , as he left for the meeting of the five-nation `` contact group , '' acknowledged : `` It wo n't be easy ; that wo n't surprise you . ''
Christopher wants Milosevic to threaten to seal Serbia 's border to Bosnia .
Despite a promise to halt weapons deliveries , Clinton administration officials said , arms were still getting through to fuel the Bosnian Serbs ' drive to gain more territory and to terrorize Muslim civilians .
The war has taken an estimated 200,000 lives and left many times that number homeless .
Some 500 U.N. peacekeepers have been detained by the Bosnian Serbs , contributing to the decision by the U.N. commander , Sir Michael Rose , not to conduct heavy bombing raids against the Serbs .
Christopher 's plan , which was adopted by President Clinton 's senior foreign policy advisers Monday at a White House meeting , calls for a cease-fire in the Bihac area , a cessation of hostilities for three to six months throughout Bosnia and a peace conference .
There , the Bosnian Serbs would be able to promote their aspirations for a Greater Serbia , initially with political links to Belgrade .
They hope also to establish cross-border ties to ethnic Serbs in Croatia .
Elements of the plan are similar to one rejected repeatedly by the Bosnian Serbs .
It called for them to accept Bosnia as a legitimate country and to shrink the territory under their control to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
A federation of Muslims and Croats would be in charge of 51 percent of the war-torn country .
Even that division is negotiable once peace talks are resumed , U.S. officials said , hoping to induce the Serbs to halt their attacks and to negotiate .
Ironically , it was here at a NATO summit meeting in January that Clinton and allied leaders decided that NATO warplanes should be used to protect Bosnian Muslim civilians from attacks by rebel Serbs .
Clinton had campaigned against former President Bush 's policy as not being tough enough .
He also proposed excluding the Bosnian government from a U.N. arms embargo .
But France and Britain prevailed in their resistance to a military approach .
The Clinton administration has capitulated with some grumbling over its shoulder that the United Nations should have authorized sustained bombing and that the Bush administration should have done more than provide humanitarian assistance to trapped civilians .
In weighing diplomatic approaches , the five-nation group also considered a plan to urge Serbia to recognize the borders of Croatia and Bosnia make peace with Croatia .
The incentive would be an easing of economic sanctions against Milosevic 's government .
While the ministers are trying to enlist Milosevic , Christopher said , it would not be proper to have a further easing of sanctions against Belgrade .
When Milosevic promised to cut off arms supplies to Bosnian Serbs , some of the sanctions were lifted .
This included opening of the Belgrade airport .
Again signaling a willingness to compromise with the Serbs , Christopher did not rule out political union between the Serbs in Bosnia with Serbia itself `` if it would mean reaching a peaceful resolution '' of the war .
He said that was a constitutional issue the parties -- Serbs , Muslims and Croats -- should decide among themselves .
