President Nelson Mandela 's government started fulfilling campaign promises Friday , allocating more than 1 billion rand -LRB- dlrs 285 million -RRB- for health care and development projects .
Most of the money for the Reconstruction and Development Program went for health projects , including 500 million rand -LRB- dlrs 142.5 million -RRB- to provide free health care for children and pregnant women .
Another 472 million rand -LRB- dlrs 133 million -RRB- went for feeding schemes at schools in rural areas and black townships .
The government designated 2 billion rand -LRB- dlrs 570 million -RRB- for the development program in the 1994-1995 budget year , and Friday 's announcement was the first direct allocation of some of that money .
Mandela and his African National Congress promised the multibillion rand reconstruction program during campaigning for the nation 's first all-race election in April .
The ANC won the vote and heads the first black-led government .
The Reconstruction and Development Program is an ambitious five-year plan that calls for building 1 million houses , providing power and running water to millions of poor blacks and creating jobs .
Critics question if the government can afford the plan .
Along with the free health care and school feeding projects , money was allocated for building health clinics , running the government 's land reform program and providing grants to help people buy land .
Lebanon 's prime minister , once hailed as the savior of a country ravaged by 15 years of civil war , promised to resign Friday , but hinted he might return to office if quarrelsome ministers are ousted .
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri told the president during a stormy Cabinet meeting Thursday night that he was quitting after more than two years in office .
He planned to sumbit a letter of resignation next week , aides said .
Hariri , a 51-year-old billionaire , has long been frustrated by opposition to his economic and reconstruction policies by several Cabinet ministers allied with neighboring Syria , the undisputed power in Lebanon .
His resignation would be a severe setback to efforts to rebuild Lebanon from the destruction of the 1975-90 civil war , which killed 150,000 people , maimed tens of thousands and caused an estimated dlrs 25 billion in damage .
But in his first public appearance since the Cabinet meeting , Hariri hinted he could accept reappointment as prime minister if ministers blocking his programs were excluded from the new government .
`` We will not retreat from our latest move , '' Hariri said at the inauguration of a book fair .
`` We will not backtrack from rebuilding the country ... whether we are still in power or not , '' he said in a 15-minute speech punctuated by applause .
`` God willing , Lebanon will move forward and a bunch of gamblers , arrogant people and adventurers will not be able to halt the course of development and reconstruction , '' he said .
`` It 's imperative that a government of institutions evolve in Lebanon rather than a government of outlaws who join the system . ''
It was by far the sharpest attack by the soft-spoken Hariri against opponents , some of whom are former militia warlords appointed to government posts as part of Muslim-Christian reconciliation pact .
Syrian and Lebanese officials tried to talk Hariri out of resigning .
But his aides said he plans to submit a letter of resignation to President Elias Hrawi next week after a trip to Damascus Sunday .
Hariri canceled a weekend trip to China and another to Morocco next week .
The crisis erupted after the government on Thursday night decreed a 20 percent pay raise for workers , which was promptly rejected by the General Federation of Labor Unions .
The federation , which represents 350,000 workers , insists on an 80 percent hike to keep pace with rampant inflation .
The unions staged a one-day warning strike Tuesday to press their demands and threatened to escalate their protests Dec. 5 .
The government has also been beset by corruption allegations , which prompted a heated exchange during Thursday night 's Cabinet session .
Housing Minister Mahmoud Abu Hamdan claimed Hariri , who has a fortune estimated at dlrs 3 billion , would benefit from a real estate deal in Beirut .
Hariri stormed out of the Cabinet room .
He later telephoned Hrawi and told him that he was determined to step down .
Hariri was appointed prime minister Oct. 22 , 1992 .
Many welcomed his ascent to power as a harbinger of Lebanon 's return to regional prominence as a financial and trading hub .
But corruption charges have dogged his two-year tenure and his high-handed style has angered opponents .
Western allies and Russia on Friday discussed new ideas for peace in Bosnia , including a suggestion of a confederation between Bosnian Serbs and Serbia .
The foreign ministers of the Bosnia ` Contact Group ' nations gathered after U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher endorsed the European view that diplomacy is the best way to deal with the conflict that has dragged on for 31 months .
Thus , Christopher sought to heal a rift with NATO allies France and Britain over the alliance 's use of force in Bosnia .
On a visit to the NATO headquarters Thursday , Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev said he endorsed a confederation of Bosnian Serbs with neighboring Serbia .
`` We do support the suggestion -LRB- of -RRB- an unambiguous recognition '' of Bosnian Serbs ' right to forge political links with the government in Belgrade , Kozyrev told reporters .
Russia , France , Germany , Britain , France , and the U.S. comprise the contact group .
Kozyrev met here with Christopher in the margin of a NATO meeting before going over to the EU headquarters for the Contact Group talks .
A U.S. official said Christopher 's `` understanding of Foreign Minister Kozyrev 's position is very clear , '' but that a Bosnian Serbs-Serbia political alliance was `` not a proposal we support at this time . ''
Also attending the meeting were Douglas Hurd and Alain Juppe , the British and French foreign ministers who will go to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , on Sunday for talks with President Slobodan Milosevic .
The Contact Group , officials said , hoped to launch a new diplomatic initiative to try to draw the Bosnian Serbs into negotiations with the Muslims and Croats .
It was expected to call for a cease-fire around Bihac , the northwestern Muslim enclave that Serbs are pummeling , a pledge to cease hostilities across Bosnia for up to six months , followed by an international peace conference .
On offer for the Bosnian Serbs , who control about 70 percent of Bosnia , would be an opportunity to press their demand for cross-border political ties to Serbia .
Hurd said this week that would not amount to giving in to Serb aspirations of a Greater Serbia .
The current peace plan , that Bosnian Serbs have rejected , envisions a confederation between Croatia and the Muslim-led government in Sarajevo .
The core of the peace plan Bosnian Serbs have rejected is a division of Bosnia that would required them to return much territory they have seized in battle .
The Contact Group meeting caps an eventful week in which U.N. Secretary General Boutros-Boutros Ghali failed in his bid to meet with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Kardazic .
More than 400 of the 24,000 U.N. soldiers in Bosnia are being detained by the Serbs as insurance against NATO airstrikes .
