A U.S. official said Christopher 's `` understanding of Foreign Minister Kozyrev 's position is very clear , '' but that a Bosnian Serbs-Serbia political alliance was `` not a proposal we support at this time . ''
Also attending the meeting were Douglas Hurd and Alain Juppe , the British and French foreign ministers who will go to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , on Sunday for talks with President Slobodan Milosevic .
The Contact Group , officials said , hoped to launch a new diplomatic initiative to try to draw the Bosnian Serbs into negotiations with the Muslims and Croats .
It was expected to call for a cease-fire around Bihac , the northwestern Muslim enclave that Serbs are pummeling , a pledge to cease hostilities across Bosnia for up to six months , followed by an international peace conference .
On offer for the Bosnian Serbs , who control about 70 percent of Bosnia , would be an opportunity to press their demand for cross-border political ties to Serbia .
Hurd said this week that would not amount to giving in to Serb aspirations of a Greater Serbia .
The current peace plan , that Bosnian Serbs have rejected , envisions a confederation between Croatia and the Muslim-led government in Sarajevo .
The core of the peace plan Bosnian Serbs have rejected is a division of Bosnia that would required them to return much territory they have seized in battle .
The Contact Group meeting caps an eventful week in which U.N. Secretary General Boutros-Boutros Ghali failed in his bid to meet with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Kardazic .
More than 400 of the 24,000 U.N. soldiers in Bosnia are being detained by the Serbs as insurance against NATO airstrikes .
NATO struck three times last week , but the attacks did nothing to stop the Serb assault on Bihac .
Stefan Edberg had to rally from match point in the final set and Magnus Larsson likewise prevailed in five sets Friday , giving Sweden a sweep of opening singles and a 2-0 lead over Russia in the Davis Cup final .
Edberg faced match point trailing 5-4 in the fifth set , but rallied to beat Alexander Volkov 6-4 , 6-2 , 6-7 -LRB- 2-7 -RRB- , 0-6 , 8-6 .
Larsson , ranked 19th by the ATP Tour , followed by overcoming a whistling , foot-stomping home crowd of 12,000 , to beat No. 11 ranked Yevgeny Kafelnikov 6-0 , 6-2 , 3-6 , 2-6 , 6-3 victory .
The opening-day setbacks severely hurt Russia 's chances of becoming the first unseeded team to win the Davis Cup .
On Saturday , Kafelnikov and Andrei Olhovskiy must upset the top-ranked doubles team and recently crowned ATP Tour doubles champions Jonas Bjorkman and Jan Apell to keep their hopes alive and send the best-of-five match to Sunday 's reverse singles .
Friday loss was Kafelnikov 's first in eight Davis Cup matches .
His only other loss was in his debut to Germany 's Michael Stich in March 1993 .
Kafelnikov said he felt `` mental and psychological pressure '' after Volkov 's dramatic defeat , and said he said he injured his left wrist in the second game of the crucial last set .
He strained the same wrist last week .
`` It did n't really hurt but I felt very insecure .
I could n't hit slices , '' he said .
Volkov held match point on his serve leading 5-4 when Edberg sent a backhand down the line to send it to deuce .
He went on to break Volkov and then earned the critical break in the final game .
`` Maybe he played it a little safe , '' Edberg said about facing match point .
`` I took charge of the match in that game .
I took a few chances and it paid off . ''
After winning the first two sets , the seventh-ranked Edberg appeared enroute to an easy victory .
But buoyed by the flag-waving , cheering crowd , Volkov battled back in the third set , punctuated with a crowd-pleasing ace to take the tiebreaker .
The 27-year-old Volkov then dominated Edberg in the fourth set with devastating passing shots and seemed set to take the match , serving for the victory in the final set .
`` I needed to kick myself , especially in the fifth set , '' Edberg said .
`` I was a little bit depressed .
I had the match in my hand and became defensive ... I felt I was getting closer and closer in every game in the fifth set . ''
Having broken Volkov to tie the set , Edberg had the added distraction of Russian President Boris Yeltsin entering Olympic Stadium just as the Swede was preparing to start the next game .
Edberg , who had been whistled in derision by the crowd , paced along the baseline as Yeltsin and his entourage took their seats .
`` I saw a lot of people coming in , but I did n't know it was Yeltsin , '' Edberg said .
`` I just put it aside .
I felt so happy being back in the match . ''
Considering the outcome , `` maybe I should thank Boris for coming in , '' he added .
Volkov did not blame Yeltsin for his loss .
`` I could n't have failed to notice when the president arrived , '' he said .
`` -LRB- But -RRB- I can say it interfered with my game as much as rain outside would have , because I had lost my serve by then . ''
The left-handed Volkov was repeatedly rattled in the first two sets , hurling his racket to the ground twice after failing to reach Edberg returns at the baseline .
Edberg was troubled by inconsistent serves .
`` I 've been in the same situation .
He 's probably feeling quite depressed tonight , '' Edberg said about Volkov .
`` On the other hand , he was out of the match and came back . ''
Sweden has beaten Russia in their two previous Davis Cup encounters , but the two have not faced each other since 1982 .
Russia hopes to become the first unseeded team to win the title .
It is only the seventh to reach the final .
Many countries continue to resist according foreign banks the same operating rights as domestic ones , the U.S. Treasury Department reported to Congress Friday .
`` Intensive multilateral and bilateral negotiations have led to significant improvements in the terms on which U.S. firms compete in offering financial services abroad , '' the Treasury Department said in its 1994 study on national treatment for banks .
The study cited the North American Free Trade Agreement , which opened the Mexican market to U.S. financial institutions for the first time in over 50 years .
And it noted progress in a number of key areas in negotiations with Japan , China , Korea and Taiwan .
It also noted that the new global trade agreement has established a multilateral framework that could be applied to trade in financial services .
But Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen said in a statement accompanying the report `` while many countries have begun to recognize the economic benefits that come from liberalization of the financial sector , national treatment is still the exception rather than the rule in too many important markets . ''
The Treasury is required to provide Congress with updates on national treatment issues every four years .
National treatment is the equal application of rules and regulations among domestic and foreign companies .
Bentsen said President Clinton 's administration continues to seek open markets .
`` But unless other commercially important countries are prepared to commit to open their markets to U.S. financial institutions , the United States will not be prepared to accept -LRB- a most-favored nation -RRB- obligation in financial services in the WTO , '' he said .
The Senate gave final congressional approval Thursday night to legislation implementing U.S. participation in a vastly expanded world free trade agreement to be enforced by the WTO , or World Trade Organization .
Bentsen said that , in addition to the multilateral global trade talks , bilateral negotiations continue in several key markets , including `` a satisfactory outcome in the Japan Framework Talks on financial services . ''
U.S. policy provides that the results achieved in the U.S.-Japan negotiations be extended to all countries on a most-favored nation basis .
The report notes a `` large and diverse presence '' of foreign financial institutions in the United States , including 288 foreign banks from 60 countries that operate 580 agencies and branches , and 91 banking subsidiaries .
`` We want to continue to keep our markets open to foreign financial institutions , '' Bentsen said .
`` They play an important role in financing investment in the United States and they help keep our financial markets the most competitive and innovative in the world .
`` But we also need to ensure that foreign countries provide the same degree of access to our firms in their markets , '' he added .
Iberia airline pilots Friday said they were prepared to take pay cuts to rescue the near-bankrupt company but insisted the reductions must be part of a genuine viability plan that would guarantee Iberia 's future .
Following an all-day meeting , the pilots ' union SEPLA said a meeting was scheduled Monday with Iberia management .
The union said it was prepared to consider demands for salary reductions .
But the pilots ' insistence that any wage cut must be part of an `` authentic viability plan '' appeared to suggest that they still did not fully accept Iberia 's latest restructuring plan as it stands .
`` You ca n't center everything on a salary reduction in exchange for a ` now we 'll see what we can do ' attitude , '' said SEPLA chief Armando Guajardo .
`` We 're not prepared to hand over the money with our eyes closed . ''
Hopes of implementing the viability plan appeared dashed Thursday when talks between management and SEPLA broke down over the issue of a sliding scale wage reduction of 15 percent .
The plan , accepted in principle by the company 's other main unions , also entails a wage freeze and a reduction of some 3,500 jobs through early retirements and pay-offs .
A restructuring plan agreed on by all unions is crucial if the European Commission is to consider allowing the Spanish government to grant Iberia a 130 billion peseta -LRB- dlrs 1 billion -RRB- capital injection .
Iberia has posted losses since 1990 .
It ended last year 67 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 530 million -RRB- in the red while losses for this year are expected to top 40 billion pesetas -LRB- dlrs 300 million -RRB- .
Chairman Javier Salas has warned that the company would be technically bankrupt by March 1995 .
If finally accepted by SEPLA , the plan would be put to a vote among the company 's 24,000 employees .
The viability proposals were thrashed out between management and the principal unions except SEPLA after the company threatened to enforce emergency measures , including the axing of 5,200 jobs and the sale of company assets .
That threat sparked a one-day walk-out on Monday that paralyzed the country 's airports .
Pilots represent some 5 percent of the 24,000-strong staff .
As the scorched Achillo Lauro sank Friday into the Indian Ocean , a surviving passenger said one of the victims who died was injured when the crew dropped inflatable rafts on top of a crowded lifeboat .
The 979 passengers and crew who survived the fire on the Italian luxury liner were headed for three African and Middle Eastern ports aboard 10 rescue vessels , including freighters and U.S. warships .
They abandoned the blazing ship two days ago .
The Achille Lauro was once a gleaming blue-and-white luxury liner that sailed around the world in 80 days .
But it was best known for the 1985 hijacking by Palestinian terrorists , who killed an elderly Jewish American passenger , Leon Klinghoffer , and dumped his body overboard in his wheelchair .
The terrorists escaped aboard a jet , but U.S. fighter planes forced the plane down in Italy and the hijackers were arrested and later tried .
Wednesday 's fire began in the engine room before dawn .
Two elderly passengers died , one apparently of a heart attack .
Eight people were injured as lifeboats and rafts were launched and the ship was abandoned .
According to passenger Geoffrey Wall , interviewed Friday by Britain 's Sky TV , one man was injured when crew members released inflatable rafts onto the lifeboat , which held about 35 people .
`` It was tilting at an angle , '' said Wall , a Briton , describing attempts to lower a lifeboat .
`` They got it near the water .
They could n't lower it properly .
Then somebody hit the wrong -- I do n't know what it is that they release them with -- but they dropped two of these inflatable life boats on top of us , resulting in injury to one man . ''
He said people gave the ailing man mouth-to-mouth resuscitation before a rescue ship arrived about four hours later .
`` We were in 100 yards -LRB- meters -RRB- or so of the rescue ship when he started to go ... unfortunately he died , '' Wall said .
It was not immediately clear if the man died of his injuries .
The ship 's owner , Naples , Italy-based Starlauro , had no immediate comment .
Passenger Dennis Bassett , also told Sky TV that crew members did not alert all the passengers until only minutes before the order sounded to abandon ship .
`` Some passengers at 7 o'clock in the morning were still in bed , '' he said .
The ship 's captain , Giuseppe Orsi , was the last to abandon the ship , which sank Friday evening off the coast of Somalia shortly after Italian tugboats reached the ailing vessel .
`` She was hooked up to the -LRB- tug -RRB- Solano and in 10 minutes , she collapsed -- pfft , she disappeared , '' said Antonio de Rosa , marketing director for Starlauro .
He put the loss at dlrs 25 million .
Starlauro had hired seagoing tugs to bring the vessel home to try to save her .
Italian coast guard Lt. Francesco D'Amico said the ship was unrecoverable .
Orsi , aboard the oil tanker Hawaiian King , told the Italian news agency ANSA by radio phone he was `` very sorry '' about the news .
`` I knew that by now she was unseaworthy , but what happened has greatly displeased me , '' he said .
`` The fire had destroyed her almost completely . ''
Eight cargo vessels and two American warships , the USS Gettysburg and Halyburton , were carrying the surviving passengers and crew members to Djibouti , Mombasa in Kenya and Muskat in Oman .
Most were heading for Mombasa .
The first ship was expected to dock in Djibouti on Saturday ; the rest were scheduled to make port on Sunday .
The first fire aboard the Achille Lauro came in 1981 off the Canary Islands .
Passengers leaped from the decks into the Atlantic and two died .
Bosnian Serb gunners ringing Sarajevo fired five anti-tank missiles at the capital Friday , including two which hit government headquarters minutes before the chief U.N. envoy arrived for talks .
It was yet another sign of the contempt with which Serbs hold the United Nations mission to Bosnia .
More than 300 U.N. peacekeepers remained hostages of the Serbs , as insurance against further NATO airstrikes , but 70 were released Friday after being detained for seven days .
Two Sagger wire-guided missiles hit the Bosnian presidency building , which houses the offices of the top government officials , minutes before U.N. envoy Yasushi Akashi arrived for talks .
One destroyed the office of Miro Lazovic moments after he left for the Akashi meeting .
Lazovic is an ethnic Serb member of Bosnia 's collective presidency .
Later , three missiles hit nearby buildings as Akashi met in the presidency with top government and military officials .
There were no injuries .
`` Until we achieve something tangible , this shuttle diplomacy must continue , '' Akashi told reporters in Sarajevo before leaving for Pale , the Bosnian Serb headquarters east of Sarajevo .
But the Bosnian government blasted the United Nations for failing to use the necessary force to halt the Serb attack on Bihac , even as fighting continued in that northwest region Friday .
`` Instead of doing what they have to do , the U.N. is driving back and forth .
... This Munich policy is a humiliation of the international community , '' said Kemal Muftic , chief adviser to Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic , referring to European capitulation to Adolf Hitler before World War II .
Charles Redman , the former U.S. member of the Contact Group , was also back in Sarajevo , leading bilateral talks with Izetbegovic and Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic that presumably focused on a proposed new peace plan .
Redman , now ambassador to Germany , helped draft the first Contact Group peace plan , which the Serbs have repeatedly rejected .
Although that proposal was presented to the Serbs as a take-it-or-leave-it plan , the lack of Western will to use force has allowed the Serbs to demand , apparently successfully , the right of future confederal links with Serb-led Yugoslavia .
The original plan denied Serbs that as punishment for starting the war , though it granted the Bosnian Croat-Muslim federation similar rights to link with Croatia .
Akashi , on a mission to end the peacekeepers ' detention and win freedom of movement for U.N. convoys , hoped to have more success with the Serbs than his boss , Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali .
Boutros-Ghali was rebuffed in even trying to meet the Bosnian Serbs on Wednesday , and afterwards said intransigence by the warring sides might force the end of the U.N. mission .
Seventy Dutch peacekeepers arrived in Zagreb , Croatia , Friday after being released from a seven-day detention by the Serbs in eastern Bosnia , U.N. officials said .
But Serbs continued to hold about 20 other Dutch peacekeepers , along with hundreds of British , Ukrainians and Canadians , at various points throughout Bosnia .
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi also wanted to discuss with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic fighting around the government enclave of Bihac .
The United Nations is trying to broker a cease-fire there .
A number of detonations were reported on the outskirts of Bihac Friday , along with machine-gun and small arms fire , U.N. officials said .
But the heaviest fighting appeared concentrated around Velika Kladusa , north of Bihac , where Serbs were apparently closing in on the government army 's 5th Corps .
The Serbs , backed by Serbs from neighboring Croatia , want to wipe out the 5th Corps , which launched a briefly successful offensive from the Bihac enclave , part of which is a U.N. `` safe area , '' in late October .
There were also signs that frontlines south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , allied with Muslim-led government forces against the Serbs , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
A Croat militia and the Bosnian army took Kupres from the Serbs in a joint attack last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Serbs in neighboring Croatia also had shelled his forces across the border , near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
The Croatian government and leaders of the rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement Friday that , if implemented , could lead to normalized relations between the two enemies .
A six-month war in 1991 -- at the start of the violent breakup of Yugoslavia -- left Serbs in control of one-third of Croatian territory .
There have been thousands of skirmishes and larger confrontations between the two since a January 1992 ceasefire halted the war
The economic agreement calls for restoring water and electricity supplies and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital Belgrade .
Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220 mile -RRB- highway are ontrolled by Croatian Serbs .
The signing of the agreement came amid the fiercest battlefield clashes since the U.N. brokered another cease-fire last March , Michael Williams , a U.N. spokesman in Zagreb , said .
Artillery duels continued for the third day Friday in the area of Lake Peruca , about 30 kilometers -LRB- 18.6 miles -RRB- southeast of Knin , the capital of Serb-held territory in Croatia , Alexander Ivanko , another U.N. spokesman in Zagreb , said .
He said six Serb soldiers were reported wounded .
Meanwhile , the Belgrade-based Tanjug news agency quoted Bosnian Serb sources as saying that `` regular Croatian troops supported by HVO -LRB- Bosnian Croat militia -RRB- continued their offensive Friday against Bosnian Serb territories '' in the region between Grahovo and Livno .
It claimed that seven Serb civilians and soldiers had been killed while 3,000 people fled their homes .
There was no U.N. confirmation .
Representatives of the Croatian government signed the economic accord Friday morning at U.N. headquarters in Zagreb , with international mediators Lord David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg as co-signers .
The document was then brought to Knin , rebel Serb headquarters , where their leaders signed it .
`` The significance of the agreement is going to depend on the parties to the agreement , '' Owen told The Associated Press in Knin .
The two sides `` have it in their power to implement the agreement if they want to , '' he added .
`` For many people it has been senseless to be deprived of water , electricity , '' Owen said .
`` The basics of economic life can now be made available to all . ''
But he warned : `` This agreement can easily be blown up literally and metaphorically .
The fighting is continued challenge to it . ''
Croatian Serb representative Borislav Mikelic , though signing the agreement , remained firm in the Serbs ' refusal to accept any reintegration with Croatia .
`` By signing this agreement we once more proved that we are in favor of a peaceful solution to the crisis here and we also showed that we 're interested in the economic progress and economic opening to Europe and the world , '' Mikelic said .
But he refused to discuss the crucial overall political solution , saying , `` This is not the time to talk about it . ''
The self-styled Croatian Serb assembly approved the economic accord late Thursday .
Negotiations between the two sides had been stalled .
But the Croatian Serbs relented after a recent clandestine meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic , the Balkans power broker .
Thousands of peacekeepers have been deployed between the warring sides in the disputed territories since the 1992 cease-fire .
But international efforts toward lasting peace have failed over what seemed to be irreconcilable differences .
This is the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their 1991 war .
Russian lawmakers negotiating the release of prisoners in Chechnya accused their own government Friday of sending the jets that have attacked the breakaway republic .
The four-person delegation of Russian parliament members is trying to get Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev to release about 70 Russians , including Army soldiers and officers , who were captured in fighting .
Dudayev , who declared independence for his Caucasus Mountain republic in 1991 , says Moscow is arming and leading the rebels against him .
President Boris Yeltsin 's government has denied providing anything but political support , even as the rebel offensive has escalated from small-arms fire to jet attacks .
Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has called the captives mercenaries .
Jets roared over the Chechen capital , Grozny , for a fourth day Friday .
Raids this week have killed at least four civilians and an airport guard , and destroyed planes at civilian and military airports .
`` It is clear that these planes are not English or French but Russian , '' said Ella Pamfilova , a parliament member and Yeltsin 's former social welfare minister , who is part of the delegation in Grozny .
`` This is against the law . ''
`` You can rest assured that President Yeltsin has recognized the prisoners as members of the Russian Army , '' delegation leader Sergei Yushenkov said .
A dozen of the prisoners , interviewed by The Associated Press while Chechen guards watched , said they were hired by Russia 's Federal Counterintelligence Service for secret operations with the Chechen rebels .
The men said they were promised money when the operation was over .
But they said it went off badly , and that some of their Chechen allies did not know how to use guns and fled .
`` There are n't the words , '' imprisoned Capt. Alexander Tryukov said when asked how he felt about Grachev .
Counterintelligence spokesman Alexander Mikhailov , asked about such reports at a news conference Friday , said only that Chechnya is part of Russia and that the servicemen should therefore be called volunteers , not mercenaries , ITAR-Tass and Interfax said .
Dudayev first threatened to kill the prisoners if Russia did not claim them , but later said they would be tried in court .
Yeltsin threatened to send troops if they were not released .
Moscow has since toned down the threat .
But it continued to beef up troops on Chechnya 's borders , news reports said .
Lawmaker Anatoly Shabad , a delegation member , said he believes the Russians will be released , but he criticized the rebels .
`` We are against the way in which the opposition has used people with guns -- first locals and then Russian soldiers , '' Shabad said .
Since the air offensive began last week , thousands of people have fled Grozny , a city of 300,000 .
Chechen officials said a raid Friday targeted a tank regiment east of Grozny .
Four people were killed in a missile attack Thursday at Katayama , about 20 kilometers -LRB- 12 miles -RRB- from Grozny .
A bus was hit and Dudayev said his home was bombed .
The opposition accuses Dudayev of running Chechnya 's economy into the ground .
The main industry , oil refining , is operating at about 10 percent of capacity .
But Chechen pride and age-old enmity with Russia have rallied many people to Dudayev 's side , including some volunteers from other Caucasus regions .
Russia conquered the mainly Muslim Chechens in its imperial drive towards the Black Sea last century .
Ethnic tensions suppressed in Soviet times have boiled over since the 1991 Soviet collapse .
Many Russian nationalists vow never to let Chechnya go .
But at a pro-Dudayev camp outside Grozny , 24-year-old Sergei Chicherov , a blue-eyed Cossack , had cast his lot with the Chechens .
`` If someone comes and attacks your home , are you supposed to just sit and watch ? ''
Still angry about NATO 's plans to admit former Warsaw Pact members , Russia on Friday brushed aside attempts to get it to follow through on plans for close military links with the alliance .
Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev refused to soften his opposition to a NATO blueprint setting out conditions for the entry of East European countries in the coming years .
He told a closed-door meeting of NATO and East European foreign ministers that Moscow could not move closer to the alliance until it provided more details about its intentions , sources said .
Kozyrev , they said , questioned whether there had been any change in NATO since it was a military machine arrayed against the Soviet Union during the Cold War era .
On Thursday , he stunned U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and other foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization by blasting the plan and backing out of a program for close military and political ties .
He complained NATO 's proposals would create a new division on the European continent .
A day later , Christopher sought to play down the embarrassing incident , which ruined the alliance 's efforts to present a united front on the sensitive issue of expanding NATO territory farther east .
He and others expressed confidence Moscow would eventually agree to a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts , which were designed to ease Russia 's fears of being isolated .
`` I think that will all get sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd .
Ties between NATO and Russia , he said , are `` too important to be lost . ''
Despite Russia 's objections , NATO Secretary-General Willy Claes insisted , `` We are not ready to change any words in our decision '' ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the conditions for expansion .
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would be attached .
The allies , though , have been hesitant about moving too quickly to admit their one-time foes for fear of upsetting and isolating Russia , still a formidable military power .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , which was seen as a waiting room for East Europeans eager to join .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to push ahead and ordered a blueprint of terms , costs and conditions for expanding the alliance .
But , mindful of Russia 's worries , they promised not to identify any front-runners for membership nor set any entry dates .
`` The Russians will have a chance to analyze what we did yesterday , and I think they 'll find it to be responsible and deliberate , '' Christopher said .
The city health department on Friday opened a room where heroin addicts can take drugs in clean surroundings with fresh needles .
Backers of the project , which aims to convince 150 long-term addicts to try methadone or withdrawal treatment and stop the spread of AIDS , had to override objections from national officials who said it could encourage use of illegal drugs .
Similar `` junkie rooms '' have been set up in several European cities to entice addicts out of squalid conditions .
The Swiss cities Basel and Zurich have such places , and in the Netherlands , Rotterdam has a designated place by the central train station where junkies can do whatever they please .
The Frankfurt drugs commissioner , Margarethe Nimsch , opened the so-called Gesundheitraum -- Health Room -- in an factory building .
A shuttle bus will carry addicts to the facility from the train station , which is next to a counseling office and a hostel for addicts .
`` It is a command of humanity to help addicts out of their misery and not to fence them out , '' Ms. Nimsch said .
Police and prosecutors have agreed to tolerate the project as long as those using it show they are over 18 and addicted but not in a withdrawal or methadone program .
They have to bring their own drugs -- sales on the premises are not permitted -- but fresh syringes are supplied .
