On Thursday , he stunned U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and other foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization by blasting the plan and backing out of a program for close military and political ties .
He complained NATO 's proposals would create a new division on the European continent .
A day later , Christopher sought to play down the embarrassing incident , which ruined the alliance 's efforts to present a united front on the sensitive issue of expanding NATO territory farther east .
He and others expressed confidence Moscow would eventually agree to a wide-ranging program of military and political contacts , which were designed to ease Russia 's fears of being isolated .
`` I think that will all get sorted out ... How soon I do n't know , '' said British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd .
Ties between NATO and Russia , he said , are `` too important to be lost . ''
Despite Russia 's objections , NATO Secretary-General Willy Claes insisted , `` We are not ready to change any words in our decision '' ordering aides to conduct a 12-month study of the conditions for expansion .
Poland , Hungary , the Czech Republic and others have repeatedly demanded NATO membership and the security guarantees that would be attached .
The allies , though , have been hesitant about moving too quickly to admit their one-time foes for fear of upsetting and isolating Russia , still a formidable military power .
At a summit last January , President Clinton and other allied leaders approved a U.S. initiative , Partnership for Peace , which was seen as a waiting room for East Europeans eager to join .
Twenty-three nations , including Russia , have enrolled in the project , which allows them to take part for the first time in military exercises and other alliance activities .
On Thursday , the allies decided to push ahead and ordered a blueprint of terms , costs and conditions for expanding the alliance .
But , mindful of Russia 's worries , they promised not to identify any front-runners for membership nor set any entry dates .
`` The Russians will have a chance to analyze what we did yesterday , and I think they 'll find it to be responsible and deliberate , '' Christopher said .
Joe Montana angrily denied a published report that he is retiring at the end of the American National Football League season on Friday and said that although he is injured , he is not yet finished with football .
`` It 's ridiculous , '' the Kansas City quarterback said Friday at Arrowhead Stadium during his weekly news conference .
`` I had n't heard about it until I got here today .
I think , first of all , you guys are going to start having to stand up for what you write .
It hurts the credibility of your field . ''
In an exclusive story by NFL writer Gary Myers , the New York Daily News on Friday cited unidentified league sources as saying that Montana would retire when this season ended .
`` All I can tell you is that I stand by story , '' Myers said Friday .
Myers ' report was also broadcast Thursday night on the cable television program `` Inside the NFL . ''
Montana sprained a foot in Sunday 's loss to Seattle and rumors started that he would be out for a lengthy period and would not be back next year .
`` I 've got a sprained ankle and some guy writes that I 'm retiring , '' Montana said .
`` I had a hangnail last week and he did n't write about that . ''
`` It 's irritating .
It 's irritating that you have to put people through this .
It 's irritating that I should have to stand up here and go through this , '' Montana said .
He said chances are `` pretty slim '' that he will be able to play against Denver Sunday in Kansas City .
He said the ankle feels better but is still sore .
Asked earlier about the New York Daily News report , Chiefs spokesman Bob Moore said that Montana has always said he would make no decision until after the end of the season .
Moore said `` it is just natural that from now until the end of the season there will be all kinds of speculation about Montana 's future plans . ''
Montana , 38 , spent 14 seasons with the San Francisco 49ers and helped them win four Super Bowls .
After playing just one game in 1991 and 1992 , he was traded to Kansas City in April , 1993 , along with safety David Whitmore and a third-round draft pick in exchange for a first-round draft choice that the 49ers later traded away .
Montana was reported to have considered retirement last season after sustaining a concussion in Kansas City 's AFC championship game loss in Buffalo .
Until last Sunday , this season was relatively injury-free for Montana .
Retired Gen. Colin Powell , former chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff , said he was proud to help broker the controversial last-minute accord that averted a U.S. invasion of Haiti .
Powell , a child of Jamaican immigrants , spoke at the University of the West Indies late Thursday after accepting the university 's honorary Doctor of Laws degree .
`` I was pleased to be a member of the delegation that President Clinton sent to Haiti to persuade the generals and the colonels to step down , to tell them that their time had passsed .
To tell them that democracy had to return to Haiti , '' Powell said .
`` We succeeded without the need for an invasion which would have killed innocent young Haitians and innocent young Americans .
Instead we have the democratically elected president back in Port-au-Prince and American troops arrived as friends and not as enemies . ''
Powell participated in a U.S. delegation led by former President Jimmy Carter that secured a Sept. 18 pledge by the Haitian military leaders to step down and allow the peaceful arrival of U.S. troops to prepare for the Oct. 15 return of elected Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide .
Some analysts criticized the accord as giving away too much to the Haitian coup leaders , who had ousted Aristide in 1991 .
Also , the Pentagon was relunctant to get involved in Haiti .
However , since U.S. forces entered Haiti without major problems , U.S. military chiefs have said they should stay until they accomplish their U.N.-sanctioned mission , which is to create a safe environment that can be turned over to a U.N. peacekeeping force .
Powell , 57 , frequently mentioned as a possible contender for the U.S. presidency in 1996 , said , `` Haiti now begins the hard journey to real democracy and economic reform .
It is a journey many other nations are taking ... in a spirit of reconciliation and moving away from all patterns of ideological confrontation . ''
The former military chief said Jamaica and other Caribbean nations played vital roles in creating the conditions which allowed the U.S.-led forces to go into Haiti and restore democracy .
Earlier in the day , Powell accepted the Order of Jamaica , the nation 's equivalent to knighthood in the British system .
Others who have received the University of the West Indies ' honorary degree include American civil rights leader Dr. Martin Luther King and South African President Nelson Mandela .
The International Committee of the Red Cross will continue its humanitarian mission in Bosnia even if U.N. peacekeepers pull out , the organization 's president said Friday .
The U.N. departure would be regretted `` because the presence of so many blue helmets has certainly had a deterrent effect to the conduct of war , '' Cornelio Sommaruga said , referring to the United Nations military force in the former Yugoslavia .
Faced with an escalation of the fighting and increased harassment of the peacekeepers by Bosnian Serbs , U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali said this week that the world body 's 23,000 soldiers may be withdrawn unless the warring sides agree to cooperate with the mission .
There has been no indication , however , that a U.N. pullout , which would require a Security Council decision , is imminent .
Countries contributing the bulk of the U.N. troops , including Britain and France , also have said they would pull their men out if the fighting persists .
The Red Cross `` has a mission to protect and assist victims wherever there is a conflict , and this mission is completely independent from the U.N. , '' Sommaruga said in an interview .
`` We would certainly continue to be there . ''
In the past , there have been serious doubts whether scores of international humanitarian organizations , which have provided massive relief aid to needy Bosnians in the past 2 -LCB- years , could continue to operate if the peacekeepers withdrew .
But the decision by a major relief supplier such as the International Committee of the Red Cross to remain in Bosnia may sway other groups to continue providing assistance in such an event .
Sommaruga said the Geneva-based body already had prepared contingency plans for a possible U.N. withdrawal .
In addition to providing food and medical aid , the 130-year-old organization is engaged in tracing , visiting and freeing prisoners of war held by the various warring factions , and in reuniting families dispersed by the conflict .
While the United Nations deliberates whether to continue operations in Bosnia , the Bosnian Serbs basically are deciding the issue .
They 've virtually closed the mission down .
Consider : -- Delivery of humanitarian aid to civilians is basic to the U.N. mission .
But Bosnian Serbs have refused to approve convoys through their territory .
-- Sarajevo depends on the U.N. airlift for 80 percent of its supplies .
For more than a week , the up-again , down-again airlift has not flown because the Serbs refuse to approve flights .
To reinforce the message , the Serbs deployed surface-to-air missiles in the air corridor approaching Sarajevo .
-- More than 400 peacekeepers , including French , British , Dutch , Canadians and Ukrainians , have been taken hostage against future NATO strikes .
Apart from delivering humanitarian aid , the U.N. mission is supposed to enforce agreements , such as those on removal of heavy weapons from the Sarajevo area and on protection of U.N. `` safe areas . ''
Those military functions have been severely curtailed .
The United Nations is unable even to get permission from the Bosnian Serbs to resupply its own units in isolated Muslim enclaves such as Bihac and Srebrenica .
Most of the detained peacekeepers were guarding collection points in the Sarajevo area , where Bosnian Serbs stored heavy guns after last February 's NATO ultimatum to remove such weapons from within 12.5 miles of Sarajevo .
Both the Bosnian Serb and government forces routinely have put banned weapons in the zone .
Apart from bluff and bluster , the U.N. has found no tools to force compliance .
Last week , Bosnian Serb soldiers simply drove up to the nine collection points and surrounded them , trapping the peacekeepers inside .
The presence of U.N. hostages virtually guarantees no NATO air strikes to follow three last week .
U.N. relations with both sides have been touchy , and are getting worse .
The Serbs are in a position to punish the United Nations .
Sources who attended a U.N. staff meeting Thursday quoted the commander for Bosnia , Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Rose , as saying that the Bosnian Serbs `` have declared war '' on the United Nations .
On Wednesday , Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic refused to meet U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali at the Sarajevo airport .
Boutros-Ghali had come to Sarajevo to warn the two sides that the United Nations might pull out of Bosnia-Herzegovina entirely if they did not cooperate with the peacekeepers .
U.N. officials , speaking on condition of anonymity , say they fear the Bosnian Serbs have decided to step up harassment in hopes the U.N. packs up and leaves .
During the past 2 -LCB- years , the United Nations has faced similar periods of harassment .
But U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , Thant Myint-U , described the current level of hostility as unprecedented .
`` While we will certainly continue operations throughout the country in fulfillment of our various mandates as best we can , this unprecedented level of non-cooperation by the Bosnian Serb party is certainly not making our jobs any easier , '' Thant said .
Thant said the level of harassment is so intense and widespread that the United Nations believes it must have been approved at the highest level , presumably by Karadzic and his military chief , Gen. Ratko Mladic .
Since all U.N. operations here can only be carried out with the approval of the warring sides , absence of cooperation means the mission grinds to a halt .
Seattle Seahawks running back Chris Warren was arrested after a car he was driving crashed into a utility pole , injuring him and two teammates .
One player , defensive tackle Michael Frier , suffered a serious neck injury .
Warren , 27 , the fourth-leading rusher in the U.S. National Football League this season ; rookie running back Lamar Smith , 24 ; and a third player who was not unidentified pending notification of his parents , were taken to Overlake Medical Center in Bellevue after the Thursday night crash .
Frier 's condition was improved from critical to serious on Friday .
Team orthopedic surgeon Pierce Scranton refused to say whether Frier was paralyzed .
Warren , who suffered two cracked ribs , was treated and released .
Smith had chip fractures in his spine and ankle and was hospitalized overnight .
Warren , driving a Chevy Blazer -- a small truck-like vehicle , was arrested at the scene for investigation of vehicular assault , Sgt. Mark Smith said .
Smith said it appeared Warren was driving too fast for the rain-slicked road .
The crash set the utility pole on fire and the players had to be pulled from the vehicle by passersby and firefighters , Smith said .
Police would not comment on whether drugs or alcohol were involved .
Warren was released on his own recognizance , police dispatcher Jill Roberts said .
The accident happened about 8:40 p.m. near the team 's training center .
`` You read about it , you hear about it , but when it happens to somebody very close it really is a shock , '' Seahawks coach Tom Flores told KIRO radio early today .
`` It 's something that we all have to keep praying for that they all recover . ''
The power line suspended on the pole was severed in the collision , causing a large electrical flash and disabling three substations , said Kristen Wappler , a spokeswoman for Puget Sound Power and Light Co.
The accident knocked out electricity to some 4,500 Puget Power customers for about an hour .
Warren , a fifth-year , Pro Bowl running back , is the first Seahawks player to rush for 1,000 yards in three consecutive seasons .
He started this week as the second-leading rusher in the American conference with 1,096 yards , just 5 yards behind San Diego 's Natrone Means .
He also is second in the AFC in total yards .
The Seahawks play Indianapolis Sunday in the Kingdome .
The accident was the latest in a number of auto accidents involving NFL players this season .
Dallas offensive lineman Erik Williams was lost for the season when he tore knee ligaments in an Oct. 24 crash .
Williams pleaded no contest to drunken driving .
Teammate Shante Carver , a defensive end , also was involved in an accident in October when his speeding truck crashed into a concrete retaining wall .
