Part of an express train headed from eastern Hungary to Budapest derailed Friday , causing an undetermined number of deaths and injuries .
The state news agency MTI cited the National Ambulance Service as saying `` several people have died and the number of injured is high . ''
Precise figures were not immediately available .
But doctors at one hospital near Szolnok , close to the site of the accident , said 26 injured , including two critical cases , were admitted to their hospital alone , with several others also taking in injured .
The accident occurred at Szajol , a station near Szolnok about 70 kilometers -LRB- 40 miles -RRB- southeast of the Hungarian capital .
The second car of the express train derailed , dragging three other cars with it and the overturned carriages smashed into the station building , railway officials said .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 160 kilometers -LRB- 100 miles -RRB- east of Budapest .
The Danish capital , already filled with bicyclists on city streets , is trying to get even more people on two wheels -- for free .
Under a private project backed by the government , cyclists will deposit a 20-kroner coin -LRB- dlrs 3.30 -RRB- at a special rack to pick up one of the 1,000 city-provided bikes .
The money will be returned when the bike is taken back to any one of 200 racks throughout the city .
`` In a city where everyone is bicycling there 's a need for free bikes , '' said Bente Frost , Copenhagen 's transportation chief , after her first ride on a city bike .
Thirty percent of Copenhagen residents bike to work during the summer , and the city hopes the program will help the environment and curb bicycle thefts .
Each year about 27,000 bicycles are stolen in Copenhagen , costing insurance companies 41 million kroner -LRB- dlrs 6.7 million -RRB- .
Frost said up to 5,000 bicycles would be ready when Copenhagen becomes the European cultural capital in 1996 .
Nadia Comaneci completed a 10-day visit to her homeland by promising to return in 1996 to marry American fiance Bart Conner .
The 33-year-old gymnast , who scored the first-ever perfect 10 in the 1976 Montreal Olympic Games , said she was `` very moved '' by the warm welcome given her five years after she defected in what turned out to be the waning days of Communist rule .
During her stay , she returned to her hometown , met the president and performed in front of the prime minister .
`` People are more open , they are freer and say what they think .
I know how it was before , '' she said in Romanian , translating for Conner .
Conner , a two-time Olympic gymnastics champion , spoke of the `` warm and exciting reception '' the couple received , saying the most memorable moment was when he asked Gheorghe Comeneci for his daughter 's hand in marriage .
Nadia Comaneci left Romania five years ago , a month before the collapse of the regime of dictator Nicolae Ceausescu .
Croatia and its rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement Friday touted as a framework for normalized relations .
But the worst Serb-Croat clashes in months cast doubt on the pact 's chances for success .
The agreement calls for restoring water and electricity supplies and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital Belgrade .
Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220-mile -RRB- highway are controlled by Croatian Serbs .
Representatives of the Croatian government signed the accord Friday morning at U.N. headquarters in Zagreb , with international mediators Lord David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg as co-signers .
The document was then brought to Knin , rebel Serb headquarters , where their leaders signed it .
Croatia was effectively partitioned after a six-month war in 1991 at the start of the breakup of Yugoslavia .
A cease-fire in January 1992 halted the war , but left Serbs in control of a third of Croatia .
Since then , thousands of skirmishes and larger clashes have threatened the truce .
On Friday , U.N. spokesman Michael Williams reported the fiercest battlefield clashes since the United Nations brokered another cease-fire last March .
It was the third day of artillery duels around Lake Peruca , about 30 kilometers -LRB- 18.6 miles -RRB- southeast of Knin , Alexander Ivanko , another U.N. spokesman , said in Zagreb .
Six Serb soldiers were reported wounded , he said .
Nevertheless , an international mediator said the agreement could be made to work .
`` The significance of the agreement is going to depend on the parties to the agreement , '' Owen told The Associated Press in Knin .
The two sides `` have it in their power to implement the agreement if they want to , '' he added .
But he warned : `` This agreement can easily be blown up literally and metaphorically .
The fighting is continued challenge to it . ''
Croatian Serb representative Borislav Mikelic , though signing the agreement , remained firm in the Serbs ' refusal to accept any reintegration with Croatia .
`` By signing this agreement we once more proved that we are in favor of a peaceful solution to the crisis here and we also showed that we 're interested in the economic progress and economic opening to Europe and the world , '' Mikelic said .
But he refused to discuss the crucial overall political solution , saying , `` This is not the time to talk about it . ''
The self-styled Croatian Serb assembly approved the economic accord late Thursday .
Negotiations between the two sides had been stalled .
But the Croatian Serbs relented after a recent meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic , the Balkans power broker .
Thousands of peacekeepers have been deployed between the warring sides in the disputed territories since the 1992 cease-fire .
But international efforts toward lasting peace have failed over what seemed to be irreconcilable differences .
This is the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their 1991 war .
