In weighing diplomatic approaches , the five-nation group also considered a plan to urge Serbia to recognize the borders of Croatia and Bosnia make peace with Croatia .
The incentive would be an easing of economic sanctions against Milosevic 's government .
While the ministers are trying to enlist Milosevic , Christopher said , it would not be proper to have a further easing of sanctions against Belgrade .
When Milosevic promised to cut off arms supplies to Bosnian Serbs , some of the sanctions were lifted .
This included opening of the Belgrade airport .
Again signaling a willingness to compromise with the Serbs , Christopher did not rule out political union between the Serbs in Bosnia with Serbia itself `` if it would mean reaching a peaceful resolution '' of the war .
He said that was a constitutional issue the parties -- Serbs , Muslims and Croats -- should decide among themselves .
For a while , it looked like Union Carbide itself would not survive the worst industrial accident in history .
But in the 10 years since a cyanide gas leak left nearly 4,000 people dead in Bhopal , India , Carbide has engineered a dramatic turnaround .
Today , Carbide is a smaller , more focused company built around core chemicals businesses .
The company has sold or spun off most of its non-core divisions , shaved dlrs 575 million from its annual operating costs and radically cut its work force .
`` There 's no comparison to the Carbide that was and the Carbide that is , '' Carbide chairman and Chief Executive Officer Robert D. Kennedy said in a recent interview .
But no matter how well it fares financially , Union Carbide remains in the shadow of Bhopal .
It was early on Dec. 3 , 1984 that the company 's downward spiral began .
Methyl isocyanate gas , an ingredient in pesticides , leaked out of Carbide 's plant in Bhopal killing 3,800 people living nearby in crowded , dilapidated houses .
A legal battle over compensation for the victims of Bhopal went on for years .
Carbide , which concluded the gas leak was the result of employee sabotage , tried to defend itself from accusations by the Indian government and environmental groups who claimed the company did n't care enough about the indigent residents of Bhopal to take necessary safety precautions .
A Bhopal court issued a warrant for the arrest of former Carbide chairman Warren Anderson and unsuccessfully sought his extradition to face homicide charges .
The legal problems caused by Bhopal were resolved in 1989 , when Carbide paid dlrs 470 million to settle the claims , as directed by the Supreme Court of India .
There were other problems .
Soon after the disaster , the company became the target of a takeover bid by GAF Corp. , a specialty chemicals maker .
As a defense , Carbide sold its profitable consumer products group -- including Glad garbage bags , Eveready batteries and Prestone antifreeze -- and bought back 56 percent of its own stock .
In the process , the company saddled itself with dlrs 3.3 billion in new debt and made it difficult to diversify into other businesses .
Sales dropped from approximately dlrs 9.99 billion in 1980 to dlrs 6.39 billion in 1985 .
Over the next few years , Carbide spun off non-core businesses including pesticides , silicones and , in 1992 , Linde , its industrial gases unit .
Union Carbide is almost unrecognizable from its pre-Bhopal days as a conglomerate with about 20 different businesses .
Its worldwide work force has been slashed dramatically -- from 98,400 in 1984 to about 12,000 today .
The company is even looking to lease out space at its sprawling Danbury headquarters , built before the Bhopal accident and now too large for the new , leaner Carbide .
Wall Street seems to approve of the redesigned Carbide .
`` Bhopal almost destroyed the company .
It was the beginning of a series of problems ... but today I 'd call it a big Wall Street success story , '' said James Hickman , a chemicals industry analyst at CS First Boston in New York .
`` -LRB- The turnaround -RRB- involved some divestiture , some head count reductions and efficiency improvements , and the market -- skeptical at first -- ultimately rewarded the company , and the stock price improved dramatically , '' he said .
The company 's shares appreciated almost 35 percent in 1993 to close at dlrs 22.375 , the fifth-best performance for the year among the 30 companies on the Dow Jones industrial list .
Today it is trading in the high dlrs 20 range .
Analysts credit the company 's cost-cutting program for the company 's revival .
In late 1990 , Carbide announced a plan to cut dlrs 200 million from its operating budget by the end of 1994 .
Within a year , the company increased that target to dlrs 400 million , and in 1993 , to dlrs 575 million , a goal the company said it will reach by the end of this year .
`` That transformed them from a high-cost producer to one of the lower cost producers , '' said Paul Raman , an analyst with S.G. Warburg , a New York investment bank .
But critics are still mindful of Bhopal .
Environmental groups are familiar fixtures at the company 's annual stockholders ' meeting .
A former Christian warlord standing trial on charges of bombing a church and killing a rival politician said Friday he did not commit murder and complained of mistreatment in prison .
Samir Geagea , 43 , was the leader of the Lebanese Forces , the Christians ' main militia until it was disarmed in 1990 at the end of Lebanon 's 15-year civil war .
Friday 's session was devoted to the murder of Dany Chamoun , 56 , his half-German wife Ingrid Abdel-Noor , and their two sons , Tarek , 7 , and Julien , 5 .
They were killed by unidentified gunmen who broke into their house in suburban Baabda east of Beirut at dawn on Oct. 21 , 1990 .
Chamoun headed the right-wing National Liberal Party , long at odds with Geagea 's Lebanese Forces , which ruled most of the Christian hinterland north and northeast of Beirut during the war .
Geagea faces the death penalty if convicted of either charge .
He told the judges he did not kill Chamoun .
`` You should realize that we are innocent and that we have been framed , '' Geagea said in his first comments in court .
`` I have been held for 250 days in a cell without light ... sometimes blindfolded , '' Geagea told the five-judge tribunal .
`` In our cell I can sometimes hear screams '' coming from elsewhere in the Defense Ministry detention center .
In the other case , Geagea is accused of masterminding an explosion at a church in the Christian port city of Jounieh on Feb. 27 .
Eleven worshipers were killed and 60 were wounded .
Also on trial for the two crimes are four Geagea aides , including his chief of staff , Fuad Malek .
Fourteen others , including his top security chief , Ghassan Touma , are being tried on the same charges in absentia .
A U.N. commission of experts reiterated charges Friday that Hutu leaders were guilty of genocide against the minority Tutsi group in Rwanda , adding to legal evidence that may be brought before a war crimes tribunal .
In its final report to the U.N. Security Council , the three-man panel said it had been unable to find evidence that the new Tutsi-led Royal Patriotic Front government had instigated systematic killings after it assumed power last July .
However , it added that it was `` disturbed by ongoing violence committed by some RPF soldiers , '' and recommended that investigations should continue .
It said it had not had enough time itself to complete the inquiry .
U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali ordered the commission to check into alleged massacres by RPF soldiers after the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said they had carried out reprisal killings of up to 30,000 people late August and early September .
The government arrested some of its own soldiers after the allegations but maintains it is powerless to clamp down on all abuses because of lack of international help to restore the shattered law and order system .
The commission 's final report added added little to its interim conclusions issued in October .
`` After careful deliberation , the Commission of Experts has concluded that there exists overwhelming evidence to prove that acts of genocide against the Tutsi group were perpetrated by Hutu elements in a concerted , planned , systematic and methodical way , '' the 58-page document said .
Atsu-Koffi Amega , a former judge from Togo , heads the commission .
The other members are Salifou Fomba , a law professor from Mali , and Haby Dieng , a prosecutor from Guinea .
Their work is in addition to inquiries carried out by the U.N. Human Rights Center .
The Security Council voted last month to set up an international tribunal for genocide in Rwanda , with a maximum sentence of life imprisonment for those found guilty .
However , it may be months before a tribunal starts work , and the Rwandan government objects to the U.N. plans because they exclude the death penalty .
An estimated 500,000 people , mostly ethnic Tutsis and moderate Hutus , were massacred by the Hutu army and militias after the death of the Hutu president in a mysterious plane crash April 6 released an orgy of violence .
Many of those accused of the worst atrocities are now sheltering in refugee camps in neighboring Zaire and there are fears that -- with the help of international aid -- they are preparing a violent invasion of Rwanda .
John , Paul , George and Ringo have a new record in British and Irish shops this week .
So does Pope John Paul II .
The pope is featured on half of a double album , reciting the rosary in Latin .
The other half is a recording of an Irish priest , the Rev. Colm Kilcoyne , reciting the rosary in English .
The recording of the pope , made from a Vatican Radio broadcast , was first sold in Spain , said Colin Elms , national account executive for Telstar Records PLC of London .
The recording came out two days before EMI released double album `` Live At the BBC , '' a collection of Beatles ' recordings from the 1960s .
The pope 's disc was a best seller in Spain , and a platinum record was presented to the pope at the Vatican three weeks ago .
In Britain , the recording entered the chart at No. 52 at midweek , indicating sales of about 4,000 in three days , Elms said .
Bosnian Serb gunners ringing Sarajevo fired five anti-tank missiles at the capital Friday , including two which hit government headquarters minutes before the chief U.N. envoy arrived for talks .
It was yet another sign of the contempt with which Serbs hold the United Nations mission to Bosnia .
More than 300 U.N. peacekeepers remained hostages of the Serbs , as insurance against further NATO airstrikes , but 70 were released Friday after being detained for seven days .
Two missiles hit the Bosnian presidency building , which houses the offices of the top government officials , minutes before U.N. envoy Yasushi Akashi arrived for talks .
One destroyed the office of Miro Lazovic moments after he left for the Akashi meeting .
Lazovic is an ethnic Serb member of Bosnia 's collective presidency .
Later , three missiles hit nearby buildings as Akashi met in the presidency with top government and military officials .
There were no injuries .
`` Until we achieve something tangible , this shuttle diplomacy must continue , '' Akashi told reporters in Sarajevo before leaving for Pale , the Bosnian Serb headquarters east of Sarajevo .
But the Bosnian government blasted the United Nations for failing to use the necessary force to halt the Serb attack on Bihac , even as fighting continued in that northwest region Friday .
`` Instead of doing what they have to do , the U.N. is driving back and forth .
... This Munich policy is a humiliation of the international community , '' said Kemal Muftic , chief adviser to Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic , referring to European capitulation to Adolf Hitler before World War II .
Charles Redman , the former U.S. member of the Contact Group , was also back in Sarajevo , leading bilateral talks with Izetbegovic and Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic that presumably focused on a proposed new peace plan .
Redman , now ambassador to Germany , helped draft the first Contact Group peace plan , which the Serbs have repeatedly rejected .
Although that proposal was presented to the Serbs as a take-it-or-leave-it plan , the lack of Western will to use force has allowed the Serbs to demand , apparently successfully , the right of future confederal links with Serb-led Yugoslavia .
The original plan denied Serbs that as punishment for starting the war , though it granted the Bosnian Croat-Muslim federation similar rights to link with Croatia .
Akashi , on a mission to end the peacekeepers ' detention and win freedom of movement for U.N. convoys , hoped to have more success with the Serbs than his boss , Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali .
Boutros-Ghali was rebuffed in even trying to meet the Bosnian Serbs on Wednesday , and afterwards said intransigence by the warring sides might force the end of the U.N. mission .
Seventy Dutch peacekeepers arrived in Zagreb , Croatia , Friday after being released from a seven-day detention by the Serbs in eastern Bosnia , U.N. officials said .
But Serbs continued to hold about 20 other Dutch peacekeepers , along with hundreds of British , Ukrainians and Canadians , at various points throughout Bosnia .
In New York , Russia and Ukraine issued a statement Friday calling on U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and the UNPROFOR command to take `` all appropriate measures ... to facilitate the release of all captured or detained UNPROFOR personnel . ''
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi also wanted to discuss with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic fighting around the government enclave of Bihac .
The United Nations is trying to broker a cease-fire there .
A number of detonations were reported on the outskirts of Bihac Friday , along with machine-gun and small arms fire , U.N. officials said .
But the heaviest fighting appeared concentrated around Velika Kladusa , north of Bihac , where Serbs were apparently closing in on the government army 's 5th Corps .
The Serbs , backed by Serbs from neighboring Croatia , want to wipe out the 5th Corps , which launched a briefly successful offensive from the Bihac enclave , part of which is a U.N. `` safe area , '' in late October .
There were also signs that frontlines south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , allied with Muslim-led government forces against the Serbs , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
A Croat militia and the Bosnian army took Kupres from the Serbs in a joint attack last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Serbs in neighboring Croatia also had shelled his forces across the border , near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
CourmAosta of Italy , helped by Dallas Star Dave Gagner , won a semifinal game Friday in the `` Six Nations '' tournament of European professional ice hockey teams , beating Austria 's Villach 3-1 .
Gagner and Pittsburgh Penguin star Jaromir Jagr are taking part courtesy of the labor dispute that has stilled the NHL season .
`` I did not play a great game today , and the team did not either , '' Gagner said . ''
Villach is a very good defensive team .
They play just like the North American style -- they clutch and grab -- and it was very hard to find open ice . ''
Villach scored first at 19:29 of the first period with a goal by Gerald Ressmann .
Bob Reynolds tied it for CourmAosta at 10:41 of the second period .
Courmaosta scored two more in the third , with a goal at 11:08 by Sim Camazzola and at 11:43 by Alberto Scapinello .
Teams from Austria , Italy , Slovenia , France , Holland and Denmark were invited to the tournament .
Gagner signed to play part of the Italian season for CourmAosta after the NHL season was put on hold , and Jagr has contracted to play in the tournament for Wurth Bolzano .
