Accusing Iran 's Islamic regime of giving the orders , prosecutors Friday demanded a life sentence for an Iranian accused of leading a commando team that murdered former Iranian Prime Minister Shahpour Bakhtiar .
Prosecutor Jacques Mouton , saying the assassination was carried out `` with perfect mastery in perfect cold blood , '' demanded terms of 13-15 years for two other defendants , accused of helping the killers enter France and escape .
Bakhtiar , an exiled opposition leader , and his secretary , Soroush Katibeh , were strangled and slashed to death Aug. 6 , 1991 , at his home in suburban Paris .
Police guards failed to detect the murders for two days .
Presenting five hours of final arguments to the special anti-terrorist court , Mouton said that the killers walked away from the `` butchery '' with a calm that amounted to disdain .
Mouton asked for a life sentence with a minimum of 18 years behind bars for the alleged leader of the hit team , Ali Vakili Rad , 35 , who was arrested in Switzerland 15 days after the killing .
The other two accused assassins got away .
Vakili Rad claims he actually belonged to Bakhtiar 's opposition group but was duped by his cohorts .
Mouton called him a liar .
Vakili Rad and the other defendants -- Massoud Hendi , 47 , once Paris bureau chief of the Islamic Republic Broadcasting Network , and Zeynalabedine Sarhadi , 28 , an archivist at Iran 's embassy in Bern , Switzerland -- mount their final defense in the month-long trial Monday .
The seven-judge panel will render its verdict Monday or Tuesday .
Reviewing tomes of evidence , Mouton spared no words for Iran , suggesting the Islamic state was implicated through a vast , complicated network with its hub in Tehran officialdom .
The Iranian Ministry of Telecommunications `` was at the heart of this assassination , '' Mouton said .
Many of the dozens of telephone calls at critical moments before and after the murder were traced by the French secret service to the ministry .
Among the suspects France wants to try but remain at large is Hossein Sheikhattar , who headed the ministry 's satellite division .
Hendi said in testimony that Sheikhattar asked him to procure visas for two of the suspected killers , including Vakili Rad .
The Iranian Embassy in Paris has denied any role by the government in the slayings .
At least 63 Iranians have been killed in exile since the Islamic Republic was founded in 1979 .
But , if the defendants are found guilty , this would be the first trial directly implicating the regime .
American Hilary Lindh earned her second career World Cup victory , capturing the opening women 's downhill race of the season on Friday .
Lindh , 25 , prevailed by 29-hundredths of a second over Isolde Kostner of Italy .
Defending World Cup downhill champion Katja Seizinger of Germany finished third .
Austria 's Stefanie Schuster overcame a late start number to finish a career-best fourth , Switzerland 's Heidi Zurbriggen was fifth , and Sweden 's Pernilla Wiberg took sixth .
Lindh , winning on a course that she admitted did n't fit her style because of tight turns at the bottom , was timed in 1 minute , 45.00 seconds .
Her best previous finish on this course was sixth place two years ago .
Kostner , the last of the top-seeded skiers to complete the run , could n't overcome Lindh 's solid effort , coming across in 1:45.29 .
Seizinger was timed in 1:45.44 .
Three other favorites -- Anja Haas of Austria , Melanie Suchet of France and American Picabo Street -- fell and did not finish .
Street made a minor mistake early in her run and , in an effort to make up time , got out of control near the finish , did the splits and crashed .
Haas had the fastest intermediate time one-third of the way down the course when she fell .
Lindh , the 1992 Olympic downhill silver medalist , posted her first victory on the World Cup circuit last February in Sierra Nevada , Spain .
For the first time , downhillers in the top seed of 15 were allowed to select starting numbers from 1 through 30 , and most of the favorites chose numbers in the 20s .
The course appeared to speed up slightly during the race as a bright sun glazed the snow , making it slicker .
Part of an express train headed from eastern Hungary to Budapest derailed Friday , its cars sliding into a station building and burying passengers underneath the rubble .
Police said at least 20 people died .
The accident occurred at Szajol , a station near Szolnok about 70 kilometers -LRB- 40 miles -RRB- southeast of the Hungarian capital .
The second car of the express train derailed , dragging three other cars with it , and the overturned carriages smashed into the station building , railway officials said .
`` There was a tremedous explosion , like the end of the world , '' said a railway employee who witnessed the accident and asked not to be identified .
He said in a telephone interview that people remained buried in the wreckage more than four hours after the crash , which occured at 4:45 p.m. local time .
National Police Maj. Imre Olah said 20 deaths had been confirmed `` but that 's not the final count by any means . ''
Ambulance crews taking victims to the hospital said between 20 and 40 people were believed injured .
Doctors at one hospital near Szolnok , close to the site of the accident , said 26 injured , including two critical cases , were admitted to their hospital alone , with several others also taking in injured .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 160 kilometers -LRB- 100 miles -RRB- east of Budapest .
Serbian police have arrested 156 ethnic Albanians , all former police officers , who they claim were plotting rebellion in Kosovo province , the public prosecutor announced Friday .
In the first official confirmation of the crackdown over the past ten days , Serbian prosecutor Miodrag Brkljac said the ethnic Albanians were members of an illegal group which planned `` armed rebellion against '' Serbia .
It was the biggest police raid in Kosovo since 1989 when Serbia revoked the autonomy of its southern province , where ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the 1.9 million population .
Serbian police now keep a firm grip on any ethnic Albanian dissent .
Ethnic Albanian officials deny planning any armed rebellion against Serbia , saying that would be against their peaceful resistance policy .
Serbia regards Kosovo as the cradle of its history and culture and has vowed never to give it up to the ethnic Albanians who seek independence .
Expectations of continued robust strength for the economy were tempered Friday by reports suggesting the pace could slacken next year .
The government 's main forecasting gauge of future economic activity fell in October for the first time in 15 months .
Also , new orders to U.S. factories slipped for the first time in three months as demand for cars and other transportation equipment plummeted .
`` The slowdown is still an expectation rather than a reality , '' said economist Norman Robertson of Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh .
The data `` tend to suggest that sometime in 1995 we will see a slower-paced expansion . ''
The Commerce Department said its Index of Leading Economic Indicators declined 0.1 percent in October after edging up 0.1 percent in September and climbing 0.5 percent in August .
When the index moves in the same direction for three straight months , it is considered a sign of an economic trend six months down the road .
Analysts had expected the index to rise moderately in October .
But seven of its 11 components fell , led by a slower rate of increase for raw material prices due largely to declines for some paper products .
Other negative factors in the index were a slowing in business orders for plant and equipment , higher weekly initial claims for unemployment insurance , lower money supply , fewer building permits , lower stock prices and declining unfilled orders for durable goods .
The four components that made positive contributions to the index were slower business delivery times that usually are a sign of rising orders , increased average workweek , rising consumer expectations and more new orders for consumer goods .
The Commerce Department also said that factory orders fell 0.4 percent in October after a rise of less than 0.1 percent the previous month .
The decrease , caused by an 8.8 percent drop in transportation equipment led by declining car demand , was expected .
The reports softened somewhat the impact of other data that pointed to a still-surging economy and possible rising inflation .
The Labor Department said unemployment fell to 5.6 percent in November , its lowest rate in four years , as a seasonally adjusted 350,000 new workers were added to the nation 's nonfarm payrolls ,
Reports earlier in the week signaled brisk growth .
Analysts said they doubt the Federal Reserve will move this month to raise short-term interest rates a seventh time this year .
`` I suppose they do n't want to be Scrooge-like and do it before Christmas , '' said Robertson .
`` And there are ambiguities in the numbers . ''
The Federal Open Market Committee , which sets policy for the Federal Reserve , next meets on Dec. 20 and then has a two-day meeting concluding Feb. 1 .
New factory orders , a key gauge of the nation 's manufacturing sector , have risen in 13 of the last 15 months including a 4.7 percent jump in August that was led by auto demand .
They last fell in July , when they were off 2 percent .
Excluding the volatile transportation component , orders rose 0.9 percent in October .
Croatia and its rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement Friday touted as a framework for normalized relations .
But the worst Serb-Croat clashes in months cast doubt on the pact 's chance for success .
The agreement calls for restoring water and electricity supplies and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital Belgrade .
Two sections of the 360-kilometer -LRB- 220-mile -RRB- highway are controlled by Croatian Serbs .
Representatives of the Croatian government signed the accord Friday morning at U.N. headquarters in Zagreb , with international mediators Lord David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg as co-signers .
The document was then brought to Knin , rebel Serb headquarters , where their leaders signed it .
Croatia was effectively partitioned after a six-month war in 1991 .
A cease-fire in January 1992 halted the war , but left Serbs in control of a third of Croatia .
Since then , thousands of skirmishes and bigger clashes have threatened the truce .
On Friday , U.N. spokesman Michael Williams reported the fiercest clashes since the United Nations brokered another cease-fire last March .
It was the third day of artillery duels around Lake Peruca , about 30 kilometers -LRB- 18.6 miles -RRB- southeast of Knin , Alexander Ivanko , another U.N. spokesman , said in Zagreb .
Six Serb soldiers were reported wounded , he said .
Nevertheless , an international mediator said the agreement could be made to work .
`` The significance of the agreement is going to depend on the parties to the agreement , '' Owen told The Associated Press in Knin .
The two sides `` have it in their power to implement the agreement if they want to , '' he added .
But he warned : `` This agreement can easily be blown up literally and metaphorically .
The fighting is continued challenge to it . ''
Croatian President Franjo Tudjman , on a three-day visit to Argentina , called the agreement `` an important step toward the total return of our occupied territories . ''
He said , however , if Serbs refuse to relinquish the territory , `` Croatia will resort to other means , backed by the international community . ''
He did not elaborate .
Croatian Serb representative Borislav Mikelic , though signing the accord , remained firm in the Serbs ' refusal to accept any reintegration with Croatia .
`` By signing this agreement we once more proved that we are in favor of a peaceful solution to the crisis here and we also showed that we 're interested in the economic progress and economic opening to Europe and the world , '' Mikelic said .
But he refused to discuss the crucial overall political solution , saying , `` This is not the time to talk about it . ''
The self-styled Croatian Serb assembly approved the economic accord late Thursday .
Negotiations between the two sides had been stalled .
But the Croatian Serbs relented after a recent meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic , the Balkans ' power broker .
Thousands of peacekeepers have been deployed between the warring sides in the disputed territories since the 1992 cease-fire .
But international efforts toward lasting peace have failed over what seemed to be irreconcilable differences .
This is the first accord between the foes since they agreed March 29 on a formal cease-fire to end their 1991 war .
Sweden 's new government is trying to retake a central role alongside Norway in the Middle East peace process after a three-year hiatus .
The government 's initiative features an unusual trip to Israel this weekend by an ex-foreign minister to hammer out an economic assistance plan for Palestinian territories .
Sweden 's `` concrete plan '' will detail immediate improvements in conditions for Gaza and the West Bank , the Swedish newspaper Dagens Nyheter reported this week .
Sweden hopes the effort , undertaken at the request of Israel and the PLO , will include `` political '' issues , said the official , Sten Andersson , who was involved in talks leading to the 1991 Madrid peace conference .
`` This is social and economic and political , '' Andersson told The Associated Press before leaving Sweden Friday .
`` It 's high time for Sweden to do something .
The peace process is in a very critical stage right now .
There must be some signs for the -LRB- Palestinian -RRB- population that something will happen . ''
Administration and economic development in Gaza are priorities for Arafat , who is facing pressure from Islamic radicals because of dismal conditions in the territories .
Israeli officials have hinted they want to speed up the process .
In Brussels this week , foreign donors released dlrs 125 million pledged earlier for the Palestinians .
Among the plans already under consideration are job-creation programs and the establishment of an industrial zone along Gaza 's borders to attract investment .
