In its final report to the Security Council , a U.N. commission again charged Rwanda 's Hutu leaders with genocide and said Friday it could find no evidence the new government engaged in systematic killings .
The findings , particularly of genocide , add to the legal evidence that may be used against any Hutu leaders brought before a war crimes tribunal .
But the commission 's final report added little to its initial conclusions in October .
The 58-page document explicitly blamed Hutus for mass killings carried out `` in a concerted , planned , systematic and methodical way . ''
An estimated 500,000 people , mostly ethnic Tutsis and moderate Hutus , were massacred by the Hutu army and militias after the death of the Hutu president in a mysterious plane crash on April 6 .
Many of those accused of the worst atrocities are now sheltering in refugee camps in neighboring Zaire and there are fears that -- with the help of international aid -- they are preparing a violent invasion of Rwanda .
The three-man panel said it had been unable to find evidence that the new Tutsi-led Royal Patriotic Front government had instigated systematic killings after it assumed power last July .
But it added that it was `` disturbed by ongoing violence committed by some RPF soldiers , '' and recommended that investigations should continue .
It said it had not had enough time itself to complete the inquiry .
Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali ordered the commission to check into alleged massacres by RPF soldiers after some U.N. officials said they had carried out reprisal killings of up to 30,000 people in August and September .
The government arrested some of its own soldiers after the allegations .
An express train derailed Friday sending cars smashing into a railroad station southeast of Budapest and burying people under the rubble .
At least 20 people were killed , police said .
The accident occurred at 4:45 p.m. in Szajol , a station near Szolnok about 70 kilometers -LRB- 43 miles -RRB- southeast of the Hungarian capital .
The second car of the train derailed , dragging three other cars with it , and the overturned carriages crashed into the station building , railway officials said .
`` There was a tremedous explosion , like the end of the world , '' said a railway employee who witnessed the accident and asked not to be identified .
He said in a telephone interview that people remained buried in the wreckage more than four hours after the crash .
National Police Maj. Imre Olah said 20 deaths had been confirmed , `` but that 's not the final count by any means . ''
Ambulance crews said between 20 and 40 people were believed injured .
Doctors at one hospital near Szolnok said 26 injured people , including two critical cases , had been admitted to their hospital .
Several other hospitals were also taking in the injured .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 160 kilometers -LRB- 100 miles -RRB- east of Budapest , to the capital .
