Sweden 's new government wants to retake a central role alongside Norway in the Mideast peace process after a three-year hiatus .
The government 's initiative features an unusual trip to Israel this weekend by a former foreign minister to devise an economic assistance plan for Palestinian territories .
The plan will detail immediate improvements in conditions for Gaza and the West Bank , the Swedish newspaper Dagens Nyheter reported this week .
Sweden hopes the effort , undertaken at the request of Israel and the PLO , will include `` political '' issues , said the official , Sten Andersson , who was involved in talks leading to the 1991 Madrid peace conference .
`` It 's high time for Sweden to do something , '' Andersson told The Associated Press before leaving Sweden Friday .
`` The peace process is in a very critical stage right now .
There must be some signs for the -LRB- Palestinian -RRB- population that something will happen . ''
Administration and economic development in Gaza are priorities for PLO leader Yasser Arafat , who is facing pressure from Islamic radicals .
Israeli officials have hinted they want to speed up the process .
In Brussels this week , foreign donors released dlrs 125 million pledged earlier for the Palestinians .
Among the plans under consideration are job-creation programs and the establishment of an industrial zone along Gaza 's borders to attract investment .
Andersson , 71 , declined to detail his initiative , other than saying he had new ideas which could be included in the plan to be discussed in Stockholm Dec. 12 by Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres .
Sweden 's neighbor , Norway , already has been deeply involved in the peace process since the country established its acclaimed `` Oslo Channel '' two years ago .
That channel led to last year 's peace treaty signed in Washington .
In what may be mainly a footnote to history , Sweden 's new initiative arises from a domestic political feud and a friendly rivalry with Norway for the mantle of peacemaker in the Middle East .
Swedish officials , led by Andersson , had been intimately involved in Israeli-Palestinian contacts until 1991 , when the Social Democrats lost elections to a center-conservative coalition led by former Prime Minister Carl Bildt .
According to Andersson and other officials , the Social Democrats at the time had close contacts with the Palestine Liberation Organization , and Arafat was looking for a third country to foster contacts with Israel .
`` The -LRB- conservative -RRB- Bildt government was very passive , that was a pity , '' said Andersson , a career Social Democrat .
`` So then I recommended to the PLO that they go to the Norwegians . ''
Norway 's government was led by Social Democrats also .
Palestinians then turned to Norwegian diplomats to set up talks which eventually led to the `` Oslo Channel , '' a Scandinavian diplomat involved with the talks said on condition of anonymity .
The diplomat , however , said the relationship had been established well before the change of power in Sweden .
Andersson , now retired , insisted the new Social Democratic government , which returned to power last September , was not trying to take over Norway 's role in the peace process .
`` The Norwegians have done a magnificent job and I 'm not here to compete with them , '' Andersson said .
Bildt 's spokeswoman referred all questions about the period to Bildt or his former aides , none of whom could be reached for comment Friday .
An unemployed maid and mother of seven burned a winning dlrs 60,000 lottery ticket because her minister said she would go to hell if she took the devil 's money .
Maria Benoiza Nascimento , 39 , said she was `` confused '' by the warning from her minister at an Assembly of God church in Fortaleza , 1,200 miles -LRB- 1,900 kilometers -RRB- northeast of Brasilia , the Correio Braziliense newspaper reported Friday .
