An express train headed from eastern Hungary to Budapest derailed Friday and slammed into a station building , killing at least 20 people .
Between 20 and 40 people were believed injured , according to ambulance crews taking victims to hospitals .
The accident occurred at Szajol , about 40 miles southeast of the Hungarian capital , when the second car of an express train derailed and dragged three other cars off the tracks .
The overturned carriages smashed into the station building , railway officials said .
`` There was a tremedous explosion , like the end of the world , '' a railway employee who witnessed the accident said in a telephone interview .
People were still buried in the wreckage more than four hours after the crash , said the employee , who spoke on condition of anonymity .
National Police Maj. Imre Olah said 20 deaths had been confirmed `` but that 's not the final count by any means . ''
Doctors at a hospital near Szolnok , close to the site of the accident , said they admitted 26 injured people to their hospital alone .
Several other hospitals also took in injured .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 100 miles east of Budapest .
Rwanda 's prime minister warned Friday that a proposed U.N. force to restore security in refugee camps will fail unless militiamen in the camps are convinced they can not overthrow the new government .
Prime Minister Faustin Twagiramungu also appealed for international aid to help his government stabilize the chaos in Rwanda .
U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali last week recommended sending as many as 5,000 peacekeepers to the camps in neighboring Zaire , which shelter hundreds of thousands of Rwandan refugees .
The Security Council has not yet acted on the proposal and Twagiramungu 's warning is likely to make the council more cautious .
Militiamen and soldiers who fled Rwanda with an estimated 1.2 million refugees are in effect controlling camps and there is evidence that they are planning an invasion of Rwanda .
`` You must convince soldiers there that their aim of coming to Rwanda by violence is no longer possible , '' Twagiramungu said .
`` They can not win the war they want to win . ''
He said the United Nations must also help persuade refugees that they can safely return to Rwanda .
`` Otherwise if you go into the camps ... I am afraid that certain conflict is going to break -LRB- out -RRB- and it can take us too far . ''
Twagiramungu said the Rwandan army could stop any attempted invasion by soldiers of the former government `` unless there is ... outside assistance . ''
But he said there were fears that the militiamen could carry out a protracted guerrilla war .
In an appeal to the refugees , Twagiramungu said that `` those who want to rebuild their nation , they must come back . ''
Rwanda has warned that it will prosecute militiamen responsible for massacres .
Twagiramungu , however , said he believed that `` 90 percent '' of the refugees were innocent of genocide .
The Tutsi-led rebels , the Rwandan Patriotic Front , defeated the Hutu government after the death of Rwanda 's president in a plane crash sparked a massacre , mostly of minority Tutsis .
Between April and June , an estimated 500,000 people were killed .
