The U.S. Postal Service on Friday defended its stamp recalling the atomic bombing of Japan saying that it could not omit such a major event from its World War II history series .
The stamp , showing a mushroom-shaped cloud rising from an atomic blast , is one of a set of 10 stamps marking major events of 1945 to be sold on a sheet titled `` 1945 : Victory at Last . ''
Forty stamps have already been issued in similar sets for the 50th anniversary of the 1941-44 war years .
But the atomic bomb stamp is drawing sharp criticism in Japan .
Sunao Tsuboi , acting director of the 30,000-member Hiroshima Prefectural Confederation of A-bomb Survivors Organizations , termed it `` outrageous . ''
Japan surrendered Aug. 15 , 1945 , days after atomic bombs were dropped on the cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki .
`` Atomic bombs hasten war 's end , August 1945 , '' says the caption on the mushroom cloud stamp .
Postal Service spokesman Robin Wright said the World War II series was developed in cooperation with the State and Defense departments to assure historical accuracy .
As far as the atomic bomb stamp , he said , `` we would be remiss in omitting such a watershed and historically critical event as the use of the atomic bomb . ''
`` Our purpose is to provide a comprehensive history of events of World War II , and we are not making a value judgment on any of those events , '' Wright added .
Other stamps in the 1945 set picture U.S. Marines raising the American flag on Iwo Jima , `` Okinawa , the last big battle , '' liberations of Manila and of Holocaust survivors in Europe , Germany 's surrender at Reims , refugees uprooted by war and U.S. celebrations of Japanese surrender .
The 1941 set , titled `` A World at War '' included stamps showing Japanese bombing Pearl Harbor , Hawaii , and President Roosevelt and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill framing the Atlantic Charter .
The 1944 set , titled `` Road to Victory '' included the allied Normandy landings , the liberation of Rome and the battles of Leyte Gulf in the Pacific and the Bulge in Belgium .
Growers , sellers and users of marijuana gathered here Friday at an event that was part drug festival , part trade fair .
The second annual Netherweed Festival drew about 2,000 enthusiastic visitors with a mixture of events ranging from a contest to decide the nation 's best Dutch-grown weed to a fashion show and pop music .
But for many it was a chance to meet business contacts and do deals in the growers ' room , although selling the product was not allowed .
Giving it away , maybe .
Netherweed has become the generic term for high-power marijuana developed and grown in the Netherlands , a nation known for its high-tech agricultural techniques .
`` There are about 20 paying stalls here and a couple of non-commercial stands , '' said Henk van Velthooven , spokesman for the organizer , the Dutch marijuana magazine `` High Life . ''
He spoke proudly of how the commercial stalls were helping out by sponsoring the event at the Marcanti Plaza , while non-commercials like the Dutch Cannabis Consumers ' Union was there for free , trying to recruit new members .
If anyone could see the stall through the dense smoke .
`` Before we took over , there were a lot of local harvest festivals , but we 've taken this to a national level , '' said Van Velthooven .
One man at the festival for business rather than pleasure was John Campion , 34 , of Hartlepool in northeast England .
`` I 've been running a shop selling growing kits for five months and in that time I 've had a turnover of about 150,000 pounds -LRB- dlrs 230,000 -RRB- , '' he said .
`` I do like a smoke , but this is business .
I regard it solely as business . ''
Campion said he exploits a loophole in British law that allows him to sell equipment for growing marijuana , but does not allow people to use the equipment after they 've bought it .
`` We do n't ask people what they are going to do with it , '' said Campion with a wink .
In the Netherlands , the sale and possession of both hard and soft drugs in small quantities are non-prosecutable offenses , although technically still illegal .
Police prefer to concentrate on arresting large-scale traffickers .
Ed Rosenthal , a self-proclaimed `` marijuana expert '' from Oakland , Calif. , was invited to the festival to give a speech on growing techniques .
When he arrived , there was no microphone and no projector for his slides , but he did n't seem to mind .
`` Get me a chair to stand on and a joint , pure marijuana with hashish and we 'll be alright , '' he told the organizers .
`` If they had an event like this in America , the police would be in here arresting everybody , '' added Rosenthal .
Another aspect of the festival was a competition for the best marijuana grown in the Netherlands .
A jury of experts was hoping to give its verdict after weeks of testing .
`` If there 's anyone still standing , '' said Van Velthooven .
Russian lawmakers negotiating the release of prisoners in Chechnya accused their own government Friday of sending the jets that have attacked the breakaway republic .
Four Russian parliament members , allies of President Boris Yeltsin , are trying to get Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev to release about 70 Russians , including Army soldiers , who were captured in fighting .
Dudayev , who declared independence for his Caucasus Mountain republic in 1991 , says Moscow is arming and leading the rebels .
Yeltsin 's government has denied providing anything but political support , even as jets have attacked and Russian soldiers have been captured .
Jets roared over Grozny , the Chechen capital , for a fourth day Friday .
Raids this week have killed at least four civilians and an airport guard , and destroyed planes at civilian and military airports .
`` It is clear that these planes are not English or French , but Russian , '' said Ella Pamfilova , a parliament member a member of the delegation .
`` This is against the law . ''
`` You can rest assured that President Yeltsin has recognized the prisoners as members of the Russian Army , '' delegation leader Sergei Yushenkov said .
Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has called the captives mercenaries .
A dozen prisoners , interviewed by The Associated Press while Chechen guards watched , said they were promised money by Russia 's Federal Counterintelligence Service for fighting with the Chechen rebels .
But they said the operations went badly , and that some of their Chechen allies did not know how to use guns and fled .
Counterintelligence spokesman Alexander Mikhailov , asked about such reports at a news conference Friday , said only that Chechnya is part of Russia and that the servicemen should be called volunteers , not mercenaries , ITAR-Tass and Interfax said .
Dudayev first threatened to kill the prisoners if Russia did not claim them , but later said they would be tried in court .
Yeltsin had threatened to send troops if they were not released .
Moscow has toned down the threat .
