Akashi went to Pale for talks with the Bosnian Serb leadership after meetings with Bosnia 's Muslim-led government in Sarajevo .
Shortly before he arrived at the presidency , where the Bosnian government has its offices , Bosnian Serb gunners ringing the capital fired two anti-tank missiles at the building .
One destroyed the office of Miro Lazovic moments after he left for the Akashi meeting .
Lazovic is an ethnic Serb member of Bosnia 's collective presidency .
A short while later , three more missiles hit nearby buildings .
There were no injuries .
The Bosnian government complained about Akashi 's `` shuttle diplomacy '' and blasted the United Nations for failing to use force to halt the Serb attack on Bihac , as fighting continued in that northwest region Friday .
`` Instead of doing what they have to do , the U.N. is driving back and forth .
... This Munich policy is a humiliation of the international community , '' said Kemal Muftic , chief adviser to Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic .
He was referring to European appeasement of Adolf Hitler at a 1938 meeting in Munich before World War II .
Charles Redman , a U.S. diplomat , was also back in Sarajevo , leading talks with Izetbegovic and Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic that presumably focused on a proposed new peace plan .
Redman , now U.S. ambassador to Germany , helped draft the first international peace plan drawn up by the five-nation Contact Group , which the Serbs have repeatedly rejected .
Although that proposal was presented to the Serbs as a take-it-or-leave-it plan , the lack of Western will to use force has allowed the Serbs to demand , apparently successfully , the right of future confederal links with Serb-led Yugoslavia .
The original plan denied Serbs that as punishment for starting the war , though it granted the Bosnian Croat-Muslim federation similar rights to link with Croatia .
Akashi hoped to have more success with the Serbs than his boss , Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali .
Boutros-Ghali was rebuffed in even trying to meet the Bosnian Serbs on Wednesday , and afterwards said intransigence by the warring sides might force the end of the U.N. mission .
Seventy Dutch peacekeepers arrived in Zagreb , Croatia , Friday after being released from a seven-day detention by the Serbs in eastern Bosnia , U.N. officials said .
But Serbs continued to hold about 20 other Dutch peacekeepers , along with hundreds of British , Ukrainians and Canadians , at various points throughout Bosnia .
In New York , Russia and Ukraine issued a statement Friday calling on U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and the U.N. command to take `` all appropriate measures ... to facilitate the release of all captured or detained '' U.N. personnel .
Earlier in Bosnia , U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi also wanted to discuss with Karadzic the continued fighting around Bihac , where the United Nations is trying to broker a cease-fire .
There was no immediate indication of any progress .
A number of detonations were reported on the edge of the Bihac `` safe area '' Friday , along with machine-gun and small arms fire , U.N. officials said .
But the heaviest fighting appeared concentrated around Velika Kladusa , north of Bihac , where Serbs were apparently closing in on the government army 's 5th Corps .
The Bosnian Serbs , backed by Serbs from neighboring Croatia , want to wipe out the 5th Corps , which launched a briefly successful offensive from the Bihac enclave , part of which is a U.N.-designated `` safe area , '' in late October .
There were also signs that the frontlines south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , who are allied with the Muslim-led government forces , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
A Croat militia and the Bosnian army took Kupres from the Serbs in a joint attack last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Serbs in neighboring Croatia also had shelled his forces across the border , near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
Most of the 608 passengers aboard the Cebu City were sleeping when a freighter slammed into the ferry Friday in Manila Bay .
The ferry sank a half hour later , a one-meter -LRB- three-foot -RRB- hole in the lower deck .
At least 34 people drowned .
Divers discovered more bodies in the ship , lying under 30 meters -LRB- 100 feet -RRB- of water , but could not get to them before the search for the more than 100 people still missing was called off for the night .
`` Suddenly we heard a crash , '' Erwin Maravilla said .
`` I grabbed my two children , but when the ferry sank we were sucked under the water with it .
A piece of metal hit my arm , and I lost hold of my two kids . ''
His wife also was among the missing .
Ships in the area plucked 451 people from the sea , many coated with the diesel oil disgorged as the ferry sank .
The freighter , the Singapore-registered Kota Suria , joined in the rescue effort , its bow badly bent .
Survivors complained the crew did little to save people .
The radio room may have been severely damaged because the distress signals came from other ships .
Maximo Calamba , who was rescued with his wife and 1-year-old son , said he heard many cries for help .
`` There was no alarm .
We were thrown off our cots and everybody was on their own . ''
The collision occurred before dawn near the town of Rosario , about 55 kilometers -LRB- 35 miles -RRB- southwest of Manila .
The freighter , five times the ferry 's size , destroyed the bridge and tore a gaping hole in the lower deck .
The captain and his mates were in the bridge , the control section of the ferry , said one crewman , Jacob Cabatuan .
They were among the missing .
The cause of the accident , which occurred in calm seas under clear night skies , is under investigation .
The company that owns the ferry said it was rammed .
Danny Dalugdog , a driver and bodyguard , was separated from his wife and 3-month-old son in the confusion .
`` I thought they were gone . ''
But he found his wife on the freighter .
Then , as they transferred to a coast guard ship to return to Manila , a passenger called out that he found a baby boy .
`` It turned out to be my son , '' Dalugdog said .
A coast guard spokesman , Lt. Cmdr. Amado Samante , said 451 passengers had been rescued and 34 bodies recovered , many children and women .
`` There were more bodies inside the cabins , '' said Angel Espidido , a coast guard diver .
Divers could see the dead through the portholes but were unable to open the doors late Friday .
`` Tomorrow we will go back to unlock them . ''
Cargo containers and rubber rafts floated in the sea , but many survivors apparently never got a chance to use them .
`` I was jolted by the crash and I woke up , '' said Melissa Selosia , who was on her way to going to Mindanao Island , 780 kilometers -LRB- 485 miles -RRB- south of Manila for Christmas with her four children .
`` I grabbed a life jacket and made for the upper deck and then I jumped into the water . ''
She said she swam as quickly as possible from the sinking ferry , recalling her seaman husband 's words that a sinking boat will suck down everything around it .
The ferry 's owner , the William Lines shipping company , said 608 people were on board .
The accident coincided with the company 's initial public stock offering Friday .
The ferry , which can carry 800 people , was en route to Tagbilaran , capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- southeast of Manila .
The worst peacetime ferry disaster occurred in the Philippines in December 1987 when 4,341 people died in the collision of the ferry Dona Paz with the oil tanker Vector off Mindoro Island , 130 kilometers -LRB- 80 miles -RRB- south of Manila .
Church of England leaders on Friday decided to examine their policy against church remarriage of divorced people .
Some vicars now bend the existing guidelines and allow new marriages , others follow the letter of the law and refuse to marry divorcees , while still others seek permission from their bishops .
The state church 's ruling General Synod on Friday told members of the House of Bishops to examine the issue and report back .
The church 's second-highest ranking prelate appeared to throw his weight behind change .
Archbishop of York John Habgood said the time had come to clear up the confusion and find common agreement .
But said he believed the situation had changed in recent years .
Divorced people could now become priests -- a move that was `` not nearly so difficult as was first feared . ''
He told the Synod 's 560 members at their London meeting : `` I hope we can reflect on that and how that is viewed in our own dioceses .
We may find grounds for bringing a more coordinated policy back . ''
In a bizarre raid lasting several hours Friday night , heavily armed police in ski masks blocked off a downtown building that houses city government and the offices of one of Russia 's top bankers .
It was not clear who conducted the raid or whether it actually had anything to do with banker Vladimir Gusinsky or his prominent Most Group .
But six of the bank 's employees were detained , and company cars and employees were searched as they tried to leave .
Gusinsky called it the latest case of harassment against Russia 's entrepreneurs , and drafted a letter to President Boris Yeltsin demanding an investigation .
The banker said the armed men blocked off his offices without explanation at about 5 p.m.
They left about five hours later .
The Interior Ministry eventually told him the gunmen were part of a task force against organized crime , Gusinsky said .
The Interfax news agency cited non-official sources saying the action was in response to shots fired near the building , which is across the street from the White House , the Russian government 's headquarters .
Two Most Group drivers and four guards were detained , regional prosecutor Alexander Silykhovkin said .
He gave no other details .
The Most Group has more than 10 different companies , including a bank , newspaper and TV network .
The Association of Russian Banks issued a protest .
