First-place Borussia Dortmund defeated MSV Duisburg 1-0 Friday to win some distance from pursuers in the Bundesliga , Germany 's first-division soccer league .
Veteran national player Karlheinz Riedle scored in the 45th minute for Dortmund , which went into the weekend 's round only one point ahead of Werder Bremen .
On Saturday , Bremen plays away at Karlsruhe .
In Friday 's only other game , Stefan Kuntz scored in the 81st minute to give Kaiserslautern a tough 1-1 tie at home with 1860 Munich .
Bernhard Winkler headed in a goal for Munich in the 54th minute .
Columns of refugees freezing in the snow .
NATO embroiled in a savage war in mountain bottlenecks .
UN soldiers dying along impassable roads .
The consequences of suddenly pulling UN peacekeepers out of the former Yugoslavia are things that give military planners nightmares .
`` Getting out of there is going to take casualties , there 's no way around it , '' said Jim Dunnigan , a New York-based author and military analyst .
Some politicans say the UN should just withdraw , but it 's easier said than done .
Winter weather , bad roads , potential opposition and the mobs of refugees that might tag along on a retreat could create disaster .
Officials at the UN estimate it would take five months to pull the 23,000 peacekeepers from 20 nations out of Bosnia-Herzegovina under ideal conditions .
In the face of opposition , retreat could mean death and destruction .
Gen. John de Chastelain , Canada 's top soldier , says evacuation plans exist , but adds that all contingencies have to be taken into account and that there 's no intention of pulling out Canada 's 2,000 soldiers .
He admits a sudden , opposed withdrawal would be difficult .
It likely would be opposed right now .
To the Muslims , the UN is a protector and provider of food , fuel and medicine .
Bosnian Serbs see peacekeepers as a handy shield against air attacks .
`` The UN 's scattered all over hell 's half acre in penny packets , '' said Martin Shadwick of York University .
`` It 's not as if they 're all in one or two super bases where you could collect them from .
Getting them to collection points would be tricky . ''
They 'd likely have to destroy tonnes of supplies and equipment to keep them from one side or another .
Would the factions stand idly by and watch food , medicine , ammunition and vehicles burned or ruined ?
Once the peacekeepers assembled , how would they escape ?
Helicopters and transport planes are big , noisy and slow .
`` They make beautiful targets , '' said Dunnigan .
Lew MacKenzie , the retired peacekeeping general , said allied air power might try to clear a corridor 20 kilometres wide on either side of the evacuation route to hold off artillery attacks .
`` The aircraft will try to maintain combat air patrol over you the entire way to the border and even then -LRB- attackers -RRB- will be able to slip through .
One anti-tank weapon knocking out the leading vehicle will do the job . ''
Sean Henry , a retired artillery colonel , said a hostile withdrawal in winter conditions `` would quickly degenerate into a very serious situation .
`` They would either have to fight their way out and absorb casualties or somehow or other have a force of Americans , Britons and French come ashore and establish a defended corridor or a series of defended corridors and routes . ''
That would mean extensive clashes in mountainous terrain under winter skies that make flying iffy .
Henry 's advice : Do n't leave unless it 's the only choice .
What if thousands of refugees clog the roads ?
`` We 're just not the kind of people that drive over kids that are sitting in front of the tracks , '' said MacKenzie .
Dunnigan offers a novel approach : bribe your way out .
He admits that `` people back here , safe and sound by their hearth , will say , What ! ''
But it could work and save lives , he said .
`` Buy off the local gunsels .
That 's the sort of thing these guys will listen to . ''
Bosnian Serb leaders were reported Friday to have promised to release hundreds of detained UN peacekeepers , but Canadian officials in Paris could not confirm the report .
There was also no sign of any change in the status of the 55 Canadian peacekeepers facing a second weekend being detained by Bosnian Serbs .
Reuters news agency and the Associated Press quoted UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi as saying Bosnian Serb leaders had agreed to release Ukrainian peacekeepers held in northern Bosnia , as well as Dutch and British convoys detained since Saturday .
`` In addition , we have agreed that normal activities be restored to the Canadians -- 55 Canadians near Visoko -- and all other soldiers from other countries that were doing their work at weapons collection sites , '' Akashi was quoted as saying after talks with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic in Pale , near Sarajevo .
Whether the promises would be kept remained to be seen , as Serbs have repeatedly broken their word to the United Nations .
The Serbs have been holding about 400 UN soldiers as insurance against NATO airstrikes on their siege of the Muslim pocket of Bihac , a UN-declared safe haven in northwest Bosnia .
In Paris , senior Canadian officials said the situation was still evolving and they could not confirm any dead had been reached .
`` When the hostages are free , that will be a confirmation , '' one senior official said .
The officials are in Paris with Prime Minister Jean Chretien .
A UN spokesman in Zagreb , Croatia said he had heard the news reports about such an agreement `` but we 're not officially confirming that at the moment . ''
Reuters reported the Serbs apparently rejected a new ceasefire proposal drafted by the United Nations which the Bosnian government accepted hours ago .
Yet the Serbs also released 70 Dutch peacekeepers taken hostage Saturday near Zvornik in eastern Bosnia .
The soldiers were in good condition , Dutch officials said .
The 55 Canadians have been held for the past 10 days at various sites in Serb-held territory near their peacekeeping camp in Visoko , near Sarajevo .
About 20 are at a police complex in the village of Illijas .
The rest are at checkpoints and observation posts .
The soldiers are in radio contact with their camp and those at observation posts carry on their work .
Maj. Dean Milner , the senior officer among the detainees , is able to drive around in his vehicle and visit his soldiers .
The Serbs are allowing supply vehicles from camp to reach the soldiers with mail , food and other items .
Akashi , the top UN civilian leader in Bosnia set out Friday to hold talks with the Bosnian government in Sarajevo and with Serb leader Karadzic in Pale .
His mission started badly .
Three missiles hit the Bosnian government building shortly before he arrived .
Growers , sellers and users of marijuana gathered here Friday at an event that was part drug festival , part trade fair .
The second annual Netherweed Festival drew about 2,000 enthusiastic visitors with a mixture of events ranging from a contest to decide the nation 's best Dutch-grown weed to a fashion show and pop music .
But for many it was a chance to meet business contacts and do deals in the growers ' room , although selling the product was not allowed .
Giving it away , maybe .
Netherweed has become the generic term for high-power marijuana developed and grown in the Netherlands , a nation known for its high-tech agricultural techniques .
`` There are about 20 paying stalls here and a couple of non-commercial stands , '' said Henk van Velthooven , spokesman for the organizer , the Dutch marijuana magazine `` High Life . ''
He spoke proudly of how the commercial stalls were helping out by sponsoring the event at the Marcanti Plaza , while non-commercials like the Dutch Cannabis Consumers ' Union was there for free , trying to recruit new members .
If anyone could see the stall through the dense smoke .
`` Before we took over , there were a lot of local harvest festivals , but we 've taken this to a national level , '' said Van Velthooven .
One man at the festival for business rather than pleasure was John Campion , 34 , of Hartlepool in northeast England .
`` I 've been running a shop selling growing kits for five months and in that time I 've had a turnover of about 150,000 pounds -LRB- dlrs 230,000 -RRB- , '' he said .
`` I do like a smoke , but this is business .
I regard it solely as business . ''
Campion said he exploits a loophole in British law that allows him to sell equipment for growing marijuana , but does not allow people to use the equipment after they 've bought it .
`` We do n't ask people what they are going to do with it , '' said Campion with a wink .
In the Netherlands , the sale and possession of both hard and soft drugs in small quantities are non-prosecutable offenses , although technically still illegal .
Police prefer to concentrate on arresting large-scale traffickers .
Ed Rosenthal , a self-proclaimed `` marijuana expert '' from Oakland , Calif. , was invited to the festival to give a speech on growing techniques .
When he arrived , there was no microphone and no projector for his slides , but he did n't seem to mind .
`` Get me a chair to stand on and a joint , pure marijuana with hashish and we 'll be alright , '' he told the organizers .
