Boris Yeltsin was bad luck for Russian tennis on Friday , and Sweden 's Davis Cup team hopes to see him again soon .
The Russian president and his entourage interrupted play at a critical moment in the tense fifth set of Stefan Edberg 's match against Alexander Volkov .
Edberg , energized by the pause , ended Volkov 's come-from-behind drive and led Sweden to a 2-0 singles sweep , winning 6-4 , 6-2 , 6-7 -LRB- 2-7 -RRB- , 0-6 , 8-6 .
Magnus Larsson , ranked 19th by the ATP Tour , went on to defeat No. 11-ranked Yevgeny Kafelnikov in another five set thriller , 6-0 , 6-2 , 3-6 , 2-6 , 6-3 .
The losses disappointed the whistling , foot-stomping hometown crowd of 12,000 at Olympic Stadium , and likely doomed Russia 's chances of becoming the first unseeded team to win the Davis Cup .
On Saturday , Kafelnikov and Andrei Olhovskiy upset the top-ranked doubles team and recently crowned ATP Tour doubles champions Jonas Bjorkman and Jan Apell to keep their hopes alive and send the best-of-five match to Sunday 's reverse singles .
Kafelnikov accused Yeltsin of ruining Volkov 's concentration .
Unlike other fans , a smiling and waving Yeltsin took his seat without waiting for the brief break when the players change sides .
`` Do you remember what the score was when the president arrived ? ''
`` It was 5-5 .
Is there a switch then ?
What sensible person in a decisive game like this , with the score 5-5 , would do something like that in such a tense situation ? ''
Volkov , however , did not blame Yeltsin .
`` I could n't have failed to notice when the president arrived , '' he said .
`` -LRB- But -RRB- I can say it interfered with my game as much as rain outside would have , because I had lost my serve by then . ''
Edberg said he did n't realize until later that it was Yeltsin who had caused the delay .
But considering the outcome , `` maybe I should thank Boris for coming in , '' he said .
Larsson said he hopes to see more of Yeltsin .
`` I wish him welcome tomorrow for doubles , '' he said .
`` But maybe he can come in during the changeover next time . ''
Volkov held match point on his serve leading 5-4 when Edberg sent a backhand down the line to send it to deuce .
He went on to break Volkov and then earned the critical break in the final game .
`` Maybe he played it a little safe , '' Edberg said about facing match point .
`` I took charge of the match in that game .
I took a few chances and it paid off . ''
After winning the first two sets , the seventh-ranked Edberg appeared en route to an easy victory .
But buoyed by the flag-waving , cheering crowd , Volkov battled back in the third set , punctuated with a crowd-pleasing ace to take the tiebreaker .
Volkov , 27 , then dominated Edberg in the fourth set with devastating passing shots and seemed set to take the match , serving for the victory in the final set .
`` I needed to kick myself , especially in the fifth set , '' Edberg said .
`` I was a little bit depressed .
I had the match in my hand and became defensive ... I felt I was getting closer and closer in every game in the fifth set . ''
Friday 's loss was Kafelnikov 's first in eight Davis Cup matches .
His only other loss was in his debut to Germany 's Michael Stich in March 1993 .
Kafelnikov said he felt `` mental and psychological pressure '' after Volkov 's dramatic defeat , and said he said he injured his left wrist in the second game of the last set .
He strained the same wrist last week .
`` It did n't really hurt but I felt very insecure .
I could n't hit slices , '' he said .
The government may suspend its case against General Motors pickup trucks alleged to be fire hazards in crashes , sources close to the case said Friday .
For its part , GM would spend up to dlrs 60 million on safety and research programs .
Transportation Secretary Federico Pena scheduled a news conference for 3:30 p.m. in Washington concerning the trucks .
The sources , who spoke on condition they not be identified , said the idea behind the deal would be that the safety and research program GM would fund has the potential to save more lives than a recall of GM 's 1973-87 C-K pickups .
Pena announced Oct. 17 that he had determined the trucks present an unreasonable risk of fire in side-impact collisions because their fuel tanks are mounted outside the vehicle frame .
He scheduled a public meeting , set for Tuesday in Washington , to gather additional information on whether he should order a recall .
The deal described by the sources would cancel the meeting , and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and the Transportation Department would not proceed with further steps toward a recall .
GM has never wavered in its argument that the trucks are among the safest vehicles on the road .
NHTSA began investigating them two years ago after consumer groups petitioned for a recall .
The agency asked GM to voluntarily recall the trucks in 1993 .
Pena acknowledged in October that the trucks meet federal crash safety standards , but he said the law requires that they be safe in real-world conditions as well .
GM filed suit last month seeking to block any further action by him in the case .
About 9 million of the trucks were built between model years 1973 and 1987 and sold under Chevrolet and GMC nameplates .
GM estimates about 5 million still are in use .
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and NATO 's top civilian official denied Friday that the alliance had abandoned its enforcement of the U.N. `` no-fly '' zone over Bosnia .
`` NATO is continuing to enforce the no-fly zone , '' Christopher said , amid continued confusion between the United Nations and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization over how to deal with the crisis in Bosnia .
Earlier Friday , Wing Commander Timothy Hewlet , U.N. director for air operations in Bosnia , told reporters in Sarajevo that Bosnian Serbs had activated several surface-to-air missile sites throughout the country , threatening humanitarian flights and NATO jets .
Hewlet said NATO had agreed to a `` cooling off '' period to calm tensions , but was able to `` control '' the situation with AWACs planes flying outside Bosnian air space .
`` There are no flights over Bosnia at the moment that I am aware of , '' he said .
At NATO headquarters , Secretary-General Willy Claes said he was unaware of any request from the United Nations to halt or scale-down Allied patrols enforcing of the military flight ban , designed to protect Bosnian civilians from bombardment .
`` We have never received any request , can I be any clearer than that ? ''
However , Yasushi Akashi , the chief U.N. envoy in former Yugoslavia , acknowledged talks on the issue were underway .
`` I can not comment on internal discussions which we are conducting with NATO , '' Akashi told reporters after meeting with Bosnian Serb leaders in Pale , their stronghold east of Sarajevo .
`` But I am glad that NATO is adopting an attitude that they are essentially at the service of UNPROFOR in the peacekeeping mission . ''
NATO and the United Nations have repeatedly talked of the need to `` show presence '' in the skies over Bosnia .
But NATO sources in Brussels said Allied planes had been fired on nine times in recent days by Serb missiles and fixed by targeting radar some 15 times .
Under current rules of engagement , NATO planes can strike back if targeted without prior approval from the United Nations .
Thant Myint-U , a U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , cautioned that such retaliation could lead to an increase in fighting at a time when international negotiators were trying to revive flagging peace efforts .
`` There would be massive escalation in the situation on the ground that could spin out of control , '' Thant said .
Christopher told reporters Serb anti-missile batteries posed a problem .
But , he said , NATO was capable of dealing with them , `` and we continue to police the ` no-fly ' zone in the effective way we have in the past . ''
In Washington however , a senior U.S. military officer acknowledged that pilots and other NATO forces were taking steps to lessen the threat to aircraft .
He would not elaborate .
On Tuesday , officials said the United Nations requested and NATO agreed that planes would not fly over Bosnia for a 48-hour period while U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and other peace negotiators visited Sarajevo .
Western military sources said it appeared that request was extended slightly , and it was not clear if NATO planes were back in Bosnian airspace .
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic , speaking in Pale after his meeting with Akashi , said , `` We would like to see skies clear of ... NATO aircraft . ''
`` If NATO is flying around there is more risk of misunderstandings and incidents , '' Karadzic added .
CHICAGO -LRB- AP -RRB- - Grain and soybean futures prices rose strongly Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade on signs of brisk export demand .
Soybeans reversed a three-day slide after the Agriculture Department reported U.S. soybean exports totaled 60,000 metric tons last week , a robust figure according to Victor Lespinasse , assistant vice president in the grain trading division of Dean Witter , Discover and Co.
Soybeans also were bolstered by a sharp increase in Malaysian palm oil futures overseas and higher bids for soybean oil in Rotterdam , the main port of entry for U.S. farm goods into Europe .
