Azerbaijan 's parliament passed an unusual law Friday guaranteeing a multibillion-dollar Caspian Sea oil development contract with a consortium of Western companies .
The law said simply that Azerbaijan 's parliament and president `` guarantee the implementation '' of the 30-year deal , which involves dlrs 7.4 billion in investments into three of the country 's oilfields .
A consortium of eight Western oil companies and one Russian one signed the contract in September , and parliament ratified it Nov. 15 .
But the Western partners wrote parliament last week saying ratification alone was not enough .
In the absence of legislation regulating oil production , they asked for special guarantees .
Western partners have been made nervous partly because Azerbaijan has indicated it will turn to Iran for financing help .
The consortium envisions the start of production about four years after development begins , increasing to a rate of about 86,000 metric tons -LRB- 600,000 barrels -RRB- a day by the end of the decade .
They expect to extract a total of 511 million metric tons -LRB- 3.5 billion barrels -RRB- of crude oil .
Bosnian Serb leaders promised Friday to release hundreds of detained U.N. peacekeepers and allow free movement of aid convoys , the chief U.N. envoy said .
Yasushi Akashi , speaking at Bosnian Serb headquarters in Pale , east of Sarajevo , told reporters he had won assurances that Ukrainian peacekeepers held in northern Bosnia , as well as Dutch and British convoys detained since Saturday , would be freed .
`` In addition , we have agreed that normal activities be restored to the Canadians -- 55 Canadians near Visoko -- and all other soldiers from other countries that were doing their work at weapons collection sites , '' Akashi said .
Serbs had detained more than 400 U.N. personnel throughout Bosnia for more than a week as insurance against further NATO airstrikes .
Earlier Friday , they released 70 Dutch peacekeepers who arrived in Zagreb , Croatia , after being held for seven days in eastern Bosnia .
The U.N. envoy to former Yugoslavia also said the Serbs had promised to allow Bangladeshi peacekeepers stranded in the besieged Bihac enclave in northwestern Bosnia to be resupplied .
Akashi said he was pleased with the `` willingness of the Bosnian Serb leadership to respond to our urgent appeal . ''
Whether the promises would be kept remained to be seen , as Serbs have repeatedly broken their word to the United Nations .
Earlier Friday , they once again made clear their contempt for the U.N. mission , firing anti-armor missiles at the Bosnian presidency building minutes before Akashi arrived there for talks with government leaders .
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic promised his side would normalize relations with the United Nations , but also called for another meeting first .
`` We certainly need some meeting of the military people of the U.N. and the Serb army , '' Karadzic said .
`` Some issues do not have to wait for the meeting , but some of them require that kind of meeting because of the technical issues . ''
It was not immediately clear whether Karadzic 's comments hinted at potential stumbling blocks to carrying out the promises announced by Akashi .
`` More or less , we can say we are moving fast to normalization of our relations , '' Karadzic said .
Akashi went to Pale for talks with the Bosnian Serb leadership after meetings with Bosnia 's Muslim-led government in Sarajevo .
Shortly before he arrived at the presidency , where the Bosnian government has its offices , Bosnian Serb gunners ringing the capital fired two anti-tank missiles at the building .
One destroyed the office of Miro Lazovic moments after he left for the Akashi meeting .
Lazovic is an ethnic Serb member of Bosnia 's collective presidency .
A short while later , three more missiles hit nearby buildings .
There were no injuries .
The Bosnian government complained about Akashi 's `` shuttle diplomacy '' and blasted the United Nations for failing to use force to halt the Serb attack on Bihac , as fighting continued in that northwest region Friday .
`` Instead of doing what they have to do , the U.N. is driving back and forth .
... This Munich policy is a humiliation of the international community , '' said Kemal Muftic , chief adviser to Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic .
He was referring to European appeasement of Adolf Hitler at a 1938 meeting in Munich before World War II .
Charles Redman , a U.S. diplomat , was also back in Sarajevo , leading talks with Izetbegovic and Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic that presumably focused on a proposed new peace plan .
Redman , now U.S. ambassador to Germany , helped draft the first international peace plan drawn up by the five-nation Contact Group , which the Serbs have repeatedly rejected .
Although that proposal was presented to the Serbs as a take-it-or-leave-it plan , the lack of Western will to use force has allowed the Serbs to demand , apparently successfully , the right of future confederal links with Serb-led Yugoslavia .
The original plan denied Serbs that as punishment for starting the war , though it granted the Bosnian Croat-Muslim federation similar rights to link with Croatia .
Akashi hoped to have more success with the Serbs than his boss , Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali .
Boutros-Ghali was rebuffed in even trying to meet the Bosnian Serbs on Wednesday , and afterwards said intransigence by the warring sides might force the end of the U.N. mission .
Earlier , U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi also wanted to discuss with Karadzic the continued fighting around Bihac , where the United Nations is trying to broker a cease-fire .
There was no immediate indication of any progress .
A number of detonations were reported on the edge of the Bihac `` safe area '' Friday , along with machine-gun and small arms fire , U.N. officials said .
But the heaviest fighting appeared concentrated around Velika Kladusa , north of Bihac , where Serbs were apparently closing in on the government army 's 5th Corps .
The Bosnian Serbs , backed by Serbs from neighboring Croatia , want to wipe out the 5th Corps , which launched a briefly successful offensive from the Bihac enclave , part of which is a U.N.-designated `` safe area , '' in late October .
There were also signs that the frontlines south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , who are allied with the Muslim-led government forces , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
A Croat militia and the Bosnian army took Kupres from the Serbs in a joint attack last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Serbs in neighboring Croatia also had shelled his forces across the border , near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
