Bosnian Serbs , seeing U.S. policy swinging in their favor , said Friday the new U.S. approach to the war in former Yugoslavia is `` a step in the right direction . ''
But an emissary , Danielle Sremac , rejected some key elements of a peace proposal U.S. officials are now pushing in Europe .
`` A U.S. policy change that recognizes the rights of Serbs in Bosnia is a step in the right direction , '' Ms. Sremac said , adding that U.S. policy is key to resolution of the 21\/2 - year war .
`` The U.S. policy of siding with the Muslims has been one of the main obstacles to peace , '' she said at a forum sponsored by the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace .
A Belgrade-born U.S. citizen who is not recognized as an official emissary by the U.S. government , Ms. Sremac has served as a U.S.-based spokeswoman for Bosnian Serb leaders since May .
She recently returned from consultations in Pale , the unofficial Bosnian Serb capital .
The Clinton administration , rebuffed by Britain and France in its efforts to use more NATO military force to quell Serb aggression , is now working for a diplomatic solution in Bosnia .
The latest U.S. stance provides `` a good sign for peace in Bosnia , '' Ms. Sremac said .
But she said Bosnian Serbs still demand a contiguous country of their own , links to other Serbian areas of the former Yugoslavia and control over parts of the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo and other Bosnian cities with large Serbian populations .
Secretary of State Warren Christopher , at NATO meetings in Brussels , has been promoting a new U.S. plan that calls for an international conference to resolve the crisis and a three - to six-month cease-fire around besieged Bihac , which Serbs are poised to overrun .
Ms. Sremac said Bosnian Serbs reject the cease-fire because it would give Bosnia 's outgunned government forces the winter months to regroup and plan new attacks .
Bosnian Serbs want permanent ceasefire negotiations , she said .
They also continue to reject the plan drawn up by the United States , Britain , France , Germany and Russia that would allow them to control about half of the country but still maintain Bosnia 's borders .
U.S. officials , however , have expressed a new willingness to discuss a political link between Serbia and Bosnian Serbs .
Christopher said this week that political union between the Serbs in Bosnia with Serbia itself might be possible `` if it would mean reaching a peaceful resolution '' of the war .
A link among Serbs in former Yugoslav states has been a principle demand of Bosnian Serbs throughout the war that has killed 200,000 people .
A Serb union would likely mean the end of Bosnia as a multiethnic state .
Bosnian Serbs , who hold about 70 percent of Bosnia , would be willing to accept some reduction in the territory they now control , Ms. Sremac said , if they could form a `` fully functioning state '' and establish ties to Serbia .
Their leaders have in the past indicated they would be willing to settle for about two-thirds of the republic .
