U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and NATO 's top civilian official denied Friday that the alliance had abandoned its enforcement of the U.N. `` no-fly '' zone over Bosnia .
`` NATO is continuing to enforce the no-fly zone , '' Christopher said , amid continued confusion between the United Nations and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization over how to deal with the crisis in Bosnia .
Earlier Friday , Wing Commander Timothy Hewlet , U.N. director for air operations in Bosnia , told reporters in Sarajevo that Bosnian Serbs had activated several surface-to-air missile sites throughout the country , threatening humanitarian flights and NATO jets .
Hewlet said NATO had agreed to a `` cooling off '' period to calm tensions , but was able to `` control '' the situation with AWACs radar planes flying outside Bosnian air space .
`` There are no flights over Bosnia at the moment that I am aware of , '' he said .
At NATO headquarters , Secretary-General Willy Claes said he was unaware of any request from the United Nations to halt or scale-down allied patrols enforcing the military flight ban , designed to protect Bosnian civilians from bombardment .
`` We have never received any request , can I be any clearer than that ? ''
However , Yasushi Akashi , the chief U.N. envoy in former Yugoslavia , acknowledged talks on the issue were under way .
`` I can not comment on internal discussions which we are conducting with NATO , '' Akashi told reporters after meeting with Bosnian Serb leaders in Pale , their stronghold east of Sarajevo .
`` But I am glad that NATO is adopting an attitude that they are essentially at the service of UNPROFOR -LRB- the U.N. protection force -RRB- in the peacekeeping mission . ''
NATO and the United Nations have repeatedly talked of the need to `` show presence '' in the skies over Bosnia .
But NATO sources in Brussels said allied planes had been fired on nine times in recent days by Serb missiles and fixed by targeting radar some 15 times .
Under current rules of engagement , NATO planes can strike back if targeted without seeking prior approval from the United Nations .
Thant Myint-U , a U.N. spokesman in Sarajevo , cautioned that such retaliation could lead to an increase in fighting at a time when international negotiators were trying to revive flagging peace efforts .
`` There would be massive escalation in the situation on the ground that could spin out of control , '' Thant said .
Christopher told reporters that Serb anti-missile batteries posed a problem .
But , he said , NATO was capable of dealing with them , `` and we continue to police the ` no-fly ' zone in the effective way we have in the past . ''
In Washington however , a senior U.S. military officer , speaking on condition of anonymity , acknowledged that pilots and other NATO forces were taking steps to lessen the threat to aircraft .
He would not elaborate .
On Tuesday , officials said the United Nations requested and NATO agreed that planes would not fly over Bosnia for a 48-hour period while U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and other peace negotiators visited Sarajevo .
Western military sources said it appeared that request was extended slightly , and it was not clear if NATO planes were back in Bosnian airspace .
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic , speaking in Pale after his meeting with Akashi , said , `` We would like to see skies clear of ... NATO aircraft . ''
`` If NATO is flying around there is more risk of misunderstandings and incidents , '' Karadzic added .
All of the recognizable names have dropped out of a conference pitched by the Clinton administration as a `` first-ever '' hemispheric gathering on trade and finance at the Summit of the Americas .
The accumulated cancellations by top U.S. officials are an embarrassment for the White House , which has been criticized for slighting trade -- the top priority of Latin American and Caribbean leaders -- on the 34-nation summit agenda .
`` The -LRB- public relations staff -RRB- may have a little problem fixing that one , '' said Steve Albee , publisher of Inside Latin America , a Miami newsletter produced for the accounting firm of Coopers & Lybrand .
`` The summit may end up being a great big barbecue , but with little accomplished . ''
Calls to the White House for comment were not immediately returned .
Asked whether the disrupted schedule validated criticism about the U.S. commitment to improved trade in the hemisphere , a U.S. government source speaking on condition of anonymity said Friday , `` sort of makes you wonder , does n't it ? ''
This week 's GATT votes and schedule conflicts were given as explanations for the cancellations , but passage of the world trade agreement would have given U.S. officials bragging rights at the meeting .
Vice President Al Gore ca n't make it .
Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen and U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor will send three-minute video greetings instead of giving keynote speeches .
Commerce Secretary Ron Brown , Transportation Secretary Federico Pena and Florida Gov. Lawton Chiles canceled Wednesday .
In their place will be an assortment of undersecretaries , deputies and assistants , but no big wheels .
Customs Commissioner George Weise is still committed to the conference sponsored by his agency .
Lame-duck Florida Comptroller Gerald Lewis will offer luncheon introductions .
`` We are still of the opinion that we have an exceedingly high-caliber group of speakers and panelists , '' Customs spokesman Michael Sheehan said .
Versions of the much-altered schedule note the times they were written so organizers know they 're dealing with the latest draft .
About 1,000 people , including 300 foreigners , signed up for the Customs Service conference on customs , trade and finance by Wednesday 's deadline , said Sheehan .
They wo n't get word of the new lineup until they register .
One of the conference attractions promoted in a four-color brochure was `` direct access '' to U.S. and foreign customs , banking and finance officials .
`` The thrust of our conference from the beginning has been to allow people , ordinary business people involved in international trade , an opportunity to have access to and resolve problems with the actual government officials and private sector experts that they need to deal with , '' Sheehan said .
The conference was formulated in November in place of a business roundtable announced by Brown with great fanfare on a special trip to Miami on Oct. 28 .
It was the same day an op-ed piece in the Wall Street Journal complained of a lack of trade emphasis in summit planning .
Brown 's roundtable never materialized .
`` I know that the Customs summit was put together in an effort to make the business community feel that the summit had some value , and it 's unfortunate that the big guns have decided not to be there , '' Albee said .
`` The whole thing was added to try to bring the business community into the event . ''
