American Hilary Lindh overcame a course that does n't suit her to win the opening women 's World Cup downhill ski race of the season on Friday .
Just one day after dismissing herself as a favorite , Lindh flashed to a winning margin of 29-hundredths of a second over Isolde Kostner of Italy .
Defending World Cup downhill champion Katja Seizinger of Germany finished third .
Austria 's Stefanie Schuster overcame a late start number to finish a career-best fourth , Switzerland 's Heidi Zurbriggen was fifth , and Sweden 's Pernilla Wiberg took sixth .
Lindh , the 1992 Olympic downhill silver medalist , won for only the second time on the World Cup circuit .
Her first career victory came last February in a downhill in Sierra Nevada , Spain .
The 25-year-old Alaskan , whose best previous finish on this course was sixth place two years ago , was timed in 1 minute , 45.00 seconds .
A day earlier , Lindh said , `` Certain people have courses they do well on , and this does n't happen to be one of mine .
I 've always had a hard time on the turns at the bottom .
The last 20 seconds is where I lose it all . ''
`` I do n't know if I nailed it -LRB- the bottom -RRB- , but it was very much improved from training , '' Lindh said .
`` It felt solid and pretty quick . ''
Kostner , the last of the top-seeded skiers to complete the run , could n't overtake Lindh , coming across in 1:45.29 .
Seizinger was timed in 1:45.44 .
Kostner , 19 , who has had six top-three finishes in the last two seasons including two Olympic bronze medals , said , `` This was n't surprising because in training I was skiing well .
I always like to go fast . ''
`` When I saw Hilary 's time , I knew she had had a great run , '' Seizinger said .
`` The first two-thirds of this course is very flat , a little problem for me .
But third place is n't bad . ''
Three other favorites -- Anja Haas of Austria , Melanie Suchet of France and American Picabo Street -- fell and did not finish .
Street made a minor mistake early in her run and , in an effort to make up time , got out of control near the finish , did the splits and crashed .
Haas had the fastest intermediate time one-third of the way down the course when she fell .
American Megan Gerety came in eighth .
The top Canadian was Kate Pace , who had trouble at the bottom and placed 11th .
Vreni Schneider of Switzerland , the overall standings leader , was 23rd .
For the first time , downhillers in the top seed of 15 were allowed to select starting numbers from 1 through 30 , and most of the favorites chose numbers in the 20s .
