The United States has elevated Greece to a `` priority watch list '' because of alleged piracy of American motion pictures and recordings .
U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor said Friday a `` large number '' of unlicensed Greek television stations are broadcasting American movies without paying the U.S. motion picture industry for their use .
`` We note that the Greek government has very recently moved against one such station , '' Kantor said in a statement .
`` We hope this is the start of a sustained campaign against these unauthorized broadcasts . ''
If it were , the United States could re-examine Greece 's status , Kantor said .
But continued unauthorized broadcast of copyrighted material could result in a formal investigation leading to retaliation against imports from Greece , he added .
Two other nations -- Egypt and the United Arab Emirates -- were kept on a U.S. non-priority watch list .
Kantor urged Egypt to enact a strong patent law that would protect foreign pharmaceuticals and agricultural chemicals from piracy .
He also said the U.S. government remains concerned about alleged piracy of computer software and other copyrighted material in the UAE .
The estranged wife of President Alberto Fujimori has announced she will run for Congress and head a new political alliance in next year 's elections .
Susana Higuchi , who previously was disqualified from seeking the presidency , announced her congressional candidacy Thursday night .
She said she would lead a coalition between her Harmony 21st Century party and the Civilian , Military and Police Front , known by its acronym FREMPOL .
FREMPOL is small party made up mostly of retired police and career military officers whose main interest is increasing their pensions .
The alliance gives Higuchi the chance to stand for Congress because FREMPOL is already qualified to take part in the April 9 elections .
Higuchi 's party was disqualified in October along with her presidential bid for lack of sufficient signatures on its election petition .
But the National Elections Board said it would still have to rule on whether Higuchi is eligible to hold national office .
Congress in July passed a law , known locally as the `` Susana Law , '' prohibiting the president 's immediate family members from running for president , vice president or Congress .
The elections board on Friday published a ruling that banned the state-run news media from promoting political candidates .
It was aimed at ending the pro-Fujimori publicity in the state-owned newspaper , television channel and radio station .
The board 's ruling came in response to on-going criticism by the opposition that Fujimori is taking advantage of his office to campaign at state expense .
The board said the state media , government officials , the police and the military were prohibited from engaging in political campaigning .
But it said the public stations and newspaper could accept paid political advertising .
It also said the state television and radio stations should , as a traditional public service , run free half-hour spots for candidates once a day during the month before the elections .
The United States , France , Britain , Germany and Russia on Friday sought to revive the peace initiative for Bosnia by unveiling new proposals including the suggestion of a confederation between Bosnian Serbs and Serbia .
The foreign ministers of the Bosnia ` Contact Group ' nations launched a new drive to end the fighting , after U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher endorsed the European view that diplomacy is the best way to deal with the conflict that has dragged on for 31 months .
