Juppe and his British counterpart Douglas Hurd will travel to Belgrade on Sunday to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , on Sunday for talks with President Slobodan Milosevic .
When the Rolling Stones began their current concer tour , there were worries that time was no longer on their side .
But despite some heavy competition , the Stones are likely to end 1994 as the year 's top concert draw in North America , according to two concert industry trade publications .
When their U.S. tiour ends on Dec. 18 , the Stones will have earned an estimated dlrs 119.4 million , Performance magazine said .
That total does n't count four shows where the band did n't report its earnings because of slow ticket sales .
More than 2 million people have seen the Stones this year .
`` They 're still incredible performers , '' said Jane Cohen , senior editor of Performance , on Friday .
`` They 're still the premiere rock 'n' roll band .
But I do n't think you 're going to see them tour at this level again . ''
Ticket sales for the Stones ' tour were initially slow , but that was largely because there was so much competition on the road , said Gary Bongiovanni , editor of Pollstar , which will also report the Stones as top earners .
Pink Floyd , which lumbers along despite internal strife and poorly-received albums , drew more than 3 million fans and earned dlrs 104.6 million , Performance said .
Billy Joel performed before nearly 2 million people and earned dlrs 75.8 million to finish third , followed by the Eagles .
Barbra Streisand , criticized for steep ticket prices , took in dlrs 58.9 million while performing before nearly 300,000 .
More than four times as many people saw Elton John , but his concert gross was only dlrs 56.8 million .
The Grateful Dead , the Lollapalooza tour , Phil Collins and Michael Bolton rounded out Performance 's list of top earners .
`` It 's been a very good year for concerts , '' Bongiovanni said .
R.E.M. , Tom Petty and Van Halen are expected to be among the big concert draws next year .
Former Led Zeppelin partners Robert Plant and Jimmy Page are heading on tour , Bongiovanni said .
The Eagles , who had to reschedule concerts because of Glenn Frey 's illness , will also be back on the road .
