`` There was a tremedous explosion , like the end of the world , '' said a railway employee who witnessed the accident and asked not to be identified .
He said in a telephone interview that people remained buried in the wreckage into Friday night , although the crash occured at 4:45 p.m. local time .
State television showed horrific pictures of battered and broken railway cars covered in brick torn loose from the building and rescue crews frantically dragging bloody bodies from the wreckage .
Laszlo Garamvoelgyi , a National Police spokesman , said the death toll had risen to 21 by late Friday with 60 others injured , some seriously .
With temperatures below freezing and others left in the wreckage the death toll was expected to rise - Garamvoelgyi said the latest count `` was not the final one by any means . ''
The severity of the accident eclipsed the previous most serious train tragedy of recent years .
Ten children died last February , in a bus-train collision .
Transport ministry officials said the accident occured at a rail switch and suggested that it was possibly caused by the switch not being thrown .
They had no information about the speed of the train when the cars derailed .
Doctors at one hospital near Szolnok , close to the site of the accident , said 26 injured , including two critical cases , were admitted to their hospital alone , with several others also taking in injured .
Among senior officials at the scene by late Friday evening was Interior Minister Laszlo Kuncze .
`` We are witnesses to a terrible tragedy , '' Kuncze said .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 160 kilometers -LRB- 100 miles -RRB- east of Budapest .
Bosnian Serb leaders promised Friday to release hundreds of detained peacekeepers and allow free movement of certain U.N. convoys , the chief U.N. envoy announced .
Yasushi Akashi , speaking after talks with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic at his headquarters east of Sarajevo , told reporters he had been assured that Ukrainian peacekeepers kidnapped in northern Bosnia , as well as Dutch and British resupply convoys detained since Saturday , would be freed .
`` In addition , we have agreed that normal activities be restored to the Canadians ... and all other soldiers from other countries that were doing their work at weapons collection sites , '' Akashi said .
Serbs detained more than 400 U.N. personnel throughout Bosnia as insurance against further NATO airstrikes after alliance planes struck Serb targets three times last week .
Earlier Friday , they released 70 Dutch peacekeepers , detained with a convoy bound for the eastern enclave of Srebrenica .
Akashi also said the Serbs promised to allow Bangladeshi peacekeepers stranded in the besieged Bihac enclave to be resupplied .
`` I am very pleased to find willingness of the Bosnian Serb leadership to respond to our urgent appeal , '' Akashi said .
Whether the promises would be fulfilled remained to be seen , as Serbs have repeatedly broken their word to the United Nations .
Karadzic promised normalized relations , but also called for another meeting first .
`` We certainly need some meeting of the military people of the U.N. and the Serb army , '' Karadzic said , without elaborating .
`` Some issues do not have to wait for the meeting , but some of them require that kind of meeting because of the technical issues . ''
Karadzic also issued a veiled warning against NATO warplanes .
`` We would like to see skies clear of our aircrafts and of NATO aircrafts , '' Karadzic said .
`` If NATO is flying around there is more risk of misunderstandings and incidents . ''
NATO sources said allied planes had been fired on by Serb missiles nine times in recent days and fixed by targeting radar some 15 times .
Akashi , addressing conflicting reports over whether NATO warplanes were over Bosnia enforcing the U.N. `` no fly '' zone , said :
`` I can not comment on internal discussions which we are conducting with NATO , '' Akashi said .
`` But , I am glad that NATO is adopting an attitude that they are essentially at the service of UNPROFOR in the peacekeeping mission . ''
Under rules of engagement , NATO planes can defend themselves against attack without prior U.N. approval .
U.N. officials fear that could escalate tensions as they try to salvage stalled peace talks .
`` What may seem as an innocent step ... can be fraught with difficulties , '' Akashi said .
`` For example , this NATO air activity : the NATO flying over the skies may also bring about enhanced air defense system against which then NATO has to bring in more planes to defend itself , so we have to ... break this vicious circle . ''
