Stocks posted substantial gains Friday as bond prices rallied on economic data that showed steady but non-inflationary growth in the economy .
Traders said the market was also staging a technical rebound from losses earlier this week .
Bond prices moved sharply higher , with the 30-year U.S. Treasury bond up more than dlrs 10 per dlrs 1,000 face value and yielding 7.91 percent .
Bonds got a lift from part of a Labor Department November jobs report that showed declines in the average hourly wage and work week .
The overall report showed a gain of 350,000 jobs in nonfarm payrolls in November , pushing the unemployment rate to 5.6 percent from 5.8 percent in October .
Analysts had expected an increase in nonfarm jobs of about 250,000 , and for the unemployment rate to remain at 5.8 percent .
The overall jobs data showed a stronger-than expected growth in the economy , which analysts said might encourage the Federal Reserve to further tighten interest rates .
But fears of higher interest rates were softened by the wage and work-week components of the Labor Department report , as well as a drop of 0.1 percent in October in the government 's index of leading indicators , and a 0.4-percentage point drop in factory orders in October , analysts said .
Bonds initially dipped on the jobs report but then quickly rallied , pulling stocks higher with them .
`` The conclusion , at least for today -- and it 's only tentative -- is that the economy is going to slow to a no-boom , no-bust sustainable , non-inflationary pace , '' said Hugh Johnson , chief market strategist at First Albany Corp.
But Johnson and others said the market had been technically poised to rally after losing substantial ground earlier in the week , and that technical factors , like program trading , were responsible for some of the market 's gains .
`` Stock investors are very very tentative , '' Johnson said .
`` The level of confidence is not high . ''
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stock rose 44.75 to 3,745.62 .
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 3 to 2 on the New York Stock Exchange , with 1,397 up , 899 down and 623 unchanged .
Big Board volume totaled 284.74 million shares as of 4 p.m. -LRB- 2100 GMT -RRB- , against 285.93 million in the previous session .
The NYSE 's composite index rose 1.97 to 248.01 .
Standard and Poor 's 500-stock index rose 4.38 to 453.30 .
The Nasdaq composite index rose 1.93 to 743.12 .
At the American Stock Exchange , the market value index rose 1.27 to 452.46 .
