Bosnian Serbs promised Friday to release hundreds of peacekeepers and allow aid deliveries as the chief U.N. envoy tried to salvage what was left of the ailing U.N. mission in Bosnia .
Earlier , Serb gunners surrounding Sarajevo hit the presidency building with anti-tank missiles just minutes before U.N. envoy Yasushi Akashi arrived for talks with the Muslim-led Bosnian government .
It was yet another sign of Serb contempt for the peacekeeping effort , which has virtually ground to a halt .
The Serb rebels have stopped U.N. aid convoys , attacked a U.N.-declared `` safe area , '' and taken peacekeepers hostage .
In Brussels , Belgium , Secretary of State Warren Christopher met with European foreign ministers to discuss a U.S. plan for a cease-fire that would lead to peace talks in the 2 -LCB- - year-old war .
The plan would grant the Serbs their main aim in the conflict : the right to ties with Serb-led Yugoslavia .
The Serbs on Friday released 70 peacekeepers who had been held a week , but more than 300 peacekeepers remained hostage as insurance against NATO airstrikes .
Two wire-guided missiles hit the presidency building minutes before Akashi arrived for talks .
One destroyed the office of Miro Lazovic , an ethnic Serb member of Bosnia 's collective presidency .
Three missiles hit nearby buildings while Akashi was meeting top government and military officials .
There were no injuries .
`` Until we achieve something tangible , this shuttle diplomacy must continue , '' Akashi told reporters before leaving for Pale , the Bosnian Serb headquarters east of Sarajevo .
Akashi later said Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic had promised to release hundreds of detained peacekeepers and allow free movement of aid convoys .
`` More or less , we can say we are moving fast to normalization of our relations , '' Karadzic said .
But he also called for more talks .
The Bosnian government blasted the United Nations for not using force to halt fighting at Bihac , the embattled government-held enclave in the northwest .
Serb forces have seized 30 percent to 40 percent of the `` safe area , '' and fighting continued there Friday .
U.S. Ambassador to Germany Charles Redman held talks in Sarajevo with Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic and Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic on the U.S. peace plan .
Redman helped draft an earlier plan that the Serbs rejected .
The war began when Serbs rebelled against a vote for independence from Yugoslavia by Bosnia-Herzegovina 's Muslims and Croats .
More than 200,000 people are dead or missing in the war , and the Serbs have seized 70 percent of Bosnia .
Following the secession during the past three years of Slovenia , Croatia , Bosnia and Macedonia , Yugoslavia now is comprised only of Serbia and tiny Montenegro .
Serb nationalists in Yugoslavia , Croatia and Bosnia have pressed for a unified `` Greater Serbia . ''
The rejected peace plan denied Serbs the right to links with Yugoslavia as punishment for starting the war and granted them 49 percent of Bosnia .
It allowed Bosnia 's Croats and Muslims the right to ties with Croatia .
Akashi hopes to have more success than U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali , who was rebuffed Wednesday when he tried to meet with Bosnian Serb leaders .
Boutros-Ghali said afterwards that intransigence by the warring sides might force the U.N. mission to withdraw .
Seventy Dutch peacekeepers arrived in Zagreb , Croatia , after being released from a seven-day detention by the Serbs in eastern Bosnia , U.N. officials said .
But Serbs continued to hold about 20 other Dutch peacekeepers , plus hundreds of British , Ukrainians and Canadians , at various points throughout Bosnia .
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi also wanted to discuss the fighting around Bihac with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic .
The United Nations is trying to broker a cease-fire there .
Machine-gun and small arms fire was reported on the outskirts of Bihac , U.N. officials said .
The heaviest fighting appeared concentrated around Velika Kladusa , north of Bihac , where Serbs were apparently closing in on the government army 's 5th Corps .
The Bosnian Serbs , backed by Serbs from neighboring Croatia , want to wipe out the 5th Corps , which launched a briefly successful offensive from the Bihac enclave in late October .
There were also signs that fronts south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , allied with Muslim-led government forces , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
Croat militia and Bosnian army soldiers took Kupres from the Serbs last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Serbs in neighboring Croatia had shelled his forces across the border , near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
In Knin , Croatia , the Croatian government and leaders of the rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement that , if implemented , could lead to normalized relations between the two enemies .
The agreement calls for restoring water and electricity supplies and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade .
