Azerbaijan 's parliament guaranteed Friday a multibillion-dollar Caspian Sea oil development contract with a consortium of foreign companies that had sought greater security for their investment .
The unusual law said Azerbaijan 's parliament and president `` guarantee the implementation '' of the 30-year deal , which involves $ 7.4 billion to develop three sites containing an estimated 3.6 billion barrels of oil .
A consortium of eight Western oil companies and one Russian company signed the contract in September .
Parliament ratified it Nov. 15 .
But the Western partners said last week that in the absence of legislation regulating oil production special guarantees were also needed .
The companies have been nervous partly because Azerbaijan traded a quarter of its 20 percent stake in the project to Iran in exchange for financing .
The consortium expects to start pumping oil in about four years and eventually produce about 600,000 barrels of oil a day .
The consortium includes British Petroleum PLC , Amoco Corp. , Pennzoil Co. , Ramco Oil Services Inc. , Unocal Corp. , McDermott International Inc. , Turkish Petroleum Co. and Norway 's Statoil AS .
The Russian company Lukoil and the Azerbaijani state oil company are also participants .
Riddick Bowe , the odd man out in the heavyweight title picture , tries to fight his way back in Saturday night in a risky bout against undefeated Larry Donald .
Thirteen months after losing his heavyweight titles to Evander Holyfield , there are more questions than answers about a fighter many predicted would dominate the heavyweight ranks for a long time .
Injury and weight problems have dogged Bowe , who has been mostly inactive since losing a close decision to Holyfield .
Take away an aborted no contest fight against Buster Mathis Jr. and the best shots Bowe has thrown since his loss were a left-right combination to Donald 's head at a Los Angeles news conference this week .
`` I 'm still the best heavyweight in the world , '' Bowe said .
`` As long as I 'm in shape I beat all of them .
They can only hope I 'm fat and come in out of condition . ''
That hope may have been put to rest Thursday when Bowe weighed in at 241 pounds -LRB- 109 kilos -RRB- for the scheduled 12-round fight at Caesars Palace .
It was the lightest Bowe has weighed since winning the titles from Holyfield in November 1992 .
`` This is the best I 've felt since the first Holyfield fight , '' Bowe said .
Bowe , who has seen the WBA and IBF titles he once held change hands twice more since his loss , is taking a chance fighting Donald , an up-and-coming 1992 Olympian who is undefeated in 16 professional fights .
But he has little choice in a division where the two acknowledged champions , George Foreman and Oliver McCall , have shown no interest in fighting him .
`` Foreman will never fight Riddick Bowe and it 's just as well , '' Bowe 's manager , Rock Newman , said .
`` He would get massacred .
McCall will never fight Riddick either , but who cares about him . ''
Bowe instead hopes to tiptoe around the three major boxing organizations by beating Donald to set up a fight against Herbie Hide , who holds the lightly regarded WBO version of the crown .
Newman said negotiations were close to being finalized for a fight against Hide in the spring .
`` I believe I can legitimize the WBO the same way Larry Holmes legitimized the IBF , '' Bowe said .
`` I do n't care what title I have as long as it indicates I 'm heavyweight champion of the world . ''
First , though , there 's the matter of Donald , who is a slick boxer and has shown flashes of power in scoring 12 knockouts in 16 wins as a pro .
Boxers who can move have given Bowe -LRB- 34-1 -RRB- trouble in the past , but he is a 4-1 pick to beat Donald .
`` It 's going to be a great fight if Larry comes to fight , '' Bowe said .
`` He 's perhaps a little better than Mathis because he 's more my size and he possesses a good left jab .
If he has a chin , he 'll take a beating for 12 rounds . ''
Donald , who weighed in at 228 pounds -LRB- 103 kilos -RRB- , is 27 , the same age as Bowe .
But he did n't take up boxing until he was 19 and developed late as an amateur .
Donald 's biggest fights have been a decision win over Jeremy Williams and a knockout of former heavyweight contender Bert Cooper .
`` I 'm on my way up , '' Donald said .
`` I 'm loaded with confidence for this fight . ''
By taking the fight , Donald , whose first pro fight was in January 1993 , violated the boxing maxim that a young contender should never be put in a tough fight .
But his trainer , Janks Morton , said the fight was one Donald actively sought .
`` Bowe is the best heavyweight out there , that 's why we asked for him , '' Morton said .
`` Larry Donald is a better heavyweight than Bowe . ''
Bowe will earn dlrs 1 million for the fight , while Donald will get dlrs 490,000 , his biggest payday .
The United States , France , Britain , Germany and Russia on Friday sought to revive the peace initiative for Bosnia by unveiling new proposals , including a confederation between Bosnian Serbs and Serbia .
The foreign ministers of the Bosnia ` Contact Group ' nations launched a new drive to end the fighting , after U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher endorsed the European view that diplomacy is the best way to deal with the conflict that has dragged on for 31 months .
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe told reporters that at the meeting it was agreed `` to devise a constitutional arrangement '' enabling Bosnian Serbs to link up politically with Belgrade without undermining the integrity as a sovereign nation .
Juppe and his British counterpart Douglas Hurd will travel on Sunday to Belgrade , the Serbian capital , for talks with President Slobodan Milosevic .
Speaking to reporters after the meeting , Christopher made clear that the current peace initiative -- and its territorial division giving Bosnian Serbs 49 percent of the territory -- remains intact .
`` The contact group plan with its 51-49 division of territory , must be the basis of a settlement of the conflict . ''
Allowing a link up between the Bosnian Serbs and Serbia has been one of the main war aims of the Serbs and will be seen as a step toward the `` Greater Serbia '' which has so far been resisted by the West .
Hurd said the alternative to a negotiated settlement that provides for some form of Serb confederation is `` more dangerous , even disastrous . ''
Earlier , Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic suggested that the possible offer of confederal links with Serbia would not be enough to get his side to accept a peace plan .
He asked for international recognition of the Bosnian Serb sovereignty .
`` Everything can be solved by recognition of our sovereignty .
Then we can stay in association with Muslims , Croats , Serbia etc , '' Karadzic said at his headquarters in Pale , Bosnia .
`` We have to be either recognized or destroyed . ''
The idea of a political alliance of Bosnian Serbs with Belgrade is akin to the confederation that the current peace plan , rejected by the Bosnian Serbs , allows between Bosnian Croats and the Muslim-led government with Croatia .
The contact group nations also called for an immediate end to all hostilities across Bosnia , especially in the embattled enclave of Bihac , and demanded free passage for U.N. peacekeeping forces .
In a statement , the contact group nations said the 49 percent of land offered to the Serbs and the 51 percent to the Muslim-Croat alliance under the group 's plan , `` can be adjusted by mutual agreement between the parties . ''
The Bosnian Serbs currently control about 70 percent of the territory .
Bosnian Serb promised Friday to release hundreds of detained UN peacekeepers .
Canadian officials confirmed the report but said the Canadians were not yet free to move .
UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi said Bosnian Serb leaders had agreed to release Ukrainian peacekeepers held in northern Bosnia , as well as Dutch and British convoys detained since Saturday .
`` In addition , we have agreed that normal activities be restored to the Canadians -- 55 Canadians near Visoko -- and all other soldiers from other countries that were doing their work at weapons collection sites , '' Akashi said after talks with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic in Pale , near Sarajevo .
Canadian officials confirmed the UN has negotiated the release of the Canadian peacekeepers .
`` But the release has not been effected , '' John Williston , press secretary to Defense Minister David Collenette , said in Ottawa .
`` That may happen in the next 24 to 48 hours . ''
Whether the promises would be kept remained to be seen , as Serbs have repeatedly broken their word to the United Nations .
In Paris , Peter Donolo , a spokesman for Prime Minister Jean Chretien , said : `` Obviously we 're encouraged by the developments .
We 're keeping our fingers crossed , but we 're not going to rest until our troops have full freedom of movement .
We 've been let down before . ''
The Serbs have been holding about 400 UN soldiers as insurance against NATO airstrikes on their siege of the Muslim pocket of Bihac , a UN-declared safe haven in northwest Bosnia .
The Serbs released 70 Dutch peacekeepers taken hostage Saturday near Zvornik in eastern Bosnia .
The soldiers were in good condition , Dutch officials said .
The Canadians have been held for the past 10 days at various sites in Serb-held territory near their peacekeeping camp in Visoko , near Sarajevo .
About 20 are at a police complex in the village of Illijas .
The rest are at checkpoints and observation posts .
The soldiers are in radio contact with their camp and those at observation posts carry on their work .
Maj. Dean Milner , the senior officer among the detainees , is able to drive around in his vehicle and visit his soldiers .
The Serbs are allowing supply vehicles from camp to reach the soldiers with mail , food and other items .
Akashi , the top UN civilian leader in Bosnia set out Friday to hold talks with the Bosnian government in Sarajevo and with Serb leader Karadzic in Pale .
His mission started badly .
Three missiles hit the Bosnian government building shortly before he arrived .
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and NATO 's top civilian official denied Friday that the alliance had abandoned its enforcement of the U.N. `` no-fly '' zone over Bosnia .
`` NATO is continuing to enforce the no-fly zone , '' Christopher said , amid continued confusion between the United Nations and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization over how to deal with the crisis in Bosnia .
Earlier Friday , Wing Commander Timothy Hewlet , U.N. director for air operations in Bosnia , told reporters in Sarajevo that Bosnian Serbs had activated several surface-to-air missile sites throughout the country , threatening humanitarian flights and NATO jets .
Hewlet said NATO had agreed to a `` cooling off '' period to calm tensions , but was able to `` control '' the situation with AWACs planes flying outside Bosnian air space .
`` There are no flights over Bosnia at the moment that I am aware of , '' he said .
At NATO headquarters , Secretary-General Willy Claes said he was unaware of any request from the United Nations to halt or scale-down Allied patrols enforcing of the military flight ban , designed to protect Bosnian civilians from bombardment .
`` We have never received any request , can I be any clearer than that ? ''
However , Yasushi Akashi , the chief U.N. envoy in former Yugoslavia , acknowledged talks on the issue were underway .
`` I can not comment on internal discussions which we are conducting with NATO , '' Akashi told reporters after meeting with Bosnian Serb leaders in Pale , their stronghold east of Sarajevo .
`` But I am glad that NATO is adopting an attitude that they are essentially at the service of UNPROFOR in the peacekeeping mission . ''
NATO and the United Nations have repeatedly talked of the need to `` show presence '' in the skies over Bosnia .
But NATO sources in Brussels said Allied planes had been fired on nine times in recent days by Serb missiles and fixed by targeting radar some 15 times .
Under current rules of engagement , NATO planes can strike back if targeted without prior approval from the United Nations .
Akashi cautioned that NATO air action could threaten delicate negotiations to revive flagging peace efforts and lead to an escalation of fighting .
`` One miscalculation , one misunderstanding and it might become beyond our control , '' he told reporters .
Christopher told reporters Serb anti-missile batteries posed a problem .
But , he said , NATO was capable of dealing with them , `` and we continue to police the ` no-fly ' zone in the effective way we have in the past . ''
In Washington however , a senior U.S. military officer acknowledged that pilots and other NATO forces were taking steps to lessen the threat to aircraft .
He would not elaborate .
On Tuesday , officials said the United Nations requested and NATO agreed that planes would not fly over Bosnia for a 48-hour period while U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and other peace negotiators visited Sarajevo .
Western military sources said it appeared that request was extended slightly , and it was not clear if NATO planes were back in Bosnian airspace .
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic , speaking in Pale after his meeting with Akashi , said , `` We would like to see skies clear of ... NATO aircraft . ''
Cash registers jingled this week in St. Thomas as 200 sailors from the USS Gallery enjoyed shore leave in the Navy 's first visit in 13 months .
`` We did an extra $ 5,000 to $ 8,000 during the four days they were here , '' said Guy Revelle , owner of Fat Tuesday 's , a downtown Charlotte Amalie bar and restaurant .
John Chamber of Commerce director Joseph Aubain said it was too soon to total up what the sailors spent Sunday through Wednesday .
Earlier estimates indicated the territory lost $ 15 million a year in revenue when the Navy stopped its visits .
The Navy canceled all shore leave here last October after the number of assaults against sailors began to escalate .
One sailor was killed while making a call from a public telephone .
The Navy returned this week for a trial visit following a massive campaign by St. Thomas government officials and business people to reduce violent crimes on the island .
Revelle of Fat Tuesday 's said the sailors were well behaved .
`` There were zero incidents '' during the shore leave , said Lt. Cmdr. Ed Barker , spokesman for Fleet Air Caribbean at Roosevelt Roads Naval Station in Puerto Rico .
During the visit , Adm. William J. Flannagan Jr. , commander of the U.S. Atlantic Fleet , toured downtown Charlotte Amalie to see what measures the government had taken to ensure the sailors ' safety .
`` It looks extremely promising for another visit , '' Barker said .
The jury in the Hollywood Madam case Friday convicted Heidi Fleiss of running a high-priced prostitution ring .
In a case that drew the attention of the country , the 28-year-old pediatrician 's daughter was found guilty on three of five pandering charges .
The seven-man , five-woman jury deadlocked on the two other counts and acquitted her of supplying cocaine to an undercover police officer .
The verdict came after four days of deliberations during which the jurors were asked to decide whose conduct was more objectionable , that of Fleiss or that of the undercover officers who the defense claimed had entrapped her .
Fleiss was arrested after providing dlrs 1,500 prostitutes for officers posing as businessmen .
After the scandal broke last year , there was speculation that Fleiss ' alleged clients included Hollywood stars and moguls .
But her so-called black book was never made public ; the judge ruled the names of her customers were irrelevant .
