Liquidators of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International have taken a new settlement plan for the failed bank to a Luxembourg court , court officials said Friday .
Judge Maryse Welter is to rule Jan. 12 on the plan to repay 250,000 creditors and depositors around the world some dlrs 10 billion , said court registrar Maryse Schumacher .
A creditors ' committee approved the plan in September .
It would provide dlrs 1.8 billion from the bank 's majority shareholders , the government and ruling family of Abu Dhabi .
Liquidators say the plan could repay creditors 30 to 40 cents on the dollar .
But many depositors worry their savings have disappeared in legal costs during the four years it has taken to wind up the bank .
An earlier settlement plan for BCCI depositors was shot down by a Luxembourg judge last year as too favorable to Abu Dhabi .
Abu Dhabi was to have paid dlrs 1.7 billion into a fund for creditors in the earlier deal .
The new deal increases the amount of money and changes the wording to accommodate what technical objections raised by the judges last year .
Schumacher said no creditors opposed the plan during two days of court hearings Wednesday and Thursday .
But a lawyer for Luxembourg 's banking supervisors , the Luxembourg Monetary Institute , argued against what it considers is still too easy a deal for Abu Dhabi .
Banking regulators closed BCCI branches around the world in July 1991 , leaving claims of about dlrs 10 billion .
Officials alleged BCCI was used to launder money for drug dealers and dictators around the globe , but some of the depositors who lost their money blame the troubles on lax regulation by the authorities , including the Bank of England .
The standoff between the U.S. PGA Tour and the new World Golf Tour has turned into a contest of credibility with both sides claiming a victory of sorts .
The World Golf Tour on Friday issued a statement saying it was `` continuing to move ahead as planned '' with its venture to stage six to eight tournaments in 1995 , some of which would conflict with PGA Tour events .
The statement also said that Greg Norman 's commitment to the World Golf Tour `` is as firm as ever . ''
This all came one day after PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem released a statement in which he said Norman told him he had had a `` re-evaluation of this situation '' and had told Finchem `` he would not support any venture that would damage the PGA Tour . ''
Norman , who joined World Golf Tour executive director John Montgomery Jr. and Fox Television in announcing the new tour two weeks ago , has wavered in his support of the venture since Finchem announced that he would suspend any PGA Tour member who played in events that conflict with the tour .
No American professionals have committed to the world tour , and no dates , sites or sponsors have been announced for the tournaments .
`` They are very keen to keep communications open , '' Norman , who is in Australia , said about the PGA Tour .
`` He -LRB- Finchem -RRB- asked me to see him when I get home , and I will do that .
Right now , the World Tour and the PGA Tour have a chance of working this thing out . ''
Norman is scheduled to meet with Finchem and Montgomery separately when he returns to the United States next week .
Fox Sports spokesman Vince Wladika said the network was still interested in broadcasting the tournaments if the world tour went forward as planned .
As proposed , the new tour would have a 40-man field , based on the world rankings .
