Earlier Friday , Akashi met with Bosnian government officials in Sarajevo .
Minutes before he arrived for those talks , two anti-tank missiles slammed into the presidency building where the meeting was to occur .
Three more missiles hit nearby buildings during the talks .
There were no injuries .
U.N. officials said it appeared to be Serb fire ; the Serbs later accused the Bosnians of attacking themselves to cause trouble .
The Bosnian government complained about Akashi 's `` shuttle diplomacy '' while the United Nations failed to use force to halt the Serb attack on Bihac , a U.N. `` safe area . ''
`` Instead of doing what they have to do , the U.N. is driving back and forth .
... This Munich policy is a humiliation of the international community , '' said Kemal Muftic , chief adviser to Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic , referring to European capitulation to Adolf Hitler before World War II .
Charles Redman , the former U.S. member of the Contact Group and now ambassador to Germany , was also back in Sarajevo , leading bilateral talks with Izetbegovic and Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic on new efforts to reach a peace settlement .
Those new efforts , unveiled Friday night in Brussels by the five-nation Contact Group , include allowing Bosnian Serbs to have some form of political ties to Serb-led Yugoslavia , which they had long sought .
Critics of that new plan said it amounted to appeasement .
But Karadzic suggested even that might not now be enough .
He said the Bosnians Serbs must first be guaranteed sovereignty .
`` Everything can be solved by recognition of our sovereignty .
... We have to be either recognized or destroyed . ''
In a letter to Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali , carried by his news service SRNA , Karadzic warned the United Nations to drop its `` illusion that Bosnia exists .
... This illusion has cost us hundreds of thousands of human lives . ''
Akashi also discussed a possible cease-fire for Bihac and beyond .
But the Serbs maintained their rejection of a temporary cease-fire , saying they would accept only an end to the war .
The Bosnian government fears that would cement Serb territorial gains of 70 percent of the country .
U.N. officials said fighting continued Friday around Bihac .
But the heaviest action was around Velika Kladusa , north of Bihac , where Serbs were apparently closing in on the government army 's 5th Corps .
The Serbs , backed by Serbs from neighboring Croatia , want to wipe out the 5th Corps , which launched a briefly successful offensive from the Bihac enclave in late October .
There were also signs that frontlines south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , allied with Muslim-led government forces , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
Those allied forces took Kupres from the Serbs in a joint attack last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Serbs in neighboring Croatia had shelled his forces across the border .
He said his troops returned fire .
Karadzic claimed regular Croatian army troops were fighting alongside the Bosnian Croats and warned Akashi to get them out , saying , `` otherwise we will be forced to declare we are in war with Croatia . ''
