The American dollar surged against the Japanese yen Friday , closing above the key 100-yen level for the first time in seven weeks , in a move that many analysts said signaled the U.S. currency 's long-awaited recovery .
Data released in Tokyo and Washington pointed to changes in economic fundamentals that according to currency market participants should shift the global flow of capital back toward U.S. assets and drive up demand for the dollar .
`` We 're seeing a fundamental reappraisal of the dollar , '' said Robert Brusca , chief financial economist at Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. `` It 's turned a pretty important corner . ''
In late New York trading , the dollar was quoted at 100.61 yen , up from 99.34 late Thursday .
It was the currency 's first close above 100 yen since Oct. 11 and the highest since Oct. 7 .
In London , the dollar rose to 100.36 yen from 99.35 .
In Tokyo , where the trading day begins , the U.S. currency finished the week at 99.58 yen .
The dollar also surged to a three-month high against the German mark and advanced vs. most other major currencies .
But dealers said trading centered on the yen , which weakened broadly .
The dollar rose in Asian dealings after the Japanese government reported the country 's trade surplus fell sharply in October , the third-consecutive monthly decline , while the economy grew at a 3.7 percent annual rate in the third quarter .
Those numbers suggested a reduction of the huge stockpiles of dollars Japan earns by exporting goods to the United States .
Constant selling of dollars for yen by Japanese companies had helped to push the U.S. currency to record lows this year .
In addition , a strong Japanese economy should absorb more imports , which must be paid for in foreign currencies .
`` Some of the reasons for the stronger yen may no longer be as valid , '' said Ezra Zask , president of Norfolk , Conn.-based money-management firm Ezra Zask Associates Inc.
The dollar was further bolstered in European and American trading by a stronger-than-expected report on U.S. employment in November .
The Labor Department said the economy created 350,000 jobs last month , pushing the unemployment rate to a four-year low of 5.6 percent .
That combined with other recent evidence of economic strength increases the liklihood that the Federal Reserve will raise short-term interest rates again , perhaps as soon as this month .
The central bank has boosted rates six times this year in an effort to head off inflation , which reduces the value of many investments .
Receding inflation fears and the higher returns offered on shorter-term U.S. investments vs. those in Europe and Japan are providing a powerful draw , particularly at a time when Tokyo stock prices seem to have peaked .
`` There is a realization in the foreign exchange market of a shifting out of yen-denominated assets and into dollar assets , '' said Bob Near , a vice president at the Bank of New York .
Brusca added that the Japanese had been hesitant this year to buy into American financial markets for fear that their investments would decline in value as the dollar dropped .
That 's likely to change now that the dollar has breached 100 yen .
`` A dollar below 100 yen reflected a currency that was too weak and deterred people from bringing money into the country , '' he said .
The stronger dollar `` inspires more confidence from investors .
The United States now stands a better chance of attracting Japanese capital . ''
The dollar was changing hands late in New York at 1.5802 marks -- the best finish against that currency since Aug. 31 -- up from 1.5733 .
In London , the dollar advanced to 1.5763 marks from 1.5743 .
Other late dollar rates in New York , compared with late Thursday : 1.3338 Swiss francs , up from 1.3295 ; 5.4190 French francs , up from 5.3915 ; 1,618 Italian lire , up from 1,614 ; and 1.3712 Canadian dollars , down from 1.3776 .
The British pound was quoted at dlrs 1.5603 , down from dlrs 1.5669 .
In London , the pound dropped to dlrs 1.5605 from dlrs 1.5655 .
Lacking a witness to testify billions of dollars in Japanese bonds are really fakes , federal prosecutors dropped charges against two St. Petersburg men and a South Korean .
The three were accused of trying to parlay dlrs 4.1 billion worth of purportedly counterfeit Japanese government bonds into multimillion-dollar lines of credit at four Tampa Bay-area financial institutions .
Charges of bank and wire fraud , conspiracy and counterfeiting were dropped Thursday after a federal judge denied the government 's request to delay the trial until a witness could be brought from Japan .
U.S. District Judge H. Dale Cook said he would decide early next year whether the government can refile the charges .
Prosecutors had hoped Cook would allow the witness , a Japanese government official , to testify via a videocassette tape made when he was in town to testify in another case in October .
But the tape ran out after two hours of testimony and defense attorneys never got a chance to cross-examine the witness .
The witness , Hideo Inoue of the Japanese Ministry of Finance , then announced he would be leaving for Japan the next day .
`` It was a hoot , '' defense attorney John Swisher said Thursday of the abortive taping session .
Swisher said prosecutors searched for a fresh tape and came up empty .
Assistant U.S. Attorney Edward Page said Inoue apparently did not enjoy testifying in court -- and then coming under hours of cross-examination -- during a similar bond case earlier the day of the taping .
Inoue testified in the trial of former Assistant U.S. Attorney General Norbert Schlei and three others .
The group was charged with attempting to sell up to dlrs 16 billion in forged Japanese bonds .
Inoue 's testimony is key to both cases because without him prosecutors have no Japanese government witness to say the bonds are fake .
The bonds in the two cases are nearly identical , but the cases share no other connection .
Page said the government hopes to refile charges against William Woo Am Choi , 59 , of St. Petersburg ; his son Samuel Choi , 25 ; and Joung Joon An , 56 , of South Korea .
Joung and William Choi were to be released after the charges were dropped .
Samuel Choi already was free on bail .
The trial of Schlei and the three others continues next week .
The United States , France , Britain , Germany and Russia on Friday sought to restart the drive for a peace deal in Bosnia by endorsing a confederation of Bosnian Serbs and neighboring Serbia .
The foreign ministers of the Bosnia ` Contact Group ' nations met after U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher endorsed the European view that diplomacy is the best way to deal with the conflict that has dragged on for 31 months .
`` The road will be very difficult , '' Christopher told reporters after the meeting .
`` But we do not see any other responsible road to take other than to redouble our efforts '' to find a political settlement .
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said it was agreed `` to devise a constitutional arrangement '' enabling Bosnian Serbs to link up politically with Belgrade without undermining Bosnia 's sovereignty .
Such an alliance has been a key aim of Serbs throughout the Bosnian crisis .
The endorsement of it is bound to be seen as acquiescing in a `` Greater Serbia '' which has so far been resisted by the Contact Group members .
The immediate reaction to the latest peace plan version from Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic was not encouraging .
He asked for international recognition of the Bosnian Serb sovereignty .
`` Everything can be solved by recognition of our sovereignty .
Then we can stay in association with Muslims , Croats , Serbia etc , '' Karadzic said at his headquarters in Pale , Bosnia .
`` We have to be either recognized or destroyed . ''
Juppe and his British counterpart Douglas Hurd are to visit the Serbian capital of Belgrade Sunday for talks with President Slobodan Milosevic .
`` We shall keep trying '' to find a negotiated settlement , Juppe said .
Christopher said the core of a Bosnian peace plan remained a strict territorial division giving Bosnian Serbs 49 percent of Bosnia .
`` The Contact Group plan with its 51-49 division of territory , must be the basis of a settlement of the conflict , '' Christopher said
Hurd said the alternative to a negotiated settlement that provides for some form of Serb confederation is `` more dangerous , even disastrous . ''
The idea of a political alliance of Bosnian Serbs with Belgrade is akin to the confederation that the current peace plan , rejected by the Bosnian Serbs , allows between Bosnian Croats and the Muslim-led government with Croatia .
The contact group nations also called for an immediate end to all hostilities across Bosnia , especially in the embattled enclave of Bihac , and demanded free passage for U.N. peacekeeping forces .
In a statement , the contact group nations said the 49 percent of land offered to the Serbs and the 51 percent to the Muslim-Croat alliance under the group 's plan , `` can be adjusted by mutual agreement between the parties . ''
The Bosnian Serbs currently control about 70 percent of the territory .
