However , Yasushi Akashi , the chief U.N. envoy in former Yugoslavia , acknowledged talks on the issue were under way .
`` I can not comment on internal discussions which we are conducting with NATO , '' Akashi told reporters after meeting with Bosnian Serb leaders in Pale , their stronghold east of Sarajevo .
`` But I am glad that NATO is adopting an attitude that they are essentially at the service of UNPROFOR -LRB- the U.N. protection force -RRB- in the peacekeeping mission . ''
NATO and the United Nations have repeatedly talked of the need to `` show presence '' in the skies over Bosnia .
But NATO sources in Brussels said allied planes had been fired on nine times in recent days by Serb missiles and fixed by targeting radar some 15 times .
Under current rules of engagement , NATO planes can strike back if targeted without seeking prior approval from the United Nations .
Akashi cautioned that NATO air action could threaten delicate negotiations to revive flagging peace efforts and lead to an escalation of fighting .
`` One miscalculation , one misunderstanding and it might become beyond our control , '' he told reporters .
Christopher told reporters that Serb anti-missile batteries posed a problem .
But , he said , NATO was capable of dealing with them , `` and we continue to police the ` no-fly ' zone in the effective way we have in the past . ''
In Washington however , a senior U.S. military officer , speaking on condition of anonymity , acknowledged that pilots and other NATO forces were taking steps to lessen the threat to aircraft .
He would not elaborate .
On Tuesday , officials said the United Nations requested and NATO agreed that planes would not fly over Bosnia for a 48-hour period while U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and other peace negotiators visited Sarajevo .
Western military sources said it appeared that request was extended slightly , and it was not clear if NATO planes were back in Bosnian airspace .
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic , speaking in Pale after his meeting with Akashi , said , `` We would like to see skies clear of ... NATO aircraft . ''
`` If NATO is flying around there is more risk of misunderstandings and incidents , '' Karadzic added .
Part of an express train headed west for Budapest derailed Friday , its cars sliding into a station building and burying passengers , rail workers and their family members underneath the rubble .
Police said at least 24 people died .
The accident occurred at Szajol , a station near Szolnok about 70 kilometers -LRB- 40 miles -RRB- southeast of the Hungarian capital .
The second car of the express train derailed , dragging three other cars with it , and some of the overturned carriages smashed into the station building , railway officials said .
`` There was a tremedous explosion , like the end of the world , '' said a railway employee who witnessed the accident and asked not to be identified .
People remained buried in the wreckage into Friday night , although the crash occured at 4:45 p.m. local time .
Battered and broken railway cars were covered in brick torn loose from the building .
Rescue crews frantically dragged bloody bodies from the wreckage .
One car , partially twisted beyond recognition , remained skewering the collapsed building as a huge crane was positioned shortly before midnight to pluck it from the crumbling brick and mortar .
About 100 soldiers and 100 police officers worked into the night looking for survivors and keeping away the curious , as the ministers of defense , interior and transport converged on the accident site .
Rescue workers said part of the the destroyed building was sleeping quarters for railway personnel and their families , including small children who were likely victims and that they continued to hear voices from within the wreck .
Defense Minister Gyoergy Keleti said dogs normally used to locate victims of mining disasters had found three children who were dug from the rubble .
Laszlo Garamvoelgyi , a National Police spokesman , said the death toll had risen to 24 by late Friday with 60 others injured , some seriously .
With temperatures below freezing and others left in the wreckage , the death toll was expected to rise - Garamvoelgyi said the latest count `` was not the final one by any means . ''
The severity of the accident eclipsed the previous most serious train tragedy of recent years .
Te car that skewered the building jumped four tracks .
Transport Minister Mihaly Lotz said human error seemed to have caused the accident but investigations continued .
Local Police Chief Gyoergy Lengyel said the train was traveling at about 110 kilometers -LRB- 66 miles -RRB- and hour , normal speed past a station that was not a stop .
Doctors at one hospital near Szolnok said 26 injured , including two critical cases , were admitted to their hospital alone , with three others also taking in injured .
`` We are witnesses to a terrible tragedy , '' said Interior Minister Gabor Kuncze .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 160 kilometers -LRB- 100 miles -RRB- east of Budapest .
