Bosnian Serbs promised Friday to release hundreds of peacekeepers and allow aid deliveries as the chief U.N. envoy tried to salvage what was left of the ailing U.N. mission in Bosnia .
Earlier , two anti-tank missiles slammed into the presidency building just minutes before U.N. envoy Yasushi Akashi arrived for talks with the Muslim-led Bosnian government .
U.N. officials said the missiles appeared to come from Serb positions , but the Serbs said the government attacked itself to cause trouble .
It was yet another sign of Serb contempt for the peacekeeping effort , which has virtually ground to a halt .
The Serb rebels have stopped U.N. aid convoys , attacked a U.N.-declared `` safe area , '' and taken peacekeepers hostage .
In Brussels , Belgium , Secretary of State Warren Christopher and European foreign ministers endorsed a U.S. plan for a cease-fire that would lead to peace talks in the 2 -LCB- - year-old war .
The plan would also grant the Serbs their main aim in the conflict : the right to ties with Serb-led Yugoslavia .
The Serbs on Friday released 70 peacekeepers who had been held a week , but more than 300 peacekeepers remained hostage as insurance against NATO airstrikes .
Akashi , who met with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic at Serb headquarters in Pale , east of Sarajevo , said he was assured that Ukrainian peacekeepers held in northern Bosnia would be released , Dutch and British supply convoys detained since Saturday would be freed , and Bangladeshi peacekeepers stranded in Bihac would be allowed to receive supplies .
Karadzic said the Serbs and the U.N. `` are moving fast to normalization of our relations , '' but he issued a veiled warning against NATO .
`` We would like to see skies clear of our aircraft and of NATO aircraft , '' he said .
`` If NATO is flying around there is more risk of misunderstandings and incidents . ''
Under current rules of engagement , the U.N. must request the NATO airstrikes , although NATO planes can defend themselves against attack without U.N. approval .
U.N. officials fear that could escalate tensions .
Akashi had met earlier with Bosnian government and military leaders in Sarevejo .
Two wire-guided missiles hit the presidency building minutes before he arrived for the talks .
One destroyed the office of Miro Lazovic , an ethnic Serb member of Bosnia 's collective presidency .
Three missiles hit nearby buildings while the meeting went on .
There were no injuries .
The Bosnian government blasted the United Nations for not using force to halt fighting at Bihac , the embattled government-held enclave in the northwest .
Serb forces have seized 30 percent to 40 percent of the `` safe area , '' and fighting continued there Friday .
U.S. Ambassador to Germany Charles Redman held talks in Sarajevo with Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic and Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic on the U.S. peace plan .
Redman helped draft an earlier plan that the Serbs rejected .
The war began when Serbs rebelled against a vote for independence from Yugoslavia by Bosnia-Herzegovina 's Muslims and Croats .
More than 200,000 people are dead or missing in the war , and the Serbs have seized 70 percent of Bosnia .
Following the secession since 1991 of Slovenia , Croatia , Bosnia and Macedonia , Yugoslavia now comprises Serbia and Montenegro .
Serb nationalists in Yugoslavia , Croatia and Bosnia have pressed for a unified `` Greater Serbia . ''
The rejected peace plan denied Serbs the right to links with Yugoslavia as punishment for starting the war , but allowed Bosnia 's Croats and Muslims the right to ties with Croatia .
The old plan also granted the Serbs 49 percent of Bosnia -- a condition the new plan also contains .
Akashi had more success than U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali , who was rebuffed Wednesday when he tried to meet with Bosnian Serb leaders .
Boutros-Ghali said afterwards that intransigence by the warring sides might force the U.N. mission to withdraw .
Seventy Dutch peacekeepers arrived in Zagreb , Croatia , after being released from a seven-day detention by the Serbs in eastern Bosnia , U.N. officials said .
But Serbs continued to hold about 20 other Dutch peacekeepers , plus hundreds of British , Ukrainians and Canadians , at various points throughout Bosnia .
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi also wanted to discuss the fighting around Bihac with Karadzic .
The United Nations is trying to broker a cease-fire there .
Machine-gun and small arms fire was reported on the outskirts of Bihac , U.N. officials said .
The heaviest fighting appeared concentrated around Velika Kladusa , north of Bihac , where Serbs were apparently closing in on the government army 's 5th Corps .
The Bosnian Serbs , backed by Serbs from neighboring Croatia , want to wipe out the 5th Corps , which launched a briefly successful offensive from the Bihac enclave in late October .
There were also signs that fronts south of Bihac were heating up .
Bosnian Croats , allied with Muslim-led government forces , claimed they captured three villages north of the town of Kupres in central Bosnia .
Croat militia and Bosnian army soldiers took Kupres from the Serbs last month .
Gen. Ante Roso , the Bosnian Croat military commander , charged that Serbs in neighboring Croatia had shelled his forces across the border , near the town of Livno .
He said his troops returned fire .
Karadzic claimed regular Croatian army troops were fighting alongside the Bosnian Croats and warned Akashi to get them out or `` we will be forced to declare we are in war with Croatia . ''
In Knin , Croatia , the Croatian government and leaders of the rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement that , if implemented , could lead to normalized relations between the two enemies .
The agreement calls for restoring water and electricity supplies and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , and the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade .
Hundreds of angry people descended on a neighborhood gunmen when multinational soldiers freed him Friday , prompting the foreign soldiers to return to save him two hours later .
Samuel Chery , who had terrorized a neighborhood in this Port-au-Prince suburb during military coup rule from 1991 to October , had been held for nearly two months after U.S. soldiers arrested him .
Chery , known as `` Ti Samuel , '' was an `` attache , '' one of thousands of thugs who had Haitian military support to beat or kill supporters of democracy .
He was freed by foreign troops at 2 p.m. , prompting uncomprehending screams by neighbors , many of whom feared their lives if the attaches returned to the streets .
Hundreds of people gathered , grabbing sticks or carrying machetes .
They surrounded Chery 's home .
He had thrown rocks out at them and locked his door .
Another Humvee carrying foreign soldiers arrived two hours later and took away Chery .
Telephones were not functioning at the U.S. military 's Joint Information Bureau late Friday , and it was not clear why Chery was freed or where he was being held .
Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsay Clark accused the United States Friday of protecting members of the right-wing terror group FRAPH even after intervening to return exiled President Jean-Bertrand Aristide .
The Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti says its converting into a political organization , and a leader , Emmanuel Constant , renounced violence at a U.S.-arranged news conference two months ago .
`` The same forces that planned the coup '' are maintaining the level of violence , Clark told reporters after a five-day fact-finding mission of his Haiti Commission human rights group .
`` The longer the criminals go unpunished , the more likely it is that the people will take justice into their own hands , '' said lawyer Michael Ratner , another commission member and director of the New York-based Center for Constititonal Rights .
The U.N. civilian mission in a Nov. 22 communique said `` a certain degree of violence prevailed until the end of October .
Since then , without having entirely disappeared , violent incidents are much rarer . ''
The mission reported , however , that many people believe `` that the disarmament and dismantlement of groups which were part of the former repressive apparatus have been insufficient . ''
The United States and four other governments on Friday tried to restart the drive for peace in Bosnia with a plea for support of a plan designed to lure advancing Serbs with a prospect of political ties to Serbia .
Secretary of State Warren Christopher said the group rejected the options of `` carpet bombing '' or surrender , agreeing to resubmit a plan whose basic terms the Serbs rejected in the past .
`` The road will be very difficult , '' Christopher said , referring to the new attempt to draw the Serbs into peace talks .
The hint of a step toward a Greater Serbia was contained in a one-page text of the agreement distributed after Christopher met with the foreign ministers of Britain , France , Germany and Russia .
It said the idea was to `` allow equitable and balanced arrangements for the Bosniac-Croat and Bosnian Serb entities . ''
This proclaims that since the Muslim-led Bosnian government and Bosnian Croats have formed a federation linked to Croatia , the Bosnian Serbs have the same right to seek cross-border political ties to Serbia .
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe , who led a successful European campaign to move the Clinton administration from its support for NATO bombing raids on Serb positions , called this assurance a matter of giving all parties `` an equal opportunity . ''
He and the other ministers stressed , however , that the Serbs must recognize the legitimacy of Bosnia-Herzegovina .
The ministers emphasized they had reached unity after lengthy wrangling on how to deal with the war over the last 31 months .
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel , who chaired the meeting of the five-nation `` contact group , '' said the fighting in the Bihac region of northwest Bosnia had reached an awful state .
He said the war can not be solved with external military force .
Juppe and British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd will go to Belgrade on Sunday in pursuit of a diplomatic solution .
Both stressed that while they would carry the joint decision with them , they would be meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic as representatives of their governments .
Michael McCurry , the State Department spokesman , said U.S. envoy Charles E. Redman went to Sarajevo on Thursday for meetings with Bosnian Muslim leaders .
He also told reporters the proposal Christopher had prepared for an international peace conference was being held `` in abeyance '' until the various consultations .
The meeting of the U.S.-allied contact group came as the Bosnian Serbs tightened their grip on the mostly Muslim Bihac enclave and as the conflict threatened to spread into Croatia .
Christopher wants Milosevic to threaten to seal Serbia 's border to Bosnia .
Despite a promise to halt weapons deliveries , Clinton administration officials said , arms were still getting through to fuel the Bosnian Serbs ' drive to gain more territory and to terrorize Muslim civilians .
The war has taken an estimated 200,000 lives and left many times that number homeless .
Some 500 U.N. peacekeepers have been detained by the Bosnian Serbs , contributing to the decision by the U.N. commander , Sir Michael Rose , not to conduct heavy bombing raids against the Serbs .
Meanwhile , a senior U.S. military officer , briefing reporters at the Pentagon , reported that NATO has begun planning to prepare for its role in the possible evacuation of U.N. peacekeepers .
`` We are doing planning at the NATO level for a withdrawal -- when and if that ever comes about , '' said the officer , who spoke on condition his name not be used .
The officer emphasized that no request to help in such a move had come from the United Nations , but that it was `` prudent '' to prepare for such a move , even though a U.N. withdrawal did not appear imminent .
Christopher 's plan , which was adopted by President Clinton 's senior foreign policy advisers Monday at a White House meeting , calls for a cease-fire in the Bihac area , a cessation of hostilities for three to six months throughout Bosnia and a peace conference .
There , the Bosnian Serbs would be able to promote their aspirations for a Greater Serbia , initially with political links to Belgrade .
They hope also to establish cross-border ties to ethnic Serbs in Croatia .
Elements of the plan are similar to one rejected repeatedly by the Bosnian Serbs .
It called for them to accept Bosnia as a legitimate country and to shrink the territory under their control to 49 percent from about 70 percent .
A federation of Muslims and Croats would be in charge of 51 percent of the war-torn country .
Even that division is negotiable once peace talks are resumed , U.S. officials said , hoping to induce the Serbs to halt their attacks and to negotiate .
Zachariah Toungate has spent a third of his life fighting for the right to wear a ponytail to school .
About the only thing that 's changed in those four years is the length of his hair .
State District Judge Norman Lanford ruled this week that the Bastrop school district 's above-the-bottom-of-the-collar hair rule for boys violates the Texas Constitution 's Equal Rights Amendment .
But he said the courts have given administrators broad authority in running schools , and refused to revoke the rule .
Though Zach wo n't be returning to school -- and may appeal -- the 12-year-old said he feels good about the ruling .
`` The judge said it was unconstitutional , and he said that he thought that was wrong , '' said the boy , whose ponytail is now about 15 inches -LRB- 38 centimeters -RRB- long .
Ray Long , president of the School Board , said there is no sentiment on the board to change the rule .
`` I think that hair , dress and grooming standards are good , '' Long said .
The fight started in 1990 when Zach refused to cut his hair .
He was separated from other third-graders and taught alone .
He was prohibited from participating in extracurricular activities .
In 1991 , Zach 's parents withdrew him from school and taught him at home .
They sued to abolish the rule so he could return to class .
The case finally went to trial in October in Bastrop , a town of 4,000 people about 35 miles -LRB- 56 kilometers -RRB- east of Austin .
The jury ruled in the school district 's favor , but the judge indicated jurors may have been confused , and he issued his own ruling .
School officials had argued that if the hair-length rule were repealed , it would lead to gangs .
But Lanford , in his ruling Tuesday , said that argument was `` solely designed to frighten the jury . ''
He said the district had failed to prove that students ' schooling would be disrupted .
Zach continues to receive schooling at home , studying reading , math and history through correspondence courses .
The seventh-grader said it 's difficult to make new friends since he does n't go to school .
Zach 's mother , September , and father , Stanley , are backing their son .
`` It has been worth it .
Discrimination is wrong , '' said his mother , a 33-year-old nurse at an adolescent psychological center .
The boy 's father , a 44-year-old auto mechanic and electrician , had long hair when Zach decided to grow his long , too , said the boy 's lawyer , Charles Beall .
Later , the elder Toungate cut his hair .
Skirting differences over tax cuts , welfare and health insurance , President Clinton and leaders of the incoming Republican Congress agreed at a White House summit Friday to work together on a batch of less-divisive issues .
Emerging from their first talks with Clinton since November elections gave the Republicans control of Congress , incoming Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole said , `` certainly it 's in our interest , where possible , to be together . ''
Rep. Newt Gingrich , the incoming House of Representatives speaker , said , `` We agreed as a principle that there would be areas in which we would disagree but I do n't think we actually spent much time on them . ''
The Republicans said the meeting was positive ; Gingrich called it `` superb . ''
But it was clear they avoided areas of likely disagreement such as taxes .
`` We did n't cover everything , we did n't get down to the T 's , '' Dole said .
Hours before the meeting , Clinton served notice in a speech that he would fight tax cuts that inflate the budget deficit and any attempt to repeal the new ban on assault weapons .
Gingrich said Clinton agreed to work with Republicans on easing costly requirements imposed on the states by Washington and enacting a line-item veto allowing the president to delete some projects from legislation without killing it altogether .
Dole said he suggested that Clinton consult with Republicans more on foreign policy .
As for further talks with Clinton , Dole said , `` I assume anytime we want to meet , the president 's going to be accessible . ''
`` I hope and believe we can cooperate with the new Congress , '' Clinton said earlier .
`` But cooperation for me can not mean abandoning principle , abandoning the hard work we have already accomplished together in our fight to restore the economy , our fight against crime . ''
Addressing a national meeting of mayors and city officiais , he drew the line against relaxing gun controls enacted by the just-ended Congress over opposition from the National Rifle Association .
`` The assault weapons ban that you helped to win stands between the citizens you and I must protect and the gangs and thugs that would terrorize them , '' he said .
`` I will do all in my power to keep the next Congress from doing anything that will jeopardize the safety of our people . ''
Separately , Clinton also met in the Cabinet Room with newly named Congressional leaders of his Democratic Party , now in the minority .
Afterwards , Sen. Tom Daschle , the new Democratic leader , said Democrats will work with the White House but that , `` Clearly , we have our own agenda as well . ''
`` It 's no secret that the landscape in Washington shifted dramatically last month , '' Clinton said ruefully , referring to the November elections that gave Republicans control of both houses of Congress for the first time in 40 years and a majority of U.S. state governorships .
Clinton 's administration fears the rival parties might try to outdo each other on tax cuts .
He said he would fight any proposal that would `` explode the deficit ... my standard will be : Will it help increase incomes for the middle class , will it promote jobs and growth and can we pay for it ? ''
In his speech broadcast from Washington to the National League of Cities conference in Minneapolis , Clinton said , `` We need to give hard working middle-class people a dividend from the end of the Cold War and the dramatic downsizing of the federal government . ''
The Republican campaign 's Contract with America called for an array of tax credits .
Clinton urged city officials who have been complaining about inadequate funds for essential services `` to make sure that the Congress understands what the consequences are of all these budgetary decisions . ''
In the afterglow of bipartisan support for the new world trade agreement , Clinton said he hoped to work with Republicans on welfare and health-care reform , cost-controls on medical care and easing the financial demands imposed on cities and states by Washington .
