The chief drug enforcement official of the U.S. government Friday congratulated Thailand for arresting 10 people believed to be top lieutenants of one of the world 's biggest heroin traffickers .
The arrests came after two years of internatioanl cooperation and a months-long pursuit of the 10 suspects , said DEA Administrator Thomas A. Constantine .
Police of Thailand 's Narcotics Suppression Bureau carried out the arrests this past week in Bangkok and northern Thailand .
Those arrested are said to be close aides of the notorious drug warlord Khun Sa , who is based in the Burmese jungle in the `` Golden Triangle '' region where the borders of Thailand , Burma and Laos meet .
`` That 's like going into Sicily and grabbing the 10 biggest Mafia figures
and taking them away , '' said Constantine , who is on a tour of the region .
Most of the heroin that comes to the United States originates in the Golden Triangle , and U.S. authorities say Khun Sa is the trade 's kingpin there .
He has an estimated 10,000 men in his Shan United Army , whose main purpose Khun Sa claims is to press Burma 's central government for autonomy for the Shan ethnic minority .
Speaking at a news conference , Constantine described heroin trafficking and addiction as a growing social problem for the United States and much of the world .
He said that heroin sold in major cities in the United States is now 100 times as pure as it was in the early 1970s -- jumping from 7 percent to 70 percent -- while its price has been cut by half .
Violent crime , as well as the spread of AIDS through the sharing of needles by addicts , are only two of its consequences , he said .
`` The individual primarily responsible for this worldwide devastation of drug addiction is Khun Sa and his Shan United Army , '' said Constantine .
`` He has delivered as much evil to this world as any Mafia don has ever done in our history . ''
Constantine revealed details behind the recent arrests , which were carried out by police of Thailand 's Narcotics Suppression Bureau , with little fanfare .
He said that for the past two years a combined group of Thai police and military , narcotics units , and border police , along with American DEA , State Department , immigration and customs officials have targeted Khun Sa as `` the kingpin Mafia druglord most important in the entire globe . ''
As a result of their investigations , a U.S. federal court in New York City had issued indictments against major figures in Khun Sa 's drug trafficking ring , he said .
The same task force that conducted the investigations has been tracking `` for months '' the people arrested this week .
`` When these druglords are brought to the justice that I think they so richly deserve , and the appropriate punishment is given to them for the evil they have produced , then the whole world can properly thank Thailand and these dedicated public servants for their contributions to making this a better world , '' Constantine said .
Constantine came to Thailand from Hong Kong , and will next visit Malaysia and Singapore .
The purpose of his tour , a DEA spokeswoman said , is `` to see firsthand the extent of heroin production and trafficking and to ask the governments with which we deal about how we can help cooperate for greater progress in this area . ''
Constantine said he hopes some way could be found to more effectively tackle drug production in Burma , where the United States maintains a minimal drug enforcement presence because of concerns over human rights abuses by that country 's ruling military junta .
`` My position is that this is a country which produces between 60 and 70 percent of the world 's heroin ; they are inflicting , that group of people on the border area , ... great damage on the world .
And I think we have to find some resolution to the problem so we can address it . ''
An express train derailed southeast of Budapest Friday sending cars smashing into a railroad station building and burying passengers , railroad workers and their family under the rubble .
At least 24 people were killed , police said .
The accident occurred at 4:45 p.m. in Szajol , a station near Szolnok about 70 kilometers -LRB- 43 miles -RRB- southeast of the Hungarian capital .
The second car of the train derailed , dragging three other cars with it , and the overturned carriages crashed into a station building used as sleeping quarters by railway personnel and their families , railway officials said .
`` There was a tremendous explosion , like the end of the world , '' said a railway employee who witnessed the accident and asked not to be identified .
He said in a telephone interview that some people remained buried in the wreckage into Friday night .
`` We are witnesses to a terrible tragedy , '' said Interior Minister Laszlo Kuncze , who joined other senior officials at the scene late Friday evening .
Battered and broken railway cars were covered by bricks torn loose from the building .
Rescue crews frantically dragged bloody bodies from the wreckage .
One car , partially twisted beyond recognition , remained skewering the building .
A huge crane was positioned shortly before midnight to pluck it from the crumbling brick and mortar .
About 100 soldiers and 100 police officers worked into the night looking for survivors and keeping away onlookers .
Rescue workers said they continued to hear voices from within the wreckage .
Defense Minister Gyoergy Keleti said dogs normally used to locate victims of mining disasters had found three children who were dug out from the rubble .
National police spokesman Laszlo Garamvoelgyi said the death toll had risen to 24 by late Friday with 60 others injured , some seriously .
With temperatures below freezing and others still trapped in the wreckage , the death toll was expected to rise , Garamvoelgyi said .
There were fears the victims could include the children of the railway workers .
Transport ministry officials said the accident occurred at a rail switch and suggested it was possibly caused by the switch not being completely thrown .
The car that skewered the building jumped four tracks .
Transport Minister Mihaly Lotz said human error appeared to have caused the accident but the investigation continued .
Local police Chief Gyoergy Lengyel said the train was traveling at about 110 kilometers -LRB- 66 miles -RRB- an hour , the normal speed for passing a station that was not a stop .
Doctors at one hospital near Szolnok said 26 injured people , including two critical cases , had been admitted to their hospital .
Several other hospitals were also taking in the injured .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 160 kilometers -LRB- 100 miles -RRB- east of Budapest , to the capital .
A U.S. lawyer who is in Guatemala searching for her guerrilla husband was banned Friday from leaving the country .
Jennifer Harbury had said she intended to file charges against the government in the disappearance of her husband , Efrain Bamaca .
She was barred from leaving under a complex law that requires a person to file charges against the state after saying that they intend to do so .
`` Any person who has stated their intention to press charges against the state ... can in turn be legally forced by the state to pursue the accusation , '' said her lawyer , Antonio Argueta .
`` In Jennifer 's case we do not see it as a purely legal measure but as a ... way to debilitate the search for her husband , '' Argueta added .
Harbury , based in Washington , D.C. , contends the government illegally detained and tortured Bamaca , who has not been seen since 1992 .
`` I was always going to press charges against those military officials ... who saw my husband being tortured inside a military base but now the Guatemalan government is forcing me to do it sooner , '' Harbury told The Associated Press .
Guatemala gives a person 15 days to file charges after announcing an intent to do so .
Harbury returned to Guatemala to cooperate with investigations by the Supreme Court of Justice and a government human rights office into her husband 's whereabouts .
Both the military and the government deny Bamaca was ever captured .
President Ramiro de Leon Carpio repeatedly claims Bamaca died in combat and says clandestine jails do not exist in Guatemala .
However , evidence made public by the U.S. State Department in November indicates that Bamaca was captured alive by the Guatemalan army with slight injuries .
The U.S. Postal Service on Friday defended its stamp recalling the atomic bombing of Japan saying that it could not omit such a major event from its World War II history series .
The stamp , showing a mushroom-shaped cloud rising from an atomic blast , is one of a set of 10 stamps marking major events of 1945 to be sold on a sheet titled `` 1945 : Victory at Last . ''
Forty stamps have already been issued in similar sets for the 50th anniversary of the 1941-44 war years .
But the atomic bomb stamp is drawing sharp criticism in Japan .
Sunao Tsuboi , acting director of the 30,000-member Hiroshima Prefectural Confederation of A-bomb Survivors Organizations , termed it `` outrageous . ''
Japan surrendered Aug. 15 , 1945 , days after atomic bombs were dropped on the cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki .
`` Atomic bombs hasten war 's end , August 1945 , '' says the caption on the mushroom cloud stamp .
Postal Service spokesman Robin Wright said the World War II series was developed in cooperation with the State and Defense departments to assure historical accuracy .
As far as the atomic bomb stamp , he said , `` we would be remiss in omitting such a watershed and historically critical event as the use of the atomic bomb . ''
`` Our purpose is to provide a comprehensive history of events of World War II , and we are not making a value judgment on any of those events , '' Wright added .
Asked for comment on the issue , the State Department said in a statement late Friday it has been in contact with the Postal Service , and understands that `` the stamps are not intended for the general public but rather for philatelists . ''
`` We understand the matter is still under consideration , '' the statement added .
It did not reply to a question whether there had been discussions with the Japanese government explaining the matter .
Other stamps in the 1945 set picture U.S. Marines raising the American flag on Iwo Jima , `` Okinawa , the last big battle , '' liberations of Manila and of Holocaust survivors in Europe , Germany 's surrender at Reims , refugees uprooted by war and U.S. celebrations of Japanese surrender .
The 1941 set , titled `` A World at War '' included stamps showing Japanese bombing Pearl Harbor , Hawaii , and President Roosevelt and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill framing the Atlantic Charter .
The 1944 set , titled `` Road to Victory '' included the allied Normandy landings , the liberation of Rome and the battles of Leyte Gulf in the Pacific and the Bulge in Belgium .
The United States has offered shelter in its refugee camps to up to 900 of the Cubans who have fled to this tiny British territory , Cayman officials said Friday .
If the Cubans accept the offer , they would go to camps at the U.S. Naval Base at Guantanamo Bay , Cuba , and in Panama , Gerry Maguire , the territory 's chief immigration officer , told the refugees in a meeting at their tented camp .
The U.S. camps already hold thousands of refugees .
The Cayman refugees probably would n't be transferred until early next year , government spokeswoman Pat Ebanks said .
`` It will be a significant weight off our shoulders , '' Ebanks said .
The announcement came after months of talks with U.S. officials and the day after more than 300 Cuban women and children marched peacefully through George Town calling on the United States to let them in .
Also Friday , the United States announced new immigration rules that will allow more Cuban families now sheltered in refugee camps to enter .
Hundreds of Cubans fled here after riots in Havana in early August prompted Cuban President Fidel Castro to say he would not prevent people from leaving .
The approximately 1,150 Cubans now sheltered here represent about 4 percent of the 30,000 residents of this tourist resort and offshore banking center just 70 miles -LRB- 110 kilometers -RRB- south of Cuba .
But the Caymans ' Cuban problem is far from resolved , Ebanks said .
Many Cubans have said they do n't want to go to Guantanamo because it 's too close to the home they want to escape and because a larger camp does n't appeal to them , Ebanks said .
Even if all 900 accept , that still leaves 250 refugees .
The Cayman government has decided to grant asylum to a small , as-yet-undetermined number of Cubans who fled political persecution , Ebanks said .
Twenty-four refugees have asked to return to their homeland and will be flown back , probably within two weeks , Ebanks said .
As a last resort , the Cayman government could repatriate those who remain , she said .
`` We 're really not heaving a sigh of relief .
Not for ourselves and not for the Cubans , '' Ebanks said .
President Clinton on Friday ordered that no U.S. government funds be spent on human embryo research , rejecting a recommendation made just hours earlier by a federal advisory committee .
`` I do not believe that federal funds should be used to support the creation of human embryos for research purposes , '' Clinton said , continuing the ban imposed by Presidents Reagan and Bush before him .
`` I have directed that the National Institutes of Health not allocate any resources for such research , '' Clinton said in a statement issued by the White House .
He said research on fertilized human eggs `` raises profound ethical and moral questions as well as issues concerning the appropriate allocation of federal funds . ''
The report of the NIH 's human embryo committee said the research had the potential of finding new ways to correct infertility , prevent or correct birth defects , and learn fundamental cell biology that might help combat cancer .
After studying the issue for nine months , the committee delivered its recommendations this week to another panel that advises NIH Director Harold Varmus .
That panel endorsed the recommendations , leaving the final decision up to Varmus on if , when and how the NIH would proceed with research grants -- until Clinton took it out of Varmus ' hands later in the day .
Clinton praised the work of the committees and said he understood how the research could make advances in in vitro fertilization , the so-called test tube baby technique .
He also said he planned to establish a bioethics advisory commission to further deliberate such issues .
The advisory committee acknowledged that many people had ethical and moral reservations about its recommendation .
Under the recommendation , embryo research would have been subject to strict controls , including limiting it to the first 14 days after fertilization .
At that point , a fertilized human egg has grown to hundreds of cells but has not yet developed a nervous system , specific tissues or a human form .
The White House announcement came as opponents of human embryo research , mostly groups that also oppose abortion , were gathering forces for a showdown in Congress .
A coalition of the opponents planned a news conference on Monday and one congressman already had pledged to support their efforts with legislation .
`` Regardless of any potential medical advancements , human dignity must not be degraded by having life created in a laboratory dish just to have it thrown out with the trash when scientists are finished with their Frankenstein-type experiments , '' said Rep. Robert Dornan , R-Calif. , who promised to carry the fight to Congress .
Richard Doerfinger of the U.S. Catholic Conference said his organization would support efforts to block any federal funding for the embryo research .
Guidelines for embryo research were first recommended by an NIH committee in 1979 , but Presidents Reagan and Bush opposed it and the process withered .
Varmus , who was appointed by President Clinton , revived the effort by naming the embryo research committee earlier this year .
Despite the lack of federal funds , clinics and universities that provide in vitro fertilization services -- the so-called test-tube-baby technique of assisting reproduction for infertile couples -- have privately financed extensive research for more than a decade .
Dr. Steven Muller , president emeritus of Johns Hopkins University and chairman of the embryo advisory panel that studied the issue for months , said members of that committee received more than 50,000 pieces of mail , most of it protesting government support for the research .
`` The public has no idea what human embryo research means , but to most people it does seem terrible , '' Muller said .
`` The extreme high level of public ignorance invites exploitation '' by opponents to the research .
This year 's drop in the stock market may accomplish what six interest-rate tightenings by the Federal Reserve have apparently failed to do : Slow the economy down .
So argues inveterate market bear Michael Metz , chief investment strategist at Oppenheimer and Co. , in a recent research report .
Despite the fact that blue-chip stocks have held up well , many investors have experienced a 5 to 10 percent drop in the value of their stock portfolios this year .
Stock investors `` feel poorer and they are poorer '' than they were last Jan. 1 , Metz said .
They will assess their losses for the year and , alarmed about the erosion of their net worth , put a tight lid on discretionary spending .
That in turn will finally put the brakes on a seemingly unstoppable economy , he said .
`` The decline in stock values -- and the drop already seen in the bond market this year -- is expected to have a tangible wealth effect on householders who now have their highest exposure in decades to stocks and bonds as a percentage of their assets , '' Metz writes in a Nov. 23 report entitled , `` Will the Stock Market do the Fed 's Work ? ''
`` The result ... '' Metz writes , `` is a slowdown in personal consumption spending generally in 1995 , and a growth recession by the second quarter of 1995 . ''
Metz turns on its head the conventional wisdom that Federal Reserve credit tightenings should , by themselves , slow the economy down .
He got some support from economic reports this past week that show the economy continues to chug along , despite a better than 2 percentage point increase in short-term interest rates since last February .
The most recent of these was a report Friday that the nation 's nonfarm payrolls added an impressive 350,000 jobs in November , pushing the unemployment rate down by 0.2 percentage points to 5.6 percent .
Stocks initially stalled on the news but then posted some respectable gains as bond prices surged , pushing inerest rates lower .
The Dow Jones industrial average finished Friday 's session at 3,745.62 , up 44.75 for the day and up 37.35 for the week .
Analysts said Friday 's rally occurred for largely technical reasons , however , and they remained cautious .
`` We have gotten through a week of news and the market has , for whatever it 's worth , held together , '' said Hugh Johnson , market strategist at First Albany Corp.
Metz argues that , whether interest rates move higher or not , the drop in the stock market itself will arrest economic growth .
But Johnson said , `` I think it 's not that easy . ''
This year 's Fed tightenings , as aggressive as they have been , have not had enough time to work , Johnson said .
Interest rate changes typically do not affect the economy for 12 to 18 months .
And exports , government spending and business investments , all of which have a big impact on the economy , are likely to ebb and flow independently of the stock market , Johnson said .
Still , Metz pointed out that when the stock market crashed in 1987 , many investors watched from the sidelines .
A large portion of their investments were in bonds , because interest rates were relatively high at the time , Metz said .
Now , households have more than a third of their financial assets in stocks , according to industry studies .
That compares with an average of about 26 percent since 1945 and means that individual investors -- and the economy -- are especially vulnerable to market downturns , Metz said .
On Friday , the New York Stock Exchange 's composite index rose 1.97 to 248.01 , up 0.41 for the week .
The Standard and Poor 's 500-stock index rose 4.38 to 453.30 , up 1.01 for the week .
The Nasdaq composite index rose 3.83 to 745.02 , up 2.50 for the week .
The American Stock Exchange 's market value index rose 1.27 to 432.46 , up 2.23 for the week .
The Wilshire Associates Equity Index , which is the market value of NYSE , American , and over-the-counter issues , ended the week at dlrs 4.476 trillion , up dlrs 4.644 billion from the previous week .
Bosnian Serb leaders promised Friday to release hundreds of detained United Nations peacekeepers .
But there was no confirmation that 55 detained Canadians peacekeepers were free to move .
Here are some key dates surrounding their detention :
Nov. 19 -- UN Security Council extends NATO air authority to Croatia after Serb warplanes flying from an air base in Udbina , in Serb-controlled Croatia , launch air strikes on the UN-declared safe haven of Bihac in northwest Bosnia .
Nov. 21 -- NATO planes bomb the Udbina airport and two Serb missile sites in Bosnia near Bihac .
Nov. 22 -- Serbs fire surface-to-air missiles at two NATO jets flying over Serb-held Banja Luka , in northwest Bosnia , and set villages ablaze and send civilians fleeing in the Bihac pocket in retaliation for NATO air strikes .
Nov. 23 -- Serbs detain some 250 UN peacekeepers , including 55 Canadian troops near their base in Visoko , Bosnia , hours after renewed NATO air strikes against Serb positions near Bihac in Bosnia and Croatia .
Nov. 24 -- UN officials attempt to negotiate the release of the Canadians and the other UN peacekeepers in talks with Serb leaders .
Bosnian Muslim-led government troops block attempt to transfer 150 non-essential personnel from the Canadian base at Visoko to Kiseljak , some 15 kilometres away .
Nov. 25 -- NATO jets fly over Serb positions near Bihac but due to darkness drop no bombs as Serb forces advance into the enclave , controlled by the Muslim-led government army .
Serbs allow some of the detained Canadians to carry out work at their observation posts .
Muslims lift blockade of Canadian camp .
Nov. 26 -- Canadian troops come under fire three times .
No one is injured : a convoy of buses carrying Canadians to Visoko from Split , Croatia , is hit by five mortars ; two rifle grenades hit Canadian headquarters in Knin in Serb-controlled Croatia ; mortar round lands near Canadian vehicle in Knin area .
Nov. 27 -- Between six and 10 rockets fired by Bosnian Serbs land near the Canadian camp in Visoko .
Shrapnel from two rockets damages a camp building where Canadian soldiers are sleeping .
No one is injured .
Negotiations to free the detained Canadians continue .
Nov. 28 -- The UN commander in Bosnia , Lt.-Gen .
Sir Michael Rose , and Col. Bill Brough , commander of the Canadian battalion in Visoko , fail to win release of the Canadians .
A Serb offer to let the Canadians return to base if they 're replaced by another 55 Canadians is rejected .
Nov. 30 -- a Bosnian Serb threat to shell the Canadian camp within 48 hours passed without incident .
However , the peacekeepers increased security and placed sandbags around sleeping quarters .
Dec. 2 -- UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi said Bosnian-Serb leaders agreed to allow the detained peacekeepers to go about their normal activities .
Canadian officers could n't confirm the reports of agreement .
Next week 's talks between Britain and the IRA 's political allies will be delayed by two days at the party 's request , the government announced Friday .
There was no immediate explanation from Sinn Fein for the delay of the long-sought talks that are the next big step in the search for a political settlement in Northern Ireland following the Irish Republican Army 's 3-month-old cease-fire .
Prime Minister John Major on Thursday invited Sinn Fein to meet government officials in Belfast on Wednesday , Dec. 7 .
The government 's Northern Ireland Office said Friday that the first exploratory dialogue will now take place Friday , Dec. 9 .
Government officials said the Northern Ireland Office had no problem with opening the talks 48 hours later .
Officials said there had been contact between the two sides on Friday and that Sinn Fein had said they could not manage to make the meeting on Wednesday .
The talks will be the first publicly acknowledged meeting between the two sides since the conflict over British rule of Northern Ireland ignited in 1969 .
The meeting evolved from the peace process begun last December when the British and Irish governments offered Sinn Fein a place in talks if the IRA laid down its arms .
The outlawed group began an open-ended truce Sept. 1 .
News reports , meanwhile , reported that suspects arrested in a West Belfast robbery were known republicans .
Police would not confirm that , saying they did not know who those being questioned were .
They said that after the robbery of a filling station Friday morning , police made `` a number of arrests '' and found an imitation firearm , masks and a sum of money .
Heidi Fleiss , who once boasted that her prostitution ring catered to the `` top 1 percent '' of Hollywood 's elite , was convicted Friday of providing high-price call girls to undercover police officers .
After four days of deliberations , a jury found the 28-year-old pediatrician 's daughter guilty on three of five pandering charges .
The seven-man , five-woman jury deadlocked on the two other counts , and acquitted her of supplying cocaine to an undercover police officer .
Fleiss was visibly unhappy with the outcome .
She slammed her hands on the defense table and laid down her head as the guilty verdicts were read .
Her father , seated behind her in the front row of the courtroom , hung his head .
Fleiss faces a minimum of three years , and up to eight years and eight months in prison .
A sentencing hearing was set for Jan. 20 .
Fleiss and her father , Paul , await a second trial in January on federal charges they laundered profits from the call-girl ring .
Prosecutor Alan Carter said he was pleased with the verdict .
The district attorney 's office had n't immediately decided whether to retry Fleiss on the two deadlocked counts .
Fleiss posted the dlrs 75,000 bail set by Superior Court Judge Judith L. Champagne .
Much of the six-day trial focused on police conduct , with Fleiss ' attorneys insisting she was entrapped .
Juror Nancy Reyes , 24 , said Fleiss was acquitted on the cocaine charge and two of the pandering counts because the jury felt the police acted unethically .
`` I personally feel the police went beyond reasonable conduct , '' she said .
`` They 're supposed to follow restrained steps . ''
Juror Sheila Mitrowski criticized the broad scope of the investigation and said she felt police `` were fishing for a whale and came up very short . ''
After the scandal broke last year , there was speculation that Fleiss ' clients included Hollywood stars and moguls .
But her so-called `` black book '' of clients was never made public ; the judge ruled the names of her customers were irrelevant .
Fleiss was captured on video and audiotapes during a Beverly Hills sting last year and charged with offering undercover police officers four women for prostitution .
Two of the women testified under immunity that they were to give Fleiss 40 percent of their dlrs 1,500 fees .
One woman also testified she charged up to dlrs 10,000 for a night of sex .
On the tapes Fleiss was heard boasting that her call girl ring catered to `` the top 1 percent '' of entertainment , corporate and political circles .
During the sting , Beverly Hills Detective Sammy Lee posed as a Hawaiian millionaire and spoke gibberish meant to pass as Japanese .
Videotapes show him arranging to purchase four women for himself and three colleagues .
The women are shown in a luxurious hotel suite accepting money , discussing what sex acts they would do and disrobing .
At that point , they were arrested .
Maj. Rita LePage , UN military spokeswoman in Zagreb , Croatia , said that while promises have been made , no timetable has been given for the possible release of the Canadian peacekeepers .
Bosnian Serbs said details would be provided as soon as possible , said LePage .
As the scorched Achille Lauro has sunk into the Indian Ocean , a surviving passenger blamed the crew for dropping inflatable rafts on top of a crowded lifeboat , injuring one man who later died .
The victim was one of two elderly passengers who died as a result of the fire on the Italian luxury liner .
The 979 passengers and crew who survived were headed for three African and Middle Eastern ports aboard 10 rescue vessels , including freighters and U.S. warships .
They abandoned the blazing ship Wednesday .
The Achille Lauro was once a gleaming blue-and-white luxury liner that sailed around the world in 80 days .
But it was best known for the 1985 hijacking by Palestinian terrorists , who killed an elderly Jewish American passenger , Leon Klinghoffer , and dumped his body overboard in his wheelchair .
The terrorists escaped aboard a jet , but U.S. fighter planes forced the plane down in Italy and the hijackers were arrested and later tried .
Eight people were injured in the fire , which began in the engine room before dawn .
Lifeboats and rafts were launched and the ship was abandoned .
According to passenger Geoffrey Wall , interviewed Friday by Britain 's Sky TV , one man was injured when crew members released inflatable rafts onto the lifeboat , which held about 35 people .
`` It was tilting at an angle , '' said Wall , a Briton , describing attempts to lower a lifeboat .
`` They got it near the water .
They could n't lower it properly .
Then somebody hit the wrong -- I do n't know what it is that they release them with -- but they dropped two of these inflatable life boats on top of us , resulting in injury to one man . ''
He said people gave the ailing man mouth-to-mouth resuscitation before a rescue ship arrived about four hours later .
`` We were in 100 yards -LRB- meters -RRB- or so of the rescue ship when he started to go ... Unfortunately , he died , '' Wall said .
It was not immediately clear if the man died of his injuries .
The ship 's owner , Naples , Italy-based Starlauro , had no immediate comment .
Passenger Dennis Bassett , also told Sky TV that crew members did not alert all the passengers until only minutes before the order sounded to abandon ship .
`` Some passengers at 7 o'clock in the morning were still in bed , '' he said .
The ship 's captain , Giuseppe Orsi , was the last to abandon the ship , which sank Friday evening about 125 miles -LRB- 200 kms -RRB- off the coast of Somalia in about 14,700 feet -LRB- 4,450 meters -RRB- of water .
The liner fell to its left side and sank as an Italian tug began to pull it , StarLauro President Nicola Coccia told the Italian news agency ANSA .
`` There probably was a movement of a mass of water inside , '' causing it to sink , he said .
`` She was hooked up to the -LRB- tug -RRB- Solano and in 10 minutes , she collapsed -- pfft , she disappeared , '' said Antonio de Rosa , marketing director for Starlauro .
He put the loss at dlrs 25 million .
Starlauro had hired the seagoing tugs to bring the vessel home to try to save her .
Italian coast guard Lt. Francesco D'Amico said the ship was unrecoverable .
Eight cargo vessels and two American warships , the USS Gettysburg and USS Halyburton , were carrying the surviving passengers and crew members to Djibouti , Mombasa in Kenya and Muskat in Oman .
Most were heading for Mombasa .
The first ship was expected to dock in Djibouti on Saturday ; the rest were scheduled to make port on Sunday .
Alitalia said Starlauro had chartered two 747s to pick up passengers from Djibouti and Mombasa and take them to Rome , for travel to their homes in Europe .
The planes leave Sunday and return Monday .
The United States and four European governments dusted off a rejected , five-month old Bosnia peace plan Friday , hoping the prospect of political ties to Serbia might lure advancing Bosnian Serbs into negotiations .
Secretary of State Warren Christopher said it would have been useless to approve `` carpet bombing '' by NATO aircraft on Serb positions .
That , he said , would have meant a `` reign of terror '' and required hundreds of thousands of allied troops to force a settlement .
And to `` walk away '' from the 31-month war that has taken some 200,000 lives is unacceptable , he said .
`` The road will be very difficult , '' Christopher said of the renewed effort to stop the bloodshed through a diplomatic attempt to effectively divide Bosnia-Herzegovina into areas dominated by the Serbs and by a Muslim-Croat federation .
The hint that the Serbs might take a step toward a Greater Serbia was in the text of a one-page agreement adopted in a four-hour meeting with the foreign ministers of Britain , France , Germany and Russia .
It said that while preserving the `` integrity '' of Bosnia as a legitimate country , the Bosnian Serbs were entitled to seek the kind of `` balanced and equitable arrangements '' worked out by the Muslims and Croats when they formed a federation in March linked to Croatia .
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe , who led a successful European campaign to persuade the Clinton administration to forgo heavy bombing as a strategy to stop the Serbs , called this assurance a matter of giving parties `` an equal opportunity . ''
The text does not specifically call for a confederation between Serbs in Bosnia and Serbia .
A senior U.S. official said Russian Foreign Minister Andrei V. Kozyrev had argued for endorsing confederation but Christopher `` beat that back . ''
The agreement also carried a hint that the 24,000 U.N. peacekeepers now in Bosnia , some 500 of whom were being held by the Serbs , might be withdrawn .
Their mission should continue `` provided that the risks do not become unacceptable , '' the agreement said .
The plan rejected repeatedly by the Serbs would give them control of 49 percent of the country , about two-thirds of the 70 percent they now occupy .
The Muslim-Croat area covered the other 51 percent .
This division `` can be adjusted by mutual arrangement , '' the ministers said , again suggesting the Serbs might do better at the bargaining table .
However , Juppe and the other ministers stressed in a joint news conference that the Serbs must recognize the legitimacy of Bosnia-Herzegovina .
They emphasized they were now united in promoting diplomacy as the only possible key to a ceasefire and a peace accord .
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel , who chaired the meeting of the five-nation `` contact group , '' said the fighting in the Bihac region of northwest Bosnia had reached an awful state .
He said the war could not be terminated through external military force .
Juppe and British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd will go to Belgrade on Sunday in pursuit of a diplomatic solution .
Both stressed that while they would carry the joint decision with them , they would meet with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic as representatives of their governments .
Michael McCurry , the State Department spokesman , said U.S. envoy Charles E. Redman went to Sarajevo on Thursday for meetings with President Alija Izetbegovic and other Bosnian government leaders .
He also told reporters the proposal Christopher had prepared for an international peace conference was being held `` in abeyance '' until the various consultations were concluded .
The meeting was held against the backdrop of a Bosnian Serb hammerlock on the mostly Muslim Bihac enclave and its 60,000 terrified civilians .
The prospect of the war spreading into Croatia also exists .
Christopher wants Milosevic to persuade Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic to accept a ceasefire and negotiations with the Muslims and Croats by threatening to seal Serbia 's border to Bosnia .
Despite a promise by Milosevic to halt weapons deliveries , Clinton administration officials said arms were still getting through to fuel the Bosnian Serbs ' drive to gain more territory .
Meanwhile , a senior U.S. military officer , briefing reporters at the Pentagon in Washington , reported that NATO has begun planning for the possible evacuation of U.N. peacekeepers .
`` We are doing planning at the NATO level for a withdrawal -- when and if that ever comes about , '' said the officer , who spoke on condition his name not be used .
Led by Wayne Gretzky , the Ninety-Nine All-Stars arrived in Finland Friday night , ready to kick off a six-game tour of the Nordic countries .
`` I did n't realize how much I missed the game until we got out there and started fooling for a couple of days of practice and then going on to play yesterday in Detroit , '' said Brett Hull of the St. Louis Blues as the touring team went through a light workout prior to Saturday 's game in Helsinki .
`` Hockey is just a part of our being , and we want to show the NHL that there is a reason for people to come and watch . ''
A group of elite National Hockey League players chosen by Gretzky , many of them his best friends , will play Finnish champion Jokerit of Helsinki on Saturday and Ilves in Tampere on Sunday .
For Gretzky , it is the second time playing in Europe .
In 1982 he came to the World Championships in Helsinki and Tampere and emerged as the top scorer after a slow start .
Canada won the bronze medal .
Gretzky is joined by some very old friends from the same season 's roster 13 years ago with the Edmonton Oilers : goaltender Grant Fuhr , defensemen Paul Coffey and Charlie Huddy and forwards Mark Messier and Jari Kurri .
The latter has been playing for Jokerit during the NHL lockout , but received permission to join Gretzky and Messier for Saturday 's game .
Eighteen players arrived in Helsinki three hours late and took the ice immediately in front of some 2,000 teenage fans .
`` This group of players is the best you 've seen in a long time , '' Gretzky said .
`` We all had an enjoyable four , five days already .
We 're happy to have had a light skate tonight and we 're excited to play tomorrow . ''
In Saturday 's game , the Ninety-Nine All-Stars will meet Finland 's top team , featuring Teemu Selanne , the Winnipeg Jets ' forward who was the NHL goal-scoring co-leader and rookie of the year in 1992-93 .
Gretzky promised a good show .
`` I think the players we have together are not quite like an all-star team , '' he said .
`` We have players that play some NHL-style hockey , with intensity and force .
We expect to hit , we expect to get hit . ''
Gretzky 's team lost its first game 4-3 Thursday to the Detroit Vipers of the International Hockey League at Auburn Hills , Mich.
But the All-Stars were shorthanded , playing with only four defensemen .
Three Detroit Red Wings , Steve Yzerman , Sergei Fedorov and Paul Coffey also skipped the game .
Gretzky 's team will play a Norwegian All-Star team in Oslo on Monday before heading to Sweden and three games against Djurgarden of Stockholm , Vastra Frolunda of Goteborg and Malmo .
Marking a milestone in Taiwan 's shift to democracy , Taiwanese voters went to the polls Saturday in the toughest electoral test for the island 's Nationalist rulers in 45 years .
The elections are part of the reforms initiated by the Nationalists , who ruled by martial law until unleashing a bloodless democratic revolution in 1987 .
Voters were electing a Taiwan governor , mayors for Taipei and Kaohsiung -- the island 's two largest cities -- local councilors and provincial assemblymen .
Polling stations opened at 8 a.m. -LRB- 0000 GMT -RRB- , and results are expected about eight hours after the planned close of 11,825 polling stations islandwide at 4 p.m. -LRB- 0800 GMT -RRB- .
Newspapers predicted up to 70 percent of Taiwan 's 13.8 million eligible voters would turn out .
The polls are a prelude to Taiwan 's first direct presidential election in 1996 .
President Lee Teng-hui 's prospects for another term will be measured by his Nationalists ' performance Saturday against the main opposition , the Democratic Progressive Party .
The Nationalists fled to Taiwan to escape the 1949 Communist takeover of mainland China .
They still say they hope one day to reunite Taiwan with the Chinese motherland .
But the DPP advocates Taiwanese independence , something China has vowed to resist by force , and DPP successes Saturday could bring warnings from Beijing .
The campaigning has focused largely on `` Tong-Du '' -- reunification vs. independence .
To the annoyance of the DPP , business leaders placed newspaper ads days before the poll warning that Taiwan 's dollar and the island 's standing with investors could plummet if pro-independence forces gain power .
But the DPP may profit from a split in the Nationalist vote caused by the recently formed New Party , which quit the Nationalists last year after accusing them of abandoning the commitment to reunification .
The DPP 's Chen Shui-bian is thought to be a frontrunner in the race fo Taipei mayor , while Nationalist James Soong has a 50-40 lead over the DPP 's Chen Ting-nan in the gubernatorial race , according to latest surveys .
Candidates held final rallies Friday night , including tens of thousands of cheering New Party supporters who packed Taipei 's municipal stadium .
The feverish election campaign , which sometimes resembled a carnival , is a sign of Taiwanese enthusiasm for democracy .
Taipei 's streets and many of its taxis were covered with flags .
In the last few days , campaigners lulled the capital to sleep at night with drums and roused it each morning with firecrackers .
Interior Minister Wu Poh-hsiung even complained that precious resources were wasted and that the campaign flags `` could have clothed 1 million refugees . ''
Enthusiasm and heated debate sometimes spilled over into violence .
Riot police were often at campaign rallies and 70,000 officers were keeping order Saturday .
In a statement Friday , President Lee appealed for calm on polling day so Taiwan can `` welcome a new era of democracy for all . ''
Other officials appealed to voters not to take bribes , a problem in past elections as well as this one .
The DPP filed a lawsuit Wednesday accusing the Nationalists of earmarking about 150 million Taiwan dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 5.6 million -RRB- to buy votes for Huang Ta-chou , Taipei 's incumbent Nationalist mayor , who is lagging in opinion polls .
The Nationalists denied the allegations and appealed against vote-buying .
Government-controlled TV ran advertisements showing vote-buyers in handcuffs .
In a small , windowless room in public school No. 728 lies what 14-year-old Anton calls Russia 's `` future '' -- the school 's only computer .
At School 728 , after spending hours in poorly heated classrooms where they have to share tattered Soviet-era textbooks , students come to the `` computer closet '' to work on the school 's innovative on-line newspaper .
Or to send e-mail to students in Minnesota .
Or to practice their French on an electronic conference with European schoolchildren .
Like most of Russia 's roads , its information highway is still ridden with potholes and Soviet-style dead-end alleys .
Nevertheless , the next generation of Russian leaders is building its own onramps and starting to cruise .
`` The kids may not understand yet what this access , this communication , means for them , '' said Volodya Pilipchuk , the school 's computer adviser and a former 728 student .
`` But 10 years from now , they will . ''
Pilipchuk 's students have joined the millions of people -- from New York businessmen to human rights activists in East Timor -- who communicate via a worldwide web of tens of thousands of interconnected computer networks .
For Anton and his classmates , it does n't seem to matter that they were born in a society famous for restricting such free information flows .
Or that some of their parents built careers on imposing those restrictions .
What matters to these kids is the computer itself .
Dozens of students huddle around its single screen during breaks , as Pilipchuk struggles to ration out computer time to eager users .
The well-worn machine is especially popular among the students here , most of whom , unlike many of their U.S. counterparts , had never seen a computer before this project began .
Olga Galkina , the founder of the school 's on-line newspaper , says the project is aimed at `` helping kids understand their global importance . ''
And ultimately , she hopes , these children may be the ones to guide the rest of the former Soviet Union into the information age .
Much of Russia 's wealth of computer expertise has been lured to the West , leaving a relatively small cadre of dedicated but underfunded programmers to bring new technologies to this vast nation .
In the meantime , the kids are just having fun .
`` Look , I can type in English , '' boasted Sasha , a 12-year-old in an L.A. Raiders sweatshirt .
`` Even my older brother ca n't do that . ''
The latest issue of `` Southern Zone , '' the on-line version of the school paper , included articles on topics from a nature reserve in Russia 's Far North to the music of David Lee Roth .
The issue was posted on the local network Glasnet , which is connected to the worldwide Internet meganetwork , allowing computers around the world access to the newspaper .
The latest publication has evoked responses from users from Holland to Minnesota .
`` The messages from the American kids are funny , '' said Alyosha , tugging on his long blond bangs .
`` Someone asked if Russia was bigger than California . ''
These kids are also proving that the information highway does not have to remain a limited access tollroad , affordable for only an elite few .
The school 's computer , a standard IBM-compatible 386 with an internal modem , is on long-term loan from John Whitely , a sociology professor at the University of California at Irvine .
Whitely loaned the machine to Galkina for the on-line newspaper project in 1992 .
And Glasnet , a non-profit Russian computer network , donated an e-mail account to the school , bringing the total cost of the project to just a few dollars per year -- less than the budget for the on-paper version of the school newspaper .
The project is a bargain even for public schools like this one .
Russia 's cash-strapped public education system is struggling to support its 65,000 schools , where teachers earn about 120,000 rubles -LRB- dlrs 40 -RRB- a month .
School 728 is just one of several seeds of hope .
At least 300 Russian schools have access to e-mail accounts , at least 250 of which are outside of Moscow .
`` The numbers are still not high , for a country this size , '' said Galkina , who is now working on a project to connect disabled children in Russia to on-line services .
`` But Russia , like the United States , wo n't become computer literate overnight . ''
Computer literacy is still not a top priority for School 728 's administrators , who pay little attention to the cramped computer closet .
`` Yes , I know there 's something going on over there , '' said Nina Mikhailova , head of the student relations department , in the opposite wing of the school .
`` But it does n't concern us .
We do n't use computers over here . ''
The administration may be wary , but its pupils are already making plans .
`` I want to be a programmer , '' Anton said , `` because the world ca n't survive without computers . ''
