The United States has offered shelter in its refugee camps to up to 900 of the Cubans who have fled to this tiny British territory , Cayman officials said Friday .
If the Cubans accept the offer , they would go to camps at the U.S. Naval Base at Guantanamo Bay , Cuba , and in Panama , Gerry Maguire , the territory 's chief immigration officer , told the refugees in a meeting at their tent camp .
The U.S. camps already hold thousands of refugees .
The Cayman refugees probably would n't be transferred until early next year , government spokeswoman Pat Ebanks said .
`` It will be a significant weight off our shoulders , '' Ebanks said .
The announcement came after months of talks with U.S. officials and a day after more than 300 Cuban women and children marched peacefully through George Town calling on the United States to let them in .
Also Friday , the United States announced new immigration rules that will allow more Cuban families now sheltered in refugee camps to enter .
Hundreds of Cubans fled here after an outbreak of hijackings and riots in early August prompted Cuban President Fidel Castro to allow people to leave by boat .
President Clinton then barred the new wave of Cuban boat people from entering the United States .
The approximately 1,150 Cubans now sheltered here represent about 4 percent of the 30,000 residents of this tourist resort and offshore banking center just 70 miles -LRB- 110 kilometers -RRB- south of Cuba .
But the Caymans ' Cuban problem is far from resolved , Ebanks said .
Many Cubans have said they do n't want to go to Guantanamo because it 's too close to the homeland they want to escape and because a larger camp does n't appeal to them , Ebanks said .
Even if all 900 accept , that still would leave about 250 refugees .
The Cayman government has decided to grant asylum to a small , as-yet-undetermined number of Cubans who fled political persecution , Ebanks said .
Twenty-four refugees have asked to return to Cuba and will be flown back , probably within two weeks , Ebanks said .
As a last resort , the Cayman government could repatriate those who remain , she said .
`` We 're really not heaving a sigh of relief .
Not for ourselves and not for the Cubans , '' Ebanks said .
A collector paid 6,325 pounds -LRB- dlrs 9,687 -RRB- on Friday for the only known letter from French author Alain Fournier to the woman on whom he based the heroine of his novel `` Le Grand Meaulnes . ''
The 10-page love letter , written in 1905 when Fournier was 19 , was sold anonymously and bought by Roy Davids , a British-based dealer and private collector .
`` Le Grand Meaulnes '' was the only novel by Fournier , who was killed in action during World War I -- September 1914 , a year after the book 's publication .
The letter , with an envelope marked Y. H. , is addressed to `` Yvonne '' -- and her identity remains a mystery .
The seller of the letter was not identified .
Fournier referred to her as `` my first Yvonne '' -- one of two Yvonnes whom he admired from afar , fell in love with and followed at a distance .
Both women provided aspects of his heroine Yvonne de Galais .
Lucien Bouchard , the charismatic Quebec separatist who leads the opposition in Canada 's House of Commons , lost his leg to a flesh-eating disease but doctors said his life was not in danger .
Bouchard , 55 , vowed to continue his political career , dedicated to making Quebec an independent country .
`` Mr. Bouchard has greatly improved over the past 12 hours , '' Dr. Patrick d'Amico told a news conference at Montreal 's St. Luc Hospital on Friday , a day after Bouchard 's leg was amputated .
D'Amico said Bouchard underwent three operations since being admitted to the hospital Tuesday .
If no further complications occur , the doctor said , Bouchard should recover fully in about three or four months .
Bouchard was struck by a rare disease known as necrotizing myositis .
It is similar to necrotizing fasciitis , the `` flesh-eating disease '' that caused alarm in Britain this year , but attacks muscle rather than connective tissue .
Dr. Francois Lamothe , a specialist in microbiology who also appeared at the news conference , said the disease is caused by the streptococcus A bacterium .
It is fatal in 80 percent of the cases .
The bacteria are common and infection usually results in sore throats or tonsillitis .
But in about one case in a million , the bacterium turns deadly .
Bouchard , a former Conservative Cabinet minister , bolted former Prime Minister Brian Mulroney 's government in 1990 and formed his own party .
The new party became , effectively , the national arm of the Parti Quebecois , the provincial party dedicated to the secession of Quebec .
In the 1993 federal elections , the Bloc Quebecois won 54 seats to become the official opposition to the ruling Liberals in the House of Commons .
Few wanted to speculate on what the absence of Bouchard would have on the political scene or a referendum on independence expected next year in Quebec .
`` Next week we 'll work with a great sense of solidarity , '' said Gilles Duceppe , the Bloc Quebecois whip .
`` We 'll just wait for Mr. Bouchard to come back . ''
Prime Minister Jean Chretien , on a trip to France , expressed a `` sincere wish for a rapid return of his health . ''
