The Muslim call to prayer drifted into Hanna Hashab 's garden cottage as Yever Rainesch surveyed the living room decorated with crocheted doilies and plastic red roses .
`` How much does it cost to buy a house in the village ? ''
asked Mrs. Rainesch , who immigrated from Russia to this Arab village in northern Israel .
Rainesch was interested in property , but she was invited to visit Hashab 's home with more grand visions in mind .
She was introduced to Hashab , an Israeli Arab , as part wide-ranging Labor Party attempt to change attitudes toward Arabs and shore up support for its peace policies , especially among young voters and immigrants from the former Soviet Union .
Russian immigrants voted 2-to-1 for Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin 's ruling Labor Party in 1992 , when it won a narrow victory over the right-wing Likud bloc .
With the next elections less than two years away , Likud has pulled even with Labor in recent polls and Labor leaders fear that one of Israel 's most powerful constituencies will swing the balance of power to the right in 1996 .
By then , the immigrants will make up 10 percent of Israel 's population of 5.4 million and could theoretically control 12 swing seats in the 120-member Parliament .
Aware of that possible electoral clout , immigrant leader Natan Sharansky says he may form a party to run in 1996 .
`` The immigrants in general feel frustrated and disappointed by the government 's treatment of their absorption , '' Sharansky said .
`` More and more immigrants feel alienated and like a second class in Israel . ''
Past elections indicate Russians almost automatically vote against the establishment and carry anti-Muslim sentiment from ethnic conflicts at home .
They are also generally suspicious of land-for-peace deals .
In an effort to change those attitudes , The Golda Meir Association , an educational institute close to the Labor Party , is taking immigrants such as Rainesch and introducing them to Israeli Arabs in their daily lives .
Earlier this month , 15 immigrants toured Kalansua 's mosque and flower hothouses , attended an Arab-style lunch and met with villagers in their homes .
Addressing the visitors at a trade union clubhouse , union secretary Asad Hadiga said : `` We are all Muslims .
We support peace as the way of Islam . ''
However , the Russians were not so easily reassured .
One woman said that since the bloody October bus bombing in Tel Aviv by a Muslim militant , she feels afraid whenever she sees an Arab .
`` We Arabs are not terrorists , '' responded one middle-aged Arab in a checkered shirt .
Another troublesome group for Labor are the 400,000 younger , first-time voters for whom Israeli control over the West Bank , the Golan Heights and Arab east Jerusalem is a fact of life .
Israel captured the lands in the 1967 Mideast war .
`` They are vulnerable to right-wing principles of having political and historical , if not religious , rights to the land , '' said Stanley Ringler , a Labor official .
In an effort to sway those voters , Labor started sending reserve generals and lawmakers to schools to explain land-for-peace policies .
Labor legislator Ori Orr , a reserve major general , kicked off the campaign this month by fielding questions at an Israeli high school .
One student questioned Rabin 's credibility , noting that during the 1992 campaign the prime minister spoke of holding onto the Golan Heights , but has since proposed a significant withdrawal .
Orr said Syria would first have to make concessions on water rights and its military presence in Lebanon before Israel would even consider giving back land .
`` If there are no answers to these questions , there wo n't be a peace treaty , '' Orr reassured the students .
The Toronto Blue Jays said Friday they intend to honor Ontario law and wo n't use replacement players in the SkyDome if owners start the season without striking Major League players .
Ontario Labor Minister Shirley Coppen said this week the province 's law barring replacement workers applies to the baseball team .
`` As far as she can determine , the Blue Jays fall under this legislation , '' Blue Jays chairman Peter Widdrington said Friday by telephone .
`` If it 's the law , we 're not going to try to obviate the law .
We will follow the law . ''
The Montreal Expos would be able to use replacement players because Quebec law applies only to unions certified in that province .
`` This is not a certified union and we have very right to do so , '' Expos president Claude Brochu said .
Major League players , upset over proposals to limit their salaries , went on strike Aug. 12 , eventually forcing owners to cancel the rest of the season and the World Series .
Boston Red Sox chief executive officer John Harrington , management 's chief labor negotiator , said Tuesday that owners intend to use replacement if the union 's strike continues into the start of the season next spring .
`` I do n't want to get into the whole discussion of replacement players , '' acting commissioner Bud Selig said Friday .
`` That 's an option that at some point if we do n't have an agreement ... we 'll have to consider . ''
Management lawyer Chuck O'Connor said the American League would have to decide how to handle the Blue Jays ' situation if other teams use replacements and Toronto ca n't play at home .
But O'Connor said management lawyers still believe it is possible to use replacements in Toronto .
`` We have n't completely foreclosed it yet , '' he said .
`` Our lawyers in Canada believe something can be done . ''
Players and owners , who are n't scheduled to meet again until next Friday , both are preparing for the possibility of replacements .
The Major League Baseball Players Association asked the U.S. Labor Department on Nov. 14 to certify the strike .
If the department grants the request , non-U.S. citizens could n't obtain visas to play in the majors unless they were on 40-man rosters Aug. 11 , the day before the strike began .
U.S. Employment Services , a division of Labor Department , will make the decision after owners repond .
`` The importation of foreign labor for the purposes of breaking a strike is fundamentally inconsistent with the code of federal regulations that INS has issued , '' said Eugene Orza , the union 's No. 2 official .
Immigration and Naturalization Service regulations state : `` If the Secretary of Labor certifies to the -LRB- INS -RRB- commissioner that a strike ... is in progress in the occupation and at the place where the beneficiary is to be employed or trained , and that the employment of training of the beneficiary would adversely affect the wages and working conditions of U.S. citizens and lawful resident-workers , a petition ... shall be denied . ''
Labor Department spokesman Camille Johnston said it was unclear how long it would take for the agency to respond to the union 's request for strike certification .
Some management officials , speaking on the condition they not be identified , have said in recent weeks that they expect Latin players will break ranks and report to spring training .
The union says there 's no evidence to support that notion .
`` I have never heard anything like that discussed , '' Selig said .
Hundreds of angry Haitians menaced a neighborhood gunman after multinational soldiers freed him Friday , prompting the foreign soldiers to return to save him two hours later .
Samuel Chery , who had terrorized a neighborhood in this Port-au-Prince suburb after the September 1991 military coup that ousted President Jean-Bertrand Aristide , had been held for nearly two months after U.S. soldiers arrested him .
Chery , known as `` Ti Samuel , '' was an `` attache , '' one of thousands of thugs who had Haitian military support to beat or kill Aristide supporters .
He was freed by foreign troops at 2 p.m. , prompting uncomprehending screams from neighbors .
Hundreds of people gathered , grabbing sticks or carrying machetes .
They surrounded Chery 's home .
He had thrown rocks at them and locked his door .
A Humvee carrying foreign soldiers arrived two hours later and took away Chery .
Telephones were not functioning at the U.S. military 's Joint Information Bureau late Friday , and it was not clear why Chery was freed or where he was being held .
Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsay Clark accused the United States on Friday of protecting members of the right-wing terror group FRAPH even after intervening to return Aristide .
The Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti says it is converting into a political organization .
A FRAPH leader , Emmanuel Constant , renounced violence at a U.S.-arranged news conference two months ago .
`` The same forces that planned the coup '' are maintaining the level of violence , Clark told reporters after a five-day fact-finding mission of his Haiti Commission human rights group .
`` The longer the criminals go unpunished , the more likely it is that the people will take justice into their own hands , '' said lawyer Michael Ratner , another commission member and director of the New York-based Center for Constitutional Rights .
The U.N. civilian mission in a Nov. 22 communique said `` a certain degree of violence prevailed until the end of October .
Since then , without having entirely disappeared , violent incidents are much rarer . ''
The mission reported , however , that many people believe `` that the disarmament and dismantlement of groups which were part of the former repressive apparatus have been insufficient . ''
