The Muslim call to prayer drifted into Hanna Hashab 's garden cottage as Yever Rainesch surveyed the living room decorated with crocheted doilies and plastic red roses .
`` How much does it cost to buy a house in the village ? ''
asked Mrs. Rainesch , who immigrated from Russia to this Arab village in northern Israel .
Rainesch was interested in property , but she was invited to visit Hashab 's home with more grand visions in mind .
She was introduced to Hashab , an Israeli Arab , as part wide-ranging Labor Party attempt to change attitudes toward Arabs and shore up support for its peace policies , especially among young voters and immigrants from the former Soviet Union .
Russian immigrants voted 2-to-1 for Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin 's ruling Labor Party in 1992 , when it won a narrow victory over the right-wing Likud bloc .
With the next elections less than two years away , Likud has pulled even with Labor in recent polls and Labor leaders fear that one of Israel 's most powerful constituencies will swing the balance of power to the right in 1996 .
By then , the immigrants will make up 10 percent of Israel 's population of 5.4 million and could theoretically control 12 swing seats in the 120-member Parliament .
Aware of that possible electoral clout , immigrant leader Natan Sharansky says he may form a party to run in 1996 .
`` The immigrants in general feel frustrated and disappointed by the government 's treatment of their absorption , '' Sharansky said .
`` More and more immigrants feel alienated and like a second class in Israel . ''
Past elections indicate Russians almost automatically vote against the establishment and carry anti-Muslim sentiment from ethnic conflicts at home .
They are also generally suspicious of land-for-peace deals .
In an effort to change those attitudes , The Golda Meir Association , an educational institute close to the Labor Party , is taking immigrants such as Rainesch and introducing them to Israeli Arabs in their daily lives .
Earlier this month , 15 immigrants toured Kalansua 's mosque and flower hothouses , attended an Arab-style lunch and met with villagers in their homes .
Addressing the visitors at a trade union clubhouse , union secretary Asad Hadiga said : `` We are all Muslims .
We support peace as the way of Islam . ''
However , the Russians were not so easily reassured .
One woman said that since the bloody October bus bombing in Tel Aviv by a Muslim militant , she feels afraid whenever she sees an Arab .
`` We Arabs are not terrorists , '' responded one middle-aged Arab in a checkered shirt .
Another troublesome group for Labor are the 400,000 younger , first-time voters for whom Israeli control over the West Bank , the Golan Heights and Arab east Jerusalem is a fact of life .
Israel captured the lands in the 1967 Mideast war .
`` They are vulnerable to right-wing principles of having political and historical , if not religious , rights to the land , '' said Stanley Ringler , a Labor official .
In an effort to sway those voters , Labor started sending reserve generals and lawmakers to schools to explain land-for-peace policies .
Labor legislator Ori Orr , a reserve major general , kicked off the campaign this month by fielding questions at an Israeli high school .
One student questioned Rabin 's credibility , noting that during the 1992 campaign the prime minister spoke of holding onto the Golan Heights , but has since proposed a significant withdrawal .
Orr said Syria would first have to make concessions on water rights and its military presence in Lebanon before Israel would even consider giving back land .
`` If there are no answers to these questions , there wo n't be a peace treaty , '' Orr reassured the students .
In a small , windowless room in public school No. 728 lies what 14-year-old Anton calls Russia 's `` future '' -- the school 's only computer .
At School 728 , after spending hours in poorly heated classrooms where they have to share tattered Soviet-era textbooks , students come to the `` computer closet '' to work on the school 's innovative on-line newspaper .
Or to send e-mail to students in Minnesota .
Or to practice their French on an electronic conference with European schoolchildren .
Like most of Russia 's roads , its information highway is still ridden with potholes and Soviet-style dead-end alleys .
Nevertheless , the next generation of Russian leaders is building its own onramps and starting to cruise .
`` The kids may not understand yet what this access , this communication , means for them , '' said Volodya Pilipchuk , the school 's computer adviser and a former 728 student .
`` But 10 years from now , they will . ''
Pilipchuk 's students have joined the millions of people -- from New York businessmen to human rights activists in East Timor -- who communicate via a worldwide web of tens of thousands of interconnected computer networks .
For Anton and his classmates , it does n't seem to matter that they were born in a society famous for restricting such free information flows .
Or that some of their parents built careers on imposing those restrictions .
What matters to these kids is the computer itself .
Dozens of students huddle around its single screen during breaks , as Pilipchuk struggles to ration out computer time to eager users .
The well-worn machine is especially popular among the students here , most of whom , unlike many of their U.S. counterparts , had never seen a computer before this project began .
Olga Galkina , the founder of the school 's on-line newspaper , says the project is aimed at `` helping kids understand their global importance . ''
And ultimately , she hopes , these children may be the ones to guide the rest of the former Soviet Union into the information age .
Much of Russia 's wealth of computer expertise has been lured to the West , leaving a relatively small cadre of dedicated but underfunded programmers to bring new technologies to this vast nation .
In the meantime , the kids are just having fun .
`` Look , I can type in English , '' boasted Sasha , a 12-year-old in an L.A. Raiders sweatshirt .
`` Even my older brother ca n't do that . ''
The latest issue of `` Southern Zone , '' the on-line version of the school paper , included articles on topics from a nature reserve in Russia 's Far North to the music of David Lee Roth .
The issue was posted on the local network Glasnet , which is connected to the worldwide Internet meganetwork , allowing computers around the world access to the newspaper .
The latest publication has evoked responses from users from Holland to Minnesota .
`` The messages from the American kids are funny , '' said Alyosha , tugging on his long blond bangs .
`` Someone asked if Russia was bigger than California . ''
These kids are also proving that the information highway does not have to remain a limited access tollroad , affordable for only an elite few .
The school 's computer , a standard IBM-compatible 386 with an internal modem , is on long-term loan from John Whitely , a sociology professor at the University of California at Irvine .
Whitely loaned the machine to Galkina for the on-line newspaper project in 1992 .
And Glasnet , a non-profit Russian computer network , donated an e-mail account to the school , bringing the total cost of the project to just a few dollars per year -- less than the budget for the on-paper version of the school newspaper .
The project is a bargain even for public schools like this one .
Russia 's cash-strapped public education system is struggling to support its 65,000 schools , where teachers earn about 120,000 rubles -LRB- dlrs 40 -RRB- a month .
School 728 is just one of several seeds of hope .
At least 300 Russian schools have access to e-mail accounts , at least 250 of which are outside of Moscow .
`` The numbers are still not high , for a country this size , '' said Galkina , who is now working on a project to connect disabled children in Russia to on-line services .
`` But Russia , like the United States , wo n't become computer literate overnight . ''
Computer literacy is still not a top priority for School 728 's administrators , who pay little attention to the cramped computer closet .
`` Yes , I know there 's something going on over there , '' said Nina Mikhailova , head of the student relations department , in the opposite wing of the school .
`` But it does n't concern us .
We do n't use computers over here . ''
The administration may be wary , but its pupils are already making plans .
`` I want to be a programmer , '' Anton said , `` because the world ca n't survive without computers . ''
Cuban exile leaders here lauded a Clinton administration decision Friday to admit Cuban children and their parents now detained at U.S. camps , but others criticized the change as politically motivated .
`` We have seen it coming , '' said Andres Gomez , head of the exile group , the Antonio Maceo Brigade .
`` -LRB- Clinton -RRB- wants to diffuse the resentment that exists among the Cubans in this city . ''
The decision announced in Washington by Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris Meissner comes one week before the Summit of the Americas , when 34 heads of state will convene in Miami .
The policy would allow about 8,000 Cuban children and parents now held in Panama and at Guantanamo Bay , Cuba , to enter the United States if they have financial sponsorship .
Cesar Odio , Miami 's city manager , said funding would be raised to cover relocation , education , health and living costs for the refugees .
`` We are working together with the government to see that ... they have full sponsorship and they are not a burden on the community , '' said Odio .
The change will not affect the status of at least 20,000 adult refugees in the camps .
Odio denied a connection to the summit , saying negotiations had been under way with the federal government on this agreement since September .
`` This has nothing to do with the summit , '' he said at a news conference early Friday .
`` And if it has something to do with it , so what ?
We want the children helped . ''
The detention of the Cubans began in August , when President Clinton ordered all Cuban boat people picked up at sea to be sent to the U.S. naval base at Guantanamo Bay .
Other camps were later set up in Panama .
Under an deal reached in September with Cuban President Fidel Castro , the United States agreed to give 20,000 visas if Castro cracked down on illegal migration from his shores .
The Cubans being detained were not to be allowed into the United States under the agreement .
They could remain at Guantanamo , return to Cuba or apply for asylum through a third country .
Bosnian Serbs promised Friday to release hundreds of U.N. peacekeepers and allow the free movement of some U.N. convoys as the chief U.N. envoy tried to salvage what was left of the ailing U.N. mission in Bosnia .
Earlier , two anti-tank missiles slammed into the presidency building in Sarajevo just minutes before U.N. envoy Yasushi Akashi arrived for talks with the Muslim-led Bosnian government .
U.N. officials said the missiles appeared to come from Serb positions , but the Serbs said the government attacked itself to cause trouble .
It was yet another sign of Serb contempt for the peacekeeping effort , which has virtually ground to a halt .
The Serb rebels have stopped U.N. convoys , attacked a U.N.-declared `` safe area , '' and taken peacekeepers hostage .
In Brussels , Belgium , U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and European foreign ministers endorsed a U.S. plan for a cease-fire that would lead to peace talks in the 21\/2 - year-old war .
The plan would also grant the Serbs their main aim in the conflict : the right to ties with Serb-led Yugoslavia .
The Serbs on Friday released 70 Dutch peacekeepers who had been held a week , but more than 300 other U.N. peacekeepers remained hostage as insurance against NATO airstrikes .
Akashi , who met with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic at Serb headquarters in Pale , east of Sarajevo , said he was assured that Ukrainian peacekeepers held in northern Bosnia would be released , Dutch and British supply convoys detained since Saturday would be freed , and Bangladeshi peacekeepers stranded in Bihac would be allowed to receive supplies .
Karadzic said the Serbs and the U.N. `` are moving fast to normalization of our relations , '' but he issued a veiled warning against NATO .
`` We would like to see skies clear of our aircraft and of NATO aircraft , '' he said .
`` If NATO is flying around there is more risk of misunderstandings and incidents . ''
Under current rules of engagement , the U.N. must request the NATO airstrikes , although NATO planes can defend themselves against attack without U.N. approval .
U.N. officials fear that could escalate tensions .
Akashi had met earlier with Bosnian government and military leaders in Sarevejo .
Two wire-guided missiles hit the presidency building minutes before he arrived for the talks .
One destroyed the office of Miro Lazovic , an ethnic Serb member of Bosnia 's collective presidency .
Three missiles hit nearby buildings while the meeting went on .
There were no injuries .
The Bosnian government blasted the United Nations for not using force to halt fighting at Bihac , the embattled government-held enclave in the northwest .
Serb forces have seized 30 percent to 40 percent of the `` safe area , '' and fighting continued there Friday .
U.S. Ambassador to Germany Charles Redman held talks in Sarajevo with Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic and Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic on the U.S. peace plan .
Redman helped draft an earlier international plan that the Serbs rejected .
The war began when Serbs rebelled against a vote for independence from Yugoslavia by Bosnia-Herzegovina 's Muslims and Croats .
More than 200,000 people are dead or missing in the war , and the Serbs have seized 70 percent of Bosnia .
Following the secession since 1991 of Slovenia , Croatia , Bosnia and Macedonia , Yugoslavia now comprises Serbia and Montenegro .
Serb nationalists in Yugoslavia , Croatia and Bosnia have pressed for a unified `` Greater Serbia . ''
The rejected peace plan denied Serbs the right to links with Yugoslavia as punishment for starting the war , but allowed Bosnia 's Croats and Muslims the right to ties with Croatia .
The old plan also granted the Serbs 49 percent of Bosnia -- a condition the new plan also contains .
Akashi had more success than U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali , who was rebuffed Wednesday when he tried to meet with Bosnian Serb leaders .
Boutros-Ghali said afterwards that intransigence by the warring sides might force the U.N. mission to withdraw .
Seventy Dutch peacekeepers arrived in Zagreb , Croatia , after being released from a seven-day detention by the Serbs in eastern Bosnia , U.N. officials said .
But Serbs continued to hold about 20 other Dutch peacekeepers , plus several hundred of Britons , Ukrainians and Canadians , at various points throughout Bosnia .
U.N. spokesman Thant Myint-U said Akashi also wanted to discuss the fighting around Bihac with Karadzic .
The United Nations is trying to broker a cease-fire there .
Machine-gun and small arms fire was reported on the outskirts of Bihac , U.N. officials said .
The heaviest fighting appeared concentrated around Velika Kladusa , north of Bihac , where Serbs were apparently closing in on the government army 's 5th Corps .
The Bosnian Serbs , backed by Serbs from neighboring Croatia , want to wipe out the 5th Corps , which launched a briefly successful offensive from the Bihac enclave in late October .
