A U.S. Army inspection found numerous deficiencies with a chemical-weapons disposal plant only a year before its scheduled opening .
The report by the Army Inspector General found security gaps in and around the site in Tooele , Utah , along with an inadequate system for containing spills , and problems with tracking the deadly bombs and shells .
An Army response attached to the report emphasizes that all the problems raised by the inspection will be addressed before the Tooele Chemical Agent Disposal Facility opens .
`` The Army is committed to ensuring that security , safety and environmental protection are not compromised at the facility . ''
The report , the Army stated , was `` aimed at identifying , in advance , problems that must be addressed before the TOCDF becomes operational . ''
The Washington Post reported on the inspector general 's findings in Friday 's editions .
Destruction of the vast U.S. chemical-weapons arsenal , a holdover from the Cold War , is part of a broader arms reduction effort and involves parallel actions by Russia .
After studying a variety of disposal methods , the Army settled on destruction by incineration .
Eventually the Army plans to operate nine disposal incinerators .
They are part of a dlrs 10 billion Army effort to comply with congressional orders to eliminate the stockpile .
Although plans for the incinerator are proceeding , environmentalists continue to criticize the destruction method , predicting toxic leaks .
Among other findings , the inspector general found that : -- Equipment such as fork lifts and cranes that will be used to move chemical weapons stockpiles are not marked with capacity ratings , creating the risk they could be overloaded .
-- There are no final plans on what to do with the solid residue of incineration .
-- The Army has not yet settled on a system of marking and identifying each shell , bomb or other chemical-weapon container .
-- During testing of one chemical-handling facility , `` a large amount of spillage was collected that exceeded the capacity of the secondary containment vessel . ''
This spill was not toxic but once the facility opens , it will handle toxic chemicals .
-- The perimeter fence could be penetrated by intruders either by cutting through or digging under the barrier .
-- Some windows and doors on buildings that will contain chemical weapons are inadequate and drainage structures and culverts leading out of the facility were not equipped with fences or grates to prevent intruders .
Canada will support former Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari to be head of the future World Trade Organization , Canada 's deputy prime minister said Friday .
`` We think Mr. Salinas did an incredible job in bringing the new face of Mexico to the people of the world , and we hope that he will have a chance to continue to do that as president of the WTO , '' said Deputy Prime Minister Sheila Copps .
Copps was here to attend Thursday 's inauguration of Mexico 's new president Ernesto Zedillo .
`` President Salinas will be known for bringing business and economic skills to a country moving away from government ownership to private ownership and I think that Dr. Zedillo will actually ensure that economic direction is shared by the people , '' she said .
The World Trade Organization will replace the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade , or GATT , on Jan 1 .
Most countries in the Western Hemisphere are backing Salinas to head the new organization .
Europe and its former African colonies are firmly behind Renato Ruggiero , a one-time Italian trade minister , while Japan and its Asian neighbors are lobbying for Trade Minister Kim Chul-su of South Korea .
Copps also said she was encouraged by Zedillo 's promises to raise Mexico 's standard of living and to increase public faith in the Mexican justice system after a series of high-profile political assassinations .
`` Mexico 's had a rough , turbulent year , and I think he gave the right signals to the people and certainly to the international community , '' she said .
`` The message he gave yesterday was very clear : that he 's there to serve all the people , that he wants to rebuild the public 's confidence in the integrity of the democratic system , '' said Copps .
Zedillo will meet Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien at next week 's Summit of the Americas in Miami , Copps said .
The three nations will also discuss the possible inclusion of Chile in the NAFTA free trade agreement linking Canada , the United States and Mexico , she said .
An express train headed from eastern Hungary to Budapest derailed Friday and slammed into a station building , killing at least 24 people .
At least 60 people were injured , said National Police spokesman Laszlo Garamvoelgyi .
The accident occurred at Szajol , about 40 miles southeast of the Hungarian capital , when the second car of an express train derailed and dragged three other cars off the tracks .
Some of the overturned carriages smashed into the station building , railway officials said .
`` There was a tremendous explosion , like the end of the world , '' a railway employee who witnessed the accident said in a telephone interview .
People were still buried in the wreckage more than four hours after the crash , said the employee , who spoke on condition of anonymity .
State television showed pictures of battered and broken railway cars covered in bricks and rescue crews dragging bloody bodies from the wreckage .
Rescue workers said part of the destroyed building held sleeping quarters for railway personnel and their families .
Defense Minister Gyoergy Keleti said dogs normally used to locate victims of mining disasters had found three children survivors who were dug from the rubble .
The death toll was expected to go higher , with temperatures below freezing and some people still trapped in the wreckage , said Garamvoelgyi , the police spokesman .
Doctors at a hospital near Szolnok , close to the site of the accident , said they admitted 26 injured people .
Other hospitals also took in injured .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 100 miles east of Budapest .
Gold in Hong Kong dropped U.S. dlrs 3.28 an ounce on Saturday , opening at U.S. dlrs 376.25 , compared to Friday 's close of U.S. dlrs 379.53 .
Boris Yeltsin was bad luck for Russian tennis on Friday , and Sweden 's Davis Cup team hopes to see him again soon .
The Russian president and his entourage interrupted play at a critical moment in the tense fifth set of Stefan Edberg 's match against Alexander Volkov .
Edberg , energized by the pause , ended Volkov 's come-from-behind drive and led Sweden to a 2-0 singles sweep , winning 6-4 , 6-2 , 6-7 -LRB- 2-7 -RRB- , 0-6 , 8-6 .
Magnus Larsson , ranked 19th by the ATP Tour , went on to defeat No. 11-ranked Yevgeny Kafelnikov in another five set thriller , 6-0 , 6-2 , 3-6 , 2-6 , 6-3 .
The losses disappointed the whistling , foot-stomping hometown crowd of 12,000 at Olympic Stadium , and likely doomed Russia 's chances of becoming the first unseeded team to win the Davis Cup .
On Saturday , Kafelnikov and Andrei Olhovskiy must upset the top-ranked doubles team and recently crowned ATP Tour doubles champions Jonas Bjorkman and Jan Apell to keep their hopes alive and send the best-of-five match to Sunday 's reverse singles .
Kafelnikov accused Yeltsin of ruining Volkov 's concentration .
Unlike other fans , a smiling and waving Yeltsin took his seat without waiting for the brief break when the players change sides .
`` Do you remember what the score was when the president arrived ? ''
`` It was 5-5 .
Is there a switch then ?
What sensible person in a decisive game like this , with the score 5-5 , would do something like that in such a tense situation ? ''
Volkov , however , did not blame Yeltsin .
`` I could n't have failed to notice when the president arrived , '' he said .
`` -LRB- But -RRB- I can say it interfered with my game as much as rain outside would have , because I had lost my serve by then . ''
Edberg said he did n't realize until later that it was Yeltsin who had caused the delay .
But considering the outcome , `` maybe I should thank Boris for coming in , '' he said .
Larsson said he hopes to see more of Yeltsin .
`` I wish him welcome tomorrow for doubles , '' he said .
`` But maybe he can come in during the changeover next time . ''
Volkov held match point on his serve leading 5-4 when Edberg sent a backhand down the line to send it to deuce .
He went on to break Volkov and then earned the critical break in the final game .
`` Maybe he played it a little safe , '' Edberg said about facing match point .
`` I took charge of the match in that game .
I took a few chances and it paid off . ''
After winning the first two sets , the seventh-ranked Edberg appeared en route to an easy victory .
But buoyed by the flag-waving , cheering crowd , Volkov battled back in the third set , punctuated with a crowd-pleasing ace to take the tiebreaker .
Volkov , 27 , then dominated Edberg in the fourth set with devastating passing shots and seemed set to take the match , serving for the victory in the final set .
`` I needed to kick myself , especially in the fifth set , '' Edberg said .
`` I was a little bit depressed .
I had the match in my hand and became defensive ... I felt I was getting closer and closer in every game in the fifth set . ''
Friday 's loss was Kafelnikov 's first in eight Davis Cup matches .
His only other loss was in his debut to Germany 's Michael Stich in March 1993 .
Kafelnikov said he felt `` mental and psychological pressure '' after Volkov 's dramatic defeat , and said he said he injured his left wrist in the second game of the last set .
He strained the same wrist last week .
`` It did n't really hurt but I felt very insecure .
I could n't hit slices , '' he said .
Beth Daniel and Davis Love III , a consistently strong team in this tournament , shared the second-round lead Friday with Helen Alfredsson and Robert Gamez in the J.C. Penney Golf Classic .
The two teams are at 12-under-par and hold a two-stroke lead in this event pairing LPGA players with PGA Tour or Senior PGA Tour pros .
Daniel and Love teamed for the first time in this event in 1990 and won .
The next year they finished third and in 1992 they were runners-up .
They did not play together last year when Love missed the tournament for the birth of his son .
They shot a first-day 65 in best-ball play at Innisbrook Resort Copperhead Course and another 65 Friday in alternate-stroke competition .
That puts them even with the 66-64 produced by Alfredsson and Gamez .
One stroke back of the co-leaders are Amy Alcott-Robin Freeman and Laura Davies-David Feherty .
Two behind are Liselotte Neumann-Tony Jacklin , Jane Geddes-Brian Claar and JoAnne Carner-Jim Albus .
`` Actually , I do n't think we 've played that great yet , really , '' Love said .
`` We 've had a couple of bursts , like one day here and one day there , but overall , we have n't played great . ''
Friday 's round was produced with six birdies and no bogeys .
The closest they came to losing a stroke was on No. 18 and Daniel saved par with a 6-foot -LRB- 2-meter -RRB- putt .
`` We both make a lot of birdies when we play our own ball , '' Daniel said .
`` Both of us hit a lot of greens .
So that 's a good combination .
And Davis hits it long and I 'm fairly long for our tour .
That 's a good combination , too .
We have a length advantage which means we 're hitting shorter clubs to the green .
That helps , too . ''
Alfredsson and Gamez kept pace on the strength of eight birdies and one bogey .
Gamez is coming off victories the last two weeks at Pebble Beach in California and at the Casio World Open in Japan .
He traveled 31 hours from Japan before arriving at the tournament Monday evening .
`` I 'm just getting my legs back from the trip and it showed a little big on the back nine , '' he said .
Nonetheless , their 64 equaled the day 's low round .
`` When we 've hit it close , we 've made the putt , '' Alfredsson said .
`` We 're having a lot of fun .
Usually during the season it 's a lot more serious .
This is a great break from the normal routine . ''
President Clinton on Friday ordered that no U. S , government funds be spent on human embryos created for research purposes only .
But Clinton did not specifically forbid federal financial support for research on human embryos that originate from in vitro fertilization -- the so-called test-tube baby technique .
`` I do not believe that federal funds should be used to support the creation of human embryos for research purposes , '' Clinton said .
His order Friday was far less sweeping than previous restrictions imposed by Presidents Reagan and Bush .
`` I have directed that the National Institutes of Health not allocate any resources '' for studies of human embryos that were created for research purposes , Clinton said .
White House press secretary Dee Dee Myers , asked to interpret Clinton 's terse statement , said `` it should be interpreted very narrowly . ''
Asked if the statement would permit federally funded research using embryos that were surplus from IVF clinics , she said : `` The president 's statement does n't outlaw that . ''
`` That 's the line that 's been drawn , '' said a senior White House official who asked not to be named publicly .
In his statement , Clinton said that research on fertilized human eggs `` raises profound ethical and moral questions as well as issues concerning the appropriate allocation of federal funds . ''
