`` I was jolted by the crash and I woke up , '' said Melissa Selosia , who was on her way to Mindanao Island , 780 kilometers -LRB- 485 miles -RRB- south of Manila for Christmas .
`` I grabbed a life jacket and made for the upper deck and then I jumped into the water . ''
The ferry was embedded in mud in about 14 fathoms -LRB- 84 feet -RRB- of water .
Four teams of coast guard and navy men were searching the ship for bodies believed trapped in the cabins , Samante said .
About 50 coast guard , navy and commercial sea vessels were involved in the search effort Saturday , he said .
`` Considering that all -LRB- passengers of the Cebu -RRB- were wearing life jackets , we are hopeful to find survivors , '' said Samante .
`` In fact , two of the survivors yesterday were found by fishermen near a coastal town . ''
Seaman Angel Espidido , one of 27 coast guard divers who joined navy frogmen Friday in the dive , said there were bodies inside the cabins he could see through portholes but that the divers were unable to open the doors .
Seaman Hermogenes Guilaran said he recovered the bodies of two elderly women and a boy who were trapped at a railing on the side of the ferry .
The 2,452-ton Cebu City had left Manila bound for the resort area of Tagbilaran , the capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- to the southeast , a 28-hour boat trip .
The ferry , usually used by families and small business owners , sank 30 minutes after it and the 12,500-ton freighter collided .
William Lines said the Cebu City had a capacity of 800 passengers .
It sank near the town of Rosario , about 50 kilometers -LRB- 35 miles -RRB- southwest of Manila in Cavite province .
The Philippines ' worst peacetime ferry disaster was in December 1987 , when 4,341 people died in the collision of the ferry Dona Paz with the oil tanker Vector off Mindoro Island , about 130 kilometers -LRB- 80 miles -RRB- south of Manila .
From opening doors to logging physical fitness tests and taking in a bit of shopping in between .
Singapore 's 275,000 regular and part-time soldiers will soon be able to do all this and more just by using a credit-card sized card that will replace their military identity cards within three years .
Releasing the first such Singapore Armed Forces Card on Friday , Defense Minister Lee Boon Yang said it was part of his ministry 's move towards creating a truly `` intelligent organization '' by the year 2001 .
The Defense Ministry is the first organization in Singapore , a prosperous city-state riding a high-technology boom , to use the smart-card technology for such wide ranging uses .
The plastic card has built in processing and data storage capabilities that will capture vital statistics about a serviceman besides other useful information such as drug allergies or vacation times .
The card would be used like any other credit card by sliding its magnetic strip through a reader or slotting it into computer-linked machines .
In army units , the card will allow the booking of conference rooms and auditoriums , access to parking lots , unlocking doors , logging onto computers and buying drinks from vending machines .
In the future , it would also act as a bank charge card in supermarkets .
The card is also a portable electronic score card for physical fitness tests .
For example , soldiers would slot the card into a computer and start doing chin-ups on a bar .
The results will be recorded electronically and stored in a training and manpower database computer .
Singapore , with 3 million people , has 50,000 regular troops in the army , navy and air force , plus 250,000 reservists .
Military services is compulsory for all males .
Seattle Seahawks tackle Mike Frier probably will never walk again after breaking his neck in a car crash that also injured two teammates , a doctor said Friday .
The issue of who was driving the car Thursday night remained uncertain after agents for the two other players -- Chris Warren and Lamar Smith -- contradicted police reports that Warren was at the wheel .
Smith 's agent , Eugene Parker , said Smith was driving .
Rick Schaeffer , a Baltimore lawyer and Warren 's agent , said his client was not driving and was not the owner of the car .
Asked why police would say Warren was the driver , Schaeffer replied , `` The best I can tell you is that it was a misunderstanding . ''
Police detective Ed Malkowski told The Journal-American the preliminary investigation points to Warren as the driver , but they are looking into the possibility it was Smith .
Malkowski confirmed the car was registered to Smith .
Warren , reached at home , refused to comment .
Kirkland police said after the accident that Warren , a running back , was driving , had been arrested for investigation of vehicular assault and was released on his own recognizance .
Detective Jim O'Toole said Friday there is `` reason to believe alcohol was involved . ''
He said blood samples were taken only from Warren .
Warren , 27 , was treated for two fractured ribs and released early Friday .
He was listed as questionable for Sunday 's game against Indianapolis in the Kingdome .
Smith , 24 , a rookie running back , sustained a chip fracture in his spine and an ankle sprain .
He was released from the hospital Friday .
Frier , 25 , `` almost certainly will be wheelchair dependent , '' Dr. Michael Schlitt told a news conference .
Frier has no use of his legs or hands and only minimal muscle function in his upper arms .
He has a broken and dislocated neck between the fifth and sixth vertebrae and his spinal cord was severely injured .
`` The likelihood that he will play football again is zero , '' Schlitt said .
`` The likelihood of walking is very poor .
He 'll regain a little bit more use in the arms .
That 's almost guaranteeable .
But it 's doubtful that he 'll have completely normal function of the hands . ''
`` He knows about his diagnosis , '' Schlitt said .
`` I 've discussed it with him .
He 's depressed as most people will be after such an injury . ''
Frier was Seattle 's seventh-round draft choice in 1992 and was picked up on waivers by Cincinnati that year .
He played in 32 games with the Bengals before being released Oct. 13 .
He played in two games as a reserve with the Seahawks this season .
`` There is a tremendous shock in the locker room right now , '' said Seahawks coach Tom Flores .
Police Sgt. Mark Smith said the initial indication was the car carrying the Seahawks pulled out to pass in the left lane .
`` Then , as they were entering the northbound lane , they continued on across -LRB- the lane -RRB- and hit the pole , '' he said .
He said there were no skid marks and it appeared the car was going too fast for the rain-slicked road .
He declined to estimate the speed .
The crash set the utility pole on fire and the players had to be pulled from the car by passersby and firefighters , he said .
Vehicular assault is punishable by up to five years in prison , although the standard sentencing range under state guidelines is three to nine months in jail , the King County prosecutor 's office said .
The charge alleges a defendant caused serious harm to another person as a result of driving a vehicle in a reckless manner or while under the influence of drugs or alcohol .
