Amid reports that detained Canadian UN soldiers may be freed by Bosnian Serbs , Prime Minister Jean Chretien said peacekeeping rules are changing faster than ceasefire agreements are broken in war-torn former Yugoslavia .
`` We went there to maintain the peace , but the war is still going on , '' he said Friday after meeting with French President Francois Mitterrand and Prime Minister Edouard Balladur .
`` We 're playing it the best we can . ''
Chretien said it 's time to intensify diplomatic efforts to end the war , adding that the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe next week in Budapest will be crucial .
`` If some initiatives are decided , it will be decided Monday and Tuesday . ''
In Pale , Bosnia , UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi said the Serbs agreed to release more than 400 detained peacekeepers , including 55 Canadians .
By the end of the day , 70 Dutch troops had been freed but there was no schedule for the others ' release and in Ottawa , Defense Minister David Collenette said : `` We have no confirmed reports concerning Canadian detainees . ''
Also Friday , Chretien elaborated on his idea of a free trade deal between North America and Europe .
He told about 400 business people that improving trade links across the Atlantic is the best way to prevent trading blocs from withdrawing `` timidly into their own shells . ''
`` This is the best way to energize relations between Canada and France , and Canada and Europe , and to fight the temptation of isolationism . ''
The prime minister first suggested the idea Thursday while speaking to the French Senate .
Federal officials said Canada has n't yet broached the subject with the U.S. or Mexico , its partners in the North America Free Trade Agreement .
Chretien said his new trade initiative did n't come up Friday in separate talks with Mitterrand and Balladur , which dealt mostly with the situation in Bosnia , in preparation for the meetings in Budapest .
Canada has extensive trade and investment links with France .
Two-way trade amounted to more than $ 4 billion in 1993 and French companies have invested $ 4.2 billion in Canada , including more than $ 2.5 billion in Ontario .
French business executives expressed curiosity about Chretien 's proposal during a private lunch but did n't endorse or reject the idea , said Canadian officials .
Chretien formally signed with Balladur a previously announced agreement that ends a long-standing dispute over fishing around the French islands of St-Pierre-Miquelon near Newfoundland .
And the prime minister expressed relief that Bloc Quebecois Leader Lucien Bouchard was out of immediate danger after his leg was amputated to save his life from a deadly bacterium .
`` I hope that he will be back in good health within months . ''
The Security Council late Friday night called on the former Soviet republic of Georgia and a breakaway province to press forward with peace talks and cautioned against a separate Abkhaz state .
Russia has repeatedly urged the council to address the conflict .
The council statement came moments after Moscow vetoed a resolution that would have limited fuel shipments to Serbia , a traditional Russian ally .
The council statement said that last week 's declaration by Abkhazia 's parliament `` purporting to establish a sovereign Abkhaz identity would violate the commitments ... to seek a comprehensive political settlement . ''
Georgia and Abkhazia signed a U.N.-brokered agreement in September that allowed for the return of refugees .
But Abkhazian authorities have refused to accept many refugees , citing Georgian violations of a cease-fire .
At issue is the plight of some 250,000 Georgians who fled Abkhazia and want to return home .
The war in Abkhazia began in the summer of 1992 when Georgian soldiers marched into the Black Sea province to crush the secessionist movement .
The fighting , which claimed 3,000 lives , ended last fall when Abkhazian forces drove out the Georgian soldiers .
A truce , monitored by Russian peacekeepers and U.N. observers , is now in place .
The United States and North Korea have wrapped up the latest round of nuclear talks on providing the communist state with modern nuclear reactors .
`` The talks addressed complex matters and were serious and useful , '' said a joint statement after the three-day talks in Beijing ended Friday .
It was carried Saturday by the North 's official Korean Central News Agency .
Under an agreement signed in October , the North is to receive two reactors in exchange for freezing and eventually dismantling its nuclear facilities , suspected of being used to develop atomic bombs .
It is also to gain diplomatic relations with Washington .
The statement said the two sides reaffirmed their intention to meet the terms of the Geneva accord on the provision of the new reactors , worth about dlrs 4 billion .
Under the agreement , Washington is to organize an international consortium to finance and build the plants by 2003 .
The new lightwater reactors would produce much less weapons-grade plutonium than the North 's present graphite-moderated reactors are capable of , experts say .
The statement gave no further details on the negotiations , except to say the two sides agreed to meet again in January .
South Korean officials say the talks focused on deciding the type of reactors to be given to the North and discussed such details as where they will be built .
South Korea is willing to bear much of the cost on condition that it makes them .
North Korea reportedly prefers Russian or German models , apparently to avoid losing face to its capitalist rival .
After spending hours in poorly heated classrooms sharing tattered , Soviet-era textbooks , students at public school No. 728 come to the `` computer closet '' to work on their on-line newspaper .
Or to send e-mail to students in Minnesota .
Or to practice their French in an electronic conference with European teens .
Like most of Russia 's roads , its information superhighway is ridden with potholes and Soviet-style dead-ends .
Nevertheless , the younger generation is building its own on-ramps and starting to cruise .
`` The kids may not understand yet what this access , this communication , means for them , '' said Volodya Pilipchuk , the school 's computer adviser and a former 728 student .
`` But 10 years from now , they will . ''
Pilipchuk 's students have joined the millions of people -- from New York CEOs to human rights activists in East Timor -- who communicate via a worldwide web of computer networks .
It does n't seem to matter to these students that they were born in a society famous for restricting information .
Or that some of their parents built careers on imposing those restrictions .
What matters is the computer itself .
Dozens of students huddle around the school 's lone unit during breaks , as Pilipchuk struggles to ration out computer time to eager users .
Most of the students here , unlike many of their U.S. counterparts , had never seen a computer before this project began .
Olga Galkina , the founder of the school 's on-line newspaper , says the project is aimed at `` helping kids understand their global importance . ''
And ultimately , she hopes , these children may be the ones to guide the rest of the former Soviet Union into the information age .
Much of Russia 's wealth of computer expertise has been lured to the West , leaving a relatively small cadre of dedicated but underfunded programmers to bring new technologies to this vast nation .
In the meantime , the kids are having fun .
`` Look , I can type in English , '' boasted Sasha , a 12-year-old wearing an L.A. Raiders sweatshirt .
`` Even my older brother ca n't do that . ''
The latest issue of `` Southern Zone , '' the on-line school paper , included articles on the music of David Lee Roth and a nature reserve in Russia 's Far North .
The issue was posted on the local network Glasnet , which is connected to the worldwide Internet , allowing computers around the world access to the newspaper .
The publication has evoked responses from users as far away as Minnesota .
`` The messages from the American kids are funny , '' said Alyosha , tugging on his long blond bangs .
`` Someone asked if Russia was bigger than California . ''
These kids are also proving that the information superhighway is not restricted to an elite few .
The school 's computer , a standard IBM-compatible 386 with an internal modem , belongs to John Whitely , a sociology professor at the University of California at Irvine .
Whitely loaned the machine to Galkina for the newspaper project in 1992 .
And Glasnet , a non-profit Russian computer network , donated an e-mail account to the school .
The project costs just a few dollars per year -- less than the paper version of the school newspaper .
The computer project is a bargain in a cash-strapped public education system struggling to support its 65,000 schools .
Teachers in Russia earn about $ 40 a month .
School 728 is just one of several seeds of hope .
At least 300 Russian schools -- most outside Moscow -- have access to e-mail accounts .
`` The numbers are still not high , for a country this size , '' said Galkina , who is now working on a project to connect disabled children in Russia to on-line services .
`` But Russia , like the U.S. , wo n't become computer literate overnight . ''
Computer literacy is not a top priority for School 728 's administrators , who pay little attention to the cramped , windowless computer room .
`` Yes , I know there 's something going on over there , '' said Nina Mikhailova , head of the student relations department , in the opposite wing of the school .
`` But it does n't concern us .
We do n't use computers over here . ''
The administration may be wary , but its pupils are already making plans .
`` I want to be a programmer , '' 14-year-old Anton said , `` because the world ca n't survive without computers . ''
Vietnam 's Ministry of Finance has raised interest rates on treasury bonds from 15 percent to 21 percent , to attract more capital needed for economic development , an official report said Saturday .
The three-year treasury bonds , which first went on sale in June , are available to foreign residents and companies with foreign investors as well as to Vietnamese buyers , the state-run Vietnam News reported .
The ministry planned earlier this year to issue the securities only if they carried an interest rate of less than 20 percent .
But a tepid public response to bond offerings so far has motivated the ministry to boost the rate to increase their appeal .
Vietnam hopes to attract as much as dlrs 55 billion in investment , loans and foreign aid to double its national per capita income to around dlrs 450 by the end of the decade .
The treasury bonds are aimed at attracting what foreign bankers estimate is some dlrs 1 billion circulating outside Vietnam 's banking system .
Many Vietnamese are wary of socialist-era banks that catered historically to state-run companies rather than retail customers , and they keep their savings at home or buy U.S. dollars or gold .
Separately , the International Nederlanden Group -LRB- ING -RRB- has received approval in principle to open a commercial bank branch in Hanoi , a bank officer said .
The ING bank becomes the first from the Netherlands to receive such approval and brings to at least 12 the number of foreign banks with branches , or permission to open branches , in the country .
ING , which opened offices here in 1992 , has no plans yet to apply for a second branch in Ho Chi Minh City , Vietnam 's business hub , said its representative in Hanoi , Nguyen Duc Phuc .
Vietnamese authorities see foreign bank branches as one way to attract investment to the capital Hanoi and speed development in the north of the country .
Citibank and the Bank of America , the last two foreign banks to receive approval in principle for branches , will open their branches in Hanoi as well .
The ING branch , once it opens , will cater to wholesale customers rather than individuals , Phuc said .
Russia believes it 's time to lift some United Nations sanctions on Serbia , its ambassador said Friday
Ambassador Sergey Lavrov spoke to reporters after blocking a resolution that would have severely limited all Serbian fuel and supplies from entering Bosnia and Croatia .
`` Russia does not think it 's appropriate '' to pass such a resolution on the same day Croatia and its rebel Serb minority signed an economic agreement touted as a framework for normalized relations , Lavrov said .
The agreement calls for restoring water and electricity and reopening oil pipelines and the highway linking Zagreb , the Croatian capital , with the Yugoslav capital , Belgrade .
Lavrov also noted Serbia has begun to cooperate with the international community by supporting the international peace process and cooperating with U.N. observers monitoring the the Bosnian-Serb border .
`` So , we believe it is high time not to reiterate sanctions against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia , but to consider further ways of lifting some of the sanctions , '' he said .
`` We had no other choice than to vote against this draft , '' Lavrov said during the council meeting .
One Western diplomat said the veto was important to Russians but will probably not get much reaction from Security Council members .
However , New Zealand Ambassador Colin Keating was unhappy with Russia 's decision to veto the resolution sponsored by Muslim and non-aligned nations .
`` We have no doubt that the consequences of today 's vote will be felt for a long time to come , '' he said .
Russia has been going along with the Western powers on most of the U.N. resolutions during the Bosnian crisis , despite its traditionally close relationship with the Serbs .
As their tiny island country is invaded by Sonoran troops , the Ginger Islands call on the United States for help .
The situation deteriorates , crisis becomes conflict .
Americans on the Gingers are evacuated .
Air Force planes begin bombing runs .
Marines are ready to land .
`` It 's a good , messy scenario , '' Rear Adm. Dennis C. Blair , commander of the Kitty Hawk carrier battle group said as the biennial Tandem Thrust maneuvers moved towards Saturday toward their climax off the real Pacific islands of Guam and Tinian .
Blair said a major feature of this year 's exercises , which involve 14,500 troops , is a more integrated approach -- Navy , Air Force , Army , Marines , and Coast Guard are all participating -- made necessary by tighter budgets and continued cuts in the size of the military .
`` We 've had a 40 percent budget cut , so we 've learned to look to other services for some of the things we used to do ourselves , '' he said .
`` Before , it was really a zone defense , '' he said , making a sports metaphor in which each player is responsible for only his own part of a court or field .
Nowhere is the new attitude of cooperation reflected better than in a cramped set of operations rooms in the Kitty Hawk , whose crew and air wing add up to 5,550 people .
Shoulder to shoulder , specialists from the different branches of the military coordinate their air missions against the imaginary Sonorans .
From that command center , crammed to overflowing with maps , message boards and state-of-the-art computers , roughly 210 sorties are planned each day , some dropping live ordnance on a small island firing range on the maneuver 's parameters .
`` So far , it 's been working magnificently well , '' said Read Adm. Herb Brown , head of the exercise 's joint air command .
Navy spokesmen stressed that the exercises , which began Nov. 26 and end Dec. 8 , are not planned as a preparation for hostilities with any particular nation but are instead a composite of potential threats and responses .
They have also been designed to emphasize the kind of hot-spot tensions that have become more common since the end of the Cold War .
As the maneuvers progress , simulated political and diplomatic activities are also underway , giving an additional dimension of uncertainty to the mission .
`` Right now , we are just trying to demonstrate to the opposition our presence , '' said Air Force Col. Ed Allen , deputy chief of the maneuver 's joint air command .
`` We are hoping the government of Sonora will back down . ''
Government troops killed four Tamil Tiger rebels in two separate clashes in eastern Sri Lanka , a military spokesman said Saturday .
Troops killed three rebels Friday in Panichchankerni , 200 kilometers -LRB- 130 miles -RRB- east of Colombo , said Brig. Gemunu Kulatunga , the military 's spokesman .
In another incident , guerrillas attacked policemen and one rebel was killed in the cross-fire in Namalpokuna and killed one rebel , Kulatunga said .
No casualties were reported on the government side .
Clashes have continued despite President Chandrika Kumaratunga 's offer of a cease-fire and restarting the peace talks .
Rebel leader Velupillai Prabhakaran has agreed to peace talks to end the 11-year-old war , but no date has been fixed for resuming negotiations suspended after a suspected rebel suicide bomber killed opposition presidential candidate Gamini Dissanayake and 56 others on Oct. 24 .
The rebels want a homeland in the north and east for Sri Lanka 's 3-million-strong Tamil minority .
They accuse the majority Buddhist Sinhalese of discrimination .
More than 34,000 people have been killed in the fighting .
Russia vetoed a Security Council resolution late Friday aimed at stopping Yugoslav fuel supplies reportedly powering a Serb offensive in northern Bosnia .
It was the first council veto in a year and a half -- and the first on the Bosnian war .
The resolution was sponsored by Islamic and non-aligned states to show sympathy for the Bosnian Muslims .
Russia , a traditional Serb ally , said it vetoed the resolution because it would tighten sanctions against Serbia .
`` We had no other choice than to vote against this draft , '' said Russian Ambassador Sergey Lavrov .
`` We hope that ultimately there will be a sound and balanced approach '' toward a political process .
Lavrov said `` a more untimely moment of this -LRB- resolution -RRB- is impossible , '' adding that Yugoslavia had closed its border with Bosnia and was cooperating with peace negotiators .
Another Russian diplomat , speaking on condition of anonymity , stressed that the veto did not represent a split within the five-nation contact group pushing for a peace agreement in Bosnia .
Hours before the veto , diplomats from Russia , the United States , France , Britain and Germany demonstrated their unity by endorsing a confederation of Bosnian Serbs and neighboring Serbia .
The last veto was in May 1993 , when Russia blocked its first resolution in nine years , killing a proposal to make all U.N. members pay for the small U.N. peacekeeping force in Cyprus .
Friday night 's veto was also an opportunity for Russia to show its muscle in the council .
Lavrov has repeatedly accused the United Nations of a `` double standard , '' saying that the council has imposed sanctions against Serbia , but has ignored Muslim acts against Serbs .
The resolution would require U.N. border monitors to severely limit shipments of fuel and other supplies crossing the border between Serbia , the dominant member of Yugoslavia , and Croatia .
The aim of the resolution is `` to totally shackle the Serb war-making capability , '' said Djibouti 's ambassador Roble Olhaye .
U.N. resolutions already ban all but humanitarian supplies from crossing the border between Yugoslavia and Bosnia , but monitors have been permitting shipments to cross Bosnia if they are destined for Croatia .
The resolution also called for the freedom of the 450 U.N. peacekeepers being held by Serb forces .
Bosnian Serbs have promised to free the peacekeepers and allow aid deliveries , but Security Council President Manzi Bakuramutsa said late Friday there was no evidence the soldiers had been released .
`` There is no confirmation yet that the restrictions have actually been lifted , '' said Bakuramutsa , the Rwandan ambassador .
`` The council members insist that all detainees ... be released immediately and that UNPROFOR 's ... freedom of movement be respected in the future . ''
UNPROFOR is the U.N. peacekeeping mission in the former Yugoslavia .
Some 100 to 150 tankers filled with fuel are being allowed to cross the Yugoslav border and reach Serb forces in Croatia , said one diplomat , speaking on condition of anonymity .
Croatian and Bosnian diplomats say the fuel is far in excess of humanitarian needs and is being used in the war effort in Bosnia .
The ambassador of Pakistan , a co-sponsor of the resolution called the Bosnians `` victims of international indifference . ''
Jamsheed Marker said his country had demanded a vote on the resolution because `` the U.N. can not stand by and permit this genocide ... -LRB- which -RRB- makes a mockery of what the U.N. stands for . ''
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic announced in August that the border with Bosnia was being sealed to all but humanitarian aid to pressure Bosnian Serbs into accepting a peace plan .
The United Nations eased its sanctions against Yugoslavia in October .
Belgrade had supplied the Bosnian Serbs throughout the 21\/2 - year war with Bosnia .
Classified U.N. reports shown to The Associated Press in Sarajevo say that U.N. observers had seen armed men crossing the border between Serb-held territory in Croatia and Bosnia in vehicles with Belgrade licenses .
With Friday 's vote , the veto has been used 281 times in the Security Council since the founding of the United Nations in 1945 .
The last veto cast by the United States was in May 1990 and blocked a resolution criticizing Israel for its activities in the occupied territories .
