A pre-trial hearing for a man accused of murdering seven backpackers has so far turned up circumstantial evidence but no direct proof placing him at the scene of the crimes .
Friends and family members of the victims gave tearful testimony in Campbelltown Local Court this past week , describing the last time they saw or heard from their loved ones .
They also identified camping equipment police found in the home of one of Milat 's brothers .
A coworker and the ex-wife of the defendant , Ivan Milat , also testified about hunting , his love for guns and the state forest where the bodies were found .
Milat is accused of shooting and stabbing the Australian , British and German backpackers and burying their bodies in shallow graves in Belanglo State Forest , southwest of Sydney .
Their bodies were found between September 1992 and November 1993 .
Charged with murder , attempted murder , armed robbery and firearms offenses , Milat faces up to life imprisonment .
Milat secured the services of a new barrister , two weeks after sacking his previous chief counsel .
The New South Wales Supreme Court gave permission for Terry Martin , a Queensland barrister , to practice in the state and represent Milat .
On Monday , before the ruling , Milat sat alone .
`` I ca n't defend myself .
... I 'm a roadworker , not a lawyer , '' Milat told Magistrate Michael Price .
`` I 'm being framed here for seven murders . ''
During testimony later in the week , Stephen Wright of England , identified with `` no doubt '' a tent found at one of Milat 's brothers as the one he gave British travelers Caroline Clarke and Joanne Walters .
The tent still had a hole Wright said he made accidentally with a knife while touring Australia in 1992 .
The parents and friends of Walters and Clarke broke down in tears during testimony by Milat 's ex-wife .
She recalled her seven-year relationship with Milat and said he kept firearms and other weapons and often carried a revolver in his sock .
`` Ivan was gun crazy with his firearms , '' said the woman who has requested her name not be used .
Milat was charged in May with murdering Melbourne couple James Gibson and Deborah Everist , both 19 ; German backpackers Simone Schmidl , 21 , Gabor Neugebauer , 21 , and Anja Habschied , 20 ; and British backpackers Clarke , 21 , and Walters , 22 .
As their tiny island country is invaded by Sonoran troops , the Ginger Islands call on the United States for help .
The situation deteriorates , crisis becomes conflict .
Americans on the Gingers are evacuated .
Air Force planes begin bombing runs .
Marines are ready to land .
`` It 's a good , messy scenario , '' Rear Adm. Dennis C. Blair , commander of the Kitty Hawk carrier battle group said as the biennial Tandem Thrust maneuvers moved Saturday toward their climax off the real Pacific islands of Guam and Tinian .
Blair said a major feature of this year 's exercises , which involve 14,500 troops , is a more integrated approach -- Navy , Air Force , Army , Marines , and Coast Guard are all participating -- made necessary by tighter budgets and continued cuts in the size of the military .
`` We 've had a 40 percent budget cut , so we 've learned to look to other services for some of the things we used to do ourselves , '' he said .
`` Before , it was really a zone defense , '' he said , making a sports metaphor in which each player is responsible for only his own part of a court or field .
Nowhere is the new attitude of cooperation reflected better than in a cramped set of operations rooms in the Kitty Hawk , whose crew and air wing add up to 5,550 people .
Shoulder to shoulder , specialists from the different branches of the military coordinate their air missions against the imaginary Sonorans .
From that command center , crammed to overflowing with maps , message boards and state-of-the-art computers , roughly 210 sorties are planned each day , some dropping live ordnance on a small island firing range on the maneuver 's parameters .
`` So far , it 's been working magnificently well , '' said Read Adm. Herb Brown , head of the exercise 's joint air command .
Navy spokesmen stressed that the exercises , which began Nov. 26 and end Dec. 8 , are not planned as a preparation for hostilities with any particular nation but are instead a composite of potential threats and responses .
They have also been designed to emphasize the kind of hot-spot tensions that have become more common since the end of the Cold War .
As the maneuvers progress , simulated political and diplomatic activities are also underway , giving an additional dimension of uncertainty to the mission .
`` Right now , we are just trying to demonstrate to the opposition our presence , '' said Air Force Col. Ed Allen , deputy chief of the maneuver 's joint air command .
`` We are hoping the government of Sonora will back down . ''
Detectives probing a spy ring that stole secrets of India 's space program have arrested a businessman , taking the number of people jailed in the case to six , newspapers reported Saturday .
Sudhir Kumar Sharma , based in the southern city of Bangalore , where the Indian Space Research Organization is located , was arrested Thursday , The Times of India said .
Sharma 's arrest came a day after police picked up Nambi Narayanan , a rocket scientist who helped develop engines for launching satellites and missiles .
Narayanan was the second space expert to be accused in the spy case exposed after the Oct. 20 arrest of a woman who allegedly seduced scientists and blackmailed them to give her designs of rocket engines .
Both arrests were made in Trivandrum on India 's southern coast , close to a small town where the liquid propulsion laboratory that Narayanan headed is located .
Newspapers quoted unidentified police sources as saying the ring was working for Pakistan , India 's arch-rival .
Pakistan has denied it was involved .
Police in the southern state of Kerala , where many other space laboratories are located , began investigating the spy ring after arresting Mariam Rasheda , a citizen of the Maldives , the reports said .
Her interrogation led to the arrests of rocket expert D. Sasikumaran ; another Maldivian woman , Fousiya Hassan ; and K. Chandrashekaran , who claimed to represent the Russian space company Glavkosmos .
Both India and Pakistan , who have fought three wars since 1947 , are believed capable of producing nuclear weapons .
India is developing its own weapons delivery system , while Pakistan buys M-11 missiles from China .
Indian scientists have been developing rockets to launch communications satellites since 1979 .
But the space laboratories also are involved in developing missile technology and have come under pressure from Western countries .
In 1992 , Russia 's Glavkosmos was forced to cancel a deal to supply rocket engines to India under pressure from Washington .
American tennis star Jennifer Capriati will continue her comeback by playing in the Australian Open championship in Melbourne from Jan. 16-30 .
Australian Open tournament director Paul McNamee , who formerly coached Capriati , said the 18-year-old , who missed most of last season after personal problems including an arrest on misdemeanor drug charges , is also planning to play in the New South Wales Open preparatory tournament in Sydney from Jan. 9 .
`` Jen is just such an exciting talent , it is going to be great to see her , '' McNamee said .
`` She loves Australia and feels very comfortable here .
It 's great for women 's tennis to have her back . ''
President Clinton voiced strong support Friday for appointment of former Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gotari to head the new World Trade Organization .
The organization will administer new international trade rules established under GATT , the General Agreement on Tariff and Trade .
U.S. participation in the trade pact got final approval from Congress this week .
A number of candidates for the trade post are expected to be offered , including some from Europe and South Korea .
But the White House said Clinton believes Salinas , who has just completed a six-year term as Mexico 's president , is `` extraordinarily well qualified to take on the challenges facing the world trading system . ''
A White House statement noted that Salinas is the only candidate who has served as a head of state and said he has a strong background in internal economics .
`` He would bring to the WTO a wealth of experience and important insights from the perspective of a developing country , '' the White House statement said .
`` As Mexico 's president for six years , President Salinas led his country through a successful process of economic reform and trade liberalization , '' it said .
`` The president believe he deserves widespread support . ''
Pakistan knows exactly what it must do to defeat defending champion the Netherlands in Sunday 's final of the World Cup field hockey tournament .
Pakistan needs to penetrate the Dutch defense with its own free-flowing attacks and to avoid conceding any penalty corners .
Easier said than done .
The Dutch have been ruthless from short corners throughout the two-week tournament .
Twelve of their 24 goals have come from set piece plays -- at which Floris Jan Bovelander and Taco van den Honert are devastating .
`` Their penalty corners are certainly better than ours , so we 'll have to be certain not to give them too many opportunities , '' said Pakistan manager Abdul Rashid .
`` But if we play our normal game I believe we can beat them . ''
Pakistan is a three-time winner of the World Cup but faces a Dutch side that is unbeaten in its last 27 games .
Coach Roelant Oltmans led the Dutch women to victory in the World Cup in Sydney four years ago and is looking to complete a double triumph Down Under .
He rejects the perception the Netherlands is a `` short corner team . ''
`` We have the best short corner specialist in the world in Bovelander , but we have scored 12 goals from the field here , '' Oltmans said .
`` We certainly do n't play only for short corners . ''
The final is a repeat of the 1990 final , in which the Netherlands beat the host nation 3-1 in front of a 65,000 crowd in Lahore .
`` That makes it special , '' said Oltmans .
Bovelander scored twice in the 1990 final and also set up this final appearance with two penalty corner strikes as the Dutch downed top seeded Australia 3-1 in their semifinal on Friday .
The Dutch played with tactical awareness in that game , depriving the Australian inners of space and stretching the ball wide when they attacked .
`` I think we 're still improving and still have to improve some more , '' said Oltmans .
`` How your forwards play comes down to how they are fed by the midfield .
`` If we can feed our forwards very quickly , which at the moment happens probably only one or two times a game , we can score more goals . ''
Pakistan 's hopes rest largely on captain and midfielder Shahbaz Ahmed , who has been troubled by a hamstring injury over the past week but still played well in Friday 's semifinal victory over Germany .
`` It is always very hard to play the Netherlands and we know we ca n't afford to give them penalty corners , '' Shahbaz said .
After 10 years without a major title , the Pakistanis won this year 's Champions Trophy in March , but then failed -- for the first time -- to make the final of the Asian Games .
In matches played Saturday , India got a 45th minute goal from Mukesh Kumar and defeated England 1-0 in the game to decide fifth and sixth places .
Argentina drew 3-3 with South Korea but then won a penalty shootout 5-3 to seal seventh place in the 12-nation tournament .
In play-offs to decide other placings , Spain drew 1-1 with Belgium and then won 8-7 on penalty strokes and South Africa beat Belarus 3-2 when captain Wayne Graham pounced on a penalty corner rebound with 37 seconds remaining .
Spain and South Africa now will contest 9th and 10th place on Sunday and Belgium and Belarus will play-off for 11th and 12th .
