Greg Chappell has warned his Australia A team that it can not afford to underestimate Zimbabwe in Sunday 's World Series limited-overs cricket match at the WACA Ground .
Zimbabwe has had mixed results since arriving in Australia , but held the top-grade Australian team to a two-wicket victory in the World Series tournament opener on Friday night .
Zimbabwe scored 166-9 and Australia replied with 167-8 from 47.2 overs .
`` If Zimbabwe can maintain that sort of competitiveness and discipline throughout the series then they are going to be a force to contend with , '' said Australia A coach Chappell .
`` Their top order looks strong .
Their middle order looks to be their Achilles heel based on yesterday 's performance , but you ca n't really make a judgement on just one game . ''
After viewing the bouncy pitch Saturday morning , Chappell was surprised it yielded such low scores and said he expects bigger totals on Sunday .
`` Whoever bats first would be looking at about 220 or 230 , '' Chappell said .
`` When you look at the start Zimbabwe got yesterday , they probably should have ended up with 220 .
`` But what happens in these one-day games is the team batting second cut their cloth accordingly .
`` If Zimbabwe had made 220 , then I think Australia would have made 220 or very close to it . ''
Chappell said the Zimbabwe pace attack looks sound and he was impressed by 24-year-old leg-spinner Paul Strang .
`` I heard he had been bowling well and he certainly lived up to that promise .
