It could even be fractured , but there is little either of them can do about it except bat on . ''
In another display of U.N. divisions over how to handle the war in Bosnia , Russia vetoed a Security Council resolution aimed at cutting Yugoslav fuel supplies reportedly powering a recent rebel Serb offensive .
The resolution brought to a vote Friday night was sponsored by Islamic and non-aligned states .
It would have required U.N. border monitors to severely limit shipments of fuel and other supplies crossing the border between Serb-dominated Yugoslavia and Croatia .
U.N. resolutions already ban shipments of all but humanitarian supplies between Yugoslavia and Bosnia .
Some 100 to 150 tankers filled with fuel are being allowed to cross the Yugoslav border and reach rebel Serb forces in Croatia , said a diplomat who requested anonymity .
Croatian and Bosnian diplomats say the fuel is well beyond humanitarian needs .
Croatian Serbs in recent weeks have crossed the border into northwest Bosnia and joined Bosnian Serbs in fighting the Bosnian government army around Bihac .
Russia said it vetoed the resolution because it would tighten sanctions against Serbia , the main remaining state in Yugoslavia .
`` We hope that ultimately there will be a sound and balanced approach '' toward making peace in Bosnia , said Russian Ambassador Sergey Lavrov .
He has repeatedly accused the United Nations of using a double standard -- imposing sanctions against Serbia but ignoring acts by Bosnia 's Muslim-led army against Serbs .
He said the resolution was `` untimely , '' since Yugoslavia had closed its border with Bosnia and was cooperating with peace negotiations .
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic announced in August that the border was being sealed to all but humanitarian aid to pressure Bosnian Serbs into accepting a peace plan , and the United Nations eased sanctions against Yugoslavia in October .
The resolution Friday also called for the release of U.N. peacekeepers being held by Serb forces .
Hours before the Security Council veto Friday -- the first in a year and a half -- diplomats from Russia , the United States , France , Britain and Germany endorsed a confederation of Bosnian Serbs and neighboring Serbia in hopes of drawing Serbs into peace negotiations to end the 2 -LCB- - year war .
Western diplomats differed over the impact of the Russian veto on the prospects for peace in Bosnia .
One said that the veto was an important sign to Russians , the Serbs ' traditional allies , but would probably get little reaction from Security Council members .
But Ambassador Paul Keating of New Zealand disagreed .
`` We have no doubt that the consequences of today 's vote will be felt for a long time to come , '' he said .
Five days after the Australian government announced it had approved more military aid for Cambodia , the Khmer Rouge guerrilla group vowed Saturday to retaliate against Australians .
In a broadcast over its private radio station using typically fiery rhetoric , the group said it would `` behead '' Australians .
Australia announced Tuesday it would give 5 million Australian dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 3.75 million -RRB- in aid to Cambodia to help retrain the country 's armed forces but had ruled out the use of Australian soldiers .
The package had no `` lethal material , '' Foreign Minister Gareth Evans and Defense Minister Robert Ray said in a joint statement .
Australia already provides dlrs 3 million a year in military assistance for mine clearing , military communications , establishment of a maritime workshop and English-language training for Cambodian military personnel .
Australian ambassador Tony Kevin on Saturday warned his countrymen to be more careful but said they should not be intimidated .
`` We encourage Australians , especially business people and aid agencies to continue to help Cambodia , '' he said .
`` We are not to going to let the security problem interfere . ''
The Khmer Rouge , responsible for the deaths of more than one million Cambodians during a reign of terror from 1975 to 1978 , boycotted last year 's U.N.-sponsored elections and have been waging a guerrilla war against the Cambodian government .
King Norodom Sihanouk , who has long attempted to negotiate an end to the bloodshed , said this week he would not meet with the guerrilla group when he returns to Cambodia in January from Beijing , where he is being treated for medical problems .
