Riddick Bowe threw one heavyweight title belt in a garbage can and lost two others in the ring .
He begins his chase for yet another on Satuday night , not picky anymore about which title he holds .
Bowe returns to the ring for only the second time since losing his World Boxing Association and International Boxing Federation titles to Evander Holyfield 13 months ago .
On Saturday night , he meets undefeated Larry Donald in a scheduled 12-round fight .
This time , though , Bowe finds himself effectively shut off from the major titles and needing a win just to get a shot at the heavyweight crown from the lowly World Boxing Organization .
`` I do n't care what title I have as long as it indicates I 'm heavyweight champion of the world , '' Bowe said .
It 's a far cry from when Bowe held all three major titles , only to throw the World Boxing Council crown into a garbage can in a show of disdain for the organization .
But with the heavyweight crown now split between George Foreman and Oliver McCall , neither of whom show any inclination to fight the former champion , Bowe can only look toward a fight with WBO champion Herbie Hide in the spring .
`` I look at myself as being the uncrowned champion , '' Bowe said .
First , though , he must beat Donald , a stylish boxer who has won all 16 of his professional fights and who matches up well physically with Bowe .
`` I 'm loaded with confidence , '' said Donald , a 4-1 underdog .
`` I 'm a master boxer and I 'm on my way up . ''
Bowe , whose only fight since losing to Holyfield was an aborted no contest against Buster Mathis Jr. in August , is taking a calculated risk in meeting an up-and-coming fighter whose style could give him problems .
Bowe 's trainer , Eddie Futch , said the former champion has regained the fire that first won him the title .
It showed at Thursday 's weigh-in , where a slimmed-down Bowe weighed 241 pounds -LRB- 109.2 kilograms -RRB- , his lightest since winning the titles from Holyfield two years ago .
Donald weighed in at 228 pounds -LRB- 103.3 kilograms -RRB- .
Bowe will earn dlrs 1 million for the bout , beginning about 6:45 p.m. local time -LRB- 0245 GMT Sunday -RRB- from Caesars Palace .
Donald will earn dlrs 490,000 .
The truth behind the standoff between the PGA Tour and the new World Golf Tour will only be known when it comes time to put up the money and stop the talk .
The World Golf Tour issued a statement Friday saying it was `` continuing to move ahead as planned '' with its venture to stage six to eight tournaments in 1995 , some of which would conflict with PGA Tour events .
Greg Norman 's commitment to the World Golf Tour `` is as firm as ever , '' the statement said .
And Norman 's agent , Frank Williams , told The New York Times that `` Greg is still going full speed ahead . ''
This all came one day after PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem released a statement in which he said Norman told him he had had a `` re-evaluation of this situation '' and had told Finchem `` he would not support any venture that would damage the PGA Tour . ''
Norman , who joined World Golf Tour executive director John Montgomery Jr. and upstart U.S. TV network Fox Television in announcing the new tour two weeks ago , has wavered in his support of the venture since Finchem announced that he would suspend any PGA Tour member who played in events that conflict with the tour .
No American professionals have committed to the world tour , no dates , sites or sponsors have been announced for the tournaments .
`` They are very keen to keep communications open , '' Norman , who is in Australia , said about the PGA Tour .
`` He -LRB- Finchem -RRB- asked me to see him when I get home , and I will do that .
Right now , the World Tour and the PGA Tour have a chance of working this thing out . ''
Norman is scheduled to meet with Finchem and Montgomery separately when he returns to the United States next week .
As proposed , the new tour would have a 40-man field , based on the world rankings .
The prize money would provide dlrs 1 million for player of the year ; dlrs 600,000 to each tournament winner , and dlrs 30,000 to the last-place finisher , as well as dlrs 50,000 to each golfer for expenses .
Michael Johnson ran only three races at 400 meters this year , but he made a huge impression .
Johnson , 27 , was honored with the Jesse Owens Award Friday night as track and field 's top performer .
His victories , the three best times in the world for the year , extended his winning streak in the 400 to 26 in a row .
`` If you run 10 or 15 races a year , you can slack off on a few , '' Johnson said .
`` If you only run three races , you 've got to make sure they 're all fast . ''
Johnson , of Rockwall , Texas , has n't lost in the 400 since 1989 .
This year he ran times of 44.32 and 44.04 seconds in August , and had a world-best 43.90 in Madrid , Spain , in September .
He also had the fastest time run by an American in 1994 at 200 meters , a 19.94 clocking at a meet in Monaco .
Johnson said he 'd run both events next year at the World Championships in Goteborg , Sweden , and also would double in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics .
Johnson edged two-time winner Jackie Joyner-Kersee , who set American records both indoors and outdoors in the long jump , in the closest balloting in history by media and the U.S. athletics community .
The award was handed out at the annual USA Track & Field convention .
Earlier in the day , Joyner-Kersee was honored as the world 's female athlete of the year by the International Athletic Foundation in Monaco .
Last month , Johnson and Joyner-Kersee were named men 's and women 's track and field athletes of the year by the U.S. Olympic Committee .
Joyner-Kersee , who is competing in Australia , won the Owens Award in 1986 and ' 87 .
