West Indies were 93 for two at lunch Saturday in response to India 's first innings total of 546 for nine declared on the third day of their second test against India in Nagpur .
Resuming at an overnight score of 15 for one , the visitors lost night watchman Anderson Cummins for 17 , but opener Phil Simmons and Brian Lara determinedly hung on to the crease .
Simmons and Cummins put on 46 runs before Cummins was caught by Sanjay Manjrekar off Venkatapathy Raju .
Simmons was batting on 45 and Lara on 13 .
A double-century stand between Sachin Tendulkar and skipper Mohammad Azharuddhin had helped India reach 546 for nine just before stumps Friday .
The visitors are down 0-1 in the three-test series .
Mark Calcavecchia shot a 2-under-par 70 Saturday and held onto his lead after the third round of the U.S. dlrs 637,500 Greg Norman Holden Classic at Royal Melbourne .
Calcavecchia had a 10-under-par total of 206 over the par-72 , 6,993-yard Royal Melbourne course for a one-stroke advantage over three Australians : Anthony Gilligan , Glenn Joyner and tournament host Norman .
Norman and Joyner both had rounds of 69 , while Gilligan carded a 70 .
Peter McWhinney , who shared the lead with Calcavecchia after the second round , stumbled from the leader board with a 76 .
Calcavecchia led by two shots at the par-5 17th hole , but found the rough , had to take a drop and missed a long putt to save par .
He had earlier bogeyed the par-5 second hole .
`` I enjoyed it today , except the two par-5 holes I bogeyed , '' said the American .
`` I was having fun .
Hopefully I 'll feel good tomorrow and keep it going .
`` There are a whole number of players that can win this tournament , but it is always better to be leading .
There are some birdie holes out there , so it is up to me to go out and make some birdies . ''
Norman , who has not won a tournament in his homeland for four years , was happier with his putting Saturday but had an up-and-down round that featured six birdies and three bogeys .
`` I think the road has straightened out , or maybe I 've just turned the corner a bit , '' said Norman .
American Brad Faxon -LRB- 70 -RRB- and Australians Robert Allenby -LRB- 69 -RRB- and Terry Price -LRB- 67 -RRB- were grouped on 208 , just two strokes behind Calcavecchia .
`` It looks like a dogfight with only two strokes separating a bunch of guys , '' said Faxon .
The tournament concludes Sunday and offers a first prize of dlrs 115,000 .
Investigators probing a spy ring that stole secrets from India 's space program have arrested a businessman , the sixth person to be detained in the case , newspapers reported Saturday .
Sudhir Kumar Sharma was arrested Thursday , The Times of India said .
He was based in the southern city of Bangalore , where the Indian Space Research Organization is located .
A day earlier , police arrested Nambi Narayanan , a rocket scientist who helped develop engines for launching satellites and missiles .
Another rocket expert , D. Sasikumaran , was arrested earlier .
Investigators cracked the ring with the Oct. 20 arrest of a woman who supposedly seduced scientists and then blackmailed them for rocket engine designs .
Newspapers , quoting unidentified police sources , reported that India 's arch-rival , Pakistan , was behind the ring .
Pakistan has denied any involvement .
India and Pakistan have fought three wars since 1947 and are believed capable of producing nuclear weapons .
While Pakistan has been buying M-11 missiles from China , India has been developing its own missile technology , a program its space laborotories have taken part in .
Narayanan and his alleged seducer , Mariam Rasheda , a citizen of the Maldives , were arrested in Trivandrum on India 's southern coast , near to the liquid propulsion laboratory that Narayanan headed .
Following Rasheda 's arrest , police also picked up Fousiya Hassan , also of the Maldives , and K. Chandrashekaran , who claimed to represent the Russian space company Glavkosmos .
In 1992 , Glavkosmos was forced to cancel a deal to supply rocket engines to India under pressure from Washington , which fears an arms race and nuclear proliferation in the region .
American Bonnie Blair easily won the women 's 500 meters while Japanese skaters swept the remaining three races Saturday in the World Cup Obihiro Meet .
Blair , gold medalist in the 500 and 1,000 meters at the 1994 Lillehammer Olympics , was timed at 41.20 seconds -- 0.26 seconds ahead of Germany 's Franziska Schenk , who was clocked at 41.46 .
Japan 's Shiho Kusunose came in third at 41.49 .
Kusunose edged out Schenk to win the women 's 1,000 meters in 1:24.49 .
Schenk finished in 1:24.82 and Blair came in third at 1:25.00 .
`` I skated at 85 percent , '' Blair said after winning the 500 meters .
In the men 's races , Hiroyasu Shimizu took the 500 meters in 37.60 seconds for his third career victory in the World Cup .
Norway 's Grunde Njos finished second in 37.62 , followed by Japan 's Manabu Horii , the bronze medalist in Lillehammer , in 37.64 .
Yukinori Miyabe won the 1,000 meters in 1:16.24 , edging out Japanese compatriot Manabu Horii , who was timed at 1:16.95 .
South Korea 's Kim Yoon-man finished third at 1:16.99 and Canadian Patrick Kelly was fourth in 1:17.14 .
Seventy-one skaters from 14 nations are competing in the two-day tournament in Obihiro , 1,000 kilometers -LRB- 620 miles -RRB- northeast of Tokyo in one of Japan 's coldest winter areas .
The tournament is one of 10 events in the men 's international World Cup series and one of nine in the women 's series .
Cyclist Greg LeMond , three-time winner of the Tour de France , will announce his retirement from racing Saturday , according to media reports .
In an interview aired Friday by Sacramento television station KXTV , the 33-year-old cyclist , who won the French bicycling classic in 1986 , 1989 and 1990 , said he was no longer able to compete at that level .
`` I have a muscular-type disorder .
They 're not sure what causes it , '' LeMond said , adding that it was not a disabling injury .
`` I may not be able to win the Tour de France , but I can still beat a lot of people on my bike . ''
LeMond said he would like to remain in the sport , possibly managing a cycling team or as a television commentator , KXTV reported .
According to The New York Times , which reported the retirement in Saturday 's editions , LeMond will make his formal announcement at a fund-raiser for the United States Cycling Federation in Beverly Hills , Calif. , Saturday night .
Naomichi `` Joe '' Ozaki bogeyed two holes Saturday after two bogey-free rounds but still kept the lead by three shots going into the final round of the Golf Nippon Series , a showdown among the Japanese tour 's top players .
Starting the third round with a five-shot lead , Ozaki , the youngest brother of golfing star Masashi `` Jumbo '' Ozaki , scattered four birdies against the bogeys on the eighth and 12th holes for a third-round 69 .
Ozaki , who ranks sixth on this season 's Japan PGA money-earnings list , compiled a 16-under-par 197 over the 7,002-yard , par-71 Yomiuri Golf Members Course in western Japan .
Yoshinori Kaneko fired a 67 for a 200 total and was three shots off the pace .
Eiji Mizoguchi and Hisayuki Sasaki were at 204 after shooting 70s .
Tsuneyuki Nakajima , seeking his second straight victory in the tournament , turned in a 67 as was tied at 205 with Masayuki Kawamura , who shot a 72 .
Taiwan 's Hsieh Chin-sheng fired the day 's best score -- a 5-under-par 66 -- for a 207 .
American David Ishii -- fifth on the money list -- shot a 71 for a 210 .
American Brian Watts , who has won five Japan PGA tournaments this season , was at 211 after firing a 71 .
Todd Hamilton of the United States , a two-time winner this season , shot a 72 for a 216 total .
The 100 million yen -LRB- dlrs 1 million -RRB- tournament is for tour event winners and the top 20 money earners this season .
However , Jumbo Ozaki , the leading money winner , is not participating .
The winner receives 30 million yen -LRB- dlrs 300,000 -RRB- .
Thousands of gaunt men and women -- the survivors of the world 's worst industrial disaster -- marched on the streets of Bhopal Saturday to mark the 10th anniversary of the calamity that killed , by official count , 7,000 people .
The central Indian city , where deadly methyl isocyanate gas leaked from a factory owned by the Indian subsidiary of the U.S.-based Union Carbide , observed a partial strike Saturday in memory of those killed in the Dec. 2-3 , 1984 disaster .
Survivors and orphaned children gathered in front of the closed factory to burn straw-and-bamboo effigies of Warren Anderson , the then chief of the Danbury , Conn.-based corporation .
Children beat the burning effigies with sticks as elders , many of them with tears in their eyes , shouted `` death to Anderson . ''
As more protestors gathered to burn effigies , some 10-feet - -LRB- 3 meter - -RRB- high , local leaders made speeches demanding that Anderson be brought to India and tried for mass murder .
Others spoke of the plight of the half-a-million survivors who are yet to get full compensation .
At other places in the city , prayer meetings were held for the dead .
`` I know all this may produce nothing , but I decided to come , '' said Kamal Pancham , who lost his daughter and father in the disaster .
`` Even after 10 years we look like beggars asking for alms , '' Rehena Begum , a voluntary worker , told a group of 500 women survivors .
India 's slow-moving courts are overwhelmed with claims .
Bureaucratic corruption and red tape add to the woes of survivors .
Every passing day brings to hospitals fresh cases of lung diseases , cancer , cataracts , gynecological disorders , and psychiatric disorders arising out of gas poisoning .
In 1989 , Union Carbide paid dlrs 470 million -- one-twelfth of India 's original claim -- in an out-of-court settlement that guaranteed immunity from prosecution for Carbide executives .
The government has paid out only dlrs 20 million so far and the balance has grown to dlrs 516 million .
Two years after the agreement , India 's Supreme Court struck down the immunity clause , while allowing the financial settlement to stand .
But the money has been locked in banks while bureaucrats and judges sort out the claims .
Eight officials of Union Carbide 's Indian subsidiary were charged with manslaughter for alleged negligence , but none has been brought to trial .
Studies have found that the gassing victims have three times more respiratory problems than the national average , get cataracts 15 years earlier and have more gynecological complications .
Nearly all the victims have low immunity , and growth of affected children is slower than normal .
The National Basketball Association on Friday night featured three winning teams each getting more than 30 points from two players .
Orlando won its ninth straight game as Shaquille O'Neal scored 38 points and Anfernee Hardaway 33 as the Magic dominated New York 125-100 .
Miami won for just the fourth time in 13 games with Glen Rice scoring 34 points and Kevin Willis 31 in a 115-97 decision over New Jersey .
At Portland , defending NBA scoring champion David Robinson scored 32 points and got help from Sean Elliott with 31 in a 95-91 victory over the Trail Blazers .
Elsewhere , it was Philadelphia 99 , Sacramento 96 ; Phoenix 107 , Boston 102 ; Washington 115 , Detroit 104 ; Atlanta 92 , Chicago 81 ; and the Los Angeles Lakers 107 , Houston 89 .
O'Neal and Hardaway were so effective that with one minute left in the third quarter , the visiting Knicks had 68 points to 64 for O'Neal and Hardaway .
`` We asked the team when they were coming out on the floor for our best 48 minutes of basketball of the year , and I think basically that 's what we got , '' coach Brian Hill said .
`` I do n't know if we can play better than we did tonight . ''
Hardaway and O'Neal sat out much of the fourth quarter , while reserves finished the rout of the Knicks , who were led by 15 points from Patrick Ewing .
San Antonio held off Portland for its second road victory in six tries this season .
Robinson 's big game was no surprise since he 's averaging 28 points , but coach Bob Hill said Robinson needs scoring support from Elliott , who 's averaging 16 .
`` He 's been struggling .
We just wanted to force-feed him and try to get him going , '' Hill said .
The Spurs scored the final four points of the game after the Blazers had scored five in a row to tie it 91-91 .
Chuck Person 's 17-footer with 35 seconds to play gave San Antonio the lead for good , 93-91 .
Clifford Robinson scored 17 points for the Blazers .
Rice was 14-for-18 and Willis 14-for-23 for Miami .
Willis also had a season-high 17 rebounds against visiting New Jersey .
`` Those are very good numbers , but I ca n't be satisfied , '' Willis said .
`` I know what I have to do .
I have to lead by example . ''
Kenny Anderson paced New Jersey with 16 points and 13 assists , but the Nets played without Derrick Coleman , their leading scorer and rebounder , because of a sprained right wrist .
Stacey Augmon scored 20 points and Craig Ehlo 's first 3-pointer of the season was a big one as Atlanta won at Chicago .
Ehlo 's shot gave the Hawks a 79-73 lead , and the Bulls got no closer than five points the rest of the way .
Ehlo was playing in only his second game after returning from arthroscopic knee surgery .
B.J. Armstrong and Toni Kukoc scored 19 points apiece for the Bulls .
Cedric Ceballos had 25 points and a career-high 16 rebounds as Los Angeles came back from its third-worst defeat in club history to stun visiting Houston .
Vlade Divac added 22 points for the Lakers , who won for the sixth time in seven games .
The Rockets got a career-high 22 points and 11 rebounds from Carl Herrera .
Washington finally won its first game with Chris Webber in the lineup as he had 18 points and nine rebounds against Detroit .
The Bullets were 0-4 since Webber joined the team after being obtained in a trade with Golden State .
Webber , who temporarily left the game in the third quarter to receive three stitches for a cut over his right eye , made eight of 11 shots in 34 minutes .
Calbert Cheaney scored 19 points for the Bullets .
Grant Hill scored 28 and Joe Dumars 20 for the Pistons , who have lost five of seven overall and four straight on the road .
Phoenix overcame a 22-point second-quarter deficit and a sensational second half by Dominique Wilkins to win at Boston .
Wilkins made 10 of his first 11 shots in the second half , and his last basket gave him 34 points and the Celtics a 100-97 lead with 1:47 left .
But the Suns responded with a 10-0 run to regain control .
Danny Manning 's three-point play and layup started the burst and put Phoenix ahead to stay , 102-100 .
The Suns , who won for the ninth time in 11 games , were led by Dan Majerle with 21 points .
Willie Burton had 25 points and Clarence Weatherspoon scored 12 of his 18 points in the final period , helping Philadelphia defeat visiting Sacramento .
The teams were tied 69-69 entering the fourth quarter before Weatherspoon scored six points in a 15-8 run to give the 76ers an 84-77 lead they never lost .
Mitch Richmond led all scorers with 30 points , but he had eight turnovers for the Kings .
Russia 's first veto of a Security Council resolution in 18 months was a show of strength that followed repeated warnings the council was ignoring Moscow 's interests .
Under strong domestic pressure to reassert its influence at the United Nations , Russia also pushed the council Friday to call for peace talks in the former Soviet republic of Georgia .
Russia 's veto blocked a resolution aimed at stopping Yugoslav fuel supplies reportedly powering a Serb offensive in northern Bosnia .
Russian Ambassador Sergey Lavrov said the resolution would have tightened sanctions against Serbia , the main remaining state in Yugoslavia , which has been cooperating with international peace efforts .
`` We had no other choice than to vote against this draft , '' Lavrov said .
The move seemed to surprise many diplomats , but it cost Russia little .
The United States did not press for the resolution and in brief remarks after the vote , deputy U.S. Ambassador Edward Gnehm made no direct mention of the veto .
Lavrov has repeatedly accused the United Nations of a double standard , saying the council has imposed sanctions against Serbia but has ignored Muslim acts against Serbs -- Russia 's traditional allies .
The veto came amid increasing signs of Russian assertiveness on the council .
On Tuesday , Russia abstained on a resolution that increased the U.N. team in Haiti tenfold to 500 members .
At the time , Lavrov accused Security Council members of focusing a `` disproportionate '' amount of attention on Haiti and of dragging its feet on `` situations that actually threaten international peace . ''
Russia has repeatedly called on the council to take a more active role in Georgia and Tajikistan , where Russia has deployed peacekeepers .
On Friday , the council acted , calling on Georgia and its breakaway province of Abkhazia to press forward with peace talks .
Russia last used its veto in May 1993 to block a proposal on financing the U.N. peacekeeping force in Cyprus .
Vetos have been used 281 times in the Security Council since the United Nations was founded in 1945 .
Lavrov said Friday 's veto did not mean the death of the five-nation contact group pushing for peace in Bosnia .
He stressed that hours before the veto , diplomats from Russia , the United States , France , Britain and Germany demonstrated their unity by endorsing a confederation of Bosnian Serbs and neighboring Serbia .
