President Kim Young-sam on Saturday ordered one of South Korea 's biggest government reshuffles , saying it will streamline key economic functions to help the country compete in the world market .
The shakeup will eliminate two Cabinet ministers , three vice ministers and dozens of other high-ranking posts .
The move , to take effect early next year , subject to parliamentary approval , is seen as part of Kim 's efforts to salvage his 20-month-old administration from gridlock .
The country has been wracked in recent months by a series of disasters , corruption scandals , violent farmers ' protests and political bickering .
In South Korea , it is common for the president to make a Cabinet reshuffle or announce important decisions to shake up a political stalemate when the government suffers serious scandals .
`` The reorganization aims at a smaller but more efficient government in an age of a global economy , '' presidential spokesman Choo Don-shik quoted Kim as telling a meeting of key government officials .
The highlight of the shakeup , one of the most extensive since the republic was founded in 1948 , is the merger of the Finance Ministry with the Economic Planning Board , a government ministry in charge of drawing up the budget and coordinating economic policies .
The sprawling Ministry of Trade , Industry and Energy will be streamlined to focus more on trade and industry .
The Transportation Ministry and the Construction Ministry are to be merged , and the Communications Ministry will take on certain functions from other ministries to deal with the information revolution , Choo said .
Kim has warned that divisive internal disputes leave South Korea badly prepared as it tries to cope with a new world trade agreement in an increasingly competitive world market .
Recently , farmers staged violent street protests over the government 's decision to open its markets to foreign farm produce .
A major bridge in Seoul collapsed in October , killing 32 people and triggering public anger over the government 's failure to manage state facilities .
Tax collectors were found to have pocketed millions of dollars in what is snowballing into a nationwide tax scandal .
Also Saturday , the opposition Democratic Party staged a massive outdoor demonstration in Puchon , just outside Seoul , to press its demand that the government indict former presidents Chun Doo-hwan and Roh Tae-woo for engineering a 1979 military coup that put Chun in power .
The opposition says it wo n't cooperate in approving the GATT deal and other important bills unless the government agrees to bring them to trial .
Chun and Roh , while still generals , established a junta to rule the country after the death of their mentor , President Park Chung-hee .
Roh succeeded Chun as president in 1988 .
Fearing their prosecution would trigger serious political unrest , Kim has urged the nation to let history judge the December 1979 coup .
Critics say Kim , a former opposition leader , owes his political success to Roh because he became president after merging his party with Roh 's governing party in 1990 .
The political scene was further strained Friday when the governing Democratic Liberal Party snubbed the opposition and unilaterally approved the 1995 budget .
Rescuers located two more survivors Saturday and recovered an additional body from a ferry with more than 600 people on board that sank after colliding with a cargo ship .
The recovery of the body of an elderly woman brought the confirmed death toll in Friday 's collision to 35 .
More than 110 people remained missing .
Rescue efforts resumed at daybreak Saturday , as the coast guard held the freighter , the Singapore-registered Kota Suria , and its 30-man crew in custody .
Coast guard spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Amado Samante said the two survivors had been taken by fishermen to the coastal town of Naic in Cavite province , a few kilometers -LRB- miles -RRB- from where the ferry Cebu City sank .
The two brought the total number of people confirmed to have survived to 453 out of the 608 on board the ferry , the boat 's owners said .
Some discrepancies remained between the coast guard 's and the owners ' figures .
The cause of the accident was not yet known , but an official of William Lines , the owners , claimed the ferry had been rammed by the freighter , which had its bow badly dented .
The freighter is to be held during the investigation , which will last several weeks , Samante said .
Jacob Cabatuan , a crewman on the ferry , said the freighter crashed bow-first into the ship , destroying the bridge and ripping a one-meter -LRB- three-foot -RRB- hole in the lower deck .
He said the ferry 's captain , first and second mates were pinned on the bridge .
Passengers , many of whom were asleep after the ferry 's predawn departure from Manila , said they had no warning of the accident .
The ferry sank into mud under about 25 meters -LRB- 85 feet -RRB- of water .
Four teams of coast guard and navy divers were searching the ship for bodies believed trapped in the cabins , Samante said .
About 50 coast guard , navy and commercial sea vessels were involved in the search effort Saturday , he said .
`` We are hopeful to find survivors , '' said Samante .
Seaman Angel Espidido , one of 27 coast guard divers who joined navy frogmen Friday , said he could see bodies trapped inside the cabins but that divers were unable to open the doors .
The 2,452-ton Cebu City had left Manila bound for the resort area of Tagbilaran , the capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- to the southeast , a 28-hour boat trip .
The ferry , usually used by families and small business owners , sank 30 minutes after it and the 12,500-ton freighter collided .
William Lines said the Cebu City had a capacity of 800 passengers .
It sank near the town of Rosario , about 50 kilometers -LRB- 35 miles -RRB- southwest of Manila in Cavite province .
