Fifty-one players made the cut at 149 and advanced to Sunday 's final round of the tournament , which offers a top prize of 10.8 million yen -LRB- dlrs 108,000 -RRB- .
Ikuyo Shiotani , currently second on the Japan LPGA money list , shot a fat 80 for a 150 and failed to make the cut , along with Ayako Okamoto , who shot a 76 for a 153 .
The 60 million yen -LRB- dlrs 600,000 -RRB- tournament is being held on the 6,274-yard , par-72 Kumamoto Chuo Country Club course in southern Japan .
A kiss is just a kiss .
But in Japan , it 's a social statement .
Kissing in public , considered shocking a few years ago , has come into vogue .
Japanese couples are bussing on buses and puckering up on park benches .
The trend has set off a debate about changing mores in a country still strongly influenced by conservative Confucian standards .
`` I feel very uncomfortable seeing them doing that , '' said Etsuko Yamashita , 38 , who lectures on feminism at Japan Women 's University .
`` If my children did that , I would scold them . ''
The kissing contingent , though , is unrepentant .
`` That kind of public kissing should be accepted , '' said 18-year-old Yuko Asayama .
Her boyfriend , Shiro Akiba , said he feels relaxed about kissing her in front of mutual friends but is still shy in public .
Part of the reason public kissing is considered so provocative is that in Japan , a kiss has traditionally been viewed as a prelude to sex .
Japanese people do not kiss and hug in greeting , but bow instead .
Kissing was prohibited in movies until after World War II .
But in a bizarre bit of social engineering , U.S. occupation forces instructed Japanese filmmakers to begin showing on-screen kisses .
Japanese actors and actresses went along , but unwillingly , using tissue paper to avoid direct lip contact .
Even with the film barrier broken , public displays of affection in Japan remained rare compared to the United States and Europe .
Analysts say the public-kissing trend was pioneered by television commercials .
A 1992 spot by the cosmetics firm Kose Corp. had a young woman exclaiming `` Chu shite ! ''
-- roughly translated as `` Kiss me , darling ! ''
Cosmetics rival Shiseido , not to be outdone , has been racking up big sales of no-smudge lipstick , which it markets with a boast that it will last through a long smooching session and leave the kissee unsmeared .
Like most trends here , the bussing boom is being explored enthusiastically by Japanese media .
One popular biweekly magazine had a recent article instructing young male readers in what it called `` the art of public kissing . ''
The magazine , Popeye , recommended coffee shops and empty train cars as good places for beginners to practice .
But it cautioned : `` Do n't get too excited . ''
Michio Koseki , a senior editor at Popeye , said the kissing trend is a sign that young people are abandoning the reticence of their elders .
`` It 's their statement that it is nothing to feel embarrassed to show the world that they 're in love and enjoying being in love , '' Koseki said .
Others believe it 's just a fad based on Western movies .
`` Those couples look extremely unnatural , '' said lawyer Mizuho Fukushima .
Japan 's sexual mores have always featured a mix of prudishness and brazen behavior .
Many young `` office ladies '' who are expected to wear demure uniforms and pour tea by day don stripper-style garb for club nights out on the town .
Scantily dressed women appear on television variety shows even during the day , and pictures of nude women are routinely printed in news magazines .
Fukushima said that even if kissing in public is only a fad , at least it does n't exploit women .
`` The current trend is not forcing women into being victims of sexism , '' she said .
`` Both parties seem to be equally enthusiastic . ''
In cars , on foot and even in wheelchairs , Taiwanese thronged to the polls Saturday in the toughest electoral test for the island 's Nationalist rulers in 45 years .
The local elections marked a milestone in Taiwan 's 7-year-old transformation from virtual dictatorship to multi-party democracy .
Voters chose a governor for the first time , and mayors for Taipei and Kaohsiung for the first time since 1967 and 1979 respectively , as well as local councils and the provincial assembly .
State-run TV said polling stations closed on schedule at 4 p.m. -LRB- 0800 GMT -RRB- and results were expected about eight hours later .
Newspapers and TV estimated that 70 percent to 80 percent of Taiwan 's 13.8 million eligible voters turned out .
President Lee Teng-hui , who is credited with steering Taiwan through its transition to democracy , cast his vote in a Taipei stadium shortly after polling stations opened at 8 a.m. -LRB- 0000 GMT -RRB- .
Older voters in wheelchairs and couples with children lined up in the rain to vote in schools , sports grounds and Buddhist temples , sometimes waiting half an hour for their turn .
Campaigning for the election was feverish and , at times , violent .
No incidents were reported during the voting , but there were fears that violence might erupt when results were announced .
Justice Minister Ma Ying-jeou appealed to people to watch the results on TV and not mass outside party headquarters .
Police said 70,000 officers were deployed , and Lee appealed to Taiwanese to `` welcome a new era of democracy for all . ''
The polls are a prelude to Taiwan 's first direct presidential election in 1996 .
Lee 's prospects for another term will be measured by his Nationalists ' performance against the main opposition , the Democratic Progressive Party .
The Nationalists fled to Taiwan to escape the 1949 Communist takeover of mainland China .
They still say they hope one day to reunite Taiwan with the Chinese motherland .
But the DPP advocates Taiwanese independence , something China has vowed to resist by force , claiming Taiwan is a renegade province .
Campaigning focused largely on `` Tong-Du '' -- reunification vs. independence -- and DPP successes could provoke misgivings in Beijing .
Business leaders placed newspaper ads warning that Taiwan 's dollar and the island 's standing with investors could plummet if pro-independence forces gained power .
But the DPP may profit from a split in the Nationalist vote caused by the recently formed New Party , which quit the Nationalists last year , accusing them of abandoning the commitment to reunification .
Opinion polls were suspended several days before the election , making it difficult to forecast the result .
But in the most recent polls , the DPP 's Chen Shui-bian was thought to be a front-runner for mayor of Taipei , while Nationalist James Soong had a 50-40 lead over the DPP 's Chen Ting-nan in the race for governor .
Candidates held final rallies Friday night , including tens of thousands of cheering New Party supporters who packed Taipei 's municipal stadium .
The carnival-like election campaign underlined Taiwan 's enthusiasm for democracy .
Taipei 's streets and many of its taxis were covered with flags .
In the last few days , campaigners lulled the capital to sleep at night with drums and roused it each morning with firecrackers .
Interior Minister Wu Poh-hsiung even complained that precious resources were wasted and that the campaign flags `` could have clothed 1 million refugees . ''
Voters also were urged not to take bribes , a problem in past elections as well as this one .
The DPP filed a lawsuit Wednesday accusing the Nationalists of earmarking about 150 million Taiwan dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 5.6 million -RRB- to buy votes for Huang Ta-chou , Taipei 's incumbent Nationalist mayor , who is lagging in opinion polls .
The Nationalists denied the allegations and denounced vote-buying .
Government-controlled TV ran advertisements showing vote-buyers in handcuffs .
Ten months after his death at age 31 , the eldest son of President Hafez Assad is a towering presence across Syria .
Giant portraits of Basil Assad , a lover of fast cars who died in a car wreck , drape the fronts of buildings .
His photographs are displayed in car windows and on the walls of offices , shops and homes .
They send a message -- not only of what might have been , but of what still can be : A new generation of the Assad family governing Syria .
There are three more Assad sons .
The second son , Bashar , is 29 .
Photographs of him are rarely seen .
But in Syria , people are used to reading between the lines of propaganda .
And hard-to-miss hints have been emerging .
In the officially sanctioned `` Paean to the Thoughts of the Hero Basil Assad , '' the author , army Col. Bahjat Suleyman , begins :
`` Hope vanished ... on a bitter winter day after he brought to us a promise of a beautiful spring that 's full of colors and birds chirping . ''
But , the book concludes , nothing can stop `` Basil Assad 's generation from clinging to the second brother , Bashar Assad , and accompanying him ... toward the third millennium A.D. ''
The question of succession is increasingly important as Syria undergoes social and economic changes and talks peace with its nemesis , Israel .
President Assad , who seized power in a bloodless coup in 1970 , is 64 .
Ever since he suffered a heart attack a decade ago , some foreign governments have periodically speculated he is in poor health .
But Assad remains very much in control and as shrewd as ever .
Syrian officials insist his health is fine .
Western diplomats in Damascus point out that many people whose health is less than robust live to old age .
Diplomats and foreign-based political analysts question whether Bashar has the right stuff to guide a nation where stability traditionally has depended on a leader of undisputed strength .
Bashar was training in England as an opthalmologist when his brother , an army major , died .
He cut short his studies and came home to enter the military academy .
He graduated in November as a captain in command of a tank regiment .
Bashar now heads most of the committees his brother presided over , mainly ones relating to sports .
Any presidential successor is likely to need the approval of Assad 's close cadre of military and intelligence advisers , many of them from Assad 's own minority Alawite sect of Islam .
In March , longtime Defense Minister Mustafa Tlass signaled support for Bashar in a speech before the president .
`` I see in the eyes of your son , Dr. Bashar Assad , the will , determination and ability to raise the banner that Basil raised , '' said Tlass , a member of the Sunni Muslim majority .
The presidential succession is a highly sensitive subject and rarely discussed in public .
Despite his severe rule , Assad is valued by many people for presiding over modern Syria 's longest-lasting government .
There were 20 coups in the first 24 years after Syria became independent from France in 1946 .
In the second 24 years , there has been only Hafez Assad .
Would-be challengers have been deterred by the example set by Assad 's suppression of a 1982 uprising by the Muslim Brotherhood in the city of Hama .
The army killed up to 10,000 people and leveled much of the city , ending a bloody five-year campaign of bombings and subversion .
But Basil 's death last Jan. 21 was a serious blow for Assad .
For years , government propaganda had molded Basil into a national hero .
He was dubbed `` the Golden Knight '' and lauded for his accomplishments as an amateur horseman .
Pictures of Basil started appearing when he was alive , usually in the windows of cars and jeeps driven by young men from politically elite circles .
Since his death , they have multiplied monthly across Syria .
At a recent crafts show , nearly all the paintings depicted Basil -- glowing on black velvet or in ethereal oils .
Along the streets and in offices , murals and photographs -- often trimmed with tinsel and decorative lights -- depict a macho young man in paratrooper 's fatigues at his father 's side or in an ivory riding suit on a polo field .
Syrians insist their adoration of Basil is spontaneous and not fostered by the government .
`` He did a lot of good things for the country , the kinds of things nobody could forget , '' said one merchant .
But like many others , he was unable to give any examples .
He also declined to give his name .
Thousands of gaunt men and women -- survivors of the world 's worst industrial disaster -- marched through Bhopal Saturday to mark the 10th anniversary of the calamity that killed 7,000 people .
The central Indian city observed a partial strike in memory of those killed when methyl isocyanate gas leaked from a pesticide plant owned by an Indian subsidiary of the U.S.-based Union Carbide Corp.
Survivors and orphaned children gathered in front of the closed factory to beat and burn straw-and-bamboo effigies of Warren Anderson , who headed Union Carbide at the time .
Elders , many with tears in their eyes , shouted `` death to Anderson . ''
Local leaders made speeches demanding Anderson be tried in India for mass murder , while others spoke of the plight of the half-million people seeking compensation .
`` I know all this may produce nothing , but I decided to come , '' said Kamal Pancham , who lost his daughter and father in the disaster .
It was the second day of demonstrations to mark the disaster .
About 3,000 people marched near the state legislature Friday , but police arrested 11,000 people as they headed to the city for the anniversary .
Tens of thousands of people fled panic-stricken the night of Dec. 2 , 1984 , when a metal tank at the plant leaked the deadly gas .
Some 4,000 people died that night ; 3,000 other deaths were later blamed on the effects of the gas .
Five years ago , Union Carbide paid dlrs 470 million -- one-twelfth of India 's original claim -- in an out-of-court settlement that guaranteed immunity from prosecution for Carbide executives .
India 's Supreme Court later struck down the immunity clause .
Eight officials of Union Carbide 's Indian subsidiary were charged with manslaughter , but none has been brought to trial .
Meanwhile , India 's slow-moving courts have been overwhelmed with claims , and bureaucratic corruption has further stymied those seeking compensation .
So far , the government has paid out only dlrs 20 million while the fund has grown to dlrs 516 million .
`` Even after 10 years we look like beggars asking for alms , '' Rehena Begum , a voluntary worker , told a group of 500 women survivors .
Step right up , it 's election time in Taiwan -- which means fun , feasting and cash to help undecided voters make up their minds .
By all accounts , Saturday 's local elections were characteristically spicy and seamy , despite official efforts to stamp the bad habits out of Taiwan 's rapidly blossoming democracy .
Saturday 's elections for a governor , mayors , local councillors and provincial assemblymen were Taiwan 's most extensive since the ruling Nationalist Party fled to the island to escape the 1949 Communist takeover of mainland China .
Campaigning was feverish , the crash of drums , cymbals and firecrackers so loud that one newspaper joked Saturday that Taiwanese were looking forward to hearing just the usual din of traffic .
Interior Minister Wu Poh-hsiung complained that the blizzard of campaign banners `` could have clothed 1 million refugees . ''
Besides a number of brawls , there was mudslinging of a highly personal nature .
For example , Chen Shui-bian , the Democratic Progressive Party 's candidate for mayor of Taipei , was reported by newspapers to have publicly declared that he had a vasectomy , thus rebutting allegations that he fathered an illegitimate son with a campaign aide .
On Wednesday the DPP filed a lawsuit Wednesday accusing the Nationalists of earmarking about 150 million Taiwan dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 5.6 million -RRB- to buy votes for Huang Ta-chou , Taipei 's incumbent Nationalist mayor , who was lagging in opinion polls .
The Nationalists denied the allegations and the government ran a vigorous publicity campaign against vote-buying , showing TV ads of offenders being led away handcuffed .
The Justice Ministry said courts received some 400 complaints of vote abuse during the campaign .
Nonetheless , newspapers reported the going rate for a vote was 500 to 1,000 Taiwan dollars -LRB- dlrs 20-40 -RRB- .
The practice is probably rooted in Taiwan 's early days , when it was regarded as natural to refund a farmer or laborer for income lost by taking a day off to vote .
As democracy developed in the late 1980s and newspapers became free to expose abuses , the Nationalists were held up as the worst offenders , and they realized that ultimately their corrupt image would jeopardize their hold on power .
So they have stiffened the penalties and launched a series of cleanup measures , forcing candidates to find more subtle means of persuasion , like banquets or sightseeing trips around the island .
Banquets for 1,000 voters are not unusual .
The sightseers are asked to pay a nominal fee so that the trip ca n't be formally termed a bribe .
A controversial feature of Taiwanese campaigning is the lightly clad women who dance on the stage at rallies .
At one rally , the attire was so scanty that James Soong , the Nationalist candidate for governor , refused to get on the stage .
And then there are the campaign promises -- of new railroads , airports , old-age pensions , hospitals -- goodies which cost an estimated 2 trillion Taiwan dollars -LRB- U.S. dlrs 74 billion -RRB- .
`` It is part of Taiwanese culture to throw banquets and send presents when you need people 's help , or when you want to get close to them , '' said Huang Hwei-chen , director of the private Institute for National Policy Research .
He saw it as an inevitable symptom of democratization .
`` Democracy seems sort of commercialized , but it is in a transition , '' he said .
A bomb explosion early Saturday at the headquarters of the pro-Kurdish newspaper Ozgur Ulke killed one person and injured 19 others , the Anatolia news agency reported .
The bomb caused heavy damage to the building , destroyed several cars in the street and shattered windows of nearby houses , Anatolia said .
Another overnight explosion at Ozgur Ulke 's Ankara office caused heavy damage , but no casualties , Anatolia added .
No one claimed immediate responsibility for either attack .
Scores of Ozgur Ulke -LRB- Free Country -RRB- employees have been jailed for supporting the Kurdish rebels , and 10 of its reporters have been killed in unsolved murders .
Human rights groups accuse the security forces of involvement in the murders , but the government denies the accusations .
Kurdish guerrillas have been fighting for autonomy in southeastern Turkey since 1984 .
More than 13,000 people have been killed in the violence .
Government forces killed four Tamil Tiger rebels this week in two separate clashes , which have continued despite the president 's offer of a cease-fire and peace talks .
Troops killed three rebels Friday in Panichchankerni , 200 kilometers -LRB- 130 miles -RRB- east of Colombo , Brig. Gemunu Kulatunga , the military 's spokesman , said today .
In Namalpokuna , guerrillas attacked policemen Thursday night and one rebel was killed in the cross fire , he said .
No casualties were reported on the government side .
Rebel leader Velupillai Prabhakaran has agreed to President Chandrika Kumaratunga 's offer to restart peace talks to end the 11-year-old war , but no date has been set .
Negotiations were suspended after a suspected rebel suicide bomber killed opposition presidential candidate Gamini Dissanayake and 56 others on Oct. 24 .
More than 34,000 people have been killed in the fighting .
The rebels want a homeland for Sri Lanka 's Tamil minority , who are mostly Hindu and comprise about 3 million of the country 's 17 million people .
They accuse the majority Buddhist Sinhalese of discrimination .
Canadian peacekeepers at their camp near Sarajevo were anxiously awaiting the release of 55 Canadians today after a Bosnian Serb promise to stop holding hundreds of UN soldiers .
But there was no sign this morning that the release was under way , said a spokesman in the Muslim village of Visoko , headquarters for the 800 Canadian troops serving with the UN Protection Force in Bosnia-Herzegovina .
The more than 400 Canadians at the camp were watching every news bulletin on television and monitoring political developments in the capital of Sarajevo .
`` Everybody here is up and hoping they 'll be released today , '' said Maj. Geoff Hall , second in command at the camp .
`` Personally , I assume nothing in Bosnia , but this time this promise just might be for real . ''
The Canadians have been held for 10 days at various sites in Serb-held territory near Visoko .
Hall said the detained Canadians , who are in radio contact with the camp , said this morning there was no indication they were about to be released .
`` There is no change among our detained Canadians , so we 'll just have to wait this one out and see what happens . ''
UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi said Friday Serb leaders agreed to release Ukrainian peacekeepers in northern Bosnia , as well as Dutch and British convoys detained since last Saturday .
`` In addition , we have agreed that normal activities be restored to the Canadians -- 55 Canadians near Visoko -- and all other soldiers from other countries that were doing their work at weapons collection sites , '' Akashi said after talks with Serb leader Radovan Karadzic in Pale , near Sarajevo .
But Defense Minister David Collenette said in Ottawa on Friday Canadian officers in Bosnia could n't confirm the reports of agreement .
And Maj. Rita Lepage , a Canadian military spokeswoman in Zagreb , Croatia , said today there was no timetable for the release .
But she did not dismiss the Serb agreement as just another broken Serb promise to the UN .
`` This is certainly the most encouraging development so far , '' she said .
The Serbs did release 70 Dutch troops in good condition Friday but are holding about 300 more to discourage NATO air strikes against a Serb siege of the Muslim pocket of Bihac , a UN-declared safe haven in northwest Bosnia .
About 20 Canadians are at a police complex in the village of Ilijas .
The rest are at checkpoints and observation posts .
Maj. Dean Milner , senior officer among the detainees , is able to drive around in his vehicle and visit his soldiers .
The Serbs also let supply vehicles from camp bring the soldiers mail , food and other items .
Hall said the Canadians , if released , would be given at least 24 hours to rest before being allowed to give media interviews .
The camp was making preparations Friday for their release , including stocking up on food for a special steak-and-eggs meal for detainees .
The detainees , when released , will be debriefed , given time to rest and then allowed to `` get things off their chest '' at counselling sessions with people of their own rank , Hall said .
The camp stayed at the high alert level of orange today , which requires personnel to wear flak jackets and helmets when moving around outside .
Hall said the camp will stay at orange until the `` whole detention problem is over . ''
Meanwhile , in Paris on Friday , Peter Donolo , a spokesman for Prime Minister Jean Chretien , said : `` Obviously we 're encouraged by the developments .
We 're keeping our fingers crossed , but we 're not going to rest until our troops have full freedom of movement .
`` We 've been let down before . ''
