Police have arrested seven people suspected of leading a riot by pedicab drivers in the West Java city of Bandung , an official said Saturday .
Thousands of pedicab drivers burned cars and smashed dozens of store windows Thursday after hearing a rumor that a fellow driver had been killed in a collision with a car belonging to the city 's Public Order Office .
Four of the 12 cars set on fire by the protesters reportedly belonged to the city .
The rioters dispersed after police told them that the pedicab driver had not been seriously injured .
`` Most shops have been reopened , but a few others are still closed , '' said Diding Kurniady , spokesman of Bandung municipality .
Gatot Irianto , a lawyer for the Legal Aid Foundation office in Bandung , 180 kilometers -LRB- 112 miles -RRB- southeast Jakarta , said about 20 riot police were still posted on the streets .
Pedicab drivers are irate over restrictions imposed by the city , and the seizure of pedicabs that violate city rules .
The more than 2,000 pedicabs , called `` becak , '' operating in Bandung are not allowed to enter the center of the city to prevent traffic jams .
They are only able to operate in narrow alleys , but drivers sometimes break the rules in an attempt to earn more money .
Col. Didi Widayadi , head of the Bandung police , said police had started questioning the seven people suspected of leading the protest .
The seven suspects were caught destroying shops and cars during the riot , he said .
He said no one was killed in the riot .
Police said eleven other protesters had been taken into custody but were later released .
The death toll increased to 29 Saturday in the crash of a Budapest-bound express train that jumped the tracks and slid into a station building .
State radio said dozens more were injured .
The accident occurred at Szajol , a station near Szolnok about 70 kilometers -LRB- 40 miles -RRB- southeast of the Hungarian capital .
The second car of the express train derailed , dragging three other cars with it , and some of the overturned carriages smashed into the station building , railway officials said .
Karoly Lotz , the transport minister , said the accident most likely was caused by a switching mistake and that an investigation was under way .
`` There was a tremedous explosion , like the end of the world , '' said a railway employee who witnessed the accident and asked not to be identified .
The crash occurred Friday afternoon , but rescue work remained in progress Saturday .
State radio said the death toll , which had been reported at 24 , increased to 29 .
It said at least 56 people were injured , several of whom were unlikely to live .
Battered and broken railway cars were covered in brick torn loose from the building .
Rescue crews frantically dragged bloody bodies from the wreckage .
One car , partially twisted beyond recognition , remained skewering the collapsed building as a huge crane was positioned shortly before midnight to pluck it from the crumbling brick and mortar .
About 100 soldiers and 100 police officers worked into the night looking for survivors and keeping away the curious .
Rescue workers said part of the destroyed building was sleeping quarters for railway personnel and their families , including small children who were likely victims .
Defense Minister Gyoergy Keleti said dogs normally used to locate victims of mining disasters had found three children who were dug from the rubble .
Local Police Chief Gyoergy Lengyel said the train was traveling at about 110 kilometers -LRB- 66 miles -RRB- per hour , normal speed past a station that was not a stop .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 160 kilometers -LRB- 100 miles -RRB- east of Budapest .
President Clinton voiced strong support Friday for appointment of former Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gotari to head the new World Trade Organization .
The organization will administer new international trade rules established under GATT , the General Agreement on Tariff and Trade .
U.S. participation in the trade pact got final approval from Congress this week .
Besides Salinas , candidates for the trade post are former Italian Trade Minister Renato Ruggiero and South Korean Trade and Industry Minister Kim Chul-su .
Ruggiero is the clear favorite .
But the White House said Clinton believes Salinas , who has just completed a six-year term as Mexico 's president , is `` extraordinarily well qualified to take on the challenges facing the world trading system . ''
A White House statement noted that Salinas is the only candidate who has served as a head of state and said he has a strong background in internal economics .
`` He would bring to the WTO a wealth of experience and important insights from the perspective of a developing country , '' the White House statement said .
`` As Mexico 's president for six years , President Salinas led his country through a successful process of economic reform and trade liberalization , '' it said .
`` The president believe he deserves widespread support . ''
Japan , the only country attacked by atomic bombs , has formally asked the United States to reconsider a plan to issue a stamp showing a nuclear mushroom cloud , a Foreign Ministry official said Saturday .
The Japanese Embassy in Washington conveyed the request on Friday , stressing that the Japanese people have strong feelings against the stamp , which is inscribed , `` Atomic bombs hasten war 's end , Aug. 1943 . ''
The official said the U.S. Department of State replied that it is studying the Japanese request .
The U.S. Postal Service plans to begin selling the stamp next September .
The stamp depicts a mushroom cloud said to be a combination of images from the explosions of U.S. atomic tests and atomic bombs dropped by U.S. forces on the Japanese cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in the closing days of World War II .
Takashi Hiraoka , the mayor of Hiroshima , said in a statement Friday that `` it is regrettable that the description under the mushroom cloud will lead to an understanding that the use of the atomic bomb was right . ''
`` Whatever reasons there were , the use of nuclear weapons is not forgiven .
It is not an appropriate time to show the power of nuclear weapons while the world is tackling nuclear disarmament , '' Hiraoka said .
In Washington , Postal Service spokesman Robin Wright said Friday that the stamp commemorated an `` historically critical event . ''
`` Our purpose is to provide a comprehensive history of events of World War II and we are not making a value judgment on any of those events , '' Wright added .
The atomic bomb killed 140,000 people in Hiroshima .
Three days later , a second bomb was dropped on Nagasaki , killing another 70,000 people .
Several days later , on Aug. 15 , Japan surrendered to the Allied Forces .
Some historians say the bombs hastened Japan 's surrender , while other say Japan was already on the verge of surrendering .
