The death toll increased to 29 Saturday in the crash of a Budapest-bound express train that derailed and slammed into a station building , state radio reported .
At least 56 people were injured Friday when the second car of the train derailed and dragged three cars off the tracks , state radio said .
Some of the cars overturned and then smashed into the station building at Szajol , about 70 kilometers -LRB- 40 miles -RRB- southeast of the Hungarian capital , railway officials said .
Karoly Lotz , the transport minister , said the accident most likely was caused by a switching mistake .
About 200 soldiers and police officers worked into the night looking for survivors and keeping away the curious .
On Saturday , rescue crews frantically dragged bloody bodies from twisted railway cars covered in brick torn from the station .
One car skewered the building and a crane was brought in to remove it .
Twenty-nine bodies had been found , five more than state radio previously reported .
Part of the building housed sleeping quarters for railway personnel and their families .
Defense Minister Gyoergy Keleti said specially trained dogs located three children who were then dug out of the rubble .
Local Police Chief Gyoergy Lengyel said the train was not stopping at Szajol and was traveling at about 110 kilometers -LRB- 66 miles -RRB- per hour , its normal speed .
The train was en route from Nyiregyhaza , about 160 kilometers -LRB- 100 miles -RRB- east of Budapest .
