A volcano which erupted two weeks ago , killing at least 52 people , has again begun releasing hot gas and lava , forcing authorities to call off a search for earlier victims .
Lieut. Col. Supiadin , military commander of Sleman regency , said red-hot lava was spewing down from the crater and more than 70 emissions of hot gas and steam had been recorded in the past day .
`` We are not taking chances and have asked everybody to stop their search until the situation gets better , '' he said Saturday .
The searchers are looking for about 200 people who are still missing from the earlier eruption .
The search will resume when the volcanic activity subsides , Supiadin said .
More than 5,000 people were evacuated two weeks ago from villages which were devastated when a huge cloud of scorching steam and gas suddenly swept down the side of Mount Merapi .
The mountain is about 580 kilometers -LRB- 360 miles -RRB- east of Indonesia 's capital of Jakarta and 30 kilometers -LRB- 20 miles -RRB- north of the tourist city of Jogjakarta .
The eruption demolished homes , flattened forests , destroyed crops and wiped out livestock .
Tons of ash were dumped on the disaster site and some lava poured out .
Scores of people were badly burned by the fast-moving cloud , which had an estimated temperature of 200 degrees Celsius -LRB- 392 F -RRB- .
Many working in rice fields or food gardens had no time to run for cover .
A promise by new President Ernesto Zedillo to reform Mexico 's corrupt and inefficient judicial system could prove to be the most difficult to fulfill .
And the most important .
Zedillo 's predecessor , President Carlos Salinas de Gortari , always said his far-reaching economic reforms would eventually lead to the democratic and judicial reforms Mexico needs to become a truly modern , developed nation .
Now it 's up to Zedillo to make sure that happens .
Democracy and justice can not thrive in a country where the laws do not apply equally to all .
`` It has to be done , '' said independent political analyst Sergio Sarmiento .
`` Judicial reforms will be the most significant and difficult challenge of this administration . ''
When he took office Thursday , Zedillo vowed one of his first acts would be to seek a constitutional amendment overhauling Mexico 's justice system .
He said he would soon submit specific proposals to lawmakers .
`` I am determined to head the creation of a nation where the rule of law prevails , '' he said .
`` In order to tackle the rampant crime , the frequent violations of civil and human rights , and the grave public insecurity , we will launch an in-depth and genuine reform of the institutions in charge of the procurement of justice , '' Zedillo added .
Zedillo also named an opposition politician as his attorney general , the first such Cabinet appointment in the 65-year history of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party -LRB- PRI -RRB- .
Debate about Mexican justice has been heated in a year marked by the assassinations of two top PRI leaders and a rebel uprising in southern Mexico .
Mexico 's is a system that often grants impunity to the rich and powerful -- too often party leaders -- while frequently denying basic human rights to the poor and powerless .
From bribe-demanding traffic police to corrupt judges who let political cronies go free , the system has long been equated with graft , laziness and bureaucratic inpetitude .
The chief investigator in the September assassination of Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu , the PRI secretary general , quit last month , charging that party leaders were blocking his probe .
That revived questions about the March assassination of presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio .
Although officials insist Colosio was killed by a lone , deranged gunman , many Mexicans suspect a larger political conspiracy .
`` The brutal assassinations of two of Mexico 's most outstanding public figures have deeply hurt our citizens , sown seeds of ... doubt regarding some institutions , and divided the people of Mexico , '' Zedillo admitted .
Meanwhile , demands for justice continue to echo from the mountains of southern Mexico , where Indian rebels are threatening to revive their New Year 's Day rebellion .
The guerrillas maintain that a left-leaning candidate for governor was cheated out of victory during August elections .
Zedillo seems to realize that the economic and democratic reforms Salinas accomplished during his administration can never be truly effective without judicial reforms .
New laws against electoral fraud are pointless unless those who burn and steal ballots are arrested and prosecuted by honest judges .
Economic reforms encouraging foreign investment wo n't work if businessmen still have to pay bribes .
Judicial reforms are likely to be opposed by many , including top government or party officials long considered above the law and the druglords who bribe police officers for protection .
`` There are a lot of skeletons in the closet in Mexico , '' said Susan Kaufman Purcell , vice president of the New York-based Americas Society .
`` And a lot of people are going to be very reluctant to have those closets opened . ''
Anita Snow is an AP correspondent based in Mexico City .
A military court on Saturday found 16 suspected Muslim extremists guilty in the killing of a German tourist and two Egyptians , and sentenced two to death .
The others received prison terms ranging from five to 15 years .
The ruling was handed down at the military base at Haekstep , which is about 15 kilometers -LRB- 9 miles -RRB- northeast of Cairo .
Earlier Saturday , two police guards were killed and two others wounded when suspected Muslim extremists opened fire on a police station in southern Egypt , security officials said .
The extremists fled with two of the policemen 's automatic rifles , the officials said .
The incident occurred in the town of Farshut in Qena province , about 465 kilometers -LRB- 290 miles -RRB- south of Cairo .
The fatal attack on the German and Egyptians occurred Sept. 27 in the Red Sea resort of Hurghada .
Another German and an Egyptian were wounded in the shooting on a crowded downtown square .
It was the first known incident involving Muslim radicals in the Hurghada area , and government officials fear it will hurt tourism there .
Muslim radicals have waged a campaign of violence since the spring of 1992 to try to overthrow Egypt 's secular government and replace it with strict Islamic rule .
More than 460 people have been killed , most of them police and extremists .
Seven foreigners have been among the victims .
Most of the violence has been blamed on al-Gamaa al-Islamiya , or the Islamic Group , which has been most active in southern Egypt in villages around the city of Assiut .
Foreign reporters and Egyptian reporters with foreign news organizations were banned from covering most sessions of the trial but were permitted in Saturday to hear the verdicts .
Hearings began Nov. 5 .
The prosecutor had argued before the three-man military tribunal that the defendants wanted to damage Egypt 's economy by carrying out attacks on foreign tourists .
Tourism is one of Egypt 's main sources of foreign currency .
The two sentenced to death were Mohammed Omar Ahmed and Rabie Mahmoud Hassanein , who are accused of opening fire at the tourists .
President Hosni Mubarak began referring Muslim extremist cases to military courts early last year to speed up the court process .
This has been widely criticized by Egyptian and international human rights groups , which argue they should be heard in civilian courts .
Forty-three suspected extremists have been executed , all but two sentenced to die by military courts .
Former world junior champion Daniel Chopra of Sweden shot a 4-under-par 68 in Saturday 's final round to win the Malaysian PGA Golf title by two strokes .
Chopra , who was third after Friday 's third round , overcame bogeys on the par-4 first and second holes to beat his closest rival , Saneh Saengsui of Thailand , on the Tropicana Golf and Country Club course .
`` After the two bogeys in the first and second , I told myself to go for a 67 .
And in the last five holes , I managed to go three-under and finally finished with a 68 which was not bad at all , '' said Chopra .
The round , which was delayed for an hour due to heavy rain , gave Chopra a four-round total of 273 .
It was Chopra 's second win on Malaysian soil and his seventh victory since turning pro in 1991 .
Saengsui , who led after Friday 's third round , had to settle for second spot after an even-par round of 72 , while local pro Mohamed Ali Kadir , who was second Friday , took third place after posting a 72 .
Saengsui also had a bad start with bogeys on the first two holes , but managed to improve his score with birdies in the sixth , seventh and 13th holes for a 275 .
After the blunders on the first and second holes , Chopra kept his composure with birdies on the fourth , fifth , ninth , 10th , 15th and 18th holes .
For his win , Chopra received U.S. dlrs 5,100 , while Saengsui earned dlrs 3,850 .
Taiwan 's ruling Nationalists , fighting their toughest election in 45 years , took the lead in the race for the island 's governorship but were lagging in the contest for mayor of the capital , initial returns showed Saturday .
With about 60 percent of the votes counted , incumbent Nationalist governor James Soong had 2.9 million , against 2.1 million for Chen Ting-nan , the candidate of the main opposition Democratic Progressive Party .
But in Taipei , Nationalist Mayor Huang Ta-chou looked in trouble .
With about 23 percent of votes counted , Huang had 90,000 , compared with 155,000 for the DPP 's Chen Shui-bian .
A DPP victory in Taipei , Taiwan 's capital and largest city , would boost the credibility of the once-banned opposition and improve its chances in the island 's first direct presidential elections in 1996 .
But the Nationalists would draw comfort from winning the governorship , presently the highest fully elected post in Taiwan .
In Kaohsiung , a port city on Taiwan 's southern coast , Nationalist incumbent Wu Tun-yi had a lead of more than 50,000 votes over the DPP 's Chang Chun-hsiung with about 30 percent of votes counted .
Taiwanese thronged to the polls on foot , by car and even in wheelchairs to vote in the local elections , which marked a milestone in Taiwan 's 7-year-old transformation from virtual dictatorship to multi-party democracy .
Never before had voters chosen a governor , and elections for mayor have not been held in Taipei and Kaohsiung since 1967 and 1979 respectively .
Voters also chose local councils and the provincial assembly .
State-run TV said polling stations closed on schedule at 4 p.m. -LRB- 0800 GMT -RRB- and results were expected about eight hours later .
Newspapers and TV estimated that 70 percent to 80 percent of Taiwan 's 13.8 million eligible voters turned out .
President Lee Teng-hui , who is credited with steering Taiwan through its transition to democracy , cast his vote in a Taipei stadium shortly after polling stations opened at 8 a.m. -LRB- 0000 GMT -RRB- .
Voters lined up in the rain to vote in schools , sports grounds and Buddhist temples , sometimes waiting half an hour for their turn .
Campaigning for the election was feverish and , at times , violent .
No incidents were reported during the voting , but there were fears that violence might erupt after final results were announced .
Justice Minister Ma Ying-jeou appealed to people to watch the results on TV and not mass outside party headquarters .
Police said 70,000 officers were deployed , and Lee appealed to Taiwanese to `` welcome a new era of democracy for all . ''
The polls are a prelude to the 1996 presidential election .
Lee 's prospects for another term will be measured by his Nationalists ' performance against the DPP , especially in the race for governor .
The Nationalists fled to Taiwan to escape the 1949 Communist takeover of mainland China .
They still say they hope one day to reunite Taiwan with the Chinese motherland .
But the DPP advocates Taiwanese independence , something China has vowed to resist by force , claiming Taiwan is a renegade province .
Campaigning focused largely on `` Tong-Du '' -- reunification vs. independence -- and DPP successes could provoke misgivings in Beijing .
Business leaders placed newspaper ads warning that Taiwan 's dollar and the island 's standing with investors could plummet if pro-independence forces gained power .
But the DPP may profit from a split in the Nationalist vote caused by the recently formed New Party , which quit the Nationalists last year , accusing them of abandoning the commitment to reunification .
U.S. telecommunications firm AT and T has won a bid to supply Vietnam with its first automatic bank teller machines , a business publication said Saturday .
The company defeated fellow American competitors IBM and Digital Equipment in bidding to sell the machines to Vietnamese commercial banks , the Vietnam Investment Review reported .
The review is published by the State Committee for Cooperation and Investment , which regulates foreign investment here .
The review quoted AT and T representative Medi Pepper as saying the firm had n't yet signed a contract for the sale .
The State Bank of Vietnam announced plans earlier this year to install 30 to 40 automatic teller machines in the country 's major cities by the middle of 1995 .
It estimated the equipment would cost dlrs 2.8 million .
A modern banking system is one of Vietnam 's key development priorities as it seeks to double per capita national income to dlrs 450 by the end of the decade .
Sixteen people were injured Saturday in a mass pileup involving about 70 vehicles on an icy , foggy highway , police said .
Police said the accident happened about 7 a.m. -LRB- 0600 GMT -RRB- on the main route from St. Gallen to Rorschach in northeastern Switzerland .
Cars , apparently traveling too fast in the bad conditions , skidded into each other on the slippery surface , causing chaos within a matter of minutes .
Rescue vehicles were delayed by the resulting traffic jams .
A helicopter trying to reach the injured was unable to land because of the thick fog .
Police said two of the injured were in a serious condition .
The rest were mainly minor injuries .
Vietnam has not discussed letting U.S. ships use port facilities at Cam Ranh Bay , the naval base American forces built during the Vietnam War , the government said Saturday .
Vietnam 's Foreign Affairs Ministry issued the denial when asked about Western news reports that the two countries have talked about arranging for American naval ships to call once again at the deep water port in former South Vietnam .
`` The issue of Cam Ranh has so far never been mentioned in any of the talks or meetings between the U.S. and Vietnam , '' the ministry said in a statement .
U.S. Admiral Richard C. Macke told reporters during an official visit to Hanoi in October that he did not rule out future military cooperation between Vietnam and the United States , once the former enemies showed more political and economic cooperation .
Asked then about Cam Ranh Bay , he said : `` I 'm a naval officer and naval officers are always looking for good ports . ''
But he added that he did not specifically discuss the port with Vietnamese officials .
The ministry statement refutes speculation that Vietnam is keen to let the U.S. Navy use the port as a way to counterbalance Chinese ambitions in the region .
Vietnam and its huge northern neighbor , China , both claim the Spratly Islands , an archipelago in the South China Sea believed to lie atop rich oil and gas deposits .
The two Communist nations also dispute oil drilling rights closer to the coast of southern Vietnam .
China 's Foreign Ministry objected last month to a suggestion that the United States might want to return to Cam Ranh Bay .
China opposes the idea of any country basing its troops or forces on foreign soil , a Chinese ministry spokesman said .
After the Vietnam War , Hanoi allowed the Soviet Union to base its ships and submarines at Cam Ranh Bay .
Russian vessels still refuel there , but their presence is greatly reduced .
The United States has had no major naval base in the Western Pacific since it withdrew from Subic Bay in the Philippines in 1992 .
KARACHI , Pakistan -LRB- AP -RRB- - About 15,000 people , including several top Pakistani celebrities , marched through the streets of this troubled port city Saturday chanting `` Save Karachi '' and demanding an end to worsening violence .
But police reported 12 people killed Friday night and Saturday in a series of shootings , including two that targeted government officials .
`` Karachi is bleeding and I have come to press for peace , '' said social worker Nargis Latif , who like most of the marchers dressed in white to signify peace .
Before the march ended , there were fresh reports of violence .
In one attack Saturday , two drivers who worked at the main government office were kidnapped and their bullet-riddle bodies discovered hours later .
On Friday night , three workers were fatally shot when gunmen opened fire outside the house of the country 's labor minister , Akbar Lasi .
The minister was not at home at the time .
Political and ethnic violence has claimed hundreds of lives in Karachi this year .
Government services have all but collapsed and many residents complain of a general sense of lawlessness .
Saturday 's march , organized by the country 's leading newspaper publisher , began in the center of the city at the mausoleum of Mohammed Ali Jinnah , Pakistan 's founding father .
In a festive atmosphere that included music and signing , the marchers traveled almost 10 kilometers -LRB- 6.2 miles -RRB- to the headquarters of the provincial government .
One of the march leaders was Imran Khan , Pakistan 's most famous cricket player .
Marchers threw rose petals on Khan and a number of film and television stars who took part in the procession .
The army , which patrolled the streets of Karachi for the past 30 months , was withdrawn Wednesday and many fear the police force and a paramilitary unit will be unable to maintain control .
The unrest has disrupted business in the country 's financial capital and frightened away potential foreign investors .
Much of the violence pits the security forces against the Mohajir Quami Movement , a powerful opposition group that represents mohajirs , or Muslim immigrants from India .
The MQM accuses Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of discriminating against mohajirs .
Ms. Bhutto 's government , meanwhile , says the MQM is a terrorist organization that uses violence to advance its cause .
Helped by Bruno Zarrillo 's goal 20 seconds before the end of the game , Bolzano beat Varese 5-4 Friday night in the semi-finals of the `` Six Nations '' tournament of European prop teams .
Jaromir Jagr , right wing of the Pittsburgh Penguins who signed a contract to play the three tournament games after the National Hockey League walkout , was playing his first game in the Bolzano jersey .
Jagr scored twice , at 54 seconds and 15:16 in the third period to even it at four points apiece in the Italian-team matchup .
`` I needed to score immediately , '' Jagr said .
`` I came to a new team and started out nervous , but after the goal I felt OK .
It was a very tough game .
We were down after the second period and everybody thought it was over , but we came back , scored two goals , and won the game . ''
Bolzano head coach , Bob Manno , a former player for the Vancouver Canucks , Toronto Maple Leafs and the Detroit Red Wings , said of Jagr : `` He definitely keeps the other team on their heels .
They are watching him , but he is a world class player and it 's almost impossible to stop him . ''
In Saturday 's games , Varese was scheduled against CourmAosta , and Bolzano against Villach , Austria .
Other nations in the tournament are Slovenia , France , the Netherlands and Denmark .
Crew members on a ferry and freighter that collided in Manila Bay , killing at least 35 people , will be tested for drugs and alcohol , the Coast Guard said Saturday .
Navy and coast guard divers , meanwhile , suspended a second day of searching for bodies trapped inside the ferry Cebu City after recovering the body of an elderly woman early in the day .
The ferry was carrying 608 people when it collided with the Kota Suria , a Singaporean-registered freighter , before dawn Friday and quickly sank .
At least 110 people are still missing , coast guard spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Loreto dela Cueva said .
Dela Cueva said divers were unable to open the cabin doors because some were locked and others were blocked by debris .
He said equipment to pry open the doors will be brought in by divers Sunday .
He said 453 people had been rescued , including two survivors brought to Manila Saturday after fishermen plucked them from the sea near Cavite province late Friday .
Lt. Cmdr. Federico Cabug , a coast guard intelligence officer , said the National Bureau of Investigation will take blood samples from the crew members on duty on the 2,432-ton ferry and the 12,500-ton freighter .
He said the blood tests were `` not a normal procedure , but in this case we have to do it . ''
`` There could be some negligence on the part of those manning the ship at the time of the incident , '' Cabug said .
`` If you are on duty , you are not supposed to be drinking or be under the influence of any kind of drug . ''
The ferry 's skipper , Wenceslao Lampong , is still missing .
A ferry crewman told reporters the freighter rammed the Cebu City at midsection , crushing the bridge and pinning the skipper and several other officers .
It is still unclear which vessel had the right of way in the passage at the time .
Coast Guard officers began interviewing Paquito Miraflor , the Filipino captain of the Kota Suria , after the freighter docked at the Manila harbor to unload more than 200 steel containers .
Officers declined to give details of the investigation and Miraflor refused to be interviewed .
But at least two of his crew members described the first few moments following the collision .
Indonesian crewman Mochamat Khotip and another who refused to be identified said they were awakened by the crash and later helped save about 230 people from the ferry .
The ferry sank into mud under about 25 meters -LRB- 85 feet -RRB- of water 30 minutes after the collision near Rosario town , about 50 kilometers -LRB- 35 miles -RRB- southwest of Manila in Cavite province .
The Cebu City had left Manila bound for Tagbilaran , the capital of Bohol Island , about 560 kilometers -LRB- 350 miles -RRB- to the southeast , a 28-hour boat trip .
The Philippines ' worst peacetime ferry disaster was in December 1987 , when 4,341 people died in the collision of the ferry Dona Paz with the oil tanker Vector off Mindoro Island , about 130 kilometers -LRB- 80 miles -RRB- south of Manila .
Canadian peacekeepers at their camp near Sarajevo anxiously awaited the release of 55 Canadians today after a Bosnian Serb promise to stop holding hundreds of UN soldiers .
But there was no sign the release was under way , said a spokesman in the Muslim village of Visoko , headquarters for the 800 Canadian troops serving with the UN Protection Force in Bosnia-Herzegovina .
The more than 400 Canadians at the camp were watching every news bulletin on television and monitoring political developments in the capital of Sarajevo .
`` Everybody here is up and hoping they 'll be released today , '' said Maj. Geoff Hall , second in command at the camp .
`` Personally , I assume nothing in Bosnia , but this time this promise just might be for real . ''
In Zagreb , Croatia , UN press spokesman Alexander Ivanko said he has been checking constantly with Serb officials and the Canadians have not been released yet .
`` We 're checking constantly but nothing is happening on the ground yet , '' he said .
