`` There is no change among our detained Canadians , so we 'll just have to wait this one out and see what happens . ''
UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi said Friday Serb leaders agreed to release Ukrainian peacekeepers in northern Bosnia , as well as Dutch and British convoys detained since last Saturday .
`` In addition , we have agreed that normal activities be restored to the Canadians -- 55 Canadians near Visoko -- and all other soldiers from other countries that were doing their work at weapons collection sites , '' Akashi said after talks with Serb leader Radovan Karadzic in Pale , near Sarajevo .
But Defense Minister David Collenette said in Ottawa on Friday Canadian officers in Bosnia could n't confirm the reports of agreement .
And Maj. Rita Lepage , a Canadian military spokeswoman in Zagreb , Croatia , said today there was no timetable for the release .
But she did not dismiss the Serb agreement as just another broken Serb promise to the UN .
`` This is certainly the most encouraging development so far , '' she said .
The Serbs did release 70 Dutch troops in good condition Friday but are holding about 300 more to discourage NATO air strikes against a Serb siege of the Muslim pocket of Bihac , a UN-declared safe haven in northwest Bosnia .
About 20 Canadians are at a police complex in the village of Ilijas .
The rest are at checkpoints and observation posts .
Maj. Dean Milner , senior officer among the detainees , is able to drive around in his vehicle and visit his soldiers .
The Serbs also let supply vehicles from camp bring the soldiers mail , food and other items .
Hall said the Canadians , if released , would be given at least 24 hours to rest before being allowed to give media interviews .
The camp was making preparations Friday for their release , including stocking up on food for a special steak-and-eggs meal for detainees .
The detainees , when released , will be debriefed , given time to rest and then allowed to `` get things off their chest '' at counselling sessions with people of their own rank , Hall said .
The camp stayed at the high alert level of orange today , which requires personnel to wear flak jackets and helmets when moving around outside .
Hall said the camp will stay at orange until the `` whole detention problem is over . ''
Meanwhile , in Paris on Friday , Peter Donolo , a spokesman for Prime Minister Jean Chretien , said : `` Obviously we 're encouraged by the developments .
We 're keeping our fingers crossed , but we 're not going to rest until our troops have full freedom of movement .
`` We 've been let down before . ''
LAGOS , Nigeria -LRB- AP -RRB- - An explosion at a gas plant in the southern oil-producing region of Rivers state killed six workers and seriously injured four , a newspaper reported Saturday .
The blast occurred Tuesday at a plant owned by the Italian oil company Agip as workers were welding valves , the state-run Lagos Times reported .
Residents of the village where the plant is located , Obrikom , fled as the blast sent a fireball into the sky and sparked blazes in nearby homes .
The accident was the second fatal explosion in a week to hit Nigeria 's beleaguered oil industry , which fuels the economy but has also been targeted by anti-government activists demanding an end to military rule .
Last week , an explosion at a pipeline killed 10 people .
Officials blamed that incident on saboteurs trying to cut into the line to steal oil .
Oil accounts for at least 80 percent of the Nigerian government 's export earnings , but the industry suffers frequent accidents because of lax safety standards caused by mismanagement and corruption .
The government owns majority shares in all international oil companies operating in Nigeria .
The oil minister , Don Etiebet , was quoted in Lagos newspapers Saturday as saying the military government was considering several options , including privatization , as a way to improve management in the industry .
Political unrest , including a nine-week oil workers ' strike , and government subsidies on oil prices have made the country 's refineries far less productive than they could be , he said .
`` The government may resort to the sale of refining and distribution assets in part or in whole to the highest bidder or companies with a track record in refinery management , '' Etiebet said .
Vietnam has not discussed letting U.S. ships use port facilities at Cam Ranh Bay , the naval base American forces built during the Vietnam War , the government said Saturday .
Vietnam 's Foreign Affairs Ministry issued the denial when asked about Western news reports that the two countries have talked about arranging for American naval ships to call once again at the deep water port in former South Vietnam .
`` The issue of Cam Ranh has so far never been mentioned in any of the talks or meetings between the U.S. and Vietnam , '' the ministry said in a statement .
U.S. Admiral Richard C. Macke told reporters during an official visit to Hanoi in October that he did not rule out future military cooperation between Vietnam and the United States , once the former enemies showed more political and economic cooperation .
Asked then about Cam Ranh Bay , Macke , the senior U.S. military commander in the Pacific , said : `` I 'm a naval officer and naval officers are always looking for good ports . ''
But he added that he did not specifically discuss the port with Vietnamese officials .
The ministry statement refutes speculation that Vietnam is keen to let the U.S. Navy use the port as a way to counterbalance Chinese ambitions in the region .
Vietnam and its huge northern neighbor , China , both claim the Spratly Islands , an archipelago in the South China Sea believed to lie atop rich oil and gas deposits .
The two Communist nations also dispute oil drilling rights closer to the coast of southern Vietnam .
China 's Foreign Ministry objected last month to a suggestion that the United States might want to return to Cam Ranh Bay .
China opposes the idea of any country basing its troops or forces on foreign soil , a Chinese ministry spokesman said .
After the Vietnam War , Hanoi allowed the Soviet Union to base its ships and submarines at Cam Ranh Bay .
Russian vessels still refuel there , but their presence is greatly reduced .
The United States has had no major naval base in the Western Pacific since it withdrew from Subic Bay in the Philippines in 1992 .
TIGNES , France -LRB- AP -RRB- - Liechtenstein 's Achim Vogt captured the first race of the men 's World Cup of Alpine Skiing season by winning the giant slaom Saturday .
Vogt , who trains with the Swiss team , had the lead after the first run course that dropped 440 meters -LRB- 1,443 feet -RRB- with a time of 1 minute , 14.19 seconds .
He then went through the second run in 1:16.57 for a total time of 2:30.76 .
Swiss Michael Von Gruenigen was second , 2:30.92 .
Third was last year 's overall World Cup winner , Kjetil-Andre Aamodt of Norway , with a total time of 2:31.06 .
The men finally opened their competition after weather had canceled races in three countries .
Tignes was one of the few places in Europe to be able to handle a race on its glacier , more than 2,600 meters -LRB- 8,500 feet -RRB- above sea level .
A slalom is scheduled for Sunday and a decision will be made concerning two downhills possibly being located in Val d'Isere next week .
China plans to set up its first private bank next year to provide loans mainly to private entrepreneurs , an official report said Saturday .
The Minsheng Bank is to have a registered capital of 2 billion yuan -LRB- dlrs 235 million -RRB- and will have a nationwide commercial business scope , the Xinhua News Agency reported , quoting the Guangdong-Hong Kong Information Daily .
The People 's Bank of China , the central bank , has yet to ratify the private bank 's management regulations , which include a list of shareholders , board members and executives , and the suggested locale of the bank .
The report said there would be a limited number of shareholders to maximize efficiency , and each shareholder will be restricted to owning less than 5 percent of the bank 's total stock .
Establishing a private bank would be another step in China 's financial reforms , which aim to bring the nation 's banking practices in line with international norms .
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Al Hariri has canceled his trip to China next week because of a political crisis at home , the Chinese Foreign Ministry announced Saturday .
Hariri was to arrive in Beijing on Monday .
Hariri , once hailed as the savior of a country ravaged by 15 years of civil war , said Friday he would resign after more than two years in office .
He has long been frustrated by opposition to his economic and reconstruction policies by several Cabinet ministers allied with neighboring Syria , the undisputed power in Lebanon .
His resignation would be a severe setback to efforts to rebuild Lebanon from the destruction of the 1975-90 civil war which killed 150,000 people , maimed tens of thousands and caused an estimated dlrs 25 billion in damage .
Bosnian Foreign Minister Ifran Ljubijankic Saturday agreed in writing that his country 's Muslim-led government will cooperate fully with the Yugoslav War Crimes Tribunal .
And tribunal spokesman Christian Chartier said a similar agreement will soon be signed with the Croatian government .
However the Bosnian Serb government and Serbian authorities in Belgrade both have indicated that they will not cooperate with the Tribunal and the vast majority of war crimes in the Balkan conflict are attributed to ethnic Serbs .
The only man so far indicted by the U.N. Tribunal is Dragan Nikolic , a Bosnian Serb alleged to have commanded a concentration camp for Bosnian Muslims .
Nikolic is thought to be in Bosnian Serb-controlled territory and it is unlikely he will ever be brought here to stand trial .
The `` memorandum of understanding '' signed by Ljubijankic and the Tribunal 's Chief Prosecutor Richard Goldstone formalizes agreements reached during Goldstone 's October visit to the Balkans .
It provides for the setting up of a Tribunal sub-office in Sarajevo , the carrying out of investigations including seizing evidence and interviewing witnesses in Bosnia and sending observers to any war crimes trials held there .
KABUL , Afghanistan -LRB- AP -RRB- - Sustained rocket attacks on the Afghan capital have wounded at least 58 people over the last two days , hospital officials said Saturday .
Most of the victims were in the government-controlled Karte Parwan area , the hospital officials said .
The main opposition force , led by Gulbuddin Hekmatyar , is dug in on the southern and eastern outskirts of Kabul and rockets the city almost daily .
Casualty figures were not available from the outlying areas that Hekmatyar controls , although government guns could be heard firing out on Friday night .
The number of dead is also unknown because they are buried immediately in accordance with Islamic custom , and rarely are the hospitals or government officials informed .
President Burhanuddin Rabbani 's troops and their allies have been battling a coalition led by Hekmatyar in a brutal battle for Kabul that erupted after the Islamic factions ousted the Communist regime of President Najibullah in 1992 .
Rockets , mortars and tank rounds frequently fall into civilian areas on both sides of the front line .
The United Nations is currently trying to negotiate a path to peace , but has achieved no real breakthroughs .
In another development , the United Nations is still trying to bring a food and medicine convoy into Kabul .
Hekmatyar 's men control the main roads into the city and have repeatedly stopped such convoys .
It was hoped that safe passage across the front line in southern Kabul could be negotiated Saturday .
But U.N. sources said they are now aiming for Monday .
If successful , it will be the first UN relief convoy to reach Kabul since June .
Chechen authorities released two Russian prisoners Saturday and turned them over to a parliamentary delegation from Moscow seeking the release of all Russians captured in a rebel offensive last week .
Chechen Foreign Minister Yousef Shamsedin said the prisoners were released because they had been wounded in the fighting .
He said they were being flown back to Moscow with the delegation .
The Interfax news agency identified the released prisoners as Lt. Dmitry Volfovich and Pvt. Alexander Danilov , both serving in the Russian army .
The four-person delegation was in the Chechen capital to negotiate the release of about 70 Russians , including army officers and soldiers , captured in an opposition assault on Grozny a week ago .
Shamsedin , asked if all the prisoners would eventually be released , obliquely replied , `` many prisoners have asked us not to send them back because they are afraid for their security . ''
Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev , who declared independence for his Caucasus Mountain republic in 1991 , claims Moscow is arming and leading the rebels against him .
President Boris Yeltsin 's government has denied providing anything but political support , even as the rebel offensive has escalated from small-arms fire to jet attacks throughout the week .
There was no fighting reported in Chechnya Saturday , and Grozny began a return to normal .
The city 's central bazaar , which had been deserted most of the week , was again buzzing with activity .
Earlier in the week , air raids killed at least four civilians and an airport guard , and destroyed planes at civilian and military airports .
`` It is clear that these planes are not English or French but Russian , '' Ella Pamfilova , a delegation member , said Friday .
`` This is against the law . ''
Sergei Yushenkov , the delegation 's leader , said , `` You can rest assured that President Yeltsin has recognized the prisoners as members of the Russian Army . ''
A dozen of the prisoners , interviewed Friday by The Associated Press , said they were hired by Russia 's Federal Counterintelligence Service for secret operations with the Chechen rebels .
Counterintelligence spokesman Alexander Mikhailov , asked about such reports at a news conference , said only that Chechnya is part of Russia and that the servicemen should therefore be called volunteers , not mercenaries , ITAR-Tass and Interfax said Friday .
Dudayev first threatened to kill the prisoners if Russia did not claim them , but later said they would be tried in court .
Yeltsin threatened to send troops if they were not released .
Moscow has since toned down the threat .
But it continued to beef up troops on Chechnya 's borders , news reports said .
The opposition accuses Dudayev of running Chechnya 's economy into the ground .
The main industry , oil refining , is operating at about 10 percent of capacity .
But Chechen pride and age-old enmity with Russia have rallied many people to Dudayev 's side , including some volunteers from other Caucasus regions .
Russia conquered the mainly Muslim Chechens in its imperial drive towards the Black Sea last century .
Ethnic tensions suppressed in Soviet times have boiled over since the 1991 Soviet collapse .
